  "3": [
    {
      "id": 17,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Man (Human Being)",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "« » commonly refers to the first human, Prophet Adam (peace be upon him). However, the word ( ) is also used to mean 'of the same kind' and 'of the same nature'. (25 verses: 2:31, 2:33, 2:34, 2:35, 2:37, 3:33, 3:59, 5:27, 7:11, 7:19, 7:26, 7:27, 7:31, 7:35, 7:172, 17:61, 17:70, 18:50, 19:58, 20:115, 20:116, 20:117, 20:120, 20:121, 36:60)",
      "d": "«اٰدَمَ» «اَدَمْ» «اَدَام» «لَوْ نَظَرْتَ إِلَيْهَا فَإِنَّهُ أَحْرَى أَنْ يُؤْدَمَ بَيْنَكُمَا»\nBesides this, other evidences are cited, but the correct evidence is this one because it is supported by Hadith.\nAdam: Abu al-Bashar, the name of Prophet Adam (peace be upon him). However, 'Adam' can also be used for his progeny (Majma' al-Bayan). Hence, 'Bani Adam' refers to all of humanity.\nMoreover, wherever 'Adam' or 'Bani Adam' is mentioned in the Quran, it relates to the history of humankind.\nFor example: Adam's creation from clay, the angels' prostration to Adam, humanity's honor as the best of creation, the covenant of 'Alast' (i.e., the pledge Allah took from Adam and his children in the world of spirits), Satan's misguidance of Adam and Bani Adam, and his dialogue with Allah, etc."
    },
    {
      "id": 18,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human (Human Being)",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "‘Ins’ is used when referring to the social aspect of human life (i.e., living together), and words derived from it are employed. When referring to the historical aspect, ‘Adam’ and ‘Bani Adam’ are used. When referring to the natural and innate aspect, the word ‘Bashar’ is used (16 verses: 6:112-6:128-6:130-7:38-7:179-27:17-41:25-41:29-46:18-51:56-55:33-55:39-55:56-55:74-72:5-72:6).",
      "d": "‘Ins’ (plural ‘Unas’) refers to groups of people who are distinct from each other due to tribe, family, or other reasons. For example, the Quran states: ‘Every group has recognized its watering place.’ (60:2) And ‘anasi’ refers to a very large group of people. For example, the Divine declaration: ‘We have created cattle and numerous humans.’ (49:25)"
    },
    {
      "id": 19,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human (Insaan)",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "« » to change the form (1 verse: 27:41-)",
      "d": "«قَامَ» «مَقَام» «وَ اتَّخِذُوۡا مِنۡ مَّقَامِ اِبۡرٰہٖمَ مُصَلًّی» «مُقَام» «قَامَ» «وَ  لِمَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ  رَبِّہٖ  جَنَّتٰنِ»"
    }
  ],
  "4": [
    {
      "id": 20,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Rest / Find Comfort",
      "hw": "آرام",
      "s": "« » comes to ask about place along with state or condition (28 verses: 2:223-2:247-2:259-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:165-5:75-6:95-6:101-9:30-10:32-10:34-19:8-19:20-23:89-29:61-34:52-35:3-36:66-39:6-40:62-40:69-43:87-44:13-47:18-63:4-89:23)",
      "d": "«حِزْب» «اَحْزَاب» «حَازَبَ» «حَزَّب» «حِزْب» «حِزْب»\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«یَحۡسَبُوۡنَ الۡاَحۡزَابَ لَمۡ  یَذۡہَبُوۡا ۚ وَ اِنۡ یَّاۡتِ الۡاَحۡزَابُ یَوَدُّوۡا لَوۡ اَنَّہُمۡ بَادُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَعۡرَابِ یَسۡاَلُوۡنَ عَنۡ اَنۡۢبَآئِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: They think that the (enemy) armies have not gone yet. And if the armies (return) come again, their desire would be that they go to the countryside and stay there (and while sitting there) continue to inquire about your news."
    },
    {
      "id": 21,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Rest / Find Comfort",
      "hw": "آرام",
      "s": "« » (Sabata) refers to a rest after which a person feels relief and tranquility (2 verses: 25:47-78:9)",
      "d": "« » means to come into existence or to be transformed into a specific state. This word is different from other words like ' ' (to create) or ' ' (to make) in that it fundamentally describes the act of something coming into existence or changing state, not just its external structure. For example, in the context of bones, ' ' refers to their composite existence or the stage of their formation.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said:\n«وَ قَالُوٓا۟ أَئِذَا كُنَّا عِظَـٰمًا وَ رُفَـٰتًا أَءِنَّا لَمَبْعُوثُونَ خَلْقًا جَدِيدًا»\nTranslation: And they say, 'When we have become bones and crumbled dust, will we indeed be resurrected as a new creation?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 22,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Rest",
      "hw": "آرام",
      "s": "« » to open and expand (1 verse: 77:9)",
      "d": "«موت» «وَضَرَبَ لَنَا مَثَلًا وَنَسِيَ خَلْقَهُ قَالَ مَنْ يُحْيِي الْعِظَامَ وَهِيَ رَمِيمٌ»"
    }
  ],
  "5": [
    {
      "id": 23,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Desire - To Desire",
      "hw": "آرزو",
      "s": "« » apparently refers to an unexpected and long-awaited desire. (3 verses: 15:3-18:46-47:25)",
      "d": "« » refers to such a desire and hope whose fulfillment is possible but difficult. Hence, Ibn Faris has defined its meaning as 'persistence and waiting' (m-l). That is, to keep hoping for a desire and wait for its completion, to remain desirous of seeing the springs of life, as a poet said in the desire for loyalty to his friend, which correctly interprets the meaning of « »: 'Loyalty is a deception, the length of hope is nothing.'\n«ذَرۡہُمۡ یَاۡکُلُوۡاوَ یَتَمَتَّعُوۡا وَ یُلۡہِہِمُ الۡاَمَلُ  فَسَوۡفَ  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 24,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Desire - To Desire",
      "hw": "آرزو",
      "s": "« » is used for false and baseless desire (and the desire that has a basis is « »). (4 verses: 2:78-2:111-4:123-57:14)",
      "d": "« » its meaning is for something to come or be brought, especially with immediacy and speed. This word differs from other words such as ' ' (to come) in that it expresses movement with purpose and subjugation. For example, in the Quran, in the mention of birds, this word was used to describe the quality of them gathering immediately by Allah's command.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is:\n«فَخُذْ أَرْبَعَةً مِّنَ الطَّيْرِ فَصُرْهُنَّ إِلَيْكَ ثُمَّ اجْعَلْ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنْهُنَّ جُزْءًا ثُمَّ ادْعُهُنَّ يَأْتِينَكَ سَعْيًا»\ntranslation: Then take four birds, incline them to you (slaughter them), then place on every mountain a portion of them, then call them; they will come to you swiftly."
    },
    {
      "id": 25,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Desire - To Desire",
      "hw": "آرزو",
      "s": "« » refers to the love and desire for anything. (25 verses: 2:96-2:105-2:109-2:266-3:30-3:69-3:118-4:42-4:73-4:89-4:102-5:82-11:90-15:2-19:96-29:25-30:21-33:20-42:23-60:1-60:2-60:7-68:9-70:11-85:14)",
      "d": "« » has two basic meanings: (1) to love something (2) to desire its attainment. Then this word is sometimes used in both meanings and sometimes in one meaning only.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«رُبَمَا یَوَدُّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ کَانُوۡا مُسۡلِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: At times, the disbelievers may wish that they had been Muslims.\nIn this verse, both aspects are present.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ سَیَجۡعَلُ  لَہُمُ  الرَّحۡمٰنُ  وُدًّا»\nTranslation: And those who believe and do righteous deeds, the Most Merciful will instill love (in the hearts of His creation) for them.\nIn this verse, only the first meaning is found.\nAlso see 'Desire'."
    }
  ],
  "6": [
    {
      "id": 26,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Barrier",
      "hw": "Barrier",
      "s": "« » in common parlance refers to the first human, Prophet Adam (peace be upon him). However, the word ( ) is also used in the meaning of having the same nature and temperament (25 verses: 2:31-2:33-2:34-2:35-2:37-3:33-3:59-5:27-7:11-7:19-7:26-7:27-7:31-7:35-7:172-17:61-17:70-18:50-19:58-20:115-20:116-20:117-20:120-20:121-36:60)",
      "d": "« » means to give the recompense for an action (from min majda). And qisas generally pertains to human blood and its organs and limbs. An example of this has passed under section b of this title, however it is not necessary.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اَلشَّہۡرُالۡحَرَامُ بِالشَّہۡرِالۡحَرَامِ وَالۡحُرُمٰتُ قِصَاصٌ»\nTranslation: The sacred month is for the sacred month, and the sacred things are retaliation."
    },
    {
      "id": 27,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Barrier",
      "hw": "Barrier",
      "s": "«بَاطِل»",
      "d": "«بَاطِل» «حَقّ» «یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ لِمَ تَلۡبِسُوۡنَ الۡحَقَّ بِالۡبَاطِلِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 29,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Hadd",
      "hw": "Barrier",
      "s": "«Hadd» refers to the ultimate limit and final edge of anything that prevents it from merging with other things (9 verses: 2:187-2:229-2:230-4:13-4:14-9:97-9:112-58:4-65:1)",
      "d": "«Hadd» its origin is «Hurr» and in its root two things are found: (1) to be free (2) to be pure from defects and shortcomings (m l). The opposite of «Hurr» is «Abd» meaning slave. And «Harra, Tahreeran» means to free a slave, so this word is specifically for freeing a slave."
    }
  ],
  "7": [
    {
      "id": 31,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to free",
      "hw": "Free",
      "s": "The word «Tahreeran» is specifically used for freeing a slave (3 verses: 4:92-5:89-58:3)",
      "d": "« » is that which is pure and clean from dirt and filth, according to Imam Raghib, it is pure from perceived impurity. And the opposite of « » is « » meaning dirt, filth, etc. (m. l) and .\n«وَسَقٰہُمۡ رَبُّہُمۡ شَرَابًا طَہُوۡرًا»\nSimilarly, a woman becoming pure from menstruation, postpartum bleeding, etc. is also tahir.\n«فَاعۡتَزِلُوا النِّسَآءَ فِی الۡمَحِیۡضِ ۙ وَلَا تَقۡرَبُوۡہُنَّ حَتّٰی یَطۡہُرۡنَ»\nAnd « » (form IV) is used for purity from both external and internal impurities.\n«وَرَبَّکَ فَکَبِّرۡ ۪وَثِیَابَکَ فَطَہِّرۡ»\n«اِنَّمَا یُرِیۡدُ اللّٰہُ لِیُذۡہِبَ عَنۡکُمُ الرِّجۡسَ اَہۡلَ الۡبَیۡتِ وَیُطَہِّرَکُمۡ تَطۡہِیۡرًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 32,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "free",
      "hw": "Free",
      "s": "«Hurr» means free in contrast to slave (2 verses: 2:178-3:35)",
      "d": "«Hurr» means free (its opposite is «Abd» meaning slave) i.e., a person who is not a slave."
    },
    {
      "id": 33,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Unrestrained",
      "hw": "Free",
      "s": "«Suddi» refers to an untethered camel upon which there is no restriction (1 verse: 75:36).",
      "d": "Some lexicologists derive it from « » meaning small ants (source: manjad), and « » is its singular, and « » means small children (source: mufradat).\n«وَاَصَابَہُ الۡکِبَرُ وَلَہٗ ذُرِّیَّۃٌ ضُعَفَآءُ»\nTranslation: And old age befell him, and he has weak young children.\n«ذَرَاَ» «ذَرَأَ الْاَرْض»\n«قَالَ اِنِّیۡ جَاعِلُکَ لِلنَّاسِ اِمَامًا  ؕ قَالَ وَمِنۡ ذُرِّیَّتِیۡ  ؕ قَالَ لَا یَنَالُ عَہۡدِی الظّٰلِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Allah said to Abraham: I will make you a leader for people. He said: And from my children? He said: My covenant does not include the wrongdoers."
    }
  ],
  "8": [
    {
      "id": 38,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To test",
      "hw": "Test",
      "s": "«Fatana» means trial/test, and this generally occurs through things to which humans have emotional attachment (54 verses: 2:102-2:191-2:193-2:217-3:7-4:91-4:101-5:41-5:49-5:71-6:53-7:27-7:155-8:25-8:28-8:39-8:73-9:47-9:48-9:49-9:126-10:83-10:85-16:110-17:60-17:73-20:40-20:85-20:90-20:131-21:35-21:111-22:11-22:53-24:63-25:20-27:47-29:2-29:3-29:10-33:14-37:63-38:24-38:34-39:49-44:17-51:14-54:27-57:14-60:5-64:15-72:17-74:31-85:10).",
      "d": "« » is a common noun meaning mountain. This word is used for every kind of mountain, whether small or big, high or low, all are included, and its plural is  . (f l 266)\n«ثُمَّ اجۡعَلۡ عَلٰی کُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنۡہُنَّ جُزۡءًا»"
    }
  ],
  "9": [
    {
      "id": 39,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Easy",
      "hw": "Easy",
      "s": "« » a child characterized by childhood habits and playing, an ignorant child (2 verses: 19:12-19:29)",
      "d": "«صَبِیٌّ» «صَبِیٌّ» «صَبِیٌّ» «یٰیَحۡیٰی خُذِ الۡکِتٰبَ بِقُوَّۃٍ ؕ وَاٰتَیۡنٰہُ الۡحُکۡمَ صَبِیًّا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 40,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Easy",
      "hw": "Easy",
      "s": "« » means ease; it is a task that is accomplished with facility and convenience (13 verses: 4:30-4:169-12:65-22:70-29:19-33:19-33:30-35:11-50:44-57:22-64:7-74:10-84:8)",
      "d": "« » its root is « » which includes the meaning of ease and lightness (m l). And « » is a task that is accomplished with facility and convenience. Its opposite is « ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمَنۡ یَّفۡعَلۡ ذٰلِکَ عُدۡوَانًا وَّ ظُلۡمًا فَسَوۡفَ نُصۡلِیۡہِ نَارًا ؕ وَ کَانَ ذٰلِکَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ یَسِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: And whoever does that in transgression and injustice - We will surely burn him in the Fire. And that, for Allah, is easy."
    }
  ],
  "10": [
    {
      "id": 41,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sky",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "« » its basic meaning is height, but there is no defined limit to this height (297 verses: 2:19-2:22-2:29-2:33-2:59-2:107-2:116-2:117-2:144-2:164-2:255-2:284-3:5-3:29-3:83-3:109-3:129-3:133-3:180-3:189-3:190-3:191-4:126-4:131-4:132-4:153-4:170-4:171-5:17-5:18-5:40-5:97-5:112-5:114-5:120-6:1-6:3-6:6-6:12-6:14-6:35-6:73-6:75-6:79-6:99-6:101-6:125-7:40-7:54-7:96-7:158-7:162-7:185-7:187-8:11-8:32-9:36-9:116-10:3-10:6-10:18-10:24-10:31-10:55-10:61-10:66-10:68-10:101-11:7-11:44-11:52-11:107-11:108-11:123-12:101-12:105-13:2-13:15-13:16-13:17-14:2-14:10-14:19-14:24-14:32-14:38-14:48-15:14-15:16-15:22-15:85-16:3-16:10-16:49-16:52-16:65-16:73-16:77-16:79-17:44-17:55-17:92-17:93-17:95-17:99-17:102-18:14-18:26-18:40-18:45-18:51-19:65-19:90-19:93-20:4-20:6-20:53-21:4-21:16-21:19-21:30-21:32-21:56-21:104-22:15-22:18-22:31-22:63-22:64-22:65-22:70-23:18-23:71-23:86-24:35-24:41-24:42-24:43-24:64-25:2-25:6-25:25-25:48-25:59-25:61-26:4-26:24-26:187-27:25-27:60-27:64-27:65-27:75-27:87-29:22-29:34-29:44-29:52-29:61-29:63-30:8-30:18-30:22-30:24-30:25-30:26-30:27-30:48-31:10-31:16-31:20-31:25-31:26-32:4-32:5-33:72-34:1-34:2-34:3-34:9-34:22-34:24-35:1-35:3-35:27-35:38-35:40-35:41-35:44-36:28-36:81-37:5-37:6-38:10-38:27-38:66-39:5-39:21-39:38-39:44-39:46-39:63-39:67-39:68-40:13-40:37-40:57-40:64-41:11-41:12-42:4-42:5-42:11-42:12-42:29-42:49-42:53-43:9-43:11-43:82-43:84-43:85-44:7-44:10-44:29-44:38-45:3-45:5-45:13-45:22-45:27-45:36-45:37-46:3-46:4-46:33-48:4-48:7-48:14-49:16-49:18-50:6-50:9-50:38-51:7-51:22-51:23-51:47-52:9-52:36-52:44-53:26-53:31-54:11-55:7-55:29-55:33-55:37-57:1-57:2-57:4-57:5-57:10-57:21-58:7-59:1-59:24-61:1-62:1-63:7-64:1-64:3-64:4-65:12-67:3-67:5-67:16-67:17-69:16-70:8-71:11-71:15-72:8-73:18-77:9-78:19-78:37-79:27-81:11-82:1-84:1-85:1-85:9-86:1-86:11-88:18-91:5)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of « » are for something to appear with its beauty and elegance (m l) while the meaning of   is only to appear.\nAnd « » refers to the upper surface of human skin.\n«لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ»\nTranslation: The fire of Hell will scorch the skin and turn it black.\nAnd its plurals are « » and « », and humans are called   because their skin, compared to other animals, is very clean and smooth due to wool, hair, etc. (muf)\nThe word   is used for singular, plural, masculine, feminine all. However, if used for two humans, then « » is said.\n«اَنُؤۡمِنُ لِبَشَرَیۡنِ مِثۡلِنَا»\nTranslation: Should we believe in two men like ourselves?\nAnd in contrast to  , the word « » (i.e., angel) is used, which is free from the material aspect, i.e., external physical and natural needs.\nThe disbelievers always had this objection that we should believe in a human like ourselves who is born and dies, eats and drinks, walks in markets, and fulfills needs like us. So what preference does he have over us that we should believe in him? But if there were an angel, free from these needs and requirements, then it would be different.\n«وَ مَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ اَنۀ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡۤا اِذۡ جَآءَہُمُ الۡہُدٰۤی اِلَّاۤ  اَنۀ قَالُوۡۤا اَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ بَشَرًارَّسُوۡلًا .قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَلٰٓئِکَۃٌ یَّمۡشُوۡنَ مُطۡمَئِنِّیۡنَ لَنَزَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ  السَّمَآءِ  مَلَکًا  رَّسُوۡلًا»\nTranslation: And when guidance came to the people, nothing prevented them from believing except that they said, 'Has Allah sent a human as a messenger?' Say, 'If there were angels in the earth walking and settling securely, We would have sent down an angel as a messenger from the heaven.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 42,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Orbit",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "« » refers to the orbits (paths) of planets (2 verses: 21:33-36:40)",
      "d": "« » means to establish a sexual relationship or to marry. Although this word is generally used in the meaning of lawful and Shariah-compliant marriage, but when it is used for a sexual relationship in an illegal or forbidden relationship, then it refers to adultery or such a severe evil (fahishah). In this case, the act of 'nikah' becomes illegal and condemnable, i.e., this act becomes forbidden because it is outside the Shariah limits.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَلَا تَنكِحُوا مَا نَكَحَ آبَاؤُكُم مِّنَ النِّسَاءِ إِلَّا مَا قَدْ سَلَفَ ۚ إِنَّهُ كَانَ فَاحِشَةً وَمَقْتًا وَسَاءَ سَبِيلًا»\nTranslation: And do not marry those women whom your fathers have married, except what has already passed. Indeed, it was an immorality, hateful, and an evil way."
    },
    {
      "id": 945,
      "hw": "Hamd",
      "s": "« » is praise and glorification from the tongue of Allah. (47 verses)",
      "d": "The word « » is Arabic and its meanings are to praise and to glorify. It is one of the attributive names of Allah (SWT). Allah (SWT) is also called by the meaning of « ». The difference between « » and « » is that « » is praise by the tongue, while « » is gratitude by the heart for a favor.\nThe meanings of « » include commendation, praise, and glorification.\nVerses: 1:1, 2:30, 3:144, 3:188, 6:1, 6:45, 7:43, 10:10, 13:13, 14:39, 15:98, 16:75, 17:44, 17:52, 17:111, 18:1, 20:130, 23:28, 25:58, 27:15, 27:59, 27:93, 28:70, 29:63, 30:18, 31:25, 32:15, 33:40, 34:1, 35:1, 35:34, 37:182, 39:29, 39:74, 39:75, 40:7, 40:55, 40:65, 42:5, 45:36, 47:2, 48:29, 50:39, 52:48, 61:6, 64:1, 110:3 (Total 47 verses)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ رَبِّ الْعٰلَمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: All praise is for Allah, Lord of the worlds.",
      "h": "to praise"
    }
  ],
  "11": [
    {
      "id": 43,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "«اَلَّا» is actually «اَنْ ۔ لَا». It means 'that not'.",
      "hw": "Jinn affliction",
      "s": "«اَلَّا» «اَنْ ۔ لَا»",
      "d": "«اِعْتَرٰی» «اَعْرٰی» «اَعْرٰی فُلَانًا صَدِیْقَہ» «عُرِیَ» «عُرْوًا» «اِعْتَرٰی»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ نَّقُوۡلُ  اِلَّا اعۡتَرٰىکَ بَعۡضُ اٰلِہَتِنَا بِسُوۡٓءٍ»\nTranslation: (The people of Hud said) We only say that some of our deities have afflicted you with evil (driven you mad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 44,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Afflict (With Calamity)",
      "hw": "Jinn affliction",
      "s": "« » is used when an affliction (illness) is related to the mind. If the affliction (illness) is related to the body, the word « » is used. (1 verse: 2:275)",
      "d": "«ثَوَاب» «یَثُوْبُ اِلَیْہِ النَّاس»\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَاِذۡ جَعَلۡنَا الۡبَیۡتَ مَثَابَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ اَمۡنًا»\nTranslation: And when we made the House a place of gathering and safety for the people.\nBy this analogy, the reward that a person gets for his deeds is called thawab (from maf). Although its usage can be for both good and evil, but generally it comes for the good reward of good deeds.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَاٰتٰىہُمُ اللّٰہُ ثَوَابَ الدُّنۡیَا وَ حُسۡنَ ثَوَابِ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ»\nTranslation: So Allah gave them the reward of the world and will give them the best reward of the Hereafter.\nAt another place, the divine decree is:\n«ہَلۡ  ثُوِّبَ الۡکُفَّارُ  مَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡعَلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: So the disbelievers got the full reward for what they used to do.\nIn this verse, the word thawab is used sarcastically."
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "a": "عَزَلَ",
      "arabic_raw": "عزل",
      "ayaat": [
        [
          11,
          42
