          51
        ]
      ],
      "hw": "",
      "h": "«حِجْر» is used for a barrier that keeps something safe from other things (3 verses: 6:138-25:22-25:53)",
      "s": "« » means to hold and not let diminish, used for every thing worthy of preservation (2 verses: 69:12-70:18)",
      "d": "«بغض» «وَدُّوا۟ لَوْ تَكْفُرُونَ كَمَا كَفَرُوا۟ فَتَكُونُونَ سَوَآءًۭ ۖ فَلَا تَتَّخِذُوا۟ مِنْهُمْ أَوْلِيَآءَ حَتَّىٰ يُهَاجِرُوا۟ فِى سَبِيلِ ٱللَّهِ ۚ فَإِن تَوَلَّوْا۟ فَخُذُوهُمْ وَٱقْتُلُوهُمْ حَيْثُ وَجَدتُّمُوهُمْ ۖ وَلَا تَتَّخِذُوا۟ مِنْهُمْ وَلِيًّۭا وَلَا نَصِيرًا إِلَّا ٱلَّذِينَ يَصِلُونَ إِلَىٰ قَوْمٍۭ بَيْنَكُمْ وَبَيْنَهُم مِّيثَـٰقٌ أَوْ جَآءُوكُمْ حَصِرَتْ صُدُورُهُمْ أَن يُقَـٰتِلُوكُمْ أَوْ يُقَـٰتِلُوا۟ قَوْمَهُمْ ۚ وَلَوْ شَآءَ ٱللَّهُ لَسَلَّطَهُمْ عَلَيْكُمْ فَلَقَـٰتَلُوكُمْ ۚ فَإِنِ ٱعْتَزَلُوكُمْ فَلَمْ يُقَـٰتِلُوكُمْ وَأَلْقَوْا۟ إِلَيْكُمُ ٱلسَّلَمَ فَمَا جَعَلَ ٱللَّهُ لَكُمْ عَلَيْهِمْ سَبِيلًۭا سَوْفَ تَجِدُونَ ءَاخَرِينَ يُرِيدُونَ أَن يَأْمَنُوكُمْ وَيَأْمَنُوا۟ قَوْمَهُمْ كُلَّ مَا رُدُّوٓا۟ إِلَى ٱلْفِتْنَةِ أُرْكِسُوا۟ فِيهَا ۚ فَإِن لَّمْ يَعْتَزِلُوكُمْ وَيُلْقُوٓا۟ إِلَيْكُمُ ٱلسَّلَمَ وَيَكُفُّوٓا۟ أَيْدِيَهُمْ فَخُذُوهُمْ وَٱقْتُلُوهُمْ حَيْثُ ثَقِفْتُمُوهُمْ ۚ وَأُو۟لَـٰٓئِكُمْ جَعَلْنَا لَكُمْ عَلَيْهِمْ سُلْطَـٰنًۭا مُّبِينًۭا»"
    }
  ],
  "12": [
    {
      "id": 47,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to burn (fire); to kindle",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » means to light a fire with fuel. (6 verses: 2:17, 5:64, 24:35, 28:38, 36:80, 104:6)",
      "d": "«وَقَدَ» «کَلِمَۃٌ تَدُلُّ عَلیٰ اِشْتِعَالِ النَّار»\nWhereas « » comes in the meaning of lighting a fire, when flames begin to appear.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَوۡقِدۡ لِیۡ یٰہَامٰنُ عَلَی الطِّیۡنِ فَاجۡعَلۡ  لِّیۡ صَرۡحًا»\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said) O Haman! Light a fire for me upon the clay, then make for me a lofty palace.\n« » is also used metaphorically.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ اَوۡقَدُوۡا  نَارًا لِّلۡحَرۡبِ اَطۡفَاَہَا اللّٰہُ»\nTranslation: Whenever they kindle a fire for war, Allah extinguishes it.\nAnd « » means to gather fuel, etc., and light a fire or lamp with great effort (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَثَلُہُمۡ کَمَثَلِ الَّذِی اسۡتَوۡقَدَ نَارًا ۚ  فَلَمَّاۤ اَضَآءَتۡ مَا حَوۡلَہٗ ذَہَبَ اللّٰہُ بِنُوۡرِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: Their example is like that of one who kindled a fire. Then when it illuminated what was around him, Allah took away their light."
    },
    {
      "id": 48,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to blaze (fire)",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » means when fire blazes intensely but without a flame. (2 verses: 70:15, 92:14)",
      "d": "«لَظٰی» «لَظَّی النَّار» «تَلَظّٰی»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَنۡذَرۡتُکُمۡ  نَارًا تَلَظّٰی»\nTranslation: So I have warned you of a blazing fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 49,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "ember of fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » is an ember upon which ash has settled and its glow has ended. (1 verse: 28:29)",
      "d": "« » is an ember upon which ash has settled and its glow has ended. (muf)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنِّیۡۤ  اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِخَبَرٍ اَوۡ جَذۡوَۃٍ مِّنَ النَّارِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, I have seen a fire, so I may bring you from it a report or a burning ember from the fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 50,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to burn (other things) with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » means to burn something with fire until it becomes ashes. (3 verses: 20:97, 21:68, 29:24)",
      "d": "«حَرَقَ» «حَرَّقَ بِالنَّار» «اِحْتَرَقَ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡاحَرِّقُوۡہُ وَانۡصُرُوۡۤا اٰلِہَتَکُمۡ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ فٰعِلِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: They said, 'Burn him and support your gods if you are to act.'\nAnother instance where the Lord's command is:\n«فَاَصَابَہَاۤ اِعۡصَارٌ فِیۡہِ نَارٌ فَاحۡتَرَقَتۡ»\nTranslation: So a hurricane with fire struck it, and it burned (and became a heap of ashes)."
    },
    {
      "id": 51,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to extinguish and be extinguished (fire)",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » means the extinction of a flame and the settling of ash upon the ember. This is an intermediate state. (1 verse: 17:97)",
      "d": "« » means for a fire's flame to become subdued and for ash to settle upon the coal or ember. (muf)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَا خَبَتۡ زِدۡنٰہُمۡ سَعِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: Whenever its fire dies down, We will increase it with blazing fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 52,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to extinguish and be extinguished (fire)",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » means the extinction of a flame. (2 verses: 21:15, 36:29)",
      "d": "«خَمَدَ» «خَمِدَتِ الْحُمّٰی» «خُمُوْد»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ کَانَتۡ  اِلَّا صَیۡحَۃً وَّاحِدَۃً  فَاِذَا ہُمۡ خٰمِدُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then it was not but a single blast, and suddenly they were extinguished (or dead)."
    },
    {
      "id": 53,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to blaze (fire); to intensify",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » means to increase the intensity of a fire's blaze. (2 verses: 40:72, 81:6)",
      "d": "«سَجَّرَ» «سَجَّرَ الْتَّنُّوْر» «سَجْر»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الۡبَحۡرِالۡمَسۡجُوۡرِ»\nTranslation: And the blazing sea.\nThis means the sea is both full and boiling with turmoil. « » refers to the fuel with which the oven is heated (menj). Thus, anything that is thrown into a fire to intensify it is called « ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فِی الۡحَمِیۡمِ ۬ ۙ ثُمَّ  فِی النَّارِ  یُسۡجَرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: They will be thrown into scorching water, then into the Fire, where they will be intensely blazed."
    },
    {
      "id": 55,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Ember of fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » A glowing, flaming ember (5 verses: 15:18-27:7-37:10-72:8-72:9)",
      "d": "« » refers to an ember that possesses both glow and flame, whether it is a fire ember or found in space (mufrad). Its plural is « ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّاَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّشُہُبًا»\nTranslation: (The jinn said) And indeed we touched the heaven and found it filled with severe guards and embers."
    },
    {
      "id": 57,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Burning other things with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » Fire with such intense heat that it roasts meat and melts fat (1 verse: 22:20)",
      "d": "« » means to heat and melt fat, etc., and « » means melted substance. A piece of fat, the marrow of a bone, and « » means one who melts or roasts meat (mufrad, manjad). Thus, « » requires such intense heat as is needed to melt substances, especially fat, and to cook meat.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُصَبُّ مِنۡ فَوۡقِ رُءُوۡسِہُمُ الۡحَمِیۡمُ ۔ یُصۡہَرُ  بِہٖ  مَا فِیۡ  بُطُوۡنِہِمۡ  وَ الۡجُلُوۡدُ»\nTranslation: Scalding water will be poured over their heads. It will melt what is in their bellies and their skins."
    },
    {
      "id": 58,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Ember of fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » A requested fire ember or flame (2 verses: 20:10-27:7)",
      "d": "« » means a requested fire ember or flame. For detailed explanation, see the entry for 'Lighting fire'."
    },
    {
      "id": 59,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Ignite Fire / To Burn",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » means to light fire from fire. (2 verses: 20:10, 27:7)",
      "d": "«قَبَسَ» «قَبَس» «قَابِس» «قَبَسَہُ النَّار» «اَقْبَسَ فُلَانًا»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنِّیۡۤ اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِقَبَسٍ  اَوۡ  اَجِدُ  عَلَی النَّارِ  ہُدًی»\nTranslation: Indeed, I have seen a fire; perhaps I can bring you from it a torch or find at the fire some guidance.\n«قَبَس» «جَذْوَۃٌ مِنَ النَّار»\n«قَبَسَ» «قَبَسَ الْعِلْم» «اِقْتَبَسَ مِنْہُ النَّارَ وَالنُّور وَالْعِلْم»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لِلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا انۡظُرُوۡنَا نَقۡتَبِسۡ مِنۡ نُّوۡرِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: O you who have believed, look at us; we would like to borrow some of your light.\nAnd in our language, the word 'iqtabas' ( ) means to take a part or piece from someone's scholarly writing or book and present it."
    },
    {
      "id": 60,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Lighting fire; to be lit",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » The initial attempt or effort to light fire (1 verse: 100:2)",
      "d": "« » means to produce fire by striking flint (manjad). Thus, the word « » is limited to the attempt and intention of producing fire only."
    },
    {
      "id": 61,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Burning other things with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » Fire or hot wind scorching the face or skin, ruining the appearance (1 verse: 23:104)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is that fire or hot wind scorches the face or skin (muf, manjad), ruining the appearance. It is as if this is a second-degree wind.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«تَلۡفَحُ وُجُوۡہَہُمُ النَّارُ وَ ہُمۡ فِیۡہَا کٰلِحُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: The fire of Hell will scorch their faces, and they will be grimacing therein."
    },
    {
      "id": 62,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Burning other things with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » Skin turning black from the heat of fire or the sun's scorching (1 verse: 74:29)",
      "d": "« » refers only to the skin turning blackish in color. Whether this happens from fire, heat, sun, thirst, or travel (manjad). That is, fire or heat touches someone in such a way that their complexion turns blackish. And « » means to heat something with fire (manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ»\nTranslation: (The fire of Hell) will blacken the skin (by scorching it)."
    },
    {
      "id": 63,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » Used for every kind of fire (138 verses: 2:17-2:24-2:39-2:80-2:81-2:126-2:167-2:174-2:175-2:201-2:217-2:221-2:257-2:266-2:275-3:10-3:16-3:24-3:103-3:116-3:131-3:151-3:183-3:185-3:191-3:192-4:10-4:14-4:30-4:56-4:145-5:29-5:37-5:64-5:72-6:27-6:128-7:12-7:36-7:38-7:44-7:47-7:50-8:14-9:17-9:35-9:63-9:68-9:81-9:109-10:8-10:27-11:16-11:17-11:98-11:106-11:113-13:5-13:17-13:35-14:30-14:50-15:27-16:62-18:29-18:53-18:96-20:10-21:39-21:69-22:19-22:72-23:104-24:35-24:57-27:7-27:8-27:90-28:29-28:41-29:24-29:25-32:20-33:66-34:42-35:36-36:80-38:27-38:59-38:61-38:64-38:76-39:8-39:16-39:19-40:6-40:41-40:43-40:46-40:47-40:49-40:72-41:19-41:24-41:28-41:40-45:34-46:20-46:34-47:12-47:15-51:13-52:13-52:14-54:48-55:15-55:35-56:71-57:15-58:17-59:3-59:17-59:20-64:10-66:6-66:10-71:25-72:23-74:31-85:5-87:12-88:4-90:20-92:14-98:6-101:11-104:6-111:3)",
      "d": "The word « » is general. It applies to all kinds of fire—whether blazing, intense, or dying, with flame or without. Whereas « » refers to a severely hot, blazing fire that has no flame (al-khalis min al-lahab, f.l. 56).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کَلَّا ؕ اِنَّہَا  لَظٰی ۔ نَزَّاعَۃً   لِّلشَّوٰی»\nTranslation: No! Indeed, it is a blazing fire. A remover of the scalp."
    },
    {
      "id": 64,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Burning other things with fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » Meat cooking solely from the heat of fire (1 verse: 4:56)",
      "d": "« » means meat cooking due to intense heat (mufrad) to the extent that its parts begin to separate. (This is a fourth-degree heat.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«سَوۡفَ نُصۡلِیۡہِمۡ نَارًا ؕ کُلَّمَا نَضِجَتۡ جُلُوۡدُہُمۡ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ جُلُوۡدًا غَیۡرَہَا»\nTranslation: We will surely admit them into the Fire. Every time their skins are roasted through, We will replace them with other skins."
    }
  ],
  "13": [
    {
      "id": 66,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » Used for giving news (2 verses: 6:109-18:19)",
      "d": "« » is used for giving news.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَابۡعَثُوۡۤا اَحَدَکُمۡ بِوَرِقِکُمۡ ہٰذِہٖۤ  اِلَی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ فَلۡیَنۡظُرۡ اَیُّہَاۤ اَزۡکٰی طَعَامًا فَلۡیَاۡتِکُمۡ بِرِزۡقٍ مِّنۡہُ  وَ لۡـیَؔ‍‍‍تَلَطَّفۡ وَ لَا یُشۡعِرَنَّ بِکُمۡ اَحَدًا»\nTranslation: (The people of the Cave, after a long sleep, awoke and began to talk among themselves) So send one of you with these silver coins of yours to the city. Let him look for which food is purest and bring you provision from it. And let him be gentle and not inform anyone about you."
    },
    {
      "id": 68,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » to reveal hidden news (2 verses: 66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "« » means to reveal something that was hidden.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«عٰلِمُ الۡغَیۡبِ فَلَا یُظۡہِرُ عَلٰی غَیۡبِہٖۤ اَحَدًا»\nTranslation: (He is Allah,) the Knower of the unseen, and He does not reveal His unseen to anyone."
    },
    {
      "id": 70,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » to tell something new (8 verses: 2:76-18:70-20:113-21:2-26:5-65:1-93:11-99:4)",
      "d": "« » means for something to occur or come into existence. It signifies something being new or the coming into being of a new thing or news (Munjid). According to Ibn al-Faris, it means 'the coming into existence of a thing that was not.' Thus, it refers to the coming into existence or manifestation of something that did not previously exist (M.L.). And the meaning of « » is to inform someone of something they did not know before, or at least the informant believes it to be so.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا لَقُوا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا  ۚ ۖ  وَ اِذَا خَلَا بَعۡضُہُمۡ  اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ قَالُوۡۤا اَتُحَدِّثُوۡنَہُمۡ بِمَا فَتَحَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ لِیُحَآجُّوۡکُمۡ بِہٖ عِنۡدَ رَبِّکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And when they (the Jews) meet those who believe, they say, 'We believe,' but when they are alone with one another, they say, 'Do you (O Muhammad) inform them (the believers) of what Allah has revealed to you so that they may argue with you about it before your Lord?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 72,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to guide",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » to show the way. To inform of something or to guide (5 verses: 20:40-20:120-28:12-34:7-61:10)",
      "d": "« » means to guide, to show the path, to inform of something, and 'dalalat' means by which the knowledge or recognition of something is obtained, such as words indicating meanings. Or, when something begins to move, a person understands that it is a living creature, so its movement indicates life (Maf). The word « » is used in both material and spiritual senses.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَمۡشِیۡۤ اُخۡتُکَ فَتَقُوۡلُ ہُلۡ اَدُلُّکُمۡ  عَلٰی مَنۡ  یَّکۡفُلُہٗ»\nTranslation: And (O Moses) your sister went and said, 'Shall I point out to you someone who will be responsible for him?'\nAt another place, the Divine declaration states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا ہُلۡ اَدُلُّکُمۡ عَلٰی تِجَارَۃٍ  تُنۡجِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡ عَذَابٍ اَلِیۡمٍ»\nTranslation: O you who have believed, shall I guide you to a transaction that will save you from a painful punishment?"
    },
    {
      "id": 73,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to become aware",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » to understand the subtleties and delicacy of a matter; to reach the depth of a matter. (27 verses: 2:9-2:12-2:154-3:69-6:26-6:109-6:123-7:95-12:15-12:107-16:21-16:26-16:45-18:19-23:56-26:113-26:202-27:18-27:50-27:65-28:9-28:11-29:53-39:25-39:55-43:66-49:2)",
      "d": "« » means hair, so « » means to acquire knowledge as fine as hair (Maf). To understand the subtleties and delicacy of a matter, or to deduce from circumstances and events, and reaching the depth of a matter is called « ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَاۤ اِنَّہُمۡ ہُمُ الۡمُفۡسِدُوۡنَ وَ لٰکِنۡ لَّا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Behold! They themselves are the corrupters, but they perceive not."
    },
    {
      "id": 74,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to become aware",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » this refers to knowledge obtained entirely from apparent circumstances and events. (27 verses: 2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "« » has two basic meanings: (1) 'strength' (2) to be evident (M.L.). Here it relates to the second meaning, the opposite of which is 'internal' (batn). Thus, « » refers to knowledge obtained entirely from apparent circumstances and events.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَوِ الطِّفۡلِ الَّذِیۡنَ لَمۡ  یَظۡہَرُوۡا عَلٰی عَوۡرٰتِ النِّسَآءِ»\nTranslation: or the children who have not yet become aware of the private aspects of women."
    },
    {
      "id": 75,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to become aware",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » to learn of something unintentionally through conversations. (2 verses: 5:107-18:21)",
      "d": "« » means to become aware of something that is learned unintentionally through conversations (Maf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ عُثِرَ عَلٰۤی اَنَّہُمَا اسۡتَحَقَّاۤ اِثۡمًا»\nTranslation: Then if it is discovered that they both (the two witnesses) have merited sin (by bearing false witness)."
    },
    {
      "id": 76,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » to make someone understand through signs and indications. (19 verses: 2:89-2:146-2:273-5:83-6:20-7:46-7:48-12:58-12:62-16:83-22:72-23:69-27:93-33:59-47:6-47:30-55:41-66:3-83:24)",
      "d": "« » means to recognize or identify something by reflecting on its signs and indications (Maf). It is evident that in recognition, a person can sometimes make mistakes; therefore, the level of 'ma'rifat' (recognition) is lower than 'ilm' (knowledge), and the opposite of 'ma'rifat' is 'inkar' (denial).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَعَرَفَہُمۡ  وَ ہُمۡ  لَہٗ  مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: So he (Prophet Yusuf) recognized them, but they did not recognize him.\nFurthermore, « » also means to perfume, and « » means to perfume or to leave a fragrance behind (Maf, Munjid). However, the general meaning of « » is to make someone familiar, to introduce, or to inform.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یُدۡخِلُہُمُ  الۡجَنَّۃَ  عَرَّفَہَا  لَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And He will admit them to Paradise, which He has made known to them.\nAnd Imam Raghib has translated it as: And Allah has made Paradise fragrant for them (Maf)."
    },
    {
      "id": 77,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to become aware",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » to obtain certainty regarding the reality of something. (20 verses: 2:60-2:65-2:102-2:187-2:235-7:160-8:23-8:66-12:21-12:37-24:41-45:9-48:18-48:27-50:4-56:62-60:10-73:20-81:14-82:5)",
      "d": "« » If familiarity with the reality of something reaches the level of certainty, that familiarity is called 'ilm' (knowledge), and its opposite is 'jahil' (ignorance).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ عَلِمُوۡا لَمَنِ اشۡتَرٰىہُ مَا لَہٗ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ مِنۡ خَلَاقٍ»\nTranslation: And they (the Jews) certainly knew that whoever purchased that (sorcery) would have no share in the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 78,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to inform (to tell)",
      "hw": "Aware",
      "s": "« » used in the meaning of teaching someone knowledge. (1 verse: 49:16)",
      "d": "« » is used in the meaning of teaching someone knowledge.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ اَتُعَلِّمُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ بِدِیۡنِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: Say (O Prophet), 'Do you (pretend to) teach Allah about your religion?'"
    }
  ],
  "14": [
    {
      "id": 79,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "to send ahead",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "« » for an action to pass by; generally used for predecessors (ancestors) as well. (8 verses: 2:275-4:22-4:23-5:95-8:38-10:30-43:56-69:24)",
      "d": "« » means for something or an action to pass by (M. A.). For example: In Islamic jurisprudence, 'bay' salf' refers to a sale where the price is paid in advance. And 'aslaf' refers to generations that have passed in previous times. Past ancestors (Munjid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِلَّا مَا قَدۡ سَلَفَ»\nTranslation: Except what has already passed.\nFurthermore, « » also has the meaning of 'to advance' (M.L., Munjid). « » means one who is ahead, one who proceeds. « » means a group of predecessors (Munjid). And « » means an action that occurred in past time.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ہُنَالِکَ تَبۡلُوۡا کُلُّ نَفۡسٍ مَّاۤ  اَسۡلَفَتۡ»\nTranslation: (1) There, every soul will be tested in what it has sent ahead (of deeds).\nTranslation: (2) There, every soul will be examined for what it had done previously. (Translation by Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 80,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Approaching",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "« » is used to mean turning towards someone and being attentive (8 verses: 12:71-28:31-37:27-37:50-37:94-51:29-52:25-68:30)",
      "d": "«اِقْبَال» «اِسْتِقْبَال» «فَاَقۡبَلَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ یَّتَلَاوَمُوۡنَ» «فَلَمَّا رَاَوۡہُ عَارِضًا مُّسۡتَقۡبِلَ اَوۡدِیَتِہِمۡ ۙ قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا عَارِضٌ مُّمۡطِرُنَا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 81,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Ahead; In Front",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "«بَیْنَ یَدَیْ ، بَیْنَ اَیْدِیْ»",
      "d": "«بَیْنَ یَدَیْ ، بَیْنَ اَیْدِیْ» «خَلَف» «فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا نَکَالًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہَا وَ مَا خَلۡفَہَا» «لَہٗ مُعَقِّبٰتٌ مِّنۡۢ بَیۡنِ یَدَیۡہِ وَ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ  یَحۡفَظُوۡنَہٗ  مِنۡ اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 82,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Advancing",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "« » conveys the meaning of advancing ahead of others in a contest (21 verses: 7:80-8:59-8:68-10:19-11:40-11:110-15:5-20:99-20:199-21:27-21:101-23:27-23:43-29:4-29:28-37:171-41:45-42:14-46:11-59:10-79:4)",
      "d": "«سَبَقَ» «السَّبْقُ» «سَابِق» «سَبَّقَ» «سَبْق» «رَبَّنَا اغۡفِرۡ لَنَا وَ لِاِخۡوَانِنَا الَّذِیۡنَ سَبَقُوۡنَا بِالۡاِیۡمَانِ» «اِسْتَبَقَ» «وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 83,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Ahead; In Front",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "«قُبُل» «بَیْنَ یَدَی»",
      "d": "«قُبْل» «دُبُر» «دُبْر» «وَلَوۡ اَنَّنَا نَزَّلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہِمُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ وَ کَلَّمَہُمُ الۡمَوۡتٰی وَ حَشَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ قُبُلًا مَّا کَانُوۡا لِیُؤۡمِنُوۡۤا» «قِبَل» «قِبَل» «بَاطِنُہٗ فِیۡہِ الرَّحۡمَۃُ وَ ظَاہِرُہٗ مِنۡ قِبَلِہِ الۡعَذَابُ» «اَوۡ تَاۡتِیَ بِاللّٰہِ  وَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ  قَبِیۡلًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 84,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Advancing",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "« » means only to walk forward or advance, while « » means to advance ahead of others in a contest, and « » means to turn towards someone or something and advance. (14 verses: 7:34-10:2-10:49-11:98-15:24-16:61-25:23-34:30-38:60-38:61-49:1-58:12-58:13-74:37)",
      "d": "«قَدَمَ» «یَقۡدُمُ  قَوۡمَہٗ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ فَاَوۡرَدَہُمُ النَّارَ» «اِسْتَقْدَمَ» «اِسْتَاخَرَ» «اِذَا جَآءَ اَجَلُہُمۡ فَلَا یَسۡتَاۡخِرُوۡنَ سَاعَۃً وَّ لَا  یَسۡتَقۡدِمُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 85,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sending Ahead",
      "hw": "آگے",
      "s": "« » means to do an act before its due time. (23 verses: 2:95-2:110-2:223-3:182-4:62-5:80-8:51-18:57-22:10-26:76-28:47-30:36-36:12-42:48-48:2-50:28-59:18-62:7-73:20-75:13-78:40-82:5-89:24)",
      "d": "«قَدَّمَ» «اَخَّرَ» «وَ لَنۡ یَّتَمَنَّوۡہُ اَبَدًۢا بِمَا قَدَّمَتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ» «قَدَّمَ» «قَالَ  لَا تَخۡتَصِمُوۡا لَدَیَّ وَ قَدۡ قَدَّمۡتُ اِلَیۡکُمۡ  بِالۡوَعِیۡدِ» «اَسْلَفَ» «اِرْتَفَاع» «عَمَق» «قَدَّمَ» «اَسْلَفَ» «کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا ہَنِیۡٓـئًۢا بِمَاۤ  اَسۡلَفۡتُمۡ فِی الۡاَیَّامِ الۡخَالِیَۃِ» «بِمَا قَدَّمَتْ اَیْدِیْکُمْ»"
    }
  ],
  "15": [
    {
      "id": 86,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Weapons of War",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "« » means all kinds of war equipment. It is a specific word for war equipment. (1 verse: 4:102)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». And everything that is a weapon with which fighting can be done is 'silah' (Lane's Lexicon). Thus, this word is specific for war weapons, whether they are an axe, spear, sword, or rifle and missile.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَدَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوْا لَوۡ تَغۡفُلُوۡنَ عَنۡ اَسۡلِحَتِکُمۡ وَ اَمۡتِعَتِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: But those who disbelieve wish that you would neglect your weapons and your baggage so they could swoop down upon you in a single attack."
    },
    {
      "id": 87,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Weapons",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "« » means weapons. If related to war, they are weapons of war; otherwise not. (11 verses: 6:31-6:164-16:25-17:15-20:87-20:100-35:18-39:7-47:4-53:38-94:2)",
      "d": "«اَوْزَار» «وِزْر» «وِزْرُالْحَرْب» «وِرْز» «حَتّٰی تَضَعَ الۡحَرۡبُ اَوۡزَارَہَا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 88,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Defensive Gear",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "« » if used in the context of war, it means defensive war equipment. (17 verses: 2:19-2:235-2:243-3:28-3:30-4:71-4:102-5:41-5:49-5:92-9:64-9:122-24:63-28:6-39:9-63:4-64:14)",
      "d": "«حِذْر» «حِذْر» «وَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِنۡ کَانَ بِکُمۡ اَذًی مِّنۡ مَّطَرٍاَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَنۡ تَضَعُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَکُمۡ ۚ وَ خُذُوۡاحِذۡرَکُمۡ» «خُذُوْا» «حِذْر»"
    },
    {
      "id": 89,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Offensive Weapons",
      "hw": "جنگ",
      "s": "« » means offensive weapons for aggressive fighting. (1 verse: 8:7)",
      "d": "«شَوْک» «درمثَاکَ» «شَوْکَۃ» «اَشْوَاک» «ذُوْشَوْکَۃ» «شَوْک» «وَ تَوَدُّوۡنَ اَنَّ غَیۡرِ ذَاتِ الشَّوۡکَۃِ تَکُوۡنُ لَکُمۡ»"
    }
  ],
  "16": [
    {
      "id": 90,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Come",
      "hw": "To come",
      "s": "« » (Atā) is used for something coming as a result of another action or coming with ease. (164 verses: 2:38-2:85-2:118-2:189-2:210-2:214-2:222-2:223-2:248-2:254-2:260-3:125-4:15-4:16-4:19-4:25-4:102-5:41-6:4-6:5-6:34-6:40-6:47-6:130-6:134-6:158-7:17-7:35-7:53-7:80-7:81-7:97-7:98-7:106-7:129-7:138-7:163-7:187-9:54-9:70-9:92-10:24-10:50-11:8-11:76-11:39-11:93-11:105-12:37-12:48-12:49-12:93-12:107-13:31-13:41-14:9-14:17-14:31-14:44-15:11-15:85-15:99-16:1-16:26-16:33-16:45-16:111-16:112-18:19-18:55-18:77-19:38-19:43-19:61-19:93-19:95-20:9-20:11-20:15-20:47-20:60-20:69-20:74-20:75-20:123-20:126-20:133-21:2-21:3-21:40-21:44-22:7-22:27-22:55-23:68-24:49-25:40-26:5-26:6-26:16-26:89-26:154-26:165-26:202-27:18-27:31-27:38-27:54-27:55-27:87-27:92-28:30-28:46-29:5-29:28-29:29-29:53-30:43-32:3-33:14-33:18-33:20-33:30-34:3-36:30-36:46-37:28-38:21-39:25-39:40-39:54-39:55-39:71-40:22-40:35-40:50-40:56-40:59-41:11-41:40-41:42-42:47-43:7-43:66-47:18-51:24-51:42-51:52-59:2-60:12-61:6-63:10-64:5-64:6-65:1-67:8-71:1-74:47-76:1-78:18-79:15-85:17-88:1-98:1)",
      "d": "« » and « » is the reward that is predetermined by a prior covenant or at the time of need, « » (the reward-giver) announces the reward and « » (the one to whom reward is given) accepts and starts the work. This is the reward for work. And it is generally used for beneficial reward. The word ajr is used for both religious and worldly rewards, but ujrah is generally used for worldly reward. And « » refers to the one who takes work, and « » refers to the one who gives work, servant, or the one who receives reward (from maf). And « » means to hire someone as a laborer or servant; the use of ajr is mentioned in the Quran in both religious and worldly contexts.\nExample (1): In the Quran it is:\n«وَلَاَجۡرُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ خَیۡرٌ لِّلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَکَانُوۡا یَتَّقُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And for those who believed and were cautious, the reward of the Hereafter is better.\nExample (2): In the Quran it is:\n«قَالَ اِنِّیۡۤ  اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اُنۡکِحَکَ اِحۡدَی ابۡنَتَیَّ ہٰتَیۡنِ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ تَاۡجُرَنِیۡ ثَمٰنِیَ حِجَجٍ»\nTranslation: He said, \"Indeed, I wish to marry one of my two daughters to you on the condition that you serve me for eight years.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 91,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Come",
      "hw": "To come",
      "s": "« » (Ta'āl) is used for summoning someone towards a lofty purpose or with respect. (8 verses: 3:61-3:64-3:167-4:61-5:104-6:151-33:28-63:5)",
      "d": "« » has its origin in ( ). It has two basic meanings.\nFirst meaning: « » means the number ten; second meaning: mixing and interference (m l) i.e., to live together and mingle with each other. And to interfere. From this, the word « » is derived, which means tribe, and « » means to live together as a clan or family.\nFor example, in the Quran, men who have complaints about their wives are commanded:\n«وَعَاشِرُوْھُنَّ بِالْمَعْرُوْفِ»\nTranslation: And live with them in a fair manner."
    },
    {
      "id": 92,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Come",
      "hw": "To come",
      "s": "« » (Jā'a) means 'to come'. For its usage, it is necessary that the act of coming has already occurred factually. (216 verses: 2:87-2:89-2:92-2:101-2:120-2:145-2:209-2:211-2:213-2:253-2:275-3:19-3:61-3:81-3:86-3:105-3:183-3:184-4:43-4:62-4:64-4:83-4:90-4:153-4:170-4:174-5:6-5:15-5:19-5:32-5:42-5:48-5:61-5:70-5:84-6:5-6:25-6:31-6:34-6:43-6:54-6:61-6:104-6:109-6:124-6:157-6:160-7:4-7:5-7:34-7:37-7:43-7:53-7:63-7:69-7:73-7:85-7:101-7:113-7:116-7:126-7:131-7:143-8:19-9:48-9:90-9:128-10:13-10:22-10:47-10:49-10:57-10:74-10:76-10:77-10:80-10:93-10:94-10:97-10:108-11:12-11:40-11:58-11:66-11:69-11:74-11:76-11:77-11:78-11:82-11:94-11:101-11:120-12:16-12:19-12:50-12:58-12:96-13:37-14:9-15:61-15:67-16:61-16:113-17:5-17:7-17:81-17:94-17:101-17:104-18:55-18:98-19:43-20:72-23:27-23:44-23:68-23:70-23:99-24:39-25:29-26:41-26:206-27:28-27:13-27:36-27:42-27:84-27:89-27:90-28:20-28:25-28:36-28:37-28:48-28:84-28:85-29:10-29:31-29:33-29:39-29:53-29:68-30:9-30:47-33:9-33:10-33:19-34:32-34:43-34:49-35:25-35:37-35:42-35:45-36:13-36:20-37:37-37:84-38:4-39:32-39:33-39:59-39:71-39:73-40:25-40:28-40:29-40:34-40:66-40:78-40:83-41:14-41:20-41:41-42:14-43:29-43:30-43:38-43:47-43:53-43:63-44:13-44:17-45:17-46:7-47:18-49:6-50:2-50:5-50:19-50:21-50:33-51:26-53:23-54:4-54:41-57:14-58:8-59:10-60:1-60:10-60:12-61:6-63:1-63:11-67:9-69:9-71:4-79:34-80:2-80:8-80:33-89:22-98:4-110:1)",
      "d": "« » (Jā'a) is the general term for 'to come'. However, for its usage, it is necessary that the act of coming has already occurred factually (Mufradat).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ جَآءُوۡۤ  اَبَاہُمۡ  عِشَآءً  یَّبۡکُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And they (the brothers of Yusuf) came to their father at night, weeping."
    }
  ],
  "17": [
    {
      "id": 95,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Eye",
      "hw": "Eye",
      "s": "« » (Baṣar) includes both the physical eye and spiritual insight. (82 verses: 2:7-2:17-2:20-3:13-6:46-6:103-6:104-6:110-7:47-7:179-7:195-7:198-7:201-10:31-10:43-10:67-11:20-14:42-15:15-16:77-16:78-16:108-17:12-17:36-17:59-18:26-19:38-19:42-20:96-21:3-21:97-22:46-23:78-24:30-24:31-24:37-24:43-24:44-27:13-27:54-27:86-28:11-28:72-29:38-32:9-32:12-32:27-33:10-36:9-36:66-37:175-37:179-38:45-38:63-40:61-41:20-41:22-43:51-45:23-46:26-47:23-50:8-50:22-51:21-52:15-53:17-54:7-54:50-56:85-59:2-67:3-67:4-67:23-68:5-68:43-68:51-69:38-69:39-70:11-70:44-75:7-79:9)",
      "d": "« » (Baṣar) includes both the physical eye and spiritual insight (Mufradat). Additionally, « » (Baṣara) is used for the act of the physical eye, i.e., seeing and looking, and then for pondering over what is seen. Examples:\nExample (1): Divine revelation states:\n«الۡحَقُّ فَاِذَا ہِیَ شَاخِصَۃٌ  اَبۡصَارُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا»\nTranslation: And when the true promise (of the Hour) draws near, the eyes of those who disbelieved will be staring in horror.\nExample (2): For 'gaze': Divine revelation states:\n«فَکَشَفۡنَا عَنۡکَ غِطَآءَکَ فَبَصَرُکَ الۡیَوۡمَ حَدِیۡدٌ»\nTranslation: Now We have removed from you your veil, so your sight today is sharp.\nExample (3): For spiritual insight: Divine revelation states:\n«وَعَلٰۤی اَبۡصَارِہِمۡ غِشَاوَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And upon their eyes is a covering.\nFrom 'Baṣar', the verbal noun 'Baṣārah' (insight) and 'Baṣīrah' (perception) are derived. 'Baṣārah' refers to physical sight, weakness in which is 'ḍaʿf al-baṣar'. 'Baṣīrah' refers to spiritual insight. A poet has clarified the difference between insight and sight:\n'Ask from Allah for a seeing heart too,\nThe light of the eye is not the light of the heart!'\nNote: (Masdar: Meaning the place of issuing forth, i.e., emerging or starting; source, origin, foundation, spring, root. Masdar: It is a noun from which other verbs can be formed, but it itself is not derived from any verb.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 96,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Eye",
      "hw": "Eye",
      "s": "« » (Ḥūr) is used for white and black eyes. In common usage, it refers to the women of Paradise. (4 verses: 44:54-52:20-55:72-56:22)",
      "d": "«مَا شَآءَ اللہُ کَانَ وَ مَا لَمْ یَشَآءُ لَمْ یَکُنْ» «یُرِیۡدُ اللّٰہُ بِکُمُ الۡیُسۡرَ وَ لَا یُرِیۡدُ بِکُمُ الۡعُسۡرَ» «وَ مَا اللّٰہُ یُرِیۡدُ ظُلۡمًا  لِّلۡعِبَادِ» «شَاءَ» «وَ مَا تَشَآءُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّشَآءَ اللّٰہُ  رَبُّ الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» «یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ  لِیُطۡفِئُوۡا  نُوۡرَ اللّٰہِ  بِاَفۡوَاہِہِمۡ وَ اللّٰہُ  مُتِمُّ  نُوۡرِہٖ  وَ لَوۡ  کَرِہَ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 97,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Eye",
      "hw": "Eye",
      "s": "The word « » ('Ayn) is used for the physical organ of sight, the eye. (35 verses: 3:13-5:45-5:83-7:116-7:179-7:195-8:44-9:92-11:31-11:37-12:84-15:88-18:28-18:86-18:101-19:26-20:39-20:40-20:131-21:61-23:27-25:74-28:9-28:13-32:17-33:19-33:51-36:66-40:19-43:71-52:48-54:14-54:37-90:8-102:7)",
      "d": "« » ('Ayn) is the well-known organ of humans with which they see, and it also means 'spring' (as in water source), wherein there are many points of similarity between the two meanings. The plural of « » is « » (A'yun) and « » ('Uyun). However, in the Quran, the plural of 'ayn (eye) is mostly « », and the plural of 'ayn (spring) is « ». The word « » is used only for the physical eye.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالۡعَیۡنَ بِالۡعَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: 'An eye for an eye' (retaliation).\nAnd in terms of qualities, two other types of eyes are mentioned in the Quran.\n« » ('Ayn) and « » (Ḥūr) are qualities of eyes. « » ('Ayn) is for large, prominent eyes, and « » (Ḥūr) is for extremely white whites and extremely black pupils. « » (Baṣar) is a word that, besides the physical organ, also means the act of seeing (gaze) and then pondering over what is seen."
    }
  ],
  "18": [
    {
      "id": 99,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Wander Aimlessly",
      "hw": "آوارہ ",
      "s": "« » (Tāha) is used for wandering in a state of bewilderment and distress. (1 verse: 5:26)",
      "d": "«تَاہَ» «جِنْسٌ مِّنَ الْحَیْرَۃ» «اَتِیَہ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاِنَّہَا مُحَرَّمَۃٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ سَنَۃً ۚ یَتِیۡہُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ»\nTranslation: Allah said, 'It will be forbidden to them for forty years; they will wander aimlessly in the land.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 100,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "To Wander Aimlessly",
      "hw": "آوارہ ",
      "s": "« » (Hām) is used for wandering due to love and passion. (1 verse: 26:225)",
      "d": "« » (Hām) means to roam in a state of frenzy. The wandering of people in the state of love (Mufradat). The author of 'Majma' writes its meaning as 'to love' and 'to wander aimlessly'.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالشُّعَرَآءُ  یَتَّبِعُہُمُ  الۡغَاوٗنَ ۔ اَلَمۡ تَرَاَنَّہُمۡ فِیۡ کُلِّ وَادٍ یَّہِیۡمُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And the poets - [only] the deviators follow them. Do you not see that in every valley they ramble aimlessly?"
    },
