  "22": [
    {
      "id": 130,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To raise; to incite",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "« » means to incite someone to an evil deed in such a way that they are unaware of it (2 Verses: 2:36-19:83)",
      "d": "« » means to incite someone to an evil deed in such a way that they are unaware of it. And to uproot someone from their place (m. l.). « » also refers to the sound of a pot boiling. This word is generally used in a negative sense.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اَنَّـاۤ اَرۡسَلۡنَا الشَّیٰطِیۡنَ عَلَی الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ تَؤُزُّہُمۡ اَزًّا»\nTranslation: Do you not see that We have appointed the devils upon the disbelievers, inciting them (to evil) continually?"
    },
    {
      "id": 131,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation; rise",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "« » refers to a small hill or mound that has no order in its height and extent (1 Verse: 20:107)",
      "d": "« » is the opposite of « » (meaning depression). « » and « » mean valleys and hills. And « » means a small hill or mound. A high place (munjad), i.e., an elevation and extent that has no order.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَّا تَرٰی فِیۡہَا عِوَجًا وَّ لَاۤ اَمۡتًا»\nTranslation: Wherein they will see no crookedness (depression) nor any mound (or elevation)."
    },
    {
      "id": 132,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To raise; to incite",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "« » is used for inciting and instigating someone towards sinful deeds (3 Verses: 5:2-5:8-40:43)",
      "d": "« » (a verbal noun) refers to sin and fault. When this verb is used, its meaning is to incite someone, to instigate them towards a grave sin, i.e., a deed that causes loss of life or is harmful. Lexicons do not support this meaning, but translations, e.g., by Jalandhari, Osmani, and Tafheem ul Quran, all confirm this meaning.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَجۡرِمَنَّکُمۡ شَنَاٰنُ قَوۡمٍ عَلَی اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا»\nTranslation: And let not the enmity of a people prevent you from being just."
    },
    {
      "id": 133,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "« » is used for a hunchback person, and also for a mound that is low in height but wide in expanse (1 verse: 21:96)",
      "d": "«حَدَبَ الرَّجُل» «حَدَب» «مُحَدَّب against مُجَوَّف» «مُحَدَّب» «حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا  فُتِحَتۡ یَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ مَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ ہُمۡ  مِّنۡ  کُلِّ  حَدَبٍ  یَّنۡسِلُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 134,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To raise; to incite",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "« » means to become severely ill, to waste away, and to be near death (3 Verses: 4:84-8:65-12:85)",
      "d": "« » means to become severely ill, to waste away, and to be near death (m. l., m. q.).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: (Jacob's sons said to their father): They said, \"By Allah, you will not cease to remember Joseph until you become ill (from grief) or become of those who perish.\"\nAnd « » means to exhort towards something, the neglect of which causes destruction and ruin (m. l.). That is, to incite someone towards such a deed, or to create eagerness for it, that if it is not done, it leads to destruction and ruin.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّبِیُّ حَرِّضِ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ عَلَی الۡقِتَالِ ؕ اِنۡ یَّکُنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ عِشۡرُوۡنَ صٰبِرُوۡنَ یَغۡلِبُوۡا مِائَتَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: O Prophet! Exhort the believers to fight. If there are twenty steadfast among you, they will overcome two hundred."
    },
    {
      "id": 136,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation; rise",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "« » means to make something thick and high, such as the height and thickness of a roof (1 Verse: 79:28)",
      "d": "«سَمْک» «سَمْک» «سَنَامٌ سَامِکٌ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَشَدُّ خَلۡقًا اَمِ السَّمَآءُ ؕ بَنٰہَا رَفَعَ سَمۡکَہَا فَسَوّٰىہَا»\nTranslation: Is your creation harder or the creation of the heaven? He raised its height and made it even."
    },
    {
      "id": 137,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation; rise",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "« » refers to a protruding bone. In the Noble Quran, this word was used for the ankle and for the houris with protruding breasts (1 Verse: 78:33)",
      "d": "«کَعَبْ» «کَعَبَتِ الْجَارِیَۃ» «کُعَب» «کاعِب» «کَوَاعِب»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ مَفَازًا حَدَآئِقَ وَ اَعۡنَابًا وَّکَوَاعِبَ اَتۡرَابًا»\nTranslation: Indeed, for the righteous is attainment (of Paradise), gardens and grapevines and full-bosomed maidens of equal age.\nIf the extent and height of an elevation are approximately equal, it is called « » and « »; the only difference is in quantity (mass). If the extent is more and the height is less, it is « ». If the extent is less and the height is more, it is « ». And if there is no order or proportion in height and extent, it is « »."
    },
    {
      "id": 138,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Elevation; rise",
      "hw": "اُبھار",
      "s": "« » is used for land that is hard and high and has no trees, etc. (1 Verse: 90:10)",
      "d": "« » means hard, high land with no trees, etc. Like 'k'ab', it is a large hill. It also means a small mountain, a valley, and the path for ascending and descending. Also, meanings related to a woman's breasts are found (munjad, m. q.). And the word « » is used idiomatically for a woman's two breasts, for the contrast between truth and falsehood, and for beautiful and ugly (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ النَّجۡدَیۡنِ . فَلَا اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ»\nTranslation: And We have shown him the two highways (of good and evil). But he has not attempted the steep path."
    }
  ],
  "23": [
    {
      "id": 139,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To bring down; to descend",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "In « », the act of bringing down occurs as a result of some good or evil deed of the one descending (2 Verses: 14:28-35:35)",
      "d": "« » means to bring someone else down to a place. And this happens as a result of an action of the one who descends. It comes in both good and bad contexts.\nFor example, for good: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوا الۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ الَّذِیۡۤ اَذۡہَبَ عَنَّا الۡحَزَنَ ؕ اِنَّ رَبَّنَا لَغَفُوۡرٌ شَکُوۡرٌ ۔ الَّذِیۡۤ اَحَلَّنَا دَارَ الۡمُقَامَۃِ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ»\nTranslation: They will say, \"All praise is for Allah, who has removed from us all sorrow. Indeed, our Lord is Forgiving and Appreciative. Who has settled us in the eternal home by His favor.\"\nAnd for evil: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡنَ بَدَّلُوۡا نِعۡمَتَ اللّٰہِ کُفۡرًا وَّاَحَلُّوۡا قَوۡمَہُمۡ دَارَالۡبَوَارِ»\nTranslation: Do you not see those who exchanged the favor of Allah for disbelief and led their people to the home of ruin?"
    },
    {
      "id": 141,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "« » is used for the purpose of settling or staying in a place (8 verses: 11:39-14:28-20:27-20:81-20:86-35:35-39:40-90:2)",
      "d": "«حَلَّ» «عَقَدَ» «اَرْبابِ حَلّ وَ عَقْد» «حَلَّ» «حَلَّ» «مَنْ جَرَّبَ الْمُجَرَّبَ حَلَّتْ بِہٖ النَّدَامَۃ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«مَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡہِ عَذَابٌ یُّخۡزِیۡہِ وَ یَحِلُّ عَلَیۡہِ عَذَابٌ مُّقِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: Upon whom comes a punishment that will disgrace him, and upon whom comes a lasting punishment?"
    },
    {
      "id": 142,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "« » is used to separate something that was previously included in it (1 verse: 20:12)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of « » is to separate something that was previously included (m. l.). The word « » also carries this meaning: a woman separates from her husband by paying compensation, and divorce occurs.\nIn the Noble Quran, this word has been used for removing shoes from the feet (taking them off).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنِّیۡۤ  اَنَا رَبُّکَ فَاخۡلَعۡ نَعۡلَیۡکَ ۚ اِنَّکَ بِالۡوَادِ الۡمُقَدَّسِ طُوًی»\nTranslation: (O Moses) Indeed, I am your Lord, so remove your sandals. You are in the sacred valley, Tuwa.\nAnd there is a strange relation in « » that in ancient civilizations, a woman was symbolized by the shoes on her feet."
    },
    {
      "id": 143,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "The word « » is general. « » is used for divine revelation, commandments, and Satanic whisperings (12 verses: 17:105-26:193-26:210-26:221-26:222-34:2-37:177-41:30-57:4-57:16-65:12-97:4)",
      "d": "The well-known meaning of « » is 'to descend.' Something coming down from a height (muf). This word is used generally. « » is also its opposite, meaning both « » (ascending) and « » (rising).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ مَا یَنۡزِلُ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ وَمَا یَعۡرُجُ فِیۡہَا»\nTranslation: And whatever descends from the heaven and whatever ascends in it.\n«تَنَزَّلَ بِہٖ» «نَزَلَ بِہٖ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«نَزَلَ بِہِ الرُّوۡحُ  الۡاَمِیۡنُ»\nTranslation: The Trustworthy Spirit descended with it.\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n« تَنَزَّلُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ وَ الرُّوۡحُ  فِیۡہَا بِاِذۡنِ رَبِّہِمۡ ۚ مِنۡ  کُلِّ  اَمۡرٍ»\nTranslation: In it (the Night of Decree), the angels and the Spirit (Al-Amin) descend with their Lord's permission for every matter.\n«تَنَزَّلَ بِہٖ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ہَلۡ اُنَبِّئُکُمۡ عَلٰی مَنۡ تَنَزَّلُ الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ تَنَزَّلُ عَلَیۡ کُلِّ اَفَّاکٍ اَثِیۡمٍ»\nTranslation: Shall I inform you upon whom the devils descend? They descend upon every lying, sinful person."
    },
    {
      "id": 144,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "« » is used for descending, falling, or coming out in a state of anger and helplessness (8 verses: 2:36-2:38-2:61-2:74-7:13-7:24-11:48-20:123)",
      "d": "« » means to come down from something in a state of anger and compulsion, or to fall, or to come out, like a stone falling from a height (muf). To come out involuntarily, to fall from one's status, and to go from height to lowliness—all are included in this meaning. Now observe some examples:\n(1) For descending from a mount:\nThe Divine command states:\n«قِیۡلَ یٰنُوۡحُ اہۡبِطۡ بِسَلٰمٍ مِّنَّا وَ بَرَکٰتٍ عَلَیۡکَ»\nTranslation: It was said, 'O Noah, descend with peace from Us and blessings upon you.'\n(2) For something descending with anxiety and fear:\nThe Divine command states:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡہَا لَمَا یَہۡبِطُ مِنۡ خَشۡیَۃِ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: And indeed, among them are those that descend (or break off) from the fear of Allah.\n(3) For coming out having fallen from one's rank (or being humiliated):\nThe Divine command states:\n«فَاَزَلَّہُمَا الشَّیۡطٰنُ عَنۡہَا فَاَخۡرَجَہُمَا مِمَّا کَانَا فِیۡہِ ۪ وَ قُلۡنَا اہۡبِطُوۡا بَعۡضُکُمۡ لِبَعۡضٍ عَدُوٌّ»\nTranslation: Then Satan caused them to slip from it (Paradise) and brought them out from what they were in. And We said, 'Descend (from here), some of you being enemies to others.'\nA poet expressed this meaning in these words:\nWe have heard of Adam's expulsion from Paradise,\nBut we came out from your lane having been greatly disgraced!"
    },
    {
      "id": 145,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to descend / to get down",
      "hw": "اتارنا ",
      "s": "« » is used for taking something down and placing it below (7 verses: 3:36-18:49-39:69-46:15-55:7-55:10-94:2)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of « » are 'to place down' (muf). The word « » is also used in the meanings of removing a burden and load, and in pregnancy, the burden is removed.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ وَضَعۡنَا عَنۡکَ وِزۡرَکَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَنۡقَضَ ظَہۡرَکَ»\nTranslation: And We have removed from you your burden which weighed down your back.\nThen this word began to be used generally for 'to take down'.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«حِیۡنَ تَضَعُوۡنَ ثِیَابَکُمۡ مِّنَ الظَّہِیۡرَۃِ»\nTranslation: And when you lay aside your clothes from the midday heat."
    }
  ],
  "24": [
    {
      "id": 146,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "« » means to walk in an arrogant manner and to consider others contemptible (3 verses: 4:36-31:18-57:23)",
      "d": "According to Ibn Faris, « » means 'a movement that changes its color every moment' (m. l.). « » means to imagine something, to be proud, and « » means to walk with a swagger and to walk with the gait of pride. (Majma') Thus, the mind of such a person is on a higher level than ordinary people, and it is a degree above « »."
    },
    {
      "id": 148,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "« » means to be ungrateful for Allah's blessing and to use it incorrectly (2 verses: 8:47-28:58)",
      "d": "« » means to go astray due to the abundance of blessings and, according to Imam Raghib, « » is a terror that befalls a person due to the misuse of prosperity, falling short in the right of a blessing, and incorrect use of a blessing (muf). And according to Ibn Faris, the original meaning of « » is 'to tear.' That is, as if the abundance of a blessing has torn someone's eyes, and he does not care for anyone. Thus, in the meaning of « », the abundance of a blessing, ingratitude, and incorrect use are present, and it is a degree above « ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ کَمۡ  اَہۡلَکۡنَا مِنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍۭ  بَطِرَتۡ مَعِیۡشَتَہَا»\nTranslation: And how many a town We have destroyed while it was arrogant in its prosperity."
    },
    {
      "id": 149,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "« » is the final degree of pride: rejecting the truth and considering people contemptible (57 verses: 2:34-2:87-2:185-4:172-4:173-5:82-6:93-7:13-6:36-7:40-7:48-7:75-7:76-7:88-7:133-7:146-7:206-10:75-14:21-16:22-16:23-16:29-16:49-21:19-22:37-23:46-23:67-25:21-28:39-29:39-31:7-32:15-34:31-34:32-34:33-37:35-38:74-38:75-39:59-39:60-39:72-40:27-40:35-40:47-40:48-40:60-40:76-41:15-41:38-45:8-45:31-46:10-46:20-59:23-63:5-71:7-74:23)",
      "d": "«تَکَبَّرَ» «الْكِبَرُ بَطَرُ الْحَقِّ وَغَمْطُ النَّاس»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قَالَ فَاہۡبِطۡ مِنۡہَا فَمَا یَکُوۡنُ لَکَ اَنۡ تَتَکَبَّرَ فِیۡہَا»\nTranslation: Allah said, 'Then get out from it (Paradise), for you have no right to be arrogant in it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 150,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "« » means to walk with arms spread out due to pride and arrogance (1 verse: 75:33)",
      "d": "« » means, in walking, pride, arrogance—to spread out one's arms, to show nonchalance. To walk with arms spread out with pride (f. l. 178).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَلَا صَدَّقَ وَلَا صَلّٰی وَ لٰکِنۡ کَذَّبَ وَتَوَلّٰی ثُمَّ ذَہَبَ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖ یَتَمَطّٰی»\nTranslation: So he neither believed nor prayed, but he denied and turned away. Then he went to his people, swaggering."
    },
    {
      "id": 151,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to be arrogant / to show pride",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "« » means to boast about things that do not even exist within oneself (4 verses: 4:36-11:10-31:18-57:23)",
      "d": "« » means to show off one's greatness, i.e., to praise oneself and to mention a quality that does not exist. For example, to boast about lineage and ancestry or to show pride in inherited wealth and property (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَلَا تُصَعِّرۡخَدَّکَ لِلنَّاسِ وَلَا تَمۡشِ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَرَحًا ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ کُلَّ مُخۡتَالٍ فَخُوۡرٍ»\nTranslation: And do not turn your cheek [in contempt] toward people and do not walk through the earth exultantly. Indeed, Allah does not like every arrogant boaster.\nIn this verse, Allah has mentioned three contemptible (bad) traits in sequence: « » (exultant walking), « » (swaggering), and « » (boasting)."
    },
    {
      "id": 152,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Arrogance / Boasting",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "« » is used to express joy and to thank God for His blessings, and also to denote arrogance and ingratitude towards them. (21 verses: 3:120-3:170-3:188-6:44-9:50-9:81-10:22-10:58-11:10-13:26-13:36-23:53-27:36-28:76-30:4-30:32-30:36-40:75-40:83-42:48-57:23)",
      "d": "«فَرِحَ» «فَرِحَ الْقَلْب» «فَرِحَ النَّفْس» «فَرِحَ الْقَلْب» «قُلۡ بِفَضۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ بِرَحۡمَتِہٖ فَبِذٰلِکَ فَلۡیَفۡرَحُوۡا ؕ ہُوَخَیۡرٌمِّمَّا یَجۡمَعُوۡنَ» «فَرِحَ النَّفْس» «اِذۡ  قَالَ لَہٗ قَوۡمُہٗ لَا تَفۡرَحۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ الۡفَرِحِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 153,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Arrogance / Boasting",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "« » is used for boasting about one's skill. (1 verse: 26:149)",
      "d": "«فَرِہَ» «فَرِہَ» «فَارِہٌ» «فَرِہَ» «وَ تَنۡحِتُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ بُیُوۡتًا فٰرِہِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 154,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Arrogance / Boasting",
      "hw": "تکبر",
      "s": "« » means to exult with joy and to walk with pride and vanity. (3 verses: 17:37-31:18-40:75)",
      "d": "«مَرَحَ» «شِدّۃُ الْفَرْحِ» «وَ لَا تَمۡشِ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَرَحًا ۚ اِنَّکَ  لَنۡ تَخۡرِقَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ لَنۡ تَبۡلُغَ الۡجِبَالَ طُوۡلًا»"
    }
  ],
  "25": [
    {
      "id": 155,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To guess randomly or to fabricate stories",
      "hw": "من گھڑت",
      "s": "« » means a statement that has some truth but the rest is fiction, a falsehood that seems true. (1 verse: 38:7)",
      "d": "«خَلَقَ» «اِخْتَلَقَ» «اِخْتِرَاع» «مَا سَمِعۡنَا بِہٰذَا فِی الۡمِلَّۃِ  الۡاٰخَرَۃِ  ۚ ۖ اِنۡ ہٰذَاۤ اِلَّا اخۡتِلَاقٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 156,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To guess randomly or to fabricate stories",
      "hw": "من گھڑت",
      "s": "« » means lying with the intention of causing corruption. (53 verses: 3:24-3:94-4:48-4:50-5:103-6:21-6:24-6:93-6:112-6:137-6:138-6:140-6:144-7:37-7:53-7:89-7:152-10:17-10:30-10:37-10:38-10:59-10:60-10:69-11:13-11:18-11:21-11:35-11:50-12:111-16:56-16:87-16:101-16:105-16:116-17:73-18:15-20:61-21:5-23:38-25:4-28:36-28:75-29:13-29:68-32:3-34:8-34:43-42:24-46:8-46:28-60:12-61:7)",
      "d": "«اِفْتَرَاء» «فَرِیَ» «فَاَتَتۡ بِہٖ قَوۡمَہَا تَحۡمِلُہٗ ؕ قَالُوۡا یٰمَرۡیَمُ لَقَدۡ جِئۡتِ شَیۡئًا فَرِیًّا» «اِفْترٰی» «وَاِنۡ کَادُوۡا لَیَفۡتِنُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الَّذِیۡۤ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ اِلَیۡکَ لِتَفۡتَرِیَ عَلَیۡنَا غَیۡرَہٗ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 157,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To guess randomly or to fabricate stories",
      "hw": "من گھڑت",
      "s": "« » means to fabricate a false statement and then attribute it to someone else. (26 verses: 2:80-2:104-2:140-2:154-2:169-6:93-6:156-6:157-7:28-7:33-7:172-7:173-10:68-10:77-16:116-17:40-20:94-24:15-39:56-39:57-39:58-52:33-61:2-61:3-69:44-72:5)",
      "d": "«تَقَوَّل» «وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ لَوۡلَا یُعَذِّبُنَا اللّٰہُ» «تَقَوَّل» «وَ لَوۡ تَقَوَّلَ عَلَیۡنَا بَعۡضَ الۡاَقَاوِیۡلِ . لَاَخَذۡنَا مِنۡہُ بِالۡیَمِیۡنِ ثُمَّ لَقَطَعۡنَا مِنۡہُ الۡوَتِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 158,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To guess randomly or to fabricate stories",
      "hw": "من گھڑت",
      "s": "« » means to rely on mere speculation and estimates without reality. (4 verses: 6:116-6:148-10:66-43:20)",
      "d": "«خَرَصَ» «خَرَصَ النَّخْلَۃَ» «خَرَّاص» «قُتِلَ الۡخَرّٰصُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "26": [
    {
      "id": 160,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift / to carry a burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » means to lift the burden of winds and clouds, considering them light. (2 verses: 7:57-9:38)",
      "d": "«اَقَلَّ» «اَقَلَّ» «اَقَلَّ، اَثَارَ» «وَہُوَالَّذِیۡ یُرۡسِلُ الرِّیٰحَ بُشۡرًۢا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡ رَحۡمَتِہٖ ؕ حَتّٰۤی اِذَاۤ اَقَلَّتۡ سَحَابًا ثِقَالًا سُقۡنٰہُ لِبَلَدٍ مَّیِّتٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 161,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift / to carry a burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » is used for picking up something fallen. (2 verses: 12:10-28:8)",
      "d": "«لَقَطَ» «لُقْطَۃ» «اِلْتَقَطَ» «قَالَ قَآئِلٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ لَا تَقۡتُلُوۡا یُوۡسُفَ وَاَلۡقُوۡہُ فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ الۡجُبِّ یَلۡتَقِطۡہُ بَعۡضُ السَّیَّارَۃِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 162,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift / to carry a burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » is used on the Day of Resurrection for raising the dead from graves. (10 verses: 18:16-21:21-42:28-43:11-44:35-74:52-77:3-80:22-81:10-94:1)",
      "d": "«نَشَرَ» «طَوَی» «نَشَرْتُ الْکِتَابَ» «طَوَیْتُہ» «وَاِذَا الصُّحُفُ نُشِرَتۡ» «نَشِرَ الْمَیِّتُ نشُوْرًا» «وَاِلَیْہِ النُّشُوْر» «اَنْشَرَ» «ثُمَّ  اَمَاتَہٗ  فَاَقۡبَرَہٗ ثُمَّ  اِذَا شَآءَ  اَنۡشَرَہٗ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 163,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » is used to mean causing movement in something to lift it (2 verses: 2:259-58:11).",
      "d": "«نَشَزَ» «نَشْزَ الرَّجُل» «اَنْشَزَ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ انۡظُرۡاِلٰی حِمَارِکَ وَ لِنَجۡعَلَکَ اٰیَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ انۡظُرۡاِلَی الۡعِظَامِ کَیۡفَ نُنۡشِزُہَا ثُمَّ نَکۡسُوۡہَا لَحۡمًا»\nTranslation: And look at your donkey, and We will make you a sign for the people, and look at the bones, how We will raise them and then clothe them with flesh. (Uthmani)\nHere, the meaning of using « » is that movement and agitation occurred in those bones. They began to join together and stood up forming the structure of the donkey.\nNote: (Transitive verb: A verb that requires an object in addition to the subject to complete its meaning)."
    },
    {
      "id": 164,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » is used for raising the dead on the Day of Resurrection (27 verses: 2:56-2:259-6:36-6:60-7:14-15:36-16:21-16:38-18:12-18:19-19:15-19:33-22:5-22:7-23:16-23:100-26:87-27:65-30:56-31:28-36:52-37:144-38:79-58:6-58:18-64:7-72:7).",
      "d": "«حَبِطَ» «حَبَِطَ دَمُّ الْقَتِیْل»\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَشۡرَکُوۡا لَحَبِطَ عَنۡہُمۡ  مَّا کَانُوۡا یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And if they had associated partners, what they used to do would have been wasted from them.\nAnd « » means to make useless or to destroy and waste.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\nTranslation: That is because they hated what Allah revealed, so He made their deeds worthless."
    },
    {
      "id": 165,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Lift; To Carry a Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » is used for carrying a burden, whether material or spiritual. It is general. (44 verses: 2:248-2:286-6:31-6:146-7:176-7:189-9:92-11:40-12:36-12:72-13:8-16:7-16:25-17:3-17:70-19:22-19:27-19:58-20:87-20:100-20:101-20:111-22:2-23:22-24:54-29:12-29:13-29:60-31:14-33:72-35:11-35:18-36:41-40:7-40:80-41:47-46:15-54:13-62:5-65:4-65:6-69:11-69:14-69:17)",
      "d": "« » is used for carrying a burden and its usage is general, applicable to both material (e.g., lifting something like luggage) and spiritual (e.g., carrying the burden of sin) meanings.\n(1) For material burden carrying: whether external or internal, such as a woman carrying the burden of a child in her womb or a tree carrying its fruit or a cloud carrying its water. In short, this word is used in all contexts.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا تَغَشّٰہَا حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا فَمَرَّتۡ بِہٖ»\nTranslation: When the man approaches her, she carries a light burden, and then she moves about with it.\n(2) For spiritual burden carrying: For example, Allah says:\n«وَعَنَتِ الۡوُجُوۡہُ لِلۡحَیِّ الۡقَیُّوۡمِ ؕ وَ قَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ حَمَلَ ظُلۡمًا»\nTranslation: And the faces will be humbled before the Ever-Living, the Self-Sustaining, and whoever carries injustice will have failed.\n«حَمَلَ عَلَیٰ» «حَمَّلَ»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَا تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡنَاۤ اِصۡرًا»\nTranslation: And do not impose a burden on us."
    },
    {
      "id": 166,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » This word is specific for carrying an internal (i.e., unseen) burden (1 verse: 15:22).",
      "d": "«لَقَحَ» «لَقَحَۃُ النَّاقَۃ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاَرۡسَلۡنَا الرِّیٰحَ لَوَاقِحَ فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً»\nTranslation: And We send the winds, fertilizing (carrying the burden of pollen), then We cause rain to descend from the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 167,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » To carry a heavier burden that can be carried with difficulty. To carry a burden with toil (1 verse: 28:76).",
      "d": "(The meaning of   is to toil strenuously and carry a burden with difficulty (M. N). To carry with difficulty due to the heaviness of the burden (M. A).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاٰتَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡکُنُوۡزِ مَاۤ اِنَّ مَفَاتِحَہٗ لَتَنُوۡٓاُ بِالۡعُصۡبَۃِ اُولِی الۡقُوَّۃِ»\nTranslation: And We gave him treasures whose keys would be a heavy burden (to carry) for a company of strong men."
    },
    {
      "id": 168,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To lift. To carry a burden.",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » Generally used for carrying the burden of sin (10 verses: 6:31-6:164-16:25-17:15-20:87-20:100-35:18-39:7-53:38-94:2).",
      "d": "« » When a person spreads his garment, places his burden in it, and then carries it and walks away, that is the correct meaning of « ». Hence, sin ( ) is called « ». That is, the person takes on the burden of his committed sin. (M L) Thus, « » is generally used for carrying burdens of sins.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ ہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ ؕ اَلَا سَآءَ مَا یَزِرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And they will be carrying their burdens on their backs. Wretched is what they will carry."
    }
  ],
  "27": [
    {
      "id": 169,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "« » To set out alone for a purpose. (1 verse: 91:12)",
      "d": "« » means to rise for work. Due to being in the form of « », its meaning is that a person rises by himself and sets out alone to accomplish an important purpose.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«کَذَّبَتۡ ثَمُوۡدُ بِطَغۡوٰىہَاۤ اِذِ انۡۢبَعَثَ اَشۡقٰہَا»\nTranslation: Thamud denied [the truth] due to their arrogance when the most wretched of them rose up."
    },
    {
      "id": 170,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "« » To stand in any condition. General. (19 verses: 2:20-3:191-4:5-4:102-4:103-4:142-5:6-5:97-9:84-9:108-18:14-18:77-25:64-36:8-39:68-51:45-72:19-73:2-74:2)",
      "d": "« » means for a sitting or lying person to stand up, or to stand while walking. It is used for everyone. Thus, it is generally used for standing up.\nFor example:\n(1) In the Quran:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَذۡکُرُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ قِیٰمًا وَّقُعُوۡدًا»\nTranslation: Those who remember Allah while standing and sitting.\n(2) In the Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡمُدَّثِّرُ قُمۡ فَاَنۡذِرۡ»\nTranslation: O you who covers himself [with a garment], arise and warn.\n(3) In the Quran:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ اَضَآءَ لَہُمۡ مَّشَوۡا فِیۡہِ٭ۙ وَاِذَاۤ اَظۡلَمَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ قَامُوۡا»\nTranslation: Whenever it shines upon them, they walk in it, and when it darkens over them, they stand still."
    },
    {
      "id": 171,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "« » Used in the meaning of rising and spreading. (5 verses: 25:3-25:40-25:47-35:19-67:15)",
      "d": "«نَشَرَ» «کَمَا مَرَّ»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَّلَا یَمۡلِکُوۡنَ مَوۡتًا وَّلَا حَیٰوۃً وَّلَا نُشُوۡرًا»\nTranslation: They have no power over death or life or resurrection.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«ہُوَالَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الَّیۡلَ لِبَاسًا وَّالنَّوۡمَ سُبَاتًا وَّ جَعَلَ النَّہَارَنُشُوۡرًا»\nTranslation: And He it is who made the night for you as clothing and sleep for rest and made the day for rising."
    },
    {
      "id": 172,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "« » Used for rising due to a movement or stir. (2 verses: 2:259-58:11)",
      "d": "« » is everything that is desirable to all. For example, justice, intellect, and wealth are also called   (m. a). Its opposite is « ».\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَاِنَّہٗ  لِحُبِّ الۡخَیۡرِلَشَدِیۡدٌ»\nTranslation: And indeed, man is intensely in love with wealth.\nMeaning:   refers to every good thing or virtuous deed, and its plural is  .\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ وَ الۡیَوۡمِ الۡاٰخِرِ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ وَ یُسَارِعُوۡنَ فِی الۡخَیۡرٰتِ»\nTranslation: They believe in Allah and the Last Day, and they enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong, and they hasten towards good deeds.\nThe word   is not only used for good things or deeds but also for good people or things, and for faith as well. In that case, its plural is  .\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ عِنۡدَنَا لَمِنَ الۡمُصۡطَفَیۡنَ الۡاَخۡیَارِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, they are with Us among the chosen and the good.\nThus, the word   is used for any good thing, deed, or person, and « » is said when one is pleased with a good thing.\nThe following verse explains this:\n«وَ لَدَارُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ خَیۡرٌ ؕ وَ لَنِعۡمَ  دَارُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: The home of the Hereafter is good, and excellent is the home of the righteous."
    }
  ],
  "28": [
    {
      "id": 173,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Taking Permission",
      "hw": "اجازت",
      "s": "« » to seek permission or approval for an action (9 verses: 9:44-9:45-9:83-9:86-9:93-24:58-24:59-24:62-33:13)",
      "d": "«اَذِنَ» «اِسْتأذَنَ» «اِسْتَأذَنَ عَلَیْہِ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَا یَسۡتَاۡذِنُکَ الَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ وَالۡیَوۡمِ الۡاٰخِرِاَنۡ یُّجَاہِدُوۡا بِاَمۡوَالِہِمۡ وَاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day do not seek your permission to stay behind. Rather, they desire to strive with their wealth and lives."
    },
    {
      "id": 174,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Taking Permission",
      "hw": "اجازت",
      "s": "« » to introduce oneself through some word or action.\nAnd for giving permission, only « » is used.\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«عَفَا اللّٰہُ عَنۡکَ ۚ لِمَ اَذِنۡتَ لَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: (O Prophet ﷺ) May Allah forgive you. Why did you give permission (to the hypocrites not to participate in Jihad)? (1 verse: 24:27)",
      "d": "«اٰنَسَ» «اٰنس الصوت» «اٰنس النار» «اِسْتَانَسَ» «اِسْتَاْنَسَ»\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَدۡخُلُوۡا بُیُوۡتًا غَیۡرَ  بُیُوۡتِکُمۡ  حَتّٰی تَسۡتَاۡنِسُوۡا وَ تُسَلِّمُوۡا عَلٰۤی اَہۡلِہَا»"
    }
  ],
  "29": [
    {
      "id": 175,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Harshness",
      "hw": "اُجڈ",
      "s": "« » ill-mannered people who have no etiquette of conversation (10 verses: 9:90-9:97-9:98-9:99-9:101-9:120-33:20-48:11-48:16-49:14)",
      "d": "« » means bedouin, unlettered, rural, jungle-dweller, uncivilized, one who has no etiquette or refinement in conversation or lifestyle. (source)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلۡاَعۡرَابُ اَشَدُّ کُفۡرًا وَّنِفَاقًا وَّاَجۡدَرُاَلَّا یَعۡلَمُوۡاحُدُوۡدَ مَاۤ اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ عَلٰی رَسُوۡلِہٖ»\nTranslation: The bedouins are the most severe in disbelief and hypocrisy, and most deserving of not knowing the commandments which Allah has revealed to His Messenger."
    },
    {
      "id": 176,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Harshness",
      "hw": "اُجڈ",
      "s": "« » used for a harsh-tempered and rigid human (2 verses: 44:47-68:13)",
      "d": "«عَتَلَ» «عَتَلَہٗٓ اِلَی السِّجْن»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: Seize him and drag him into the midst of Hell.\nAnd « » means a harsh and stubborn person (Quranic dictionary), harsh-tempered (singular).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عُتُلٍّۭ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ  زَنِیۡمٍ»\nTranslation: Harsh-tempered and besides that, of evil character."
    },
    {
      "id": 177,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Harshness",
      "hw": "اُجڈ",
      "s": "« » foul-mouthed and using abusive language in conversation (1 verse: 3:159)",
      "d": "« » means to be harsh-tempered, bad-natured. And « » means rough, harsh-tempered, harsh in speech, bitter-tongued. Its opposite is « » which means softness in speech and temperament.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَبِمَا رَحۡمَۃٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ لِنۡتَ لَہُمۡ ۚ وَلَوۡ کُنۡتَ فَظًّا غَلِیۡظَ الۡقَلۡبِ لَانۡفَضُّوۡا مِنۡ حَوۡلِکَ»\nTranslation: O Prophet ﷺ! This is a great mercy from Allah that you have been gentle with them. Had you been harsh and hard-hearted, they would have dispersed from around you."
    }
  ],
  "30": [
    {
      "id": 179,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Suddenly",
      "hw": "اچانک",
      "s": "« » the sudden appearance of something whose occurrence was not even imagined (13 verses: 6:31-6:44-6:47-7:95-7:187-12:107-21:40-22:55-26:202-29:53-39:55-43:66-47:18)",
      "d": "« » means something appearing suddenly, with no prior expectation of its occurrence (singular). The difference between « » and « » or « » is that in « », the subsequent event has some relation or connection to the preceding event, whereas « » refers only to a sudden or unexpected event.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَخَذۡنٰہُمۡ  بَغۡتَۃً وَّ ہُمۡ لَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then We seized them suddenly while they did not perceive it.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ  بَغۡتَۃً  قَالُوۡا یٰحَسۡرَتَنَا عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡنَا فِیۡہَا»\nTranslation: Until when the Hour comes upon them suddenly, they will say, 'Alas for us for what we neglected regarding it.'"
    }
  ],
  "31": [
    {
      "id": 180,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good, Excellent, Better",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "« » a word of praise (i.e., an appreciative term) said for something good (16 verses: 2:271-3:136-3:173-4:58-8:40-13:24-16:30-18:31-22:78-29:58-37:75-38:30-38:44-39:74-51:48-77:23)",
      "d": "« » is a word of praise (i.e., an appreciative term) used for all kinds of commendation and praise (singular). Its meanings are: 'How excellent!' 'How wonderful!' It is said with joy at something good. According to Ibn Faris, its original sense is inclination and leaning (root), meaning when one sees something and the nature inclines toward it, one says « ». Its opposite is « », which is a word of reproach (i.e., for evil and criticism) and is used for condemnation.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَنِعۡمَ  دَارُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And excellent is the abode of the pious."
    },
    {
      "id": 181,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good. Excellent. Better.",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "« » is used for every good thing, deed, or good person (170 verses: 2:54-2:61-2:103-2:105-2:106-2:110-2:148-2:158-2:180-2:184-2:197-2:215-2:216-2:220-2:221-2:263-2:269-2:271-2:272-2:273-2:280-3:15-3:26-3:30-3:54-3:104-3:110-3:114-3:115-3:150-3:157-3:178-3:180-3:198-4:19-4:25-4:46-4:59-4:66-4:77-4:114-4:127-4:128-4:149-4:170-4:171-5:48-5:114-6:17-6:32-6:57-6:158-7:12-7:26-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:155-7:169-7:188-8:19-8:23-8:30-8:70-9:3-9:41-9:61-9:74-9:88-9:109-10:11-10:58-10:107-10:109-11:31-11:84-11:86-12:39-12:57-12:59-12:64-12:80-12:109-16:30-16:76-16:95-16:126-17:11-17:35-18:36-18:40-18:44-18:46-18:81-18:95-19:73-19:76-20:73-20:131-21:35-21:73-21:89-21:90-22:11-22:30-22:36-22:58-22:77-23:29-23:56-23:61-23:72-23:109-23:118-24:11-24:12-24:27-24:33-24:60-25:10-25:15-25:24-27:36-27:59-27:89-28:24-28:26-28:60-28:80-28:84-29:16-30:38-33:19-33:25-34:39-35:32-37:62-38:32-38:76-41:40-41:49-42:36-43:32-43:52-43:58-44:37-46:11-47:21-49:5-49:11-50:25-54:43-55:70-58:12-61:11-62:9-62:11-64:16-66:5-68:12-68:32-70:21-70:41-73:20-87:17-93:4-97:3-98:7-99:7-100:8).",
      "d": "« » is every desirable thing. For example, justice, intellect, and wealth are also called   (M. A). Its opposite is « ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِنَّہٗ  لِحُبِّ الۡخَیۡرِلَشَدِیۡدٌ»\nTranslation: And indeed, man is intensely in love of wealth.\nThat is,   refers to every good thing or virtuous deed, and its plural is  .\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ وَ الۡیَوۡمِ الۡاٰخِرِ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ وَ یُسَارِعُوۡنَ فِی الۡخَیۡرٰتِ»\nTranslation: They believe in Allah and the Last Day and enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong and hasten to good deeds.\nThe word   is not only used for a good thing or deed but also for good people or things, and for faith. In this case, the plural becomes  .\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ عِنۡدَنَا لَمِنَ الۡمُصۡطَفَیۡنَ الۡاَخۡیَارِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, they are with Us among the chosen and the good.\nThus, the word   is used for any good thing, deed, or person. And « » is said upon seeing a good thing with pleasure.\nThe following verse clarifies this:\n«وَ لَدَارُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ خَیۡرٌ ؕ وَ لَنِعۡمَ  دَارُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: But the home of the Hereafter is best, and excellent is the home of the righteous."
    },
    {
      "id": 182,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good, Excellent, Better",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "« » used for delightful and pleasing things, both apparent and spiritual beauty and goodness (57 verses: 2:83-2:138-2:245-3:14-3:37-3:148-3:195-4:59-4:69-4:95-5:12-6:152-6:160-7:137-7:180-8:17-9:107-10:26-11:3-11:88-13:18-13:29-16:62-16:67-16:75-17:110-18:2-18:31-18:86-18:88-20:8-20:86-21:101-22:58-25:76-27:11-28:61-29:8-33:52-35:8-38:25-38:40-38:49-41:50-42:23-48:16-53:31-55:70-55:76-57:10-57:11-57:18-59:24-64:17-73:20-92:6-92:9)",
      "d": "« » means delightful and pleasing (singular). Its opposite is « ». Then this word is also used for apparent beauty and facial radiance.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فِیۡہِنَّ خَیۡرٰتٌ حِسَانٌ»\nTranslation: In them are good women, beautiful.\nIn this case, its opposite is « ». Besides this, the word is also used spiritually to denote excellence of character.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَحَسُنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ رَفِیۡقًا»\nTranslation: And excellent is the companionship of those."
    },
    {
      "id": 183,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good, Excellent, Better",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "«اَمْثَل ، مُثْلیٰ»",
      "d": "« » means for something to be present before the eyes (singular). And « » means exemplary, peerless, ideal, best (source).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ اَمۡثَلُہُمۡ طَرِیۡقَۃً»\nTranslation: At that time, the best of them in way (i.e., the wise and sensible) will say.\n«مُثْلیٰ ، اَمْثَلُ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ یَذۡہَبَا بِطَرِیۡقَتِکُمُ  الۡمُثۡلٰی»\nTranslation: And they will put an end to your exemplary way of life."
    },
    {
      "id": 184,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Good. Excellent. Better.",
      "hw": "اچھا",
      "s": "« » comes for the good deeds of any person, and for good morals. In common usage, this word is also used for apparent beauty (8 verses: 12:18-12:83-15:85-16:6-33:28-33:49-70:5-73:10).",
      "d": "« » its root word is  , which means apparent goodness, splendor, dignity, pomp, and beauty (Faq 217).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا جَمَالٌ»\nTranslation: And there is honor for you in it.\n«اَجْمَلَ فِی الْعَمَل»\n«بَلۡ سَوَّلَتۡ لَکُمۡ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ اَمۡرًا ؕ فَصَبۡرٌ  جَمِیۡلٌ»\nTranslation: Rather, your own desires have enticed you to something. So patience is good.\nAnd in the Quran, when the Prophet (ﷺ) said to his wives:\n«اِنۡ  کُنۡـتُنَّ تُرِدۡنَ  الۡحَیٰوۡفَ  الدُّنۡیَا وَ زِیۡنَتَہَا فَتَعَالَیۡنَ اُمَتِّعۡکُنَّ وَ اُسَرِّحۡکُنَّ سَرَاحًا جَمِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: If you desire the present life and its adornment, then come, I will provide for you and send you away in a good manner.\nLater, this word began to be used for the beauty of the face as well. However, there is no example of this in the Quran."
    }
  ],
  "32": [
    {
      "id": 185,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Strange. To be a stranger.",
      "hw": "اجنبی",
      "s": "« » when unfamiliarity is accompanied by dislike, it is « »; when accompanied by pleasure, it is « »; and when neither dislike nor pleasure is present, it is « » (7 verses: 11:70-18:74-18:87-27:41-31:19-54:6-65:8)",
      "d": "«نَکِرَ» «مَعْرفَۃ» «اَنْکَرَ» «تَنَاکَر» «نُکْر» «مَنْکِر» «نَکَرَ» «فَلَمَّا رَاٰۤ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ لَا تَصِلُ اِلَیۡہِ نَکِرَہُمۡ وَاَوۡجَسَ مِنۡہُمۡ خِیۡفَۃً»"
    },
    {
      "id": 186,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Strange. To be a stranger.",
      "hw": "اجنبی",
      "s": "«عَجَبَ ۔ عَجَبٌ»",
      "d": "«عَجَبَ ۔ عَجَبٌ» «عَجَبَ» «اَعْجَبَ» «عَجَبَ» «قَالُوۡۤا اَتَعۡجَبِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ رَحۡمَتُ اللّٰہِ وَ بَرَکٰتُہٗ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اَہۡلَ الۡبَیۡتِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 187,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To be amazed. To become a stranger.",
      "hw": "اجنبی",
      "s": "« » has two meanings: the first is used for a stranger, the second for an impure person (8 verses: 4:36-4:43-5:6-10:12-28:11-39:56-87:11-92:17).",
      "d": "« » means side, flank. « » means both stranger and impure. The word « » is used in singular, dual, and plural forms, and equally for men and women. (Manjad) This word has appeared in the Quran in both these meanings. When it comes in the meaning of stranger, there is no implication of dislike or pleasure.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالۡجَارِ ذِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡجَارِ الۡجُنُبِ وَ الصَّاحِبِ بِالۡجَنۡۢبِ»\nTranslation: And the neighbor who is a relative, the neighbor who is a stranger, and the companion by your side.\nAnd « » means to turn aside and become distant. And the Junub (impure person) is also commanded to stay away from prayer and the mosque, hence he is called Junub.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا»\nTranslation: And (do not approach prayer) while you are impure, unless you are passing through, until you have bathed."
    }
  ],
  "33": [
    {
      "id": 190,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To do a favor.",
      "hw": "احسان",
      "s": "« » is used for doing a favor upon someone other than oneself (63 verses: 1:6-2:40-2:47-2:122-2:150-2:211-2:231-3:103-3:171-3:174-4:69-4:72-5:3-5:6-5:7-5:11-5:20-5:23-5:110-8:53-11:10-12:6-14:6-14:28-14:34-16:18-16:53-16:71-16:72-16:81-16:83-16:112-16:114-16:121-17:83-19:58-26:22-27:19-28:17-29:67-31:20-31:31-33:9-33:37-35:3-37:57-39:8-39:49-41:51-43:13-43:59-44:27-46:15-48:2-49:8-52:29-54:35-68:2-68:49-73:11-89:15-92:19-93:11).",
      "d": "«اَلنَّعْمَۃ» «اَنْعَمَ» «اَنْعَمَ عَلیٰ فَرَسِہ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَقُوۡلُ لِلَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِ وَاَنۡعَمۡتَ عَلَیۡہِ اَمۡسِکۡ عَلَیۡکَ زَوۡجَکَ»\nTranslation: When you say to him (Zayd ibn Harithah) upon whom Allah has bestowed favor and you have bestowed favor, 'Retain your wife.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 191,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To do good",
      "hw": "احسان",
      "s": "« » is used for every good and virtuous deed, whether it pertains to one's own self or to another's self (63 verses: 2:83-2:178-2:195-2:229-3:172-4:36-4:59-4:62-4:86-4:125-5:50-5:93-6:151-6:152-6:154-7:145-9:100-9:121-10:26-11:7-12:3-12:23-12:100-16:30-16:90-16:96-16:97-16:125-17:7-17:23-17:34-17:35-17:53-18:7-18:30-19:73-19:74-23:14-23:96-24:38-25:24-25:33-28:77-29:7-29:46-32:7-37:125-39:10-39:18-39:23-39:35-39:55-40:64-41:33-41:34-46:15-46:16-53:31-55:60-64:3-65:11-67:2-95:4)",
      "d": "«شَآءَ» «شَیْء» «شَیْء» «شِیْئَۃ» «مَشِیْئَۃ» «مَشِیْئَۃ» «یَخۡلُقُ مَا یَشَآءُ ؕ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ اِنَاثًا وَّ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ الذُّکُوۡرَ»"
    }
  ],
  "34": [
    {
      "id": 192,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To have a choice/option",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "« » means to choose one option from two or more things (2 verses: 28:68-33:36)",
      "d": "«خَیْر» «خِیَرَۃ» «اِخْتَار» «وَمَا کَانَ لِمُؤۡمِنٍ وَّلَا مُؤۡمِنَۃٍ اِذَا قَضَی اللّٰہُ وَرَسُوۡلُہٗۤ اَمۡرًا اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ لَہُمُ الۡخِیَرَۃُ مِنۡ اَمۡرِہِمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 193,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To have a choice/option",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "« » means to have the authority to dispose of something (56 verses: 2:246-2:247-4:3-4:24-4:25-4:36-5:17-5:25-5:41-5:76-7:188-10:31-10:49-12:43-12:50-12:54-12:72-12:76-13:16-16:71-16:73-17:56-17:100-18:79-19:87-20:87-20:89-20:114-23:6-23:88-23:116-24:31-24:33-24:58-24:61-25:3-29:17-30:28-33:50-33:52-33:55-34:22-34:42-35:13-39:43-43:86-46:8-48:11-59:23-60:4-62:1-70:30-72:21-78:37-82:19-114:2)",
      "d": "«مِلْک» «مَلْک» «مِلْک» «مَلْک» «مَلِک» «قَالُوۡا مَاۤ اَخۡلَفۡنَا مَوۡعِدَکَ بِمَلۡکِنَا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 195,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To hold (a position of power).",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "« » when the concept of place or location is also present in the authority (1 verse: 8:71).",
      "d": "«اَمْکَنَ» «مَکَّنَ» «اَمْکَنَ الْاَمْر» «اَمْکَنَ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِنۡ یُّرِیۡدُوۡا خِیَانَتَکَ فَقَدۡ خَانُوا اللّٰہَ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ فَاَمۡکَنَ مِنۡہُمۡ»\nTranslation: If they intend to betray you, they have already betrayed Allah before, so He gave them power over you (i.e., placed them under your control). (Jalandhari) So He made them captive. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 196,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To choose",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "« » means to choose from two or more things that which is pleasing to the heart (4 verses: 9:23-14:3-16:107-41:17)",
      "d": "«حُبّ» «اِسْتَحَبَّ» «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡۤا اٰبَآءَکُمۡ وَ اِخۡوَانَکُمۡ اَوۡلِیَآءَ اِنِ اسۡتَحَبُّوا الۡکُفۡرَ عَلَی الۡاِیۡمَانِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 197,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To choose",
      "hw": "اختیار",
      "s": "« » means to select and seek that which is more worthy and better among two things. (1 Verse: 72:14)",
      "d": "«حَرْوٌ ، اَحْرٰی» «تَحَرّٰی» «فَمَنۡ اَسۡلَمَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ تَحَرَّوۡا رَشَدًا»"
    }
  ],
  "35": [
    {
      "id": 198,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Loan (Udhaar)",
      "hw": "قرض",
      "s": "« » refers to that sum of money which is taken for personal necessities with the condition of returning it after a specified period. In a 'qard hasana' (goodly loan), the period is not specified. (9 Verses: 2:245-2:282-4:11-4:12-5:12-57:11-57:18-64:17-73:20)",
      "d": "«قَرَضَ» «حَسَنًا» «وَاِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡعُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ» «مَنۡ ذَا الَّذِیۡ یُقۡرِضُ اللّٰہَ قَرۡضًا حَسَنًا فَیُضٰعِفَہٗ لَہٗ وَ لَہٗۤ اَجۡرٌ کَرِیۡمٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 199,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Debt (Dayn)",
      "hw": "قرض",
      "s": "« » If a period is specified in a loan, then it is called 'dayn' (debt). (9 Verses: 2:245-2:282-4:11-4:12-5:12-57:11-57:18-64:17-73:20)",
      "d": "«دَیْن» «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا تَدَایَنۡتُمۡ بِدَیۡنٍ اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی فَاکۡتُبُوۡہُ»"
    }
  ],
