  "37": [
    {
      "id": 208,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to fly",
      "hw": "اَڑنا",
      "s": "«mardah» being devoid of something that should be present (1 verse: 9:101)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of «mardah» is being devoid of something that should be present. «amradu» means a tree without leaves, and a young man who either has not yet grown a beard or is beardless. And «marad» refers to a devil among jinn or humans who is devoid of all kinds of good. Then this word started being used for persisting in a bad thing and remaining devoid of good (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ مِمَّنۡ حَوۡلَکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ مُنٰفِقُوۡنَ  ؕ ۛوَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ ۛ ؔ مَرَدُوۡا عَلَی النِّفَاقِ»\nTranslation: And some of the Bedouins around you are hypocrites, and some of the people of the city too, who are persistent in their hypocrisy."
    },
    {
      "id": 209,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "to fly",
      "hw": "اَڑنا",
      "s": "«lajj» enmity and going far in it (2 verses: 23:75-67:21)",
      "d": "«lajj» means to argue due to opposition. To persist in enmity, i.e., to practice enmity (manjad). And «lajjah» means depth of water, and «bahrin lujji» means deep sea. And «iltajja al-bahr» means the sea becoming agitated or entering into a storm and being turbulent (manjad). Thus, the meaning of «lajj» is found as going far in a bad deed.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَلَوۡ رَحِمۡنٰہُمۡ وَکَشَفۡنَا مَا بِہِمۡ مِّنۡ ضُرٍّلَّلُّجُّوۡا فِیۡ طُغۡیَانِہِمۡ یَعۡمَہُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And if We had mercy on them and removed what they have of distress, they would persist in their transgression, wandering blindly."
    },
    {
