  "43": [
    {
      "id": 232,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret",
      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "« » This is an expression of regret that comes from a person's mouth in distress and calamity (38 verses: 2:79-5:31-11:72-14:2-18:49-19:37-20:61-21:14-21:18-21:46-21:97-25:28-28:80-36:52-37:20-38:27-39:22-41:6-43:65-45:7-46:17-51:60-52:11-68:31-77:15-77:19-77:24-77:28-77:34-77:37-77:40-77:45-77:47-77:49-83:1-83:10-104:1-107:4)",
      "d": "« » is a word of warning that, in its origin, is used as a curse and means evil and misfortune (manjad). Destruction, severe calamity (manjad), and « » meaning to curse one another (manjad). The word « » is used in bad senses and is uttered on occasions of regret (m. r). And when a human is caught in some calamity or distress, they express regret with this word. Now see its examples:\n(1) Example in times of calamity: The Almighty says:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰوَیۡلَنَا مَنۡۢ بَعَثَنَا مِنۡ مَّرۡقَدِنَا»\nTranslation: They will say, \"Alas! Who has raised us up from our resting places?\"\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَیۡلٌ یَّوۡمَئِذٍ لِّلۡمُکَذِّبِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: \"Woe to the deniers on that Day!\"\n(2) Example in times of distress: The Almighty says:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ ؕ قَالَ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤی اَعَجَزۡتُ اَنۡ اَکُوۡنَ مِثۡلَ ہٰذَا الۡغُرَابِ»\nTranslation: \"So Allah sent a raven that scratched in the earth to show him how to hide the shame of his brother. He said, 'Alas for me! Could I not have been like this raven and so hidden my brother's shame?'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 233,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret",
      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "« » is a particle of desire and comes to express regret over past shortcomings (14 verses: 4:73-6:27-18:42-19:23-25:27-25:28-28:79-33:66-36:26-43:38-69:25-69:27-78:40-89:24)",
      "d": "«لَیْتَ» «لَیْتَ الشَّبَابُ عَائِدًا»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُ یٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ کُنۡتُ تُرٰبًا»\nTranslation: \"And the disbeliever will say, 'If only I had been dust!'\"\n«إِنَّ، أَنَّ، کَأَنَّ، لٰـکِنَّ، لَیْتَ، لَعَلَّ»\nParticle of desire: a word in which the expression of desire is found."
    }
  ],
  "44": [
    {
      "id": 236,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Grant Authority",
      "hw": "اقتدار",
      "s": "« » generally used to give someone authority, choice, and governance (12 verses: 6:6-7:10-8:71-12:21-12:56-18:84-18:95-22:41-28:6-28:57-46:26)",
      "d": "« » means to give power, to grant choice, to make capable (manjad). To gain a place and status. To stand firm on one's feet and to be capable of something (m. r). That is, to grant someone authority and bestow governance.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ اِنۡ مَّکَّنّٰہُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَقَامُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اٰتَوُاالزَّکٰوۃَ وَاَمَرُوۡا بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ نَہَوۡا عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ»\nTranslation: \"[They are] those who, if We give them authority in the land, establish prayer and give zakah and enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 237,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Grant Authority",
      "hw": "اقتدار",
      "s": "« » meaning to make someone a successor or deputy (5 verses: 6:133-7:129-11:57-24:55-57:7)",
      "d": "« » means to make someone a successor or deputy (manjad. m. r). And « » means to come after or to be someone's successor.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَعَدَ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ لَیَسۡتَخۡلِفَنَّہُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ»\nTranslation: \"Allah has promised those who have believed among you and done righteous deeds that He will surely grant them succession [to authority] upon the earth.\"\nThus, the word « » also implies that the present authority is in the hands of bad people, and those who believe in Allah and do good deeds, Allah the Almighty will change this present governance and transfer authority to them."
    }
  ],
  "45": [
    {
      "id": 239,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Confess",
      "hw": "اقرار",
      "s": "« » to confess one's crime that happened in the past (3 verses: 9:102-40:11-67:11)",
      "d": "« » means to recognize someone, and « » means to confess one's crime and be humiliated (m. r). So, a criminal who is already aware and acquainted with their crime. When they confess it themselves, that is called confession, and that crime relates to the past, which they have confessed.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاعۡتَرَفُوۡا بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ ۚ فَسُحۡقًا  لِّاَصۡحٰبِ السَّعِیۡرِ»\nTranslation: \"Then they will confess their sins. So away with the companions of the Blaze!\""
    },
    {
      "id": 240,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Confess",
      "hw": "اقرار",
      "s": "« » meaning testimony, a confession related to oneself (60 verses: 2:23-2:84-2:133-2:143-2:185-2:204-2:282-3:18-3:52-3:64-3:70-3:81-3:86-3:99-3:140-4:6-4:15-4:69-4:135-4:166-5:8-5:44-5:111-6:19-6:130-6:144-6:150-7:37-7:172-9:107-11:54-12:26-12:81-18:51-19:37-21:61-22:28-22:78-24:2-24:4-24:6-24:8-24:13-24:24-25:72-27:32-27:49-36:65-39:69-41:20-41:21-41:22-43:19-43:86-46:10-57:19-59:11-63:1-65:2-83:21)",
      "d": "« » means testimony. And this testimony is of two types. One is eyewitness testimony, meaning a fact that a person has complete certainty about, and they give witness of it before a judge. The second is heart's testimony, like the testimony of faith (Shahadah). Every Muslim gives witness of it, although they have not seen Allah, and except for the Companions (ra), other Muslims have not seen the Messenger of Allah (ﷺ) either. Then when this heart's testimony is related to oneself, its meaning becomes \"to confess\".\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قَالُوۡا شَہِدۡنَا عَلٰۤی اَنۡفُسِنَا وَ غَرَّتۡہُمُ الۡحَیٰوۃُ الدُّنۡیَا»\nTranslation: \"They will say, 'Our Lord, we have confessed against ourselves.' And the worldly life had deluded them.\""
    }
  ],
  "46": [
    {
      "id": 241,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Unique",
      "hw": "اکیلا",
      "s": "« » unique, peerless, used for Allah or a creation without equal (72 verses: 2:96-2:102-2:136-2:180-2:266-2:285-3:73-3:84-3:91-3:153-4:18-4:43-4:152-5:6-5:20-5:27-5:106-5:115-6:61-7:80-9:4-9:6-9:84-9:127-11:81-12:4-12:36-12:41-12:78-15:65-16:58-16:76-17:23-18:19-18:22-18:26-18:32-18:38-18:42-18:47-18:49-18:110-19:26-19:98-23:99-24:6-24:21-24:28-29:28-33:32-33:39-33:40-35:41-38:35-43:17-49:12-59:11-63:10-69:47-72:2-72:7-72:18-72:20-72:22-72:26-89:25-89:26-90:5-90:7-92:19-112:1-112:4)",
      "d": "«اَحَد» «وَاحِد» «اَحَد» «وَاحِد» «اَحَدَ عَشَرَ، اَحَدَھُمَ، اَحَدٌ مِّنْکُم، اَحَدُکُم، یَوَمُ الْاَحَد» «لَیْسَ فِی الدَّارِاَحَدٌ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَمَا مِنۡکُمۡ مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ عَنۡہُ حٰجِزِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: \"Then none of you will be able to hinder Us from [punishing] him.\"\n«وَاحِد» «ھُوَ اللہُ الْوَاحِدُ الْقَھَّارُ» «قُلۡ ہُوَ اللّٰہُ اَحَدٌ»\nTranslation: \"Say, 'He is Allah, the One.'\"\nWe say it means He is unique, peerless, and one of a kind. And in these meanings, this word is specific to the essence of Allah the Almighty."
    },
    {
      "id": 242,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Unique",
      "hw": "اکیلا",
      "s": "« » unique, peerless, used for creations (1 verse: 74:11)",
      "d": "«وَاحِد» «وَحِیْد» «اَلشَّمْسُ وَاحِدَۃٌ» «فُلَانٌ وَاحِدُ عَصْرِہٖ» «وَحِیْد»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ذَرۡنِیۡ وَ مَنۡ خَلَقۡتُ وَحِیۡدًا»\nTranslation: \"Leave Me and whom I created alone.\"\nThis verse is about Walid ibn al-Mughirah, who at that time had no equal in offspring and in honor and wealth."
    }
  ],
  "47": [
    {
      "id": 246,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Uprooting. To be uprooted.",
      "hw": "اکھاڑنا",
      "s": "« » is used for the uprooting of large trees whose roots go deep into the ground (1 verse: 54:20).",
      "d": "«قَعَرَ» «اَقْعَرَ الْبِئْر» «اَقْعَرَ الشَّجر»\nThus, « » is a word used for the uprooting of very large trees whose roots have extended deep into the earth, and « » is used when the action of doing this occurs or is apparent on that thing.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«تَنۡزِعُ  النَّاسَ ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اَعۡجَازُ نَخۡلٍ مُّنۡقَعِرٍ»\nTranslation: (The violent wind) would snatch away people as if they were uprooted palm trunks.\nNote: (Uprooting: meaning to destroy something, to demolish, to uproot from the root, to dig up the root, to cut off the lineage, to annihilate)."
    }
  ],
  "48": [
    {
      "id": 247,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "« » is a general word for gathering. The word 'gathering' is used for bringing together different parts of one thing or different things (113 verses: 2:29-2:38-2:148-2:161-2:165-3:25-3:87-3:103-3:155-3:157-3:166-3:173-4:23-4:71-4:87-4:139-4:140-4:172-5:17-5:32-5:36-5:48-5:105-5:109-6:12-6:22-6:35-6:128-6:149-7:18-7:38-7:48-7:124-7:158-8:37-8:41-8:63-10:4-10:28-10:58-10:65-10:99-11:55-11:119-12:15-12:83-12:93-13:18-13:31-13:42-14:8-14:21-15:30-15:39-15:43-15:59-15:92-16:9-17:103-18:60-18:61-18:99-20:60-20:64-20:123-21:77-24:31-24:61-26:38-26:49-26:56-26:61-26:65-26:95-26:170-27:51-28:78-32:13-34:26-34:40-35:10-36:32-36:53-37:134-38:73-38:82-38:85-39:44-39:47-39:53-39:67-42:7-42:15-42:29-43:32-43:55-44:40-45:13-45:26-54:44-54:45-58:6-58:18-59:14-64:9-70:14-70:18-75:3-75:9-75:17-77:38-100:5-104:2).",
      "d": "The word « » comes for bringing together different parts of one thing, or different things. These can be animate or inanimate.\nFor example: For animate things: The divine command states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ  قَالَ لَہُمُ النَّاسُ  اِنَّ النَّاسَ قَدۡ جَمُوۡا لَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: When those people came and said, 'Indeed, the disbelievers have gathered against you (a great army).'\nAnd for inanimate things: The divine command states:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَمَعَ  مَالًا  وَّ عَدَّدَہٗ»\nTranslation: Who gathers wealth and counts it over and over.\nThen the word 'gathering' is also used for apparent things. It is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَتَوَلّٰی فِرۡعَوۡنُ فَجَمَعَ  کَیۡدَہٗ  ثُمَّ  اَتٰی»\nTranslation: Then Pharaoh turned back and gathered his plan, then came (Othmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 248,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "« » is used only for gathering living beings (3 verses: 17:88-22:73-26:39).",
      "d": "The word « » is only used for the gathering of those with intellect (possessing reason). Whether they are of the same kind or different.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّئِنِ اجۡتَمَعَتِ الۡاِنۡسُ وَ الۡجِنُّ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ یَّاۡتُوۡا بِمِثۡلِ ہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنِ لَا یَاۡتُوۡنَ بِمِثۡلِہٖ»\nTranslation: Say, 'If mankind and the jinn gathered together to produce the like of this Quran, they could not produce the like thereof.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 249,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "« », meaning assembly, crowd, throng, is used for gathering living beings by raising them from their places to one location (39 verses: 2:203-3:12-3:158-4:172-5:96-6:22-6:38-6:51-6:72-6:111-6:128-8:24-8:36-10:28-10:45-15:25-17:97-18:47-19:68-19:85-20:59-20:102-20:124-20:125-23:79-25:17-25:34-27:17-27:83-34:40-37:22-41:19-46:6-50:44-58:9-59:2-67:24-79:23-81:5).",
      "d": "«حَشَرَ» «اَلْحَشْرُ الْجَمْعُ مَعَ سَوْق»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَحَشَرَ فَنَادٰی فَقَالَ اَنَا رَبُّکُمُ الۡاَعۡلٰی»\nTranslation: So (Pharaoh) gathered (his people) and called out, saying, 'I am your lord, the most high.'\nThen this word is sometimes also used in the meanings of « » or « » (m, l), i.e., to resurrect the dead or to take to a specific purpose. See the following example in the meaning of « »:\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«قَالَ رَبِّ  لِمَ حَشَرۡتَنِیۡۤ  اَعۡمٰی وَ قَدۡ کُنۡتُ  بَصِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: He will say, 'My Lord, why have You gathered me [from the grave] blind while I was [once] a seeing [person]?'\nAnd sometimes in the usage of this word, the meanings of «  ,  » and « » are all found.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یَوۡمَ نُسَیِّرُ الۡجِبَالَ وَ تَرَی الۡاَرۡضَ بَارِزَۃً ۙ وَّ حَشَرۡنٰہُمۡ  فَلَمۡ  نُغَادِرۡ  مِنۡہِمۡ اَحَدًا»\nTranslation: And [mention] the Day We will move the mountains and you will see the earth exposed, and We will gather them and not leave from them anyone."
    },
    {
      "id": 250,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "« » is used for gathering necessary things for the future (1 verse: 3:49).",
      "d": "The original root of « » is « » which means to store provisions, i.e., edible things, for future needs. To stockpile (mufrad). And many other living beings besides humans also do this storing. Ibn Faris writes two basic things in its meaning: to gather and to preserve it (m, l). And « » also comes in this same meaning. The gathered thing is called « » and « ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اُنَبِّئُکُمۡ بِمَا تَاۡکُلُوۡنَ وَمَا تَدَّخِرُوۡنَ ۙ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: (Jesus, peace be upon him, said) And I inform you of what you eat and what you store in your houses."
    },
    {
      "id": 251,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Gather; To Be Gathered",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "« » To gather (for protection) (13 verses: 6:50-11:31-12:55-15:21-15:22-17:100-38:9-39:71-39:73-40:49-52:37-63:7-67:8)",
      "d": "«خَزَنَ» «خَزَنْتُ الدَّرَاھِمَ» «خَزَنْتُ السِّرَّ» «خَازِنْ» «خَزَنَۃُ»\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ  اُلۡقِیَ فِیۡہَا  فَوۡجٌ سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ  اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ »\nTranslation: Whenever a group is thrown into it (Hell), its keepers (guardians) will ask them: Did no warner come to you?\nAnd where something is gathered, that place is called « » and « », and its plural is « ». In the mentioned verse, the gathered things are the sinful people, Hell is the treasury, and the guardian or keeper is the  ."
    },
    {
      "id": 253,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "« » meaning to gather and take into custody, to collect (1 verse: 77:25).",
      "d": "«کَفَتَ» «کَفِیْت» «اَللّٰھُمَّ اکْفِہٖ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ نَجۡعَلِ الۡاَرۡضَ  کِفَاتًا اَحۡیَآءً وَّاَمۡوَاتًا»\nTranslation: Have We not made the earth a container [that gathers] the living and the dead?"
    },
    {
      "id": 254,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To gather. To be gathered.",
      "hw": "اکٹھا ",
      "s": "« » meaning to gather and to put in order, i.e., to fix (1 verse: 89:19).",
      "d": "« » meaning to gather something and to arrange it or to fix it (mufrad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَتَاۡکُلُوۡنَ التُّرَاثَ اَکۡلًا لَّمًّا»\nTranslation: And you consume the inheritance, devouring it greedily."
    }
  ],
  "49": [
    {
      "id": 257,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "If",
      "hw": "اگر",
      "s": "« » It is called the conditional particle in Arabic grammar. Used for the future. (531 verses: 2:23-2:24-2:31-2:70-2:78-2:85-2:91-2:93-2:94-2:11-2:137-2:143-2:172-2:180-2:184-2:191-2:192-2:193-2:196-2:198-2:209-2:217-2:220-2:226-2:227-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:233-2:236-2:237-2:239-2:240-2:246-2:248-2:265-2:271-2:278-2:279-2:280-2:282-2:283-2:284-2:286-3:20-3:29-3:31-3:32-3:49-3:63-3:64-3:75-3:93-3:100-3:111-3:118-3:120-3:125-3:139-3:140-3:144-3:149-3:160-3:164-3:168-3:175-3:179-3:183-3:184-3:186-4:3-4:4-4:6-4:11-4:12-4:15-4:16-4:19-4:20-4:23-4:25-4:31-4:34-4:35-4:40-4:43-4:59-4:62-4:72-4:78-4:89-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:101-4:102-4:104-4:117-4:128-4:129-4:130-4:131-4:133-4:135-4:141-4:147-4:149-4:159-4:170-4:176-5:6-5:17-5:22-5:23-5:41-5:42-5:49-5:57-5:67-5:73-5:92-5:101-5:106-5:107-5:110-5:112-5:116-5:118-6:7-6:15-6:17-6:25-6:26-6:29-6:35-6:40-6:41-6:46-6:47-6:50-6:57-6:70-6:81-6:89-6:90-6:116-6:118-6:121-6:133-6:139-6:143-6:147-6:148-6:150-6:156-7:23-7:70-7:77-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:102-7:106-7:113-7:131-7:143-7:146-7:155-7:169-7:176-7:184-7:188-7:193-7:194-7:198-8:1-8:19-8:29-8:31-8:32-8:34-8:38-8:39-8:40-8:41-8:61-8:62-8:65-8:66-8:70-8:71-8:72-9:3-9:5-9:6-9:8-9:11-9:12-9:13-9:23-9:24-9:28-9:41-9:50-9:58-9:62-9:66-9:74-9:80-9:83-9:96-9:107-9:129-10:15-10:29-10:38-10:41-10:48-10:50-10:66-10:68-10:71-10:72-10:84-10:94-10:104-10:106-10:107-11:3-11:7-11:13-11:28-11:29-11:30-11:32-11:33-11:34-11:35-11:38-11:50-11:51-11:54-11:57-11:63-11:86-11:88-12:3-12:10-12:26-12:27-12:31-12:40-12:43-12:60-12:67-12:74-12:77-12:91-12:99-12:104-13:5-13:40-14:8-14:10-14:11-14:19-14:34-14:46-15:7-15:21-15:71-15:78-16:18-16:37-16:43-16:82-16:95-16:114-16:126-17:7-17:8-17:25-17:44-17:47-17:52-17:54-17:58-17:73-17:76-17:108-18:5-18:6-18:20-18:29-18:39-18:57-18:69-18:70-18:76-19:18-19:71-19:93-20:7-20:63-20:103-20:104-21:7-21:17-21:34-21:36-21:38-21:47-21:63-21:68-21:109-21:111-22:5-22:11-22:41-22:42-22:68-22:73-23:25-23:30-23:37-23:38-23:83-23:84-23:88-23:107-23:114-24:2-24:7-24:9-24:17-24:28-24:32-24:33-24:49-24:54-25:4-25:8-25:10-25:41-25:42-25:44-26:4-26:24-26:28-26:31-26:40-26:41-26:97-26:109-26:113-26:115-26:127-26:137-26:145-26:154-26:164-26:180-26:186-26:187-26:205-26:216-27:64-27:68-27:71-27:81-28:10-28:19-28:27-28:49-28:50-28:57-28:71-28:72-29:8-29:16-29:18-29:29-30:36-30:49-30:53-30:58-31:15-31:16-32:28-33:5-33:13-33:16-33:17-33:20-33:24-33:28-33:29-33:32-33:50-33:54-34:9-34:29-34:43-34:46-34:47-34:50-35:4-35:14-35:16-35:18-35:23-35:24-35:25-35:40-35:41-36:15-36:23-36:29-36:32-36:43-36:47-36:48-36:53-36:69-37:15-37:56-37:102-37:157-37:167-38:7-38:14-38:70-38:87-39:7-39:13-39:38-39:56-40:12-40:28-40:29-40:56-41:13-41:24-41:37-41:38-41:49-41:52-42:24-42:33-42:48-43:20-43:35-43:59-43:81-44:7-44:21-44:35-44:36-45:24-45:25-45:32-46:4-46:8-46:9-46:10-46:22-46:26-47:7-47:22-47:36-47:37-47:38-48:11-48:16-48:27-49:6-49:9-49:14-49:17-52:34-52:44-53:4-53:23-53:28-54:2-55:33-56:86-56:87-56:88-56:90-56:92-57:8-58:2-58:12-59:11-60:1-60:2-60:10-60:11-61:11-62:2-62:6-62:9-63:4-64:12-64:14-64:17-65:4-65:6-66:4-66:5-67:9-67:20-67:21-67:25-67:28-67:30-68:22-68:41-68:51-71:27-72:25-73:17-74:24-74:25-77:39-81:27-86:4-87:9-96:11-96:13)",
      "d": "« » is a conditional particle. It is used for the future. The first clause (condition) is always a verb, and the second clause (result) follows.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اِنۡ تُعَذِّبۡہُمۡ فَاِنَّہُمۡ عِبَادُکَ»\nTranslation: If You punish them, they are Your servants."
    },
    {
      "id": 258,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "If",
      "hw": "اگر",
      "s": "« » in Arabic grammar, when « » comes in the meaning of 'if', it has the extra particle « » which comes only for emphasis ( beautification of speech) (22 verses: 2:38-6:68-7:35-7:115-7:200-8:57-8:58-9:106-10:46-17:23-17:28-18:86-19:26-19:75-20:65-20:123-23:93-40:77-41:36-43:41-47:4-76:3).",
      "d": "«اِنْ ۔ مَا» «اِنْ» «مَا»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِمَّا یَبۡلُغَنَّ عِنۡدَکَ الۡکِبَرَ اَحَدُہِمَاۤ»\nTranslation: If one of them or both of them reaches old age in your presence.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«فَاِمَّا تَرَیِنَّ مِنَ الۡبَشَرِ اَحَدًا»\nTranslation: Then (O Mary!) if you see any human being..."
    },
    {
      "id": 259,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "If",
      "hw": "اگر",
      "s": "In « », the consequence is always attached to the condition (i.e., a condition is stipulated in return for an action). (214 verses: 2:20-2:64-2:96-2:102-2:103-2:109-2:251-2:165-2:167-2:220-2:221-2:253-3:30-3:69-3:91-3:110-3:154-3:156-3:159-3:167-3:168-4:9-4:39-4:42-4:46-4:64-4:66-4:78-4:82-4:83-4:89-4:90-4:102-4:113-4:129-4:135-5:36-5:48-5:65-5:66-5:81-5:100-5:106-6:7-6:8-6:9-6:27-6:28-6:30-6:35-6:58-6:88-6:93-6:107-6:111-6:112-6:137-6:148-6:149-6:152-6:157-7:43-7:96-7:100-7:155-7:176-7:188-8:8-8:19-8:23-8:31-8:42-8:43-8:50-8:63-8:68-9:32-9:33-9:42-9:46-9:47-9:57-9:59-9:81-9:113-10:11-10:16-10:19-10:42-10:43-10:54-10:82-10:97-10:99-11:80-11:91-11:110-11:118-12:17-12:24-12:94-12:103-13:18-13:31-14:21-15:2-15:7-15:14-16:9-16:35-16:41-16:61-16:93-17:42-17:74-17:88-17:95-17:100-18:18-18:58-18:77-18:109-20:129-20:134-21:17-21:22-21:39-21:99-22:40-22:73-23:24-23:71-23:75-23:114-24:10-24:14-24:20-24:21-24:35-25:42-25:45-25:51-25:77-26:102-26:113-26:198-28:10-28:47-28:64-28:82-29:41-29:53-29:64-31:27-32:12-32:13-33:14-33:20-33:52-34:14-34:31-34:51-35:14-35:18-35:45-36:47-36:66-36:67-37:57-37:143-37:168-39:4-39:26-39:47-39:57-39:58-40:14-41:14-41:44-41:45-42:8-42:14-42:21-42:27-43:20-43:33-43:60-46:11-47:4-47:21-47:30-48:22-48:25-49:5-49:7-56:65-56:70-56:76-58:22-59:3-59:9-59:21-60:2-61:8-61:9-67:10-68:9-68:33-68:49-69:44-70:11-71:4-75:15-102:5)",
      "d": "« » is a conditional particle, but its consequence is always attached to the condition (i.e., a condition is stipulated in return for an action), and its consequence includes the particle « » (lam).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَوۡ کَانَ عَرَضًا قَرِیۡبًا وَّ سَفَرًا قَاصِدًا لَّاتَّبَعُوۡکَ»\nTranslation: If the spoils had been near and the journey short, they would have followed you (O Prophet).\nAnd if « » precedes « », as in « », it gives the meaning of 'even if' or 'although'.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَیۡنَ مَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا یُدۡرِکۡکُّمُ الۡمَوۡتُ وَ لَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ  فِیۡ  بُرُوۡجٍ مُّشَیَّدَۃٍ»\nTranslation: Wherever you may be, death will overtake you, even if you are in fortified towers.\nAnd adding « » after « » creates the meaning of 'if not'.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنۡتُمۡ لَکُنَّا مُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: If it were not for you, we would certainly have been believers."
    }
  ],
  "50": [
    {
      "id": 260,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "The meaning of « » is to turn something onto its head (i.e., head down and feet up). (2 verses: 4:88-4:91)",
      "d": "«اَرْکَسَ» «اَرْکَسَ الثَّوبُ فِی الصَّبْغِ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ اَرۡکَسَہُمۡ بِمَا کَسَبُوۡا»\nTranslation: Allah has turned them (the hypocrites) upside down because of what they earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 261,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "« » means to turn to a direction other than the correct one. (3 verses: 9:70-53:53-69:9)",
      "d": "« » means to turn someone away from the correct path. And if one is turned to a direction other than the correct one, it is called « ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الۡمُؤۡتَفِکَۃَ  اَہۡوٰی»\nTranslation: And He turned upside down the overturned towns."
    },
    {
      "id": 262,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "« » means to fall or become stuck face down. (5 verses: 7:78-7:91-11:67-11:94-29:37)",
      "d": "« » refers to a bird sitting on its chest on the ground and then sticking there. Figuratively, it means for a person to lie face down on the ground.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَخَذَتۡہُمُ الرَّجۡفَۃُ فَاَصۡبَحُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِہِمۡ  جٰثِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: So the earthquake seized them, and they became lying upside down in their homes."
    },
    {
      "id": 263,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "« » means to fall face down. (3 verses: 26:94-27:90-67:22)",
      "d": "«کَبَّ الْاِنَاءَ» «کَبَّ فُلَانًا»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ جَآءَ بِالسَّیِّئَۃِ  فَکُبَّتۡ وُجُوۡہُہُمۡ  فِی النَّارِ»\nTranslation: And whoever comes with an evil deed, their faces will be turned upside down in the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 264,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To turn upside down, to invert",
      "hw": "الٹ",
      "s": "« » means to tumble and throw headfirst into a pit. (1 verse: 26:94)",
      "d": "In « », there is reduplication which intensifies its meaning. It means to throw something down from above, tumbling it, into a pit.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَکُبۡکِبُوۡا فِیۡہَا  ہُمۡ  وَ الۡغَاوٗنَ»\nTranslation: So they and the misguided (i.e., the idols and idolaters) will be tumbled headfirst into it."
    }
  ],
  "51": [
    {
      "id": 267,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to divide or isolate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » means to split something apart and separate it. (32 verses: 2:50-2:53-2:102-2:136-2:185-2:285-3:4-3:84-3:103-3:105-4:130-4:150-4:152-5:25-6:153-6:159-8:29-8:41-12:39-12:67-17:106-20:94-21:48-25:1-26:63-30:14-30:32-42:13-42:14-44:4-77:4-98:4)",
      "d": "« » means to split something apart and separate it. Then the separated thing is called « ». And if the separated things are groups of people, they are called factions. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ»\nTranslation: And when We parted the sea for you.\nIn another instance, the Divine declaration is:\n«فَانۡفَلَقَ فَکَانَ کُلُّ فِرۡقٍ  کَالطَّوۡدِ  الۡعَظِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: So it parted, and each portion became like a great mountain.\nThen « » is also used in a spiritual sense. That is, to separate two types of things that may appear similar but are essentially different.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ رَبِّ اِنِّیۡ  لَاۤ  اَمۡلِکُ اِلَّا نَفۡسِیۡ وَ اَخِیۡ فَافۡرُقۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَ الۡقَوۡمِ الۡفٰسِقِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Moses said, 'My Lord, I have no control over myself or my brother, so separate between us and the defiant people.'\nAnd « » means to separate from a group, to form a separate faction.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ فَرَّقُوۡا دِیۡنَہُمۡ  وَ کَانُوۡا  شِیَعًا»\nTranslation: Indeed, those who split their religion and became factions."
    },
    {
      "id": 268,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to divide or isolate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » means to split something open and separate it, or to separate merged things. (1 verse: 21:30)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is to create a large fissure in something and open it. Like opening the musk pod (the sac in a deer where musk is stored). Or to separate two merged things. Its opposite is « », meaning something is sewn together or joined.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَنَّ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ کَانَتَا رَتۡقًا فَفَتَقۡنٰہُمَا»\nTranslation: The heavens and the earth were a joined entity, and We separated them."
    },
    {
      "id": 269,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Separate (To Make Separate or Distinct)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » To separate someone from their work. (2 verses: 11:42-33:51)",
      "d": "« » means to separate someone from their original work or purpose. To render idle. To set aside (m. r. manjad).   also comes from this. A person is called   who has been separated from work. And « » means solitude.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ مَنِ ابۡتَغَیۡتَ مِمَّنۡ عَزَلۡتَ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکَ»\nTranslation: And whoever you have separated, there is no blame on you."
    },
    {
      "id": 270,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to divide or isolate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » means to keep someone separate and away from a calamity. (3 verses: 14:35-87:11-92:17)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of « » are two: (1) side, (2) to be distant. And « » means to keep someone away from a calamity or disaster, to save them.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذۡ قَالَ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمُ رَبِّ اجۡعَلۡ ہٰذَا الۡبَلَدَ اٰمِنًا وَّاجۡنُبۡنِیۡ وَ بَنِیَّ اَنۡ نَّعۡبُدَ الۡاَصۡنَامَ»\nTranslation: And when Abraham said, 'My Lord, make this city secure and keep me and my sons away from worshipping idols.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 271,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Separate (To Make Separate or Distinct)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » To separate something from another based on superiority and preference. (2 verses: 3:179-8:37)",
      "d": "«مَازَ» «مَا زَالشَّیء»\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«مَا کَانَ اللّٰہُ لِیَذَرَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ عَلٰی مَاۤ اَنۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ حَتّٰی یَمِیۡزَ الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنَ الطَّیِّبِ»\nTranslation: Allah will not leave the believers in the state you are in until He separates the evil from the good."
    },
    {
      "id": 273,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Become Separate (To Become Distinct or Separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » To become separate and scattered from the group. (10 verses: 3:103-3:105-4:130-6:153-12:39-12:67-30:14-42:13-42:14-98:4)",
      "d": "« » is the opposite of « ». Meaning to become separate and scattered. To split and become separate (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ اعۡتَصِمُوۡا بِحَبۡلِ اللّٰہِ جَمِیۡعًا وَّ لَا تَفَرَّقُوۡا»\nTranslation: And hold firmly to the rope of Allah all together and do not become separated."
    },
    {
      "id": 275,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Become Separate (To Become Distinct or Separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » To become separate from something and go far to avoid calamity. (1 verse: 87:11)",
      "d": "« » means to stay away, to turn aside.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«سَیَذَّکَّرُ مَنۡ یَّخۡشٰی وَ  یَتَجَنَّبُہَا الۡاَشۡقَی»\nTranslation: He who fears will be reminded, and the wretched will turn aside."
    },
    {
      "id": 276,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » to be separate from others based on a characteristic (1 verse: 36:59)",
      "d": "« » means to separate the good from the evil or the evil from the good based on excellence and preference.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَامۡتَازُوا الۡیَوۡمَ اَیُّہَا الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And O you criminals! Separate yourselves today.\n«خَلَا، خَلَو، خَلَصَ، فَصَلَ، اِنْتَبَذَ، نَبَذَ، تَزَیَّلَ، زَیَّلَ، and تَجَافٰی، جَفَو»"
    },
    {
      "id": 277,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » to be separate in order to meet in solitude (9 verses: 2:14-2:76-2:214-3:119-10:102-24:34-33:38-33:62-35:24)",
      "d": "« خَلَاء ، یَخْلُو» «خَلَا الزَّمَان» «خَلَا الرَّجُل»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَاِذَا خَلَوۡا اِلٰی شَیٰطِیۡنِہِمۡ ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا مَعَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And when they are alone with their evil ones, they say: Indeed, we are with you. ( )"
    },
    {
      "id": 278,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » to be separate from the mixture with the original thing and to remain pure (24 verses: 2:139-4:146-7:29-10:22-12:24-12:54-12:80-15:40-19:51-29:65-31:32-37:40-37:74-37:128-37:160-37:169-38:46-38:83-39:2-39:11-39:14-40:14-40:65-98:5)",
      "d": "« » means to purify a thing from mixture and to separate the mixture from it, and its opposite is « ».\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّا اسۡتَیۡئَسُوۡا مِنۡہُ خَلَصُوۡا نَجِیًّا»\nTranslation: When they lost hope from him, they consulted in private.\nmeaning they went and sat apart from others in order to consult among themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 279,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » to separate two things from each other in such a way that a distance is created between them (20 verses: 2:249-6:65-6:97-6:98-6:114-6:119-6:126-7:32-7:52-7:133-7:174-9:11-10:5-10:24-11:1-12:94-17:12-30:28-41:3-41:44)",
      "d": "« » means for two things to be separate such that a distance exists between them (see Mufradat) or to depart from a place:\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّا فَصَلَ طَالُوۡتُ بِالۡجُنُوۡدِ  ۙ قَالَ  اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مُبۡتَلِیۡکُمۡ بِنَہَرٍ»\nTranslation: So when Talut departed with the armies, he said: Indeed, Allah will test you with a river."
    },
    {
      "id": 280,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » to be separate from others due to a feeling of inferiority (2 verses: 19:16-19:22)",
      "d": "« » means to throw something considering it unworthy of attention (i.e., something that is forgettable and not worthy of consideration) (see Mufradat), and « » means to be separate from others while being in a state of self-perceived inferiority.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَاذۡکُرۡ فِی الۡکِتٰبِ مَرۡیَمَ ۘ اِذِ انۡتَبَذَتۡ مِنۡ اَہۡلِہَا مَکَانًا شَرۡقِیًّا»\nTranslation: And mention in the Book (the story of) Maryam when she withdrew from her family to a place towards the east.\nAt this point, the word « » is used for Maryam (Mary) because, due to the pregnancy of Prophet Isa (Jesus), she went away in solitude to avoid people's objections and curses."
    },
    {
      "id": 281,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » to leave one's place and to move aside, to become separate (1 verse: 48:25)",
      "d": "« » means to remove something from its place (see Mufradat), and accordingly, « » means for something to leave its place and scatter around, to move aside and go far away.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«لَوۡ تَزَیَّلُوۡا لَعَذَّبۡنَا الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡہُمۡ عَذَابًا اَلِیۡمًا»\nTranslation: And if they had separated, We would have punished those among them who disbelieved with a painful punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 282,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To separate (to be different, to be separate)",
      "hw": "الگ",
      "s": "« » to be separate from something due to restlessness (1 verse: 32:16)",
      "d": "«جَفْوَۃٌ» «جَفَاءٌ» «جَفَا یَجْفُوا» «تَجَافٰی»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«تَتَجَافٰی جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ عَنِ الۡمَضَاجِعِ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ خَوۡفًا وَّ طَمَعًا»\nTranslation: Their sides (i.e., their bodies) keep away from the beds (as they pray) while they call upon their Lord in fear and hope."
    }
  ],
  "52": [
    {
      "id": 283,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To hope",
      "hw": "امید",
      "s": "« » is used for hope that is long-awaited and seemingly unexpected (3 verses: 15:3-18:46-47:25)",
      "d": "The discussion of « » has passed in 'desire' ( ), and its meaning is such a desire and hope that is seemingly unexpected and long-awaited. Thus, « » includes the concept of duration and waiting. In this sense, it comes to mean 'to place hope'.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ الۡبٰقِیٰتُ الصّٰلِحٰتُ خَیۡرٌ عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ ثَوَابًا وَّخَیۡرٌاَمَلًا»\nTranslation: And the lasting righteous deeds are better for your Lord in reward and better for hope."
    },
    {
      "id": 284,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To hope",
      "hw": "امید",
      "s": "« » is used for instilling false hopes (2 verses: 4:119-22:52)",
      "d": "«اَمْنِیَۃ» «اَمَانِی» «اَمْنٰی»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَّ لَاُضِلَّنَّہُمۡ وَ لَاُمَنِّیَنَّہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And I will surely mislead them and surely instill false hopes in them."
    }
  ],
  "53": [
    {
      "id": 286,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Intestines",
      "hw": "انتڑیاں",
      "s": "« » is used for those intestines which appear like the coil of a snake (1 verse: 6:146)",
      "d": "«حَوَایَا» «حَوِیَّۃ» «حَیَّۃٌ» «تَحْوِی الْحَیّۃ» «حَاوِی»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«حَرَّمۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ شُحُوۡمَہُمَاۤ اِلَّا مَا حَمَلَتۡ ظُہُوۡرُہُمَاۤ اَوِالۡحَوَایَاۤ اَوۡمَا اخۡتَلَطَ بِعَظۡمٍ»\nTranslation: And We have forbidden them the fat of both (the cow and the goat) except what is on their backs or the intestines or what is mixed with bone."
    },
    {
      "id": 287,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Intestines",
      "hw": "انتڑیاں",
      "s": "« » is used for all kinds of small and large intestines (1 verse: 47:15)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». This word is general and is used for all kinds of small and large intestines.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَسُقُوۡا مَآءً حَمِیۡمًا فَقَطَّعَ اَمۡعَآءَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And they will be given to drink boiling water which will cut their intestines."
    }
  ],
  "54": [
    {
      "id": 290,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Wait",
      "hw": "انتظار",
      "s": "« » is waiting for a period to gain benefit or for a specified period (12 verses: 2:226, 2:228, 2:234, 4:141, 9:24, 9:52, 9:98, 20:135, 23:25, 52:30, 52:31, 57:14)",
      "d": "«رَبَصَ» «تَرَبُّص» «تَرَبُّص بِسِلْعَۃٍ»\nSimilarly, for a woman, waiting to complete her 'iddah (waiting period) will be called « », and it also means waiting to gain more benefit. (Faq. 59)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قُلۡ ہَلۡ تَرَبَّصُوۡنَ بِنَاۤ اِلَّاۤ اِحۡدَی الۡحُسۡنَیَیۡنِ ؕ وَنَحۡنُ نَتَرَبَّصُ بِکُمۡ اَنۡ یُّصِیۡبَکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِعَذَابٍ مِّنۡ عِنۡدِہٖۤ اَوۡبِاَیۡدِیۡنَا ۫ ۖ فَتَرَبَّصُوۡۤا اِنَّا مَعَکُمۡ مُّتَرَبِّصُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Say, 'Do you wait for us except one of the two good things (martyrdom or victory)? And we are waiting for you that Allah will afflict you with a punishment from Himself or by our hands. So wait, indeed we, with you, are waiting.'"
    }
  ],
  "55": [
    {
      "id": 293,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Outcome (of an action)",
      "hw": "انجام",
      "s": "« » is used for the outcome of an action and its recompense (32 verses: 3:137-6:11-6:135-7:84-7:86-7:103-7:128-10:39-10:73-11:49-12:109-16:36-20:132-22:41-27:14-27:51-27:69-28:37-28:40-28:83-30:9-30:10-30:42-31:22-35:44-37:73-40:21-40:82-43:25-47:10-59:17-65:9)",
      "d": "« » means heel, and « » means to follow behind someone and to come behind, and « » is the end of everything or the outcome of an action (see Mufradat). Then in the meaning of ' ', intensity and hardship are also found. « » means to seize someone in return for their action, and the word « » is generally used for the recompense of a bad deed.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَجٰدَلُوۡا بِالۡبَاطِلِ لِیُدۡحِضُوۡا بِہِ الۡحَقَّ فَاَخَذۡتُہُمۡ ۟ فَکَیۡفَ کَانَ عِقَابِ»\nTranslation: And they argued by falsehood to refute the truth, so I seized them. So how was My punishment?\nThus, the word « » is applied not only to the outcome of an action but also to its recompense.\nFor example, for good, the divine command is:\n«اِنَّ الۡاَرۡضَ لِلّٰہِ ۟ ۙ یُوۡرِثُہَا مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِہٖ ؕ وَ الۡعَاقِبَۃُ  لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Indeed, the earth belongs to Allah; He causes to inherit it whom He wills of His servants. And the (good) outcome is for the pious.\nAnd for evil, the divine command is:\n«قَدۡ خَلَتۡ مِنۡ قَبۡلِکُمۡ سُنَنٌ ۙ فَسِیۡرُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡظُرُوۡا کَیۡفَ کَانَ عَاقِبَۃُ الۡمُکَذِّبِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: There have already passed before you ways of life. So travel through the earth and observe how was the end of the deniers."
    }
  ],
  "56": [
    {
      "id": 294,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Estimate",
      "hw": "اندازہ ",
      "s": "« » is an estimate based on conjecture and guess rather than knowledge and reality. And it is unreliable (4 verses: 6:116, 6:148, 10:66, 43:20)",
      "d": "«خَرَصَ» «خَرَصَ النَّخْلَۃ» «خَرَّاص» «خَرَّاص»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنۡ تَتَّبِعُوۡنَ اِلَّا الظَّنَّ وَ اِنۡ اَنۡتُمۡ اِلَّا تَخۡرُصُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: You follow not except assumption, and indeed, you do nothing but lie."
    },
    {
      "id": 295,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Estimate",
      "hw": "اندازہ ",
      "s": "« » refers to those natural laws which Allah, the Exalted, has decreed with His knowledge and wisdom, and they are firmly established. And « » is the term for an estimate based on such laws (11 verses: 13:26, 17:30, 28:82, 29:62, 30:37, 34:36, 34:39, 39:52, 42:12, 65:7, 89:16)",
      "d": "« » means to devise a matter, to prepare something, and to manage it (Munjid). And « » refers to those natural laws under which a thing comes into existence and is organized (Muf). And this attribute is specific to Allah, the Exalted, and comes only in good meanings. (Faq. 157)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنَّا کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ خَلَقۡنٰہُ بِقَدَرٍ»\nTranslation: We have created all things according to a precise measure.\n«قَدَّرَ» «وَالْقَدْرِ خَیْرِہٖ وَشَرِّہٖ مِنَ اللہِ تَعَالیٰ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ الشَّمۡسَ ضِیَآءً وَّ الۡقَمَرَ نُوۡرًا وَّ قَدَّرَہٗ  مَنَازِلَ  لِتَعۡلَمُوۡا عَدَدَ السِّنِیۡنَ وَ الۡحِسَابَ»\nTranslation: It is He who made the sun a shining light and the moon a derived light and determined for it phases that you may know the number of years and the account."
    }
  ],
  "57": [
    {
      "id": 298,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Inside",
      "hw": "اندر",
      "s": "« » is the internal cavity of something (1 verse: 33:4)",
      "d": "«سَمَاء» «سَمُوْء»\n«وَّ اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً»\nTranslation: And He sent down water from the sky.\n«اِنَّا زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ  الدُّنۡیَا بِزِیۡنَۃِۣ الۡکَوَاکِبِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, We have adorned the nearest heaven with the beauty of the stars.\nHere, the height referred to is as far as the stars shine, whether they are at hundreds of thousands of miles like the moon, or tens of millions like the sun, or billions of miles like Scorpio, etc.\n« » is a relative noun, and its opposite is « ». That is, every thing is   from the perspective of what is beneath it, and the same thing is also   from the perspective of what is above it (m.f.). So, a thing that is   relative to what is below it is also   relative to what is above it.\n«اَللّٰہُ  الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ سَبۡعَ  سَمٰوٰتٍ وَّ مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ مِثۡلَہُنَّ»\nTranslation: Allah is the One who created seven heavens and from the earth, similar to them.\nIn this verse, this meaning is found.\nThen, just as   is used in the meaning of height, « » is also used in the meaning of lowness.\n«وَ لَوۡ شِئۡنَا لَرَفَعۡنٰہُ بِہَا وَ لٰکِنَّہٗۤ اَخۡلَدَ اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ اتَّبَعَ ہَوٰىہُ»\nTranslation: And if We had willed, We could have elevated him thereby, but he adhered to the earth and followed his desire."
    }
  ],
  "58": [
    {
      "id": 299,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Blind",
      "hw": "اندھا",
      "s": "« » means blind (28 verses: 2:18, 2:171, 6:50, 6:104, 7:64, 10:43, 11:24, 11:28, 13:16, 13:19, 17:72, 17:97, 20:124, 20:125, 22:46, 24:61, 25:73, 27:81, 28:66, 30:53, 35:19, 40:58, 41:17, 41:44, 43:40, 47:23, 48:17, 80:20)",
      "d": "« » means blind, sightless, deprived of sight. Blindness of the eyes. (Fal. 39)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ہَلۡ یَسۡتَوِی الۡاَعۡمٰی وَ الۡبَصِیۡرُ»\nTranslation: Are the blind and the seeing equal?\nAlthough the application of this word is generally for physical blindness of the eyes, sometimes it is also used for blindness of the heart.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَمَاۤ اَنۡتَ بِہٰدِی الۡعُمۡیِ عَنۡ ضَلٰلَتِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And you cannot guide the blind away from their error."
    },
    {
      "id": 300,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Blind",
      "hw": "اندھا",
      "s": "« » is used for a person who is congenitally blind (2 verses: 3:49-5:110)",
      "d": "« » refers to a person who is blind from birth (m. l. manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ تُبۡرِیُٔ الۡاَکۡمَہَ وَ الۡاَبۡرَصَ بِاِذۡنِیۡ»\nTranslation: And (O Jesus PBUH) you used to cure the congenitally blind and the leper with My permission."
    }
  ],
  "59": [
    {
      "id": 302,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Justice",
      "hw": "انصاف",
      "s": "The word « » is used for giving someone their full right, whether all at once or in installments. (24 verses: 2:282-3:18-3:21-4:3-4:127-4:135-5:8-5:42-6:152-7:29-10:4-10:47-10:54-11:85-17:35-21:47-26:182-33:5-49:9-55:9-57:25-60:8-72:14-72:15)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is to give someone their full right completely; its fundamental meaning is to avoid injustice. (muf) In this sense, its meaning is taken as 'to do justice'. Its application is on doing justice in apparent matters. Therefore, the scales and measures for weighing are also called « » (faql 194).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاَقِیۡمُوا الۡوَزۡنَ بِالۡقِسۡطِ وَلَا تُخۡسِرُواالۡمِیۡزَانَ»\nTranslation: And establish weight in justice and do not make the scale deficient.\n«قِسْط» «قَسَطَ یَقْسُطُ» «قَسَطَ یَقْسِطُ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاَمَّا الۡقٰسِطُوۡنَ فَکَانُوۡا لِجَہَنَّمَ حَطَبًا»\nTranslation: And those who were unjust (oppressive) became fuel for Hell. (Uthmani RA)\nThen, whether someone's right is to be paid in one handful or in several parts, the words « » and « » are used for that. Thus, the word « » is used for the payment of a right in both its entirety and its parts. However, in the Quran, it is not used in these meanings. But if the chapter is of verbs (af'āl), it will come in the meanings of doing justice.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَقۡسِطُوۡا ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الۡمُقۡسِطِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And do justice. Indeed, Allah loves those who do justice.\nNote: (Al-iddād refers to words that have two separate meanings that are opposite and contradictory to each other)."
    }
  ],
  "60": [
    {
      "id": 304,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Deny",
      "hw": "انکار",
      "s": "« » means to refuse to accept something, to reject, to not agree, to not acknowledge. (9 verses: 2:34-9:8-9:32-15:31-17:89-17:99-20:56-20:116-25:50)",
      "d": "« » means to not acknowledge something, to refuse firmly. (muf) Disobedience, not accepting, rejecting (m. r.), and « » also means to consider something detestable, i.e., disapproving of it, to be displeased with something. (manjad)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذۡ قُلۡنَا لِلۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ اسۡجُدُوۡا لِاٰدَمَ فَسَجَدُوۡۤا اِلَّاۤ اِبۡلِیۡسَ ؕ اَبٰی وَ اسۡتَکۡبَرَ ٭۫ وَکَانَ مِنَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And when We said to the angels, 'Prostrate before Adam,' they all prostrated except Iblis. He refused and became arrogant, and he became one of the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 305,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Deny",
      "hw": "انکار",
      "s": "« » means to deny something because one does not recognize it. (7 verses: 12:58-13:36-16:22-16:83-21:50-23:69-40:81)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is to not recognize something, to be a stranger to something or a matter (m. r.) Such a matter which a person's heart does not accept and which seems strange and astonishing. Whether one does not understand it due to ignorance. (muf) And its opposite is « », meaning to recognize something.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَجَآءَ اِخۡوَۃُ یُوۡسُفَ فَدَخَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِ فَعَرَفَہُمۡ وَہُمۡ لَہٗ مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And the brothers of Yusuf came and entered upon him; he recognized them, but they did not recognize him.\nAt another place, the declaration of the Lord Almighty is:\n«وَہٰذَا ذِکۡرٌ مُّبٰرَکٌ اَنۡزَلۡنٰہُ ؕ اَفَاَنۡتُمۡ لَہٗ مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And this is a blessed reminder which We have revealed. So do you deny it?"
    },
    {
      "id": 306,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Deny",
      "hw": "انکار",
      "s": "« » means to deny something while having certainty about it in the heart. (12 verses: 6:33-7:51-11:59-16:71-27:14-29:47-29:49-31:32-40:63-41:15-41:28-46:26)",
      "d": "« » means to deny something knowingly after having knowledge of it (m. r.) To deny with the tongue something which the heart truly acknowledges.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَجَحَدُوۡا بِہَا وَ اسۡتَیۡقَنَتۡہَاۤ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ ظُلۡمًا وَّعُلُوًّا»\nTranslation: And they denied them while their souls were convinced of them, out of injustice and arrogance."
    },
    {
      "id": 307,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Deny",
      "hw": "انکار",
      "s": "« » means to deny while covering up the truth. (297 verses: 2:6-2:26-2:28-2:39-2:61-2:85-2:88-2:89-2:90-2:91-2:93-2:99-2:102-2:105-2:108-2:121-2:126-2:152-2:161-2:171-2:212-2:217-2:253-2:256-2:257-2:258-3:4-3:10-3:12-3:19-3:21-3:52-3:55-3:56-3:70-3:72-3:80-3:86-3:90-3:91-3:97-3:98-3:101-3:106-3:112-3:115-3:116-3:127-3:149-3:151-3:156-3:167-3:176-3:177-3:178-3:196-4:42-4:46-4:51-4:56-4:60-4:76-4:84-4:89-4:101-4:102-4:131-4:136-4:137-4:140-4:150-4:155-4:156-4:167-4:168-4:170-5:3-5:5-5:10-5:12-5:17-5:36-5:41-5:61-5:64-5:68-5:72-5:73-5:78-5:80-5:86-5:103-5:110-5:115-6:1-6:7-6:25-6:30-6:70-6:89-7:66-7:90-8:12-8:15-8:30-8:35-8:36-8:38-8:50-8:52-8:55-8:59-8:65-8:73-9:3-9:12-9:17-9:23-9:26-9:30-9:37-9:40-9:54-9:66-9:74-9:80-9:84-9:90-9:97-9:107-10:4-10:70-11:7-11:17-11:27-11:60-11:68-13:5-13:7-13:27-13:30-13:31-13:32-13:33-13:43-14:7-14:8-14:9-14:13-14:18-14:22-14:28-15:2-16:39-16:55-16:72-16:84-16:88-16:106-16:112-17:69-17:98-18:29-18:37-18:56-18:80-18:102-18:105-18:106-19:37-19:73-19:77-19:82-21:30-21:36-21:39-21:94-21:97-22:19-22:25-22:55-22:57-22:72-23:24-23:33-24:39-24:55-24:57-25:4-25:32-27:40-27:67-28:48-29:12-29:23-29:25-29:52-29:66-29:67-30:16-30:34-30:44-30:51-30:58-31:12-31:23-32:29-33:25-34:3-34:7-34:17-34:31-34:33-34:43-34:53-35:7-35:14-35:26-35:36-35:39-36:47-36:64-37:170-38:2-38:27-39:7-39:8-39:63-39:71-40:4-40:6-40:10-40:12-40:22-40:42-40:84-41:9-41:26-41:27-41:29-41:41-41:50-41:52-43:33-45:11-45:31-46:3-46:7-46:10-46:11-46:20-46:34-47:1-47:3-47:4-47:8-47:12-47:32-47:34-48:22-48:25-48:26-49:7-51:60-52:42-54:14-57:15-57:19-59:2-59:11-59:16-60:1-60:2-60:4-60:5-61:14-63:3-64:5-64:6-64:7-64:10-66:7-66:10-67:6-67:27-68:51-70:36-73:17-74:31-80:17-80:42-84:22-85:19-88:23-90:19-98:1-98:6)",
      "d": "« » means to not recognize the truth (m. r.) and its fundamental meanings are to conceal something and to place a cover over it. A farmer (kisfār) is also called a kāfir (manjad) because he covers the seed in the earth. And this word has been used in the Quran in these meanings as well.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کَمَثَلِ غَیۡثٍ اَعۡجَبَ الۡکُفَّارَ نَبَاتُہٗ»\nTranslation: Like the example of rain whose vegetation pleases the farmers.\nAnd the opposite of kufr is īmān (faith), and it is called kufr because it conceals īmān (m. l).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ لَہٗ صَاحِبُہٗ وَ ہُوَیُحَاوِرُہٗۤ اَکَفَرۡتَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ مِنۡ تُرَابٍ»\nTranslation: So his companion, while he was arguing with him, said: 'Do you disbelieve in He who created you from dust?' (Uthmani RA)\nAnd « » also means ingratitude. In this meaning, its opposite is « » (14/7)."
    }
  ],
  "61": [
    {
      "id": 308,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fingers",
      "hw": "انگلیاں",
      "s": "« » is used for the joints of the fingers. (2 verses: 2:19-71:7)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». It refers to the joint of the finger that has a nail. It is the combination of the bend and the joint. (muf)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَجۡعَلُوۡنَ اَصَابِعَہُمۡ فِیۡۤ اٰذَانِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: They place their fingers in their ears.\nAnd for the joints alone, the word « » has come, whose singular is « ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«بَلٰی قٰدِرِیۡنَ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ نُّسَوِّیَ بَنَانَہٗ»\nTranslation: Yes, We are able to proportion his fingertips."
    },
    {
      "id": 309,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fingers",
      "hw": "انگلیاں",
      "s": "« » refers to the tips of the fingers where the nails are. (1 verse: 3:119)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». It refers to the upper part of the finger and its sides. (muf)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا خَلَوۡاعَضُّوۡاعَلَیۡکُمُ الۡاَنَامِلَ مِنَ الۡغَیۡظِ»\nTranslation: And when they are alone with you, they bite their fingertips in rage."
    }
  ],
  "63": [
    {
      "id": 313,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Children",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "« » means sons, daughters, grandsons, granddaughters, and so on. (22 verses: 2:233-3:10-3:116-4:11-6:137-6:140-6:151-8:28-9:55-9:69-9:85-17:31-17:64-34:35-34:37-57:20-58:17-60:3-60:12-63:9-64:14-64:15)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « », meaning a born child. And « » is generally applied to sons, daughters, grandsons, granddaughters, and downwards.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُوۡصِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡۤ اَوۡلَادِکُمۡ لِلذَّکَرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: Allah instructs you concerning your children: for the male, the share of two females."
    },
    {
      "id": 314,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«Asbāt» refers to grandsons, granddaughters, and beyond (5 verses: 2:136-2:140-3:84-4:163-7:160)",
      "d": "«Sibṭ» «Ḥafīd» «Ḥafdah» «Asbāt» «Am taqūlūna inna Ibrāhīma wa Ismā'īla wa Isḥāqa wa Ya'qūba wal-Asbāta kānū hūdan aw Naṣārā»"
    },
    {
      "id": 315,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«Dhurriyah» includes grandsons, granddaughters, all are included, used for all (30 verses: 2:124-2:128-2:266-3:34-3:36-3:38-4:9-6:84-6:87-6:133-7:172-7:173-10:83-13:23-13:38-14:37-14:40-17:3-17:62-18:50-19:58-25:74-29:27-36:41-37:77-37:113-40:8-46:15-52:21-57:26)",
      "d": "«Dhurr» «Dhurrah» «Dhurriyah» «Wa āṣābahul-kibaru wa lahu dhurriyyunḍu'a'ā» «Dhara'a» «Dhara'al-ard» «Qāla innī jā'iluka lin-nāsi imāmā. Qāla wa min dhurriyatī. Qāla lā yanālu 'ahdīẓ-ẓālimīn»"
    },
    {
      "id": 316,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«'Aqib» one can call the offspring of someone after death as 'Aqib, but not during their life (1 verse: 43:28)",
      "d": "«'Aqab» means heel, son, grandson, and «'Aqqaba» means to follow behind, and «A'qaba» means to be a successor ( ) and «'Aqib» is applied to the offspring left behind after a person's death. For example, in the Quran: «Waja'alahā kalimatan bāqiyatan fī 'aqibih» ( 43/28 ). Translation: And he left it as a lasting word among his descendants."
    },
    {
      "id": 317,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«Nasl» all the lower generations of a person are called his lineage (2 verses: 2:205-32:8)",
      "d": "«Nasala» «Hattā idhā futiḥat yājūju wa mājūju wa hum min kulli ḥadabin yansilūn» «Nusālah» «nasl» «Nasl» «dhurriyah» «Wa badā khalqal-insāni min ṭīnin thumma ja'ala naslahu min sulālatim mā'in muhīn»"
    },
    {
      "id": 318,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Offspring",
      "hw": "اولاد",
      "s": "«Ḥafdah» is applied to sons-in-law and children, covering relatives from both sides (1 verse: 16:72)",
      "d": "«Ḥafada» «wa ilayka nas'ā wa naḥfidu» «ḥāfid» «ḥāfid» «ḥafīd» «ḥāfid» «ḥafdah» «ḥafdah» «Waja'ala lakum min azwājikum banīna wa ḥafdah»"
    }
  ],
