  "65": [
    {
      "id": 322,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Ibil» is a generic noun used for all types of camels, both male and female (2 verses: 6:144-88:17)",
      "d": "«Ibil» is a generic noun used for all types of camels, both male and female. Its dual and plural forms do not occur, and this word also refers to the camel's hump ( ). For example, in the Quran: «Afalā yanẓurūna ilā al-ibili kayfa khuliqat» ( 88/17 ). Translation: Do these people not look at the camels how they are created?"
    },
    {
      "id": 323,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Ba'īr» when a camel becomes four years old and capable of carrying loads, it is called «Ba'īr» (2 verses: 12:65-12:72)",
      "d": "«Ba'īr» «Ba'īr» «Qālū nafqidu ṣuwā'al-maliki wa liman jā'a biḥi ḥimlu ba'īrin wa anā bihi za'īm»"
    },
    {
      "id": 324,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Jamal» a male camel over five years old. A beautiful camel. (2 verses: 7:40-77:33)",
      "d": "«Jamal» «jimālatun» «Innahā tarmī bishararin kal-qasri kāannahu jimālatun ṣufr»"
    },
    {
      "id": 325,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Hīm» a camel suffering from extreme thirst (1 verse: 56:55)",
      "d": "«Hām» has two meanings: (1) to wander in a state of passionate madness, and (2) to suffer from extreme thirst. Here the second meaning is under discussion, and «Hiyām» is a disease in camels where they become so thirsty that they do not quench their thirst ( ) and «Hīm» refers to a camel that is extremely thirsty. For example, in the Quran: «Fashāribūna 'alayhi min al-ḥamīmi fashāribūna sharba al-hīmi» ( 56/54 55 ). Translation: And they will drink from the scalding water, and they will drink as the thirsty camels drink."
    },
    {
      "id": 326,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Rikāb» refers to the place where a rider places their feet while mounting. (10 verses: 11:41, 11:42, 16:8, 18:71, 29:65, 36:42, 40:79, 43:12, 59:6, 84:19)",
      "d": "«Rakaba» «Rikāb» «rukbān, rakab» «rukūb» «rikāb» «فَمَاۤ اَوۡجَفۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡ خَیۡلٍ وَّ لَا رِکَابٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 327,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Ḍāmir» means a lean, thin, and swift camel, applicable to both male and female. (1 verse: 22:27)",
      "d": "«Ḍamara» «ḍāmir» «Miḍmār» «ḍāmir» «وَاَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ یَاۡتُوۡکَ رِجَالًا وَّعَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 328,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Budna» refers to a sacrificial camel that is taken to the Sacred House (Ka'bah) to be slaughtered. (1 verse: 22:36)",
      "d": "«اِذَا» «وَ اِذَا لَقُوا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا» «اِذَا الشَّمۡسُ کُوِّرَتۡ» «اِذًا» «اِذًا لَّارۡتَابَ الۡمُبۡطِلُوۡنَ» «حِیْن» «حِیْنَئِذٍ» «یَوْمَ» «یَوْمَئِذٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 329,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«Nāqah» is a she-camel that has reached the age of maturity and is capable of breeding. (7 verses: 7:73, 7:77, 11:64, 17:59, 26:155, 54:27, 91:13)",
      "d": "«Nāq» «وَیٰقَوۡمِ ہٰذِہٖ نَاقَۃُ اللّٰہِ لَکُمۡ اٰیَۃً»"
    },
    {
      "id": 330,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "«ʿIshār» refers to pregnant she-camels that have completed ten months of gestation. (2 verses: 34:45, 81:4)",
      "d": "«ʿIshār» «ʿashrā'» «ʿAshar» «ʿAshrā'» «وَاِذَا الۡعِشَارُعُطِّلَتۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 331,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "« »  « »  « », and « » were terms used in the pre-Islamic period for animals dedicated as vows or sacrifices to idols under various conditions. (1 verse: 5:103)",
      "d": "When a she-camel or she-goat gave birth to ten offspring, the Arabs would dedicate it for sacrifice to their idols, pierce its ears as a mark, set it free, and no one could milk it. And upon its death, its meat was considered lawful for men but forbidden for women."
    },
    {
      "id": 333,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "« » (the she-camel that has consecutively given birth to female offspring and has not produced any male) (1 verse: 5:103)",
      "d": "« » was the term for a young she-camel that gives birth to a female offspring the first time and then again a female the second time. They would also set it free in the name of their idols, but only if she consecutively gives birth to two females without any male offspring in between."
    },
    {
      "id": 334,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Camel",
      "hw": "اُونٹ",
      "s": "« » refers to a male camel from whose semen at least ten offspring have been born. (1 verse: 5:103)",
      "d": "« » is the male camel from whose semen at least ten offspring have been born. And when he has produced so many offspring, they would also set him free in the name of their idols, not ride him or load him.\nNow observe the divine decree regarding such sacrifices:\n«مَا جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ مِنۡۢ بَحِیۡرَۃٍ  وَّ لَا سَآئِبَۃٍ  وَّ لَا وَصِیۡلَۃٍ وَّ لَا حَامٍ ۙ وَّ لٰکِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا یَفۡتَرُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ»\nTranslation: Allah has not appointed any such thing as bahirah, or sa'ibah, or wasilah, or ham. But those who disbelieve invent lies against Allah.\nThe disbelievers had themselves coined these names and claimed that this was the law of Abraham and that it brought them closer to Allah."
    }
  ],
  "66": [
    {
      "id": 335,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Drowsiness",
      "hw": "اُونگھ",
      "s": "«Nuʿās» refers to the initial state of drowsiness or light sleep. (2 verses: 3:154, 8:11)",
      "d": "«Naʿas» «nuʿās» «اِذۡ یُغَشِّیۡکُمُ النُّعَاسَ اَمَنَۃً مِّنۡہُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 336,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Drowsiness",
      "hw": "اُونگھ",
      "s": "«Sinah» is a drowsiness where one feels heaviness in the head and the head begins to nod. It is an intermediate state between drowsiness and sleep. (2 verses: 2:255, 33:19)",
      "d": "«Sinah» «اَللّٰہُ لَاۤ اِلٰہَ اِلَّا ہُوَۚ اَلۡحَیُّ الۡقَیُّوۡمُ ۬ ۚ لَا تَاۡخُذُہٗ سِنَۃٌ وَّلَا نَوۡمٌ»"
    }
  ],
  "67": [
    {
      "id": 337,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fuel",
      "hw": "ایندھن",
      "s": "« » refers to plant-based fuel, worthless wood that is only fit for burning (2 verses: 72:15-111:4)",
      "d": "« » is plant-based fuel. Worthless wood, twigs, and brush that are only fit for burning.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّامۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ الۡحَطَبِ»\nTranslation: And his (Abu Lahab's) wife also carries firewood on her back.\nAnd wood that is useful is called « »."
    },
    {
      "id": 338,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fuel",
      "hw": "ایندھن",
      "s": "« » refers to mineral-based fuel. For example, sulfur, potash, and other flammable substances (5 verses: 17:68-21:98-29:40-54:34-67:17)",
      "d": "« » means stones, pebbles, and the like; and « » refers to the fierce wind that carries pebbles and small stones (manjada). Thus, this word is used in the Quran to mean a shower of stones (67/17). And « » also means fuel (manjada), referring to mineral-based fuel such as sulfur, potash, and other flammable substances. And stones, etc., in short, anything that intensifies fire is « » (f l 16).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّکُمۡ وَ مَا تَعۡبُدُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ حَصَبُ جَہَنَّمَ»\nTranslation: On that Day, you and those you worship besides Allah will be the fuel of Hell."
    },
    {
      "id": 339,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Fuel",
      "hw": "ایندھن",
      "s": "« » refers to burning fuel, regardless of its type (4 verses: 2:24-3:10-66:6-85:5)",
      "d": "« » means to kindle a fire, and « » is any fuel that burns by producing flames (f l 31), whether it be wood, stone, or humans. Sometimes, the intensity of fire reaches such an extent that water, instead of extinguishing it, causes it to burn more fiercely. In such a case, water also becomes part of the fuel. Any type of fuel, when burning, is called « », not before.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاتَّقُوا النَّارَ الَّتِیۡ وَقُوۡدُہَا النَّاسُ وَ الۡحِجَارَۃُ»\nTranslation: So fear the Fire whose fuel will be people and stones."
    }
  ],
  "69": [
    {
      "id": 340,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Father",
      "hw": "باپ",
      "s": "« » is used exclusively for father (22 verses: 2:83-2:180-2:215-2:233-4:7-4:33-4:36-4:135-5:110-6:151-14:41-17:23-19:14-19:32-27:19-29:8-31:14-31:33-46:15-46:17-71:28-90:3)",
      "d": "« » is used exclusively for father. Similarly, the word for mother is used only for a woman who has given birth.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَّا یَجۡزِیۡ وَالِدٌ عَنۡ وَّلَدِہٖ وَلَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ ہُوَجَازٍعَنۡ وَّالِدِہٖ شَیۡئًا»\nTranslation: Neither will a father be of any benefit to his child, nor will a child be of any benefit to his father.\nAnd for both parents, the word « » is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَنِ اشۡکُرۡ لِیۡ وَ لِوَالِدَیۡکَ»\nTranslation: Be grateful to Me and to your parents."
    },
    {
      "id": 341,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Father",
      "hw": "باپ",
      "s": "« » is used broadly for father, grandfather, great-grandfather, and all paternal ancestors (104 verses: 2:133-2:170-2:200-4:11-4:22-5:104-6:74-6:87-6:91-6:148-7:27-7:28-7:70-7:71-7:95-7:173-9:23-9:24-9:114-10:78-11:62-11:87-11:109-12:4-12:6-12:8-12:9-12:11-12:16-12:17-12:38-12:40-12:59-12:61-12:63-12:65-12:68-12:78-12:80-12:81-12:93-12:94-12:97-12:99-12:100-13:23-14:10-16:35-18:5-18:80-18:82-19:28-19:42-19:43-19:44-19:45-21:44-21:52-21:53-21:54-22:78-23:24-23:68-23:83-24:31-24:61-25:18-26:26-26:70-26:74-26:76-26:86-27:67-27:68-28:23-28:25-28:26-28:36-31:21-33:5-33:40-33:55-34:43-36:6-37:17-37:69-37:85-37:102-37:126-40:8-43:22-43:23-43:24-43:26-43:29-44:8-44:36-45:25-53:23-56:48-58:22-60:4-80:35-111:1)",
      "d": "« » is used in a very broad sense. This word is used for father, grandfather, great-grandfather, and all paternal ancestors. And for both parents, « » or « » is used contextually.\nNow, consider these examples:\n(1) Used only for parents:\n(Allah says)\n«وَ اَمَّا الۡغُلٰمُ فَکَانَ اَبَوٰہُ  مُؤۡمِنَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: As for the boy, his parents were believers.\n(2) Used for several generations:\n(Allah says)\n«مَّا سَمِعۡنَا بِہٰذَا فِیۡۤ  اٰبَآئِنَا  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: We have not heard of this from our forefathers of old.\nAnd these ancestors can be many generations.\nAs in (Allah says):\n«مِلَّۃَ اَبِیۡکُمۡ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ ؕ ہُوَ سَمّٰىکُمُ الۡمُسۡلِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: (And for you) the religion of your father Abraham is (approved). He named you Muslims.\nNote that between the Prophet ﷺ and Abraham, there were about 62 generations. Even for Adam, the ultimate ancestor of humanity, the word « » is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ اٰدَمَ لَا یَفۡتِنَنَّکُمُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ کَمَاۤ اَخۡرَجَ اَبَوَیۡکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡجَنَّۃِ»\nTranslation: O children of Adam! Do not let Satan deceive you as he expelled your parents from Paradise.\n« » originally is « », which implies providing nourishment and upbringing (m l). Therefore, when a son addresses his father, he usually uses « », as when Prophet Yusuf said to his father:\n(Allah says)\n«یٰۤاَبَتِ ہٰذَا تَاۡوِیۡلُ رُءۡیَایَ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ»\nTranslation: My dear father! This is the interpretation of my dream from before.\nThen, the word « » is sometimes used due to a particular attribute, such as calling a host « » and a warrior « ». In the Quran, « » is used due to this attribute because his complexion was radiant like a flame. Similarly, kuniyas (nicknames) are given due to relation and affection, such as Abu Hurairah and Abu Turab, etc."
    }
  ],
  "70": [
    {
      "id": 343,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be blessed",
      "hw": "بابرکت",
      "s": "« » refers to goodness and blessings that are naturally present. Blessings (5 verses: 19:52-20:80-28:30-56:8-90:18)",
      "d": "«یَمِیْن» «اَصْحٰبُ الْیَمِیْن» «یَمَنَ یَیْمَنُ» «تَیَمُّن» «مَیْمُون» «مَیْمُون» «اَیْمَن»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَتٰىہَا نُوۡدِیَ مِنۡ شَاطِیَٔ الۡوَادِ الۡاَیۡمَنِ»\nTranslation: Then when he (Musa) came to it, he was called from the right side of the valley, in a blessed spot."
    }
  ],
  "71": [
    {
      "id": 345,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "« » refers to any speech, whether meaningless or meaningful, whether in the heart or ideological (327 verses: 2:8-2:26-2:58-2:59-2:68-2:69-2:71-2:79-2:80-2:83-2:102-2:104-2:113-2:117-2:118-2:136-2:140-2:142-2:154-2:169-2:200-2:201-2:204-2:214-2:235-2:263-3:7-3:16-3:47-3:64-3:75-3:78-3:79-3:124-3:147-3:154-3:167-3:181-4:5-4:8-4:9-4:43-4:46-4:51-4:63-4:73-4:75-4:78-4:81-4:94-4:108-4:148-4:150-4:155-4:156-4:157-4:171-5:19-5:41-5:52-5:53-5:63-5:73-5:83-5:109-5:116-6:22-6:25-6:33-6:50-6:53-6:73-6:93-6:105-6:112-6:148-6:156-6:157-7:28-7:33-7:53-7:105-7:161-7:162-7:169-7:172-7:173-7:205-8:49-9:30-9:40-9:49-9:50-9:61-9:65-9:124-10:18-10:20-10:28-10:31-10:38-10:48-10:65-10:68-10:77-11:7-11:8-11:10-11:12-11:13-11:18-11:31-11:35-11:40-11:53-11:54-11:91-12:66-12:81-13:5-13:7-13:10-13:27-13:33-13:43-14:27-14:44-15:97-16:27-16:32-16:40-16:86-16:103-16:116-17:16-17:23-17:28-17:40-17:42-17:43-17:47-17:51-17:53-17:108-18:5-18:22-18:23-18:42-18:49-18:52-18:88-18:93-19:26-19:34-19:35-19:66-19:79-19:80-20:7-20:28-20:40-20:44-20:47-20:89-20:94-20:97-20:104-20:109-20:130-21:4-21:27-21:38-21:46-21:110-22:24-22:30-22:40-23:27-23:68-23:70-23:85-23:87-23:89-23:109-24:15-24:26-24:47-24:51-25:17-25:19-25:22-25:27-25:65-25:74-26:16-26:203-26:226-27:19-27:49-27:71-27:82-27:85-28:28-28:47-28:51-28:62-28:63-28:65-28:74-28:82-29:2-29:10-29:46-29:55-29:61-29:63-30:58-31:25-32:3-32:13-32:28-33:4-33:12-33:13-33:32-33:37-33:66-33:70-34:29-34:31-34:40-34:42-36:7-36:48-36:58-36:70-36:76-36:82-37:31-37:36-37:52-37:151-37:167-38:17-38:84-39:18-39:38-39:56-39:57-39:58-40:28-40:44-40:47-40:68-41:25-41:33-41:50-42:24-42:44-43:9-43:13-43:87-44:34-46:8-46:11-46:17-46:18-47:20-47:21-47:30-48:11-48:15-49:2-49:14-50:18-50:29-50:30-52:33-50:39-50:45-51:8-52:30-52:33-52:44-54:2-54:8-54:44-56:47-57:13-58:1-58:2-58:8-59:10-59:11-60:4-61:2-61:3-63:4-63:7-63:8-63:10-66:8-67:13-67:25-68:51-69:19-69:25-69:40-69:41-69:42-69:44-72:4-72:5-73:5-73:10-74:25-74:31-75:10-78:40-79:10-81:19-81:25-86:13-89:15-89:16-89:24-90:6)",
      "d": "«قَوْل» «اَقْوَال» «اَلْجَمْعُ اَقَاوِیْل»\nExamples:\n(1) For uttered speech, Allah says:\n«قَالَ قَآئِلٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ کَمۡ لَبِثۡتُمۡ»\nTranslation: One of them said, 'How long have you stayed?'\n(2) For speech in the heart, Allah says:\n«وَیَقُوۡلُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ لَوۡلَا یُعَذِّبُنَا اللّٰہُ»\nTranslation: And they say within themselves, 'If this were true, Allah would not punish us.'\n(3) For a doctrine, Allah says:\n«ذٰلِکَ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ ۚ قَوۡلَ الۡحَقِّ الَّذِیۡ  فِیۡہِ  یَمۡتَرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: That is Jesus, son of Mary - a statement of truth about which they are in doubt."
    },
    {
      "id": 346,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "« » refers to new speech, something that common people are unfamiliar with (28 verses: 4:42-4:78-4:87-4:140-6:68-7:185-12:6-12:21-12:101-12:111-18:6-20:9-23:44-31:6-33:53-34:19-39:23-45:6-51:24-52:34-53:59-56:81-66:3-68:44-77:50-79:15-85:17-88:1)",
      "d": "« » means for something to appear, for an event to occur, for a new thing or speech to come into existence (manjada). Its opposite is « ». In Ibn Faris's words, it is the coming into existence of something that did not exist before (m l). And « » refers to new speech or a doctrine that relates to common people and with which most people were previously unfamiliar.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَا تَدۡرِیۡ لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ اَمۡرًا»\nTranslation: You do not know; perhaps Allah will bring about after that a new situation.\nAlso, Allah says:\n«اَللّٰہُ نَزَّلَ اَحۡسَنَ الۡحَدِیۡثِ»\nTranslation: Allah has sent down the best of statements.\nHere, « » refers to the Quran, and evidently, according to the views and ideas of the people of that time, this was something new. Then, the word « » is also used for an old saying or event that has generally faded from people's minds. In such a case, its meaning would be a forgotten story or tale.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَا جَآءَ اُمَّۃً  رَّسُوۡلُہَا کَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَاَتۡبَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ بَعۡضًا وَّ جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ اَحَادِیۡثَ»\nTranslation: Whenever a messenger came to a nation, they denied him. So We made some of them follow others, and We made them into tales."
    },
    {
      "id": 347,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Word",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "« » refers only to meaningful speech, God's commands, and wonders of creation, etc. (47 verses: 2:37-2:75-2:124-3:39-3:45-3:64-4:46-4:171-5:13-5:41-6:34-6:115-7:137-7:144-7:158-8:7-9:6-9:40-9:74-10:19-10:33-10:64-10:82-10:96-11:110-11:119-14:24-14:26-18:5-18:27-18:109-20:129-23:100-31:27-35:10-37:171-39:19-39:71-40:6-41:45-42:14-42:21-42:24-43:28-48:15-48:26-66:12)",
      "d": "« » linguistically means 'meaningful speech' that can be heard and understood (muf). For example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّہَا کَلِمَۃٌ ہُوَ قَآئِلُہَا»\nTranslation: It will be a single statement, and he who says it.\nBut when the word « » is attributed to Allah, it refers to the wonders of His power, the laws of nature, and His creative works (Tafhim al-Quran). For example, the Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ الۡبَحۡرُ مِدَادًا لِّکَلِمٰتِ رَبِّیۡ لَنَفِدَ الۡبَحۡرُقَبۡلَ اَنۡ تَنۡفَدَ کَلِمٰتُ رَبِّیۡ وَ لَوۡجِئۡنَا بِمِثۡلِہٖ مَدَدًا»\nTranslation: Say, 'If the sea were ink for [writing] the words of my Lord, the sea would be exhausted before the words of my Lord were exhausted, even if We brought the like of it in addition.'\nAnd when the word is attributed from Allah to humans, it refers to His commands and decrees:\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَفَمَنۡ حَقَّ عَلَیۡہِ کَلِمَۃُ الۡعَذَابِ ؕ اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ»\nTranslation: Then, is he who has deserved the decree of punishment [any better]? So can you save one who is in the Fire?"
    },
    {
      "id": 348,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "« » is a general term for conversation, usually used for brief and immediate dialogue (24 verses: 2:118-2:174-2:253-3:41-3:46-3:77-4:164-5:110-6:111-7:143-7:148-11:105-12:54-13:31-19:10-19:26-19:29-23:108-24:16-27:82-30:35-36:65-42:51-78:38)",
      "d": "« » means to converse, to talk (manjada). It is generally used for brief conversations or for matters where a response can be given immediately upon hearing. Moreover, « » does not necessarily imply two-way conversation; it can sometimes be one-way.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَا یُکَلِّمُہُمُ اللّٰہُ وَلَا یَنۡظُرُ اِلَیۡہِمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ»\nTranslation: And Allah will not speak to them or look at them on the Day of Resurrection."
    },
    {
      "id": 349,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "«ḥāwara» is a conversation in the style of question and answer that is conducted with thought and understanding and is lengthy (3 verses: 18:34-18:37-58:1)",
      "d": "Ibn Faris says that in «ḥawran», there are basically two things: (1) to refer to speech and (2) to turn a thing to one side and then to the other side (m l). And the author of Munajid writes the meanings of «ḥāra» as to return and also to be perplexed (astonished). Thus, «ḥāwara» means such conversation that is in the form of question and answer. And the listener has to give the answer after thinking and understanding. Such conversation is generally lengthy. From this, the word 'muhawarah' (proverb) is derived. Which means that the speech is said after thinking and understanding and is also common, famous, and comprehensible.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«قَالَ لَہٗ صَاحِبُہٗ وَ ہُوَ یُحَاوِرُہٗۤ اَکَفَرۡتَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ مِنۡ تُرَابٍ ثُمَّ مِنۡ نُّطۡفَۃٍ ثُمَّ سَوّٰىکَ رَجُلًا»\nTranslation: So his companion, who was conversing with him, will say: Do you disbelieve in Him who created you from dust, then from a sperm-drop, then proportioned you as a man?"
    },
    {
      "id": 350,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "«khāṭaba» is generally a one-sided speech. Or one gives a reply if the addressee prefers or deems it necessary (3 verses: 11:37-23:27-25:63)",
      "d": "«khāṭaba» also comes in the meanings of speaking (Munajid). And 'khatbah' means sermon, exhortation, and speech, which is generally one-sided. The khatib (speaker) means one who delivers a sermon, speaks with clarification (m q). And sometimes it happens that the listener gives a brief reply and silences the one addressing.\nThus, in the Quran, Allah Almighty says to Prophet Noah (peace be upon him):\n«وَاصۡنَعِ الۡفُلۡکَ بِاَعۡیُنِنَا وَ وَحۡیِنَا وَ لَا تُخَاطِبۡنِیۡ فِی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا»\nTranslation: And construct the ship under Our observation and Our inspiration, and do not address Me concerning those who have wronged.\nIn another place, Allah Almighty, describing the attributes of His servants, says:\n«وَّاِذَا خَاطَبَہُمُ الۡجٰہِلُوۡنَ  قَالُوۡا سَلٰمًا»\nTranslation: And when the ignorant address them, they say [words of] peace."
    }
  ],
  "72": [
    {
      "id": 351,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Sovereignty",
      "hw": "بادشاہی",
      "s": "«sulṭān» when the expression of authority and grandeur is intended, then «sulṭān» is used, and when the expression of the vastness of territory is intended, then the word «mulk» is used (39 verses: 3:151-4:90-4:91-4:144-4:153-6:81-7:33-7:71-10:68-11:96-12:40-14:10-14:11-14:22-15:42-16:99-16:100-17:33-17:65-17:80-18:15-22:71-23:45-27:21-28:35-30:35-34:21-37:30-37:156-40:23-40:35-40:56-44:19-51:38-52:38-53:23-55:33-59:6-69:29)",
      "d": "The word «sulṭān» comes in three meanings:\n(1) Meaning evidence that has the status of a document or certificate. Authority. In these meanings, this word appears frequently in the Quran.\n(2) Kingdom or sovereignty. In this meaning, it appears only once in the Quran.\n(3) Meaning king (plural: sultans). In these meanings, this word does not appear in the Quran, and the meaning of sultan as king is not from the literal language but is a derived meaning.\nWhen this word comes in the meanings of kingdom or sovereignty, it refers to the territory that is under the control of a person, institution, or king, and over which he has dominion.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said that the disbeliever will say on the Day of Judgment:\n«مَاۤ اَغۡنٰی عَنِّیۡ مَالِیَہۡ ہَلَکَ عَنِّیۡ سُلۡطٰنِیَہۡ»\nTranslation: My wealth has availed me not; gone is my sovereignty."
    }
  ],
  "73": [
    {
      "id": 354,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«ghammām» when the cloud becomes thick and provides shade, then it is called ghamām (4 verses: 2:57-2:210-7:160-25:25)",
      "d": "«ghamm» means to cover (Munajid). And «ghammām» is that cloud which becomes thick layer upon layer and prevents the sunlight from reaching the earth. (f l 254) i.e., it becomes shade-casting on the earth.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَ ظَلَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡغَمَامَ وَ اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡمَنَّ وَ السَّلۡوٰی»\nTranslation: And We shaded you with the cloud and sent down upon you manna and salwa."
    },
    {
      "id": 355,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«ʿāriḍ» is a cloud in which the beginning of rainfall has already started (1 verse: 46:24)",
      "d": "Then when from the thick and spread-out cloud, rainfall also begins, then it is called «ʿāriḍ» (f l 254)\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا عَارِضٌ مُّمۡطِرُنَا ؕ بَلۡ ہُوَمَا اسۡتَعۡجَلۡتُمۡ بِہٖ ؕ رِیۡحٌ  فِیۡہَا عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: They said, 'This is a cloud that will rain upon us.' Rather, it is that for which you were impatient: a wind within it a painful punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 356,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«muʿṣirāt» clouds full of water (1 verse: 78:14)",
      "d": "«ʿaṣara» means to wring clothes and (to extract juice from fruits, etc.). Also, the extracted juice is called 'ʿaṣr' (m l). And «aʿṣara al-qawm» means to send rain upon the people (Munajid). And «muʿṣirāt» is the plural of «muʿṣirah», i.e., such clouds that are laden with water and are about to rain, dripping clouds.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَّاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ الۡمُعۡصِرٰتِ مَآءً  ثَجَّاجًا»\nTranslation: And We sent down from the rain-bearing clouds water in abundance."
    },
    {
      "id": 357,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«muzn» white shining clouds (1 verse: 56:69)",
      "d": "«mazana» means to fill a skin (i.e., a water container) with water, etc. And «ibn al-muznah» refers to the moon that appears from among the clouds (muf). And «mazan» refers to white and shining clouds (muf. f l 255). And «ḥabb al-muzn» refers to hail (Munajid). And «muzn» refers to rain-bearing clouds (Munajid).\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡزَلۡتُمُوۡہُ مِنَ الۡمُزۡنِ اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الۡمُنۡزِلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Is it you who brought it down from the clouds, or are We the bringers?"
    },
    {
      "id": 358,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Cloud",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "«ṣayyib» is said for a cloud with intense thunder (1 verse: 2:19)",
      "d": "«ṣayyib» is a cloud with intense thunder (f l 255). Whereas the author of al-Muntahi al-Arb takes it to mean a heavy rain (m. l). According to Munajid, any rain-bearing cloud is «ṣayyib».\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اَوۡ کَصَیِّبٍ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فِیۡہِ ظُلُمٰتٌ وَّ رَعۡدٌ وَّ بَرۡقٌ»\nTranslation: Or [it is] like a rainstorm from the sky within which is darkness, thunder, and lightning."
    }
  ],
  "74": [
    {
      "id": 359,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Time, Occasion, Instance",
      "hw": "بار ",
      "s": "«marrah» is a general word for time, occasion, or instance (13 verses: 6:94-6:110-8:56-9:13-9:80-9:83-9:126-17:7-17:51-18:48-20:37-36:79-41:21)",
      "d": "«marra» means to pass by a place (muf) and also to pass in time. And in this sense, it means to pass once or to do something once. Its dual is «marratan» or «marratayn», and plural is «marat» and «mararan» (meaning many times).\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اَوَلَا یَرَوۡنَ اَنَّہُمۡ یُفۡتَنُوۡنَ فِیۡ کُلِّ عَامٍ مَّرَّۃً اَوۡ مَرَّتَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: Do they not see that they are tried every year once or twice?"
    },
    {
      "id": 361,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Time, Occasion, Instance",
      "hw": "بار ",
      "s": "«tārah» meaning sometimes at some time, again doing that work which has been done before (2 verses: 17:69-20:55)",
      "d": "«tārah» some have included it under «tawr» and some under «tār». And its meaning is «iʿādatan baʿda marrah» (m. q) and meaning time and once (m. r). i.e., sometimes at some time, again doing that work «faʿaltu tārah hādhā aw tārah dhāk» meaning I have done this work sometimes and that sometimes (Munajid). Thus, «tārah» is a repetition of an action that was done at some time in the past.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«مِنۡہَا خَلَقۡنٰکُمۡ وَ فِیۡہَا نُعِیۡدُکُمۡ وَمِنۡہَا نُخۡرِجُکُمۡ تَارَۃً اُخۡرٰی»\nTranslation: From it We created you, and into it We will return you, and from it We will bring you out a second time."
    }
  ],
  "75": [
    {
      "id": 362,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » is used for all types of rain. It is a generic term (9 verses: 4:102--7:84-8:32-11:82-15:74-25:40-26:173-27:58-46:24)",
      "d": "« » is a general term for rain. Whether the rain is beneficial or harmful, whether water or something else falls, the word « » can be used for all, and « » means to send rain.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَاَمۡطَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مَّطَرًا ۚ فَسَآءَ مَطَرُالۡمُنۡذَرِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And We sent upon them a severe rain. So evil was the rain of those who were warned."
    },
    {
      "id": 363,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » literally means water, but is used metaphorically for rain (34 verses: 2:22-2:164-4:43-5:6-6:99-8:11-13:17-14:16-14:32-15:22-16:10-16:65-20:53-22:63-23:18-24:39-24:45-25:48-27:60-28:23-29:63-30:24-31:10-32:8-35:27-39:21-43:11-47:15-50:9-72:16-77:20-77:27-78:14-86:6)",
      "d": "« » literally means water; « » is used metaphorically for rain.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَّاَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً فَاَخۡرَجَ بِہٖ مِنَ الثَّمَرٰتِ رِزۡقًا لَّکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And We sent down from the sky water, then We brought forth thereby fruits as provision for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 364,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » means dew or light rain (1 verse: 2:265)",
      "d": "« » means a very light and weak rain (F L 256. M L). The word « » is used for both dew and light rain (F. M).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاِنۡ لَّمۡ یُصِبۡہَا وَابِلٌ فَطَلٌّ»\nTranslation: Then if no heavy rain befalls it, then a light rain is sufficient."
    },
    {
      "id": 365,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » means continuous and gentle rain (2 verses: 24:43, 30:48)",
      "d": "« » is the term for rain that continues continuously (F L 258). Such rain generally is slow and lasts for a long time.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ رُکَامًا فَتَرَی الۡوَدۡقَ یَخۡرُجُ مِنۡ خِلٰلِہٖ»\nTranslation: Then He makes them layers, and you see the rain coming forth from between them."
    },
    {
      "id": 366,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » is rain that occurs at the time of need and according to the need (3 verses: 31:34, 42:28, 57:20)",
      "d": "« » is the rain that comes at the time of need and according to the need (F L 258. M L).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«کَمَثَلِ غَیۡثٍ اَعۡجَبَ الۡکُفَّارَ نَبَاتُہٗ»\nTranslation: Like the rain whose growth delights the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 368,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » is rain that is abundant in water and also beneficial, i.e., causes vegetation to grow (1 verse: 72:16)",
      "d": "«غَدَق» «غَدَقَۃٌ» «غَدَقَ الْمَکَان» «غَدِق» «غَدَق»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَّاَنۡ لَّوِ اسۡتَقَامُوۡاعَلَی الطَّرِیۡقَۃِ لَاَسۡقَیۡنٰہُمۡ مَّآءً غَدَقًا»\nTranslation: And if they had remained steadfast on the path, We would have given them abundant water to drink."
    },
    {
      "id": 369,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » is a forceful rain with large droplets (1 verse: 2:19)",
      "d": "« » refers to such a forceful rain in which there are loud thundering clouds and flashing lightning (F L 255. M R). And according to Ibn al-Faris, it is rain that pours down heavily (M L). Such rain is called 'phanda' in Punjabi.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَوۡ کَصَیِّبٍ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فِیۡہِ ظُلُمٰتٌ وَّ رَعۡدٌ وَّ بَرۡقٌ»\nTranslation: Or [it is] like a rain from the sky within which are darknesses, thunder, and lightning."
    },
    {
      "id": 370,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » is such a severe rain that carries away straw and chaff (i.e., grass, twigs, rubbish) (2 verses: 2:264, 2:265)",
      "d": "« » means to beat continuously with a stick (Munjid). In its meaning, intensity and weight are found. Ibn Faris says that « » gives the meaning of intensity and abundance in something, and « » means a severe type of rain (M L). Thus, « » is the rain that, due to the abundance of water and its intensity and speed, carries away straw and chaff (i.e., grass, twigs, rubbish), and this is the highest degree of rain.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَمَثَلُہٗ کَمَثَلِ صَفۡوَانٍ عَلَیۡہِ تُرَابٌ فَاَصَابَہٗ وَابِلٌ فَتَرَکَہٗ صَلۃً»\nTranslation: Its example is like a rock on which a little dust is lying, and a heavy rain falls on it and cleans it."
    }
  ],
  "76": [
    {
      "id": 372,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to return",
      "hw": "باز",
      "s": "« » means to free someone from a bond or to forcibly stop someone from doing something (1 verse: 98:1)",
      "d": "«فَکّ» «فَکُ الْاَسِیْر» «اِنْفِکَاک» «اِنْفِکَاکُ الْعَبْد» «اِنْفَکَّ الْعَظْمُ» «اِنْفِکَاک»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«لَمۡ یَکُنِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ وَالۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ مُنۡفَکِّیۡنَ حَتّٰی تَاۡتِیَہُمُ الۡبَیِّنَۃُ»\nTranslation: Those who disbelieved from among the People of the Book and the polytheists were not ones to desist until the clear proof came to them.\nAnd this clear proof was the Prophethood and the dominance of Islam, which forced them to desist from disbelief and polytheism."
    }
  ],
