      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Garden",
      "hw": "باغ",
      "s": "« » refers to a garden whose ground is not visible due to trees and grass (143 verses: 2:25-2:35-2:82-2:111-2:214-2:221-2:265-2:266-3:15-3:133-3:136-3:142-3:185-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-4:124-5:12-5:65-5:72-5:85-5:119-6:99-6:141-7:19-7:22-7:27-7:40-7:42-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:49-7:50-9:21-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:111-10:9-10:26-11:23-11:108-13:4-13:23-13:35-14:23-15:45-16:31-16:32-17:91-18:31-18:32-18:33-18:35-18:39-18:40-18:107-19:60-19:61-19:63-20:76-20:117-20:121-22:14-22:23-22:56-23:19-25:8-25:10-25:15-25:24-26:57-26:85-26:90-26:134-26:147-29:58-31:8-32:19-34:15-34:16-35:33-36:26-36:34-36:55-37:43-38:50-39:73-39:74-40:8-40:40-41:30-42:7-42:22-43:70-43:72-44:25-44:52-46:14-46:16-47:6-47:12-47:15-48:5-48:17-50:9-50:31-51:15-52:17-53:15-54:54-55:46-55:54-55:62-56:12-56:89-57:12-57:21-58:22-59:20-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-66:11-68:17-68:34-69:22-70:35-70:38-71:12-74:40-76:12-78:16-79:41-81:13-85:11-88:10-89:30-98:8)",
      "d": "«جَنَّۃ» «جَنَّ» «جَنّۃٌ» «جَنَّۃٌ» «کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 377,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Garden",
      "hw": "باغ",
      "s": "« » refers to such gardens or orchards that have a four-walled enclosure built around them for protection (3 verses: 27:60-78:32-80:30)",
      "d": "«حَدَآئِق» «حَدِیْقَۃ» «حَدِیْقَۃ» «حَدَقَ» «حَدِیْقَۃ» «فَاَنۡۢبَتۡنَا بِہٖ حَدَآئِقَ ذَاتَ بَہۡجَۃٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 378,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Garden",
      "hw": "باغ",
      "s": "« » refers to that part or place within a garden which is very lush and spring-like. And usually, pavilions or similar structures are built in such places (2 verses: 30:15-42:22)",
      "d": "«رَوْضَۃ» «رَوْضَات» «رَوْض» «رَوَّضَ الْمَطْرُالْاَرْضَ» «رَوْضَۃ» «رَوْضَہ» «فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ فَہُمۡ فِیۡ رَوۡضَۃٍ یُّحۡبَرُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "79": [
    {
      "id": 379,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Keep/Leave",
      "hw": "باقی",
      "s": "« » means to keep something's existence established and enduring (14 verses: 2:248-2:278-11:86-11:116-20:71-20:73-20:127-20:131-28:60-42:36-53:51-55:27-74:28-87:17)",
      "d": "«بَقٰی» «فَنٰی» «ھَلَکَ» «اَبْقٰی» «وَاَنَّہٗۤ اَہۡلَکَ عَادَۨا الۡاُوۡلٰیوَاَنَّہٗۤ اَہۡلَکَ عَادَۨا الۡاُوۡلٰی وَثَمُوۡدَا۠ فَمَاۤ اَبۡقٰی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 380,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Keep/Leave",
      "hw": "باقی",
      "s": "« » means to keep something in its state, enduring and established (12 verses: 2:250-3:147-8:11-8:12-8:45-11:120-13:39-14:27-16:102-17:74-25:32-47:7)",
      "d": "«ثَبَتَ» «زَالَ» «اَثْبَتَ» «یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 381,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Keep/Leave",
      "hw": "باقی",
      "s": "« » means to leave one thing among many things (2 verses: 18:47-18:49)",
      "d": "«غَدَرَ» «غَادَرَ» «وَیَقُوۡلُوۡنَ یٰوَیۡلَتَنَا مَالِ ہٰذَا الۡکِتٰبِ لَا یُغَادِرُ صَغِیۡرَۃً وَّ لَا کَبِیۡرَۃً  اِلَّاۤ اَحۡصٰہَا»"
    }
  ],
  "80": [
    {
      "id": 382,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Hair",
      "hw": "بال",
      "s": "« » refers to the hair of all living beings, including humans (1 verse: 16:80)",
      "d": "« » is the hair of all living beings, including humans. This word is general, and its plural is « » (f l 98)."
    },
    {
      "id": 383,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Hair",
      "hw": "بال",
      "s": "« » refers to the hair of camels and birds (1 verse: 16:80)",
      "d": "« » is the hair of camels and birds, and it is flowing. Its plural is « » (f l 98)."
    },
    {
      "id": 384,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wool",
      "hw": "بال",
      "s": "« » is used for the wool and hair of sheep, goats, etc. (1 Verse: 16:80)",
      "d": "« » is used for the wool and hair of sheep, goats, etc. Its plural is « » (F L 98).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمِنۡ اَصۡوَافِہَا وَاَوۡبَارِہَا وَاَشۡعَارِہَاۤ اَثَاثًا وَّمَتَاعًا اِلٰی حِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: And from their wool, their hair, and their fur, they make domestic articles and wares that last for a time."
    }
  ],
  "81": [
    {
      "id": 385,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Barren (Woman)",
      "hw": "بانجھ",
      "s": "« » refers to a woman who previously bore children but has since become barren. (3 Verses: 3:40, 19:5, 19:8)",
      "d": "«عَاقِر» «عَقَر» «اَلْکَلْبُ الْعَقُوْر» «عَقَرَ النَّخلَۃ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَکَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَعَقَرُوۡہَا»\nTranslation: So they denied him and they hamstrung the she-camel.\nThen, « » also refers to the last child after whom no offspring follows (Muf). Thus, « » is used for a woman who was fertile but later, due to a wound in her womb, cessation of menstruation, or another reason, ceased to bear children. Moreover, this word is used for both men and women.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِنِّیۡ خِفۡتُ الۡمَوَالِیَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِیۡی وَ کَانَتِ امۡرَاَتِیۡ عَاقِرًا فَہَبۡ لِیۡ مِنۡ لَّدُنۡکَ  وَلِیًّا»\nTranslation: (Prophet Zakariya supplicated to God) And I fear my heirs after me, and my wife is barren, so grant me from Yourself an heir."
    },
    {
      "id": 386,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Barren (Person)",
      "hw": "بانجھ",
      "s": "« » refers to a woman who does not bear children, and a man whose sperm does not result in conception. It is used for both barren women and men. (4 Verses: 22:55, 42:50, 51:29, 51:41)",
      "d": "«عَقِیْم» «عَاقِر» «عَقِیْم» «رِیْحٌ عَقِیْمٌ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَفِیْ عَادٍ اِذْ اَرْسَلْنَا عَلَیْہِمُ الرِّیْحَ الْعَقِیْمَۚ»\nTranslation: And in 'Ad (there is a sign) when We sent against them the barren wind.\nAnd « » is a person whose reproductive material is absent or whose semen is dead (in common terms, a man lacking the ability to procreate). Similarly, « » refers to a woman who does not accept a man's semen at all (M. R). Thus, « » is a man or woman who has never had any offspring from the beginning.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَوۡ یُزَوِّجُہُمۡ ذُکۡرَانًا وَّاِنَاثًا ۚ وَیَجۡعَلُ مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ عَقِیۡمًا»\nTranslation: Or He grants them both sons and daughters, and He makes whom He wills barren."
    }
  ],
  "82": [
    {
      "id": 387,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Tie/Bind",
      "hw": "باندھنا",
      "s": "«رَبَطَ» «رَبَطَ اللہُ عَلیٰ قَلْبِہٖ»",
      "d": "«رَبَطَ» «مِرْبَطُ» «مَرْبَطُ» «رَبَّاط» «رَبَیْطَہ» «رَبَطَ اللہُ عَلیٰ قَلْبِہٖ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ کَادَتۡ لَتُبۡدِیۡ بِہٖ لَوۡلَاۤ اَنۡ رَّبَطۡنَا عَلٰی قَلۡبِہَا»\nTranslation: Had We not fortified her heart, she would almost have disclosed the matter."
    },
    {
      "id": 389,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Chains/Miser",
      "hw": "باندھنا",
      "s": "« » refers to a miserly person. That is, such a person's hands are tied from spending. (3 Verses: 5:64, 12:23, 17:29)",
      "d": "«غُلّ» «اَغْلَال» «مَغْلُولُ الْیَد»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَقَالَتِ الۡیَہُوۡدُ یَدُ اللّٰہِ مَغۡلُوۡلَۃٌ ؕ غُلَّتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ لُعِنُوۡا بِمَا قَالُوۡا ۘ بَلۡ یَدٰہُ مَبۡسُوۡطَتٰنِ ۙ یُنۡفِقُ کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ»\nTranslation: And the Jews say, 'The hand of Allah is chained.' Chained are their hands, and cursed are they for what they say. Nay, both His hands are widely outstretched; He spends how He wills."
    }
  ],
  "83": [
    {
      "id": 390,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idol",
      "hw": "بت",
      "s": "« » refers to idols carved from silver, copper, or wood. (5 Verses: 6:74, 7:138, 14:35, 21:57, 26:71)",
      "d": "«صَنَم» «اَصْنَام» «صَنَّاعَۃُ الْاَصْنَام»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّاجۡنُبۡنِیۡ وَ بَنِیَّ اَنۡ نَّعۡبُدَ الۡاَصۡنَامَ»\nTranslation: And (O my Lord) keep me and my sons away from worshipping idols."
    },
    {
      "id": 392,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idol (Natural Object of Worship)",
      "hw": "بت",
      "s": "« » refers to beginning the worship of God's attributes in specific places like rocks, trees, stars, or rivers, etc. (3 Verses: 22:30, 29:17, 29:25)",
      "d": "The plural of « » is « ». It means idols that remain fixed and stationary in their place. These are not carved or erected idols. Rather, worship begins by holding the belief of God's attributes in specific places like rocks, trees, stars, or rivers, etc. « » refers to an idolater, and « » refers to idolatry (Manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاجۡتَنِبُواالرِّجۡسَ مِنَ الۡاَوۡثَانِ وَاجۡتَنِبُوۡا قَوۡلَ الزُّوۡرِ»\nTranslation: So avoid the impurity of idols and avoid false speech."
    },
    {
      "id": 393,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idol/Sorcery",
      "hw": "بت",
      "s": "« » means idol, soothsayer, divination, and anything that contains no good. For example, magic spells. (1 Verse: 4:51)",
      "d": "« » means idol, soothsayer, divination, and anything that contains no good. For example, magic spells (M. R). This word is essentially an umbrella term for superstitions, illusions, and myths. It includes magic, incantations, amulets, the influences of stars, talismans, engravings, etc."
    },
    {
      "id": 394,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "False Deity/Tyrant",
      "hw": "بت",
      "s": "« » refers to all false and rebellious systems or powers that incline towards opposing God's commands and are accepted as such. (15 Verses: 2:256, 2:257, 4:51, 4:60, 4:76, 5:60, 16:36, 37:30, 38:55, 39:17, 51:53, 52:32, 68:31, 69:5, 78:22)",
      "d": "« » means 'idol, tyrant, sorcerer, soothsayer, falsehood, idol, and worship of other than God, and rebellious' (M. R). Thus, « » refers to all false and rebellious systems or powers that incline towards opposing God's commands and are accepted as such.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡنَ اُوۡتُوۡا نَصِیۡبًا مِّنَ الۡکِتٰبِ یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِالۡجِبۡتِ وَالطَّاغُوۡتِ»\nTranslation: Have you not seen those who were given a portion of the Scripture believing in the idol and the false deity?"
    }
  ],
