  "89": [
    {
      "id": 422,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "« » Not spending from one's accumulated wealth even in places where spending is required. (7 verses: 3:180-4:37-9:76-47:37-47:38-57:24-92:8)",
      "d": "« » Not spending from one's accumulated wealth even in places where spending is required. (Muf.) Stinginess is of two types: (1) Being stingy in fulfilling others' rights or in spending in the way of Allah, i.e., in Allah's path. (2) Not spending even on one's legitimate necessities. Both types of stinginess are condemnable, i.e., bad and detestable. And this word is general that can be used for all forms of stinginess.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَبۡخَلُوۡنَ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ النَّاسَ بِالۡبُخۡلِ وَیَکۡتُمُوۡنَ مَاۤ اٰتٰہُمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ ؕ وَاَعۡتَدۡنَا لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ عَذَابًا مُّہِیۡنًا»\nTranslation: Those who are stingy themselves and enjoin stinginess upon others and conceal what Allah has bestowed upon them of His bounty. And We have prepared for the disbelievers a humiliating punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 423,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "« » To hold back whatever one has; it is also used in the meaning of stinginess. (22 verses: 2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-7:170-16:59-16:79-17:100-22:65-31:22-33:37-35:2-35:41-38:39-39:38-39:42-43:21-43:43-60:10-65:2-67:19-67:21)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is not to let something one possesses slip from one's hand and to hold it back. Or to cling to something and protect it. (Muf.) And « » means stinginess, and « » also means a miser. (Maj.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّوۡ اَنۡتُمۡ تَمۡلِکُوۡنَ خَزَآئِنَ رَحۡمَۃِ رَبِّیۡۤ اِذًالَّاَمۡسَکۡتُمۡ خَشۡیَۃَ الۡاِنۡفَاقِ»\nTranslation: Say, [O Muhammad], 'If you possessed the treasures of the mercy of my Lord, then you would surely hold back [from spending] for fear of expenditure.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 424,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be stingy",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "« » to hold and not let decrease, used for anything worth preserving (2  : 69:12-70:18)",
      "d": "«اَلْاِیْعَاء» «وِعَاء»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«تَدۡعُوۡا مَنۡ اَدۡبَرَوَ تَوَلّٰی وَ جَمَعَ فَاَوۡعٰی»\nTranslation: It will call those who turned away and disobeyed and collected and hoarded (wealth).\n«اُذُنٌ وَّاعِیَۃٌ» «وعٰی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 425,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "« » To stop after a little spending or to intend but not complete [spending]. (2 verses: 7:58-53:34)",
      "d": "«کُدْیَۃٌ» «حَفَرَ فَاَکْدٰی» «اَکْدٰی»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَفَرَءَیۡتَ الَّذِیۡ تَوَلّٰی وَاَعۡطٰی قَلِیۡلًا وَّاَکۡدٰی»\nTranslation: Have you seen the one who turned away and gave a little, then stopped?"
    },
    {
      "id": 426,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "« » To be stingy in providing for one's family and dependents or to be stingy in spending on oneself as well. (2 verses: 2:236-25:67)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is to spend very little. (Muf.) And « » is the opposite of israf (extravagance). That is, to spend less than necessary even on one's legitimate needs and to be stingy. According to the author of 'Muntahi al-Arab', its meaning is 'a person who has made the maintenance (nafaqah) for his family and dependents very tight.' (Maj.) Allah Almighty, describing the attributes of His servants, says:\nArshad Bari Ta'ala says:\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ اَنۡفَقُوۡا لَمۡ یُسۡرِفُوۡاوَلَمۡ یَقۡتُرُوۡا وَکَانَ بَیۡنَ ذٰلِکَ قَوَامًا»\nTranslation: And those who, when they spend, are not extravagant and not stingy, but are moderate between that [extremity]."
    },
    {
      "id": 427,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "« » To be stingy in giving something desirable and beloved. (2 verses: 20:124-81:24)",
      "d": "« » means to be stingy in giving something desirable and beloved. (Muf.) And « » are things with which one is stingy due to their preciousness. (Maj.) For example, a physician being stingy in sharing his proven remedy.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَا ہُوَ عَلَی الۡغَیۡبِ بِضَنِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: And he (the Prophet, peace be upon him) is not stingy regarding the unseen (i.e., he does not conceal knowledge of the unseen)."
    },
    {
      "id": 428,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Stinginess",
      "hw": "بخل",
      "s": "« » When both stinginess and greed combine, it is called « ». (4 verses: 4:128-33:19-59:9-64:16)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is to be stingy and to crave and be greedy. (Maj.) When both stinginess and greed combine, it is called « ». (Fal 33, Maj.) And its other name is 'shiddat al-hirs' (intensity of greed), meaning to constantly worry about amassing wealth and to be stingy in spending.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یُّوۡقَ شُحَّ نَفۡسِہٖ  فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ  الۡمُفۡلِحُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And whoever is saved from the stinginess of his soul, it is they who will be the successful.\nAnd « » means a miser and greedy person; its plurals are « » and « ».\nFor example: The command of Allah Almighty is:\n«فَاِذَا ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ  اَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ»\nTranslation: Then when fear departs, they will assail you with sharp tongues, being stingy with regard to wealth. (Jalandhari) They are niggardly regarding good. (Osmani)"
    }
  ],
  "90": [
    {
      "id": 430,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Misfortune",
      "hw": "بدبختی",
      "s": "« » A person who is inherently unfortunate or ill-fated, and misfortune is his destined lot. (9 verses: 11:105-11:106-19:4-19:32-19:48-23:106-87:11-91:12-92:15)",
      "d": "« » and « » both mean misfortune, and its opposite is « ». And just as « » is among the accidental attributes (i.e., additional characteristics), similarly « » and « » are also among the accidental attributes. And « » is a person who is inherently unfortunate or ill-fated. (Muf.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا غَلَبَتۡ عَلَیۡنَا شِقۡوَتُنَا وَ کُنَّا قَوۡمًا ضَآلِّیۡنَ»\nTranslation: They (the disbelievers) will say, 'Our Lord, our misfortune has overcome us, and we were a people astray.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 431,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Misfortune",
      "hw": "بدبختی",
      "s": "« » Meaning a time of misfortune and hardship. (2 verses: 41:16-54:19)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is also brass, and a flame of fire whose color is like brass. And « » means the sky turning red and taking on the color of brass, and this is a proverb for ill-omen. And « » and « » mean a time of hardship and misfortune. The opposite of « » is « ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ رِیۡحًا صَرۡصَرًا فِیۡۤ اَیَّامٍ نَّحِسَاتٍ»\nTranslation: So We sent upon them a furious wind during days of misfortune."
    },
    {
      "id": 433,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Misfortune",
      "hw": "بدبختی",
      "s": "«شَئُوْم ۔ شَامَۃ»",
      "d": "«الشَّأمَۃَ الْمَشْئَمَۃ» «تَشَاءُم» «تَیَمُّن»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ کَانَ مِنَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَتَوَاصَوۡا بِالصَّبۡرِ وَتَوَاصَوۡا بِالۡمَرۡحَمَۃِ اُولٰٓئِکَ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡمَیۡمَنَۃِ وَالَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا بِاٰیٰتِنَا ہُمۡ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡمَشۡئَمَۃِ»\nTranslation: Then they (the believers) will be among those who have believed and advised one another to patience and advised one another to mercy. Those are the companions of the right. But those who disbelieved in Our signs, they are the companions of the left."
    },
    {
      "id": 434,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Devastating Calamity",
      "hw": "بدبختی",
      "s": "« » A calamity that erases all traces of a person (1 Verse: 69:7)",
      "d": "« » means to cut off something and erase its name and signs. And « » means sword. Then « » also refers to such a calamity or punishment that erases a person's very trace (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاَمَّا عَادٌ فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍعَاتِیَۃٍ سَخَّرَہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَبۡعَ لَیَالٍ وَّثَمٰنِیَۃَ اَیَّامٍ ۙ حُسُوۡمًا ۙ فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ اَعۡجَازُنَخۡلٍ خَاوِیَۃٍ»\nTranslation: As for 'Ad, they were utterly destroyed by a furious, screaming wind that We made rage against them for seven nights and eight days consecutively. So you could see the people lying prostrate as if they were hollow trunks of palm trees."
    }
  ],
  "91": [
    {
      "id": 435,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Curse",
      "hw": "بددعا ",
      "s": "« » A curse invoking distance from God's mercy and success (34 Verses: 2:88-2:89-2:159-2:161-3:61-3:87-4:46-4:47-4:52-4:93-4:118-5:13-5:60-5:64-5:78-7:38-7:44-9:68-11:18-11:60-11:99-13:25-15:35-24:7-24:23-28:42-29:25-33:57-33:64-33:68-38:78-40:52-47:23-48:6)",
      "d": "« » means to distance someone in anger and to revile them. When attributed to Allah Almighty, it means being distanced from His mercy and success (muf). It also means to revile, to remove from goodness, and to curse. It is a general and comprehensive word for cursing and invoking evil (manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لُعِنَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡۢ بَنِیۡۤ اِسۡرَآءِیۡلَ عَلٰی لِسَانِ دَاوٗدَ وَعِیۡسَی ابۡنِ مَرۡیَمَ»\nTranslation: Those among the Children of Israel who disbelieved were cursed on the tongue of David and Jesus, the son of Mary."
    },
    {
      "id": 437,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Curse",
      "hw": "بددعا ",
      "s": "« » Used for cursing. Its meaning carries more intensity than « » (1 Verse: 67:11)",
      "d": "«سَحَقَ» «اَسْحَقَ الثَّوْب» «اَسْحَقَہُ اللہ» «سَحِقَ سُحْقًا» «اِسْتَحَقَ» «بُعْدًا»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاعۡتَرَفُوۡا بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ ۚ فَسُحۡقًا لِّاَصۡحٰبِ السَّعِیۡرِ»\nTranslation: So they will confess their sins. So away with the companions of the Blaze! (Jalandhari )"
    }
  ],
  "92": [
    {
      "id": 439,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Deform / To Become Ugly",
      "hw": "بدصورت",
      "s": "« » Used for spoiling a good form and shape and making it bad (1 Verse: 36:67)",
      "d": "« » means to spoil the form and shape and to ruin it (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَوۡ نَشَآءُ لَمَسَخۡنٰہُمۡ عَلٰی مَکَانَتِہِمۡ فَمَا اسۡتَطَاعُوۡا مُضِیًّا وَّلَا یَرۡجِعُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And if We willed, We could have deformed them in their places, so they would not be able to move forward nor return."
    },
    {
      "id": 440,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Deform / To Become Ugly",
      "hw": "بدصورت",
      "s": "« » Used for the face and its surroundings becoming temporarily ugly due to some affliction, trouble, or emotion (1 Verse: 23:104)",
      "d": "«کَلَحَۃ» «كَالِحُ» «کَلَحَ ، کَلَّحَ» «اِکْلَوَّحَ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«تَلۡفَحُ وُجُوۡہَہُمُ النَّارُ وَہُمۡ فِیۡہَا کٰلِحُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: The Fire will scorch their faces, and they will be grimacing in it."
    },
    {
      "id": 441,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Deform / To Become Ugly",
      "hw": "بدصورت",
      "s": "« » To be inherently ugly in form and shape, and also used for bad qualities (1 Verse: 28:42)",
      "d": "« » means to be ugly, to be ill-favored. And « » means bad, ill-favored, ugly. The word « » is also used metaphorically to mean a statement, action, or form being bad (manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَیَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمَقۡبُوۡحِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And on the Day of Resurrection, they will be among the despised.\nIn this verse, « » carries both meanings."
    }
  ],
  "93": [
    {
      "id": 442,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Adultery / Fornication",
      "hw": "بدکاری",
      "s": "« » A well-known term. Committing illicit sexual relations with someone other than one's husband or wife (3 Verses: 17:32-24:2-24:3)",
      "d": "« » is a well-known term. That is, a man having illicit sexual relations with a woman other than his wife, or a woman having illicit relations with a man other than her husband, is called zina (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَقۡرَبُوا الزِّنٰۤی اِنَّہٗ کَانَ فَاحِشَۃً ؕ وَسَآءَ سَبِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And do not approach adultery. Indeed, it is an abomination and an evil way."
    },
    {
      "id": 443,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Adultery / Fornication",
      "hw": "بدکاری",
      "s": "« » A slave girl committing adultery or a prostitute making fornication her profession (18 Verses: 2:90-2:213-3:19-6:146-7:33-10:23-10:90-16:90-19:20-19:28-22:60-24:33-38:24-42:14-42:39-45:17-49:9-55:20)",
      "d": "«بَغِیَ» «بَاغَتِ الْاَمَۃُ بِغَآءً» «بَغِیّ» «بِغَاء»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ»\nTranslation: And do not compel your slave girls to prostitution.\nAt another place in the Quran, the Jews, addressing Mary (peace be upon her), say:\n«یٰۤاُخۡتَ ہٰرُوۡنَ مَا کَانَ  اَبُوۡکِ امۡرَ اَ سَوۡءٍ وَّ مَا  کَانَتۡ  اُمُّکِ  بَغِیًّا»\nTranslation: O sister of Aaron! Your father was not a man of evil, nor was your mother a fornicatress."
    },
    {
      "id": 444,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Adultery / Fornication",
      "hw": "بدکاری",
      "s": "« » To openly maintain illicit sexual relations with someone other than one's husband or wife (3 Verses: 4:24-4:25-5:5)",
      "d": "«سَفَحَ» «سَافَحَ» «صَبَّ الْمَاء بِلَا عَقْدِ نِکَاحٍ» «سَافَحَ» «مُسَافِحِیْن» «مُحْصِنِیْن» «سَافَحَ» «مُسَافِح»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَانۡکِحُوۡہُنَّ بِاِذۡنِ اَہۡلِہِنَّ وَ اٰتُوۡہُنَّ اُجُوۡرَہُنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ مُحۡصَنٰتٍ غَیۡرَ مُسٰفِحٰتٍ وَّ لَا مُتَّخِذٰتِ اَخۡدَانٍ»\nTranslation: Then marry them with the permission of their owners and give them their dowry according to what is reasonable, [being] chaste women, not those who commit open fornication, nor those who take paramours."
    },
    {
      "id": 445,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Adultery / Fornication",
      "hw": "بدکاری",
      "s": "« » Used for acts and words that lead towards adultery. Or it refers to an accusation of adultery that requires evidence (23 Verses: 2:169-2:268-3:135-4:15-4:19-4:22-4:25-6:151-7:28-7:33-7:80-12:24-16:90-17:32-24:19-24:21-27:54-29:28-29:45-33:30-42:37-53:32-65:1)",
      "d": "«فَحَشَ» «فَاحِشَۃٍ مُبَیِّنَۃ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَعۡضُلُوۡہُنَّ لِتَذۡہَبُوۡا بِبَعۡضِ مَاۤ اٰتَیۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ بِفَاحِشَۃٍ مُّبَیِّنَۃٍ»\nTranslation: And do not withhold from them [their due] in order to take [back] some of what you gave them, unless they commit a clear immorality.\nAnd the word 'fahisha' is used for an act of adultery where the proof is not yet established.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالّٰتِیۡ یَاۡتِیۡنَ الۡفَاحِشَۃَ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِکُمۡ فَاسۡتَشۡہِدُوۡا عَلَیۡہِنَّ اَرۡبَعَۃً مِّنۡکُمۡ»\nTranslation: O believers! Those among your women who commit lewdness—bring four witnesses from among you against them."
    }
  ],
  "94": [
    {
      "id": 446,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To substitute",
      "hw": "بدل",
      "s": "« » means to terminate one thing and bring another in its place (33 verses: 2:59-2:61-2:108-2:181-2:211-4:2-4:56-6:34-6:115-7:95-7:162-9:39-10:15-14:28-14:48-16:101-18:27-18:81-24:55-25:70-27:11-33:23-33:52-34:16-40:26-47:38-48:15-50:29-56:61-66:5-68:32-70:41-76:28)",
      "d": "« » is a well-known term meaning to bring one thing in place of another (transitive). Essentially, the original intention was for the first thing, but something else took its place."
    },
    {
      "id": 450,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To change",
      "hw": "بدل",
      "s": "« » to change the form (1  : 27:41-)",
      "d": "«نَکَّرَ» «نَکَّرَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ نَـکِّرُوۡا لَہَا عَرۡشَہَا»\nTranslation: Solomon ﷺ said, Change the appearance of her throne for her."
    },
    {
      "id": 451,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To change",
      "hw": "بدل",
      "s": "« » to exchange and bring to a better state (1  : 3:140)",
      "d": "«اَلدَّوْلَۃ وَالدُّوْلَۃ» «دَالَ» «دَارَ» «دَوْر» «دَائِرَۃ» «دَوْلَۃُ» «دَاوَل»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ تِلۡکَ الۡاَیَّامُ نُدَاوِلُہَا بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ»\nTranslation: And those days – We alternate them among the people."
    }
  ],
  "95": [
    {
      "id": 452,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Compensation",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » is the general term for compensation, whether less or more, good or bad (6 verses: 18:50-24:55-25:70-33:52-66:5-68:32)",
      "d": "« » means to bring one thing in place of another (transitive), and this can be less or more, good or bad, similar or different. Essentially, it is a general term for compensation. We limit ourselves to two examples here:\n«اَفَتَتَّخِذُوۡنَہٗ وَذُرِّیَّتَہٗۤ اَوۡلِیَآءَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِیۡ وَہُمۡ لَکُمۡ عَدُوٌّ ؕ بِئۡسَ لِلظّٰلِمِیۡنَ بَدَلًا»\nTranslation: Do you take Satan and his offspring as allies instead of Me, while they are your enemies? Evil is the compensation for the wrongdoers. (Jalandhari)\nAt another place, God Almighty says:\n«اِلَّا مَنۡ تَابَ وَاٰمَنَ وَعَمِلَ عَمَلًا صَالِحًا فَاُولٰٓئِکَ یُبَدِّلُ اللّٰہُ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ حَسَنٰتٍ»\nTranslation: But whoever repents, believes, and does righteous deeds, for them Allah will change their evil deeds into good ones."
    },
    {
      "id": 454,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Just compensation",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » means balanced, equal, and proportionate compensation to the original thing (24 verses: 2:48-2:123-2:282-4:3-4:58-4:129-4:135-5:8-5:95-5:106-6:1-6:70-6:115-6:150-6:152-7:159-7:181-16:76-16:90-27:60-42:15-49:9-65:2-82:7)",
      "d": "« » is compensation that is balanced, equal, and proportionate to the original thing. (See details under 'to do justice').\n«وَّلَا یُقۡبَلُ مِنۡہَا شَفَاعَۃٌ وَّلَا یُؤۡخَذُ مِنۡہَا عَدۡلٌ»\nTranslation: Neither intercession will be accepted from it, nor will any compensation be taken from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 455,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Reward",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » predetermined reward. Compensation for service. (87 verses: 2:62-2:112-2:262-2:274-2:277-3:136-3:171-3:172-3:179-3:199-4:40-4:67-4:74-4:95-4:100-4:114-4:146-4:162-5:9-6:90-7:113-7:170-8:28-9:22-9:120-10:72-11:11-11:29-11:51-11:115-12:56-12:57-12:90-12:104-16:41-16:96-16:97-17:9-18:2-18:30-18:77-25:57-26:41-26:109-26:127-26:145-26:164-26:180-28:25-28:26-28:27-28:54-29:27-29:58-33:29-33:31-33:35-33:44-34:47-35:7-36:11-36:21-38:86-39:10-39:35-39:74-41:8-42:23-42:40-48:10-48:16-48:29-49:3-52:40-57:7-57:11-57:18-57:19-57:27-64:15-65:5-67:12-68:3-68:46-73:20-84:25-95:6)",
      "d": "« » and « » is the reward that has been predetermined by a prior covenant, or at the time of need, « » (the one who gives reward) announces the reward, and « » (the one to whom reward is given) accepts it and starts the work. This is compensation for work. And it is generally used for beneficial reward. The word   comes for both religious and worldly rewards. But the word   is generally used for worldly compensation. And « » refers to the one who takes on work, and « » to the one who gives work, the servant, or the one receiving compensation (Muf). And « » means to hire someone as a laborer or servant. The use of   is mentioned in the Quran in both religious and worldly contexts.\nExample (1): The Quran says:\n«وَلَاَجۡرُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ خَیۡرٌ لِّلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَکَانُوۡا یَتَّقُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And for those who believed and remained conscious of Allah, the reward of the Hereafter is best.\nExample (2): The Quran says:\n«قَالَ اِنِّیۡۤ  اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اُنۡکِحَکَ اِحۡدَی ابۡنَتَیَّ ہٰتَیۡنِ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ تَاۡجُرَنِیۡ ثَمٰنِیَ حِجَجٍ»\nTranslation: He said, \"Indeed, I wish to marry one of my two daughters to you, on the condition that you serve me for eight years.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 457,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Reward",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » meaning good reward for good deeds. (16 verses: 2:103-2:125-3:145-3:148-3:153-3:195-4:134-5:60-5:85-18:31-18:44-18:46-19:76-28:80-48:18-83:36)",
      "d": "«ثَوَاب» «یَثُوْبُ اِلَیْہِ النَّاس»\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَاِذۡ جَعَلۡنَا الۡبَیۡتَ مَثَابَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ اَمۡنًا»\nTranslation: And when We made the House a place of return for the people and [a place of] security.\nThus, the reward that a person receives for his deeds is called   (Muf). Although its use can be for both good and evil, but generally it comes for good reward for good deeds.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَاٰتٰىہُمُ اللّٰہُ ثَوَابَ الدُّنۡیَا وَ حُسۡنَ ثَوَابِ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ»\nTranslation: So Allah gave them the reward of this world and the good reward of the Hereafter.\nAt another place, the divine command says:\n«ہَلۡ  ثُوِّبَ الۡکُفَّارُ  مَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡعَلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then the disbelievers will be recompensed for what they used to do.\nIn this verse, the word   has been used sarcastically."
    },
    {
      "id": 460,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Reward",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » severe punishment in the form of recompense. (4 verses: 5:95-59:15-64:5-65:9)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of « » include « » and « » (Muf, Majma). And it means to beat with a stick. And the word   is used for the severe punishment of a bad deed. This punishment may be in this world or the Hereafter. But mostly it is found in the form of worldly seizure or recompense.\nNow see examples:\nExample (1):   in the form of expiation:\nThe divine command says:\n«اَوۡ کَفَّارَۃٌ  طَعَامُ مَسٰکِیۡنَ اَوۡ عَدۡلُ ذٰلِکَ صِیَامًا لِّیَذُوۡقَ وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہٖ»\nTranslation: Or an expiation: the feeding of the poor or the equivalent of that in fasting, so that he may taste the consequence of his deed.\nExample (2): The divine command says:\n«کَمَثَلِ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ قَرِیۡبًا ذَاقُوۡا وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہِمۡ ۚ وَلَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: Their example is that of those who, before them, tasted the consequence of their deeds; and for them is a painful punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 461,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Reward",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » retribution for unjust killing and bodily harm. (4 verses: 2:178-2:179-2:194-5:45)",
      "d": "« » means to recompense for an action (Majma). And   generally relates to human blood and its limbs and organs. An example of this has already passed under the same title in section b, however, it is not necessary.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«اَلشَّہۡرُالۡحَرَامُ بِالشَّہۡرِالۡحَرَامِ وَالۡحُرُمٰتُ قِصَاصٌ»\nTranslation: The sacred month is for the sacred month, and the sacred things are [subject to] retaliation."
    },
    {
      "id": 463,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Blood money",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » means blood money paid by the killer or his heirs to the heirs of the victim (1 verse: 4:92)",
      "d": "«( وَدِی ) وَدَی یَدِیْ وَدْیًا وَدِیَۃً» «اَوْدٰی» «دِیَۃٌ»\n«وَ مَنۡ قَتَلَ مُؤۡمِنًا خَطَئًا فَتَحۡرِیۡرُ رَقَبَۃٍ مُّؤۡمِنَۃٍ وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا»\nTranslation: And whoever kills a believer unintentionally, then he must free a believing slave and pay blood money to the victim's heirs, unless they remit it as charity."
    },
    {
      "id": 465,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To take revenge",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » is used for severe punishment (45 verses: 2:284-3:56-3:128-3:129-4:173-5:18-5:40-5:115-5:118-7:164-8:33-8:34-9:14-9:26-9:39-9:55-9:66-9:74-9:85-9:101-9:106-17:15-17:54-17:58-18:86-18:87-20:47-26:138-26:213-27:21-29:21-33:24-33:73-34:35-37:59-48:6-48:14-48:16-48:17-48:25-58:8-59:3-65:8-88:24-89:25)",
      "d": "«عَذُبَ» «عَذْب» «مَاءٌ عَذْبٌ» «اَعْذَبْ» «باب تفعیل» «عَذَّبَ» «اَلْاَ لَمَ الْمُسْتَقِرّ» «وَمَا کُنَّا مُعَذِّبِیۡنَ حَتّٰی نَبۡعَثَ رَسُوۡلًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 466,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To take revenge",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » is used to highlight the aspect of ruler and subject in reward and punishment (84 verses: 1:3-2:132-2:193-2:217-2:256-3:19-3:24-3:73-3:83-3:85-4:46-4:125-4:146-4:171-5:3-5:54-5:57-5:77-6:70-6:137-6:159-6:161-7:29-7:51-8:39-8:49-8:72-9:11-9:12-9:29-9:33-9:36-9:122-10:22-10:104-10:105-12:40-12:76-15:35-16:52-22:78-24:2-24:25-24:55-26:82-29:65-30:30-30:32-30:43-31:32-33:5-37:20-37:53-38:78-39:2-39:3-39:11-39:14-40:14-40:26-40:65-42:13-42:21-48:28-49:16-51:6-51:12-56:56-56:86-60:8-60:9-61:9-70:26-74:46-82:9-82:15-82:17-82:18-83:11-95:7-98:5-107:1-109:6-110:2)",
      "d": "«اَلدَّیْن» «اَلَا لِلّٰہِ الدِّیۡنُ الۡخَالِصُ» «مٰلک یومِ الدین» «فَلَوۡ لَاۤ اِنۡ  کُنۡتُمۡ غَیۡرَ مَدِیۡنِیۡنَ تَرۡجِعُوۡنَہَاۤ اِنۡ  کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 467,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To take revenge",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » means to follow someone behind to take revenge for what they did (3 verses: 16:126-22:60-11:60)",
      "d": "«عَقَب» «عَقَبَ» «عَاقِب» «وَ اِنۡ عَاقَبۡتُمۡ فَعَاقِبُوۡا بِمِثۚ مَا عُوۡقِبۡتُمۡ بِہٖ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 468,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To take revenge",
      "hw": "بدلہ",
      "s": "« » means to take revenge, to inflict punishment (12 verses: 3:4-5:95-7:136-14:47-15:79-30:47-32:22-39:37-43:25-43:41-43:55-44:16)",
      "d": "«نَقَمَ» «وَ مَا نَقَمُوۡا مِنۡہُمۡ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ الۡعَزِیۡزِالۡحَمِیۡدِ» «اِنْتَقَام» «وَمَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ مِمَّنۡ ذُکِّرَ بِاٰیٰتِ رَبِّہٖ ثُمَّ اَعۡرَضَ عَنۡہَا ؕ اِنَّا مِنَ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ مُنۡتَقِمُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "96": [
    {
      "id": 470,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become insane",
      "hw": "بدمست",
      "s": "« » means the gradual, little-by-little cessation of a person's reason, degree by degree, i.e., to become insane (2 verses: 37:47-56:19)",
      "d": "«نَزَفَ» «نَزَفَ الْمَاءَ الْبِئْرَ» «نُزِفَ الْمَآء» «نُزِفَ دَمْعَہٗ» «نُزِفَ الرَّجُلُ» «لَّا یُصَدَّعُوۡنَ عَنۡہَا وَلَا یُنۡزِفُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 472,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become insane",
      "hw": "بدمست",
      "s": "« » refers to intoxication caused by drink; however, this word is also used in contexts of overwhelming love or terror (6 verses: 4:43-15:15-15:72-16:67-22:2-50:19)",
      "d": "«سُکَر» «سَکَر» «سکّر» «سَکْرَاتُ الْمَوْت» «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَقۡرَبُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَاَنۡتُمۡ سُکٰرٰی»"
    }
  ],
  "97": [
    {
      "id": 473,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bad / Evil",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "« » is used to condemn a bad deed or evil statement (39 verses: 2:90-2:93-2:102-2:126-2:206-3:12-3:151-3:162-3:187-3:197-5:62-5:63-5:79-5:80-7:150-8:16-9:73-11:98-11:99-13:18-14:29-16:29-18:29-18:50-22:13-22:72-24:57-38:56-38:60-39:72-40:76-43:38-49:11-57:15-58:8-62:5-64:10-66:9-67:6)",
      "d": "«بِئْسَ» «نِعْمَ» «فَحَسۡبُہٗ جَہَنَّمُ ؕ وَ لَبِئۡسَ الۡمِہَادُ» «نِعۡم» «عسی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 474,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bad / Evil",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "« » means evil; it is used in the senses of bad, wickedness, and affliction — anything that everyone dislikes or that causes harm (29 verses: 2:216-3:180-5:60-8:22-8:55-10:11-12:77-17:11-17:83-19:75-21:35-22:72-24:11-25:34-38:55-38:62-41:49-41:51-70:20-72:10-76:7-76:11-98:6-99:8-113:2-113:3-113:4-113:5-114:4)",
      "d": "«شَرّ» «خَیْر» «شَرّ» «شرارة» «شرر» «شرارت» «شریر» «أَشْرَار» «وَ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ تَکۡرَہُوۡا شَیۡئًا وَّ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ لَّکُمۡ ۚ وَ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ تُحِبُّوۡا شَیۡئًا وَّ ہُوَ شَرٌّ لَّکُمۡ» «وَ قَالُوۡا مَا لَنَا لَا نَرٰی رِجَالًا کُنَّا نَعُدُّہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡاَشۡرَارِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 475,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bad / Evil",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "« » means to be ugly or bad, both outwardly and inwardly; its opposite is « » (139 verses: 2:49-2:81-2:169-2:271-3:30-3:120-3:174-3:193-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:22-4:31-4:38-4:78-4:79-4:85-4:97-4:110-4:115-4:123-4:148-4:149-5:12-5:65-5:66-6:31-6:54-6:136-6:157-6:160-7:73-7:95-7:131-7:141-7:153-7:165-7:167-7:168-7:177-7:188-8:29-9:9-9:37-9:98-9:102-10:27-11:10-11:54-11:64-11:78-11:114-12:24-12:25-12:51-12:53-13:6-13:11-13:18-13:21-13:22-13:25-14:6-16:25-16:27-16:28-16:34-16:45-16:59-16:60-16:94-16:119-17:7-17:32-17:38-18:29-19:28-20:22-20:101-21:74-21:77-23:96-25:40-25:66-25:70-26:156-26:173-27:5-27:11-27:12-27:46-27:58-27:62-27:90-28:32-28:54-28:84-29:4-29:7-30:10-30:36-33:17-35:8-35:10-35:43-37:177-39:24-39:47-39:48-39:51-39:61-40:9-40:37-40:40-40:45-40:52-40:58-41:34-41:46-42:25-42:40-42:48-45:15-45:21-45:33-46:16-47:2-47:14-48:5-48:6-48:12-53:31-58:15-60:2-63:2-64:9-65:5-66:8-67:27)",
      "d": "«سَاءَ» «حَسُنَ» «سَیِّئَات» «حَسَنَات» «سَاءَ» «وَ ہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ ؕ اَلَا سَآءَ  مَا یَزِرُوۡنَ» «فَلَمَّا رَاَوۡہُ   زُلۡفَۃً  سِیۡٓئَتۡ وُجُوۡہُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» «سَآءَ» «اَسَآءَ» «فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  لِیَسُوۡٓءٗا  وُجُوۡہَکُمۡ» «سَوْء» «اِمْرَأَسَوْءٍ» «سُوْءٓ» «مُسِیْء» «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ وَ لَا الۡمُسِیۡٓءُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 476,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Bad / Evil",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "« » means to be in a bad state or to have a bad appearance; it is used for the evil of speech, action, and form; generally used outwardly (1 verse: 28:42)",
      "d": "«قَبَحَ» «قبیح» «بَدَنما» «قَبِیْح» «وَاَتۡبَعۡنٰہُمۡ فِیۡ ہٰذِہِ الدُّنۡیَا لَعۡنَۃً ۚ وَ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمَقۡبُوۡحِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 477,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak ill",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "« » means to disgrace someone by mentioning their faults (3 verses: 17:18-17:22-68:49)",
      "d": "« » means to do evil, to find faults. « » means to consider insignificant and « » means to avoid someone and consider them shameful and disgraceful for oneself (Munjid). And « » means sanctity and honor, and « » means he greatly disgraced him (M. Q.). Thus, the word « » is used for fault-finding or disgraceful acts that bring shame to the doer, and its opposite is « » (to praise).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«ثُمَّ جَعَلۡنَا لَہٗ جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلٰىہَا مَذۡمُوۡمًا مَّدۡحُوۡرًا»\nTranslation: Then We have prepared for him Hell, wherein he will enter disgraced and humiliated."
    },
    {
      "id": 478,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak ill",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "« » means to express mild reproach or resentment to remove displeasure (4 verses: 16:84-30:57-41:24-45:35)",
      "d": "« » means to reproach, to show resentment. (This word is from lexical opposites.) « » means to reproach and to be angry, and also to address with disdain. And « » means to cause displeasure to be removed, and « » means to satisfy someone and to appease someone who is angry (Munjid). Thus, « » refers to such mild reproaches and criticisms whose ultimate purpose is to gain satisfaction and acceptance. And the use of 'ataab' also applies to ruining relationships of friendship and compassion (Faqih 39).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَاِنۡ یَّسۡتَعۡتِبُوۡا فَمَا ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمُعۡتَبِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: If they seek to be appeased, they will not be the ones who are appeased.\nNote: (Lexical opposites are words that have two separate meanings that are opposite to each other.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 479,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak ill",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "« » means to blame someone for their action or to warn them of its consequences (11 verses: 5:54-14:22-17:29-17:39-23:6-37:142-51:40-51:54-68:30-70:30-75:2)",
      "d": "« » means to consider an action bad and then blame the doer (Mufradat), whether the action is inherently bad or not, and also to warn someone about the consequences of their action (Faqih 39).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«یُجَاہِدُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَلَا یَخَافُوۡنَ لَوۡمَۃَ لَآئِمٍ»\nTranslation: They strive in the way of Allah and do not fear the blame of any blamer."
    },
    {
      "id": 481,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak ill",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "« » means to reproach and scold someone for their bad deed (1 verse: 12:92)",
      "d": "« » means to reproach and scold someone for their bad deed (Mufradat)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«لَا تَثۡرِیۡبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡیَوۡمَ ؕ یَغۡفِرُ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: (Prophet Yusuf said to his brothers) There is no blame on you today. May Allah forgive you."
    },
    {
      "id": 482,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To seem bad",
      "hw": " برائی",
      "s": "« » means anything that is offensive or disliked in the eyes of common people (7 verses: 11:70-18:74-18:87-27:41-31:19-54:6-65:8)",
      "d": "« » essentially has two aspects: (1) strangeness, (2) offensiveness. And « » means to deny, and also to be amazed (i.e., to consider something surprising). And « » means anything that is disliked in the eyes of common society or that Sharia has declared disliked. And « » means such a bad thing that is offensive to everyone and seems bad.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَتَوَلَّ عَنۡہِمۡ ۘ یَوۡمَ یَدۡعُ الدَّاعِ اِلٰی شَیۡءٍ نُّکُرٍ»\nTranslation: So turn away from them until the Day when the caller will call to something offensive."
    }
  ],
  "98": [
    {
      "id": 484,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Equality ۔ To be equal ۔ To make equal",
      "hw": "برابر",
      "s": "« » refers to equality in things related to measurement, weight, or perceptible by external senses (24 verses: 2:48-2:123-2:282-4:3-4:58-4:129-4:135-5:8-5:95-5:106-6:1-6:70-6:115-6:150-6:152-7:159-7:181-16:76-16:90-27:60-42:15-49:9-65:2-82:7)",
      "d": "« » refers to equality in things related to measurement, weight, or perceptible by external senses (Mufradat). Based on these external senses, 'adl' is also called justice.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اَوۡعَدۡلُ ذٰلِکَ صِیَامًا لِّیَذُوۡقَ وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہٖ»\nTranslation: Or the equivalent of that in fasting, so that he may taste the consequence of his deed."
    },
    {
      "id": 485,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Equality ۔ To be equal ۔ To make equal",
      "hw": "برابر",
      "s": "«سَوَاء ، اَسْتَوٰی»",
      "d": "«سَوَاء ، اَسْتَوٰی»\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ ءَاَنۡذَرۡتَہُمۡ اَمۡ لَمۡ تُنۡذِرۡہُمۡ»\nTranslation: Indeed, those who disbelieve, it is all the same to them whether you warn them or do not warn them.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«ہَلۡ یَسۡتَوِی الۡاَعۡمٰی وَ الۡبَصِیۡرُ ۬ ۙ اَمۡ ہَلۡ تَسۡتَوِی الظُّلُمٰتُ وَ النُّوۡرُ»\nTranslation: Can the blind and the seeing be equal? Or can the darkness and the light be equal?\n«اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» «سَوّٰی»\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ فَسَوّٰىکَ فَعَدَلَکَ»\nTranslation: The One who created you, then made you firm, then made you equal (proportionate and balanced).\nAnd the word « » is also wide in meaning. It includes completing, making equal, making correct and proper, everything."
    }
  ],
  "99": [
    {
      "id": 487,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be wasted. To do (to be wasted. To do)",
      "hw": "برباد",
      "s": "« » meaning that an action does not yield results due to some other reasons. Good deeds being wasted due to bad deeds. (16 verses: 2:217-3:22-5:5-5:53-6:88-7:147-9:17-9:69-11:16-18:105-33:19-39:65-47:9-47:28-47:32-49:2)",
      "d": "«حَبِطَ» «حَبَِطَ دَمُّ الْقَتِیْل»\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَشۡرَکُوۡا لَحَبِطَ عَنۡہُمۡ  مَّا کَانُوۡا یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And if they had associated partners with Allah, whatever they used to do would have been wasted.\nAnd « » means to make useless or to render wasted and destroyed.\nFor example: The Quran says:\nTranslation: That is because they disliked what Allah revealed, so He rendered their deeds worthless."
    },
    {
      "id": 488,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be wasted ۔ To waste (To be lost ۔ To lose)",
      "hw": "برباد",
      "s": "« » means an opposing action that nullifies a previous action (10 verses: 2:264-7:118-7:173-8:8-10:81-29:48-30:58-40:78-45:27-47:33)",
      "d": "« » means an invalid and baseless action is called « ». Its opposite is truth. After investigation, that in which stability and permanence are not seen is batil (Mufradat). And « » means to be futile and ineffective due to not having results. Like bad omen treatment makes the benefit ineffective, or treatment eliminates the effects of disease and ends it.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَوَقَعَ الۡحَقُّ وَ بَطَلَ مَا کَانُوۡا یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then the truth prevailed, and what they used to do became false.\nAnd « » means to make an action ineffective and fruitless, which is caused by an opposing action.\nFor example, Allah says:\n«لَا تُبۡطِلُوۡا صَدَقٰتِکُمۡ بِالۡمَنِّ وَالۡاَذٰی»\nTranslation: Do not invalidate your charities by reminding (people of your favors) and causing them pain."
    },
    {
      "id": 489,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be wasted ۔ To waste (To be lost ۔ To lose)",
      "hw": "برباد",
      "s": "« » means to waste or ruin something for any reason (1 verse: 19:59)",
      "d": "« » means to waste, to destroy, to ruin, whether for any reason—it is general.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ  غَیًّا»\nTranslation: Then after them succeeded [unworthy] successors who neglected prayer and pursued desires. So they will meet evil."
    }
  ],
  "100": [
    {
