    },
    {
      "id": 515,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Scattering (Becoming Scattered)",
      "hw": "بکھرنا",
      "s": "« » means to separate and fall down (used for non-living things) (1 verse: 82:2)",
      "d": "«نَثَرَ» «اِنْتِشَار» «نَثَر» «کلمۃ تَدُلُّ عَلیٰ اِلْقَاءِ شَیْءٍ مُّتَفَرِّقٍ» «نَثَر» «اِنْتَثَر»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِذَا السَّمَآءُ انۡفَطَرَتۡ وَاِذَا الۡکَوَاکِبُ انۡتَثَرَتۡ»\nTranslation: When the heaven splits asunder, and when the stars scatter."
    },
    {
      "id": 516,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to scatter (to become dispersed)",
      "hw": "بکھرنا",
      "s": "« » means for something to scatter and spread out in the air (1 verse: 76:7)",
      "d": "« » means to fly (like a winged creature or thing) in the air, and « » means a bird, its plural is « ». « » means for something to rise high in the air and then scatter and disperse.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُوۡفُوۡنَ بِالنَّذۡرِ وَیَخَافُوۡنَ یَوۡمًا کَانَ شَرُّہٗ  مُسۡتَطِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: They fulfill their vows and fear a day whose evil will be widespread."
    }
  ],
  "106": [
    {
      "id": 517,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to raise (to make high)",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "« » means to lift something from the ground, to make it high (22 verses: 2:63-2:93-2:127-2:253-4:154-4:158-6:83-6:165-7:176-12:76-12:100-13:2-19:57-24:36-35:10-43:32-49:2-55:7-58:11-79:28-88:18-94:4)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is to raise. If this verb relates to lifting and raising something from the ground, its opposite is « ». If it relates to raising a voice, its opposite is « ».\nFor example, for raising something, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذۡ یَرۡفَعُ  اِبۡرٰہٖمُ  الۡقَوَاعِدَ مِنَ الۡبَیۡتِ وَ اِسۡمٰعِیۡلُ»\nTranslation: And when Abraham and Ishmael were raising the foundations of the House.\nAnd for raising a voice, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَرۡفَعُوۡۤا اَصۡوَاتَکُمۡ  فَوۡقَ صَوۡتِ النَّبِیِّ»\nTranslation: O you who believe! Do not raise your voices above the voice of the Prophet."
    },
    {
      "id": 518,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to raise (to make high)",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "« » means to create something. To nurture and to raise up (35 verses: 2:259-6:6-6:83-6:98-6:133-6:141-11:61-13:12-21:11-21:21-23:14-23:19-23:31-23:42-23:78-25:3-25:40-25:47-28:45-29:20-35:9-36:79-43:11-43:18-44:35-53:32-53:47-55:24-56:35-56:61-56:62-56:72-67:15-67:23-88:22-)",
      "d": "« » means for something to rise and become high (intransitive). Its meaning also includes nurturing and bringing something to maturity (transitive). « » is used in the meaning of raising. Here, the aspect of 'becoming high' of this word is under discussion. And « » means to create something, to raise it, and to bring it to maturity.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ہُوَالَّذِیۡ یُرِیۡکُمُ  الۡبَرۡقَ خَوۡفًا وَّطَمَعًا وَّ یُنۡشِئُ السَّحَابَ الثِّقَالَ»\nTranslation: He it is who shows you the lightning, causing fear and hope, and He creates the heavy clouds. (Jalandhari) He raises them. (Osmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 519,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to become high. to be elevated",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "The use of « » is general, but it is used for the height of tall trees, especially date palms (6 verses: 4:34-9:40-19:50-19:57-23:91-28:4)",
      "d": "« » means to become high, and its opposite is « ». This word is used in both places for bodies/entities (i.e., for the rank of something) and for physical height. That is, it is used for the height of a place and a body, and also for the elevation of rank. Moreover, this word is used in both blameworthy (negative description) and praiseworthy (positive description) contexts.\nNow, observe the examples:\n(1) For the height of a place, the Quran states:\n«وَّرَفَعۡنٰہُ مَکَانًا عَلِیًّا»\nTranslation: And We raised him to a high station. (Jalandhari) And We elevated him to an exalted place. (Osmani)\n(2) For the elevation of rank, the Quran states:\n«وَجَعَلۡنَا لَہُمۡ لِسَانَ صِدۡقٍ عَلِیًّا»\nTranslation: And We granted them a high reputation for truth. (Jalandhari) And We made for them a true, exalted speech. (Osmani)\n(3) Example of a blameworthy context: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ فِرۡعَوۡنَ عَلَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, Pharaoh exalted himself in the land."
    },
    {
      "id": 520,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to become high. to be elevated",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "« » literally means to become high. It is used for the height of tall and lofty trees, especially date palms (1 verse: 50:10)",
      "d": "« » is used specifically for tall and lofty trees, especially the height of date palms. (F L 43)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالنَّخۡلَ بٰسِقٰتٍ لَّہَا طَلۡعٌ نَّضِیۡدٌ»\nTranslation: And the date-palms, tall, with their fruit in clusters."
    },
    {
      "id": 521,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to become high. to be elevated",
      "hw": "بلند",
      "s": "« » is used for the height of mountains and lofty buildings (1 verse: 77:27)",
      "d": "The word « » indicates that something is great and high (M L). It is used for the height of mountains and lofty buildings (F L 43), sky-touching height. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَّجَعَلۡنَا فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ شٰمِخٰتٍ»\nTranslation: And We placed therein lofty, firmly-set mountains."
    }
  ],
  "107": [
    {
      "id": 522,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to make",
      "hw": "بنانا",
      "s": "« » its meanings are to make, but its usage is general, whether that work pertains to origination/creation or merely to arranging/giving a state (305 verses: 2:19-2:22-2:30-2:66-2:125-126-2:128-2:143-2:224-2:259-2:260-3:41-3:61-3:126-3:156-3:176-4:5-4:15-4:19-4:33-4:75-4:90-4:91-4:141-4:144-5:6-5:13-5:20-5:48-5:60-5:97-5:103-6:1-6:6-6:9-6:25-6:39-6:91-6:96-6:97-6:100-6:107-6:112-6:122-6:123-6:124-6:125-6:136-6:165-7:10-7:27-7:47-7:69-7:74-7:138-7:143-7:150-7:189-7:190-8:10-8:29-8:37-9:19-9:40-10:5-10:14-10:24-10:59-10:67-10:73-10:85-10:87-10:100-11:82-11:118-12:15-12:55-12:62-12:70-12:100-13:3-13:16-13:33-13:38-14:30-14:35-14:37-14:40-15:16-15:20-15:74-15:91-15:96-16:56-16:57-16:62-16:72-16:78-16:80-16:81-16:91-16:93-16:124-17:2-17:6-17:8-17:12-17:18-17:22-17:29-17:33-17:39-17:45-17:46-17:60-17:80-17:99-18:1-18:7-18:32-18:48-18:52-18:57-18:59-18:90-18:94-18:95-18:96-18:98-19:6-19:7-19:10-19:21-19:24-19:30-19:31-19:32-19:49-19:50-19:96-20:29-20:53-20:58-21:8-21:15-21:30-21:31-21:32-21:34-21:58-21:70-21:72-21:73-21:91-22:25-22:34-22:36-22:53-22:67-22:78-23:13-23:41-23:44-23:50-23:94-24:40-24:43-24:63-25:10-25:20-25:23-25:31-25:35-25:37-25:45-25:47-25:53-25:54-25:61-25:62-25:74-26:21-26:29-26:84-26:85-27:34-27:61-27:62-27:86-28:4-28:5-28:35-28:38-28:41-28:71-28:72-28:73-28:83-29:10-29:15-29:27-29:67-30:21-30:48-30:54-32:8-32:9-32:23-32:24-33:4-34:18-34:19-34:33-35:11-35:39-36:8-36:9-36:27-36:34-36:80-37:63-37:77-37:98-37:158-38:5-38:26-38:28-39:6-39:8-39:21-40:61-40:64-40:79-41:9-41:10-41:29-41:44-42:8-42:11-42:50-42:52-43:3-43:10-43:12-43:15-43:19-43:28-43:33-43:45-43:56-43:59-43:60-45:18-45:21-45:23-46:26-48:26-48:27-49:13-50:26-51:42-51:51-56:36-56:65-56:70-56:73-56:82-57:7-57:26-57:27-57:28-59:10-60:5-60:7-65:2-65:3-65:4-65:7-67:5-67:15-67:23-68:35-68:50-69:12-71:7-71:12-71:16-71:19-72:25-73:17-74:12-74:31-75:39-76:2-77:21-77:25-77:27-78:6-78:9-78:10-78:11-78:13-87:5-90:8-105:2-105:5)",
      "d": "The use of « » for making is general. Whether that work pertains to origination and creation or merely to arranging/giving a state.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ فِرَاشًا وَّ السَّمَآءَ بِنَآءً»\nTranslation: Who has made the earth a resting place for you and the sky a canopy."
    },
    {
      "id": 523,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to make",
      "hw": "بنانا",
      "s": "« » means to build a structure, etc. (10 verses: 9:109-9:110-16:26-18:21-37:97-40:36-50:6-51:47-61:4-78:12)",
      "d": "«بَنٰی» «بُنْیَان» «بَنَاءَ الشَّیْ بِضَمٍّ بَعْضَہٗ اِلی١ بَعْضٍ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالسَّمَآءَ  بَنَیۡنٰہَا بِاَیۡىدٍ وَّ اِنَّا لَمُوۡسِعُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And the sky We built with might, and indeed, We are expanders."
    },
    {
      "id": 524,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to make",
      "hw": "بنانا",
      "s": "« » means to make something with skilled craftsmanship (18 verses: 5:14-5:63-7:137-11:16-11:37-11:38-13:31-16:112-18:104-20:39-20:41-20:69-21:80-23:27-24:30-27:88-29:45-35:8)",
      "d": "« » means to make something beautifully with skilled craftsmanship (transitive). And « » refers to a skilled craftsman or artist. And « » means to make something with skilled craftsmanship and special attention (transitive).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاصۡنَعِ الۡفُلۡکَ بِاَعۡیُنِنَا وَ وَحۡیِنَا»\nTranslation: And construct the ship under Our observation and Our inspiration.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَاصۡطَنَعۡتُکَ لِنَفۡسِیۡ»\nTranslation: And I chose you for Myself."
    },
    {
      "id": 525,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to make",
      "hw": "بنانا",
      "s": "« », by taking two objects, means to make, and it implies continuity (i.e., the action of continuing persistently). (117 verses: 2:51-2:67-2:80-2:92-2:116-2:125-2:165-2:231-3:28-3:64-3:80-3:118-3:140-4:25-4:89-4:119-4:125-4:139-4:144-4:150-4:153-5:5-5:51-5:57-5:58-5:81-5:116-6:14-6:70-6:74-7:30-7:51-7:74-7:146-7:148-7:152-9:16-9:23-9:31-9:98-9:99-9:107-10:68-11:92-12:21-13:16-16:51-16:67-16:68-16:92-16:94-17:2-17:40-17:73-17:111-18:4-18:15-18:21-18:50-18:51-18:56-18:61-18:63-18:86-18:102-18:106-19:17-19:35-19:81-18:88-19:92-21:17-21:21-21:24-21:26-21:36-23:91-23:110-25:2-25:3-25:18-25:27-25:28-25:30-25:41-25:43-25:57-26:29-26:129-28:9-29:25-29:41-31:6-35:6-36:23-36:74-38:63-39:3-39:4-39:43-42:6-42:9-43:16-43:32-45:9-45:10-45:23-45:35-46:28-58:16-60:1-63:2-72:3-73:9-73:19-76:29-78:39)",
      "d": "« » means to take, to grasp, to acquire something. To take into possession. And « », by taking two objects, becomes a continuous form of « ». (transitive) In it, neither arrangement nor creation is involved. And it implies continuity (i.e., the action of continuing persistently).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَقَالَ الَّذِی اشۡتَرٰىہُ مِنۡ مِّصۡرَ لِامۡرَاَتِہٖۤ اَکۡرِمِیۡ مَثۡوٰىہُ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ یَّنۡفَعَنَاۤ  اَوۡنَتَّخِذَہٗ وَلَدًا»\nTranslation: And the one who bought him from Egypt said to his wife, 'Honor his lodging; perhaps he will benefit us, or we will adopt him as a son.'"
    }
  ],
  "108": [
    {
      "id": 526,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to close; to be closed",
      "hw": "بند",
      "s": "« » is used for closing doors, etc. (1 verse: 12:23)",
      "d": "«غَلَقَ» «فَکَّ» «غَلْق» «غَلَّقَ الْبَاب»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَغَلَّقَتِ الۡاَبۡوَابَ وَ قَالَتۡ ہَیۡتَ لَکَ»\nTranslation: And that woman (Zulaikha) closed the doors and said, 'Come quickly, O Joseph.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 527,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Close; To Be Closed",
      "hw": "بند",
      "s": "« » means to close something in such a way that nothing can come out (10 verses: 2:217-4:167-13:33-16:88-27:43-40:37-47:1-47:32-47:34-48:25)",
      "d": "«وَصَدَ» «اَلْوَصْدُ خَتْمُ شَیْءٍ اِلیٰ شَیْءٍ» «اَوْصَدْتُ الْقِدْرَ» «اَوْصَدْتُ الْبَابَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عَلَیۡہِمۡ نَارٌمُّؤۡصَدَۃٌ»\nTranslation: Upon them will be a fire closed (in on them)."
    },
    {
      "id": 528,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Close; To Be Closed",
      "hw": "بند",
      "s": "« » is used in the meaning of being confined or closed in a place (5 verses: 7:74-22:45-25:10-55:72-77:32)",
      "d": "«قَصَرَ» «حَبَسَ» «قَصَرَ فِی بَیْتِہٖ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حُوۡرٌ مَّقۡصُوۡرٰتٌ فِی الۡخِیَامِ»\nTranslation: (There will be) Houris, confined in pavilions."
    },
    {
      "id": 529,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to close; to be closed",
      "hw": "بند",
      "s": "« » means to grasp something in the fist and take it into one's grasp. (6 verses: 2:245-9:67-20:96-25:46-39:67-67:19)",
      "d": "« » means to grasp something in the fist, and « » is the fist. (Maf) Therefore, « » is used in meanings of shrinking, decreasing, tightening, and closing.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمُنۡکَرِ وَیَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَیَقۡبِضُوۡنَ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: (Hypocrites) enjoin evil and forbid good, and they keep their hands closed (from spending)."
    }
  ],
  "109": [
    {
      "id": 530,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to weave",
      "hw": "بُننا",
      "s": "« » is used in the sense of weaving something, such as weaving cloth. (1 verse: 51:7)",
      "d": "«حَبَّاک» «حَبَکَ الثَّوْبَ» «حَبَکَ حَابِکَ الثَّوْب» «حَبَک» «حُبُک»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالسَّمَآءِ ذَاتِ الۡحُبُکِ»\nTranslation: And by the sky possessing a web. (Meaning the sky is spread with a network of stars.) (Uthmani) And by the sky in which there are paths. (Jalandhri)"
    },
    {
      "id": 531,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to weave",
      "hw": "بُننا",
      "s": "« » is said for weaving something firmly. (1 verse: 56:15)",
      "d": "« » originally means armor-making (i.e., working with gold threads on cloth). And by extension, it is said for anything woven firmly. (Maf) And « » means finely woven or made of gold and silver. (Munjid)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«عَلٰی سُرُرٍ مَّوۡضُوۡنَۃٍ مُّتَّکِئِیۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا مُتَقٰبِلِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: On thrones, well-woven (or inlaid), reclining on them, facing each other."
    }
  ],
  "110": [
    {
      "id": 532,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » generally refers to a traveler's luggage and other heavy things (25 verses: 4:40-7:8-7:57-7:187-7:189-9:41-10:61-13:12-16:7-21:47-23:102-29:13-31:16-34:3-34:22-35:18-52:40-55:31-68:46-73:5-76:27-99:2-99:7-99:8-101:6)",
      "d": "« » means a traveler's luggage, burden, weight, etc. It is generally used for material and tangible burdens. The opposite of « » is « », meaning light in weight.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡفِرُوۡا خِفَافًا وَّ ثِقَالًا»\nTranslation: March forth, whether you are light or heavy (in burden).\nThe plural of « » is « ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَتَحۡمِلُ اَثۡقَالَکُمۡ اِلٰی بَلَدٍ لَّمۡ تَکُوۡنُوۡا بٰلِغِیۡہِ اِلَّا بِشِقِّ الۡاَنۡفُسِ»\nTranslation: And they carry your loads to a land you could not reach except with great personal hardship. Indeed, your Lord is Full of Pity, Most Merciful.\n« » can also be used metaphorically for heavy and burdensome things.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّا سَنُلۡقِیۡ عَلَیۡکَ قَوۡلًا ثَقِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: We will soon cast upon you a weighty Word. Here, « » refers to a matter, speech, or command that is very burdensome on one's nature and acting upon it requires great courage."
    },
    {
      "id": 533,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » refers to a burden that the bearer carries within themselves, such as a child in the womb, fruit on a tree, or water in a cloud. (43 verses: 2:248-2:286-6:31-6:146-7:189-9:92-11:40-12:36-12:72-13:8-16:7-16:25-17:3-17:70-19:22-19:27-19:58-20:87-20:100-20:101-20:111-22:2-23:22-24:54-29:12-29:13-29:60-31:14-33:72-35:11-35:18-36:41-40:7-40:80-41:47-46:15-54:13-62:5-65:4-65:6-69:11-69:14-69:17)",
      "d": "« » means to carry a burden, and « » is such a burden that is contained within. For example, a child in the womb, fruit on a tree, or water in a cloud. (Maf)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا تَغَشّٰہَا حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا فَمَرَّتۡ بِہٖ»\nTranslation: When the man approaches her, she conceives a light burden, then she moves about with it.\nAnd « » is the burden that is carried on the back in a sensory way. (Maf) But according to the author of 'Muntahi al-Arb', « » means bar-i-sir or bar-i-pusht, i.e., the maximum load that a carrier can carry. And this definition seems more correct. And the Quran supports this meaning:\n«قَالُوۡا نَفۡقِدُ صُوَاعَ الۡمَلِکِ وَلِمَنۡ جَآءَ بِہٖ حِمۡلُ بَعِیۡرٍ وَّاَنَا بِہٖ زَعِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: They said, 'We have lost the measure of the king, and for whoever brings it is the reward of a camel's load, and I am responsible for it.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 534,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » is generally used for a spiritual burden. And « » means the maximum possible spiritual burden according to the strength of the bearer (7 verses: 6:25-17:46-18:57-31:7-41:5-41:44-51:2)",
      "d": "«وَقْر» «فِیْ صَدْرِہٖ وَقْرٌ» «فِیْ اُذُنِہٖ وَقْرٌ» «وَقْر»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّجَعَلۡنَا عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ اَکِنَّۃً اَنۡ یَّفۡقَہُوۡہُ وَفِیۡۤ اٰذَانِہِمۡ وَقۡرًا»\nTranslation: And We have placed covers on their hearts so they do not understand it, and (We have placed) deafness in their ears.\nThe word « » refers to the maximum amount of this spiritual burden that is in accordance with the bearer's capacity and strength.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالذّٰرِیٰتِ ذَرۡوًا فَالۡحٰمِلٰتِ وِقۡرًا»\nTranslation: By the scatterers scattering, then the carriers bearing a heavy load."
    },
    {
      "id": 535,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » is generally used for the burdens of sins. (10 verses: 6:31-6:164-16:25-17:15-20:87-20:100-35:18-39:7-53:38-94:2)",
      "d": "«وِزْر» «اَلْذَنْبُ» «وِزْر» «وِزْر» «اَوْزَار» «اَوْزَرَ اِیْزَارًا» «وَزَرُ» «وِزْر»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ ؕ اَلَا سَآءَ مَا یَزِرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And they will bear their burdens on their backs. Evil is what they bear."
    },
    {
      "id": 536,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » means covenant and pledge, responsibilities of religious commands, or bonds of tradition (3 verses: 2:286-3:81-7:157)",
      "d": "« » has two meanings: (1) to bind with a rope and (2) to forcibly restrain something. In this sense, the burden of adhering to one's covenant and fulfilling religious obligations is « ». According to Ibn Faris, every contract, covenant, and relationship is an « ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«رَبَّنَا وَلَا تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡنَاۤ اِصۡرًا کَمَا حَمَلۡتَہٗ عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِنَا»\nTranslation: \"Our Lord, do not impose upon us a burden like that which You imposed upon those before us.\"\nFurthermore, « » is also applied to the obstacles that arise from a society's traditions when choosing the path of truth.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَیَضَعُ عَنۡہُمۡ اِصۡرَہُمۡ وَ الۡاَغۡلٰلَ الَّتِیۡ کَانَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ»\nTranslation: \"And He will remove from them their burden and the shackles which were upon them.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 537,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "« » refers to the burden of raising an orphan who is helpless and weak (1 verse: 16:76)",
      "d": "« » means needy, dependent, orphan, helpless, feeble, and burden. The meaning here is the responsibility of upbringing or the burden of maintenance and provision.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَحَدُہُمَاۤ اَبۡکَمُ لَا یَقۡدِرُعَلٰی شَیۡءٍ وَّہُوَ کَلٌّ عَلٰی مَوۡلٰىہُ ۙ اَیۡنَمَا یُوَجِّہۡہُّ لَایَاۡتِ بِخَیۡرٍ»\nTranslation: \"One of them is mute, unable to do anything, and is a burden on his master. Wherever he directs him, he does not bring any good.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 538,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Burden",
      "hw": "بوجھ",
      "s": "«وَزْن، مَوَازِیْن»",
      "d": "« » means scales by which something is weighed. « » is the weight placed on one of the scale's pans for weighing. « » means both the scales and the amount of weight; its plural is « ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا مَنۡ ثَقُلَتۡ مَوَازِیۡنُہٗ فَہُوَ فِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ»\nTranslation: \"Then as for one whose scales are heavy [with good deeds], he will be in a pleasant life.\""
    }
  ],
  "111": [
    {
      "id": 539,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Become Heavy (or Burdensome)",
      "hw": "بوجھل",
      "s": "« » means for something to become heavy in weight (16 verses: 7:8-7:57-7:187-7:189-9:41-13:12-16:7-23:102-29:13-35:18-52:40-68:46-73:5-76:27-99:2-101:6)",
      "d": "« » means to become heavy in weight.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا مَنۡ ثَقُلَتۡ مَوَازِیۡنُہٗ فَہُوَ فِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ»\nTranslation: \"Then as for one whose scales are heavy [with good deeds], he will be in a pleasant life.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 540,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Become Heavy (or Burdensome)",
      "hw": "بوجھل",
      "s": "« » means for one's nature to become heavy and sluggish due to laziness (2 verses: 4:142-9:54)",
      "d": "« » means for one's nature to become heavy and sluggish due to laziness. « » means to show heaviness (burden) in a matter where heaviness is inappropriate.\nFor example, regarding the hypocrites, Allah says:\n«وَلَا یَاۡتُوۡنَ الصَّلٰوۃَ اِلَّا وَ ہُمۡ کُسَالٰی»\nTranslation: \"And they do not attend to prayer except while they are lazy.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 541,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Become Heavy (or Burdensome)",
      "hw": "بوجھل",
      "s": "« » means for one's nature to become heavy due to excessive toil and hardship (1 verse: 2:255)",
      "d": "« » means for one's nature to become heavy due to excessive toil and hardship.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَا یَئُوۡدُہٗ حِفۡظُہُمَا ۚ وَ ہُوَالۡعَلِیُّ الۡعَظِیۡمُ»\nTranslation: \"And their preservation tires Him not, and He is the Most High, the Most Great.\""
    }
  ],
  "112": [
    {
      "id": 543,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Old Age",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "« » means old (elderly). It is generally used for an elderly person. It is also used for someone honored and respected, or a scholar (4 verses: 11:72-12:78-28:23-40:67)",
      "d": "«شَیْخ» «شَیْخُ الْمِرْأَۃ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ لِتَبۡلُغُوۡۤا اَشُدَّکُمۡ ثُمَّ لِتَکُوۡنُوۡا شُیُوۡخًا»\nTranslation: Then that you reach your maturity, then that you become elderly."
    },
    {
      "id": 544,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Old Age",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "« » refers to a person whose hair has started turning white (3 verses: 19:4-30:54-73:17)",
      "d": "«شَابَ» «شَابَتْ رُءُوْسُ الْاٰکَام» «اَشْیَب» «شِیْب» «شَیْب» «شِیْب»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَکَیۡفَ تَتَّقُوۡنَ اِنۡ کَفَرۡتُمۡ یَوۡمًا یَّجۡعَلُ الۡوِلۡدَانَ شِیۡبَۨا»\nTranslation: So how will you be, if you disbelieve, on a Day that will make children white-haired?"
    },
    {
      "id": 545,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Old (Elderly)",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "« » is used for middle age, between forty and sixty years (2 verses: 3:46-5:110)",
      "d": "«کَھَل» «کَھْل» «کَاہَلَ الرَّجُل»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ یُکَلِّمُ النَّاسَ فِی الۡمَہۡدِ وَ کَہۡلًا»\nTranslation: \"And he will speak to the people in the cradle and in maturity.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 546,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Old (Elderly)",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "« » is used for an old woman (it is exclusively feminine) (4 verses: 11:72-26:171-37:135-51:29)",
      "d": "« » is exclusively feminine, meaning an old woman who can no longer bear children. « » refers to one's last child.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَتۡ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤیءَ اَلِدُ وَ اَنَا عَجُوۡزٌ وَّ ہٰذَا بَعۡلِیۡ شَیۡخًا»\nTranslation: \"She said, \"Woe to me! Shall I give birth while I am an old woman, and this, my husband, is an old man?\"\""
    },
    {
      "id": 547,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Aged",
      "hw": "بوڑھا",
      "s": "«Mu'ammar»: one who lives beyond sixty years of age (11 verses: 2:96-10:16-15:72-16:70-21:44-22:5-26:18-28:45-35:11-35:37-36:68)",
      "d": "«Mu'ammar» means one who lives to a ripe old age.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَمَا یُعَمَّرُ مِنۡ مُّعَمَّرٍ وَّلَا یُنۡقَصُ مِنۡ عُمُرِہٖۤ اِلَّا فِیۡ کِتٰبٍ»\nTranslation: And no long-lived person is granted increase in age nor is his life shortened except that it is recorded in a book."
    }
  ],
  "113": [
    {
      "id": 550,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become rotten",
      "hw": "بوسیدہ",
      "s": "«Wahiya»: for something's joints to become loose (1 verse: 69:16)",
      "d": "«Wahiya» «وَحْیَ الثَّوْبَ وَالْحَبْل»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَانۡشَقَّتِ السَّمَاءُ فَہِیَ یَوۡمَئِذٍ وَّاہِیَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And the sky will split open, so on that day it will be weak (and rotten)."
    },
    {
      "id": 552,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become rotten",
      "hw": "بوسیدہ",
      "s": "«Rafata»: to crumble into pieces due to decay (2 verses: 17:49-17:98)",
      "d": "«Rafata» «رَفَتَ الْعَظْم» «الرَّفَات»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَقَالُوۡۤاءَ اِذَا کُنَّا عِظَامًا وَّرُفَاتًاءَ اِنَّا لَمَبۡعُوۡثُوۡنَ خَلۡقًا جَدِیۡدًا»\nTranslation: And they say, 'When we are bones and crumbled pieces, will we indeed be raised as a new creation?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 553,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To become rotten",
      "hw": "بوسیدہ",
      "s": "«Nakhira»: (of bones) to become hollow inside due to decay (1 verse: 79:11)",
      "d": "«Nakhira» means to become rotten and crumbled (manjad). « » means for a bone to become rotten and hollow inside or to have holes in it.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ ءَاِنَّا لَمَرۡدُوۡدُوۡنَ فِی الۡحَافِرَۃِ ءَ اِذَا کُنَّا عِظَامًا نَّخِرَۃً»\nTranslation: They say, 'Will we indeed be returned to the earth, even when we are hollow bones?'"
    }
  ],
  "114": [
    {
      "id": 555,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speaking",
      "hw": "بولنا",
      "s": "« » means to utter understandable speech, i.e., to say something whose meaning can be comprehended (11 verses: 21:63-21:65-23:62-27:16-27:85-37:92-41:21-45:29-51:23-53:3-77:35)",
      "d": "«نَطَقَ» «اَلْمَالُ النَّاطِقُ وَالصَّامِت» «مَنْطِقَ الطَّیْر» «نُطْقٌ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَمَا یَنۡطِقُ عَنِ الۡہَوٰی اِنۡ ہُوَاِلَّا وَحۡیٌ یُّوۡحٰی»\nTranslation: And he (Muhammad ﷺ) does not speak from his own desire. This (Quran) is nothing but revelation that is revealed.\nRegarding Prophet Solomon (peace be upon him), the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّاسُ عُلِّمۡنَا مَنۡطِقَ الطَّیۡرِ»\nTranslation: O people! We have been taught the language of birds. Here, « » is used in relation to Solomon's (peace be upon him) understanding and the birds' speaking.\nJust as « » is external and refers to comprehensible speech, it is also internal, referring to understanding, perception, or the language of the heart (state).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ہٰذَا کِتٰبُنَا یَنۡطِقُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ اِنَّا کُنَّا نَسۡتَنۡسِخُ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: This, our record, speaks the truth about you. Indeed, We were recording all that you used to do."
    },
    {
      "id": 558,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak",
      "hw": "بولنا",
      "s": "«Takallama»: to bring a meaningful utterance to the tongue, which another hears (10 verses: 3:41-5:110-11:105-19:10-23:108-24:16-27:82-30:35-36:65-78:38)",
      "d": "«Kallama» means to converse or talk, and «Takallama» means to speak or to bring an utterance to the tongue.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«لَّا یَتَکَلَّمُوۡنَ اِلَّا مَنۡ اَذِنَ لَہُ الرَّحۡمٰنُ»\nTranslation: No one will speak except he whom the Most Merciful permits."
    },
    {
      "id": 559,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To speak",
      "hw": "بولنا",
      "s": "«Lahina»: to adopt a different manner of speech deviating from the common way (1 verse: 47:30)",
      "d": "«Lahina» «لحن القول» «اللحن» «لَحَّنَ» «لَحَن»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَلَتَعۡرِفَنَّہُمۡ  فِیۡ لَحۡنِ الۡقَوۡلِ»\nTranslation: And you will recognize them by the tone of their speech."
    }
  ],
  "115": [
    {
      "id": 560,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To cause to flow and to flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "«Asala»: to cause any flowing thing to flow (3 verses: 13:17-34:12-34:16)",
      "d": "«Sala» means (for liquids) to flow or gush out, and «Sayl» means flowing water, flood. And «Sayyal» means flowing vigorously (manjad). Also, every flowing thing is called «Sayyal». And «Asala» means to cause (a flowing or liquid thing) to flow.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَاَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ»\nTranslation: And We caused a spring of molten copper to flow for him."
    },
    {
      "id": 562,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To cause to flow and to flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "«Sakaba»: to pour a flowing substance in such quantity that it flows (1 verse: 56:31)",
      "d": "«Sakaba» «الأسْکُوب» «الأسْکُوب» «Sakaba» «مَآءٍ مَّسْکُوْبٍ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّظِلٍّ مَّمۡدُوۡدٍ وَّمَآءٍ مَّسۡکُوۡبٍ»\nTranslation: And extended shade and flowing water. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 563,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To cause to flow and to flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "«Safaka»: commonly used for shedding blood (2 verses: 2:30-2:84)",
      "d": "«Safaka» means to shed blood or water. But it is mostly used for shedding blood. And « » means a bloodshedding person (m r).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَاِذۡ اَخَذۡنَا مِیۡثَاقَکُمۡ لَا تَسۡفِکُوۡنَ دِمَآءَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And [recall] when We took your covenant, [saying], 'You shall not shed one another's blood.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 564,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Cause to Flow / To Flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "« » denotes the rapid flowing of a fluid (3 verses: 4:24-4:25-5:5)",
      "d": "«سَفَحَ» «دَمًا مَّسْفُوْحًا» «مُسَافِحٌ» «مُسَافِحَۃ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاُحِلَّ لَکُمۡ مَّا وَرَآءَ ذٰلِکُمۡ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغُوۡا بِاَمۡوَالِکُمۡ مُّحۡصِنِیۡنَ غَیۡرَ مُسٰفِحِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And all women are lawful for you beyond those [already mentioned]. Thus, marry them with your wealth, seeking chastity and not fornication."
    },
    {
      "id": 565,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Cause to Flow / To Flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "« » means to spread over a wide area (9 verses: 2:60-2:74-17:90-17:91-18:33-36:34-54:12-76:6-82:3)",
      "d": "The primary meaning of « » is to tear something widely (m.f.), and when used for flowing things, it indicates extensiveness.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَقَالُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی تَفۡجُرَ لَنَا مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ یَنۡۢبُوۡعًا»\nTranslation: (The disbelievers) said, 'We will never believe you until you cause a spring to gush forth for us from the ground.'\nFor flowing, « » and « » have already been discussed above. Now see their examples.\n(1) Example of « »: The Quran states:\n«اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا»\nTranslation: He sent down water from the sky, so the valleys flowed according to their capacity.\n(2) Example of « »: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا سَمِعُوۡا مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَی الرَّسُوۡلِ تَرٰۤی اَعۡیُنَہُمۡ تَفِیۡضُ مِنَ الدَّمۡعِ مِمَّا عَرَفُوۡا مِنَ الۡحَقِّ»\nTranslation: And when they hear what has been revealed to the Messenger, you see their eyes overflowing with tears because they recognize the truth."
    },
    {
      "id": 566,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Cause to Flow / To Flow",
      "hw": "بہنا",
      "s": "« » means to flow or move continuously over a distance or time (60 verses: 2:25-2:164-2:266-3:15-3:136-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-5:12-5:85-5:119-6:6-7:43-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:9-10:22-11:42-13:2-13:35-14:23-14:32-16:31-18:31-20:76-21:81-22:14-22:23-22:65-25:10-29:58-30:46-31:29-31:31-35:13-36:38-38:36-39:5-39:20-43:51-45:12-47:12-48:5-48:17-51:3-54:14-55:50-57:12-58:22-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-69:11-85:11-88:12-98:8)",
      "d": "«جَرْیًا وَجِرْیَانًا»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فِیۡہَا عَیۡنٌ جَارِیَۃٌ»\nTranslation: In it (Paradise) is a flowing spring.\nThen this word began to be used for anything that flows or moves continuously over distance or time. Thus, its usage became common in both temporal and spatial contexts. For instance, in the Quran, it is used for winds or the movement of the moon and sun. Moreover, it is used metaphorically, such as the famous term 'Sunnah Jariyah' (continuous tradition)."
    }
  ],
  "116": [
    {
      "id": 567,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Excuse: Making an Excuse",
      "hw": "بہانہ",
      "s": "« » means to present a reason to dismiss an accusation, and « » is used for making a false excuse. (6 verses: 7:164-9:90-18:76-30:57-40:52-77:6)",
      "d": "« » means to present a reason to dismiss an accusation. According to Imam Raghib, it is an attempt by which a person seeks to erase their sins. And « » means to accept an excuse, « » means to give a small excuse or state a false and weak reason, and « » means to present an excuse. Now, this excuse also has three types: the first type is « »."
    },
    {
      "id": 568,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Excuse: Making an Excuse",
      "hw": "بہانہ",
      "s": "« » is when a person uses falsehood to deny an accusation or sin. (1 verse: 6:23)",
      "d": "« » is when a person uses falsehood to deny that very accusation or sin. For this, the Quran has used the word « ».\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«ثُمَّ لَمۡ تَکُنۡ فِتۡنَتُہُمۡ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ قَالُوۡا وَاللّٰہِ رَبِّنَا مَا کُنَّا مُشۡرِکِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then their [attempted] excuse will not be except that they will say, 'By Allah, our Lord, we were not polytheists.'\nThe word 'fitnah' is also used for testing, examining, and scrutinizing someone."
    },
    {
      "id": 569,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Excuse: Making an Excuse",
      "hw": "بہانہ",
      "s": "« » means to present an excuse for not doing something, whether the excuse is false or true. (6 verses: 7:164-9:90-18:76-30:57-40:52-77:6)",
      "d": "« » is when a person presents a false reason or lie to absolve themselves. Therefore, the Quran has used the word « ».\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ جَآءَ الۡمُعَذِّرُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ لِیُؤۡذَنَ لَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And some of the desert Arabs came to you to be excused [from Jihad] so that they may be permitted [to stay behind].\nIt is also possible that the excuse is actually valid and reasonable. For this, the words « » and « » appear in the Quran.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَاِذۡ قَالَتۡ اُمَّۃٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ لِمَ تَعِظُوۡنَ قَوۡمَۨا ۙ اللّٰہُ مُہۡلِکُہُمۡ اَوۡ مُعَذِّبُہُمۡ عَذَابًا شَدِیۡدًا ؕ قَالُوۡا مَعۡذِرَۃً اِلٰی رَبِّکُمۡ  وَلَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَّقُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And when a group among them said, 'Why do you advise a people whom Allah will destroy or punish with a severe punishment?' They said, '[We advise them] as an excuse to your Lord, and perhaps they may fear [Allah].'"
    }
  ],
  "117": [
    {
      "id": 570,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Slander",
      "hw": "بہتان",
      "s": "« » is an accusation that throws people into a pit of astonishment (8 verses: 2:258-4:20-4:112-4:156-21:40-24:16-33:58-60:12)",
      "d": "« » means to be astonished and bewildered (m.f.) or to become silent and speechless due to amazement (minjadd). And « » is a statement that, upon hearing, makes people lose their senses, remain astonished and perplexed, and cannot believe that such a thing is possible.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَوۡلَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ قُلۡتُمۡ مَّا یَکُوۡنُ لَنَاۤ اَنۡ نَّتَکَلَّمَ بِہٰذَا ٭ۖ سُبۡحٰنَکَ ہٰذَا بُہۡتَانٌ عَظِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: And why did you not, when you heard it, say, 'It is not for us to speak of this. Exalted are You! This is a great slander.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 571,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Slander",
      "hw": "بہتان",
      "s": "« » is a baseless accusation, a fabricated story by distorting the original matter (12 verses: 7:17-24:11-24:12-25:4-26:45-29:17-34:43-37:151-46:11-46:22-46:28-51:9)",
      "d": "« » means to turn something away from its correct direction (m.f.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَجِئۡتَنَا لِتَاۡفِکَنَا عَنۡ اٰلِہَتِنَا»\nTranslation: They (the people of 'Ad) said, 'Have you come to turn us away from our gods?'\n«اِفْک» «اِفْک» «اَفَّاک» «اِفْک» «فَاحِشَ اَلْقُبْح»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَوۡلَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ ظَنَّ الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَالۡمُؤۡمِنٰتُ بِاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ خَیۡرًا ۙ وَّقَالُوۡا ہٰذَاۤ اِفۡکٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ»\nTranslation: When you heard it, why did the believing men and women not think well of themselves and say, 'This is a clear fabrication'?\nThus, « » is such that it is based on baseless talks and such a big lie that sound reason is stunned, considering it a slander."
    }
  ],
  "118": [
    {
      "id": 574,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Mislead and to be Misled",
      "hw": "بہکنا",
      "s": "« » means to become entangled in a wrong action due to ignorance. (13 verses: 2:256-7:16-7:146-7:202-11:34-15:39-19:59-20:121-28:18-28:63-37:32-38:82-53:2)",
      "d": "« » means to become entangled in a wrong action due to ignorance (m. r.) and then to become hopeless from the right path (m. r.), and its usage is only in religious matters. (Faqih 177)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَعَصٰۤی اٰدَمُ رَبَّہٗ فَغَوٰی»\nTranslation: And Adam disobeyed his Lord and became astray.\nThe opposite of « » is « », meaning to become established on the straight path and adopt good conduct. And « » means guided.\nFor example, Allah says:\n«قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ»\nTranslation: Guidance has become clear from misguidance.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«مَا ضَلَّ صَاحِبُکُمۡ وَمَا غَوٰی»\nTranslation: Your companion [Muhammad] has neither strayed nor become astray."
    },
    {
      "id": 575,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Mislead and to be Misled",
      "hw": "بہکنا",
      "s": "« » refers to a flat plain where one who walks becomes lost. (1 verse: 5:26)",
      "d": "«تَاہَ، تِیْہ، تِیْھَاء» «تَاہَ»\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَالَ فَاِنَّہَا مُحَرَّمَۃٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ سَنَۃً ۚ یَتِیۡہُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ»\nTranslation: Allah said, 'Then indeed, it is forbidden to them for forty years; they will wander throughout the land.'"
    }
  ],
  "119": [
    {
      "id": 576,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "« » means to flee, especially of an accused person (10 verses: 18:18-26:21-33:13-33:16-51:50-62:8-71:6-74:51-75:10-80:34)",
      "d": "«فَرَّ» «فَرَّمِنَ الْحَرْبِ فِرَارًا» «مَفَرّ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّنۡ یَّنۡفَعَکُمُ الۡفِرَارُ اِنۡ فَرَرۡتُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمَوۡتِ اَوِالۡقَتۡلِ وَاِذًا لَّا تُمَتَّعُوۡنَ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: Say, 'Your fleeing will not benefit you if you flee from death or killing, and then you will not be given enjoyment except for a little.'\n«اَلْفَرَّار» «مَفَرٌ مِّنَ الْخَیْل»\nThe divine command states:\n«فَفِرُّوۡۤا اِلَی اللّٰہِ ؕ اِنِّیۡ لَکُمۡ  مِّنۡہُ نَذِیۡرٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ»\nTranslation: 'So flee to Allah. Indeed, I am to you from Him a clear warner.'\nIn this verse, both the aforementioned meanings are found."
    },
    {
      "id": 577,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "« » means for a slave to flee from his master or to escape from responsibilities (1 verse: 37:140)",
      "d": "The word « » is specific for a slave fleeing from his master (m.f., minjadd), especially when there is no danger from the master (f.l. 31). This word is also used for escaping from one's responsibilities.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِنَّ یُوۡنُسَ لَمِنَ الۡمُرۡسَلِیۡنَ اِذۡاَبَقَ اِلَی الۡفُلۡکِ الۡمَشۡحُوۡنِ»\nTranslation: And indeed, Jonah was among the messengers when he fled to the laden ship.\nIn this verse, the word « » conveys all these meanings."
    },
    {
      "id": 578,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "« » means to flee after being weakened and defeated (1 verse: 17:81)",
      "d": "«زَھَقَ» «زَھَقَتْ نَفْسُہٗ» «زَاهِقُ» «اَزْھَقَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَقُلۡ جَآءَ الۡحَقُّ وَ زَہَقَ الۡبَاطِلُ ؕ اِنَّ الۡبَاطِلَ کَانَ زَہُوۡقًا»\nTranslation: And say, 'Truth has come and falsehood has vanished. Indeed, falsehood is bound to vanish.' (Jalandhari)\nAnd say, 'Has truth come and falsehood fled?' Indeed, falsehood is one that flees. (Osmani)\nNote: (In lexicology, addad are words that have two opposite meanings.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 579,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "« » means for a criminal to flee in such a way during the commission of a crime as to avoid being caught (1 verse: 72:12)",
      "d": "« » means to flee due to the risk of being caught oneself (f.l. 31), such as a thief fleeing upon being detected during theft or stealing goods and taking them away. And « » means tax evasion, and « » is used in the sense of smuggling (Qamus al-Jadid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّاَنَّا ظَنَنَّاۤ اَنۡ لَّنۡ نُّعۡجِزَاللّٰہَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَلَنۡ نُّعۡجِزَہٗ ہَرَبًا»\nTranslation: And we thought that we could not escape Allah in the land, nor could we flee from Him by running away."
    },
    {
      "id": 580,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Flee / To Cause to Flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "« » means to flee in fright (7 verses: 4:71-9:38-9:39-9:41-9:81-9:122-74:50)",
      "d": "« » means to go out for war, etc., and « » means to flee in fright from something (m.f.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کَاَنَّہُمۡ حُمُرٌ مُّسۡتَنۡفِرَۃٌ فَرَّتۡ مِنۡ قَسۡوَرَۃٍ»\nTranslation: As if they were donkeys fleeing from a lion."
    },
    {
      "id": 581,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To flee; to cause to flee",
      "hw": "بھاگنا",
      "s": "«شَرَّدَ الْبَعِیْر»",
      "d": "«شَرَّدَ الْبَعِیْر» «شَرَّدَ» «فَاِمَّا تَثۡقَفَنَّہُمۡ فِی الۡحَرۡبِ فَشَرِّدۡ بِہِمۡ مَّنۡ خَلۡفَہُمۡ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَذَّکَّرُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "120": [
    {
      "id": 582,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Brother",
      "hw": "بھائی",
      "s": "« » is used for both brothers and sisters (14 verses: 4:11-4:23-4:176-12:5-12:7-12:8-12:58-12:69-12:100-20:42-24:31-24:61-33:55-49:10)",
      "d": "«اِخوَۃٌ» «فَاِنۡ کَانَ لَہٗۤ اِخۡوَۃٌ» «اِخْوَۃٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 583,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "brother",
      "hw": "بھائی",
      "s": "« » is used for brotherhood, fraternal relations, and friendship (21 verses: 2:220-3:103-3:156-3:168-6:87-7:202-9:11-9:23-9:24-15:47-17:27-26:106-26:124-26:142-26:161-33:5-33:18-50:13-58:22-59:10-59:11)",
      "d": "The word « » denotes sincerity, friendship, and brotherhood.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ رَبَّنَا اغۡفِرۡ لَنَا وَلِاِخۡوَانِنَا الَّذِیۡنَ سَبَقُوۡنَا بِالۡاِیۡمَانِ»\nTranslation: They say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.'\nAnd the command of Allah is:\n«اِنَّمَا الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ اِخۡوَۃٌ»\nTranslation: The believers are but brothers.\nIn this verse, it is indicated that the believers should not be considered merely as having a relationship of sincerity and friendship, but should be regarded as a fraternal bond like blood relations."
    }
  ],
  "121": [
