    },
    {
      "id": 598,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to send",
      "hw": "بھیجنا",
      "s": "« » means to send someone alone for the accomplishment of a purpose (54 verses: 2:56-2:129-2:213-2:246-2:247-2:259-3:164-4:35-5:12-5:31-6:36-6:60-6:65-7:14-7:103-7:167-10:74-10:75-15:36-16:21-16:36-16:38-16:84-16:89-17:5-17:15-17:79-17:94-18:12-18:19-19:15-19:33-22:5-22:7-23:16-23:100-25:41-25:51-26:36-26:87-27:65-28:59-30:56-31:28-36:52-37:144-38:79-40:34-58:6-58:18-62:2-64:7-72:7-91:12)",
      "d": "«بَعَثَ» «بَعَثْتُ الْبَعِیْر»\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ»\nTranslation: And God sent a crow that began to scratch the earth.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«ہُوَالَّذِیۡ بَعَثَ فِی الۡاُمِّیّٖنَ رَسُوۡلًا مِّنۡہُمۡ یَتۡلُوۡاعَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِہٖ وَیُزَکِّیۡہِمۡ»\nTranslation: He it is who sent among the unlettered a messenger from themselves, reciting to them His verses and purifying them."
    }
  ],
  "126": [
    {
      "id": 599,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "« » means to describe the state of something (14 verses: 6:100-6:139-12:18-12:77-16:62-16:116-21:18-21:22-21:112-23:91-23:96-37:159-37:180-43:82)",
      "d": "« » means to describe the state and definition of something (whether true or false), to depict. (mufrad)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَالَ بَلۡ سَوَّلَتۡ لَکُمۡ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ اَمۡرًا ؕ فَصَبۡرٌ جَمِیۡلٌ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ الۡمُسۡتَعَانُ عَلٰی مَا تَصِفُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Jacob (peace be upon him) said, \"Rather, you have fabricated a matter yourselves. So patience is most fitting. And God is the one sought for help against what you describe.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 600,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "« » means to narrate a story or event (20 verses: 3:62-4:164-6:57-6:130-7:7-7:35-7:101-7:176-11:100-11:120-12:3-12:5-12:111-16:118-18:13-18:64-20:99-27:76-28:25-40:78)",
      "d": "« » means to follow someone's footsteps (mufrad).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَارۡتَدَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمَا قَصَصًا»\nTranslation: So they both turned back, following their footprints.\nFrom this, « » also means to follow gradually, i.e., to proceed step by step (manjad), meaning to narrate an event or story that has been passed down through generations.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«نَحۡنُ نَقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ اَحۡسَنَ الۡقَصَصِ بِمَاۤ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ اِلَیۡکَ ہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنَ»\nTranslation: We relate to you the best of stories in what We have revealed to you of this Quran.\nThen this word came to be used for narrating any general event or story.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«فَلَمَّا جَآءَہٗ وَقَصَّ عَلَیۡہِ الۡقَصَصَ ۙ قَالَ لَا تَخَفۡ ٝ۟ نَجَوۡتَ مِنَ الۡقَوۡمِ الظّٰلِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: When Moses came to him and narrated his story to him, he said, \"Do not fear; you have escaped from the wrongdoing people.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 601,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "«ضَرَبَ ، مَثَلًا»",
      "d": "«مَثَلًا» «ضَرْبُ الْمِثْل»\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡیٖۤ اَنۡ یَّضۡرِبَ مَثَلًا مَّا بَعُوۡضَۃً فَمَا فَوۡقَہَا»\nTranslation: Indeed, God is not ashamed to set forth an example of a mosquito or what is smaller than it."
    },
    {
      "id": 602,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "« » means to inform of something that common people are unaware of (8 verses: 2:76-18:70-20:113-21:2-26:5-65:1-93:11-99:4)",
      "d": "« » means for something to come into existence that was not present before (m. l). And « » means to inform of something that common people are unaware of.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَقَالَ الۡاِنۡسَانُ مَا لَہَا ، یَوۡمَئِذٍ تُحَدِّثُ اَخۡبَارَہَا»\nTranslation: And man will say, \"What is the matter with her?\" On that Day, she will narrate her news."
    },
    {
      "id": 604,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "« » means to shed light on different aspects of a matter (26 verses: 3:152-6:16-6:46-6:65-6:105-7:47-7:58-7:146-9:127-10:32-12:24-12:33-12:34-17:41-17:89-18:53-18:54-20:113-24:43-25:19-25:50-25:65-39:6-40:69-46:27-46:29)",
      "d": "« » means to turn something from one state to another, and « » means to repeat and describe something (mufrad). That is, to explain a matter by presenting it in different ways and shedding light on its various aspects.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اُنۡظُرۡ کَیۡکَ نُصَرِّفُ الۡاٰیٰتِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: See how We diversify the verses so that they may understand."
    },
    {
      "id": 605,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "« » means to state something in an ordered and separate manner (33 verses: 2:249-6:55-6:97-6:98-6:114-6:119-6:126-7:32-7:52-7:133-7:174-9:11-10:5-10:24-11:1-12:94-13:2-17:12-22:17-30:28-32:25-37:21-38:20-41:3-41:44-42:21-44:40-60:3-77:13-77:14-77:38-78:17-86:13)",
      "d": "« » means for one thing to be separate from another such that there is a distance between them. And « » means to separate and arrange a matter and state it in an ordered manner.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَکُلَّ شَیۡءٍ فَصَّلۡنٰہُ تَفۡصِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And We have detailed everything in detail."
    },
    {
      "id": 606,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to describe",
      "hw": "بیان",
      "s": "« » means to explain ambiguous and difficult passages (1 verse: 25:33)",
      "d": "« » means to state the spiritual attributes of something (mufrad). Also, « » means to explain the meaning and intent. And « » means to remove the veil from something (m. l. manjad). And this is generally done with two words: 1. With « » the ambiguous (i.e., that which is not clear in meaning and not understood) is explained, and with « » the meaning and intent are explained. And it means to state each word of a sentence clearly and consider the revelation (faq l 43).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَلَا یَاۡتُوۡنَکَ بِمَثَلٍ اِلَّا جِئۡنٰکَ بِالۡحَقِّ وَاَحۡسَنَ  تَفۡسِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: And they do not come to you with an example except that We bring you the truth and the best explanation."
    }
  ],
  "127": [
    {
      "id": 607,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "son and daughter",
      "hw": "بیٹا",
      "s": "« » literal meaning is boy (40 verses: 2:116-2:233-3:47-4:11-4:12-4:75-4:98-4:127-4:171-4:176-6:101-10:68-12:21-17:111-18:4-18:39-19:15-19:33-19:35-19:77-19:88-19:91-19:92-21:26-23:91-25:2-26:18-28:9-31:33-37:152-39:4-43:81-56:17-58:2-71:21-72:3-73:17-76:19-90:3-112:3)",
      "d": "«وَلَدُ» «وَلَدُ، وَلِیْد، مَوْلُوْد» «وَلِیْد» «وَلِیْدَۃ» «وَلِیْدَۃ» «وَلَدُ» «وَلَدُ» «وَلِیْد»\n«اَلَمۡ نُرَبِّکَ فِیۡنَا وَلِیۡدًا»\nTranslation: Did we not raise you among us as a child?\nAnd « » is generally attributed to the father. It is rarely attributed to the mother. And « » comes in the meaning of son. Its application is generally for a young child (manjad), but it can also be for an adult. As the Almighty says:\n«وَلَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ ہُوَ جَازٍعَنۡ وَّالِدِہٖ شَیۡئًا»\nTranslation: And no son will bear the burden of his father."
    }
  ],
  "128": [
    {
      "id": 609,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "to sit",
      "hw": "بیٹھنا",
      "s": "« » means to sit after lying down, standing, or moving, i.e., after any movement (1 verse: 58:11)",
      "d": "« » is commonly used in the meaning of sitting. Whether one sits after lying down or after coming from somewhere or after standing, and its opposite is « ». And « » means high and hard ground, and « » means to place one's seat on hard ground and sit. The place of sitting is called « », and those who sit together are also called « ». Its plural is « ». And « » is a repeated noun, meaning to sit once or the state of sitting. (muf. manjad)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا قِیۡلَ لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا یَفۡسَحِ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when it is said to you, \"Make room in the assemblies,\" then make room; God will make room for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 610,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To sit",
      "hw": "بیٹھنا",
      "s": "« » means to sit (20 verses: 2:127-3:168-3:191-4:103-4:140-6:68-7:16-7:86-9:5-9:46-9:81-9:83-9:90-16:26-17:22-17:29-24:60-54:55-72:9-85:6)",
      "d": "«قَعَدَ» «قَعْدَۃ» «فَلَا تَقۡعُدۡ بَعۡدَ الذِّکۡرٰی مَعَ الۡقَوۡمِ الظّٰلِمِیۡنَ» «وَجَآءَ الۡمُعَذِّرُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ لِیُؤۡذَنَ لَہُمۡ وَقَعَدَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَذَبُوا اللّٰہَ وَرَسُوۡلَہٗ» «قَعَدَ» «قَعُوْدًا» «مَقْعَد» «فِیۡ مَقۡعَدِ صِدۡقٍ عِنۡدَ مَلِیۡکٍ مُّقۡتَدِرٍ» «قَعَدَ» «قَعَدَ لِلْحَرْبِ» «فَاقۡتُلُواالۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ حَیۡثُ وَجَدۡتُّمُوۡہُمۡ وَخُذُوۡہُمۡ وَاحۡصُرُوۡہُمۡ وَاقۡعُدُوۡا لَہُمۡ کُلَّ مَرۡصَدٍ» «قَعِیْدَہ» «قواعد» «وَالۡقَوَاعِدُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ الّٰتِیۡ لَا یَرۡجُوۡنَ نِکَاحًا»"
    }
  ],
  "129": [
    {
      "id": 612,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Sick",
      "hw": "بیمار",
      "s": "« » is used only for minor physical ailments (2 verses: 37:89-37:145)",
      "d": "«سَقِمَ» «سَقِمَ» «فَنَظَرَ نَظۡرَۃً فِی النُّجُوۡمِ، فَقَالَ اِنِّیۡ سَقِیۡمٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 613,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Sick (general)",
      "hw": "بیمار",
      "s": "« » is used for all types of sickness—physical, mental, minor, or severe (23 verses: 2:10-2:184-2:185-2:196-4:43-4:102-5:6-5:52-8:49-9:91-9:125-22:53-24:50-24:61-26:80-33:12-33:32-33:60-47:20-47:29-48:17-73:20-74:31)",
      "d": "«مَرِیْض» «سَقِیْمٌ» «مَرَضُ الْمَوْت» «مرض»\n«فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ مَّرَضٌ ۙ فَزَادَہُمُ اللّٰہُ مَرَضًا»\nTranslation: There is a disease in their hearts, and Allah has increased them in disease.\nAnd by 'mental ailments' are meant vile morals, such as cowardice, stinginess, hypocrisy, disbelief, etc.\nThe plural of « » is « », and its plural is « ».\n«لَیۡسَ عَلَی الضُّعَفَآءِ وَلَا عَلَی الۡمَرۡضٰی وَلَاعَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ مَا یُنۡفِقُوۡنَ حَرَجٌ»\nTranslation: There is no blame upon the weak, nor upon the sick, nor upon those who find nothing to spend (for Jihad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 614,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Sick (severe/terminal)",
      "hw": "بیمار",
      "s": "« » refers to a patient who is emaciated, weak, and near death (1 verse: 12:85)",
      "d": "«حَرَضَ» «اَحْرَضَہُ الْمَرَضَ اَوِ الْحُزْن» «حَرَضَ»\n«قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ  یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: They said, 'By Allah, you will not cease remembering Yusuf until you become gravely ill or become of those who perish.'"
    }
  ],
  "130": [
    {
      "id": 615,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "« » is used for wife in Arabic (72 verses: 2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7)",
      "d": "«زَوْج» «زَوْج» «زَوْج» «وَ قُلۡنَا یٰۤاٰدَمُ اسۡکُنۡ اَنۡتَ وَ زَوۡجُکَ الۡجَنَّۃَ» «قَدۡ سَمِعَ اللّٰہُ قَوۡلَ الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 616,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "« » means a woman who is in one's marriage (1 verse: 4:23)",
      "d": "«حَلَائِل» «حَلِیْلَہ» «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» «حَلِیْل» «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» «حَلِیْل» «حَلِیْل» «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» «حَلَائِل» «حَلِیْل» «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» «وَ حَلَآئِلُ اَبۡنَآئِکُمُ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَصۡلَابِکُمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 617,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife (general woman)",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "« » means a general woman and is also used for a wife (25 verses: 2:282-3:35-3:40-4:12-4:128-7:83-11:71-11:81-12:21-12:30-12:51-15:60-19:5-19:8-27:23-27:57-28:9-28:23-29:32-29:33-33:50-51:29-66:10-66:11-111:4)",
      "d": "« » means a general woman, and this word has also been used for a wife.\n«ضَرَبَ اللّٰہُ مَثَلًا  لِّلَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوا امۡرَاَتَ نُوۡحٍ وَّامۡرَاَتَ لُوۡطٍ»\nTranslation: Allah has set forth an example for those who disbelieve: the wife of Noah and the wife of Lot."
    },
    {
      "id": 618,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "« » means woman and is also used for wives (51 verses: 2:49-2:187-2:222-2:223-2:226-2:231-2:232-2:235-2:236-3:14-3:42-3:61-4:1-4:3-4:4-4:7-4:11-4:15-4:19-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:32-4:34-4:43-4:75-4:98-4:127-4:176-5:6-7:81-7:127-7:141-14:6-24:31-24:60-27:55-28:4-33:30-33:32-33:52-33:55-33:59-40:25-48:25-49:11-58:2-58:3-65:1-65:4)",
      "d": "«اِمْرَأَۃٌ» «یٰنِسَآءَ النَّبِیِّ لَسۡتُنَّ کَاَحَدٍ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 619,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife (honorific)",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "« » is used as an honorific to address a woman, e.g., 'Mrs.' and is also used for a wife (4 verses: 6:101-70:12-72:3-80:36)",
      "d": "« » means companion and friend. From it, the feminine « » is derived, which has been used in the meaning of a wife.\n«یَوۡمَ یَفِرُّالۡمَرۡءُ مِنۡ اَخِیۡہِ ، وَاُمِّہٖ وَاَبِیۡہِ ، وَصَاحِبَتِہٖ وَ بَنِیۡہِ»\nTranslation: The Day when a man will flee from his brother, his mother, his father, his wife, and his children."
    },
    {
      "id": 620,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Wife (household/family)",
      "hw": "بیوی",
      "s": "«اَھْل» «اَھْلَ الرَّجُل»",
      "d": "«اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» «اَھْلَ الرَّجُل»\n«قَالَتۡ مَا جَزَآءُ مَنۡ اَرَادَ بِاَہۡلِکَ سُوۡٓءً»\nTranslation: She [Zulaikha] said to her husband, 'What is the punishment for one who intends evil against your wife?'"
    }
  ],
  "131": [
    {
      "id": 622,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Injustice; to do injustice",
      "hw": "نا انصافی",
      "s": "« » refers to any injustice, whether related to God's rights or others' rights (128 verses: 2:54-2:57-2:59-2:150-2:165-2:231-2:272-2:279-2:281-3:25-3:108-3:117-3:135-3:161-4:10-4:30-4:40-4:49-4:64-4:77-4:110-4:124-4:148-4:153-4:160-4:168-5:39-6:21-6:45-6:82-6:93-6:131-6:144-6:157-6:160-7:9-7:23-7:37-7:103-7:160-7:162-7:165-7:177-8:25-8:60-9:36-9:70-10:13-10:17-10:44-10:47-10:52-10:54-11:18-11:37-11:67-11:94-11:101-11:113-11:116-11:117-13:6-14:44-14:45-16:33-16:41-16:61-16:85-16:111-16:118-17:59-17:71-18:15-18:33-18:49-18:57-18:59-18:87-19:60-20:111-20:112-21:3-21:47-22:25-22:39-23:27-23:62-25:4-25:19-26:227-27:11-27:14-27:44-27:52-27:85-28:16-29:40-29:46-29:68-30:9-30:29-30:57-31:13-32:22-34:19-34:42-36:54-37:22-38:24-39:32-39:47-39:51-39:69-40:17-40:31-42:41-42:42-43:39-43:65-43:76-45:22-46:12-46:19-51:59-52:47-53:52-61:7-65:1)",
      "d": "«ظَلَمَ» «ظُلْمَتْ» «ظُلُمٰت» «اَلْجَمْعُ ظَّلَام» «یٰبُنَیَّ لَا تُشۡرِکۡ بِاللّٰہِ ؕ ؔاِنَّ الشِّرۡکَ لَظُلۡمٌ عَظِیۡمٌ» «لَا یُحِبُّ اللّٰہُ الۡجَہۡرَ بِالسُّوۡٓءِ مِنَ الۡقَوۡلِ اِلَّا مَنۡ ظُلِمَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 623,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Injustice or doing injustice",
      "hw": "نا انصافی",
      "s": "« » means to show bias in fulfilling the rights of another and to give less (1 verse: 24:50)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of « » is « » or inclination towards a side (m. l.), i.e., to lean towards one side while judging and not to do justice (muf). Then, the meanings of « » also include to diminish something from its sides and to reduce it (manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَمۡ یَخَافُوۡنَ اَنۡ یَّحِیۡفَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وَ رَسُوۡلُہٗ»\nTranslation: Or do they fear that Allah and His Messenger will deal unjustly with them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 624,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Injustice or doing injustice",
      "hw": "نا انصافی",
      "s": "« » To commit such an injustice wherein the right of another is also violated, and the one whose right is suppressed also feels burdened (1 verse: 4:3)",
      "d": "« » means to commit injustice. To deviate from the straight path (manjad). And « » is used for every such thing or action that burdens a person and causes them to be crushed under its weight. So, its meaning is to wrongfully take more than one's rightful share, i.e., to commit injustice by taking more than one's due right (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا فَوَاحِدَۃً اَوۡ مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ ؕ ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی اَلَّا تَعُوۡلُوۡا»\nTranslation: And if you fear that you will not deal justly with the orphan girls, then marry those that please you of [other] women, one or two or three or four. But if you fear that you will not be just, then [marry only] one or those your right hands possess. That is more suitable that you may not incline [to injustice]."
    },
    {
      "id": 625,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Injustice or doing injustice",
      "hw": "نا انصافی",
      "s": "« » To commit extreme lawlessness in the determination of rights (1 verse: 53:22)",
      "d": "«ضَازَ» «ضَیْز» «قِسْمَۃٌ ضِیْزٰی»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَکُمُ الذَّکَرُ وَلَہُ الۡاُنۡثٰی ، تِلۡکَ اِذًا قِسۡمَۃٌ ضِیۡزٰی»\nTranslation: [O disbelievers], for you is the male, and for Him is the female? That is a great division indeed."
    }
  ],
  "132": [
    {
      "id": 627,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be averse (to women)",
      "hw": "بے رغبتی",
      "s": "« » means a person who is averse to women (1 verse: 3:39)",
      "d": "« » means to confine by constricting. « » means to be confined or restricted. And « » is the term for a person who remains aloof from women and does not have inclination towards them.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَنَّ اللّٰہَ یُبَشِّرُکَ بِیَحۡیٰی مُصَدِّقًۢا بِکَلِمَۃٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ وَ سَیِّدًا وَّ حَصُوۡرًا وَّ نَبِیًّا مِّنَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah gives you glad tidings of John, who will confirm a word from Allah and [be] a master of etiquette, chaste, and a prophet from among the righteous."
    }
  ],
  "133": [
    {
      "id": 631,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To feel aversion/disgust",
      "hw": "بیزار",
      "s": "« » Intense dislike and aversion towards a reprehensible (evil) act (5 verses: 4:22-35:39-40:10-40:35-61:3)",
      "d": "« » means to be intensely angry and disgusted upon committing a vile act. And it is the next degree after « » (f.l. 166).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَنۡکِحُوۡا مَا نَکَحَ اٰبَآؤُکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ اِلَّا مَا قَدۡ سَلَفَ ؕ اِنَّہٗ کَانَ فَاحِشَۃً وَّ مَقۡتًا ؕ وَسَآءَ سَبِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And do not marry those [women] whom your fathers married, except what has already occurred. Indeed, it was an immorality and hateful, and how evil was the practice."
    }
  ],
  "134": [
    {
      "id": 632,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Indeed, Verily",
      "hw": "بیشک",
      "s": "«اِنَّ ، اَنَّ» «اِنّ» «اَنَّ»",
      "d": "«اِنَّ ، اَنَّ» «اِنّ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ قَدِیۡرٌ »\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is over all things competent.\nBut « » comes in the middle.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَعۡلَمُ  اَنَّ اللّٰہَ  عَلٰی کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ قَدِیۡرٌ»\nTranslation: I know that Allah is over all things competent.\nIt is necessary to remember that after « » and its derivatives, « » will also come in the middle of the speech.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ اِنَّہٗ یَقُوۡلُ اِنَّہَا بَقَرَۃٌ»\nTranslation: He (Moses) said, 'Indeed, he says, 'It is a cow.''\nGrammatically, after « » and « », « » should come in the middle of the speech (as in the example above). However, there is an instance in the Quran where « » is used after « » and « » as well.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«وَاللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ  اِنَّکَ لَرَسُوۡلُہٗ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ یَشۡہَدُ اِنَّ الۡمُنٰفِقِیۡنَ لَکٰذِبُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And Allah knows that you are His Messenger, and Allah bears witness that the hypocrites are liars."
    },
    {
      "id": 633,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Indeed, Verily",
      "hw": "بیشک",
      "s": "« » In Arabic grammar, this word is used for additional emphasis and affirmation (5 verses: 11:22-16:23-16:62-16:109-40:43)",
      "d": "There is scholarly disagreement regarding the meaning of « ». Most translators write its meaning as 'indeed' or 'verily'. Al-Munjid writes its meaning as 'By Allah's oath'. This word appears three times in the Quran, and all three times it comes before « » (11/22, 16/23, 16/109), which means it comes for additional affirmation. However, if we take Al-Munjid's meaning of 'By Allah's oath', it is also correct and adds further emphasis.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا جَرَمَ اَنَّہُمۡ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ ہُمُ الۡاَخۡسَرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Indeed, those will be the greatest losers in the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 634,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Indeed, Verily",
      "hw": "بیشک",
      "s": "« » When it enters upon a past tense verb, it gives the meaning of affirmation and also brings it close to the present tense. That is, it changes the past tense verb to the recent past (212 verses: 2:60-2:75-2:108-2:118-2:134-2:137-2:141-2:144-2:231-2:237-2:246-2:247-2:256-2:269-3:13-3:20-3:40-3:49-3:101-3:118-3:137-3:140-3:143-3:144-3:154-3:165-3:173-3:183-3:184-3:185-3:192-4:21-4:22-4:23-4:48-4:54-4:60-4:72-4:80-4:100-4:112-4:116-4:119-4:136-4:140-4:153-4:161-4:164-4:167-4:170-4:174-5:5-5:12-5:15-5:19-5:61-5:72-5:75-5:77-5:102-5:113-5:116-6:5-6:16-6:31-6:33-6:56-6:80-6:89-6:97-6:98-6:104-6:119-6:126-6:128-6:140-6:157-7:26-7:38-7:44-7:53-7:71-7:73-7:85-7:89-7:95-7:105-7:149-7:160-7:185-8:16-8:19-8:31-8:38-8:71-9:40-9:50-9:66-9:94-10:16-10:45-10:51-10:57-10:89-10:91-10:108-11:32-11:36-11:57-11:62-11:76-12:30-12:77-12:80-12:90-12:100-12:101-12:110-13:6-13:30-13:42-14:12-14:46-15:13-16:26-16:91-17:33-17:77-18:76-18:91-19:8-19:9-19:24-19:43-20:36-20:47-20:48-20:61-20:64-20:75-20:80-20:81-20:85-20:99-20:111-20:125-21:97-22:42-23:1-23:66-24:41-24:63-24:64-25:4-25:19-25:77-26:6-28:78-29:18-29:38-31:22-33:18-33:36-33:50-33:58-33:71-34:53-35:4-35:25-37:105-39:50-39:59-40:9-40:28-40:48-40:85-41:25-41:43-43:63-44:13-46:17-46:18-46:21-47:18-48:21-48:23-50:4-50:28-54:12-57:8-57:17-58:1-58:5-60:1-60:4-60:5-60:13-65:1-65:3-65:10-65:11-65:12-66:2-66:4-67:9-68:43-71:14-71:24-72:28-87:14-91:9-91:10)",
      "d": "« » When it enters upon a past tense verb, it gives the meaning of affirmation and also brings it close to the present tense. That is, it changes the past tense verb to the recent past.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَدۡ سَمِعَ اللّٰہُ قَوۡلَ الَّتِیۡ»\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah has heard the statement of the woman..."
    }
  ],
  "135": [
    {
      "id": 635,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To be restless / agitated",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "« » The heart being empty of patience and composure (1 verse: 28:10)",
      "d": "«فَرَغَ» «شَغَلَ» «قَلْبُ فَارِغٌ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاَصۡبَحَ فُؤَادُ اُمِّ مُوۡسٰی فٰرِغًا ؕ اِنۡ کَادَتۡ لَتُبۡدِیۡ بِہٖ لَوۡلَاۤ اَنۡ رَّبَطۡنَا عَلٰی قَلۡبِہَا»\nTranslation: And the heart of the mother of Moses became empty [of patience]. She would have disclosed [the matter] had We not bound her heart [with conviction]."
    },
    {
      "id": 636,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«jaz'a» to become impatient and start wailing from the tongue (1 verse: 14:21)",
      "d": "«jaz'a» to become impatient and start wailing from the tongue. And its opposite is «sabara» (to be patient). This word is used when a person, instead of being patient upon pain or calamity, starts expressing grief and sorrow verbally (Munjid).\n«سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡنَاۤ اَجَزِعۡنَاۤ اَمۡ صَبَرۡنَا مَا لَنَا مِنۡ مَّحِیۡصٍ»\nTranslation: It is equal for us whether we show restlessness or patience; there is no escape for us. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 638,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«karuba» such restlessness that also includes an element of grief (4 verses: 6:64-21:76-37:36-37:115)",
      "d": "«karuba» such restlessness that includes grief (F. L. 170) restlessness, anxiety, and agitation.\n«وَنُوۡحًا اِذۡ نَادٰی مِنۡ قَبۡلُ فَاسۡتَجَبۡنَا لَہٗ فَنَجَّیۡنٰہُ وَاَہۡلَہٗ مِنَ الۡکَرۡبِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: And (remember) Noah when he called Us before, so We responded to him and saved him and his companions from the great distress."
    },
    {
      "id": 639,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«hal'a» the extreme state of impatience (1 verse: 70:19)",
      "d": "«hal'a» the extreme state of impatience, and according to the scholar of language, it is the extreme degree of «jaz'a» (F L 48) to be without courage and impatient.\n«اِنَّ الۡاِنۡسَانَ خُلِقَ ہَلُوۡعًا اِذَا مَسَّہُ الشَّرُّ جَزُوۡعًا»\nTranslation: Indeed, man is created weak. When evil touches him, he becomes despairing."
    },
    {
      "id": 640,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«iṭṭar ra» to be restless for the fulfillment of a necessary need (8 verses: 2:126-2:173-5:3-6:119-6:145-16:115-27:62-31:24)",
      "d": "«ḍar ra» and «ḍur ra» mean to cause trouble to someone, to inflict loss. And «aḍarra fulanan 'ala al-amri» means to force someone into something. And «iṭṭar ra» means to force someone, to make needy (Munjid). Thus, «iṭṭarar» is such restlessness that is connected to some need of a person.\n«فَمَنِ اضۡطُرَّ غَیۡرَ بَاغٍ وَّلَا عَادٍ فَلَاۤ اِثۡمَ عَلَیۡہِ»\nTranslation: Then whoever is forced, without being rebellious or transgressing, there is no sin upon him."
    },
    {
      "id": 641,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Restlessness; Anxiety",
      "hw": "گھبرانا",
      "s": "«istafazza» to cause someone to be in a state of agitation (3 verses: 17:64-17:76-17:103)",
      "d": "«fazza» means to deprive someone of their senses, to cause someone to be in agitation and then remove them. And «istafazza» means to make someone restless and anxious, (Mufradat) and also comes in the meaning of considering someone humiliated.\n«وَاسۡتَفۡزِزۡ مَنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ مِنۡہُمۡ بِصَوۡتِکَ»\nTranslation: And incite whoever you can among them with your voice."
    }
  ],
  "136": [
    {
      "id": 642,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idleness",
      "hw": "بےکار",
      "s": "«faragha» the intermediate pause after finishing one task and before starting another (2 verses: 55:31-94:7)",
      "d": "«faragha» to be free from a task, and its opposite is «shaghil» (Mufradat) meaning a person being free after completing a task.\n«فَاِذَا فَرَغۡتَ فَانۡصَبۡ وَاِلٰی رَبِّکَ فَارۡغَبۡ»\nTranslation: So when you have free time, strive (in worship) and turn to your Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 643,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Idleness",
      "hw": "بےکار",
      "s": "«'at ala» idleness that is not within one's control or not by one's choice (2 verses: 22:45-81:4)",
      "d": "«'at ala» means a laborer being idle or a woman being without jewelry (Mufradat). And «'at tala» means to leave someone idle.\n«وَاِذَا الۡعِشَارُعُطِّلَتۡ»\nTranslation: And when the she-camels are left untended."
    }
  ],
  "137": [
    {
      "id": 644,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Deprived; Unfortunate",
      "hw": "بے نصیب",
      "s": "«mahrum» is used for one who is economically deprived or unfortunate. And it is used in meanings of being forbidden, prohibited, denied, prevented, haram, forbidden (4 verses: 51:19-56:67-68:27-70:25)",
      "d": "«mahrum» is used for one who is unfortunate in terms of economy. And haram is that from which one is prohibited. Then this prohibition sometimes is enticing (to attract or make obedient), sometimes coercive, and sometimes Shariah. And mahrum is the person from whom abundance of sustenance and prosperity has been withheld (Mufradat). The word mahrum appears in the Quran probably three times, and in every context it means the destitute.\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡۤ اَمۡوَالِہِمۡ حَقٌّ مَّعۡلُوۡمٌ . لِّلسَّآئِلِ وَالۡمَحۡرُوۡمِ»\nTranslation: And in their wealth is a known share for the asker and the deprived."
    },
    {
      "id": 645,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Deprived; Unfortunate",
      "hw": "بے نصیب",
      "s": "«shaqiyyan» is used for an unfortunate and ill-fated person (9 verses: 11:105-11:106-19:4-19:32-19:48-23:106-87:11-91:12-92:15)",
      "d": "The opposite of «shaqi» is «sa'id». And «sa'id» is the person who is naturally fortunate. Similarly, «shaqi» is the person who is naturally deprived of good fortune.\n«وَّلَمۡ اَکُنۡۢ بِدُعَآئِکَ رَبِّ شَقِیًّا»\nTranslation: (Prophet Zakariya said) And O my Lord, I have never been deprived in my supplication to You."
    }
  ],
  "138": [
    {
      "id": 646,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Independent; Self-sufficient",
      "hw": "بے نیاز",
      "s": "«ghani» the essence that has no need for anyone else (35 verses: 2:263-2:267-2:273-3:97-3:181-4:6-4:130-4:131-4:135-6:133-9:28-9:74-9:93-10:68-14:8-22:64-24:32-24:33-27:40-29:6-31:12-31:26-35:15-39:7-47:38-53:48-57:24-59:7-60:6-64:6-80:5-80:37-92:8-93:8-96:7)",
      "d": "«ghani» the essence that has no need for anyone else. And its opposite is faqir, meaning needy. And the word «ghani» often comes in the meaning of being independent of wealth and riches, and «ghani» is also used for a wealthy person, and its plural is «aghniya'». Meaning, at least wealthy enough that in terms of livelihood, he has no need for others (Mufradat, Munjid).\n«یَحۡسَبُہُمُ الۡجَاہِلُ اَغۡنِیَآءَ مِنَ التَّعَفُّفِ»\nTranslation: The ignorant person considers them rich due to their not asking."
    },
    {
      "id": 647,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Independent",
      "hw": "بے نیاز",
      "s": "« » refers to a being that is not in need of anyone, but all others are in need of it. (1 verse: 112:2)",
      "d": "In « », there are two fundamental aspects: (1) something being solid and strong, (2) people turning towards it from all directions (m. l. manjad). That is, a being that is not dependent on anyone, but all others are dependent on it.\nThe difference between « » and « » is that « » relates more to financial matters, while « » is independent in all aspects and others are dependent on it.\n«قُلۡ ہُوَاللّٰہُ اَحَدٌ اَللّٰہُ الصَّمَدُ»\nTranslation: Say, 'He is Allah, the One. Allah, the Independent.'"
    }
  ],
  "139": [
    {
      "id": 648,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Futile Speech",
      "hw": "بے ہودہ کلام",
      "s": "« » means idle talk, nonsense, and thoughtless noise. (11 verses: 2:225-5:89-19:62-23:3-25:72-28:55-41:26-52:23-56:25-78:35-88:11)",
      "d": "«لَغٰی ، یَلْغُوا» «لَغَی الطَیرُبَا صْواتِھا» «لَاغِیْۃ»\n«لَا یَسۡمَعُوۡنَ فِیۡہَا لَغۡوًا اِلَّا سَلٰمًا»\nTranslation: They will not hear any idle talk therein except peace.\n«لَّا تَسۡمَعُ فِیۡہَا لَاغِیَۃً»\nTranslation: They will not hear any nonsense therein. (Osmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 650,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Futile Speech",
      "hw": "بے ہودہ کلام",
      "s": "« » means stammering, nonsensical talk that a drunk person engages in. (2 verses: 37:47-56:19)",
      "d": "«نَزَفَ» «نَزِفَ دَمُہٗ» «نَزِیْف» «نَزَفَ الْمَاء» «نَزَفَ»\n«بَیۡضَآءَ لَذَّۃٍ لِّلشّٰرِبِیۡنَ ، لَا فِیۡہَا غَوۡلٌ وَّلَا ہُمۡ عَنۡہَا یُنۡزَفُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: White, delicious for the drinkers, in which there is no headache, nor are they made senseless by it."
    }
  ],
  "140": [
    {
      "id": 651,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "« » means to be stunned due to a heavenly event. (3 verses: 7:143-39:68-52:45)",
      "d": "« » means to be stunned due to terror and panic (f. l 130). And « » refers to a falling lightning or that terrifying explosion related to celestial bodies (see lightning for details).\n«فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ دَکًّا وَّخَرَّ مُوۡسٰی صَعِقًا»\nTranslation: When his Lord manifested Himself to the mountain, He made it [appear as] a dust mote, and Moses fell stunned."
    },
    {
      "id": 652,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Intoxicated",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "« » generally refers to intoxication from alcohol or intoxicants. (4 verses: 15:15-15:72-16:67-50:19)",
      "d": "« » generally refers to intoxication from alcohol or intoxicants. And « » is the state when a person loses their intellect and senses (muf).\n«وَجَآءَتۡ سَکۡرَۃُ الۡمَوۡتِ بِالۡحَقِّ»\nTranslation: And the intoxication of death will come with truth.\n«وَمِنۡ ثَمَرٰتِ النَّخِیۡلِ وَالۡاَعۡنَابِ تَتَّخِذُوۡنَ مِنۡہُ سَکَرًا وَّرِزۡقًا حَسَنًا»\nTranslation: And from the fruits of the date-palm and grapes, you take intoxicants and good provision.\nAnd « » means to become intoxicated from wine, and the adjective is 'skran'. The feminine form is « » and its plural is « » (manjad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 653,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "« » means to be stunned due to calamities and hardships. (4 verses: 6:93-23:54-23:63-51:11)",
      "d": "«غَمِرَ» «غَمَرَاتُ الْمَوْت» «غَمَرَۃٌ» «غَمِرَ»\n«وَلَوۡ تَرٰۤی اِذِ الظّٰلِمُوۡنَ فِیۡ غَمَرٰتِ الۡمَوۡتِ وَالۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ بَاسِطُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And if you could see when the wrongdoers are in the agonies of death and the angels are extending their hands.\n«بَلۡ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ فِیۡ غَمۡرَۃٍ مِّنۡ ہٰذَا»\nTranslation: No! Their hearts are in a stupor from this. (Osmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 654,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "« » means to fall to the ground due to fainting. (1 verse: 69:7)",
      "d": "« » means to die or refers to the well-known disease 'mother of children' where a person faints and falls to the ground. And « » means to fall to the ground due to restlessness and panic (f. l 130).\n«فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی»\nTranslation: Then you will see the people prostrated therein. (Osmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 655,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "بیہوش",
      "s": "« » means to be stunned due to terror, illness, or any other reason. (23 verses: 2:7-3:154-7:54-7:189-8:11-10:27-11:5-13:3-14:50-20:78-24:40-29:55-31:32-33:19-36:9-44:11-45:23-47:20-53:16-53:54-71:7-91:4-92:1)",
      "d": "« » means to cover something and veil it. When a person's intellect is veiled and their senses don't function, it's called 'ghashy'. The cause could be terror, fear, or anything else. And « » is the person who has been stunned.\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ الۡخَوۡفُ رَاَیۡتَہُمۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ اِلَیۡکَ تَدُوۡرُ اَعۡیُنُہُمۡ کَالَّذِیۡ یُغۡشٰی عَلَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡمَوۡتِ»\nTranslation: Then when fear comes, you will see them looking at you, their eyes revolving like those who are overwhelmed by the pangs of death."
    }
  ],
  "141": [
    {
      "id": 656,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Near",
      "hw": "پاس",
      "s": "« » means near, whether in terms of place or time. (185 verses: 2:54-2:62-2:76-2:79-2:80-2:89-2:94-2:101-2:103-2:109-2:110-2:112-2:140-2:191-2:198-2:217-2:255-2:262-2:274-2:277-2:282-3:7-3:14-3:15-3:19-3:37-3:59-3:73-3:78-3:126-3:156-3:163-3:165-3:169-3:195-3:198-3:199-4:78-4:81-4:82-4:94-4:134-4:139-5:43-5:52-5:60-6:2-6:50-6:57-6:58-6:59-6:109-6:124-6:127-6:148-7:29-7:31-7:131-7:134-7:157-7:187-7:206-8:4-8:10-8:22-8:28-8:32-8:35-8:55-9:7-9:19-9:20-9:22-9:36-9:52-9:99-10:2-10:18-10:68-10:76-11:28-11:31-11:83-12:17-12:42-12:60-12:79-13:8-13:39-13:43-14:37-14:46-15:21-16:95-16:96-17:23-17:38-18:46-18:65-18:86-19:55-19:76-19:78-19:87-20:52-21:19-21:84-22:30-22:47-23:117-24:13-24:15-24:39-24:61-27:40-27:47-28:27-28:37-28:48-28:49-28:60-28:78-29:17-29:50-30:39-31:34-32:12-33:5-33:53-33:63-33:69-34:23-34:31-34:37-35:39-37:48-37:168-38:9-38:25-38:40-38:47-38:52-39:31-39:34-40:25-40:35-40:83-41:38-41:50-41:52-42:16-42:22-42:36-43:35-43:49-43:85-44:5-46:10-46:23-47:16-48:5-49:3-49:13-50:4-51:34-52:37-52:41-53:14-53:15-53:35-54:35-54:55-57:19-61:3-62:11-63:7-64:15-66:11-67:26-68:34-68:47-73:20-81:20-92:19-98:8)",
      "d": "«عِنْد» «عِنْدَ الْمَکَان» «عِنْدَ الْلَیْل»\n«مَاعِنۡدَکُمۡ یَنۡفَدُ وَمَا عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ بَاقٍ»\nTranslation: Whatever is with you will perish, and whatever is with Allah will remain.\nSometimes « » comes before « » for emphasis, meaning 'from near' or 'from the side of'.\n«قُلۡتُمۡ اَنّٰی ہٰذَا ؕ قُلۡ ہُوَ مِنۡ عِنۡدِ اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: You said, 'Whence is this?' Say, 'It is from yourselves.'\nWhen « » is included, it adds more emphasis."
    },
    {
      "id": 658,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Near",
      "hw": "پاس",
      "s": "« » means to meet someone, to face, to encounter by chance. (4 verses: 7:47-10:15-21:103-28:22)",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ یَلْقِیْ لِقَاءً» «تِلْقَاء ، لِقَاء» «جَلَسَ تِلْقَاءِیْ»\n«وَلَمَّا تَوَجَّہَ تِلۡقَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ»\nTranslation: And when he turned his face towards Madyan.\n«تِلْقَاءَ نَفْس» «فَعَلَ الْاَمْر مَنْ تلْقاءِ نَفْسِہٖ»\n«قُلۡ مَا یَکُوۡنُ لِیۡۤ اَنۡ اُبَدِّلَہٗ مِنۡ تِلۡقَآیِٔ  نَفۡسِیۡ»\nTranslation: Say, 'It is not for me to alter it from my own inclination.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 659,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Around",
      "hw": "پاس",
      "s": "« » means to be around something or in its vicinity (16 verses: 2:17-3:159-6:92-8:24-9:101-9:120-17:1-19:68-26:25-26:34-27:8-29:67-39:75-40:7-42:7-46:27)",
      "d": "«حَالَ» «حَوْلَ الشَّیْء»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَضَآءَتۡ مَا حَوۡلَہٗ ذَہَبَ اللّٰہُ بِنُوۡرِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: 'Then when the fire illuminated what was around it, Allah took away their light.'"
    }
  ],
  "142": [
    {
      "id": 660,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » is the Being who is free from all kinds of flaws, deficiencies, and shortcomings, and it is only Allah (41 verses: 2:32-2:116-3:191-4:171-5:116-6:100-7:143-9:31-10:10-10:18-10:68-12:108-16:1-16:57-17:1-17:43-17:93-17:108-19:35-21:22-21:26-21:87-23:91-24:16-25:18-27:8-28:68-30:17-30:40-34:41-36:36-36:83-37:159-37:180-39:4-39:67-43:13-43:82-52:43-59:23-68:29)",
      "d": "According to Ibn Faris, the word « » has two basic meanings: (1) a form of worship, (2) a form of running. (m. l)\n«سَبَحَ» «سَبَّاح» «فَرَسٌ سَبُوْحٌ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَہُوَالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الَّیۡلَ وَالنَّہَارَ وَالشَّمۡسَ وَالۡقَمَرَ ؕ کُلٌّ فِیۡ فَلَکٍ یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: 'And He it is Who created the night and the day, the sun and the moon. Each one is floating in an orbit.'\nAt another place, the divine command says:\n«وَّالسّٰبِحٰتِ سَبۡحًا»\nTranslation: 'And by the angels who float (in space).'\nThen this word began to be used for doing something with speed and haste.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنَّ لَکَ فِی النَّہَارِ سَبۡحًا طَوِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: 'Indeed, you have in the day a prolonged occupation.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 661,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » refers to a Being who is free from all imperfections (41 verses: 2:32-2:116-3:191-4:171-5:116-6:100-7:143-9:31-10:10-10:18-10:68-12:108-16:1-16:57-17:1-17:43-17:93-17:108-19:35-21:22-21:26-21:87-23:91-24:16-25:18-27:8-28:68-30:17-30:40-34:41-36:36-36:83-37:159-37:180-39:4-39:67-43:13-43:82-52:43-59:23-68:29)",
      "d": "« » is derived from « ». Just as « » gives « », millions and billions of planets are revolving at great speed in space. In them, there is no vibration, oscillation, collision, or impact. This clearly indicates that the Administrator who controls them with such firm determination and management can only be an existence completely free from any flaw or deficiency. And this is the meaning of « ». Furthermore, it is necessary that such a Managing Being, who runs the universe with such firm management, could, if He willed, introduce disruption and disorder into that system. Therefore, « » means an existence that is free from flaws and deficiencies, and is also All-Powerful without any partner, and holds complete control over all things in the universe.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَقَالُوااتَّخَذَ اللّٰہُ وَلَدًا ۙ سُبۡحٰنَہٗ  ؕ بَلۡ لَّہٗ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالۡاَرۡضِ  ؕ کُلٌّ لَّہٗ قٰنِتُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: \"And these people say, 'Allah has taken a son.' Exalted is He! Rather, to Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth, and all are devoutly obedient to Him.\"\nAnd the coordinated and orderly motion of all things in the universe is itself testifying that the Managing Being who administers it is a Pure Essence, free from all kinds of flaws, deficiencies, and polytheism.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سَبَّحَ لِلّٰہِ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَمَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ ۚ وَہُوَالۡعَزِیۡزُالۡحَکِیۡمُ»\nTranslation: \"Whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth exalts Allah, and He is the Exalted in Might, the Wise.\"\nThen, another aspect of this coordinated and orderly operation of the universe and all its contents is that its system, regulation, administration, and regularity, where even a moment's precedence is impossible, has no oscillation, collision, or impact. Seeing all these things, man drowns in an ocean of wonder, and his tongue involuntarily begins to glorify and praise the Administrator of the universe. Hence, the word « » is also used at a time when the artistry and creation of the universe's Creator plunge man into an ocean of wonder. And generally, \"Glory be to Your power\" is said on such occasions.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا مِّنَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ اِلَی الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡاَقۡصَا»\nTranslation: \"Exalted is He who took His Servant by night from al-Masjid al-Haram to al-Masjid al-Aqsa...\"\nThe use of « » at this point is evidence that this journey was spiritual, not physical."
    },
    {
      "id": 662,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » is the name of Allah, the Exalted. A being or station that is pure and blessed from shirk and similar evils (10 verses: 2:30-2:87-2:253-5:21-5:110-16:102-20:12-59:23-62:1-79:16)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is to be pure and clean. (muf) And according to the author of al-Munjid, it means to be pure and blessed.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«قُلۡ نَزَّلَہٗ رُوۡحُ الۡقُدُسِ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ بِالۡحَقِّ»\nTranslation: 'Say, \"The Pure Spirit has brought it down from your Lord in truth.\"'\nSo here, by Ruh al-Quds is meant that Jibril (peace be upon him) kept Allah's word pure and free from all kinds of impurity and filth, and delivered it to the prophets. That is why he is also called Ruh al-Amin at another place. And by Ard al-Muqaddasah is meant that pure and blessed land which became blessed due to the birth and burial of prophets and remained pure from the filth of polytheism due to their propagation.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یٰقَوۡمِ ادۡخُلُوا الۡاَرۡضَ الۡمُقَدَّسَۃَ الَّتِیۡ کَتَبَ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: 'O my people, enter the holy land which Allah has assigned to you.'\nAnd « » is the name of Allah, the Exalted, meaning the entity that is pure from shirk and all evil, and blessed. (manjad)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یُسَبِّحُ لِلّٰہِ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ الۡمَلِکِ الۡقُدُّوۡسِ الۡعَزِیۡزِالۡحَکِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: 'Whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth glorifies Allah, the King, the Pure, the Exalted in Might, the Wise.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 663,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » means the purity of the soul from evil traits and its refinement (26 verses: 2:129-2:151-2:174-2:232-3:77-3:164-4:49-9:103-18:19-18:74-18:81-19:13-19:19-20:76-24:21-24:28-24:30-35:18-53:32-62:2-79:18-80:3-80:7-87:14-91:9-92:18)",
      "d": "«زَکٰی ، زُكُوًّا» «زَکّٰی» «زَکّٰی نَفْسَہٗ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَا تُزَکُّوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ ؕ ہُوَاَعۡلَمُ بِمَنِ اتَّقٰی»\nTranslation: \"So do not claim purity for yourselves. He is most knowing of who fears Him.\" (Jalandhari)\nTranslation: \"So do not boast of your virtues; He knows best who it is that guards against evil.\" (Osmani)\n«تَزْکِیَہ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَدۡ اَفۡلَحَ مَنۡ زَکّٰىہَا وَقَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ دَسّٰىہَا»\nTranslation: \"He who purifies it (the soul) has succeeded, and he who corrupts it has failed.\"\nAnd a pure soul is one that is innocent and free from all accusations.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ اَقَتَلۡتَ نَفۡسًا زَکِیَّۃًۢ بِغَیۡرِ نَفۡسٍ ؕ لَقَدۡ جِئۡتَ شَیۡئًا نُّکۡرًا»\nTranslation: \"[Moses] said, 'You have killed a pure soul for no reason. You have certainly done a terrible thing.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 664,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » means to be clean and pure from dirt, filth, and impurity (26 verses: 2:25-2:125-2:222-2:232-3:15-3:42-3:55-4:57-5:6-5:41-7:82-8:11-9:103-9:108-11:78-22:26-25:48-27:56-33:33-33:53-56:79-58:12-74:4-76:21-80:14-98:2)",
      "d": "« » is that which is clean and pure from dirt, filth, and impurity. According to Imam Raghib, it means being free from perceptible filth. And the opposite of « » is « », meaning dirt, filth, etc. (M, L).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَسَقٰہُمۡ رَبُّہُمۡ شَرَابًا طَہُوۡرًا»\nTranslation: \"And their Lord will give them a drink of pure wine.\"\nSimilarly, a woman becoming pure from menstruation and postpartum bleeding is also  .\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاعۡتَزِلُوا النِّسَآءَ فِی الۡمَحِیۡضِ ۙ وَلَا تَقۡرَبُوۡہُنَّ حَتّٰی یَطۡہُرۡنَ»\nTranslation: \"So keep away from women during menstruation and do not approach them until they are pure.\"\nAnd « » (Form IV) is used for purification from both external and internal impurities.\nFor example, for removing external impurities, the divine command is:\n«وَرَبَّکَ فَکَبِّرۡ ۪وَثِیَابَکَ فَطَہِّرۡ»\nTranslation: \"And glorify your Lord and purify your clothing.\"\nAnd for cleansing internal evils, the divine command is:\n«اِنَّمَا یُرِیۡدُ اللّٰہُ لِیُذۡہِبَ عَنۡکُمُ الرِّجۡسَ اَہۡلَ الۡبَیۡتِ وَیُطَہِّرَکُمۡ تَطۡہِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: \"Allah intends only to remove from you, O [people of the] household [of the Prophet], any impurity and to purify you with [ thorough] purification.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 665,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Pure",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » means outwardly pure, lawful, and pleasant (43 verses: 2:57-2:168-2:172-2:267-3:38-3:179-4:2-4:3-4:43-4:160-5:4-5:5-5:6-5:87-5:88-5:100-7:32-7:58-7:157-7:160-8:26-8:37-8:69-9:72-10:22-10:93-14:24-16:32-16:72-16:97-16:114-17:70-20:81-22:24-23:51-24:26-24:61-34:15-35:10-40:64-45:16-46:20-61:12)",
      "d": "« » means for something to be pleasing to the heart, to be of good taste.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَانۡکِحُوۡا مَا طَابَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ»\nTranslation: 'So marry those that please you among women.' (Osmani)\nAnd « » means fragrance. (manjad) And « » means heart's pleasure and satisfaction. (m. q) And « » is everything that is pleasant, pure, and lawful. (muf) And its opposite is « ».\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا کُلُوۡا مِنۡ طَیِّبٰتِ مَا رَزَقۡنٰکُمۡ»\nTranslation: 'O you who have believed, eat from the good things which We have provided for you.'\n«بَلَدَۃً طَٰیِّبَۃً»"
    },
    {
      "id": 666,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To purify",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » means to purify something from external and internal impurities and weaknesses (2 verses: 3:141-3:154)",
      "d": "«مَحَصَ» «مَحَصَ الذَّھَبَ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَلِیُمَحِّصَ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَیَمۡحَقَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: 'And that Allah may purify the believers [through trials] and destroy the disbelievers.'\nAt this place, Allah is mentioning the practical weaknesses of the Muslims and guiding them to improvement. So « » here means to purify a person from weaknesses and demands in practical life."
    },
    {
      "id": 667,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To purify",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » means to purify the self from bad ethics (26 verses: 2:129-2:151-2:174-2:232-3:77-3:164-4:49-9:103-18:19-18:74-18:81-19:13-19:19-20:76-24:21-24:28-24:30-35:18-53:32-62:2-79:18-80:3-80:7-87:14-91:9-92:18)",
      "d": "« » means to purify the self from spiritual filth, diseases, and bad ethics.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«قَدْ اَفْلَحَ مَنْ تَزَكّٰى»\nTranslation: 'Indeed, he who purifies himself has succeeded.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 668,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To purify",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » means to be free from both external and internal impurities, and also to purify from shirk and evil suggestions (26 verses: 2:25-2:125-2:222-2:232-3:15-3:42-3:55-4:57-5:6-5:41-7:82-8:11-9:103-9:108-11:78-22:26-25:48-27:56-33:33-33:53-56:79-58:12-74:4-76:21-80:14-98:2)",
      "d": "« » means to remove external impurities. And also to purify the heart from shirk and satanic suggestions. Details have passed in « »."
    },
    {
      "id": 669,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to purify",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » means for something to be pure and free from all kinds of admixture (1 verse: 47:15)",
      "d": "«صَفَّا» «صَفّٰی» «وَاَنۡہٰرٌ مِّنۡ عَسَلٍ مُّصَفًّی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 670,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Clear",
      "hw": "پاک",
      "s": "« » means to clear someone from a slander or defect (1 verse: 33:69)",
      "d": "« » means to recover from an illness. « » means to make healthy. And « » means to clear someone from a slander or defect, to declare innocent (i.e., to acquit of a crime). (Munajid, Mufradat)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَبَرَّاَہُ اللّٰہُ مِمَّا قَالُوۡا ؕ وَکَانَ عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ وَجِیۡہًا»\nTranslation: \"So Allah cleared him of the charge they had brought against him, and he was in the sight of Allah, distinguished.\""
    }
  ],
  "143": [
    {
      "id": 671,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Find",
      "hw": "پانا",
      "s": "« » means to find or see something that exists (35 verses: 3:37-4:64-4:82-4:89-5:104-7:28-7:44-7:102-9:5-10:78-12:65-12:75-12:79-18:49-18:65-18:77-18:86-18:90-18:93-21:53-24:39-26:74-27:23-27:24-28:15-28:23-31:21-38:44-43:22-43:23-43:24-51:36-72:8-93:7-93:8)",
      "d": "« » is a general term for finding or seeing something that exists and can be used everywhere. (Mufradat)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَا دَخَلَ عَلَیۡہَا زَکَرِیَّا الۡمِحۡرَابَ ۙ وَجَدَ عِنۡدَہَا رِزۡقًا»\nTranslation: \"Whenever Zakariya entered upon her in the prayer chamber, he found with her provision.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 672,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Skillfully Acquire",
      "hw": "پانا",
      "s": "« » means to use skill and expertise in obtaining something. To capture desired individuals during war (6 verses: 2:191-3:112-4:91-8:57-33:61-60:2)",
      "d": "« » means to use prudence and skill in obtaining something or doing a task. (Mufradat) And « » refers to an expert and master in war and fighting. (M, R) « » means wise (prudent) and alert. And « » means wisdom (prudence) and skill. And « » means to capture someone, to get good information about them, and to achieve victory over them. (M, R)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاقۡتُلُوۡہُمۡ حَیۡثُ ثَقِفۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ وَاَخۡرِجُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ حَیۡثُ اَخۡرَجُوۡکُمۡ»\nTranslation: \"And kill them wherever you overtake them and expel them from wherever they have expelled you.\"\nAt another place, for exactly the same situation, the word « » was used instead of « », which indicates the generality of « ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَخُذُوۡہُمۡ وَ اقۡتُلُوۡہُمۡ حَیۡثُ وَجَدۡتُّمُوۡہُمۡ»\nTranslation: \"Then seize them and kill them wherever you find them.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 673,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Encounter",
      "hw": "پانا",
      "s": "« » means to find something by chance. To find something present when a veil is lifted. To find something spontaneously (3 verses: 2:170-12:25-37:69)",
      "d": "« » means for a thing's veil to be removed from before it and for it to become apparent. (M, L) And « » means for something to come into one's knowledge spontaneously or for something to appear.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ وَّ اَلۡفَیَا سَیِّدَہَا لَدَا الۡبَابِ»\nTranslation: \"And they both raced to the door, and she tore his shirt from the back, and they found her husband at the door.\"\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«قَالُوۡا بَلۡ نَتَّبِعُ مَاۤ اَلۡفَیۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ اٰبَآءَنَا»\nTranslation: \"They say, 'Rather, we will follow that on which we found our fathers.'\"\nIn this verse, « » is used in the sense that the thing was inherited by them from generation to generation. At another place, for exactly the same situation, the word « » was used instead of « », which indicates the generality of « ».\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«قَالُوۡا حَسۡبُنَا مَا وَجَدۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ اٰبَآءَنَا»\nTranslation: \"They say, 'What we found our fathers upon is enough for us.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 674,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Reach the End",
      "hw": "پانا",
      "s": "« » means to reach the extremity of something and thus obtain it (8 verses: 4:78-4:100-4:145-6:103-10:90-20:77-26:61-36:40)",
      "d": "«دَرَکَ» «دَرَجَ» «دَرَجَ» «دَرَجَۃً» «دَرَکَ» «دَرَجَاتُ الْجَنَّۃ» «دَرَکَاتُ النَّار»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الۡمُنٰفِقِیۡنَ فِی الدَّرۡکِ الۡاَسۡفَلِ مِنَ النَّارِ»\nTranslation: \"Indeed, the hypocrites will be in the lowest depths of the Fire.\"\n«اَدْرَکَ» «اَدْرَکَ الثَّمَرُ» «اَدْرَکَ الْوَلَد»\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«لَا تُدۡرِکُہُ الۡاَبۡصَارُ وَہُوَ یُدۡرِکُ الۡاَبۡصَارَ»\nTranslation: \"Vision perceives Him not, but He perceives [all] vision; and He is the Subtle, the Acquainted.\" (Osmani)"
    }
  ],
  "144": [
    {
      "id": 675,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its Types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » means hot water (19 verses: 6:70-10:4-22:19-26:101-37:67-38:57-40:18-40:72-41:34-44:46-44:48-47:15-55:44-56:42-56:54-56:93-69:35-70:10-78:25)",
      "d": "«حَمِیْم» «حَمّٰی» «حَمِیْم»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیْنَ کَفَرُوْا لَہُمْ شَرَابٌ مِّنْ حَمِیْمٍ»\nTranslation: \"And for those who disbelieve is a drink of scalding water.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 676,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its Types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » means cold and foul water or pus (2 verses: 38:57-78:25)",
      "d": "«غَسَّاق» «حَمِیْم» «غَسَّاق»\nExample for « »: The divine command states:\n«لَا یَذُوۡقُوۡنَ فِیۡہَا بَرۡدًا وَّلَا شَرَابًا اِلَّا حَمِیۡمًا وَّغَسَّاقًا»\nTranslation: \"They will not taste therein any coolness or drink except scalding water and pus.\" (Jalandhari)\nExample for « »: The divine command states:\n«جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ۚ فَبِئۡسَ الۡمِہَادُ ہٰذَا ۙ فَلۡیَذُوۡقُوۡہُ حَمِیۡمٌ وَّغَسَّاقٌ»\nTranslation: \"Hell, which they will [enter to] burn, and wretched is the resting place. They will have nothing therein but scalding water and pus.\" (Jalandhari)"
    },
    {
      "id": 678,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » meaning water that is underground (2 verses: 18:41-67:30)",
      "d": "« » is the water that is deep underground (F L 259). And the author of Munjid writes the meaning of « » as 'water that is absorbed into the earth'."
    },
    {
      "id": 679,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » meaning water that flows gently on the surface of the earth (4 verses: 23:50-37:45-56:18-67:30)",
      "d": "« » means water flowing with a gentle pace (Munjid) and « » is water that flows on the surface (F L 259), like a flood but not with intensity and speed, rather flowing with gentleness and ease (M. L).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَصۡبَحَ مَآؤُکُمۡ غَوۡرًا فَمَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِمَآءٍ مَّعِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: Say, 'Tell me, if your water becomes sunken, who can bring you flowing water?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 680,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » meaning cold and sweet water (2 verses: 25:53-35:12)",
      "d": "« » means sweet and pleasant water (source) cold and sweet water that is desirable to drink. (detailed)"
    },
    {
      "id": 681,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » meaning cool and sweet water when it is in large quantity (3 verses: 25:53-35:12-77:27)",
      "d": "«فُرَاتٌ» «فُرَاتَان» «فَرَتِ الْمَاءِ» «فُرَاتٌ» «عَذْبٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 682,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » salty water, sea water (2 verses: 25:53-35:12)",
      "d": "« » means brackish water, salty water, sea water, water with salt (F. L 33)."
    },
    {
      "id": 683,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water and its types!",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » bitter and salty water (3 verses: 25:53-35:12-56:70)",
      "d": "« » means water that is both salty and bitter (F L 33), intensely salty and hot, burning the chest (Maf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ مَا یَسۡتَوِی الۡبَحۡرٰنِ ٭ۖ ہٰذَا عَذۡبٌ فُرَاتٌ سَآئِغٌ  شَرَابُہٗ  وَہٰذَا مِلۡحٌ اُجَاجٌ»\nTranslation: 'And the two seas are not equal. This one is sweet, pleasant to drink, and this one is salty, bitter.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 684,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water's paths and reserves",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » meaning streams, rivulets (2 verses: 13:17-46:24)",
      "d": "It is the plural of « ». Originally, 'wadi' refers to a wide valley between mountains and the slope that is between mountains where water flows (Maf). Due to being between mountains, it is necessary for streams to flow in that valley. These are the paths of rainwater and melted glacial water flowing from the mountains. Then the word 'wadi' is sometimes used in the meaning of a wide valley and sometimes in the meaning of streams and rivulets.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ  مَآءً  فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا»\nTranslation: He sent down water from the sky, so the valleys flowed according to their capacity."
    },
    {
      "id": 685,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Paths and reserves of water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » spring, lake, etc. (21 verses: 2:60-7:160-15:45-18:86-26:57-26:134-26:147-34:12-36:34-44:25-44:52-51:15-54:12-55:50-55:66-76:6-76:18-77:41-83:28-88:5-88:12)",
      "d": "«عَیْن» «عُیُوْن» «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا بَلَغَ مَغۡرِبَ الشَّمۡسِ وَجَدَہَا تَغۡرُبُ فِیۡ عَیۡنٍ حَمِئَۃٍ» «عَیْن» «بَحْر» «عَیْن»"
    },
    {
      "id": 687,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water's paths and reserves",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » meaning a small stream (1 verse: 19:24)",
      "d": "In « », two concepts are found: (1) moving at night, (2) being small. « » means a small army and a small boat. Its plural is « ». And « » means a small army moving at night. And « » means a small flowing stream (Munjid. F L 36).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قَدۡ جَعَلَ  رَبُّکِ  تَحۡتَکِ سَرِیًّا»\nTranslation: Your Lord has made a stream flow beneath you."
    },
    {
      "id": 688,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Paths and reserves of water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » a large water reserve that flows downhill (7 verses: 7:136-20:39-20:78-20:97-28:7-28:40-51:40)",
      "d": "«یَمّ» «یَمّ» «اَنِ اقۡذِفِیۡہِ فِی التَّابُوۡتِ فَاقۡذِفِیۡہِ فِی الۡیَمِّ فَلۡیُلۡقِہِ الۡیَمُّ بِالسَّاحِلِ یَاۡخُذۡہُ عَدُوٌّ لِّیۡ وَ عَدُوٌّ لَّہٗ» «وَ قَالَتۡ لِاُخۡتِہٖ قُصِّیۡہِ ۫ فَبَصُرَتۡ بِہٖ عَنۡ جُنُبٍ  وَّ ہُمۡ لَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» «یَمّ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 689,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Paths and reserves of water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » used for sea or river (39 verses: 2:50-2:164-5:96-6:59-6:63-6:97-7:138-7:163-10:22-10:90-14:32-16:14-17:66-17:67-17:70-18:60-18:61-18:63-18:79-18:109-20:77-22:65-24:40-25:53-26:63-27:61-27:63-30:41-31:27-31:31-35:12-42:32-44:24-45:12-52:6-55:19-55:24-81:6-82:3)",
      "d": "«بَحْر» «اَبْحُرْ» «بَحْر» «بَحْر» «بُحَیِرَہ» «بَحْر» «بُحَیِرَہ» «بَحْر» «بَحْر» «وَ اِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ وَ اَغۡرَقۡنَاۤ اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» «مَرَجَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ بَیۡنَہُمَا بَرۡزَخٌ  لَّا یَبۡغِیٰنِ» «بَحْر»"
    },
    {
      "id": 690,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Asking for water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "« » meaning asking for water to drink (24 verses: 2:60-2:71-7:160-9:19-12:41-12:70-13:4-14:16-15:22-16:66-23:21-25:49-26:79-28:23-28:24-28:25-47:15-72:16-76:17-76:21-77:27-83:25-88:5-91:13)",
      "d": "«سَقٰی» «اَسْقٰی» «اِسْتَسْقٰی» «وَ اِذِ اسۡتَسۡقٰی مُوۡسٰی لِقَوۡمِہٖ فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ»"
    }
  ],
  "145": [
    {
      "id": 692,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Foot (paer)",
      "hw": "پاؤں",
      "s": "« » refers to the part from below the ankle to the toes of the foot (18 verses: 2:239-5:6-5:33-5:66-6:65-7:124-7:195-17:64-20:71-22:27-24:24-24:31-24:45-26:49-29:55-36:65-38:42-60:12)",
      "d": "«رِجْلٌ» «اَرْجُلٌ» «اُرۡکُضۡ بِرِجۡلِکَ ۚ ہٰذَا مُغۡتَسَلٌۢ بَارِدٌ وَّ شَرَابٌ» «رَجُلٌ» «رِجَالٌ» «رِجَالًا» «رُکْبَانًا» «فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ فَرِجَالًا اَوۡ رُکۡبَانًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 693,
