      "h": "To Follow / Pursue",
      "hw": "پیچھا",
      "s": "« » To follow someone and go with them (150 verses: 2:38, 2:102, 2:120, 2:143, 2:145, 2:166, 2:167, 2:168, 2:170, 2:208, 2:262, 2:263, 3:7, 3:20, 3:31, 3:53, 3:55, 3:68, 3:73, 3:95, 3:162, 3:167, 3:174, 4:27, 4:83, 4:115, 4:125, 4:135, 5:16, 5:48, 5:49, 5:77, 6:50, 6:56, 6:106, 6:116, 6:142, 6:148, 6:150, 6:153, 6:155, 7:3, 7:18, 7:90, 7:142, 7:157, 7:158, 7:175, 7:176, 7:193, 7:203, 8:64, 9:42, 9:100, 9:117, 10:15, 10:35, 10:36, 10:66, 10:89, 10:90, 10:109, 11:27, 11:59, 11:60, 11:97, 11:99, 11:116, 12:38, 12:108, 13:37, 14:21, 14:36, 14:44, 15:18, 15:42, 15:65, 16:123, 17:47, 17:63, 18:28, 18:66, 18:70, 18:85, 18:89, 18:92, 19:43, 19:59, 20:16, 20:47, 20:78, 20:90, 20:93, 20:108, 20:123, 20:134, 22:3, 23:44, 23:71, 24:21, 25:8, 26:40, 26:52, 26:60, 26:111, 26:215, 26:224, 28:35, 28:42, 28:47, 28:49, 28:50, 28:57, 29:12, 30:29, 31:15, 31:21, 33:2, 34:20, 36:11, 36:20, 36:21, 37:10, 38:26, 38:85, 39:18, 39:55, 40:7, 40:38, 40:47, 42:15, 43:61, 44:23, 45:18, 46:9, 47:3, 47:14, 47:16, 47:28, 48:15, 52:21, 53:23, 53:28, 54:3, 54:24, 57:27, 71:21, 75:18, 77:17, 79:7)",
      "d": "«اَتْبَعَ» «فَاَتۡبَعُوۡہُمۡ مُّشۡرِقِیۡنَ فَلَمَّا تَرَآءَ الۡجَمۡعٰنِ قَالَ اَصۡحٰبُ مُوۡسٰۤی اِنَّا لَمُدۡرَکُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "179": [
    {
      "id": 862,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Behind / After",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » (In terms of time) A past time, a previous era (189 verses: 2:27, 2:51, 2:52, 2:56, 2:64, 2:74, 2:75, 2:87, 2:92, 2:109, 2:120, 2:133, 2:145, 2:159, 2:164, 2:178, 2:181, 2:209, 2:211, 2:213, 2:230, 2:246, 2:253, 2:259, 3:8, 3:19, 3:61, 3:65, 3:80, 3:82, 3:86, 3:89, 3:90, 3:94, 3:100, 3:105, 3:106, 3:152, 3:154, 3:160, 3:172, 4:11, 4:12, 4:24, 4:115, 4:153, 4:163, 4:165, 5:12, 5:32, 5:39, 5:41, 5:43, 5:94, 5:106, 5:108, 5:115, 6:6, 6:54, 6:68, 6:71, 6:133, 7:56, 7:69, 7:74, 7:85, 7:89, 7:100, 7:103, 7:129, 7:148, 7:150, 7:153, 7:169, 7:173, 7:185, 8:6, 8:75, 9:12, 9:27, 9:28, 9:66, 9:74, 9:113, 9:115, 9:117, 10:3, 10:14, 10:21, 10:32, 10:74, 10:75, 11:7, 11:10, 12:9, 12:35, 12:45, 12:48, 12:49, 12:100, 13:25, 13:37, 14:9, 14:14, 16:41, 16:65, 16:70, 16:91, 16:92, 16:94, 16:106, 16:110, 16:119, 17:17, 17:104, 18:76, 19:59, 20:85, 21:11, 21:57, 21:105, 22:5, 23:15, 23:31, 23:42, 23:44, 24:5, 24:33, 24:47, 24:55, 24:58, 25:29, 26:120, 26:227, 27:11, 28:43, 28:58, 28:87, 29:63, 30:3, 30:4, 30:19, 30:24, 30:50, 30:51, 30:54, 31:27, 33:52, 33:53, 34:32, 35:2, 35:9, 35:41, 36:28, 38:35, 38:88, 39:6, 40:5, 40:31, 40:34, 41:50, 42:14, 42:16, 42:28, 42:41, 42:44, 45:5, 45:6, 45:17, 45:23, 46:30, 47:4, 47:25, 47:32, 48:24, 49:11, 53:26, 57:10, 57:17, 59:10, 61:6, 65:1, 65:7, 66:4, 68:13, 77:50, 79:30, 95:7, 98:4)",
      "d": "«بَعْدُ» «قَبْل» «ثُمَّ بَعَثۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مَوۡتِکُمۡ لَعَلَّکُمۡ تَشۡکُرُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 863,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Behind/After",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » refers to something happening immediately after the completion of an action, or right after it. Its opposite is « ». (37 verses: 3:11-4:47-5:21-8:15-8:16-8:50-9:25-12:25-12:27-12:28-15:65-17:46-21:57-27:10-27:80-28:31-30:52-33:15-37:90-40:33-47:25-47:27-48:22-50:40-52:49-54:45-59:12-70:17-74:23-74:33-79:22)",
      "d": "«دُبْر» «قُبل» «دُبْرُ الصَّلوٰۃ» «اَدْبَار»\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَسَبِّحۡہُ  وَاَدۡبَارَ السُّجُوۡدِ»\nTranslation: And glorify Him during the night and after the prostrations (i.e., after the prayers).\nAnd « » can also mean turning one's back and disappearing.\nThus, at another place, the Almighty declares:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَسَبِّحۡہُ وَ اِدۡبَارَ النُّجُوۡمِ»\nTranslation: And glorify Him during part of the night and at the setting of the stars.\nIn this verse, the eloquence is that the meaning of « » also brings in the meaning of « »."
    },
    {
      "id": 865,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Behind/Ahead",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means ahead or behind, this side or that side, here or there, this side or that side (it is a word of opposites). (24 verses: 2:91-2:101-3:187-4:24-4:102-6:94-11:71-11:92-14:16-14:17-18:79-19:5-23:7-23:100-33:53-42:51-45:10-49:4-57:13-59:14-70:31-76:27-84:10-85:20)",
      "d": "« » means ahead or behind (it is a word of opposites). It is masculine and feminine (as per 'Manjad') and is used as both a temporal and spatial adverb. Now consider its examples:\n(1) Spatial adverb meaning 'behind':\nThe Almighty declares:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُنَادُوۡنَکَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ الۡحُجُرٰتِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, those who call you from behind the partitions (from outside).\n(2) Temporal adverb meaning 'after':\nThe Almighty declares:\n«فَبَشَّرۡنٰہَا بِاِسۡحٰقَ ۙ وَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ اِسۡحٰقَ یَعۡقُوۡبَ»\nTranslation: So We gave her glad tidings of Isaac and, after Isaac, of Jacob.\n(3) Spatial adverb meaning 'ahead':\nThe Almighty declares:\n«وَ کَانَ  وَرَآءَہُمۡ مَّلِکٌ یَّاۡخُذُ کُلَّ  سَفِیۡنَۃٍ غَصۡبًا»\nTranslation: And there was a king before them (ahead of them) who seized every ship by force.\nThen this word is also used to mean 'besides' or 'other than'.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَمَنِ ابۡتَغٰی وَرَآءَ ذٰلِکَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الۡعٰدُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And whoever seeks beyond that, they are the transgressors.\n«وَرَآءَ الْاِنْسَان» «وَرَآء»\nFor instance, the Almighty declares:\n«فَاِذَا سَجَدُوۡا فَلۡیَکُوۡنُوۡا مِنۡ وَّرَآئِکُمۡ ۪ وَ لۡتَاۡتِ طَآئِفَۃٌ اُخۡرٰی لَمۡ یُصَلُّوۡا فَلۡیُصَلُّوۡا مَعَکَ»\nTranslation: When you have prostrated, let them (the other group) be behind you, and let another group who have not yet prayed come and pray with you."
    },
    {
      "id": 866,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Come Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » is used in all these meanings: those who come after, later people, successors, past, offspring of the elders, heir, offspring, deputy, successor. (14 verses: 6:133-7:69-7:74-7:129-7:142-7:150-7:169-11:57-19:59-24:55-27:62-43:60-46:21-57:7)",
      "d": "« » is the opposite of « » and comes as a temporal adverb. It means 'to come after', 'to be a deputy', 'to be a successor' (as per 'Manjad'). And generally, « » refers to unworthy and incompetent successors.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَاتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ غَیًّا»\nTranslation: Then, after them succeeded [other] generations who neglected prayer and pursued desires. So they will soon face perdition.\nAnd « » means two things coming one after the other, one after the other, one following the other continuously. (as per 'Manjad')\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَہُوَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ خِلۡفَۃً»\nTranslation: And it is He who made the night and day in succession (one following the other)."
    },
    {
      "id": 869,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Leave Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means to leave someone behind or push back in terms of time. (6 verses: 3:153-7:38-7:39-11:8-75:13-82:5)",
      "d": "« » is the opposite of « ». It is used as a temporal adverb, meaning to leave behind or push back. Then this word is also used to postpone an action, and if it relates to someone else, it is used in the meaning of granting respite.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«یُنَبَّؤُا الۡاِنۡسَانُ یَوۡمَئِذٍۭ بِمَا قَدَّمَ وَاَخَّرَ»\nTranslation: On that Day, man will be informed of what he sent ahead and what he left behind."
    },
    {
      "id": 870,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Leave Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means to leave someone behind (spatial adverb), to be behind someone, to remain behind, to catch someone from behind. (6 verses: 9:81-9:118-9:120-48:11-48:15-48:16-)",
      "d": "« » means to leave behind. It is used when both temporal and spatial contexts apply.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَّ عَلَی الثَّلٰثَۃِ الَّذِیۡنَ خُلِّفُوۡا»\nTranslation:\n1 - And upon the three who were left behind (i.e., their matter was deferred). (Jalandhari)\n2 - And upon those persons who were kept behind (i.e., did not join the expedition). (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 871,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Remain Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means to remain behind by one's own will and choice. (10 verses: 2:203-7:34-10:49-15:5-15:24-16:61-23:43-34:30-48:2-74:37)",
      "d": "« » means to remain behind by one's own will and choice.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَمَنْ تَعَجَّلَ فِي یَوْمَیۡنِ فَلَا إِثْمَ عَلَیۡهِ وَمَنْ تَأَخَّرَ فَلَا إِثْمَ عَلَیۡهِ»\nTranslation: So whoever hastens [his departure] by two days, there is no sin upon him; and whoever delays [his departure], there is no sin upon him."
    },
    {
      "id": 872,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Remain Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means to remain behind due to deficiency and shortcoming. (3 verses: 9:83-9:87-9:93)",
      "d": "« » means to remain behind due to deficiency and shortcoming (as per 'Mufradat'). Its other meaning is 'to oppose'. And « » refers to one who remains behind due to his laziness or incompetence (as per 'Mufradat'). And « » also means 'foolish' and one who sits back after someone has left (as per 'Manjad').\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّکُمۡ رَضِیۡتُمۡ بِالۡقُعُوۡدِ اَوَّلَ مَرَّۃٍ  فَاقۡعُدُوۡا مَعَ الۡخٰلِفِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: You were satisfied with sitting back the first time, so sit [now] with those who remain behind.\nAnd the feminine form of « » is « », and generally it refers to a housewife who stays at home during jihad. And its plural is « » (as per 'Mufradat'). For instance, the Quran states:\n«رَضُوۡا بِاَنۡ یَّکُوۡنُوۡا مَعَ الۡخَوَالِفِ»\nTranslation: They are pleased to be with those [women] who remain behind (at home)."
    },
    {
      "id": 873,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Remain Behind",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means to remain behind from one's companions due to failure or shortcoming. (7 verses: 7:83-15:60-26:171-27:57-29:32-29:33-37:135)",
      "d": "« » means to remain behind from one's companions due to failure or shortcoming. (as per 'Mufradat')\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰہُ وَ اَہۡلَہٗۤ  اِلَّا امۡرَاَتَہٗ  ۫ ۖکَانَتۡ مِنَ الۡغٰبِرِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And We saved him and his family, except his wife; she was of those who remained behind."
    },
    {
      "id": 874,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Postpone/Put Back",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means to postpone or put back from an appointed time, or to grant respite. (10 verses: 4:77-11:104-14:10-14:42-14:44-16:61-17:62-35:45-63:11-71:4)",
      "d": "« » means to postpone from an appointed time or to grant respite (as per 'Manjad' and 'Mufradat'). This word is used generally.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَلَنۡ یُّؤَخِّرَ اللّٰہُ  نَفۡسًا اِذَا جَآءَ اَجَلُہَا»\nTranslation: And Allah will not delay a soul when its appointed time has come."
    },
    {
      "id": 875,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Postpone/Put Back",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means a delay in which there is a possibility of attaining joy and happiness; to delay something while hoping for it. (1 verse: 33:51)",
      "d": "« » means an expectation in which there is a possibility of attaining joy (as per 'Mufradat'). Its opposite is « ». And « » and « » are concomitant (i.e., both are necessary for each other). When there is hope for attaining a beloved thing, there will also be anxiety about its loss. Similarly, in the opposite situation, anxiety about loss is accompanied by hope for attainment. And « » means to postpone something in which there is a possibility of attaining joy (happiness).\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«تُرۡجِیۡ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ مِنۡہُنَّ وَ تُـئۡوِیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکَ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ»\nTranslation: You may defer whom you will of them, and you may receive whom you will of them."
    },
    {
      "id": 876,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to delay or postpone",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » refers to a delay made with caution so that the matter can be corrected (2 verses: 7:111-26:36)",
      "d": "«رَجَہَ» «اَرْجَہَ الْاَمْر» «اَرْجَہَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَرۡجِہۡ  وَاَخَاہُ وَاَرۡسِلۡ فِی الۡمَدَآئِنِ حٰشِرِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: They said, 'Give him and his brother respite and send heralds to the cities.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 877,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to delay or postpone",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means to be hasty in one matter and to delay in another (1 verse: 9:37)",
      "d": "«نَسَأَ» «نَسَاَکَ اللہُ فِیْٓ اَجَلِکَ» «نَسِیْءُ» «نَسِیْءُ»\nFor example: The command of Allah Almighty is:\n«اِنَّمَا النَّسِیۡٓءُ زِیَادَۃٌ فِی الۡکُفۡرِ  یُضَلُّ بِہِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا یُحِلُّوۡنَہٗ عَامًا وَّ یُحَرِّمُوۡنَہٗ عَامًا»\nTranslation: To remove a sacred month and then insert it elsewhere is only an addition to disbelief, whereby those who disbelieve are led astray. They make it lawful one year and forbidden another year."
    },
    {
      "id": 878,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To follow. To be followed.",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » To go behind, to accompany, to follow, to be a follower, to come after someone, to be subordinate. It is used in all these meanings (150 verses: 2:38-2:102-2:120-2:143-2:145-2:166-2:167-2:168-2:170-2:208-2:262-2:263-3:7-3:20-3:31-3:53-3:55-3:68-3:73-3:95-3:162-3:167-3:174-4:27-4:83-4:115-4:125-4:135-5:16-5:48-5:49-5:77-6:50-6:56-6:106-6:116-6:142-6:148-6:150-6:153-6:155-7:3-7:18-7:90-7:142-7:157-7:158-7:175-7:176-7:193-7:203-8:64-9:42-9:100-9:117-10:15-10:35-10:36-10:66-10:89-10:90-10:109-11:27-11:59-11:60-11:97-11:99-11:116-12:38-12:108-13:37-14:21-14:36-14:44-15:18-15:42-15:65-16:123-17:47-17:63-18:28-18:66-18:70-18:85-18:89-18:92-19:43-19:59-20:16-20:47-20:78-20:90-20:93-20:108-20:123-20:134-22:3-23:44-23:71-24:21-25:8-26:40-26:52-26:60-26:111-26:215-26:224-28:35-28:42-28:47-28:49-28:50-28:57-29:12-30:29-31:15-31:21-33:2-34:20-36:11-36:20-36:21-37:10-38:26-38:85-39:18-39:55-40:7-40:38-40:47-42:15-43:61-44:23-45:18-46:9-47:3-47:14-47:16-47:28-48:15-52:21-53:23-53:28-54:3-54:24-57:27-71:21-75:18-77:17-79:7)",
      "d": "« » is used both as a intransitive ( ) and transitive ( ) verb. When intransitive, its meaning is to go behind or to pursue.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَتۡبَعُوۡہُمۡ مُّشۡرِقِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: So the courtiers of Pharaoh pursued them at sunrise.\nAnd when transitive, its meaning is to make someone follow.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَتۡبَعۡنٰہُمۡ فِیۡ ہٰذِہِ الدُّنۡیَا لَعۡنَۃً»\nTranslation: And We followed them in this world with a curse.\nNote:"
    },
    {
      "id": 880,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to follow or to be followed",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means to incite or urge something, causing others to follow behind it (2 verses: 5:14-33:60)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is to incite or urge a dog or a hunting animal and make it follow the prey (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَغۡرَیۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمُ الۡعَدَاوَۃَ وَ الۡبَغۡضَآءَ»\nTranslation: Then We cast enmity and hatred between them. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 882,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "other derivatives of 'following'",
      "hw": "پیچھے",
      "s": "« » means to take one step back while walking straight, or to retreat while watching, or to retreat stealthily and secretly (2 verses: 81:15-114:4)",
      "d": "«خَنَّسَ ، خَنْس» «خَانِسْ» «خنَّس»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَاۤ اُقۡسِمُ  بِالۡخُنَّسِ الۡجَوَارِ الۡکُنَّسِ»\nTranslation: So I swear by the stars that retreat, that move about, and that vanish.\nAnd « » has more emphasis than « ». That is, one who has made retreating his habit repeatedly.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«مِنۡ شَرِّ الۡوَسۡوَاسِ ۙ الۡخَنَّاسِ»\nTranslation: (I seek refuge in Allah) from the evil of the whisperer who withdraws (to deceive)."
    }
  ],
  "180": [
    {
      "id": 884,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to create",
      "hw": "پیدا",
      "s": "« » means to make or create for the first time without a model or imitation (3 verses: 2:117-6:101-46:9)",
      "d": "« » means to make or create for the first time without a model or imitation. (muf) And 'badee' means one who creates something unique (minjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَدِیۡعُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ»\nTranslation: He is the Originator of the heavens and the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 885,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to create",
      "hw": "پیدا",
      "s": "« » means to fashion beautifully by carving and shaping (14 verses: 6:14-6:79-11:51-12:101-14:10-17:51-20:72-21:56-30:30-35:1-36:22-39:46-42:11-43:27-67-3)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is to create beautifully by carving and shaping.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فِطۡرَتَ اللّٰہِ الَّتِیۡ فَطَرَ  النَّاسَ عَلَیۡہَا»\nTranslation: So direct your face toward the religion, inclining to truth. [It is] the fitrah of Allah upon which He has created [all] people.\nAt another place, the command of Allah Almighty is:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ فَاطِرِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ»\nTranslation: All praise is [due] to Allah, Originator of the heavens and the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 886,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to create",
      "hw": "پیدا",
      "s": "« » means to make a thing whose material already exists (210 verses: 2:21-2:29-2:164-2:228-3:47-3:49-3:59-3:190-3:191-4:1-4:28-4:119-5:17-5:18-5:110-6:1-6:2-6:73-6:94-6:100-6:101-6:102-7:11-7:12-7:54-7:69-7:181-7:185-7:189-7:191-9:36-10:3-10:4-10:5-10:6-10:34-11:7-11:119-13:5-13:16-14:19-14:32-15:26-15:27-15:28-15:33-15:85-16:3-16:4-16:5-16:8-16:17-16:20-16:48-16:70-16:81-17:49-17:51-17:61-17:70-17:98-17:99-18:37-18:48-18:51-19:9-19:67-20:4-20:50-20:55-21:16-21:33-21:37-21:104-22:5-22:73-23:12-23:14-23:17-23:91-23:115-24:45-25:2-25:3-25:49-25:54-25:59-26:78-26:166-26:184-27:60-27:64-28:68-29:17-29:19-29:20-29:44-29:61-30:8-30:11-30:20-30:21-30:22-30:27-30:30-30:40-30:54-31:10-31:11-31:25-31:28-32:4-32:7-32:10-34:7-35:1-35:3-35:11-35:16-35:40-36:36-36:42-36:68-36:71-36:77-36:78-36:79-36:81-37:11-37:96-37:125-37:150-38:27-38:71-38:75-38:76-39:4-39:5-39:6-39:38-39:62-40:57-40:62-40:67-41:9-41:15-41:21-41:37-42:29-42:49-43:9-43:12-43:16-43:19-43:87-44:38-44:39-45:4-45:22-46:3-46:4-46:33-49:13-50:15-50:16-50:38-51:49-51:56-52:35-52:36-53:45-54:49-55:3-55:14-55:15-56:57-56:59-57:4-59:24-64:2-64:3-65:12-67:2-67:3-67:14-70:19-70:39-71:14-71:15-74:11-75:38-76:2-76:28-77:20-78:8-79:27-80:18-80:19-82:7-86:5-86:6-87:2-88:17-89:8-90:4-92:3-95:4-96:1-96:2-113:2)",
      "d": "The word « » is used in many meanings.\nFor example:\n(1) To conceive or design something for making (muf). That is, creation can also be a mental act, and its attribution can also be to other than Allah.\n«خَلَقَ ، اِبْدَاع» «خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالْاَرْضِ» «بَدِیْعُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالْاَرْضِ»\n(3) And the general meaning of « » is that one thing is made from another. If the primary material exists, then another thing is created from it.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«خَلَقَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ وَّ خَلَقَ مِنۡہَا زَوۡجَہَا وَ بَثَّ مِنۡہُمَا رِجَالًا کَثِیۡرًا وَّ نِسَآءً»\nTranslation: He created you from one soul and created from it its mate and dispersed from both of them many men and women.\nIn this case, its attribution can also be to other than Allah. As when Allah Almighty says to Prophet Jesus (peace be upon him):\n«وَاِذۡ تَخۡلُقُ مِنَ الطِّیۡنِ کَہَیۡئَۃِ الطَّیۡرِ»\nTranslation: And when you design from clay [a figure] like that of a bird. (Uthmani)\nFurthermore, at another place, the command of Allah Almighty is:\n«فَتَبٰرَکَ اللّٰہُ  اَحۡسَنُ  الۡخٰلِقِیۡنَ»\nTranslation:\n1 - So blessed is Allah, the best of creators. (Jalandhari)\n2 - The best creator. (Uthmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 887,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to create",
      "hw": "پیدا",
      "s": "« » means to create and to nurture/grow (23 verses: 6:6-6:98-6:133-6:141-11:61-21:11-23:14-23:19-23:31-23:42-23:78-28:45-29:20-36:79-43:18-53:32-53:47-55:24-56:35-56:61-56:62-56:72-67:23)",
      "d": "« » basically has two meanings: (1) to create something, and (2) then to nurture and grow it (m. l. minjad). And this word is used in both these meanings separately and also in a combined sense.\n(1) Example of the meaning of creation:\nThe command of Allah Almighty is:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡشَاَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ»\nTranslation: And He is the One Who produced you from a single soul.\n(2) Example of the meaning of nurturing:\nThe command of Allah Almighty is:\n«اَوَ مَنۡ یُّنَشَّؤُا فِی الۡحِلۡیَۃِ»\nTranslation: Or is He [to be compared to one] who is brought up in adornments? (i.e., idols)\n(3) Example of the combined act of creation and growth:\nThe command of Allah Almighty is:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡشَاۡتُمۡ شَجَرَتَہَاۤ  اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الۡمُنۡشِئُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Have you caused to grow it, or are We the grower?"
    }
  ],
  "181": [
    {
      "id": 889,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "to present",
      "hw": "پیش",
      "s": "« » means to present, to bring forward; it is used for non-rational things, i.e., things that do not possess reason (11 verses: 2:31-11:18-18:48-18:100-33:72-38:31-40:46-42:45-46:20-46:34-69:18)",
      "d": "« » means to present, to bring forward (minjad). And it generally comes for non-rational beings (i.e., things that do not possess reason). Such as petitions, presentations, reports, messages, or other objects, and generally used in a spiritual sense. (muf)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ عَلَّمَ اٰدَمَ الۡاَسۡمَآءَ کُلَّہَا ثُمَّ عَرَضَہُمۡ عَلَی الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ»\nTranslation: And He taught Adam the names - all of them. Then He showed them to the angels and said, 'Inform Me of the names of these, if you are truthful.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 890,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Present",
      "hw": "پیش",
      "s": "« » means to present or bring someone forward, to make present, and the existence and observation of that thing are necessary.",
      "d": "« » means to come forward, to be present. And « » means to present or bring someone forward, to make present, and in this, the existence and observation of that thing are necessary (m. l). And this generally comes for those of sound intellect (i.e., those who possess intellect). And it is used in a negative sense, such as presenting a criminal, and the word 'ihdar' indicates anger and wrath (f. l 77).\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«فَوَ رَبِّکَ لَنَحۡشُرَنَّہُمۡ وَ الشَّیٰطِیۡنَ ثُمَّ لَنُحۡضِرَنَّہُمۡ حَوۡلَ جَہَنَّمَ جِثِیًّا»\nTranslation: By your Lord! We will surely gather them and the devils as well, then We will bring them all around Hell, humbled."
    }
  ],
  "182": [
    {
      "id": 891,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Forehead (Temple)",
      "hw": "پیشانی",
      "s": "« » refers to one side of the forehead, right or left.",
      "d": "« » means the edge of the forehead (manjad), and the two sides of the forehead (right and left) are called « ».\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَسۡلَمَا و تَلَّہٗ لِلۡجَبِیۡنِ»\nTranslation: When both submitted, the father laid the son prostrate on his forehead."
    },
    {
      "id": 892,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Forehead (Temple)",
      "hw": "پیشانی",
      "s": "« » means the middle part of the forehead.",
      "d": "« » means the breadth and beauty of the forehead (manjad). « » actually refers to the front and middle part of the forehead that touches the ground during prostration. And its plural is « ».\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«فَتُکۡوٰی بِہَا جِبَاہُہُمۡ وَ جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ وَ ظُہُوۡرُہُمۡ»\nTranslation: Then their foreheads, their sides, and their backs will be branded with it."
    },
    {
      "id": 893,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Forehead (Temple)",
      "hw": "پیشانی",
      "s": "« » means the forehead or the hair of the forehead when they are long (manjad).",
      "d": "« » means the forehead or the hair of the forehead when they are long (manjad). Its application is to the hair on the forehead as well as the forehead itself. Its plural is « ».\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«یُعۡرَفُ الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ فَیُؤۡخَذُ بِالنَّوَاصِیۡ وَ الۡاَقۡدَامِ»\nTranslation: The criminals will be recognized by their marks, then they will be seized by the forelocks and the feet."
    }
  ],
  "183": [
    {
      "id": 896,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Adversaries of the Prophets",
      "hw": "پیغمبر",
      "s": "« » means a sorcerer, one who acquires satanic sciences in opposition to the sciences of prophethood.",
      "d": "« » means a sorcerer, one who acquires satanic sciences in opposition to the sciences of prophethood. The prophets and messengers were often granted miracles by Allah, sometimes on their own, sometimes at the demand of the disbelievers, and sometimes under extreme necessity, so the disbelievers immediately accuse them of being sorcerers.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اِقۡتَرَبَتِ السَّاعَۃُ وَ انۡشَقَّ الۡقَمَرُ ، وَاِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَیَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ»\nTranslation: The Hour has drawn near, and the moon has split. And if they see a sign, they turn away and say, 'This is continuous magic.'\nHere, after describing the miracle of the moon's splitting, the reality is immediately stated that the disbelievers' habit is to dismiss miracles as magic. Therefore, it is necessary to understand the difference between magic and miracle. The differences are as follows:\n(1) In magic, the essence and reality of things do not change; rather, magic is performed on people's eyes, and they begin to see something as something else. Regarding the snakes that the magicians made from ropes and staffs against Moses (peace be upon him), the divine command says:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَلۡقَوۡا سَحَرُوۡۤا اَعۡیُنَ النَّاسِ وَاسۡتَرۡہَبُوۡہُمۡ وَجَآءُوۡ بِسِحۡرٍعَظِیۡمٍ»\nTranslation: When the magicians threw their staffs, they deceived the people's eyes and terrified them, and they brought a great magic.\nWhereas in the case of a miracle, the essence and reality of the thing change. For example, when Moses (peace be upon him) threw his staff, it became a snake, but upon picking it up, it returned to its original state.\n(2) In the case of a miracle, the newly created thing either remains in that state or returns to its original state. For example, the spring of Zamzam or the bursting of twelve springs, or returning to the original state like the splitting of the moon, the staff of Moses, or the shining hand. A miracle cannot be destroyed or countered, whereas magic can be destroyed or countered. For example, the snakes made by the magicians were swallowed by Moses' staff (snake).\n«اٰیَۃ ، اٰیَۃٌ بَیِّنَۃ ، مُبْصِرَۃ» «بُرْھَان» «سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَسۡرٰی» «سُبْحَان»\n(3) Magic is an art acquired through practice and effort, whereas a miracle is a divine gift that is not acquired through practice and effort. This is why the magicians who came against Moses, who were at the pinnacle of the art of magic, realized that what Moses presented was above the art of magic. Therefore, they immediately embraced faith.\n(4) The character and conduct of magicians is detestable, and people fear their evil. Whereas the lives of prophets are extremely pure, and in this regard, they are honored and beloved among people."
    },
    {
      "id": 898,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Adversaries of the Prophets",
      "hw": "پیغمبر",
      "s": "« » means a person whose intellect is veiled and who speaks nonsensically.",
      "d": "« » means a person whose intellect is veiled and who speaks nonsensically. The Arabs used to call a madman 'majnun' because, according to their belief, if a jinn enters a human, it deprives him of his senses and he starts speaking irrationally. Since the teachings of the prophets were against the society's intellect and customs, the disbelievers also addressed the prophets as 'majnun'.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«کَذٰلِکَ مَاۤ اَتَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ  مِّنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ اِلَّا قَالُوۡا سَاحِرٌ اَوۡمَجۡنُوۡنٌ»\nTranslation: Similarly, there never came to those before them any messenger but they said, 'A sorcerer or a madman.'\nThe basic difference between a prophet and a madman is that the prophet's call, though contrary to the society's intellect and customs, he always remains firm on himself, demonstrates it through action, and establishes the seal of verification on his words through his pure character and conduct. Whereas a madman is devoid of these three things."
    }
  ],
  "184": [
    {
      "id": 899,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Drink",
      "hw": "پینا",
      "s": "« » means to drink water or any other drinkable thing.",
      "d": "« » means to drink water or any other drinkable thing. (Maf) It is general for drinking. 'Sharab' means any drinkable thing. «  .  » means a drink or a single drink. And « » means a place to drink. Ghat (manjad)\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«فَمَنۡ شَرِبَ مِنۡہُ فَلَیۡسَ مِنِّیۡ»\nTranslation: So whoever drinks from it will not be from me."
    },
    {
      "id": 900,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Drink",
      "hw": "پینا",
      "s": "« » means to drink in gulps.",
      "d": "« » means to drink in gulps (manjad). And « » means a gulp, and « » means to drink in one go (manjad).\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«یَّتَجَرَّعُہٗ  وَلَا یَکَادُ یُسِیۡغُہٗ»\nTranslation: He will gulp it down and will hardly swallow it."
    },
    {
      "id": 901,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Drink",
      "hw": "پینا",
      "s": "« » means to drink easily and smoothly due to the pleasant taste of the beverage.",
      "d": "« » means for a drink to go down the throat easily (muf). To drink smoothly and easily. And « » means a pleasant drink or beverage (sarrah). Its opposite is « » which means something that does not go down easily and gets stuck.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«نُسۡقِیۡکُمۡ  مِّمَّا فِیۡ بُطُوۡنِہٖ مِنۡۢ  بَیۡنِ  فَرۡثٍ وَّ دَمٍ لَّبَنًا خَالِصًا سَآئِغًا لِّلشّٰرِبِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: We give you to drink from what is in their bellies, between feces and blood, pure milk, palatable for the drinkers."
    }
  ],
  "185": [
    {
      "id": 902,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Star (Types)",
      "hw": "تارا",
      "s": "« » means to appear, to become visible, the rising of stars.",
      "d": "« » basically comes in two meanings: (1) Plants without stems, i.e., herbs and shrubs. (2) Planets that rise and set. And its plural is 'nujoom'. And 'najm' is used as a generic noun.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَ بِالنَّجۡمِ  ہُمۡ  یَہۡتَدُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And by the stars, they are guided."
    },
    {
      "id": 903,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Star (Types)",
      "hw": "تارا",
      "s": "« » refers to every large star, whether it is a star or a planet (5 verses: 6:76, 12:4, 24:35, 37:6, 82:2)",
      "d": "«کَوْکِبَۃٌ» «کَوْکَب» «کَوَاکِب» «کَوْکَبَ الْجَدِیْد» «کَوکَب»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّا زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ  الدُّنۡیَا بِزِیۡنَۃِۣ الۡکَوَاکِبِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, We have adorned the nearest heaven with an adornment of stars.\nThe Quran mentions the following types of stars:\n(1) « »: The name of a bright star that rises in the intense heat season (Maf). In pre-Islamic times, it was worshipped. For more details, see 'Ma'boodan-e-Batil' (1/5). Allah Almighty told the polytheists:\n«وَاَنَّہٗ ہُوَ رَبُّ الشِّعۡرٰی»\nTranslation: And that He is the Lord of Shi'ra (the bright star).\n«خُنَّس ، خَنَسَ» «خَانِسْ» «خُنَّس» «خُنَّس»\n«خمسہ متحیرہ»\n«جَوَار ، جَار ، جَوْرًا» «جَوَار»\n«کُنَّس ، کَنَّسَ» «كِنَاسُ» «کَانَس» «کَانَس» «کُنَّس»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَاۤ اُقۡسِمُ  بِالۡخُنَّسِ الۡجَوَارِ الۡکُنَّسِ»\nTranslation: So, I swear by the retreating stars, the moving planets, and the disappearing ones."
    }
  ],
  "186": [
    {
      "id": 904,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "« » means the evening twilight/darkness that covers immediately after sunset (1 verse: 81:17)",
      "d": "« » means the dusk, the light darkness of the evening. The darkness that covers right after sunset. Similarly, the light darkness before sunrise (Maf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الَّیۡلِ اِذَا عَسۡعَسَ وَالصُّبۡحِ اِذَا تَنَفَّسَ»\nTranslation: And by the night when it covers, and by the morning when it appears."
    },
    {
      "id": 905,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "« » the initial part of the night (2 verses: 17:78, 113:3)",
      "d": "« » means after the disappearance of the twilight (the reddish glow visible on the horizon at sunrise and sunset). It refers to the darkness of the early night, the first part of the night (F. L 34).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ  لِدُلُوۡکِ الشَّمۡسِ اِلٰی غَسَقِ الَّیۡلِ وَ قُرۡاٰنَ الۡفَجۡرِ»\nTranslation: Establish prayer from the declining of the sun until the darkness of the night and the Quran of dawn (i.e., the recitation of the Quran in the morning prayer). (Jalandhari)"
    },
    {
      "id": 906,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "« » such darkness that objects are not clearly visible (1 verse: 79:29)",
      "d": "« » means the night to be dark. And « » means weak or dim sight. Similarly, « » refers to both the darkness of the night and weakness of sight (Munjid). That is, such darkness in which objects appear dim.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَغۡطَشَ لَیۡلَہَا وَ اَخۡرَجَ ضُحٰہَا»\nTranslation: And He made its night dark and brought forth its daylight."
    },
    {
      "id": 907,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "« » such darkness that objects become completely hidden within it (1 verse: 113:3)",
      "d": "«وَقْب» «وَقَبَ» «وَقَبَ الشَّمْس» «وَقَبَ الظَّلَام»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَمِنۡ شَرِّ غَاسِقٍ اِذَا وَقَبَ»\nTranslation: And from the evil of the darkness when it covers."
    },
    {
      "id": 908,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Darkness Covering",
      "hw": "تاریکی",
      "s": "« » the stillness and darkness of the night (1 verse: 93:2)",
      "d": "«سَجَی الْلَیْل» «سَجَی الْمَیِّتَ» «سَجَّ مَعَائِبِ اَخِیْکَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالضُّحٰی وَ الَّیۡلِ اِذَا سَجٰی»\nTranslation: By the day and its brightness, and by the night when it covers."
    }
  ],
  "187": [
    {
      "id": 910,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Fresh",
      "hw": "تازہ",
      "s": "« » means fresh and tender; generally used for meat (2 verses: 16:14, 35:12)",
      "d": "« » means fresh and tender. Its usage is generally for meat (F. L 54). « » means freshness and tenderness.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مِنۡ کُلٍّ تَاۡکُلُوۡنَ لَحۡمًا طَرِیًّا وَّ تَسۡتَخۡرِجُوۡنَ حِلۡیَۃً تَلۡبَسُوۡنَہَا»\nTranslation: And from each (sea) you eat tender meat and extract ornaments which you wear."
    },
    {
      "id": 911,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Fresh",
      "hw": "تازہ",
      "s": "« » means fresh and tender; specifically used for ripe dates (2 verses: 6:59, 19:25)",
      "d": "« » means fresh and tender; its opposite is « » meaning dried. However, in common usage, « » is specifically used for ripe and fresh dates (Maf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ہُزِّیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکِ بِجِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ  تُسٰقِطۡ عَلَیۡکِ  رُطَبًا جَنِیًّا»\nTranslation: And shake the trunk of the palm tree toward you; it will drop upon you fresh ripe dates."
    },
    {
      "id": 912,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Fresh",
      "hw": "تازہ",
      "s": "« » the freshness and radiance of a face and the purity of an atmosphere (3 verses: 75:22, 76:11, 83:24)",
      "d": "« » means to be soft, fresh, and beautiful (Munjid, M. L). And « » refers to the beauty of complexion and grace (M. L). The freshness, radiance, and cheerfulness of a face.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَوَقٰہُمُ  اللّٰہُ  شَرَّ ذٰلِکَ الۡیَوۡمِ وَلَقّٰہُمۡ نَضۡرَۃً  وَّ سُرُوۡرًا»\nTranslation: So, Allah will protect them from the evil of that Day and will grant them freshness and joy."
    },
    {
      "id": 913,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Fresh",
      "hw": "تازہ",
      "s": "« » the freshness of faces due to abundance of blessings and prosperity (1 verse: 88:8)",
      "d": "« » means a life of prosperity. Prosperity (Munjid). The freshness of faces resulting from the abundance of blessings and a prosperous state.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ نَّاعِمَۃٌ لِّسَعۡیِہَا رَاضِیَۃٌ»\nTranslation: Faces on that Day will be fresh, pleased with their effort."
    }
  ],
  "188": [
    {
      "id": 915,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "So that",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "« » Meaning 'so that'. It comes after a verb to state the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the 'lightened imperfect particle of subordination' – the particle that makes the verb subjunctive. Often, the preposition 'lam' ( ) accompanies 'kay' ( ), and this 'lam' is frequently omitted. (3 verses: 20:33-20:40-28:13)",
      "d": "« » Meaning 'so that'. It comes after a verb to state the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the 'lightened imperfect particle of subordination' – the particle that makes the verb subjunctive. Often, the preposition 'lam' ( ) accompanies 'kay' ( ), and this 'lam' is frequently omitted.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n« كَيْ تَقَرَّ عَیۡنُہَا وَ لَا تَحۡزَنَ»\nTranslation: So that her eyes may be cooled and she may not grieve."
    },
    {
      "id": 916,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "In order to",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "« » is referred to as a 'masdar particle' in Arabic grammar because when combined with a verb, it imparts the meaning of a verbal noun (masdar). (488 verses: 2:26-2:27-2:67-2:75-2:90-2:96-2:105-2:108-2:114-2:125-2:158-2:169-2:177-2:184-2:198-2:210-2:214-2:216-2:224-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:232-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:248-2:254-2:258-2:266-2:267-2:280-2:282-3:28-3:73-3:79-3:80-3:93-3:122-3:124-3:142-3:143-3:145-3:147-3:161-3:188-3:193-4:6-4:19-4:23-4:24-4:25-4:27-4:28-4:29-4:44-4:47-4:48-4:58-4:60-4:66-4:84-4:88-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:99-4:101-4:102-4:113-4:116-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:131-4:135-4:140-4:144-4:150-4:153-4:171-4:172-4:176-5:2-5:3-5:11-5:17-5:19-5:29-5:31-5:33-5:34-5:37-5:41-5:49-5:52-5:59-5:80-5:84-5:91-5:108-5:111-5:112-5:113-5:116-5:117-6:14-6:23-6:25-6:35-6:37-6:51-6:56-6:65-6:70-6:72-6:80-6:111-6:125-6:131-6:145-6:156-6:158-7:5-7:13-7:20-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:50-7:63-7:69-7:82-7:89-7:97-7:98-7:100-7:105-7:110-7:115-7:117-7:123-7:126-7:129-7:160-7:169-7:172-7:185-8:7-8:26-8:62-8:67-9:13-9:16-9:17-9:18-9:32-9:44-9:52-9:54-9:62-9:64-9:74-9:81-9:85-9:86-9:102-9:108-9:110-9:113-9:118-9:120-10:2-10:10-10:15-10:35-10:37-10:72-10:83-10:87-10:100-10:104-10:105-11:3-11:12-11:14-11:26-11:34-11:46-11:47-11:62-11:69-11:87-11:88-11:89-12:13-12:15-12:21-12:24-12:25-12:37-12:38-12:66-12:76-12:79-12:83-12:94-12:96-12:100-12:107-13:21-13:25-13:31-13:36-13:38-14:5-14:10-14:11-14:22-14:31-14:35-15:31-15:54-16:2-16:15-16:33-16:36-16:40-16:45-16:68-16:92-16:123-17:8-17:16-17:46-17:51-17:59-17:68-17:69-17:74-17:79-17:88-17:94-17:99-17:103-18:24-18:35-18:40-18:55-18:57-18:63-18:66-18:77-18:79-18:80-18:81-18:82-18:86-18:94-18:97-18:102-18:109-19:11-19:35-19:45-19:91-19:92-20:39-20:45-20:59-20:63-20:65-20:71-20:77-20:86-20:94-20:97-20:114-20:134-21:17-21:31-21:57-21:87-22:15-22:22-22:26-22:40-22:65-23:24-23:27-23:32-23:95-23:98-24:8-24:16-24:17-24:19-24:22-24:29-24:36-24:50-24:51-24:60-24:61-24:63-25:18-25:42-25:57-25:62-26:10-26:12-26:14-26:17-26:22-26:35-26:49-26:51-26:52-26:63-26:82-26:197-27:8-27:19-27:38-27:39-27:40-27:45-27:56-27:60-27:72-27:91-27:92-28:5-28:7-28:9-28:10-28:19-28:22-28:27-28:30-28:31-28:33-28:34-28:47-28:67-28:82-28:86-29:2-29:4-29:24-29:29-29:33-30:10-30:20-30:21-30:25-30:43-30:46-30:49-31:10-31:12-31:14-31:15-32:20-33:6-33:36-33:37-33:49-33:50-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:59-33:72-34:11-34:14-34:33-34:43-34:46-35:41-36:40-36:60-36:61-36:81-36:82-37:104-38:4-38:6-38:75-39:4-39:11-39:17-39:54-39:55-39:56-40:26-40:28-40:66-40:78-41:22-42:13-42:47-42:51-43:5-43:33-43:66-44:18-44:19-44:20-45:21-45:25-46:15-46:17-46:33-47:18-47:22-47:29-48:12-48:15-48:24-48:25-49:2-49:6-49:11-49:12-49:17-50:2-51:57-53:26-53:39-55:33-56:61-57:16-57:22-58:3-58:4-58:13-59:2-59:3-60:1-60:7-60:8-60:9-60:10-60:12-61:3-63:10-64:7-65:1-65:4-66:5-66:8-67:16-67:17-68:14-68:22-68:24-68:32-68:49-70:38-70:41-71:1-71:3-72:5-72:7-72:12-72:16-72:28-73:20-74:15-74:37-74:52-74:56-75:4-75:25-75:36-75:40-76:30-79:18-80:2-81:28-81:29-84:14-85:8-90:5-90:7-96:7)",
      "d": "« » is referred to as a 'masdar particle' in Arabic grammar because when combined with a verb, it imparts the meaning of a verbal noun (masdar).\n«ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی  اَنۡ تَقَرَّ اَعۡیُنُہُنَّ»\nTranslation: This is more likely to cool their eyes."
    },
    {
      "id": 917,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "So that",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "«کَیْ لَا»",
      "d": "«کَیْ لَا»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«كَيْ لَا یَکُوۡنَ دُوۡلَۃًۢ  بَیۡنَ الۡاَغۡنِیَآءِ مِنۡکُمۡ»\nTranslation: So that (the wealth) does not become a commodity between the rich among you."
    },
    {
      "id": 918,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "So that",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "« » Meaning 'so that'. It comes after a verb to state the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the 'lightened imperfect particle of subordination' – the particle that makes the verb subjunctive. ' ' is written combined with the negative particle ' '.   +   =   (6 verses: 3:153-16:70-22:5-33:37-33:50-57:23)",
      "d": "«لِکَیْلَا»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَحۡزَنُوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: So that you may not grieve over what has escaped you."
    },
    {
      "id": 919,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "In order to",
      "hw": "تاکہ",
      "s": "« » means 'lest' or 'so that not'. (3 verses: 2:150-4:165-57:29)",
      "d": "« » means 'lest' or 'so that not'.\n«لِئَلَّا یَکُوۡنَ  لِلنَّاسِ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حُجَّۃٌ»\nTranslation: lest the people have an argument against you."
    }
  ],
  "189": [
    {
      "id": 920,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Molten copper",
      "hw": "تانبا",
      "s": "« » Molten copper (3 verses: 14:50-18:96-34:12)",
      "d": "« » is a specific word for molten copper (m.f. manjada).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ»\nTranslation: And We made for him a spring of molten copper."
    },
    {
      "id": 921,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Molten copper",
      "hw": "تانبا",
      "s": "« » Molten metals other than copper, and any loathsome, flowing discharge (3 verses: 18:29-44:45-70:8)",
      "d": "« » means ' ' – mineral substances that can be melted, like gold, silver, iron, copper. Molten metals. Thin pitch (flowing sulfur). Poison. Pus (manjada). And « » and « » mean yellowish water (pus, foul matter from a wound or boil, or the corrupt fluid that oozes from a corpse). That is, the thin yellowish discharge that comes out of a corpse (manjada. m.q.). So, « » refers to molten metals other than copper, as well as any flowing yellowish discharge (yellowish filth). Therefore, some scholars have also translated it as 'pus'.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡا یُغَاثُوۡا بِمَآءٍ کَالۡمُہۡلِ یَشۡوِی الۡوُجُوۡہَ ؕ بِئۡسَ الشَّرَابُ»\nTranslation: And if they seek help, they will be helped with water like molten metal, which scalds their faces. Wretched is the drink, and evil is the resting place."
    }
  ],
  "190": [
    {
      "id": 922,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Throne",
      "hw": "تخت",
      "s": "« » Used for a royal throne (29 verses: 2:259-7:54-9:129-10:3-11:7-12:100-13:2-17:42-18:42-20:5-21:22-22:45-23:86-23:116-25:59-27:23-27:26-27:38-27:41-27:42-32:4-39:75-40:7-40:15-43:82-57:4-69:17-81:20-85:15)",
      "d": "« » is used for a royal throne. (f.l. 230)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ رَفَعَ اَبَوَیۡہِ عَلَی الۡعَرۡشِ»\nTranslation: And he (Yusuf) raised his parents to the throne.\n«عَرْشَ الْبَیْت» «عَرَشَ یَعْرِشُ» «عَرْشَ الْبَیْت»"
    }
  ],
  "191": [
    {
      "id": 926,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Plank/Tablet",
      "hw": "تختہ",
      "s": "« » refers to wooden planks or writing tablets. (5 verses: 7:145-7:150-7:154-54:13-85:22)",
      "d": "« » – its singular is « », meaning a plank of a ship, etc.\n«وَ حَمَلۡنٰہُ عَلٰی ذَاتِ اَلۡوَاحٍ  وَّدُسُرٍ»\nTranslation: And We carried him on a ship made of planks and nails.\nAlso, « » refers to a plank or tablet of wood, etc., on which something is written.\n«وَ کَتَبۡنَا لَہٗ  فِی الۡاَلۡوَاحِ  مِنۡ کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ مَّوۡعِظَۃً»\nTranslation: And We wrote for him on the tablets [of the Torah] a lesson from every thing."
    }
  ],
  "192": [
    {
      "id": 927,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "to deliberate",
      "hw": "تدبیر",
      "s": "« » means to consider with foresight regarding the outcome of an affair (9 verses: 4:82, 10:3, 10:31, 13:2, 23:68, 32:5, 38:29, 47:24, 79:5)",
      "d": "«دَبَّرَ» «وَ مَنۡ یُّدَبِّرُ الۡاَمۡرَ ؕ فَسَیَقُوۡلُوۡنَ اللّٰہُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 928,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Devise / To Plot",
      "hw": "تدبیر",
      "s": "« » (Kaid) is a secret scheme or plot that causes someone to encounter something detestable or evil. On a small scale, it is called « » (makr), and on a large scale, it is called « » (kaid). (29 verses: 3:120-4:76-7:183-7:195-8:18-11:55-12:5-12:28-12:33-12:34-12:50-12:52-12:76-20:60-20:64-20:69-21:57-21:70-22:15-37:98-40:25-40:37-52:42-52:46-68:45-77:39-86:15-86:16-105:2)",
      "d": "«کَیْد» «کَیْدُ سَاحِرٍ» «کَذٰلِکَ کِدۡنَا لِیُوۡسُفَ» «فَاِنۡ کَانَ لَکُمۡ کَیۡدٌ فَکِیۡدُوۡنِ» «مَکَرَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 929,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Devise / To Plot",
      "hw": "تدبیر",
      "s": "« » (Makara) means deception, fraud, a secret scheme by which another person is prevented from achieving their goal. (23 verses: 3:54-6:123-6:124-7:99-7:123-8:30-10:21-12:31-12:102-13:33-13:42-14:46-16:26-16:45-16:127-27:50-27:51-27:70-34:33-35:10-35:43-40:45-71:22)",
      "d": "«مَکَرَ» «مَکَرَ» «اَللہُ یَسْتَھْزِئُ بِھِمْ» «وَمَکَرُوۡا وَمَکَرَ اللّٰہُ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ خَیۡرُ الۡمٰکِرِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 930,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "To Devise / To Plot",
      "hw": "تدبیر",
      "s": "« » (Hiyalah) means to gain control or power over someone through cleverness and cunning. (1 verse: 4:98)",
      "d": "«حُوَّل ، حَوْل» «حِیَل» «حِوَل» «حیلہ» «مکر» «کَیْد» «اِلَّا الۡمُسۡتَضۡعَفِیۡنَ مِنَ الرِّجَالِ وَالنِّسَآءِ وَالۡوِلۡدَانِ لَا یَسۡتَطِیۡعُوۡنَ حِیۡلَۃً وَّلَا یَہۡتَدُوۡنَ سَبِیۡلًا»"
    }
  ],
  "193": [
    {
