      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Greens / Vegetables",
      "hw": "ترکاری",
      "s": "« » (Qaḍb) is that greens or vegetable which is eaten fresh after cutting. (1 verse: 80:28)",
      "d": "«قَضْب» «فَاَنْۢبَتْنَا فِيْہَا حَبًّا وَّعِنَبًا وَّقَضْبًا وَّ زَیۡتُوۡنًا وَّ نَخۡلًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 936,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Greens / Vegetables",
      "hw": "ترکاری",
      "s": "« » (Baql) is every kind of vegetable and greens that grows from a seed, not from a root. (1 verse: 2:61)",
      "d": "«بَقْل» «بَقْل» «بَقْل» «بَقّال» «فَادۡعُ لَنَا رَبَّکَ یُخۡرِجۡ لَنَا مِمَّا تُنۡۢبِتُ الۡاَرۡضُ مِنۡۢ بَقۡلِہَا»"
    }
  ],
  "196": [
    {
      "id": 937,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Glorification and Sanctification (Declaring Purity)",
      "hw": "پاکیزگی",
      "s": "« » (Sabbaha) means to glorify. To say 'Subhan Allah'. To mention the attributes of Allah's blessed essence and to praise Him. (42 verses: 2:30-3:41-7:206-13:13-15:98-17:44-19:11-20:33-20:130-21:20-21:79-24:36-24:41-25:58-32:15-33:42-37:143-37:166-38:18-39:75-40:7-40:55-41:38-42:5-48:9-50:39-50:40-52:48-52:49-56:74-56:96-57:1-59:1-59:24-61:1-62:1-64:1-68:28-69:52-76:26-87:1-110:3)",
      "d": "« » (Sabbaha) means to glorify. To say 'Subhan Allah' or to mention 'Subhan Allah'. To declare, with tongue or state, the attributes of that Blessed Essence who is free from every kind of defect, deficiency, and weakness. To positively mention His perfections and to praise Him. (For details, see 'Purity')."
    },
    {
      "id": 938,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Tasbih wa Taqdis (Declaring Purity)",
      "hw": "پاکیزگی",
      "s": "« » To mention a being or thing while negating negative or imperfect attributes. (8 verses: 2:30-2:87-2:253-5:21-5:110-16:102-20:12-79:16)",
      "d": "« » is a name of Allah (SWT). It means a Being who is not in need of any partner and is pure from all forms of association and impurities. (See details under 'Purity'). And « » means to declare the purity of the Essence of the Almighty and to negate all things that are unbefitting for Allah (SWT).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ نَحۡنُ نُسَبِّحُ بِحَمۡدِکَ وَ نُقَدِّسُ لَکَ»\nTranslation: (The angels said) And we continuously glorify You with praise and declare Your purity."
    },
    {
      "id": 939,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Tasbih wa Taqdis (Declaring Purity)",
      "hw": "پاکیزگی",
      "s": "« » is an exclamatory word, used in meanings similar to 'Subhan'. It comes to forcefully deny an accusation, either against oneself or someone else. (2 verses: 12:31-12:51)",
      "d": "«حَاشَ» «حَاشَا لِلّٰہِ، سُبْحَانَ اللہ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَیۡنَہٗۤ  اَکۡبَرۡنَہٗ وَ قَطَّعۡنَ اَیۡدِیَہُنَّ وَ قُلۡنَ حَاشَ لِلّٰہِ مَا ہٰذَا بَشَرًا ؕ اِنۡ  ہٰذَاۤ  اِلَّا مَلَکٌ  کَرِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: When those women saw him (Prophet Yusuf), his majesty overwhelmed them to such an extent that (while cutting fruit) they cut their own hands and exclaimed spontaneously: 'Subhan Allah! (What a stature and character!) This is not a human; this is none but a noble angel.'\nAt another place, the command of the Almighty states:\n«قَالَ مَا خَطۡبُکُنَّ اِذۡ رَاوَدۡتُّنَّ یُوۡسُفَ عَنۡ نَّفۡسِہٖ ؕ قُلۡنَ حَاشَ لِلّٰہِ مَا عَلِمۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡ سُوۡٓءٍ»\nTranslation: The king said (calling those women): What was your matter when you attempted to seduce Yusuf? They all said: 'Hasha lillah! We did not find any evil in him at all!'\n«حَاشَ وَکَلَّا» «حَاشَ»"
    }
  ],
  "197": [
    {
      "id": 940,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Taskeen (Consolation)",
      "hw": "تسکین",
      "s": "« » The word 'sakeenah' is used for peace and tranquility from grief and anxieties. (6 verses: 2:248-9:26-9:40-48:4-48:18-48:26)",
      "d": "« » refers to stillness after movement. This can be physical, mental, or cardiac. If it is mental or cardiac, it is called « ». That is, the heart finding relief from thoughts, grief, and worries. And attaining stability.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ لِصَاحِبِہٖ لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا ۚ فَاَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ سَکِیۡنَتَہٗ عَلَیۡہِ»\nTranslation: When the Prophet (ﷺ) consoled his companion, saying 'Do not grieve, indeed Allah is with us,' then Allah sent down His tranquility upon him."
    },
    {
      "id": 941,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Taskeen (Consolation)",
      "hw": "تسکین",
      "s": "« » The word 'itmi'nan' comes for relief from doubts and suspicions. (12 verses: 2:260-3:126-4:103-5:113-8:10-10:7-13:28-16:106-16:112-17:95-22:11-89:27)",
      "d": "« » means to attain tranquility. It is the soul finding peace after restlessness, anxiety, hesitation, and doubt. (muf) The natural state becoming calm.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ اَوَ لَمۡ تُؤۡمِنۡ ؕ قَالَ بَلٰی وَ لٰکِنۡ لِّیَطۡمَئِنَّ قَلۡبِیۡ»\nTranslation: (Allah) said: 'Have you not believed?' He (Ibrahim AS) said: 'Yes, but (I ask this) so that my heart may be at peace.' (Ibn Kathir)"
    }
  ],
  "198": [
    {
      "id": 942,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Interpreting (Dreams)",
      "hw": "تعبیر",
      "s": "« » and « » are words specifically used for stating the outcome (interpretation) of a dream. (7 verses: 3:13-12:43-12:111-16:66-23:21-24:44-79:26)",
      "d": "«عَبَرَ» «عِبَارَۃَ الرُّؤْیَا» «عَبَّرَ الرُّؤْیَا» «عَبَّار» «اَلْعِبْرَۃ وَالْاِعْتِبَار»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ لِلرُّءۡیَا تَعۡبُرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: If you are able to interpret dreams."
    },
    {
      "id": 943,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Interpreting (Dreams)",
      "hw": "تعبیر",
      "s": "« » To state the outcome of a matter or event; generally used for interpreting dreams. (15 verses: 3:7-4:59-7:53-10:39-12:6-12:21-12:36-12:37-12:44-12:45-12:100-12:101-17:35-18:78-18:82)",
      "d": "« » means to return something to its ultimate end or outcome. This word is more specific than 'ta'beer' because 'tawil' means to state the outcome of any matter in general, whether it is a dream or something else. Whereas the word 'ta'beer' is specific to stating the outcome of a dream. And according to 'Sahib al-Furq al-Lughawiyyah', 'tawil' is done for ambiguous (mutashabih) things only. (Faq. L 43)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ قَالَ الۡاٰخَرُ اِنِّیۡۤ  اَرٰىنِیۡۤ  اَحۡمِلُ فَوۡقَ رَاۡسِیۡ خُبۡزًا تَاۡکُلُ الطَّیۡرُ مِنۡہُ ؕ نَبِّئۡنَا بِتَاۡوِیۡلِہٖ»\nTranslation: The other (prisoner) said: 'I see myself carrying bread on my head from which birds are eating. Inform us of its interpretation.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 944,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Interpreting (Dreams)",
      "hw": "تعبیر",
      "s": "« » To provide a solution to a difficult and complex problem, which includes the interpretation of a dream. (5 verses: 4:127-4:176-12:43-12:46-27:32)",
      "d": "« » means to provide a solution to a difficult and complex problem. « » is a Shariah term meaning to present the Shariah solution for a difficult and complex problem. To explain. And 'istiftah' means to ask a scholar for the solution to a difficult and complex problem. In the Quran, the word « » has come for the interpretation of a dream only because the dream whose interpretation was sought was very complex and difficult.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡمَلَاُ  اَفۡتُوۡنِیۡ فِیۡ رُءۡیَایَ»\nTranslation: The king of Egypt said: O chiefs! Explain to me my dream.\nAnd those interpreters dismissed this complex dream by saying:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَضۡغَاثُ اَحۡلَامٍ ۚ وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِتَاۡوِیۡلِ الۡاَحۡلَامِ بِعٰلِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: The people said: 'These are confused dreams, and we are not experts in the interpretation of such dreams.'\nThen the freed companion of Yusuf said:\n«یُوۡسُفُ اَیُّہَا الصِّدِّیۡقُ اَفۡتِنَا فِیۡ سَبۡعِ بَقَرٰتٍ سِمَانٍ»\nTranslation: Yusuf! O truthful one, explain to us the interpretation of the seven fat cows."
    }
  ],
  "199": [
    {
      "id": 946,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Gratitude (Thankfulness)",
      "hw": "تعریف",
      "s": "« » Thanking; it occurs in the context of acknowledging a favor or blessing. (43 verses)",
      "d": "« » is the word used for the conception and expression of someone's favors and bounties. (muf) And its opposite is « ». It means to disregard a favor or to hide a blessing and not let it be apparent. Ingratitude or denial of a blessing. Thus, « » is also specific compared to « ». If we say, 'How beautifully Allah (SWT) has run the system of the universe,' this is « ». And if we say, 'Allah alone feeds us and gives us drink,' this is « ».\nVerses: 2:52, 2:56, 2:152, 2:172, 2:185, 2:243, 3:123, 4:147, 5:6, 5:89, 7:10, 7:58, 8:26, 10:60, 12:38, 14:7, 14:37, 16:14, 16:78, 16:114, 22:36, 23:78, 27:19, 27:40, 27:73, 28:73, 29:17, 30:46, 31:12, 31:14, 32:9, 34:13, 34:15, 35:12, 36:35, 36:73, 39:7, 40:61, 45:12, 46:15, 54:35, 56:70, 67:23 (Total 43 verses)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَئِنۡ شَکَرۡتُمۡ لَاَزِیۡدَنَّکُمۡ وَ لَئِنۡ کَفَرۡتُمۡ اِنَّ عَذَابِیۡ لَشَدِیۡدٌ»\nTranslation: If you are grateful, I will surely increase you (in favor). And if you are ungrateful, indeed My punishment is severe!"
    },
    {
      "id": 947,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "حامد",
      "hw": "حامد",
      "s": "«حامد»",
      "d": "«حامد» «حَمْد» «حَمْد» «شُکر» «حَمْد» «شُکر»\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ رَبِّ الْعٰلَمِیۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "200": [
    {
      "id": 947,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Glorification",
      "hw": "تعظیم",
      "s": "« » To regard someone as great and honorable from the heart. This is used for both animate and inanimate things. (5 verses: 6:146-19:4-22:30-22:32-65:5)",
      "d": "The meanings of « » are 'to be great' and 'bone'. Thus, in « », the concept of greatness along with firmness, strength, or hardness is also found. And « » means to regard someone as great and honorable from the heart. And it is used for both animate and inanimate things.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمَنۡ یُّعَظِّمۡ شَعَآئِرَ اللّٰہِ فَاِنَّہَا مِنۡ تَقۡوَی الۡقُلُوۡبِ»\nTranslation: And whoever glorifies the symbols of Allah, then indeed that (glorification) comes from the piety of hearts."
    }
  ],
  "201": [
    {
      "id": 949,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Until",
      "hw": "تک",
      "s": "« » In Arabic grammar, 'ila' is a preposition (harf jar) used to indicate the limit or end of something. (653 verses: [long list of references])",
      "d": "« » is called a preposition (harf jar) in Arabic grammar. It is used to state the limit or end of something. It can also govern a pronoun. For example, « », and in this case, it gives the meaning of 'towards'. But « » can only govern a demonstrative pronoun (ism dhahir). It does not govern a pronoun. It governs a noun or a verb only.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«حَتّٰی نَرَی اللّٰہَ جَہۡرَۃً»\nTranslation: Until we see Allah openly."
    },
    {
      "id": 950,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Until",
      "hw": "تک",
      "s": "« » is called a preposition in Arabic grammar, used to indicate the extremity or end of something. (138 verses: 2:55-2:102-2:109-2:120-2:187-2:191-2:193-2:196-2:214-2:217-2:221-2:222-2:230-2:235-3:92-3:152-3:179-3:183-4:6-4:15-4:18-4:43-4:65-4:89-4:140-5:22-5:68-6:25-6:31-6:34-6:44-6:61-6:68-6:124-6:148-6:152-7:37-7:38-7:40-7:57-7:87-7:95-8:39-8:53-8:67-8:72-9:6-9:24-9:29-9:43-9:48-9:115-9:118-10:22-10:24-10:88-10:90-10:93-10:97-10:99-10:109-11:40-12:35-12:66-12:80-12:85-12:110-13:11-13:31-15:99-17:15-17:34-17:90-17:93-18:60-18:70-18:71-18:74-18:77-18:86-18:90-18:93-18:96-19:75-20:91-21:15-21:44-21:96-22:55-23:25-23:54-23:64-23:77-23:99-23:110-24:27-24:28-24:33-24:39-24:62-25:18-26:201-27:18-27:32-27:84-28:23-28:59-34:23-36:39-37:174-37:178-38:32-39:71-39:73-40:34-41:20-41:53-43:29-43:38-43:83-46:15-47:4-47:16-47:31-49:5-49:9-51:43-52:45-57:14-60:4-63:7-65:6-70:42-72:24-74:47-97:5-98:1-102:2)",
      "d": "«حَتّٰی» «حَتّٰی» «اِلٰی» «حَتَّی الْاٰن» «اِلی الْاٰن» «اِلٰی» «حَتّٰی»\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«وَ قٰتِلُوۡہُمۡ حَتّٰی لَا تَکُوۡنَ فِتۡنَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And fight them until there is no fitnah."
    }
  ],
