  "244": [
    {
      "id": 1146,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "where, wherever",
      "hw": "جہاں",
      "s": "« » its meaning is (where, wherever). (29 verses: 2:35-2:58-2:144-2:149-2:150-2:191-2:199-2:222-4:89-4:91-6:124-7:19-7:27-7:161-7:182-9:5-12:56-12:68-15:65-16:26-16:45-20:69-38:36-39:25-39:74-59:2-65:3-65:6-68:44)",
      "d": "«حَیْثُ» «وَ مِنۡ حَیۡثُ خَرَجۡتَ فَوَلِّ وَجۡہَکَ شَطۡرَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1147,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "where, wherever",
      "hw": "جہاں",
      "s": "« » means 'wherever' (1 verse: 2:149)",
      "d": "« » means 'wherever'. The addition of « » is only for the sake of breadth in meaning.\n«وَ مِنۡ حَیۡثُ خَرَجۡتَ فَوَلِّ وَجۡہَکَ شَطۡرَ»\nTranslation: And wherever you may be, turn your face towards it (the Sacred Mosque)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1148,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "where, wherever",
      "hw": "جہاں",
      "s": "« » means 'where'. It is used to ask about a place (19 verses: 2:115, 2:148, 3:112, 4:78, 6:22, 7:37, 16:27, 16:76, 19:31, 26:92, 28:62, 28:74, 33:61, 40:73, 41:47, 57:4, 58:7, 75:10, 81:26)",
      "d": "« » means 'where'. It comes to ask about a place. And « » means 'any place'. In this way, « » and « » become synonymous. However, conditional meanings are also found in « » (see Manjad. Q).\n«اَیۡنَمَا ثُقِفُوۡۤا اُخِذُوۡا وَ قُتِّلُوۡا تَقۡتِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: Wherever you find them, seize them and kill them utterly."
    }
  ],
  "245": [
    {
      "id": 1149,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to scold, to rebuke",
      "hw": "جھڑکنا",
      "s": "« » means to scold, to rebuke (3 verses: 37:2, 37:19, 79:13)",
      "d": "« » means to warn someone in a loud voice. To scold. To drive away. To rebuke. And « » means a rebuke.\n«فَالزّٰجِرٰتِ زَجۡرًا»\nTranslation: Then (I swear by) the rebuking angels who rebuke."
    },
    {
      "id": 1150,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to scold, to rebuke",
      "hw": "جھڑکنا",
      "s": "« » means to expel by scolding, to drive away (2 verses: 54:4, 54:9)",
      "d": "« » means to drive someone away by scolding (transitive).\n«کَذَّبَتۡ قَبۡلَہُمۡ قَوۡمُ نُوۡحٍ فَکَذَّبُوۡا عَبۡدَنَا وَ قَالُوۡا مَجۡنُوۡنٌ وَّ ازۡدُجِرَ»\nTranslation: Before them, the people of Noah denied Our servant and said, 'He is mad!' and he was driven away with scolding."
    },
    {
      "id": 1151,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to scold, to rebuke",
      "hw": "جھڑکنا",
      "s": "« » means to scold harshly (2 verses: 17:23, 93:10)",
      "d": "«نَھَرَ» «نَھَرَ السَّائِل» «اَلزَّجْرُ الْغَلِیْظ»\n«وَ اَمَّا السَّآئِلَ فَلَا تَنۡہَرۡ»\nTranslation: And as for the asker, do not scold him harshly."
    }
  ],
  "246": [
    {
      "id": 1152,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means a natural inclination towards good, to be prone (1 verse: 8:61)",
      "d": "«جَنَحَ» «جَنَحَتِ السَّفِیْنَۃ» «جَنَاح» «جَنَاحَیْن» «جَنَاحَ» «جُنَاح»\n«وَ اِنۡ جَنَحُوۡا لِلسَّلۡمِ فَاجۡنَحۡ لَہَا»\nTranslation: And if they incline towards peace, then you too incline towards it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1153,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means a natural inclination of the temperament towards something (2 verses: 4:27, 4:129)",
      "d": "« » means natural leaning, i.e., the temperament's inclination. Attraction (see Manjad). The temperament's leaning towards something.\n«وَ لَنۡ تَسۡتَطِیۡعُوۡۤا اَنۡ تَعۡدِلُوۡا بَیۡنَ النِّسَآءِ وَ لَوۡ حَرَصۡتُمۡ فَلَا تَمِیۡلُوۡا کُلَّ الۡمَیۡلِ»\nTranslation: And you will never be able to be equal between wives, even if you try hard. So do not incline entirely (towards one)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1156,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means to incline for the sake of gaining strength or refuge (3 verses: 11:80, 11:113, 17:74)",
      "d": "« » means strength, dominance, fortress, strong side. And « » means to rely on something and incline towards it from which strength is gained (see Manjad).\n«وَ لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنۡ ثَبَّتۡنٰکَ لَقَدۡ کِدۡتَّ تَرۡکَنُ اِلَیۡہِمۡ شَیۡئًا قَلِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And had We not strengthened you, you would have almost inclined towards them a little."
    },
    {
      "id": 1157,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means to bend due to movement or weight, to sway (3 verses: 16:15, 21:31, 31:10)",
      "d": "«مَادَ» «مَادَتِ الغَّصْن»\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ رَوَاسِیَ اَنۡ تَمِیۡدَ بِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And We placed firm mountains in the earth lest it should sway with them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1158,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "to incline, to lean",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means to bend with fear and humility, whose effect is apparent on the limbs (15 verses: 2:45, 3:199, 20:108, 21:90, 23:2, 33:35, 41:39, 42:45, 54:7, 57:16, 59:21, 68:43, 70:44, 79:9, 88:2)",
      "d": "« » means to bend due to humility. Such fear whose effect is apparent on the limbs (transitive). This generally comes for the bending of the eye, face, voice, and heart. And it includes fear as well.\n«وَ خَشَعَتِ الۡاَصۡوَاتُ لِلرَّحۡمٰنِ»\nTranslation: And the voices will be humbled before the Most Merciful.\n«خَاشِعَۃً اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تَرۡہَقُہُمۡ ذِلَّۃٌ»\nTranslation: Their eyes will be humbled, and humiliation will cover them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1159,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means to bend due to force, oppression, or pressure (25 verses: 2:61-3:26-3:112-3:123-5:54-7:152-10:26-10:27-11:27-16:70-17:24-17:111-20:134-22:5-26:111-27:34-27:37-36:72-42:45-58:20-63:8-67:15-68:43-70:44-76:14)",
      "d": "« » means to bend due to force, oppression, and pressure. To become humiliated (intransitive), and its opposite is « ». The natural intensity and harshness being overcome spontaneously (intransitive).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ دَانِیَۃً  عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ظِلٰلُہَا وَ ذُلِّلَتۡ قُطُوۡفُہَا تَذۡلِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: They will be close to them (the fruit-laden branches and their shades). And the bunches of fruits will be hanging bent down."
    },
    {
      "id": 1160,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means such a bending in which another's right is violated (4 verses: 4:3-10:83-23:46-44:31)",
      "d": "« » means to oppress. To deviate from the straight path (from Munjid). « » is used for every such thing that overpowers a person and they are crushed under its burden (intransitive). This refers to such a bending in which someone's right is violated.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا فَوَاحِدَۃً اَوۡ مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ ؕ ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی اَلَّا تَعُوۡلُوۡا»\nTranslation: If you fear that you will not be able to treat all women equally, then one (woman) is sufficient, or a slave woman whom you own. This is so that you do not incline to one side (Uthmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1161,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means to bend and become close (13 verses: 2:282-4:3-5:108-6:99-30:3-33:51-33:59-53:8-53:9-55:54-69:23-73:20-76:14)",
      "d": "« » means to be near. To be close. And if its relation is towards some height, then it will mean to bend and become close.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ  جَنَا  الۡجَنَّتَیۡنِ  دَانٍ»\nTranslation: And the ripe fruits of both gardens will be bending (i.e., becoming close to the ground)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1162,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means to bend due to partisanship (1 verse: 2:182)",
      "d": "« » means to practice partisanship. To favor a side. The direction of bending towards one party.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَمَنۡ خَافَ مِنۡ مُّوۡصٍ جَنَفًا اَوۡ اِثۡمًا»\nTranslation: Then whoever fears from the testator any partisanship or injustice."
    },
    {
      "id": 1163,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکنا",
      "s": "« » means to incline towards childish, undignified movements due to childhood, to be inclined towards childlike actions (1 verse: 12:33)",
      "d": "«  ,  » means child, little boy, and its plural is «  » and « » comes meaning to be inclined towards childlike movements. And « » means to be inclined towards play (M. Q.). Thus, « » refers to such an inclination that is due to childhood.\nFor example, in the Quran it is, Joseph (peace be upon him) said:\n«وَ اِلَّا تَصۡرِفۡ عَنِّیۡ کَیۡدَہُنَّ اَصۡبُ  اِلَیۡہِنَّ»\nTranslation: (O Allah!) If You do not turn away from me their plot, I will incline towards them."
    }
  ],
  "247": [
    {
      "id": 1164,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکانا",
      "s": "« » is used for bending or lowering (4 verses: 15:88-17:24-26:215-56:3)",
      "d": "« » means to bend. To lower. And its opposite is « » meaning to raise, to elevate. « » is used in both literal and metaphorical senses. « » and « » are both names of Allah.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ»\nTranslation: And while treating them with love, bend yourself before them with humility."
    },
    {
      "id": 1165,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکانا",
      "s": "« » is used for lowering the gaze or reducing the voice (4 verses: 24:30-24:31-31:19-49:3)",
      "d": "« » is specific for lowering the gaze or reducing the voice (M. Q.).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«قُلۡ لِّلۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ یَغُضُّوۡا مِنۡ  اَبۡصَارِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: Tell the believing men to lower their gaze."
    },
    {
      "id": 1166,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "bending",
      "hw": "جھکانا",
      "s": "« » means to bend the body, specifically to bend the waist in the state of bowing (7 verses: 2:43-2:125-3:43-22:26-22:77-48:29-77:48)",
      "d": "« » means to bend the body, to lower the head. To bend the waist (intransitive). Metonymically, it means to perform prayer.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ  اِذَا قِیۡلَ لَہُمُ  ارۡکَعُوۡا  لَا  یَرۡکَعُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And when it is said to them, 'Bend (in prayer),' they do not bend."
    },
    {
      "id": 1167,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To Bow / Lower (the head)",
      "hw": "جھکانا",
      "s": "",
      "d": "«نَکَسَ رَأْسَہٗ» «تَنَکَّسَ الْعَلَم» «اِنْتَکَسَ» «نَکَسَ عَلٰی رَاْسِہٖ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  نُکِسُوۡا عَلٰی  رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ ۚ لَقَدۡ  عَلِمۡتَ مَا ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ  یَنۡطِقُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then they lowered their heads [in shame]. [Even after that, they said to Ibrahim], 'You surely know that these [idols] do not speak!'"
    }
  ],
  "248": [
    {
      "id": 1168,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "« » means to have a difference of opinion (1 verse: 4:65)",
      "d": "« » means to argue and disagree (intransitive). To discuss. To have differing opinions (from Munjid). To argue based on a difference of opinion while the parties agree on principles and the argument is of a subsidiary nature (minor issues, small matters).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَلَا وَ رَبِّکَ لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ حَتّٰی  یُحَکِّمُوۡکَ فِیۡمَا شَجَرَ  بَیۡنَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: So by your Lord, they will not believe until they make you a judge in what they dispute among themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1169,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "« » to engage in a tug-of-war over a difference of opinion (7 verses: 3:152-4:59-8:43-8:46-18:21-20:62-52:23)",
      "d": "«تَنَازَعَ» «نَزَع» «فَاِنۡ تَنَازَعۡتُمۡ فِیۡ شَیۡءٍ فَرُدُّوۡہُ اِلَی اللّٰہِ وَ الرَّسُوۡلِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1170,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "« » to argue on the basis of evidence (11 verses: 2:76-2:139-2:258-3:20-3:61-3:65-3:66-3:73-6:80-40:47-42:16)",
      "d": "«حَجَّ» «حُجَّۃٌ» «اِحْتَجَّ» «حَاجّ» «اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡ حَآجَّ اِبۡرٰہٖمَ فِیۡ رَبِّہٖۤ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1171,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "« » to try to gain superiority over another in conversation (26 verses: 4:107-4:109-6:25-6:121-7:71-8:6-11:32-11:74-13:13-16:111-16:125-18:54-18:56-22:3-22:8-22:68-29:46-31:20-40:4-40:5-40:35-40:56-40:69-42:35-43:58-58:1)",
      "d": "«جَدَلَ» «جَدَلَ» «یُجَادِلُوۡنَکَ فِی الۡحَقِّ بَعۡدَ مَا تَبَیَّنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1172,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "« » to argue about something in which there is hesitation to accept (5 verses: 18:22-42:18-53:12-53:55-54:36)",
      "d": "«مِرْیَۃ» «مَارَ» «مَا کَذَبَ الۡفُؤَادُ ی مَا  رَاٰی اَفَتُمٰرُوۡنَہٗ  عَلٰی مَا یَرٰی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1173,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "« » to argue with others on the basis of being a claimant to something (13 verses: 2:204-3:44-22:19-26:96-27:45-36:49-38:21-38:22-38:69-39:31-43:18-43:58-50:28)",
      "d": "«خَصْم» «اَخْصَمَ» «وَ ہَلۡ  اَتٰىکَ نَبَؤُا الۡخَصۡمِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1174,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "« » meaning severe quarrel (2 verses: 2:204-19:97)",
      "d": "«لَدّ» «شدّۃ الخصومۃ» «اَلَدّ» «وَ یُشۡہِدُ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی مَا فِیۡ  قَلۡبِہٖ  ۙ وَ ہُوَ  اَلَدُّ  الۡخِصَامِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1175,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "arguing",
      "hw": "جھگڑنا",
      "s": "« » to argue with each other for one's right due to ill-nature and stinginess (1 verse: 39:29)",
      "d": "«اَلشِّکْس» «تَشَاکَسَ» «شَکَسَ» «تَشَاکَسَ» «ضَرَبَ اللّٰہُ  مَثَلًا رَّجُلًا فِیۡہِ  شُرَکَآءُ مُتَشٰکِسُوۡنَ وَ رَجُلًا سَلَمًا  لِّرَجُلٍ ؕ ہَلۡ  یَسۡتَوِیٰنِ مَثَلًا»"
    }
  ],
  "249": [
    {
      "id": 1176,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "falsehood",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "« » lie, statement contrary to fact (36 verses: 3:75-3:78-3:94-4:50-5:41-5:42-5:70-5:103-6:21-6:24-6:93-6:144-7:37-7:89-10:60-10:69-11:18-12:18-12:110-16:105-16:116-18:5-18:15-20:61-23:38-29:68-34:8-39:32-39:60-42:24-53:11-56:2-58:14-61:7-72:5-78:35)",
      "d": "«کِذْب» «صِدْق» «وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ وَ ہُمۡ  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1177,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Falsehood / Lie",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "« » means something non-lasting and baseless; in a very broad sense, it includes   (lying). (25 verses: 2:42-2:188-3:71-3:191-4:29-4:161-7:139-8:8-9:34-11:16-13:17-16:72-17:81-18:56-21:18-22:62-29:52-29:67-31:30-34:49-38:27-40:5-41:42-42:24-47:3)",
      "d": "« » means something in which, after investigation, no strength or permanence is found. Unjust, baseless, useless, and frivolous talk. Its opposite is « », meaning truth, reality, and veracity. Thus, the word   is used in a wide sense, one meaning of which is   or lie.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ لِمَ تَلۡبِسُوۡنَ الۡحَقَّ بِالۡبَاطِلِ»\nTranslation: O People of the Scripture, why do you mix the truth with falsehood?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1178,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "falsehood",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "« » meaning lie against the truth and associating partners with Allah (5 verses: 18:17-22:30-25:4-25:72-58:2)",
      "d": "«زَوْرُ» «زُوْر» «زَاوَرَ» «قَوْلَ الزُّوْر» «قَوْلًا سَدِیْدًا» «قَوْلَ الزُّوْر» «زُوْر» «فَاجۡتَنِبُوا الرِّجۡسَ مِنَ الۡاَوۡثَانِ وَ اجۡتَنِبُوۡا  قَوۡلَ  الزُّوۡرِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1179,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Lie",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "« » means to fabricate something with malicious intent, and it is also related to slander. (12 verses: 7:117-24:11-24:12-25:4-26:45-29:17-34:43-37:151-46:11-46:22-46:28-51:9)",
      "d": "« » means to turn away from the correct direction with malice (singular). To make something into something else. Fabricating stories. Accusation. Slander. And this is the worst type of lie. According to the author of 'Furūq al-Lughawiyyah', this lie is related to the slander of heinous acts like adultery (Furūq 33).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«لَوۡ لَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ ظَنَّ الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتُ بِاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ خَیۡرًا ۙ وَّ قَالُوۡا ہٰذَاۤ اِفۡکٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ»\nTranslation: When you heard it, why did the believing men and women not think good of themselves and say, 'This is a clear scandal.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1180,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Telling or making a lie",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "« » means to speak a statement contrary to reality or to lie. (41 verses: 2:10-3:61-6:28-7:66-9:42-9:43-9:77-9:90-9:107-11:27-11:93-12:26-12:27-12:74-16:39-16:62-16:86-16:105-23:90-24:7-24:8-24:13-26:186-26:223-27:27-28:38-29:3-29:12-36:15-37:152-38:4-39:3-40:24-40:28-40:37-54:25-54:26-58:18-59:11-63:1-96:16)",
      "d": "« » means to deliberately give a report that is contrary to the facts.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ إِن كَانَ قَمِيصُهُ قُدَّ مِن دُبُرٍ فَكَذَبَتْ وَهُوَ مِنَ الصَّادِقِينَ»\nTranslation: And if his shirt is torn from the back, then she has lied and he is of the truthful."
    },
    {
      "id": 1181,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Telling or making a lie",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "« » means to slander someone. (2 verses: 26:222-45:7)",
      "d": "« » means to turn something away. To fabricate something with malice, as mentioned above. And this is the worst type of lie.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«هَلْ أُنَبِّئُكُمْ عَلَى مَنْ تَنَزَّلُ الشَّيَاطِينُ تَنَزَّلُ عَلَى كُلِّ أَفَّاكٍ أَثِيمٍ»\nTranslation: (Well) shall I tell you upon whom the devils descend? They descend upon every sinful liar."
    }
  ],
  "250": [
    {
      "id": 1184,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "To deny",
      "hw": "جھٹلانا",
      "s": "« » is used to prove something false through evidence, experience, and observations. (10 verses: 2:264-7:118-7:173-8:8-10:81-29:48-30:58-40:78-45:27-47:33)",
      "d": "« » means unjust and transient, and its opposite is « ». Just as truth has the meaning of truth, similarly « » also has the meaning of falsehood. And « » means to deny something or prove it false with circumstances and events.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«لِيُحِقَّ الْحَقَّ وَيُبْطِلَ الْبَاطِلَ وَلَوْ كَرِهَ الْمُجْرِمُونَ»\nTranslation: So that Allah may establish the truth and destroy the falsehood, even if the criminals dislike it."
    }
  ],
  "251": [
    {
      "id": 1185,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Key",
      "hw": "کنجی",
      "s": "« » is the plural of « », meaning keys. (2 verses: 39:63-42:12)",
      "d": "« » means to make iron pliable and to bend or twist something into a clasp. And « » or « » refers to a string of copper or brass used in a necklace. And « » means a necklace. « » is the iron key that is bent into a lock to open it. Its plurals are « » and « ». For example, the Quran says:\n«لَهُ مَقَالِيدُ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ يَبْسُطُ الرِّزْقَ لِمَنْ يَشَاءُ وَيَقْدِرُ»\nTranslation: To Him belong the keys of the heavens and the earth. He expands provision for whom He wills and restricts [for whom He wills]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1186,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Key",
      "hw": "کنجی",
      "s": "« » means keys, and it is also used in the sense of opening something or removing restrictions and complexities. (3 verses: 6:59-24:61-28:76)",
      "d": "« » means to open or to remove restrictions and complexities (mufrad). This word is used in various meanings: opening a door, opening a lock, opening a path for water to flow, deciding a case, and conquering a land. The plural of « » is « », which means keys and also water channels. (According to the lexicon) The plural of « » is « ». (According to the lexicon) This word is not used in the Quran. Thus, the word « » is more specific than « », as it pertains to removing and opening all kinds of restrictions and obstacles.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَعِنْدَهُ مَفَاتِيحُ الْغَيْبِ لَا يَعْلَمُهَا إِلَّا هُوَ»\nTranslation: And with Him are the keys of the unseen; none knows them except Him."
    }
  ],
  "252": [
    {
      "id": 1187,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Cloak",
      "hw": "چادر",
      "s": "« » means a shawl, dupatta, or veil. (1 verse: 24:31)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « », meaning a shawl, dupatta, or veil. (According to the lexicon) « » is a small cloak or dupatta with which one can cover the face and also cover the sides and chest.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَلْيَضْرِبْنَ بِخُمُرِهِنَّ عَلَى جُيُوبِهِنَّ»\nTranslation: And let them draw their shawls over their bosoms."
    },
    {
      "id": 1188,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Cloak",
      "hw": "چادر",
      "s": "« » means a cloak or shirt. (1 verse: 33:59)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « », meaning a cloak or shirt. And « » means to wear a cloak or shirt. (According to the lexicon) « » is actually a large cloak that can cover the entire body from head to toe.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا النَّبِيُّ قُل لِّأَزْوَاجِكَ وَبَنَاتِكَ وَنِسَاءِ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ يُدْنِينَ عَلَيْهِنَّ مِن جَلَابِيبِهِنَّ ۚ ذَٰلِكَ أَدْنَىٰ أَن يُعْرَفْنَ فَلَا يُؤْذَيْنَ»\nTranslation: O Prophet, tell your wives and your daughters and the women of the believers to bring down over themselves [part] of their outer garments. That is more suitable that they will be recognized and not be harmed."
    }
  ],
  "253": [
    {
      "id": 1189,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Fodder",
      "hw": "چارہ",
      "s": "« » is used for fresh fodder. (2 verses: 79:31-87:4)",
      "d": "« » means for livestock to graze on grass. The word « » also means pasture. And it also means fresh grass or fodder. (According to the lexicon)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَالَّذِي أَخْرَجَ الْمَرْعَى فَجَعَلَهُ غُثَاءً أَحْوَى»\nTranslation: And who has brought forth the pasture and made it dark stubble."
    },
    {
      "id": 1190,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Fodder",
      "hw": "چارہ",
      "s": "« » is fodder that is dry. (1 verse: 80:31)",
      "d": "« » is grass that is completely ready for animals to graze on and be cut (mufrad). According to the author of the lexicon, this word applies to all kinds of fodder, wet or dry, that is animal feed, such as chopped fodder, grass, hay, etc. Or fodder that can be stored. Just as « » (fruits) is for humans, « » is for livestock. « » means fruits, whether dry or fresh. Similarly, « » is used for dry and fresh fodder. (m. q.)\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَفَاكِهَةً وَأَبًّا مَتَاعًا لَّكُمْ وَلِأَنْعَامِكُمْ»\nTranslation: And [He produced] fruits and fodder as provision for you and for your livestock."
    },
    {
      "id": 1191,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "fodder",
      "hw": "چارہ",
      "s": "« » is that part of fodder which animals leave after grazing, i.e., leftover fodder (3 verses: 55:12-77:2-105:5)",
      "d": "«عَصْف» «عصف ماکول» «عَصَفَ» «عَاصِفَہ» «عَصْف» «فَجَعَلَہُمۡ کَعَصۡفٍ مَّاۡکُوۡلٍ»"
    }
  ],
  "254": [
    {
      "id": 1192,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "moon",
      "hw": "چاند",
      "s": "« » is the plural of « ». It refers only to the new moon or crescent-shaped moon, i.e., from the 26th day's moon up to the third (day's moon) (27 verses: 2:189-6:77-6:96-7:54-10:5-12:4-13:2-14:33-16:12-21:33-22:18-25:61-29:61-31:29-35:13-36:39-36:40-39:5-41:37-54:1-55:5-71:16-74:32-75:8-75:9-84:18-91:2)",
      "d": "«اَھِلَّۃ» «ھَلَال» «ھَلَال» «ھَلَّ» «اَھَلَّ» «یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡاَہِلَّۃِ  ؕ قُلۡ ہِیَ مَوَاقِیۡتُ لِلنَّاسِ وَ الۡحَجِّ»"
    }
  ],
  "255": [
    {
      "id": 1194,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Will / Desire (Divine Will)",
      "hw": "چاہنا",
      "s": "« » is a wish or intention that is subordinate to Allah's decree and does not occur before or after its appointed time. (190 verses: 2:20-2:70-2:90-2:105-2:142-2:212-2:213-2:220-2:247-2:251-2:253-2:255-2:261-2:269-2:272-2:284-3:6-3:13-3:26-3:27-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:73-3:74-3:129-3:179-4:48-4:49-4:90-4:116-4:133-5:17-5:18-5:40-5:48-5:54-5:64-6:35-6:39-6:41-6:80-6:83-6:88-6:107-6:111-6:112-6:128-6:133-6:137-6:138-6:148-6:149-7:89-7:100-7:128-7:155-7:156-7:188-8:31-9:15-9:27-9:28-10:16-10:25-10:49-10:99-10:107-11:33-11:87-11:107-11:108-11:118-12:56-12:76-12:99-12:100-12:110-13:13-13:26-13:27-13:31-13:39-14:4-14:11-14:19-14:27-16:2-16:9-16:31-16:35-16:93-17:18-17:30-17:54-18:24-18:29-18:39-18:69-21:9-22:5-22:18-23:24-24:21-24:35-24:38-24:43-24:45-24:46-25:10-25:16-25:45-25:57-26:4-27:87-28:27-28:56-28:68-28:82-29:21-29:62-30:5-30:37-30:48-30:54-33:24-33:51-34:9-34:13-34:36-34:39-35:1-35:8-35:16-35:22-36:43-36:47-36:66-36:67-37:102-39:4-39:23-39:34-39:52-39:68-39:74-40:15-41:14-42:8-42:12-42:13-42:19-42:22-42:27-42:29-42:33-42:49-42:50-42:51-42:52-43:20-43:60-47:4-47:30-48:14-48:25-48:27-50:35-53:26-56:65-56:70-57:21-57:29-59:6-62:4-73:19-74:31-74:37-74:55-74:56-76:29-76:30-76:31-78:39-80:12-80:22-81:28-81:29-82:8-87:7)",
      "d": "The root of « » is « », meaning 'a thing'. And « » is that which can be known and about which information can be given. Its plural is  . « » and « » are nouns meaning 'intention'. Originally, « » means the creation of something or obtaining it. But since Allah alone is the One who brings everything into existence and manages it, the term   is used only in the meaning of Divine Will.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَخۡلُقُ مَا یَشَآءُ ؕ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ اِنَاثًا وَّ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ الذُّکُوۡرَ»\nTranslation: He creates what He wills. He grants to whom He wills daughters and grants to whom He wills sons."
    },
    {
      "id": 1195,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Will / Desire (General Intention)",
      "hw": "چاہنا",
      "s": "« » is general, meaning a wish or intention that may or may not be subordinate to Divine Will and can occur before or after its appointed time. (94 verses: 2:26-2:108-2:185-2:228-2:233-2:253-3:108-3:152-3:176-4:26-4:27-4:28-4:35-4:44-4:60-4:88-4:91-4:134-4:144-4:150-5:1-5:6-5:17-5:29-5:37-5:49-5:91-5:113-6:52-7:110-8:7-8:62-8:67-8:71-9:32-9:46-9:55-9:85-10:107-11:15-11:34-11:79-11:88-11:107-12:25-13:11-14:10-17:18-17:19-17:103-18:28-18:77-18:82-20:63-21:70-22:14-22:16-22:22-23:24-25:62-26:35-28:5-28:19-28:27-28:79-28:83-30:38-30:39-32:20-33:13-33:17-33:33-33:50-34:43-35:10-36:82-37:86-37:98-38:6-39:4-39:38-40:31-42:20-48:11-48:15-51:57-52:42-61:8-72:10-74:31-74:52-75:5-76:9-85:16)",
      "d": "There is also a difference between Divine Will ( ) and Divine Intention ( ).   is an intention whose occurrence is necessary according to Allah's knowledge and decree.\n«مَا شَآءَ اللہُ کَانَ وَ مَا لَمْ یَشَآءُ لَمْ یَکُنْ»\nAnd for example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یُرِیۡدُ اللّٰہُ بِکُمُ الۡیُسۡرَ وَ لَا یُرِیۡدُ بِکُمُ الۡعُسۡرَ»\nTranslation: Allah intends for you ease and does not intend for you hardship.\nSimilarly, at another place, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ مَا اللّٰہُ یُرِیۡدُ ظُلۡمًا  لِّلۡعِبَادِ»\nTranslation: And Allah intends no injustice for [His] servants.\nEven though it is evident that hardship, constriction, and injustice are found among people. Because   necessitates these things. When the verb « » is attributed to a human, it refers to a wish or intention that is subordinate to Allah's decree.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ مَا تَشَآءُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّشَآءَ اللّٰہُ  رَبُّ الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And you do not will except what Allah wills, Lord of the worlds.\nWhereas a human's intention is free from this restriction; it can be against Divine Will. For example, a person wishes that death would not come to him. But such an occurrence is against Divine Will. Hence, it cannot happen.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ  لِیُطۡفِئُوۡا  نُوۡرَ اللّٰہِ  بِاَفۡوَاہِہِمۡ وَ اللّٰہُ  مُتِمُّ  نُوۡرِہٖ  وَ لَوۡ  کَرِہَ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: They desire to extinguish the light of Allah with their mouths, but Allah will perfect His light, even if the disbelievers dislike it.\nFurthermore, the clear difference between intention ( ) and Divine Will ( ) is that intention can occur before or after [its appointed time], but the time of Divine Will is fixed and cannot be before or after. (Fuqaha)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1196,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to desire",
      "hw": "چاہنا",
      "s": "« » means to desire desirable things, to crave natural inclinations (8 verses: 16:57-21:102-34:54-41:31-43:71-52:22-56:21-77:42)",
      "d": "«اِشْتَھٰی» «نَفَرَ» «وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَشۡتَہِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَدَّعُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1197,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to desire",
      "hw": "چاہنا",
      "s": "« » means to go beyond the limits of moderation in seeking something (79 verses: 2:90-2:187-2:198-2:207-2:213-2:265-2:272-3:7-3:19-3:83-3:85-3:99-4:24-4:34-4:94-4:104-4:114-4:139-5:2-5:35-5:50-6:35-6:114-6:146-6:164-7:33-7:45-7:86-7:140-9:47-9:48-10:23-10:90-11:19-12:65-13:17-13:22-14:3-16:14-16:90-17:12-17:28-17:42-17:57-17:66-17:110-18:64-18:108-22:60-23:7-24:33-28:55-28:73-28:76-28:77-29:17-30:23-30:46-33:51-35:12-38:22-38:24-42:14-42:27-42:39-42:42-45:12-45:17-48:29-49:9-55:20-57:27-59:8-60:1-62:10-66:1-70:31-73:20-92:20)",
      "d": "«بَغٰی» «قَالُوۡا  یٰۤاَبَانَا مَا نَبۡغِیۡ ؕ ہٰذِہٖ  بِضَاعَتُنَا رُدَّتۡ اِلَیۡنَا» «اِبْتَغٰی» «اِلَّا ابۡتِغَآءَ  وَجۡہِ  رَبِّہِ الۡاَعۡلٰی»"
    }
  ],
  "256": [
    {
      "id": 1199,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to become silent; to remain",
      "hw": "چپ",
      "s": "« » means to become silent while speaking (2 verses: 7:154-17:100)",
      "d": "«سَکَتَ» «وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ  مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1200,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Be Silent / Remain",
      "hw": "چپ",
      "s": "« » is used for a person of a silent nature or one who speaks little. (1 verse: 7:193)",
      "d": "« » means to remain silent, to be of a silent or taciturn nature.\n«مَنْ صَمَتَ نَجَا» «صَمَتَ» «نَطَقَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اَدَعَوۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ  اَمۡ  اَنۡتُمۡ  صَامِتُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: It is all the same for you whether you invite them or you are silent."
    },
    {
      "id": 1201,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to be silent; to remain",
      "hw": "چپ",
      "s": "« » means to listen silently to someone else's speech (2 verses: 7:204-46:29)",
      "d": "«نَصَتَ» «اَنْصَتَ» «وَ اِذَا قُرِئَ الۡقُرۡاٰنُ فَاسۡتَمِعُوۡا لَہٗ وَ اَنۡصِتُوۡا  لَعَلَّکُمۡ  تُرۡحَمُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "257": [
    {
      "id": 1202,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Lamp",
      "hw": "چراغ",
      "s": "« » is that which has a light that is white or bright. (3 verses: 24:35-41:12-67:5)",
      "d": "«صَبَحَ» «صَبَحَ الشَّعْر» «صَبَح الْحَدِیْد» «صَبِیْح» «صَبْحَان» «صَبَحَ» «مِصْبَاح»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«مَثَلُ نُوۡرِہٖ کَمِشۡکٰوۃٍ  فِیۡہَا مِصۡبَاحٌ»\nTranslation: The example of His light is like a niche within which is a lamp.\nThen the word « » is also used in the Noble Quran for bright stars.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ  زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ الدُّنۡیَا بِمَصَابِیۡحَ»\nTranslation: And We have certainly adorned the nearest heaven with lamps [i.e., stars]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1203,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Lamp",
      "hw": "چراغ",
      "s": "«Siraaj» is that which has a reddish light (4 verses: 25:61-33:46-71:16-78:13)",
      "d": "Ibn Faris says that the word «saraj» implies beauty, adornment, and elegance. And «siraaj» (lamp) is called «siraaj» because of its light and adornment. A horse's saddle is also called «saraj» because it is its adornment. It is said «sarraj wajhahu» meaning he adorned his face. «Sarraj sha'rahu» meaning he groomed or braided his hair. (M. L.)\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«تَبٰرَکَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ فِی السَّمَآءِ بُرُوۡجًا وَّ جَعَلَ فِیۡہَا سِرٰجًا وَّ قَمَرًا مُّنِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: (God) is the Most Blessed who has placed constellations in the heavens and made therein a lamp (the sun) and a luminous moon.\nThe lexical research presented above from Ibn al-Faris's Maqayis al-Lughah is not supported by the Quran; rather, the matter appears contrary to it. The Quran has called the sun «siraaj» (35/61) and «siraajan wa haajan» (78/13), even though its light is reddish, not white. Similarly, the Quran has called the stars «masabih», even though their light is white, not red. Therefore, the reality is that: «siraaj» is that which has reddish light, and «misbaah» is that which has white light. And Allah knows best!"
    }
  ],
  "258": [
    {
      "id": 1204,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Grazing",
      "hw": "چرانا",
      "s": "«Ra'aa» meaning to graze an animal and to protect and care for it (2 verses: 20:54-28:23)",
      "d": "«Ra'aa» meaning to graze an animal and to protect and care for it. And «ra'i» meaning herdsman. «Gadriya» (one who takes livestock to pastures and grazes them) is a service. And «mar'aa» meaning both pasture and grazing ground. (Muf) To save something from being wasted. And to remove external dangers. And its opposite is «ihmaal» meaning without a herdsman. (Faq l 15)\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ ارۡعَوۡا اَنۡعَامَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: Eat yourselves and graze your cattle.\nThe basic meaning of «ra'aa» is upbringing and care, so it can also be applied to humans. A king is a herdsman, and the public is the flock."
    },
    {
      "id": 1205,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Grazing",
      "hw": "چرانا",
      "s": "«Asama» meaning to take animals to graze (1 verse: 16:10)",
      "d": "The basic meanings of «sawama» are two: (1) to seek (2) to set out. Meaning to set out in search of something. «Samatu al-ibil» meaning the camels set out for grazing grounds. And «asama» meaning to go for grazing. (Muf)\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَّ مِنۡہُ شَجَرٌ فِیۡہِ تُسِیۡمُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And from it (the rain) are trees in which you graze your livestock."
    }
  ],
  "259": [
    {
      "id": 1206,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«'Araja» is used for ascending with pauses (5 verses: 15:14-32:5-34:2-57:4-70:4)",
      "d": "Two things are found in the meanings of «'araja»: inclination and height. (M. L.) «'Araja» meaning to walk with a limp, and «a'raj» is used for a limp person. And «'araja fi al-salam» meaning to ascend a ladder.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَوۡ فَتَحۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ بَابًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَظَلُّوۡا فِیۡہِ یَعۡرُجُوۡنَ لَقَالُوۡۤا اِنَّمَا سُکِّرَتۡ اَبۡصَارُنَا»\nTranslation: And even if We opened for them a gate from the heaven and they kept ascending therein, they would surely say, 'Our eyes are only dazzled.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1207,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Raqiya» is used for ascending according to one's capacity (1 verse: 17:93)",
      "d": "The meanings of «raqiya» include to blow away and to ascend to a height. In such a way that one expends effort according to one's capacity. To ascend gradually and gently. (Munjid) For example: «irqi 'ala zil'ika» meaning ascend according to your capacity. Do not burden your soul beyond its strength. (Munjid. Muf) And as in: «raqaytu fi al-'ilmi wa al-sharaf» I have progressed in knowledge and honor. (Faq l 152) So its usage is general.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اَوۡ تَرۡقٰی فِی السَّمَآءِ ؕ وَ لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لِرُقِیِّکَ حَتّٰی تُنَزِّلَ عَلَیۡنَا کِتٰبًا نَّقۡرَؤُہٗ»\nTranslation: Or you ascend into the sky, and we will not believe in your ascension until you bring down to us a book that we can read."
    },
    {
      "id": 1208,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Sa'ada» is used for ascending with difficulty (4 verses: 3:153-6:125-35:10-72:17)",
      "d": "Two basic things are found in the meaning of «sa'ada»: (1) height (2) difficulty. (M. L.) Meaning to ascend to a high place with difficulty. And «su'ud» means heights and valleys. And the difficult path ascending them is also called that. (Munjid) Something rising with difficulty, like smoke rising. And «mus'ad al-khar ba'iyah» means elevator. (Muf) And «as'ada» and «sa''ada» mean to ascend with time and difficulty.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«یَجۡعَلۡ صَدۡرَہٗ ضَیِّقًا حَرَجًا کَاَنَّمَا یَصَّعَّدُ فِی السَّمَآءِ»\nTranslation: He makes his breast narrow and constricted, as if he is ascending into the sky.\nNote: The opposite of the three words «'araja», «raqiya», and «sa'ada» is «nazala»."
    },
    {
      "id": 1209,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Zahara» is used for ascending to the top (27 verses: 2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "«Zahara» meaning to become apparent, to prevail, to ascend, and to ascend to the top, whether there are steps or not, even if climbing without steps.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَمَا اسۡطَاعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّظۡہَرُوۡہُ وَ مَا اسۡتَطَاعُوۡا لَہٗ نَقۡبًا»\nTranslation: Then they were not able to ascend it, nor were they able to bore through it.\nAt another place, the command of God is:\n«لِبُیُوۡتِہِمۡ سُقُفًا مِّنۡ فِضَّۃٍ وَّ مَعَارِجَ عَلَیۡہَا یَظۡہَرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: We will make their roofs of silver and stairs upon which they will ascend."
    },
    {
      "id": 1210,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Rahaqa» is used for one thing climbing over another and covering it (9 verses: 10:26-10:27-18:73-68:43-70:44-72:6-72:13-74:17-80:41)",
      "d": "«Rahaqa» meaning one thing climbing over another and covering it (there is an element of necessity in it). «Rahhaqahu al-amr» meaning the matter overwhelmed him with force and domination. (Muf) i.e., covered him. (M. L.)\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ وُجُوۡہٌ یَّوۡمَئِذٍ عَلَیۡہَا غَبَرَۃٌ تَرۡہَقُہَا قَتَرَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And faces on that day will have dust over them, and darkness will cover them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1211,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Ascending (upwards)",
      "hw": "چڑھنا",
      "s": "«Tasawwara» is used for climbing over a wall or jumping over it (1 verse: 38:21)",
      "d": "«Sawr» meaning a fortified city or a high wall that cannot be jumped over to enter. (M. L.) And «sara» meaning to climb a wall or jump over it, to leap. And «tasawwara» means to climb over a wall and jump over it, and also to wear a bracelet. «Siwar, sawar» plural «asawira» and «aswara» is derived from it meaning bracelet. (Nukila)\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ ہَلۡ اَتٰىکَ نَبَؤُا الۡخَصۡمِ ۘ اِذۡ تَسَوَّرُوا الۡمِحۡرَابَ»\nTranslation: Has there come to you the news of the disputants when they climbed over the wall of the prayer chamber?"
    }
  ],
  "260": [
    {
      "id": 1212,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "«'Ayn» a spring of flowing water (63 verses: 2:60-3:13-5:45-5:83-7:116-7:160-7:179-7:195-8:44-9:92-11:31-11:37-12:84-15:45-15:88-18:28-18:86-18:101-19:26-20:39-20:40-20:131-21:61-23:27-23:50-25:74-26:57-26:134-26:147-26:34-28:9-28:13-32:17-33:19-33:51-34:12-36:66-37:45-37:48-40:19-43:71-44:25-44:52-44:54-51:15-52:20-52:48-54:12-54:14-54:37-55:50-55:66-56:18-56:22-67:30-76:6-76:18-77:41-83:28-88:5-88:12-90:8-102:7)",
      "d": "«'Ayn» means an eye, and its plural in the Quran is «a'yun». Then, because water flows from the eye, the mouth of a waterskin is also called «'ayn». Similarly, the spring from which water flows is also called «'ayn». (Muf) And its plural in the Quran is «'uyun».\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا الۡاَرۡضَ عُیُوۡنًا فَالۡتَقَی الۡمَآءُ عَلٰۤی اَمۡرٍ قَدۡ قُدِرَ»\nTranslation: And We caused the earth to burst with springs, so the water met for a matter that was predestined.\nAnd «'ayn» can also refer to a lake or a river."
    },
    {
      "id": 1213,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring / Fountain",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "« » is a spring of water that gushes forth from the earth. (1 verse: 17:90)",
      "d": "« » means for water to gush forth from a spring. And « » is the place from where water gushes forth. And « » is a spring from which water flows abundantly. (Muf) Its plural is  .\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰۤی تَفۡجُرَ  لَنَا مِنَ  الۡاَرۡضِ  یَنۡۢبُوۡعًا»\nTranslation: And they said, 'We will not believe you until you cause a spring to gush forth for us from the earth.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1214,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Spring / Fountain",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "« » is a flowing spring that takes the form of a small river. (1 verse: 19:24)",
      "d": "« » means a small river, a flowing river. (F L 261 Munjid) Its plural is   and  . And « » also refers to a small army or military unit, whose plural is  . And « » means a small army that moves at night. (Munjid) Thus, the concept of smallness is inherent in it. (Munjid)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَدۡ جَعَلَ  رَبُّکِ  تَحۡتَکِ  سَرِیًّا»\nTranslation: [Allah said], 'And shake the trunk of the palm tree toward you, and it will drop upon you fresh ripe dates. So eat and drink and be contented.' (Note: The verse refers to a stream being made to flow beneath her)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1215,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Gushing and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "« » means for water to gush up while boiling. (4 verses: 3:125-11:40-23:27-67:7)",
      "d": "«فَارَ» «فَوْر» «فَارَ الْقِدْر» «فَارَ الْمَاء» «فَارَ الْعِرْق» «فَارَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَ اَمۡرُنَا وَ فَارَ التَّنُّوۡرُ»\nTranslation: Until, when Our command came and the oven overflowed [with water]."
    },
    {
      "id": 1216,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "The Bursting and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "« » means water gushing out and falling down (1 Verse: 56:66)",
      "d": "«نَضَخَ» «اِنْضَخَ» «نَضَّاخ» «مِنْضَخَة» «فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ نَضَّاخَتٰنِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1217,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "The Bursting and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "« » means water gushing out from a spring when the exit point is narrow (1 Verse: 7:160)",
      "d": "«اَنْبَجَسَ» «اَنْبَجَسَ» «وَ  اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ  اِلٰی مُوۡسٰۤی  اِذِ  اسۡتَسۡقٰىہُ قَوۡمُہٗۤ  اَنِ اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ ۚ فَانۡۢبَجَسَتۡ مِنۡہُ اثۡنَتَا عَشۡرَۃَ عَیۡنًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1218,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "The Bursting and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "« » means water gushing out from a spring when the exit point becomes wide (9 Verses: 2:60, 2:74, 17:90, 17:91, 18:33, 36:34, 54:12, 76:6, 82:3)",
      "d": "«اِنْفَجَرَ» «اِنْبَجَسَ» «اِنْفَجَرَ» «وَ اِذِ اسۡتَسۡقٰی مُوۡسٰی لِقَوۡمِہٖ فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ  ؕ فَانۡفَجَرَتۡ مِنۡہُ اثۡنَتَاعَشۡرَۃَ عَیۡنًا» «اِنْبَجَسَ» «اِنْفَجَرَ» «اِنْبَجَسَ» «اِنْفَجَرَ» «وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا الۡاَرۡضَ عُیُوۡنًا فَالۡتَقَی الۡمَآءُ عَلٰۤی  اَمۡرٍ  قَدۡ  قُدِرَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1219,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "The Bursting and Flowing of a Spring",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "« » involves the concept of only water or a liquid flowing (3 Verses: 13:17, 34:12, 34:16)",
      "d": "«سَالَ» «اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ  مَآءً  فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا» «وَ اَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ  عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ» «سَیْل» «سَیْل» «سَیْل» «فَاَعۡرَضُوۡا فَاَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَیۡلَ الۡعَرِمِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1220,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Flowing",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "« » means water or any other thing moving continuously at a moderate pace, for a long time or over a long distance (57 Verses: 2:25, 2:164, 2:266, 3:15, 3:136, 3:195, 3:198, 4:13, 4:57, 4:122, 5:12, 5:85, 5:119, 6:6, 7:43, 9:72, 9:89, 9:100, 10:9, 10:22, 11:42, 13:2, 13:35, 14:23, 14:32, 16:31, 18:31, 20:76, 21:81, 22:14, 22:23, 22:65, 25:10, 29:58, 30:46, 31:29, 31:31, 35:13, 36:38, 38:36, 39:5, 39:20, 43:51, 45:12, 47:12, 48:5, 48:17, 54:14, 55:50, 57:12, 58:22, 61:12, 64:9, 65:11, 66:8, 85:11, 98:8)",
      "d": "«جَرٰی» «فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ  تَجۡرِیٰنِ» «لَہُمۡ جَنّٰتٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» «جَرٰی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1221,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Flowing",
      "hw": "چشمہ",
      "s": "« » means water or any other thing begins to flow due to sheer abundance and excess (OVER FLOW) (6 Verses: 2:199, 5:83, 7:50, 9:92, 10:61, 46:8)",
      "d": "«فَیْض» «فَاضَ السَّیْلُ» «اَفَاضَ الْاِنَاء» «تَرٰۤی اَعۡیُنَہُمۡ تَفِیۡضُ مِنَ  الدَّمۡعِ مِمَّا عَرَفُوۡا مِنَ الۡحَقِّ» «ثُمَّ  اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ» «اَفَاضَ» «اِذۡ تُفِیۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ»"
    }
  ],
  "261": [
    {
      "id": 1222,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » means to walk at a normal pace. It is the general word for walking (20 Verses: 2:20, 6:122, 7:195, 17:37, 17:95, 20:40, 20:128, 24:45, 25:7, 25:20, 25:63, 28:25, 31:18, 31:19, 32:26, 38:6, 57:28, 67:15, 67:22, 68:11)",
      "d": "«مَشٰی» «وَ قَالُوۡا مَالِ ہٰذَا الرَّسُوۡلِ یَاۡکُلُ الطَّعَامَ وَ یَمۡشِیۡ  فِی الۡاَسۡوَاقِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1223,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » means to walk with a slightly lighter gait than « » (18 Verses: 2:164, 6:38, 8:22, 8:55, 11:6, 11:56, 16:49, 16:61, 22:18, 24:45, 27:82, 29:60, 31:10, 34:14, 35:28, 35:45, 42:29, 45:4)",
      "d": "«دَبّ» «مَشٰی» «دَابَّۃ» «وَ مَا مِنۡ دَآبَّۃٍ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ  اِلَّا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  رِزۡقُہَا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1224,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » meaning to set off, to start walking (9 verses: 18:71, 18:74, 18:77, 26:13, 38:6, 48:15, 68:23, 77:29, 77:30)",
      "d": "«طَلَقَ» «اِنطَلَق» «فَانۡطَلَقَا  ٝ حَتّٰۤی اِذَا رَکِبَا فِی السَّفِیۡنَۃِ» «وَ لَا یَنۡطَلِقُ لِسَانِیۡ فَاَرۡسِلۡ  اِلٰی ہٰرُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1225,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » meaning to walk along a path (12 verses: 15:12, 16:69, 20:53, 23:27, 26:200, 28:32, 39:21, 69:32, 71:20, 72:17, 72:27, 74:42)",
      "d": "«سَلَک» «ثُمَّ  کُلِیۡ مِنۡ کُلِّ الثَّمَرٰتِ فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» «نُفُوذَ الشَّیْء» «اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِ سُوۡٓءٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1226,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » meaning to go down into a hollow, to descend into a ditch (1 verse: 18:61)",
      "d": "«سَرَب» «سَرْب» «اِنْسَرَبَتِ الْحَیَّۃُ اِلٰی جُحْرِھَا» «فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِیۡلَہٗ  فِی الۡبَحۡرِ  سَرَبًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1229,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » meaning the passing of time or walking with time (5 verses: 8:38, 15:65, 18:60, 36:67, 43:8)",
      "d": "«مَضٰی» «مَضٰی» «مَضٰی مَا مَضٰی» «فَاَہۡلَکۡنَاۤ  اَشَدَّ مِنۡہُمۡ بَطۡشًا وَّ مَضٰی مَثَلُ  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» «حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ اَوۡ اَمۡضِیَ حُقُبًا» «مَضٰی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1231,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » meaning to walk around, to travel (3 verses: 12:19, 13:10, 28:29)",
      "d": "«سَارَ» «سَائِر» «سَیَّارَۃ» «فَلَمَّا قَضٰی مُوۡسَی الۡاَجَلَ وَ سَارَ بِاَہۡلِہٖۤ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1233,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » meaning to walk on foot when some are also mounted (3 verses: 2:239, 17:64, 22:27)",
      "d": "«رَجِلَ» «یَاۡتُوۡکَ  رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ » «فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ فَرِجَالًا اَوۡ رُکۡبَانًا» «مَشٰی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1234,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cause to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » meaning to drive, to make walk by driving from behind (4 verses: 8:6, 19:86, 32:27, 75:30)",
      "d": "«سَاقَ» «سَوَّاق» «وَّ نَسُوۡقُ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ اِلٰی جَہَنَّمَ وِرۡدًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1236,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cause to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » meaning to drive slowly (2 verses: 17:66, 24:43)",
      "d": "«اَزْجٰی» «مُزَجّٰی» «اَلَمۡ  تَرَ  اَنَّ اللّٰہَ یُزۡجِیۡ سَحَابًا ثُمَّ  یُؤَلِّفُ بَیۡنَہٗ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1237,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cause to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » meaning to make walk on a path or to pave a way (12 verses: 15:12, 16:69, 20:53, 23:27, 26:200, 28:32, 39:21, 69:32, 71:20, 72:17, 72:27, 74:42)",
      "d": "«سَلَک» «الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ مَہۡدًا وَّ سَلَکَ  لَکُمۡ  فِیۡہَا سُبُلًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1238,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cause to walk",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » to cause to walk, to lead (19 verses: 6:11-10:22-12:109-13:31-16:36-18:47-22:46-27:69-29:20-30:9-30:42-34:18-35:44-40:21-40:82-47:10-52:10-78:20-81:3)",
      "d": "« » means to walk, to roam, to travel. And « » means to cause to walk, to cause to travel, to send on a journey.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یُسَیِّرُکُمۡ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ»\nTranslation: He it is who causes you to travel on land and sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 1239,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to travel by night",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » to travel by night, to cause to travel by night (6 verses: 11:81-15:65-17:1-20:77-26:52-44:23)",
      "d": "« ,  » means to travel by night. And « » means to cause to travel by night, to cause to travel, to send on a journey.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاَسۡرِ  بِاَہۡلِکَ بِقِطۡعٍ مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ»\nTranslation: So travel by night with your family in a part of the night.\nAt another place, the Lord says:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا»\nTranslation: Glorified is He who took His servant by night."
    }
  ],
  "262": [
    {
      "id": 1240,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "« » to shout loudly (1 verse: 2:171)",
      "d": "« » means to call out loudly, to shout. The crow cawing loudly, the shepherd calling the flock from afar. (f l 194)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ مَثَلُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا کَمَثَلِ الَّذِیۡ یَنۡعِقُ بِمَا لَا یَسۡمَعُ اِلَّا دُعَآءً  وَّ  نِدَآءً»\nTranslation: And the example of those who disbelieve is like that of one who shouts to that which hears no more than a call and a shout."
    },
    {
      "id": 1241,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "« » to make noise indiscriminately (2 verses: 15:94-43:57)",
      "d": "« » means to make noise indiscriminately, to shout, to clamor. And « » means to clap (source: manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَمَّا ضُرِبَ ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ  مَثَلًا  اِذَا قَوۡمُکَ مِنۡہُ  یَصِدُّوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And when the son of Mary is presented as an example, your people laugh at it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1242,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "« » to groan loudly due to distress (3 verses: 16:53-23:64-23:65)",
      "d": "« » means to groan loudly, to wail (source: manjad). To make a loud sound when distressed, like wild animals such as deer. (muf)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَاۤ  اَخَذۡنَا مُتۡرَفِیۡہِمۡ بِالۡعَذَابِ اِذَا ہُمۡ  یَجۡئَرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Until when We seize their affluent ones with punishment, at that they cry out (or groan)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1243,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "« » to cry for help and shout (2 verses: 14:22-28:18)",
      "d": "« » means to scream and shout so that others may come to help, to cry out. And « » means to hear someone's cry and come to their aid. And « » means to call for help by shouting in front of those present.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاِذَا  الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ  بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ»\nTranslation: Then the one who had sought help from him the day before is now crying out to him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1244,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk; to scream",
      "hw": "چیخنا",
      "s": "« » to scream (1 verse: 51:29)",
      "d": "«صَرَ الرَّجُل» «صَرَّۃ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاَقۡبَلَتِ امۡرَاَتُہٖ  فِیۡ صَرَّۃٍ  فَصَکَّتۡ وَجۡہَہَا وَ قَالَتۡ عَجُوۡزٌ  عَقِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: So his wife came forward, crying out, and she struck her face and said, 'What! An old woman, and barren!'"
    }
  ],
  "263": [
    {
      "id": 1245,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cling",
      "hw": "چمٹنا",
      "s": "« » to cling to someone and urge them to do something (1 verse: 2:273)",
      "d": "«لِحَاف» «اَلْحَفْتُہٗ فَالْتَحَفَ» «اِلْحَاف»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«تَعۡرِفُہُمۡ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ ۚ لَا یَسۡئَلُوۡنَ النَّاسَ اِلۡحَافًا»\nTranslation: You will know them by their mark; they do not ask people importunately."
    },
    {
      "id": 1246,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cling",
      "hw": "چمٹنا",
      "s": "« » to stick or cling due to being sticky or viscous (1 verse: 37:11)",
      "d": "« » refers to something that becomes firmly attached and clings (source: maf). And according to scholars of language, « » means sticky and viscous mud (source: f l 268). In the Quran, this word is used only for mud. Thus, both meanings are supported.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُمۡ مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ لَّازِبٍ»\nTranslation: Indeed, We created them from sticky mud."
    },
    {
      "id": 1247,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to cling",
      "hw": "چمٹنا",
      "s": "« » for one thing to adhere to another for a long time (2 verses: 20:129-25:77)",
      "d": "« » implies both fixation and duration. i.e., for something to remain fixed or attached in one place for a long time (source: maf). According to this meaning, this word is translated into different words in Urdu at different contexts.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا کَلِمَۃٌ سَبَقَتۡ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ لَکَانَ لِزَامًا  وَّ  اَجَلٌ  مُّسَمًّی»\nTranslation: And if not for a word that preceded from your Lord, it would have been an obligation [to punish them immediately] and a specified time."
    }
  ],
  "264": [
    {
      "id": 1248,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Shining",
      "hw": "چمک",
      "s": "« » means the glittering or shining of stars, planets, moon, and sun at the time of rising. (2 verses: 6:77-6:78)",
      "d": "«بَزَغَ» «نُجُوْمٌ بَوَازِغٌ»\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَ الشَّمۡسَ بَازِغَۃً  قَالَ ہٰذَا رَبِّیۡ»\nTranslation: Then when he saw the sun rising, he said, 'This is my Lord.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1249,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Shining",
      "hw": "چمک",
      "s": "« » means light falling on something and spreading, and illuminating it. (2 verses: 38:18-39:69)",
      "d": "« » means the opening or spreading of light (root). And « » means to illuminate something. To cast full light on it so that it shines. (lex.)\n«وَ اَشۡرَقَتِ  الۡاَرۡضُ بِنُوۡرِ رَبِّہَا»\nTranslation: And the earth shone with the light of its Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 1250,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Shining",
      "hw": "چمک",
      "s": "« » means the piercing passage of red and intense light. (2 verses: 37:10-86:3)",
      "d": "« » means the blazing of fire. The shining of a star. And « » means being like fire in redness, i.e., fiery. (dict.) The meaning is the complete penetration and passage of light. (lex.) « » means to pierce through something, and « » means so bright that its rays pierce through whatever they fall on. (lex.) Thus, « » conveys the idea of intensity and fiery red light.\n«اِلَّا مَنۡ خَطِفَ الۡخَطۡفَۃَ فَاَتۡبَعَہٗ شِہَابٌ  ثَاقِبٌ»\nTranslation: But whoever snatches away the snatch, a blazing flame will follow him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1251,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Shining",
      "hw": "چمک",
      "s": "« » is the light that dazzles the eyes. (1 verse: 24:43)",
      "d": "« » means (the flash of lightning) that dazzles. The light that dazzles the eyes. (dict.)\n«یَکَادُ سَنَا بَرۡقِہٖ یَذۡہَبُ بِالۡاَبۡصَارِ»\nTranslation: The flash of its lightning almost takes away the sight."
    }
  ],
  "265": [
    {
      "id": 1253,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Few",
      "hw": "چند",
      "s": "« » means few in count, opposite of many. (7 verses: 2:80-2:184-2:203-3:24-11:8-11:104-12:20)",
      "d": "« » means few in number, one, or little. Opposite of many. Just as hundreds are few compared to thousands. (lex.)\n«وَ شَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ»\nTranslation: And they sold him for a small price, a few coins."
    },
    {
      "id": 1254,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Few",
      "hw": "چند",
      "s": "« » is used for numbers from 3 to 9 only. (2 verses: 12:42-30:4)",
      "d": "« » can be said for each number from three to ten (f l 76. lex.) Only the odd numbers from 3 to 9 are « ». (lex.)\n«وَ ہُمۡ مِّنۡۢ  بَعۡدِ غَلَبِہِمۡ سَیَغۡلِبُوۡنَ فِیۡ بِضۡعِ سِنِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And they will soon prevail after their defeat, in a few years."
    },
    {
      "id": 1255,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Few",
      "hw": "چند",
      "s": "« » means a group of three to ten individuals. It is used for rational beings. (3 verses: 18:34-46:29-72:1)",
      "d": "«اَلنَّفَرُ» «ثَلَاثَۃُ نَفَرٍ اَوْ اَنْفَازٍ»\n«قُلۡ  اُوۡحِیَ  اِلَیَّ  اَنَّہُ  اسۡتَمَعَ  نَفَرٌ مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ فَقَالُوۡۤا  اِنَّا سَمِعۡنَا قُرۡاٰنًا عَجَبًا»\nTranslation: Say, 'It has been revealed to me that a group of jinn listened and said, 'Indeed, we have heard a wonderful Quran.'"
    }
  ],
  "266": [
    {
      "id": 1256,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Choosing",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "« » means to choose a better thing from many things. (2 verses: 7:155-28:68)",
      "d": "« » means every thing or matter that is desirable to all. (lex.) And « » means to choose a better thing from many things of the same kind. (lex.)\n«وَ اخۡتَارَ مُوۡسٰی قَوۡمَہٗ سَبۡعِیۡنَ رَجُلًا لِّمِیۡقَاتِنَا»\nTranslation: And Moses chose seventy men from his people for Our appointment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1257,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Choosing",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "« » means to choose something based on its purity and cleanliness. (12 verses: 2:130-2:132-2:247-3:33-3:42-7:144-22:75-27:59-35:32-37:153-38:47-39:4)",
      "d": "« » and « » mean pure and clean. (lex.) « » and « » mean a sincere friend. (dict.) And « » means to choose something based on purity and cleanliness of the soul.\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ اصۡطَفٰۤی اٰدَمَ وَ نُوۡحًا وَّ اٰلَ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ  وَ اٰلَ عِمۡرٰنَ عَلَی الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah chose Adam, Noah, the family of Abraham, and the family of Imran over the worlds."
    },
    {
      "id": 1258,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Choosing",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "« » means to choose someone and make them one's close confidant. (10 verses: 3:179-6:87-7:203-12:6-16:121-19:58-20:122-22:78-42:13-68:50)",
      "d": "«جَبُو» «یُجْمَعُ وَ یُحْمَلْ» «جَمْعُ الشَّیءُ وَالْتَجَمَّعُ» «جَبُو» «مُجْبٰی»\n«یُّجۡبٰۤی  اِلَیۡہِ  ثَمَرٰتُ  کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ»\nTranslation: Meaning, in Mecca, the fruits of all things are drawn and brought. (Ottoman) or delivered. (Jalandhri)\nAnd « » means to choose a noble thing and bring it close, to make it a confidant and chosen one.\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ یَجۡتَبِیۡکَ رَبُّکَ وَ یُعَلِّمُکَ مِنۡ تَاۡوِیۡلِ الۡاَحَادِیۡثِ»\nTranslation: And thus your Lord will choose you and teach you the interpretation of events."
    },
    {
      "id": 1259,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Selecting",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "« » means to choose someone for a specific purpose.",
      "d": "« » means to be pure, free from mixture and impurity. « » means to make pure (cf. manjad), and its opposite is « ». Therefore, « » means to choose someone and designate them exclusively for oneself.\n«وَ قَالَ الۡمَلِکُ ائۡتُوۡنِیۡ بِہٖۤ  اَسۡتَخۡلِصۡہُ لِنَفۡسِیۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1260,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Selecting",
      "hw": "چن",
      "s": "« » means to choose someone for a specific purpose and train them in a suitable manner.",
      "d": "« » means to make something with technical skill. And « » means to choose a suitable person for a specific purpose and train them specially.\n«وَ اصۡطَنَعۡتُکَ  لِنَفۡسِیۡ»"
    }
  ],
  "267": [
    {
      "id": 1261,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Animals",
      "hw": "چوپائے",
      "s": "« » means wild animals, beasts.",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». And « » is the opposite of « », meaning creatures that are not familiar with humans. Wild animals and beasts, etc. (mufradat)\n«وَ  اِذَا  الۡوُحُوۡشُ حُشِرَتۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1262,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Animals",
      "hw": "چوپائے",
      "s": "« » means cattle excluding wild animals; generally used for sheep and cows.",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». It applies to all types of cattle except wild ones (mufradat), whether land or sea animals (manjad). However, it is mostly used for sheep and cows (manjad). « » refers to a lamb (mufradat), and one definition of « » is cattle (excluding predators) that lack the power of speech (manjad). Also, « » means a difficult task, and « » means mute (manjad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1263,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Animals",
      "hw": "چوپائے",
      "s": "« » means cattle, generally used for camels.",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». Although this word can apply to all animals except predators, it is mostly used for camels (fala 134) because for Arabs, there was no greater blessing than a camel. In the Quran, the word 'an'am' also appears in singular form.\n«مَّتَاعًا  لَّکُمۡ  وَ لِاَنۡعَامِکُمۡ»\n«کُلُوۡا وَ ارۡعَوۡا اَنۡعَامَکُمۡ»\nBut the word « » (in singular form) often comes with the word 'an'am'.\n«مِّنۡۢ بَہِیۡمَۃِ  الۡاَنۡعَامِ ۚ فَکُلُوۡا مِنۡہَا وَ اَطۡعِمُوا  الۡبَآئِسَ  الۡفَقِیۡرَ»\n«اُحِلَّتۡ لَکُمۡ بَہِیۡمَۃُ  الۡاَنۡعَامِ  اِلَّا مَا یُتۡلٰی عَلَیۡکُمۡ»"
    }
  ],
  "268": [
    {
      "id": 1265,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "« » means cut, dry grass; dry fragments of all kinds of plants. Hay (2 verses: 18:45-54:31)",
      "d": "« » means to cut. And « » refers to cut, dry grass (manjad), and by it is meant the fragments, debris, and chaff of all kinds of plants.\n«اِنَّاۤ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ صَیۡحَۃً  وَّاحِدَۃً فَکَانُوۡا کَہَشِیۡمِ  الۡمُحۡتَظِرِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1266,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "« » means dry plants; fragments made by grinding and crushing (6 verses: 27:18-39:21-56:65-57:20-104:4-104:5)",
      "d": "« » means to break, to shatter. And « » refers to a violent, fierce wind that breaks and shatters everything. And « » means something broken, shattered, or reduced to fragments (manjad). This word is also used for something ground and reduced to dust (mufradat).\n«ثُمَّ یُخۡرِجُ بِہٖ زَرۡعًا مُّخۡتَلِفًا  اَلۡوَانُہٗ  ثُمَّ یَہِیۡجُ  فَتَرٰىہُ مُصۡفَرًّا ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ  حُطَامًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1267,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "« » means debris, rubbish, trash (2 verses: 23:41-87:5)",
      "d": "«غُثَآء» «غَثِیَ الْکَلَام» «غُثَآء»\n«وَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَخۡرَجَ  الۡمَرۡعٰی فَجَعَلَہٗ  غُثَآءً  اَحۡوٰی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1268,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "« » means dust, flying particles of everything (2 verses: 25:23-56:6)",
      "d": "« » means dust that is blown by the wind; flying dust (fala 253), fine particles of soil spread in the air. And « » refers to whirlwinds of dust (manjad).\n«وَ قَدِمۡنَاۤ اِلٰی مَا عَمِلُوۡا مِنۡ عَمَلٍ فَجَعَلۡنٰہُ  ہَبَآءً  مَّنۡثُوۡرًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1269,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Scattered Fragments",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "« » means to become scattered fragments due to decay (2 verses: 17:49-17:98)",
      "d": "« » means to break and crush (manjad). And « » means crushed, pulverized; decayed (manjad). This word is used for something that becomes scattered fragments due to decay.\n«وَ قَالُوۡۤاءَ اِذَا کُنَّا عِظَامًا  وَّ  رُفَاتًاءَ اِنَّا  لَمَبۡعُوۡثُوۡنَ  خَلۡقًا جَدِیۡدًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1270,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Crushed to Pieces or Fragmented",
      "hw": "ریزہ",
      "s": "« » means for stones or something to be crushed to pieces (1 Verse: 56:5)",
      "d": "« » means for stones to be crushed to fragments (mufrad). According to the author of Mu‘jam Maqayis al-Lughah, its two basic meanings are: (1) to crush something and (2) to mix it with something else. Both meanings are supported in the Noble Quran.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَّ  بُسَّتِ الۡجِبَالُ  بَسًّا فَکَانَتۡ ہَبَآءً  مُّنۡۢبَثًّا»\nTranslation: And the mountains will be crushed to pieces, so they will become dust scattered about."
    }
  ],
  "269": [
    {
      "id": 1272,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Steal",
      "hw": "چوری",
      "s": "« » is the general term for stealing (6 Verses: 5:38-12:70-12:73-12:77-12:81-60:12)",
      "d": "« » is a well-known word meaning to secretly take someone else's owned property from a secure place.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ السَّارِقُ وَ السَّارِقَۃُ فَاقۡطَعُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیَہُمَا»\nTranslation: Cut off the hands of the male thief and the female thief.\n«اِسْتَرَق» «اِسْتَرَقُ السَّمْع»\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«اِلَّا مَنِ اسۡتَرَقَ السَّمۡعَ فَاَتۡبَعَہٗ شِہَابٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ»\nTranslation: But whoever seeks to eavesdrop, a clear flame will pursue him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1273,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Steal",
      "hw": "چوری",
      "s": "« » is a blended form of theft and betrayal (1 Verse: 3:161)",
      "d": "« » means to secretly take something and keep it in one's belongings (manjad, Mu‘jam). This is essentially a blend of theft and betrayal. Therefore, this word can be translated as both 'to steal' and 'to betray'. For example, taking something from shared war spoils that does not fulfill the conditions of lawful acquisition, etc.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّغۡلُلۡ یَاۡتِ بِمَا غَلَّ  یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ»\nTranslation: And whoever comes on the Day of Resurrection with a sin, he will come with it. (Ibn Kathir)"
    }
  ],
  "270": [
    {
      "id": 1274,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Guard",
      "hw": "چوکیدار",
      "s": "« » a guard who supervises and protects for a specified period (1 Verse: 72:8)",
      "d": "«حَرَسَ» «حَرَسَ» «حَرَسَ الْمَلِکْ»\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ اَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ  فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّ  شُہُبًا»\nTranslation: And we (the jinn) indeed touched the sky but found it filled with severe guards and meteors."
    },
    {
      "id": 1275,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Guard",
      "hw": "چوکیدار",
      "s": "« » a guard lying in ambush, ready to seize prey the moment it appears (6 Verses: 9:5-9:107-72:9-72:27-78:21-89:14)",
      "d": "« » means to sit in wait, to lie in ambush. And « » means the place of lying in ambush. And « » means the one lying in ambush; its plural is « » and « ».\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِلَّا مَنِ ارۡتَضٰی مِنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ فَاِنَّہٗ یَسۡلُکُ مِنۡۢ  بَیۡنِ یَدِیۡہِ  وَ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ رَصَدًا»\nTranslation: But whomsoever He chooses from His messengers, He indeed sends guardians before him and behind him."
    }
  ],
  "271": [
    {
      "id": 1277,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "« » for something to be out of the reach of the five senses—i.e., grasp, power, and authority (52 Verses: 2:3-2:33-3:44-3:179-4:34-5:94-6:50-6:59-6:73-7:7-7:188-9:94-9:105-10:20-11:31-11:49-11:123-12:52-12:81-12:102-13:9-16:77-18:22-18:26-19:61-19:78-21:49-23:92-27:20-27:65-27:75-32:6-34:3-34:14-34:53-35:18-35:38-36:11-39:46-49:18-50:33-52:41-53:35-57:25-59:22-62:8-64:18-67:12-68:47-72:26-81:24-82:16)",
      "d": "The word « » is general. « » refers to something concealed. Anything that becomes hidden from sight for any reason or at any time (m, l). Therefore, its usage is general. Its opposite is « ». However, according to the scholar of fiqh al-lughah, everything is 'ghaib' (absent) that is hidden from human knowledge and senses, though a conception of it can be formed in the heart (Fall 16).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا مِنۡ غَآئِبَۃٍ  فِی السَّمَآءِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ  اِلَّا  فِیۡ  کِتٰبٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: And there is not a thing hidden within the heavens and the earth except that it is in a clear Book."
    },
    {
      "id": 1278,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "« » this word is used for the setting or disappearance of celestial bodies (e.g., sun, moon, stars) (3 Verses: 6:76-6:77-6:78)",
      "d": "« » is used for the setting or disappearance of celestial bodies (e.g., sun, moon, stars) (mufrad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَ الۡقَمَرَ بَازِغًا قَالَ ہٰذَا رَبِّیۡ ۚ فَلَمَّاۤ اَفَلَ قَالَ لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ یَہۡدِنِیۡ رَبِّیۡ لَاَکُوۡنَنَّ مِنَ الۡقَوۡمِ الضَّآلِّیۡنَ»\nTranslation: So when he saw the moon rising, he said, 'This is my Lord.' But when it set, he said, 'If my Lord does not guide me, I will surely be among the people astray.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1279,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "« » the setting of the sun (15 Verses: 2:115-2:142-2:177-2:258-7:137-18:17-18:86-20:130-24:35-26:28-28:44-50:39-55:17-70:40-73:9)",
      "d": "« » this word is used for the setting or disappearance of the sun. Just as « » is used for rising and « » includes the sun along with all planets (mufrad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تَرَی الشَّمۡسَ  اِذَا طَلَعَتۡ  تَّزٰوَرُ عَنۡ کَہۡفِہِمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ اِذَا غَرَبَتۡ تَّقۡرِضُہُمۡ ذَاتَ الشِّمَالِ»\nTranslation: And you will see the sun when it rises, inclining away from their cave towards the right, and when it sets, passing away from them towards the left."
    },
    {
      "id": 1280,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "« » to become absent due to moving far away (2 Verses: 10:61-34:3)",
      "d": "« » means to become invisible to the eyes by moving far away. And « » is said about a man who goes far away from his family in search of pasture. And « » means to remain absent for a long time (manjad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا یَعۡزُبُ عَنۡ رَّبِّکَ مِنۡ مِّثۡقَالِ  ذَرَّۃٍ»\nTranslation: And not a thing, the weight of a speck of dust, is absent from your Lord."
    },
    {
      "id": 1281,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To Be Hidden (To Be Absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "« » to sink into a pit and become hidden (1 Verse: 113:3)",
      "d": "«وَقَبَ» «وَقَبَتِ الشَّمْس» «وَقَبَ الظَّلَام» «اَلْوَقْب» «وَقَبَ»\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مِنۡ  شَرِّ غَاسِقٍ  اِذَا وَقَبَ»\nTranslation: And from the evil of the darkness when it settles."
    },
    {
      "id": 1282,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To hide (to be absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "« » means to be completely hidden (5 verses: 3:35-6:151-7:33-24:45-37:144)",
      "d": "« » means belly or the inner part of something. And since the inner part is completely hidden, therefore « » is used for something being completely hidden and its opposite is « ». (Mufradat)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«قُلۡ  اِنَّمَا حَرَّمَ رَبِّیَ الۡفَوَاحِشَ مَا ظَہَرَ  مِنۡہَا وَ  مَا بَطَنَ»\nTranslation: Say, 'My Lord has forbidden all kinds of indecencies, whether they are apparent or hidden.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1284,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To hide (to be absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "« » means to be hidden from others. This word is more general than « » (31 verses: 2:271-2:284-3:5-3:29-3:118-3:154-4:108-4:149-5:15-6:28-6:63-6:91-7:55-11:5-13:10-14:38-19:3-20:7-20:15-24:31-27:25-32:17-33:37-33:54-40:16-40:19-41:40-42:45-60:1-69:18-87:7)",
      "d": "« » its opposite is « » and « ». Meaning to be hidden from others. In this word, there is more generality than « » (Mufradat) i.e., something that remains hidden whose concept cannot even be imagined.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا  یَخۡفٰی عَلَیۡہِ شَیۡءٌ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا فِی السَّمَآءِ»\nTranslation: Nothing in the earth or the heavens is hidden from Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1285,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To hide (to be absent)",
      "hw": "غائب",
      "s": "« » means to hide in a safe place (4 verses: 37:49-52:24-56:23-56:78)",
      "d": "« » means a safe place or a cave in a mountain where one can take refuge. And its plural is « » and « ». And « » means to be hidden in a safe place which is out of reach of common people. (Mufradat. Manjad)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«کَاَنَّہُنَّ بَیۡضٌ مَّکۡنُوۡنٌ»\nTranslation: They are like eggs in a safe place."
    }
  ],
  "272": [
    {
      "id": 1286,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "« » is generally used for deliberately hiding testimony, faith, and the truth (20 verses: 2:33-2:42-2:72-2:140-2:146-2:159-2:174-2:228-2:283-3:71-3:167-3:187-4:37-4:42-5:61-5:99-5:106-21:110-24:29-40:28)",
      "d": "« » means to deliberately keep something hidden in the heart. (Fiqh 237) This word is generally used for hiding the truth, faith, and testimony. Its opposite is « ». Now see their examples:\nDivine revelation says:\n«وَ مَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ مِمَّنۡ کَتَمَ شَہَادَۃً عِنۡدَہٗ مِنَ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: Who is more unjust than one who conceals the testimony of Allah that he has (in the Book of Allah)?\nDivine revelation says:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یَکۡتُمُوۡنَ مَاۤ اَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ الۡبَیِّنٰتِ»\nTranslation: Those who conceal what We have revealed of clear signs.\nDivine revelation says:\n«وَ قَالَ رَجُلٌ  مُّؤۡمِنٌ ٭ۖ مِّنۡ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ یَکۡتُمُ  اِیۡمَانَہٗۤ»\nTranslation: And a believing man from the family of Pharaoh said who was concealing his faith."
    },
    {
      "id": 1287,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "« » is used for hiding a reality from people (5 verses: 5:31-7:20-7:26-16:59-38:32)",
      "d": "«وَرٰی» «وَرِيَ الزَّنْدُ»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَوَسۡوَسَ لَہُمَا الشَّیۡطٰنُ لِیُبۡدِیَ لَہُمَا مَا وٗرِیَ عَنۡہُمَا مِنۡ سَوۡاٰتِہِمَا»\nTranslation: Then Satan whispered to them to reveal to them what was hidden from them of their private parts.\n«وَارٰی یُوَارِیْ»\nFor example, Divine revelation says:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ»\nTranslation: Then Allah sent a crow that scratched in the earth to show him how to hide the shame of his brother."
    },
    {
      "id": 1288,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "« » is used for hiding something in a safe place (6 verses: 2:235-6:25-16:81-17:46-18:57-41:5)",
      "d": "« » in its root, two things are basically found: (1) to hide and (2) protection (M. L.) or in other words, this word is used for hiding something in a safe place for protection (Fiqh 238) whether something is hidden in the heart or something is hidden elsewhere. « » means a cave or small cave in a mountain where one can take refuge, and its plural is « ». And « » means such veils, screens, or covers behind which something cannot proceed or enter.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ  اَکِنَّۃً  اَنۡ یَّفۡقَہُوۡہُ»\nTranslation: And We have placed covers on their hearts so that they cannot understand it.\nAnd « » in the Quran is generally used in a spiritual sense and its opposite is « ».\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ فِیۡمَا عَرَّضۡتُمۡ بِہٖ مِنۡ خِطۡبَۃِ النِّسَآءِ اَوۡ اَکۡنَنۡتُمۡ فِیۡۤ  اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: There is no blame on you for what you mention indirectly regarding women or what you conceal in your hearts.\n«نُفُوس ، نَفْس ، صُدُوْر» «قُلُوب»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1289,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "« » is used for hiding a secret out of necessity (11 verses: 5:52-10:54-12:19-12:77-13:10-20:62-21:3-34:33-66:3-67:13-71:9)",
      "d": "« » means a secret matter and its plural is « ». And « » means to hide a secret in the heart. Whether it is a truth or not. Rather, it is hidden only due to necessity. Its opposite is « » and also « ». And « » means to whisper or to talk secretly with each other. (Manjad) In the Quran, this word is used in both apparent and spiritual senses.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«قَالَ یٰبُشۡرٰی ہٰذَا غُلٰمٌ ؕ وَ اَسَرُّوۡہُ بِضَاعَۃً»\nTranslation: He said, 'O good news! This is a boy.' And they concealed him as merchandise.\nAt another place, Divine revelation says:\n«وَ اِذۡ  اَسَرَّ النَّبِیُّ  اِلٰی  بَعۡضِ  اَزۡوَاجِہٖ حَدِیۡثًا»\nTranslation: And when the Prophet confided a matter to one of his wives."
    },
    {
      "id": 1290,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "« » is that hidden matter which a person hides in his heart and does not reveal to others (4 verses: 20:7-20:15-32:17-60:1)",
      "d": "«خَفِىّ» «بَدَا» «عَلَنَ» «جَلٰی ، جَلَو» «سِرٌّ» «سِرٌّ» «خَفِىّ»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَاِنَّہٗ یَعۡلَمُ السِّرَّ وَ اَخۡفٰی»\nTranslation: Indeed, He knows the secret and the most hidden."
    },
    {
      "id": 1291,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To conceal",
      "hw": "چھپانا",
      "s": "« » hidden and concealed treasure (1 verse: 27:25)",
      "d": "«خَبَأَ» «خَابَاَ» «اِخْتَبَا لَہٗ خَبِیْئًا» «خَبۡءَ» «خَبۡءَ الْاَرْض» «خَبۡءَ السَّمَاء» «اَخْرَجَ خَبۡءَ السَّمَآءِ خَبۡءَ الْاَرْضِ»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اَلَّا یَسۡجُدُوۡا  لِلّٰہِ الَّذِیۡ یُخۡرِجُ الۡخَبۡءَ فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ وَ یَعۡلَمُ مَا تُخۡفُوۡنَ  وَ مَا  تُعۡلِنُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Why should they not prostrate to Allah who brings forth what is hidden in the heavens and the earth and knows what you conceal and what you reveal?"
    }
  ],
  "273": [
    {
      "id": 1292,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Roof",
      "hw": "چھت",
      "s": "« » roofing a house with wood (29 verses: 2:259-7:54-9:129-10:3-11:7-12:100-13:2-17:42-18:42-20:5-21:22-22:45-23:86-23:116-25:59-27:23-27:26-27:38-27:41-27:42-32:4-39:75-40:7-40:15-43:82-57:4-69:17-81:20-85:15)",
      "d": "«عَرَشَ یَعْرِشُ» «عَرَش»\nFor example, Divine revelation says:\n«اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ وَّ ہِیَ خَاوِیَۃٌ عَلٰی عُرُوۡشِہَا»\nTranslation: Or like the one who passed by a town that had fallen upon its roofs.\nAnd the example for throne:\nDivine revelation says:\n«وَ رَفَعَ اَبَوَیۡہِ عَلَی الۡعَرۡشِ»\nTranslation: And he raised his parents upon the throne."
    },
    {
      "id": 1293,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "ceiling",
      "hw": "چھت",
      "s": "« » refers to the inner part of the ceiling seen from inside the room (4 verses: 16:26-21:32-43:33-52:5)",
      "d": "« » refers to the inner part of the ceiling seen from inside the room (CEI LING) or the ceiling (M R). Plural « ».\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَخَرَّ عَلَیۡہِمُ السَّقۡفُ مِنۡ فَوۡقِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: Then the ceiling fell upon them from above."
    },
    {
      "id": 1294,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "ceiling",
      "hw": "چھت",
      "s": "« » means constructed building. (2 verses: 2:22-40:64)",
      "d": "« » means construction, any constructed building, and every part of a building can also be called « », whether it is the foundation, wall, ceiling, or the entire building. And when the word « » is used in contrast to the floor, its meaning is only ceiling, because the word « » also implies the height of a structure (M L).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ فِرَاشًا وَّ السَّمَآءَ بِنَآءً»\nTranslation: The One who has made the earth a bed for you and the sky a ceiling."
    }
  ],
  "274": [
    {
      "id": 1295,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "« » means to leave something. (34 verses: 2:17-2:180-2:248-2:264-4:7-4:9-4:11-4:12-4:33-4:176-6:94-7:176-9:16-11:87-12:17-12:37-16:61-18:99-23:100-26:146-29:2-29:35-35:45-37:78-37:108-37:119-37:129-44:24-44:25-51:37-54:15-59:5-62:11-75:36)",
      "d": "« » is a general term. Meaning to leave something, intentionally or unintentionally, optionally or necessarily (Muf). It can be used in every context.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنۡ تَرَکَ خَیۡرَۨا  ۚ ۖ  الۡوَصِیَّۃُ لِلۡوَالِدَیۡنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: If (a person) leaves good (property) then the bequest is for the parents and the near relatives.\nThis was an urgent situation. Now see an example of optional or intentional:\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ تَرَکۡنَا یُوۡسُفَ عِنۡدَ مَتَاعِنَا»\nTranslation: And we left Yusuf (Joseph) with our belongings."
    },
    {
      "id": 1296,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "« » means to leave relations or homeland. (26 verses: 2:218-3:195-4:34-4:89-4:97-4:100-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:20-9:100-9:117-16:41-16:110-19:46-22:58-24:22-25:30-29:26-33:6-33:50-59:8-59:9-60:10-73:10-74:5)",
      "d": "« » is used for a person to cut off relations with another person or people (M L).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اصۡبِرۡ عَلٰی مَا یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ وَ اہۡجُرۡہُمۡ ہَجۡرًا جَمِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And be patient with what they say and leave them (disassociate from them) in a good manner.\nThen another form of cutting off relations is to leave the area itself. In this case, the meaning of Hijrah is to leave the homeland.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ  ہَاجَرُوۡا وَ جٰہَدُوۡا فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: And those who left their homeland and strove in the way of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1297,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "« » means to leave someone idle or unemployed. (2 verses: 22:45-81:4)",
      "d": "« » means to leave something idle, to make a worker idle. (Muf) « » means holiday from work. And « » refers to an employee who is still employed but has been stopped from working.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ  اِذَا الۡعِشَارُ عُطِّلَتۡ»\nTranslation: And when the ten-month pregnant she-camels are left (idle).\n«بِئْرٌ مُعَطَّلَۃٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1299,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "« » means to leave something considering it insignificant. (43 verses: 2:234-2:240-2:278-3:179-4:129-6:70-6:91-6:110-6:112-6:120-6:137-7:70-7:73-7:127-7:180-7:186-9:86-10:11-11:64-12:47-15:3-19:72-20:106-21:89-23:54-26:166-37:125-40:26-43:83-48:15-51:42-52:45-62:9-68:44-70:42-71:23-71:26-71:27-73:11-74:11-74:28-75:21-76:27)",
      "d": "« » is an incomplete verb. Only its present tense and imperative are used; past tense is not used. It is used in two contexts:\n(1) To leave something considering it insignificant (M Q).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ ذَرِ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّخَذُوۡا دِیۡنَہُمۡ لَعِبًا وَّ لَہۡوًا»\nTranslation: And leave those who have taken their religion as play and amusement.\n(2) Not giving permission to someone to interfere or object in doing a work. In English, its equivalent is LET. And « » means (LET ME DO THIS).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«ذَرۡنِیۡ  وَ مَنۡ خَلَقۡتُ وَحِیۡدًا»\nTranslation: Leave me and whom I have created alone.\nThe meaning is that I know and he is. You do not intervene in this matter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1300,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "« » means to leave someone in a peaceful manner. (2 verses: 33:48-93:3)",
      "d": "« » is also an incomplete verb, only present and imperative are used; past is not used. And its meanings are to leave something in a peaceful way (Muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ دَعۡ  اَذٰىہُمۡ  وَ  تَوَکَّلۡ  عَلَی اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: And leave their annoyance and trust in Allah!\nAnd « » means to bid farewell to a traveler or to dismiss with happiness, honor, and dignity, which includes the aspect of separating oneself and leaving them.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«مَا وَدَّعَکَ رَبُّکَ وَ مَا قَلٰی»\nTranslation: Your Lord has neither left you nor is He displeased."
    },
    {
      "id": 1301,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To Leave/Abandon",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "« » means to leave someone due to some defect or flaw (2 Verses: 18:47, 18:49)",
      "d": "«غَدَرَ» «وَفٰی» «غَادَرَ» «وَّ حَشَرۡنٰہُمۡ  فَلَمۡ  نُغَادِرۡ  مِنۡہِمۡ اَحَدًا» «مَالِ ہٰذَا الۡکِتٰبِ لَا یُغَادِرُ صَغِیۡرَۃً وَّ لَا کَبِیۡرَۃً  اِلَّاۤ  اَحۡصٰہَا»"
    }
  ],
  "275": [
    {
      "id": 1303,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to snatch away",
      "hw": "چھڑانا",
      "s": "« » is used for snatching someone away from calamity or saving them. (5 verses: 3:103-22:73-36:23-36:43-39:19)",
      "d": "« » means to snatch a person from calamity or punishment, to save or deliver (Muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ»\nTranslation: Can you snatch away the one who is in the Fire?\nAnd « » means to snatch something away with full effort and desire.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡلُبۡہُمُ الذُّبَابُ شَیۡئًا لَّا یَسۡتَنۡقِذُوۡہُ  مِنۡہُ ؕ ضَعُفَ الطَّالِبُ وَ الۡمَطۡلُوۡبُ»\nTranslation: And if the fly snatches something from them, they cannot snatch it away from him. Weak is the seeker and the sought."
    }
  ],
  "276": [
    {
      "id": 1304,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to touch",
      "hw": "چھونا",
      "s": "« » means the contact of some part of the body with something. (58 verses: 2:80-2:214-2:236-2:237-2:275-3:24-3:47-3:120-3:140-3:174-4:43-5:6-5:73-6:7-6:17-6:49-7:73-7:95-7:188-7:201-8:68-10:12-10:21-10:107-11:10-11:48-11:64-11:113-12:88-15:48-15:54-16:53-17:67-17:83-19:20-19:45-20:97-21:46-21:83-24:14-24:35-26:156-30:33-33:49-35:35-36:18-38:41-39:8-39:49-39:61-41:49-41:50-41:51-50:38-54:48-56:79-70:20-70:21)",
      "d": "« » means the contact of some part of the body with something (Muf). This word is also used in the Quran in this meaning.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اَیُّوۡبَ اِذۡ نَادٰی رَبَّہٗۤ  اَنِّیۡ مَسَّنِیَ الضُّرُّ»\nTranslation: And Ayub (Job) when he called his Lord: Indeed, harm has touched me.\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ تَمَسَّنَا النَّارُ اِلَّاۤ اَیَّامًا مَّعۡدُوۡدَۃً»\nTranslation: And they say: The Fire will not touch us except for a few numbered days."
    },
    {
      "id": 1305,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Touching",
      "hw": "چھونا",
      "s": "« » to touch or feel something with the hand or fingers (1 verse: 72:8)",
      "d": "« » means to touch or feel something with the hand or fingers. Whether the desired thing is obtained or not (mufrad). This word has also been used in the Quran in these meanings.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ اَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ  فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّ  شُہُبًا»\nTranslation: And (the jinn said) we touched the sky and found it filled with severe guards and meteors."
    },
    {
      "id": 1306,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Touching",
      "hw": "چھونا",
      "s": "« » meaning menstrual blood (2 verses: 55:56-55:74)",
      "d": "«طَمَثَ» «طَمَثَ یَطْمِثُ»"
    }
  ],
  "277": [
    {
      "id": 1307,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Snatching or Taking Away",
      "hw": "چھین",
      "s": "« » to take something forcefully from someone (1 verse: 22:73)",
      "d": "« » to take something from someone forcefully. (manjad) To snatch or take something away right in front of someone, even if the taker is weak.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡلُبۡہُمُ الذُّبَابُ شَیۡئًا لَّا یَسۡتَنۡقِذُوۡہُ  مِنۡہُ»\nTranslation: If the fly snatches something from them, they cannot recover it from him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1308,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Snatching or Taking Away",
      "hw": "چھین",
      "s": "« » for a powerful person to forcefully seize something from a weak person (1 verse: 18:79)",
      "d": "« » to take something by oppression, excess, force, or deceit (manjad). But for taking something by deceit or trickery, there is a separate word « » (m. q). Therefore, the meanings given by Imam Raghīb are more correct. That is, for a powerful person to forcefully seize something from a weak person with oppression and excess (mufrad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ کَانَ  وَرَآءَہُمۡ مَّلِکٌ یَّاۡخُذُ کُلَّ  سَفِیۡنَۃٍ  غَصۡبًا»\nTranslation: And there was a king behind them who used to seize every ship by force."
    },
    {
      "id": 1310,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Snatching or Taking Away",
      "hw": "چھین",
      "s": "« » to snatch something quickly with speed, to grab (6 verses: 2:20-8:26-22:31-28:57-29:67-37:10)",
      "d": "« » to snatch something and run away quickly (mufrad. fal). To grab. To snatch.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَکَادُ الۡبَرۡقُ یَخۡطَفُ اَبۡصَارَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: Lightning almost snatches away their sight."
    }
  ],
  "278": [
    {
      "id": 1311,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Need",
      "hw": "حاجت",
      "s": "« » a need whose non-fulfillment causes constriction in the heart (3 verses: 12:68-40:80-59:9)",
      "d": "« » means neediness and poverty (manjad). A need or desire whose non-fulfillment causes constriction and tightness in the heart.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَا کَانَ یُغۡنِیۡ عَنۡہُمۡ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ مِنۡ شَیۡءٍ اِلَّا حَاجَۃً فِیۡ نَفۡسِ یَعۡقُوۡبَ قَضٰہَا»\nTranslation: And this plan of theirs would not avail them against Allah at all, except that it was a desire in the soul of Ya'qub which he fulfilled.\nAt another place, the Lord says:\n«وَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ  فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِہِمۡ حَاجَۃً  مِّمَّاۤ اُوۡتُوۡا»\nTranslation: And they find no dissatisfaction in their hearts for what they are given.\nThat is, even though they are given little, they are patient and grateful, and do not feel constriction or tightness in their hearts."
    },
    {
      "id": 1312,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Need",
      "hw": "حاجت",
      "s": "« » needs that are fulfilled (2 verses: 20:18-24:31)",
      "d": "«اَرْب ، اَرِب» «اِرب»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«غَیۡرِ اُولِی الۡاِرۡبَۃِ مِنَ الرِّجَالِ»\nTranslation: meaning male servants who do not yet have the need (for marriage).\nAnd « » is the plural of « », which means the fulfillment of a need or requirement.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ ہِیَ عَصَایَ ۚ اَتَوَکَّؤُا عَلَیۡہَا وَ اَہُشُّ بِہَا عَلٰی غَنَمِیۡ وَ لِیَ فِیۡہَا مَاٰرِبُ  اُخۡرٰی»\nTranslation: Moses said, 'This is my staff; I lean on it and I use it to beat down leaves for my sheep, and I have other needs for it.' (meaning other needs are also fulfilled with it)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1313,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Need",
      "hw": "حاجت",
      "s": "« » need for sexual intercourse; this word is used in the Quran but its meaning is broad (1 verse: 33:37)",
      "d": "« » means (1) need, desire (manjad). (2) cohabitation, lust (m. q). And its plural is « ». In the Quran, this word is used only in the second meaning.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضٰی زَیۡدٌ مِّنۡہَا وَطَرًا»\nTranslation: Then when Zayd had fulfilled his need of her."
    }
  ],
  "279": [
    {
      "id": 1314,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Being Present",
      "hw": "حاضر",
      "s": "« » meaning to exist, to be present (24 verses: 2:133-2:180-2:196-2:282-3:30-4:8-4:18-4:128-5:106-7:163-18:49-19:68-23:98-28:61-30:16-34:38-36:32-36:53-36:75-37:57-37:127-37:158-46:29-81:14)",
      "d": "« » is the opposite of « ». « » means to be present, to come before (mufrad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا حَضَرُوۡہُ قَالُوۡۤا  اَنۡصِتُوۡا»\nTranslation: So when they came to him, they said, 'Be silent.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1315,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Being Present",
      "hw": "حاضر",
      "s": "« » to exist. To see and to testify (60 verses: 2:23-2:84-2:133-2:143-2:185-2:204-2:282-3:18-3:52-3:64-3:70-3:81-3:86-3:99-3:140-4:6-4:15-4:69-4:135-4:166-5:8-5:44-5:111-6:19-6:130-6:144-6:150-7:37-7:172-9:107-11:54-12:26-12:81-18:51-19:37-21:61-22:28-22:78-24:2-24:4-24:6-24:8-24:13-24:24-25:72-27:32-27:49-36:65-39:69-41:20-41:21-41:22-43:19-43:86-46:10-57:19-59:11-63:1-65:2-83:21)",
      "d": "« » this word is used in many meanings. But two relevant meanings are:\n(1) to be present.\nFor example: The Lord says:\n«اَمۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ  اِنَاثًا  وَّ ہُمۡ شٰہِدُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Or did We create the angels as females while they were present?\n(2) to be present and to see something with one's own eyes. Then to testify before a judge (faq l 30). This means testimony.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَاۡبَ الشُّہَدَآءُ اِذَا مَا دُعُوۡا»\nTranslation: And let not the witnesses refuse when they are called."
    }
  ],
  "280": [
    {
      "id": 1317,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "حالت",
      "s": "« » is used for the current state when asking questions (2 verses: 12:50-20:51)",
      "d": "« » means the present state or condition. This word is general.\n«قَالَ فَمَا بَالُ الۡقُرُوۡنِ الۡاُوۡلٰی. قَالَ عِلۡمُہَا عِنۡدَ رَبِّیۡ»\nTranslation: Pharaoh asked Prophet Moses (PBUH), \"What is the state of the former nations?\" He said, \"Their knowledge is with my Lord.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1318,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "حالت",
      "s": "« » is used for inquiring about an undesirable matter (5 verses: 12:51-15:57-20:95-28:23-51:31)",
      "d": "« » means affair, state, matter—whether big or small. Generally, it is used for an undesirable matter (Munjid).\n«قَالَ فَمَا خَطۡبُکُمۡ اَیُّہَا الۡمُرۡسَلُوۡنَ. قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّاۤ اُرۡسِلۡنَاۤ اِلٰی قَوۡمٍ مُّجۡرِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Prophet Abraham (PBUH) said to the angels, \"What is your motive?\" The angels said, \"We have been sent to a criminal people.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1319,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "حالت",
      "s": "« » is used for habits and conduct (4 verses: 3:11-8:52-8:54-40:31)",
      "d": "« » means to continue continuously, permanent habit, habits and manners, gait (Munjid).\n«کَدَاۡبِ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ»\nTranslation: (Their state is) like that of the people of Pharaoh."
    },
    {
      "id": 1320,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "State/Condition",
      "hw": "حالت",
      "s": "« » comes for one form after another (1 verse: 71:14)",
      "d": "«طَوْر» «اَلنَّاسُ اَطْوَارٌ» «تَطَوُّر» «طَوْر»\n«وَ قَدۡ خَلَقَکُمۡ اَطۡوَارًا»\nTranslation: And Allah has created you in various forms."
    }
  ],
  "281": [
    {
      "id": 1321,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Authority",
      "hw": "حاکم",
      "s": "« » means a just judge who decides and prevents oppression (6 verses: 4:60-7:87-10:109-11:45-12:80-95:8)",
      "d": "« » means \"preventing oppression\" (Munjid), i.e., a judgment that prevents injustice and excess towards others. And « » means to appoint someone as a judge or ruler. And « » means to take one's case to a ruler for judgment. (Munjid) So a ruler is one who judges people's cases and prevents the oppressor from oppression.\n«وَ اِذَا حَکَمۡتُمۡ بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ اَنۡ تَحۡکُمُوۡا بِالۡعَدۡلِ»\nTranslation: And when you judge between people, judge with justice."
    },
    {
      "id": 1322,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Authority",
      "hw": "حاکم",
      "s": "«اُولِی الْاَمْر»",
      "d": "«اُولِی الْاَمْر» «وَلِیُّ الْاَمْر» «وَلّٰی»\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اَطِیۡعُوا اللّٰہَ وَ اَطِیۡعُوا الرَّسُوۡلَ وَ اُولِی الۡاَمۡرِ مِنۡکُمۡ»\nTranslation: O you who believe! Obey Allah and obey the Messenger and those in authority among you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1323,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Authority",
      "hw": "حاکم",
      "s": "« » refers to any person responsible for running an individual's, institution's, or system's affairs fairly (3 verses: 4:34-4:135-5:8)",
      "d": "« » means to stand. And « » means to straighten or establish firmly. And « » means to set right or adjust something (i.e., to make it even and correct) (Munjid). And « » or « » is a person who is responsible for running the affairs of an individual, institution, or system in a proper manner, and for its protection, supervision, and providing its necessities. (F. Q.)\n«اَلرِّجَالُ قَوّٰمُوۡنَ عَلَی النِّسَآءِ بِمَا فَضَّلَ اللّٰہُ بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ وَّ بِمَاۤ اَنۡفَقُوۡا مِنۡ اَمۡوَالِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: Men are protectors/maintainers of women, because Allah has favored some of them over others and because they spend from their wealth."
    }
  ],
  "282": [
    {
      "id": 1324,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding the Limit / Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "« » means to go beyond a designated limit (4 verses: 2:249-7:138-10:90-18:62)",
      "d": "«جَاوَزَ» «جَوَّزَ الطَّرِیّق»\n«فَلَمَّا جَاوَزَا قَالَ لِفَتٰىہُ اٰتِنَا غَدَآءَنَا ۫ لَقَدۡ لَقِیۡنَا مِنۡ سَفَرِنَا ہٰذَا نَصَبًا»\nTranslation: When they both went beyond (that place), he said to his servant, \"Bring us our morning meal; we have certainly encountered fatigue from this journey of ours.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1325,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding the Limit / Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "« » means to exceed the limit of moderation (19 verses: 5:32-6:141-7:31-7:81-10:12-10:83-17:33-20:127-21:9-25:67-26:151-36:19-39:53-40:28-40:34-40:43-43:5-44:31-51:34)",
      "d": "«اَسْرَفَ» «سَرَفَ فِی الْاَمْر» «اَسْرَفَ»\n«کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا وَ لَا تُسۡرِفُوۡا»\nTranslation: Eat and drink, but do not exceed."
    },
    {
      "id": 1326,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding the Limit / Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "« » means to exceed limits in fulfilling a desire (79 verses: 2:90-2:187-2:198-2:207-2:213-2:265-2:272-3:7-3:19-3:83-3:85-3:99-4:24-4:34-4:94-4:104-4:114-4:139-5:2-5:35-5:50-6:35-6:114-6:146-6:164-7:33-7:45-7:86-7:140-9:47-9:48-10:23-10:90-11:19-12:65-13:17-13:22-14:3-16:14-16:90-17:12-17:28-17:42-17:57-17:66-17:110-18:64-18:108-22:60-23:7-24:33-28:55-28:73-28:76-28:77-29:17-30:23-30:46-33:51-35:12-38:22-38:24-42:14-42:27-42:39-42:42-45:12-45:17-48:29-49:9-55:20-57:27-59:8-60:1-62:10-66:1-70:31-73:20-92:20)",
      "d": "« » means to go beyond the appropriate limit in seeking or fulfilling a desire (Mufradat). To try to claim more than one's right unjustly. And accordingly, to suppress the rights of others.\n«وَ اِنَّ کَثِیۡرًا مِّنَ الۡخُلَطَآءِ لَیَبۡغِیۡ بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ»\nTranslation: And indeed, many of the partners wrong each other."
    },
    {
      "id": 1328,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding Limits; Doing Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "« » to act hastily or exceed without thinking (2 verses: 18:28-20:45)",
      "d": "«فَرَطَ» «فَرَطَ مِنْہُ الْقَول» «فَرَّطَ» «وَ اتَّبَعَ ہَوٰىہُ  وَ کَانَ   اَمۡرُہٗ   فُرُطًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1329,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding Limits; Doing Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "« » to exceed against others with hand or tongue (1 verse: 33:19)",
      "d": "«سَلَقَ» «فَاِذَا  ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ  اَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1330,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding Limits; Doing Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "« » to exceed in someone's worth and status due to extreme belief; to take an extremist approach (2 verses: 4:171-5:77)",
      "d": "«غَلَا» «غَلَا السِّعْر» «غَلَا السَّہَم» «غَلَا فِی الْاَمْرِ» «یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰابِ لَا تَغۡلُوۡا فِیۡ دِیۡنِکُمۡ وَ لَا تَقُوۡلُوۡا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡحَقَّ ؕ اِنَّمَا الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ رَسُوۡلُ اللّٰہِ وَ کَلِمَتُہٗ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1331,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Exceeding Limits; Doing Excess",
      "hw": " زیادتی",
      "s": "« » to exaggerate in falsehood to such an extent that reason cannot accept it (3 verses: 18:14-38:22-72:4)",
      "d": "«شَطَطًا» «لَنۡ نَّدۡعُوَا۠ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہٖۤ  اِلٰـہًا لَّقَدۡ قُلۡنَاۤ  اِذًا  شَطَطًا»"
    }
  ],
  "283": [
    {
      "id": 1332,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Falling Short; Deficiency",
      "hw": "حد ",
      "s": "The word « » is used for not properly completing a task and for negligence (5 verses: 6:31-6:38-6:61-12:80-39:56)",
      "d": "«فَرَّطَ» «فَرَطَ» «فَرَّطَ» «اَنۡ تَقُوۡلَ نَفۡسٌ یّٰحَسۡرَتٰی عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡتُّ فِیۡ جَنۡۢبِ اللّٰہِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1333,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Falling Short; Deficiency",
      "hw": "حد ",
      "s": "« » is used for deficiency in quantity (3 verses: 4:101-7:202-48:27)",
      "d": "«قَصَرَ» «قَصَرَ السَّھْم» «قَصَرَ الصَّلوٰۃ» «قَصَّرَ الشَّعْر» «قَصُرَ» «قَصُور» «تَقْصِیْر» «قَاصِر» «فَلَیۡسَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ جُنَاحٌ اَنۡ تَقۡصُرُوۡا مِنَ الصَّلٰوۃِ»"
    }
  ],
  "284": [
    {
      "id": 1334,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Forbidden",
      "hw": "حرام",
      "s": "« » things or matters that Sharia has strictly prohibited (40 verses: 2:85-2:173-2:275-3:50-3:93-4:23-4:160-5:3-5:26-5:72-5:87-5:96-6:119-6:138-6:139-6:140-6:143-6:144-6:145-6:146-6:148-6:150-6:151-7:32-7:33-7:50-7:157-9:29-9:37-10:59-16:35-16:115-16:116-16:118-17:33-21:95-24:3-25:68-28:12-66:1)",
      "d": "«حَرَامٌ» «وَ اَحَلَّ اللّٰہُ الۡبَیۡعَ وَ حَرَّمَ الرِّبٰوا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1335,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Forbidden",
      "hw": "حرام",
      "s": "« » is used for illicit and forbidden earnings (3 verses: 5:42-5:62-5:63-)",
      "d": "«سُحْت» «سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِلۡکَذِبِ اَکّٰلُوۡنَ لِلسُّحۡتِ»"
    }
  ],
  "285": [
    {
      "id": 1336,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Part; Portion",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "« » any one part or piece of something (3 verses: 2:260-15:44-43:15)",
      "d": "«جُزْء» «اجزاء» «ثُمَّ اجۡعَلۡ عَلٰی کُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنۡہُنَّ جُزۡءًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1337,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Part; Portion",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "« » the initial part of the night (1 verse: 11:114)",
      "d": "«زُلْف» «زُلْف» «زُلْف» «اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ وَ زُلَفًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1338,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Share/Portion",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "« » means a share of goodness, virtue, and wealth (5 Verses: 3:176, 4:11, 4:176, 5:13, 5:14)",
      "d": "«حَظّ» «فَلِلذَّکُرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1339,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Khalaq",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "« » is the specific portion one receives as a result of their character (4 verses: 2:102, 2:200, 3:77, 9:69)",
      "d": "« » refers to a definite share of all kinds of goodness (m. r.), a great portion of goodness (manjad) (muf) (Faqih Lane 136). That is, the excellence a person attains through their character. This share is connected to a person's deeds.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یَّقُوۡلُ رَبَّنَاۤ  اٰتِنَا فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ مَا لَہٗ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  مِنۡ خَلَاقٍ»\nTranslation: Then among them are some who say, 'Our Lord, grant us in this world,' and for such people there will be no portion in the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1340,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Naseeb",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "« » is the portion that is destined, whether small or large (18 verses: 2:202, 3:23, 4:7, 4:32, 4:33, 4:44, 4:51, 4:53, 4:85, 4:118, 4:141, 6:136, 7:37, 11:109, 16:56, 28:77, 40:47, 42:20)",
      "d": "« » means to fix or plant something. And « » means a stone planted as a marker on a path. And « » refers to the fixed portion written in one's destiny (muf), whether it relates to something beloved or disliked (na-pasandidah) (Faqih Lane 135).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ ابۡتَغِ  فِیۡمَاۤ  اٰتٰىکَ اللّٰہُ  الدَّارَ الۡاٰخِرَۃَ  وَ لَا تَنۡسَ نَصِیۡبَکَ مِنَ الدُّنۡیَا»\nTranslation: And seek through what Allah has given you the abode of the Hereafter, and do not forget your portion of this world."
    },
    {
      "id": 1341,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Kifl",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "« » is a share as recompense for a good or bad deed (2 verses: 4:85, 57:28)",
      "d": "« » means guarantee or surety. It also means a share and the necessary recompense for an action, whether good or bad. According to Al-Munjid, it means double reward or double sin.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَنۡ یَّشۡفَعۡ شَفَاعَۃً حَسَنَۃً یَّکُنۡ لَّہٗ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّنۡہَا ۚ وَ مَنۡ یَّشۡفَعۡ شَفَاعَۃً سَیِّئَۃً یَّکُنۡ لَّہٗ کِفۡلٌ مِّنۡہَا»\nTranslation: Whoever intercedes with a good intercession will have a share from it, and whoever intercedes with an evil intercession will have a share from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1342,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Ba'dh",
      "hw": "حصہ",
      "s": "« » is a part of a complete thing, or one or some among similar things (86 verses: 2:36, 2:73, 2:76, 2:85, 2:145, 2:251, 2:253, 2:259, 2:283, 3:34, 3:50, 3:64, 3:155, 3:195, 4:19, 4:21, 4:25, 4:32, 4:34, 4:150, 5:49, 5:51, 6:53, 6:65, 6:112, 6:128, 6:129, 6:158, 6:165, 7:24, 8:37, 8:72, 8:73, 8:75, 9:67, 9:71, 9:127, 10:46, 11:12, 11:54, 12:10, 13:4, 13:36, 13:40, 16:71, 17:21, 17:55, 17:88, 18:19, 18:99, 20:123, 22:40, 23:44, 23:91, 23:113, 24:40, 24:58, 24:62, 24:63, 25:20, 26:198, 27:72, 29:25, 30:41, 33:6, 34:31, 34:42, 35:40, 37:27, 37:50, 38:22, 38:24, 40:28, 40:77, 43:32, 43:63, 43:67, 45:19, 47:4, 47:26, 49:2, 49:12, 52:25, 66:3, 68:30, 69:44)",
      "d": "« » means a portion, a piece. It is also used for a part of a whole.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبُوۡہُ بِبَعۡضِہَا»\nTranslation: So we said, 'Strike him (the slain man) with some of it (the cow).'\n«بَعْضَ النَّاس» «بَعْضَ الَلَیَالِی»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«بَعۡضُکُمۡ لِبَعۡضٍ عَدُوٌّ»\nTranslation: Some of you are enemies to others.\nAdditionally, this word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَ لِاُبَیِّنَ  لَکُمۡ بَعۡضَ الَّذِیۡ تَخۡتَلِفُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ»\nTranslation: So that I may clarify for you some of that in which you differ."
    }
  ],
  "286": [
    {
      "id": 1343,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Hifazat Karna",
      "hw": "حفاظت",
      "s": "« » to save something from being lost or destroyed (29 verses: 2:238, 2:255, 4:34, 5:44, 5:89, 6:61, 6:92, 9:112, 12:12, 12:63, 12:64, 12:65, 12:81, 13:11, 15:9, 15:17, 21:82, 23:5, 23:9, 24:30, 24:31, 33:35, 37:7, 41:12, 70:29, 70:34, 82:10, 83:33, 86:4)",
      "d": "« » is the opposite of « ». It means to save from loss and destruction (manjad), to guard (m. r.), to try to protect something from external dangers (Faqih Lane 15).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ  بَعِیۡرٍ»\nTranslation: We will protect our brother and also bring an increased measure of grain."
    },
    {
      "id": 1344,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Hifazat Karna",
      "hw": "حفاظت",
      "s": "« » to protect and remove the causes of external threats (2 verses: 20:54, 28:23)",
      "d": "« » means to protect something and to remove the causes that lead to external threats. And « » means a shepherd, a guardian. Its opposite is « », meaning a flock grazing without a shepherd (Faqih Lane 15).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِاَمٰنٰتِہِمۡ وَ عَہۡدِہِمۡ رٰعُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Who are guardians of their trusts and their covenants."
    },
    {
      "id": 1345,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Hifazat Karna",
      "hw": "حفاظت",
      "s": "« » to protect by means of a four-walled enclosure (8 verses: 4:24, 4:25, 5:5, 21:91, 24:4, 24:23, 59:14, 66:12)",
      "d": "«حِصْن» «حُصُوْن» «حَصَن» «اَلْحِفْظُ وَالْحَیَاطَۃ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَرۡیَمَ  ابۡنَتَ عِمۡرٰنَ  الَّتِیۡۤ  اَحۡصَنَتۡ فَرۡجَہَا»\nTranslation: And Maryam, daughter of Imran, who guarded her chastity.\nIt also has a meaning of entering into marriage. Because marriage also serves as a fortress against immorality.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ  اِلَّا مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And [also prohibited are] married women, except those whom your right hands possess."
    },
    {
      "id": 1346,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Hifazat Karna",
      "hw": "حفاظت",
      "s": "« » to keep something safe and sound by guarding it (1 verse: 21:42)",
      "d": "« » means to constantly watch over something and keep it intact. Essentially, two aspects are found here: (1) vigilance (2) stability (m. l. muf). It also means to save something from harm and from inclining towards calamity (Faqih Lane 169).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُلۡ مَنۡ یَّکۡلَؤُکُمۡ  بِالَّیۡلِ وَ النَّہَارِ مِنَ الرَّحۡمٰنِ»\nTranslation: Say, 'Who can protect you by night and by day from the Most Merciful?'"
    }
  ],
  "287": [
    {
      "id": 1347,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Haq-e-Mehr",
      "hw": "حق مہر",
      "s": "In « », all the obligations of a woman, including the dowry (mehr), are included. (1 verse: 4:4)",
      "d": "«صَدُقَۃ» «صَدُقٰت» «صَدَقَۃ» «اَصْدَقَ الْاِبْنَۃَ» «صَدُقَۃ» «صُدَاق» «صُدَاق»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اٰتُوا النِّسَآءَ صَدُقٰتِہِنَّ نِحۡلَۃً»\nTranslation: And give the women their dowries graciously."
    },
    {
      "id": 1348,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Haq-e-Mehr",
      "hw": "حق مہر",
      "s": "« » is used in all meanings: dowry (mehr), salary, wages, remuneration, reward, gift, compensation, and reward in the Hereafter (5 verses: 4:24, 4:25, 5:5, 33:50, 60:10)",
      "d": "« » has the plural « ». « » means remuneration or the agreed-upon compensation between « » (the one who hires) and « » (the hired one). Since in marriage, a woman accepts the compensation for her chastity as 'mehr', which is settled by mutual consent. Therefore, the word « » is used metaphorically in the Quran for the right of dowry.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اٰتُوۡہُنَّ اُجُوۡرَہُنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ»\nTranslation: And give them their dowry as an obligation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1349,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Right of Mahr",
      "hw": "حق مہر",
      "s": "« » means to prescribe, determine, or make obligatory (2 verses: 2:236-2:237).",
      "d": "« » means to prescribe, determine, or make obligatory. And « » means a prescribed or determined portion (manjid). The word 'fardh' is also used metaphorically for the right of mahr because determining the amount of mahr at the time of marriage by mutual consent is necessary.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ اِنۡ طَلَّقۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ تَمَسُّوۡہُنَّ وَ قَدۡ فَرَضۡتُمۡ لَہُنَّ فَرِیۡضَۃً فَنِصۡفُ مَا فَرَضۡتُمۡ»\nTranslation: And if you divorce them before you have touched them, but you have already prescribed for them a portion, then [pay] half of what you prescribed."
    }
  ],
  "288": [
    {
      "id": 1351,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Command",
      "hw": "حکم",
      "s": "« » refers to a command that is necessitated by divine will; otherwise, it means to grant permission or approval (46 verses: 2:97-2:102-2:213-2:221-2:249-2:251-2:255-3:49-3:145-3:152-3:166-4:25-4:64-5:16-5:110-7:58-8:66-9:43-10:3-10:59-10:100-11:105-12:80-13:38-14:1-14:11-14:23-14:25-20:109-22:39-22:65-24:36-24:62-33:46-34:12-34:23-35:32-40:78-42:21-42:51-53:26-58:10-59:5-64:11-78:38-97:4).",
      "d": "« » means to grant permission or approval. And when it means 'to command,' it refers to a command that is necessitated by divine will (muf).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فِیۡ  بُیُوۡتٍ اَذِنَ اللّٰہُ  اَنۡ تُرۡفَعَ وَ یُذۡکَرَ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُہٗ»\nTranslation: [They are] houses which Allah has permitted to be raised and in which His name is remembered."
    },
    {
      "id": 1353,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Command",
      "hw": "حکم",
      "s": "« » when attributed to Allah, means an emphatic command (18 verses: 2:132-2:180-2:182-2:240-4:11-4:12-4:131-5:106-6:144-6:151-6:152-6:153-19:31-29:8-31:14-36:50-42:13-46:15).",
      "d": "« » means to take a covenant regarding something, to command, and to bequeath (manjid). And when attributed to Allah, it means an emphatic command.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ اَوۡصٰنِیۡ بِالصَّلٰوۃِ  وَ الزَّکٰوۃِ مَا دُمۡتُ  حَیًّا»\nTranslation: And [He has enjoined upon me] prayer and zakah as long as I am alive.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«یُوۡصِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡۤ  اَوۡلَادِکُمۡ ٭ لِلذَّکَرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: Allah instructs you concerning your children: for the male, the equivalent of the share of two females."
    }
  ],
  "289": [
    {
      "id": 1354,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Attack",
      "hw": "حملہ",
      "s": "« » means to attack forcefully and to try to overpower (1 verse: 22:72).",
      "d": "«سَطْوَۃٌ  بِہٖ وَعَلَیْہِ» «سَطَا الْفَرَس» «سَطَا»\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«یَکَادُوۡنَ یَسۡطُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡنَ یَتۡلُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِنَا»\nTranslation: It is as if they were about to attack those who recite Our verses to them."
    }
  ],
  "290": [
    {
      "id": 1356,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Be Perplexed",
      "hw": "حیران",
      "s": "« » means bewildered, perplexed, astonished, dumbfounded; it is used in all these meanings (1 verse: 6:71).",
      "d": "« » is a general term. It means to remain in doubt due to not finding the path of righteousness (the path of goodness), regardless of the situation.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«کَالَّذِی اسۡتَہۡوَتۡہُ الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ حَیۡرَانَ ۪ لَہٗۤ  اَصۡحٰبٌ یَّدۡعُوۡنَہٗۤ  اِلَی الۡہُدَی ائۡتِنَا»\nTranslation: Like one whom the devils have led astray in the land, [while] he is perplexed, having friends who call him to guidance, [saying], 'Come to us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1357,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Be Stunned",
      "hw": "حیران",
      "s": "« » means to lose one's senses suddenly due to astonishment (2 verses: 2:258-21:40).",
      "d": "« » means to become suddenly speechless and silent due to astonishment, to lose consciousness (m.q., manjid). To remain bewildered and stunned. To be dumbfounded. The word « » is derived from this.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَبُہِتَ الَّذِیۡ کَفَرَ»\nTranslation: And the disbeliever was stunned.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«بَلۡ تَاۡتِیۡہِمۡ بَغۡتَۃً  فَتَبۡہَتُہُمۡ»\nTranslation: But it will come to them suddenly and will stupefy them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1358,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To Be Amazed",
      "hw": "حیران",
      "s": "« » means to be amazed at something whose cause is unknown (14 verses: 7:63-7:69-9:55-9:85-10:2-11:73-13:5-18:9-18:63-37:12-38:4-50:2-53:59-72:1).",
      "d": "« » refers to amazement whose cause is unknown (muf). And « » means to be amazed, to wonder.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«بَلۡ عَجِبُوۡۤا اَنۡ جَآءَہُمۡ مُّنۡذِرٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ»\nTranslation: But they wonder that a warner has come to them from among themselves."
    }
  ],
  "291": [
    {
      "id": 1359,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Menstruation",
      "hw": "حیض",
      "s": "« » is used in the meaning of menstruation (2 verses: 2:222-65:4).",
      "d": "«مَحِیْضٌ» «مَحِیْضٌ» «حَاضَتِ الْمِرْأَۃ»\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡمَحِیۡضِ»\nTranslation: And they ask you about menstruation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1360,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Menstrual Period / Purity",
      "hw": "حیض",
      "s": "« » is used in the meaning of a woman becoming pure from menstruation (1 verse: 2:228).",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». It means a woman's « » (purity), i.e., entering the state of menstruation. Therefore, this word is lexically applied to both « » (purity) and menstruation, and it is among the words with contradictory meanings (al-dhaad). (Al-dhaad refers to words that have two separate, opposite meanings.)\n«اُقْعُدِیْ عَنِ الصَّلٰوۃِ اَیَّامِ اَقْرَائِک»\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ الۡمُطَلَّقٰتُ یَتَرَبَّصۡنَ بِاَنۡفُسِہِنَّ ثَلٰثَۃَ قُرُوۡٓءٍ»\nTranslation: And divorced women shall wait [before marrying another] for three menstrual periods."
    }
  ],
  "292": [
    {
      "id": 1361,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "husband",
      "hw": "خاوند",
      "s": "« » refers to a husband who has consummated the marriage (4 verses: 2:228-4:128-11:72-24:31)",
      "d": "«بَعْل» «بَعُول» «بَعْل» «بَعْلَۃ» «بَاعَلَ» «بَعْل» «یوم اکل و شرب و یعال» «قَالَتۡ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤیءَ اَلِدُ وَ اَنَا عَجُوۡزٌ وَّ ہٰذَا بَعۡلِیۡ شَیۡخًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1362,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Spouse",
      "hw": "خاوند",
      "s": "« » is general for both those with intellect and those without. It is also used for both husband and wife (72 verses: 2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7).",
      "d": "« » its plural is azwaaj. It means a pair. Both husband and wife are each other's « ». Then each of them is the « » of the other. For the husband, the wife is his « », and for the wife, the husband is her « ».\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«قَدۡ سَمِعَ  اللّٰہُ  قَوۡلَ  الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا»\nTranslation: Allah has heard the statement of the woman who disputes with you concerning her husband."
    }
  ],
  "293": [
    {
      "id": 1364,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khabar",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "Khabar is that news which relates to the essence of the listener and can affect them. (2 verses: 27:7-28:29)",
      "d": "Khabar: its plural is Akhbar. It is a well-known word. An event of which a person has no knowledge, and he is informed of it through someone else, that is news. Knowledge of the circumstances and events.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَالَ لِاَہۡلِہِ امۡکُثُوۡۤا اِنِّیۡۤ اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِخَبَرٍ»\nTranslation: Moses pbuh said to his family, 'Wait here. I have seen a fire. Perhaps I can bring you some news from there.'\nAt another place, the command of Allah is:\n«قُلۡ لَّا تَعۡتَذِرُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکُمۡ قَدۡ نَبَّاَنَا اللّٰہُ مِنۡ اَخۡبَارِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: Say, 'Do not make excuses; we will not believe you. Allah has already informed us of your circumstances.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1365,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "news",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "« » news, information, notice, used in all meanings (2 verses: 18:68-18:91)",
      "d": "«خُبْر» «صَدَّقَ الْخَبْرَ الْخُبْرَ» «وَ کَیۡفَ تَصۡبِرُ عَلٰی مَا لَمۡ تُحِطۡ بِہٖ خُبۡرًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1366,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "news",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "« » to give news about an important and major matter (76 verses: 2:31-2:33-3:15-3:44-3:49-5:14-5:27-5:48-5:60-5:105-6:5-6:34-6:60-6:67-6:105-6:108-6:143-6:159-6:164-7:101-7:175-9:64-9:70-9:94-9:105-10:18-10:23-10:53-10:71-11:49-11:100-11:120-12:15-12:36-12:37-12:45-12:102-13:33-14:9-15:49-15:51-18:13-18:78-18:103-20:99-22:72-24:64-26:6-26:69-26:221-27:22-28:3-28:66-29:8-31:15-31:23-33:20-34:7-35:14-38:21-38:67-38:88-39:7-41:50-49:6-53:36-54:4-54:28-58:6-58:7-62:8-64:5-64:7-66:3-75:13-78:2)",
      "d": "«نَبَاَ» «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا»"
    }
  ],
  "294": [
    {
      "id": 1367,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "to end",
      "hw": "ختم",
      "s": "« » means for something to end completely and not remain, to perish. In it, the original thing perishes or slips from the hand, whereas in « » the thing remains restored, but no deficiency or excess can occur in it (4 verses: 16:96-18:109-31:27-38:54)",
      "d": "«نَفَدَ» «بَقِیَ» «مَا عِنۡدَکُمۡ یَنۡفَدُ وَ مَا عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ بَاقٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1368,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khatam",
      "hw": "ختم",
      "s": "Khatam: meaning seal, stamp (6 verses: 2:7-6:46-33:40-36:65-42:24-45:23)",
      "d": "Khatam: to seal something after it is complete, stamping it so that no addition or subtraction can occur (etc.) It means ultimately and end of work, i.e., to be finished with a task, and Khatam al-Kitab means to have read the entire book (Manjad).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«مَا کَانَ مُحَمَّدٌ اَبَاۤ اَحَدٍ مِّنۡ رِّجَالِکُمۡ وَ لٰکِنۡ رَّسُوۡلَ اللّٰہِ وَ خَاتَمَ النَّبِیّٖنَ»\nTranslation: Muhammad pbuh is not the father of any of your men, but he is the Messenger of Allah and the seal of the prophets (i.e., the one who ended them)."
    }
  ],
  "295": [
