  "298": [
    {
      "id": 1381,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Spend",
      "hw": "خرچ",
      "s": "« » is the general term for spending. « » means not to spend even on necessary needs or to spend less. « » means to be stingy in spending on one's family. « » means to spend beyond necessity. « » means to spend wastefully and without need (57 verses: 2:3-2:195-2:215-2:219-2:254-2:261-2:262-2:264-2:265-2:267-2:270-2:272-2:273-2:274-3:17-3:92-3:117-3:134-4:34-4:38-4:39-5:64-8:3-8:36-8:60-8:63-9:34-9:53-9:54-9:91-9:92-9:98-9:99-9:121-13:22-14:31-16:75-17:100-18:42-22:35-25:67-28:54-32:16-34:39-35:29-36:47-42:38-47:38-57:7-57:10-60:10-60:11-63:7-63:10-64:16-65:6-65:7)",
      "d": "«اَنْفَقَ» «نَفَقَ» «نیفق السّراویل» «نَافَقَ الْیَرْبُوْعُ وَ نَفَقَ» «وَ اَنۡفِقُوۡا مِنۡ مَّا  رَزَقۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلِ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیَ  اَحَدَکُمُ  الۡمَوۡتُ» «بُخْل» «اَقْتَرَ» «اَسْرَفَ» «بَذَّرَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1382,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Spend",
      "hw": "خرچ",
      "s": "« » means to spend a large amount of wealth in evil purposes (63 verses: 2:195-2:205-3:117-4:176-5:17-6:6-6:26-6:47-6:131-7:4-7:129-7:155-7:164-7:173-8:42-8:54-9:42-10:13-11:117-12:85-14:13-15:4-17:16-17:17-17:58-18:59-19:74-19:98-20:128-20:134-21:6-21:9-21:95-22:45-23:48-26:139-26:208-27:49-28:43-28:58-28:59-28:78-28:88-29:31-32:26-36:31-38:3-40:34-43:8-44:37-45:24-46:27-46:35-47:13-50:36-53:50-54:51-67:28-69:5-69:6-69:29-77:16-90:6)",
      "d": "«اَھْلَکَ» «یَقُوۡلُ  اَہۡلَکۡتُ مَالًا  لُّبَدًا»"
    }
  ],
  "299": [
    {
      "id": 1384,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Buying and Selling",
      "hw": "خرید و فروخت",
      "s": "Shira: buying and selling when the intention is to fulfill personal need. However, \"Ishtara\" is specific to the meaning of buying. (22 verses: 2:16-2:41-2:79-2:86-2:90-2:102-2:174-2:175-3:77-3:177-3:187-3:199-4:44-4:74-5:44-5:106-9:9-9:111-12:20-12:21-16:95-31:6)",
      "d": "Like Bay (sale), Shira is also from the category of opposite words (Azdad) and is used in both meanings: buying and selling. However, the word Ishtara is specific to buying. And Mushtari means buyer.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ اشۡتَرٰی مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ وَ اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ بِاَنَّ لَہُمُ الۡجَنَّۃَ»\nTranslation: Allah has purchased from the believers their lives and their wealth in exchange for Paradise.\nNote: (Azdad are words that have two separate meanings that are opposite and contradictory to each other.)"
    }
  ],
  "300": [
    {
      "id": 1386,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Treasure",
      "hw": "خزانہ",
      "s": "« » a large quantity of wealth (3 verses: 3:14-3:75-4:20)",
      "d": "«قِنْطَار» «قَنَاطِیْر» «وَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ مَنۡ  اِنۡ تَاۡمَنۡہُ بِقِنۡطَارٍ یُّؤَدِّہٖۤ  اِلَیۡکَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1387,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Treasure",
      "hw": "خزانہ",
      "s": "« » hidden accumulated wealth (5 verses: 9:34-9:35-11:12-18:82-25:8)",
      "d": "«کَنْز» «کُنُوز» «کَنَزَ المال»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اَمَّا الۡجِدَارُ فَکَانَ لِغُلٰمَیۡنِ یَتِیۡمَیۡنِ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  وَ کَانَ تَحۡتَہٗ کَنۡزٌ لَّہُمَا»\nTranslation: And as for the wall, it belonged to two orphaned boys in the city, and beneath it was a treasure belonging to them."
    }
  ],
  "301": [
    {
      "id": 1389,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Dry Up",
      "hw": "خشک",
      "s": "« » the word is general for dryness (1 verse: 20:77)",
      "d": "« » its opposite is « ». This word is general. It means the cessation of water or moisture from something or a place. The drying up of something.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَسۡرِ بِعِبَادِیۡ فَاضۡرِبۡ لَہُمۡ طَرِیۡقًا فِی الۡبَحۡرِ یَبَسًا»\nTranslation: O Moses! Take My servants by night, then strike for them a dry path through the sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 1390,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Dry Up",
      "hw": "خشک",
      "s": "« » for plants (things that grow from the earth) to naturally become dry and yellow after maturing (2 verses: 39:21-57:20)",
      "d": "«ھَاجَ» «ھَاجَ النَّبَتُ» «ھَاجَتُ الْاَرْض»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ثُمَّ یُخۡرِجُ بِہٖ زَرۡعًا مُّخۡتَلِفًا  اَلۡوَانُہٗ  ثُمَّ یَہِیۡجُ  فَتَرٰىہُ مُصۡفَرًّا ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ  حُطَامًا»\nTranslation: Then He brings forth from it vegetation in diverse colors. Then it dries up, and you see it turning yellow, then He makes it chaff."
    },
    {
      "id": 1391,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Dry Up",
      "hw": "خشک",
      "s": "« » for plants to dry up and wither when the cause is lack of water or the land becoming barren (1 verse: 22:5)",
      "d": "«ھَمَدَ» «نَبَاتٌ ھَامِدَۃٌ» «اَرْضٌ ھَامِدَۃٌ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡاَرۡضَ ہَامِدَۃً  فَاِذَاۤ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہَا الۡمَآءَ   اہۡتَزَّتۡ وَ  رَبَتۡ وَ  اَنۡۢبَتَتۡ مِنۡ  کُلِّ  زَوۡجٍۭ  بَہِیۡجٍ»\nTranslation: Then you see the earth lifeless. But when We send down water upon it, it stirs and swells and brings forth every kind of beautiful growth."
    },
    {
      "id": 1393,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To Diminish, To Recede",
      "hw": "خشک",
      "s": "« » to dry up and diminish, to shrink, for water to subside (2 verses: 11:44-13:8)",
      "d": "« » means to decrease something and for it to decrease on its own (figurative). To shrink something or for it to shrink. It can come in both transitive and intransitive forms (figurative).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ مَا تَحۡمِلُ کُلُّ اُنۡثٰی وَ مَا تَغِیۡضُ الۡاَرۡحَامُ وَ  مَا تَزۡدَادُ»\nTranslation: Allah knows what every female carries and what the wombs diminish [of their pregnancies] and what they increase.\nAnd when « » is related to water, it means the water dries up. And for the earth to absorb and cause the surface water to subside (Munjid).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ قِیۡلَ یٰۤاَرۡضُ ابۡلَعِیۡ مَآءَکِ وَ یٰسَمَآءُ اَقۡلِعِیۡ وَ غِیۡضَ الۡمَآءُ»\nTranslation: And it was said, 'O earth, swallow your water, and O sky, cease [raining].' And the water subsided."
    }
  ],
  "302": [
    {
      "id": 1394,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Attain Salvation; To Grant Salvation; Deliverance; Release",
      "hw": "رہائی",
      "s": "« » the word is general. It is used for attaining release from a predicament, sudden calamity, punishment, affliction, etc. (52 verses: 2:49-2:50-6:63-6:64-7:64-7:72-7:83-7:89-7:141-7:165-10:22-10:23-10:73-10:92-10:103-11:58-11:66-11:94-11:116-12:45-12:110-14:6-17:67-19:72-20:40-20:80-21:9-21:71-21:74-21:76-21:88-23:28-26:65-26:119-26:170-27:53-27:57-29:15-29:24-29:32-29:65-31:32-37:76-37:115-37:134-39:61-40:41-41:18-44:30-54:34-61:10-70:14)",
      "d": "« » means to escape from a sudden calamity, a difficult matter, an affliction, or a punishment. And « » means to grant release to someone else. This word is general.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اِذۡ  اَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ»\nTranslation: When We saved you from the people of Pharaoh.\nAnd « » means salvation, release, and deliverance. (Munjid)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ یٰقَوۡمِ مَا لِیۡۤ  اَدۡعُوۡکُمۡ  اِلَی النَّجٰوۃِ وَ تَدۡعُوۡنَنِیۡۤ   اِلَی  النَّارِ»\nTranslation: And O my people, what is [the matter] with me? I invite you to salvation while you invite me to the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1396,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Attain Salvation; To Grant Salvation; Deliverance; Release",
      "hw": "رہائی",
      "s": "« » this word is more specific than salvation. It comes for granting release from danger or destruction or punishment.\nAlso see 'To Attain Salvation' (5 verses: 3:103-22:73-36:23-36:43-39:19)",
      "d": "« » means to save someone from danger or destruction. To rescue and save (figurative).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ»\nTranslation: Then can you save whoever is in the Fire?"
    }
  ],
  "303": [
    {
      "id": 1397,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Creation; The Created",
      "hw": "مخلوق",
      "s": "« » means to bring something from non-existence into existence. Therefore, everything that exists is included in « » (2 verses: 98:6-98:7)",
      "d": "It is derived from « ». It means to bring something from non-existence into existence. Therefore, everything that exists is included in « ». The entire creation. All of the universe, the earth and the heavens, other planets are also included in it.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ ۙ اُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمۡ خَیۡرُ الۡبَرِیَّۃِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, those who believe and do righteous deeds - they are the best of creation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1398,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Creation; The Created",
      "hw": "مخلوق",
      "s": "« » is used for every type of creature on earth (1 verse: 55:10)",
      "d": "« » the word is used for every type of creature on earth. Whether animate or inanimate.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَضَعَہَا لِلۡاَنَامِ»\nTranslation: And He laid the earth for the creatures.\nAnd « » means the creation that exists on earth at one time. It does not include past and future generations (figurative). However, this word is not used in the Noble Quran. And its plural is « »."
    }
  ],
  "304": [
    {
      "id": 1400,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Dream",
      "hw": "خواب",
      "s": "« » the word is general for sleep (4 verses: 8:43-30:23-37:102-39:42)",
      "d": "« » means the state of sleep. And what a human sees in sleep is also « », whether it has some reality or not.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِذۡ یُرِیۡکَہُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡ مَنَامِکَ قَلِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: When Allah showed them to you in your dream as few."
    },
    {
      "id": 1402,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Dream",
      "hw": "خواب",
      "s": "Ahlam: disjointed, nonsensical, and frightening dreams (2 verses: 12:44-21:5)",
      "d": "Ahlam: plural of Hulm. Halama means to become young and mature. And Hulm means a dream of youth. Nonsensical and frightening dreams (etc.).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَضۡغَاثُ اَحۡلَامٍ ۚ وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِتَاۡوِیۡلِ الۡاَحۡلَامِ بِعٰلِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: They said, 'These are confused dreams, and we are not skilled in interpreting dreams.'"
    }
  ],
  "305": [
    {
      "id": 1404,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Desire",
      "hw": "خواہش",
      "s": "Hawa: evil desires or natural desires used in an evil way (7 verses: 2:87-4:135-5:70-38:26-53:3-53:23-79:40)",
      "d": "Hawa: its plural is Ahwa, meaning desires of the self and inclination towards them. Hawa yahwi means to fall from above. And Al-Mahwah means a pit. And Ahwa are those desires by pursuing which a person loses his worth and status (Manjad). This word is generally used in a negative sense. In the words of Ibn Faris, 'Hawa an-nafs khalun min kulli khair' meaning desires of the self are those in which there is no good.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ اَمَّا مَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ رَبِّہٖ وَ نَہَی النَّفۡسَ عَنِ الۡہَوٰی فَاِنَّ الۡجَنَّۃَ ہِیَ الۡمَاۡوٰی»\nTranslation: And whoever feared the standing before his Lord and restrained his soul from evil desires, then indeed, Paradise is the refuge."
    }
  ],
  "307": [
    {
      "id": 1410,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Food. Bringing Food",
      "hw": "خوراک",
      "s": "Qut: that amount of food by which a living being can survive (1 verse: 41:10)",
      "d": "Qut: meaning food, sustenance. That amount of food by which a living being can survive. Its plural is Aqwat. And Qata means to provide food. And Aqat means to give something from which strength is obtained. They say 'Ma lahu quwtu laylatin' meaning he has no food even for a night (etc.).\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ جَعَلَ فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ مِنۡ فَوۡقِہَا وَ بٰرَکَ فِیۡہَا وَ قَدَّرَ فِیۡہَاۤ اَقۡوَاتَہَا فِیۡۤ اَرۡبَعَۃِ اَیَّامٍ»\nTranslation: And He placed therein mountains from above it, and blessed it, and decreed its sustenance in four days."
    },
    {
      "id": 1411,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Food. Bringing Food",
      "hw": "خوراک",
      "s": "Mara: to bring food for family and dependents, and Mayr: grain or edible provisions that are stored. (1 verse: 12:65)",
      "d": "Mayr: meaning food, sustenance. And Miyarah means collected food. Its plural is Mayr. And Mara and Amara ayalahu means to bring food for one's family. And Mayir and Mayyar means the one who brings food (Manjad). Thus, Mayr refers to those provisions that are stored.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ نَمِیۡرُ اَہۡلَنَا وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ بَعِیۡرٍ»\nTranslation: And we will bring provisions for our family and protect our brother and increase the load of a camel."
    },
    {
      "id": 1412,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Food. Bringing food.",
      "hw": "خوراک",
      "s": "« » means to bring food for one's family and dependents, and « » means grain or edible provisions stored for reserve. (1 verse: 12/65)",
      "d": "«مَیْر» «مِیَرَۃ» «مَیْر» «مَارَ» «اَمَارَ عَیَالُہٗ» «مَائِر» «مَیَّار» «مَیْر»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ نَمِیۡرُ اَہۡلَنَا وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ  بَعِیۡرٍ»\nTranslation: And (this time) we will bring provisions for our household and protect our brother and bring back an extra camel-load."
    }
  ],
  "308": [
    {
      "id": 1413,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "« » is used merely to express approval. (26 verses: 2:144-4:24-5:3-5:119-9:38-9:58-9:59-9:83-9:87-9:93-9:96-9:100-10:7-19:6-19:55-20:109-27:19-33:51-46:15-48:18-58:22-69:21-88:9-89:28-98:8-101:7)",
      "d": "« » is a well-known word meaning to be pleased, to express approval. Its opposite is « » meaning to be displeased or angry (transitive/intransitive).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«لَقَدۡ رَضِیَ اللّٰہُ  عَنِ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ  اِذۡ یُبَایِعُوۡنَکَ تَحۡتَ الشَّجَرَۃِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah was pleased with the believers when they gave you their pledge under the tree."
    },
    {
      "id": 1416,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "« » means happiness derived from the cleanliness, elegance, and spring of the surroundings. (2 verses: 30:15-43:70)",
      "d": "«حَبَرَ» «حَبِرَ» «حَبِرَ الْاَرْض» «تَحَبَّر» «حَبَرَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ فَہُمۡ فِیۡ رَوۡضَۃٍ یُّحۡبَرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then as for those who believed and did righteous deeds, they will be in a garden, rejoicing."
    },
    {
      "id": 1417,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "« » means to have one's face light up upon receiving good news or a good thing (8 verses: 3:170-3:171-9:111-9:124-15:67-30:48-39:45-80:39).",
      "d": "« » means to peel skin, and « » means the surface of the skin. « » denotes joy whose effects become visible on the skin or face. Having one's face light up. When one becomes happy upon hearing good news or receiving a good thing, the word « » is used. And « » means to give good news that makes another happy. To announce glad tidings.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاسۡتَبۡشِرُوۡا بِبَیۡعِکُمُ الَّذِیۡ بَایَعۡتُمۡ بِہٖ»\nTranslation: Rejoice in the bargain which you have concluded.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَ بَشَّرُوۡہُ بِغُلٰمٍ عَلِیۡمٍ»\nTranslation: And (the angels) gave him glad tidings of a knowledgeable boy."
    },
    {
      "id": 1418,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "« » is a joy that also engages the senses (1 verse: 4:3).",
      "d": "« » is a joy that engages not only the heart but also the senses of a person. ( ) « » means pure things, and « » means fragrance. ( )\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَانۡکِحُوۡا مَا طَابَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ»\nTranslation: Marry those women who please you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1419,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "« » means to become happy and start boasting. To celebrate joy. (21 verses: 3:120-3:170-3:188-6:44-9:50-9:81-10:22-10:58-11:10-13:26-13:36-23:53-27:36-28:76-30:4-30:32-30:36-40:75-40:83-42:48-57:23)",
      "d": "«فَرِحَ» «فَرِحَ الْقَلْب»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَرِحِیۡنَ بِمَاۤ اٰتٰہُمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ»\nTranslation: They are happy with what Allah has bestowed upon them of His favor.\n«فَرِحَ النَّفْس»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَلَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ اٰتٰىکُمۡ»\nTranslation: So that you may not grieve over what you have missed nor exult over what He has given you.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«لَا تَفۡرَحۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ الۡفَرِحِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Do not exult. Indeed, Allah does not like the exultant."
    },
    {
      "id": 1420,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy, to do, and to seem",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "« » to engage in cheerful banter and to have a happy disposition (1 verse: 83:31)",
      "d": "«فَکِہَ» «طَیِّبَ النَّفْس» «وَاِذَا انۡقَلَبُوۡۤا اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہِمُ انۡقَلَبُوۡا فَکِہِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1421,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy. To do and to feel.",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "« » means to be happy at an enemy's misfortune (1 verse: 7:150).",
      "d": "«شَمِتَ» «اَشْمَتَ» «شَمَاتَتَ اَعْداء»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَا تُشۡمِتۡ بِیَ الۡاَعۡدَآءَ»\nTranslation: (Haroon (AS) said: O Musa (AS)) Do not give the enemies an occasion to rejoice over me."
    },
    {
      "id": 1422,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "To be happy, to do, and to seem",
      "hw": "خوش",
      "s": "« » to feel a delightful wonder in the heart, where the cause is unknown, a blend of joy and amazement (8 verses: 2:204-2:221-5:100-9:25-33:52-48:29-57:20-63:4)",
      "d": "«اَعْجَبَ» «وَ مِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یُّعۡجِبُکَ قَوۡلُہٗ فِی الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا»"
    }
  ],
  "309": [
    {
      "id": 1425,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperity",
      "hw": "خوشحالی",
      "s": "« » that prosperity with which the heart is also content (43 verses: 2:57-2:168-2:172-2:267-3:38-3:179-4:2-4:43-4:160-5:4-5:5-5:6-5:87-5:88-5:100-7:32-7:58-7:157-7:160-8:26-8:37-8:69-9:72-10:22-10:93-13:29-14:24-16:32-16:72-16:97-16:114-17:70-20:81-22:24-23:51-24:26-24:61-34:15-35:10-40:64-45:16-46:20-61:12)",
      "d": "«طَابَ» «طَیِّب» «طِیْب» «طُوبٰی» «اَلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ طُوۡبٰی لَہُمۡ  وَحُسۡنُ مَاٰبٍ»"
    }
  ],
  "310": [
    {
      "id": 1426,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Bunches (of fruit)",
      "hw": "خوشے",
      "s": "« » is used for the emergence of a fruit bunch from its sheath. And « » is the state of being ripe and ready to be picked. And « » is the intermediate state. But « » is used only for date and grape bunches. (4 verses: 6:99-26:148-37:65-50:10)",
      "d": "«طَلَعَ» «طَلَعَ» «وَ النَّخۡلَ بٰسِقٰتٍ  لَّہَا طَلۡعٌ  نَّضِیۡدٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1427,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Bunches (of fruit)",
      "hw": "خوشے",
      "s": "« » is such ripe fruit that is completely ready to be picked (2 verses: 69:23-76:14)",
      "d": "«قُطُوْف» «قِطْف» «قِطْف» «فَہُوَفِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ فِیۡ جَنَّۃٍ عَالِیَۃٍ قُطُوۡفُہَا دَانِیَۃٌ» «قُطُوْف»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1428,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Bunches (of fruit)",
      "hw": "خوشے",
      "s": "« » such grape and date bunches that are not yet ready to be picked (1 verse: 6:99)",
      "d": "«قِنْوَان» «قِنْو» «وَمِنَ النَّخۡلِ مِنۡ طَلۡعِہَا قِنۡوَانٌ دَانِیَۃٌ»"
    }
  ],
  "311": [
    {
      "id": 1429,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Betrayal",
      "hw": "خیانت",
      "s": "« » means breach of covenant and consuming entrusted property by trickery, whereas « » involves theft in betrayal. (8 verses: 4:105-5:13-8:27-8:58-8:71-12:52-40:19-66:10)",
      "d": "«خَانَ» «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَخُوۡنُوا اللّٰہَ وَالرَّسُوۡلَ وَتَخُوۡنُوۡۤا اَمٰنٰتِکُمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1430,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Betrayal",
      "hw": "خیانت",
      "s": "« » means to betray (1 verse: 3:161)",
      "d": "«غَلَّ» «غَلَّ» «وَمَا کَانَ لِنَبِیٍّ اَنۡ یَّغُلَّ ؕ وَمَنۡ یَّغۡلُلۡ یَاۡتِ بِمَا غَلَّ  یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ»"
    }
  ],
  "312": [
    {
      "id": 1431,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tent. Canopy.",
      "hw": "خیمہ",
      "s": "« » means tent (1 verse: 55:72).",
      "d": "« » (plural of  )   is a well-known word. It refers to canopies made of thick cloth or canvas for protection from sun and rain, which usually do not have flat roofs but are sloped. According to the author of Minjd, any covered house not made of bricks, stones, or mud. And « » also refers to a camel's howdah or litter. (Minjd) The Quran states:\n«حُوۡرٌ مَّقۡصُوۡرٰتٌ فِی الۡخِیَامِ»\nTranslation: Who are confined in the tents."
    },
    {
      "id": 1432,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tent. Canopy.",
      "hw": "خیمہ",
      "s": "« » meaning shade (2 verses: 7:171-26:189)",
      "d": "«ظُلَّۃٌ» «ظُلَّۃ» «ظلیل» «ظِلّ» «ظِلَال» «ظِلًّا ظَلِیْلًا»\n«وَاِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ»\nTranslation: And when We raised the mountain over them as if it were a canopy."
    },
    {
      "id": 1433,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tent. Canopy.",
      "hw": "خیمہ",
      "s": "« » meaning tent, shamiana, pavilion (1 verse: 18:29)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « » and refers to a shamiana that has only walls. Such canopies are used in weddings. This word is of Persian origin (i.e., a word adopted into Arabic with slight modification).\n«اِنَّاۤ اَعۡتَدۡنَا لِلظّٰلِمِیۡنَ نَارًا ۙ اَحَاطَ بِہِمۡ سُرَادِقُہَا»\nTranslation: We have prepared for the wrongdoers a fire, surrounding them are its canopies."
    }
  ],
  "313": [
    {
      "id": 1435,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To enter. To make enter.",
      "hw": "داخل",
      "s": "« » to enter a tight space (8 verses: 3:27-7:40-22:61-31:29-34:2-35:13-57:4-57:6)",
      "d": "« » means to enter a tight space (intransitive), with difficulty, to squeeze in.\n«وَلَا یَدۡخُلُوۡنَ الۡجَنَّۃَ حَتّٰی یَلِجَ الۡجَمَلُ فِیۡ سَمِّ الۡخِیَاطِ»\nTranslation: And they will not enter Paradise until the camel enters through the eye of the needle.\nFor entering or squeezing into a tight space, « » is used (transitive).\n«یُوۡلِجُ الَّیۡلَ  فِی النَّہَارِ  وَ یُوۡلِجُ النَّہَارَ فِی الَّیۡلِ»\nTranslation: Allah causes the night to enter the day and causes the day to enter the night."
    },
    {
      "id": 1436,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To enter. To make enter.",
      "hw": "داخل",
      "s": "« » meaning to enter fire (15 verses: 4:10-4:90-11:81-14:29-28:35-36:64-38:56-52:16-58:8-69:31-82:15-84:12-87:12-88:4-111:3)",
      "d": "« » is specifically used for entering fire. Meaning to enter fire and burn (intransitive).\n«جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ؕ وَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرَارُ»\nTranslation: They will enter Hell, and evil is the resting place.\nFor causing to enter fire or burn, « » is used (transitive).\n«خُذُوۡہُ فَغُلُّوۡہُ ثُمَّ الۡجَحِیۡمَ صَلُّوۡہُ»\nTranslation: Seize him and chain him, then cast him into Hell."
    },
    {
      "id": 1437,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To enter. To make enter.",
      "hw": "داخل",
      "s": "« » to pull one thing into another or to enter (12 verses: 15:12-16:69-20:53-23:27-26:200-28:32-39:21-69:32-71:20-72:17-72:27-74:42)",
      "d": "« » is used in many meanings and both transitive and intransitive forms, and in all, the meaning of entering is found.\nExamples:\n(1) To thread or pierce, like threading a needle.\n«کَذٰلِکَ سَلَکۡنٰہُ  فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Thus have We inserted disbelief into the hearts of the criminals. (Jalandhari) / Ghasaa diya (Osmani).\n(2) To put in, to enter. Like putting a hand in a pocket.\n«اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِسُوۡٓءٍ»\nTranslation: Put your hand into your bosom, it will come out white without any disease.\nNote that the same verse elsewhere uses « » instead of « ».\n«وَاَدۡخِلۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِ سُوۡٓءٍ»\nTranslation: And put your hand into your bosom, it will come out white without any disease.\n(3) To go along a path.\n«فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا»\nTranslation: Then follow the ways of your Lord submissively.\nIn this verse, « » is also translated as « » (m. q.).\n«مَا سَلَکَکُمۡ  فِیۡ سَقَرَ»\nTranslation: What has caused you to enter Hell?\nConsidering all these, the author of 'Muntahi al-Arb' states the briefest meaning of « » as 'pulling one thing into another', i.e., to draw one thing into another or to draw one thing out of another. According to 'Manjad', it means to place one thing into another. And according to 'Maqayis al-Lughah', its basic meanings are two: (1) to go along a path, (2) to enter one thing into another, to thread."
    }
  ],
  "314": [
    {
      "id": 1438,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Guardian.",
      "hw": "داروغہ",
      "s": "« » means guardian, keeper (5 verses: 15:22-39:71-39:73-40:49-67:8).",
      "d": "«خَزَنَ» «خَازِن»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ اُلۡقِیَ فِیۡہَا فَوۡجٌ سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ نَذِیۡرٌ»\nTranslation: Whenever a group is thrown into it (Hell), its keepers will ask them, 'Did no warner come to you?'\nThe difference between « » and « » is the same as between   (guardian) and   (supervisor). The responsibility of « » is merely to guard the gathered items, while « » also has strict oversight because he has authority over them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1439,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Guardian.",
      "hw": "داروغہ",
      "s": "« » means supervisor, keeper, guardian (2 verses: 52:37-88:22).",
      "d": "«مُصَیْطِر» «سطر» «سَیْطر» «سَیْطَرَ عَلٰی» «سیطر»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَذَکِّرۡ ؕ اِنَّمَاۤ اَنۡتَ مُذَکِّرٌ لَسۡتَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِمُصَۜیۡطِرٍ»\nTranslation: So remind. You are only a reminder; you are not a guardian over them.\nMeaning, you have no authority over them to compel them to accept your message."
    }
  ],
  "315": [
    {
      "id": 1440,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To brand. To mark.",
      "hw": "داغ ",
      "s": "« » meaning to inscribe on the body, to dig etc. (8 verses: 2:273-7:46-7:48-15:75-47:30-48:29-55:41-68:16)",
      "d": "« » means to mark, to brand (intransitive). And meaning to inscribe on the body, to dig etc. (transitive). And « » means to dye, and « » and « » is the thing with which one brands or colors.\n«سَنَسِمُہٗ عَلَی الۡخُرۡطُوۡمِ»\nTranslation: So We will brand him on the snout (or nose)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1442,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To brand. To mark.",
      "hw": "داغ ",
      "s": "« » such a brand or mark that is different from the body's color (1 verse: 2:71)",
      "d": "«وَشِیَ» «وَشَیْتُ الشَّیْءُ وَشْیًا» «وَشْیۃ» «شِیَۃ»\n«مُسَلَّمَۃٌ لَّا شِیَۃَ فِیۡہَا»\nTranslation: (The cow) should be without any blemish, no spot on it."
    }
  ],
  "316": [
    {
      "id": 1444,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Emaciated. Thin.",
      "hw": "دبلا",
      "s": "« » is that which becomes thin and lean due to exercise and hardship (1 verse: 22:27)",
      "d": "«ضَمَر ، اَلْاَضْمَار» «ضَامِر» «ضِامِر»\n«وَ اَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ  رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ»\nTranslation: And proclaim to the people the Hajj; they will come to you on foot and on every lean camel, coming from every distant path."
    }
  ],
  "317": [
    {
      "id": 1447,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To be distant / To make distant",
      "hw": "دراز",
      "s": "« » to increase the distance between two things and make it long (1 Verse: 34:19)",
      "d": "« » means to be far. And « » means to increase the distance between two things.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَقَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا بٰعِدۡ بَیۡنَ اَسۡفَارِنَا»\nTranslation: So they said: O our Lord! Create distance between our journeys."
    }
  ],
  "318": [
    {
      "id": 1448,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To be behind / To follow",
      "hw": "درپے",
      "s": "« » to be behind something temporarily and incidentally (1 Verse: 80:6)",
      "d": "« » means to be behind something like an echo. To pay attention (transitive). (An echo is the sound that returns after striking a mountain or dome, etc.)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اَمَّا مَنِ اسۡتَغۡنٰی فَاَنۡتَ لَہٗ تَصَدّٰی»\nTranslation: As for him who is indifferent, you are behind him (paying attention to him)."
    }
  ],
  "319": [
    {
      "id": 1451,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "« » plants without trunks, shrubs, creeping plants (13 Verses: 6:97-7:54-16:12-16:16-22:18-37:88-52:49-53:1-55:6-56:75-77:8-81:2-86:3)",
      "d": "« » means both star and plants without trunks. That is, shrubs, creeping plants, etc. (transitive)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّ النَّجۡمُ وَ الشَّجَرُ یَسۡجُدٰنِ»\nTranslation: And the plants (or stars) and the trees are prostrating (to Allah)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1452,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "« » plants with strong roots and thorny trees (1 Verse: 34:16)",
      "d": "« » means to take root in the earth. And « » is every tree whose roots are strong. Generally, it is applied to thorny trees (transitive. See Manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ بِجَنَّتَیۡہِمۡ جَنَّتَیۡنِ ذَوَاتَیۡ اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ وَّ اَثۡلٍ وَّ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡ سِدۡرٍ قَلِیۡلٍ»\nTranslation: And We replaced their two gardens with two other gardens bearing bitter fruit, and some thorny shrubs, and a few lote trees."
    },
    {
      "id": 1453,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "« » the plant that has no trunk, like the vine of a cucumber, pumpkin, gourd, etc. (1 Verse: 37:146)",
      "d": "« » means every tree that has no trunk. (transitive) It is generally applied to vine plants and specifically to the pumpkin vine.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اَنۡۢبَتۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ شَجَرَۃً مِّنۡ یَّقۡطِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: And We caused a gourd tree to grow over him."
    },
    {
      "id": 1454,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "« » thorny shrubs (1 Verse: 88:6)",
      "d": "« » means a thorny shrub or a bush with thorns (transitive)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«لَیۡسَ لَہُمۡ طَعَامٌ اِلَّا مِنۡ ضَرِیۡعٍ»\nTranslation: They will have no food except from thorny shrubs."
    },
    {
      "id": 1455,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Trees and Plants",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "« » the Zaqqum tree, whose leaves are broad, thick, thorny, and extremely bitter in taste (3 Verses: 37:62-44:43-56:52)",
      "d": "« » means the Zaqqum tree whose leaves are broad, thick, and thorny. And it is extremely bitter in taste.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنَّ شَجَرَتَ الزَّقُّوۡمِ طَعَامُ الۡاَثِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, the tree of Zaqqum is the food of the sinful."
    }
  ],
  "320": [
    {
      "id": 1456,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Correct / Right",
      "hw": "درست",
      "s": "« » correctness is related to a person's statement or opinion, while truth is everything that is proven correct through experience and observation (1 Verse: 78:38)",
      "d": "«صَوَاب» «خَطَا» «صَابَ واَصَابَ السَّھْم» «اِسْتِصْوَاب» «صَوَیْب» «مُصِیْب» «مُصِیْبَۃٌ» «صَوَاب»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«لَّا یَتَکَلَّمُوۡنَ اِلَّا مَنۡ اَذِنَ لَہُ الرَّحۡمٰنُ وَ قَالَ صَوَابًا»\nTranslation: They will not speak except for him whom the Most Merciful permits, and he will say what is correct."
    },
    {
      "id": 1457,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Correct / Right",
      "hw": "درست",
      "s": "« » is used for truth, veracity (252 Verses: 2:26-2:42-2:61-2:71-2:91-2:109-2:119-2:121-2:144-2:146-2:147-2:149-2:176-2:180-2:213-2:236-2:241-2:252-2:282-3:3-3:21-3:60-3:62-3:71-3:86-3:102-3:108-3:112-3:154-3:181-4:105-4:122-4:151-4:155-4:170-4:171-5:27-5:48-5:77-5:83-5:84-5:107-5:116-6:5-6:30-6:57-6:62-6:66-6:73-6:91-6:93-6:114-6:141-6:151-7:8-7:30-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:53-7:89-7:105-7:118-7:146-7:159-7:169-7:181-8:4-8:5-8:6-8:7-8:8-8:32-8:74-9:29-9:33-9:48-9:111-10:4-10:5-10:23-10:30-10:32-10:33-10:35-10:36-10:53-10:55-10:76-10:77-10:82-10:94-10:96-10:103-10:108-11:17-11:45-11:79-11:120-12:51-12:100-13:1-13:14-13:17-13:19-14:19-14:22-15:8-15:55-15:64-15:85-16:3-16:36-16:38-16:102-17:16-17:26-17:33-17:81-17:105-18:13-18:21-18:29-18:44-18:56-18:98-19:34-20:114-21:18-21:24-21:55-21:97-21:112-22:6-22:18-22:40-22:54-22:62-22:74-22:78-23:41-23:62-23:70-23:71-23:90-23:116-24:25-24:49-25:26-25:33-25:68-27:79-28:3-28:13-28:39-28:48-28:53-28:63-28:75-29:44-29:68-30:8-30:38-30:47-30:60-31:9-31:30-31:33-32:3-32:13-33:4-33:53-34:6-34:23-34:26-34:43-34:48-34:49-35:5-35:24-35:31-36:7-36:70-37:31-37:37-38:14-38:22-38:26-38:64-38:84-39:2-39:5-39:19-39:41-39:67-39:69-39:71-39:75-40:5-40:6-40:20-40:25-40:55-40:75-40:77-40:78-41:15-41:25-41:53-42:17-42:18-42:24-42:42-43:29-43:30-43:78-43:86-44:39-45:6-45:22-45:29-45:32-46:3-46:7-46:17-46:18-46:20-46:30-46:34-47:2-47:3-48:27-48:28-50:5-50:14-50:19-50:42-51:19-51:23-53:28-56:95-57:16-57:27-60:1-61:9-64:3-69:51-70:24-78:39-84:2-84:5-103:3)",
      "d": "« » means truth, veracity, reality. That is, everything that is proven correct through experience and observation. (transitive) Its opposite is « » (falsehood).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ وَ فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ لَہُمۡ اَنَّہُ الۡحَقُّ»\nTranslation: We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves until it becomes clear to them that it (the revelation or Quran) is the truth."
    },
    {
      "id": 1458,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To correct",
      "hw": "درست",
      "s": "« » is used to correct moral and material corruption, while « » is used to correct creative flaws (40 Verses: 2:11-2:160-2:182-2:220-2:224-2:228-3:89-4:16-4:35-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:146-5:39-6:48-6:54-7:35-7:56-7:85-11:88-17:142-7:170-8:1-10:81-11:117-13:23-16:119-21:90-24:5-26:152-27:48-28:19-33:71-40:8-42:40-46:15-47:2-47:5-49:9-49:10)",
      "d": "The opposite of « » is « » meaning corruption. And « » means to correct corruption. To remove mischief and corruption. To correct the corruption caused by excess or deficiency (surplus or shortage) in something. (transitive)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اِنۡ اُرِیۡدُ اِلَّا الۡاِصۡلَاحَ مَا اسۡتَطَعۡتُ»\nTranslation: (Prophet Shuaib (AS) said to his people) I only intend to correct (reform) what I am able to (in your affairs)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1459,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Correct / To Make Straight",
      "hw": "درست",
      "s": "« » means to correct, smooth, equalize, or straighten a task or thing. (13 verses: 4:42-15:29-19:10-19:17-19:43-20:58-20:135-26:98-38:72-67:22-75:4-75:38-87:2)",
      "d": "«سَوٰی یَسْوِی» «سَوّٰی» «اَلْاِسْتِقَامَۃ وَالْاِعْتِدَال»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ فَسَوّٰی»\nTranslation: Who created and then proportioned (or made straight)."
    }
  ],
  "321": [
    {
      "id": 1460,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between",
      "hw": "درمیان",
      "s": "« » is a preposition that indicates separation or distinction between two distinct things. (181 verses: 2:68-2:102-2:113-2:136-2:164-2:182-2:188-2:213-2:224-2:232-2:237-2:282-2:285-3:19-3:23-3:30-3:55-3:64-3:84-3:103-3:140-4:23-4:29-4:35-4:58-4:65-4:73-4:90-4:92-4:105-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:141-4:143-4:150-4:152-5:14-5:17-5:18-5:25-5:42-5:48-5:49-5:64-5:91-5:106-6:19-6:53-6:58-6:94-7:44-7:46-7:87-7:89-8:1-8:24-8:63-8:72-9:107-10:19-10:28-10:29-10:45-10:47-10:54-10:93-11:43-11:110-12:100-13:43-15:85-16:66-16:92-16:94-16:124-17:45-17:53-17:96-17:110-18:19-18:21-18:32-18:52-18:61-18:78-18:93-18:94-18:95-18:96-19:37-19:64-19:65-20:6-20:58-20:62-20:94-20:103-21:16-21:93-22:17-22:56-22:69-23:53-23:101-24:43-24:48-24:51-24:63-25:38-25:50-25:53-25:59-25:67-26:24-26:28-26:118-27:61-27:78-28:28-29:25-29:52-30:8-30:21-32:4-32:25-34:18-34:19-34:26-34:54-37:5-37:158-38:8-38:10-38:22-38:26-38:27-38:66-39:3-39:46-39:69-39:75-40:48-41:5-41:34-41:45-42:14-42:15-42:21-42:38-43:32-43:38-43:52-43:65-43:85-44:7-44:38-45:17-46:3-46:8-48:29-49:9-49:10-50:38-54:25-54:28-55:20-55:44-56:60-57:13-57:20-59:7-59:14-60:3-60:4-60:7-60:10-65:6-65:12-78:37-86:7)",
      "d": "« » is a preposition that indicates separation or distinction between two distinct things. And « » means to be distant. Therefore, « » comes for indicating distance or separation between two things. According to Ibn al-Faris, three elements are found in « »: (1) separation, (2) distance, (3) clarity. (M.L.) That is, a thing being distinct from another and clear.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَیۡنَ السَّمَآءِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ»\nTranslation: Between the heavens and the earth.\nThen this word is also used in a spiritual sense, just as it is used in a physical sense.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«فَاحۡکُمۡ بَیۡنَنَا بِالۡحَقِّ»\nTranslation: Judge between us with truth!"
    },
    {
      "id": 1461,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between.",
      "hw": "درمیان",
      "s": "« » means between different parts of the same thing or between two related things (8 verses: 9:47-14:31-17:5-17:91-18:33-24:43-27:61-30:48).",
      "d": "« » refers to a space between two things that are connected to each other. « » also means the tool for cleaning the spaces between teeth, and the act of cleaning those spaces. Similarly, during ablution, water is passed between the fingers of the hand or the beard hairs.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا خِلٰلَہُمَا نَہَرًا»\nTranslation: And We caused a river to flow between them (the two gardens).\nThen this word is also used for the space between separate parts of the same thing.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَتَرَی الۡوَدۡقَ یَخۡرُجُ مِنۡ خِلٰلِہٖ»\nTranslation: Then you see the rain droplets coming out from within it (the cloud)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1462,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Between.",
      "hw": "درمیان",
      "s": "« » means the middle of something in terms of number, quantity, or distance (2 verses: 2:143-2:238).",
      "d": "« » is the middle point of anything where the distance to both sides is equal. Or if there are more than two sides, the number on both sides is equal. Essentially, it's the point of moderation between deficiency and excess. Then this word is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حٰفِظُوۡا عَلَی الصَّلَوٰتِ وَ الصَّلَوۃِ الۡوُسۡطٰی»\nTranslation: Guard the prayers, especially the middle prayer.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ جَعَلۡنٰکُمۡ اُمَّۃً وَّسَطًا»\nTranslation: And thus We have made you a moderate nation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1464,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Moderation / The Middle Path",
      "hw": "درمیان",
      "s": "« » means the path of moderation, the middle way. (3 verses: 9:42-16:9-31:19)",
      "d": "«قَصْد» «قَصَدَ» «اِقْتَصَدَ فِی الْنَفَقَۃ» «قَصَدَ السَّبِیْل»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اقۡصِدۡ فِیۡ مَشۡیِکَ وَ اغۡضُضۡ مِنۡ صَوۡتِکَ»\nTranslation: And be moderate in your pace and lower your voice."
    }
  ],
  "322": [
    {
      "id": 1465,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy / Enmity",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "« » means enemy. (49 verses: 2:36-2:97-2:98-2:168-2:208-3:103-4:45-4:92-4:101-5:14-5:64-5:82-5:91-6:112-6:142-7:22-7:24-7:129-7:150-8:60-9:83-9:114-9:120-12:5-17:53-18:50-20:39-20:80-20:117-20:123-25:31-26:77-28:8-28:15-28:19-35:6-36:60-41:19-41:28-41:34-43:62-43:67-46:6-60:1-60:2-60:4-61:14-63:4-64:14)",
      "d": "« » its plural is « ». Such an enemy who is malevolent, harboring malice. One who thinks of evil and harm and is pleased by causing distress. And its opposite is « » (truthful friend) (F.L. 168).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الشَّیۡطٰنَ لَکُمَا عَدُوٌّ مُّبِیۡنٌ»\nTranslation: Indeed, Satan is to you both a clear enemy!\nAnd « » means enmity and malevolence. And this is the first degree of enmity. (F.L. 169) And it also means to withdraw from someone's help. Its opposite is « » (guardianship, friendship). (Faqih al-Lughah 106)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1466,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy / Enmity",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "« » means to detest or feel aversion towards something or someone. (5 verses: 3:118-5:14-5:64-5:91-60:4)",
      "d": "« » means to detest something or someone. This is the second degree of enmity and its opposite is « » (love). And « » means to intend to degrade and humiliate someone (Faqih al-Lughah 106).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَلۡقَیۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمُ الۡعَدَاوَۃَ وَ الۡبَغۡضَآءَ اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ»\nTranslation: And We have cast between them enmity and hatred until the Day of Resurrection."
    },
    {
      "id": 1467,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy / Enmity",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "« » means to harbor enmity. (3 verses: 5:2-5:8-108:3)",
      "d": "« » means to harbor enmity. To bear malice. To hate (Munjid). And its masdar (verbal noun) is « ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَجۡرِمَنَّکُمۡ شَنَاٰنُ قَوْمٍ عَلٰۤی اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا»\nTranslation: And let not the hatred of a people prevent you from being just.\nAnd « » is a person who is both malevolent (wishing ill) and harboring malice. That is, he holds enmity and also « » (some, i.e., the worst kind). Thus, he is the worst enemy, and this is the third degree of enmity. (F.L. 169)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ شَانِئَکَ ہُوَ الۡاَبۡتَرُ»\nTranslation: Indeed, your enemy will be the one cut off (without progeny)."
    }
  ],
  "323": [
    {
      "id": 1470,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Pray / To Give",
      "hw": "دعا",
      "s": "« » means to give a prayer for long life. (1 verse: 4:86)",
      "d": "«حَیَّ» «حَیَّیَ , تَحِیَّۃً» «حَیَّاکَ اللہ» «سَلَّم» «سَلَام» «سَلَّم» «حَیَّ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا حُیِّیۡتُمۡ بِتَحِیَّۃٍ فَحَیُّوۡا بِاَحۡسَنَ مِنۡہَاۤ اَوۡ رُدُّوۡہَا»\nTranslation: And when you are greeted with a greeting, greet in return with a better one or at least return it."
    }
  ],
  "324": [
    {
      "id": 1472,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "« » means (the heart) the famous organ. The source and center of spirit, life, intellect, understanding, and contemplation. (124 verses: 2:7-2:10-2:74-2:88-2:93-2:97-2:118-2:204-2:225-2:260-2:283-3:7-3:8-3:103-3:126-3:151-3:154-3:156-3:159-3:167-4:63-4:155-5:13-5:41-5:52-5:113-6:25-6:43-6:46-7:100-7:101-7:179-8:2-8:10-8:11-8:12-8:24-8:49-8:63-8:70-9:8-9:15-9:45-9:60-9:64-9:77-9:87-9:93-9:110-9:117-9:125-9:127-10:74-10:88-13:28-15:12-16:22-16:106-16:108-17:46-18:14-18:28-18:57-21:3-22:32-22:35-22:46-22:53-22:54-23:60-23:63-24:37-24:50-26:89-26:194-26:200-28:10-30:59-33:4-33:5-33:10-33:12-33:26-33:32-33:51-33:53-33:60-34:23-37:84-39:22-39:23-39:45-40:18-40:35-41:5-42:24-45:23-47:16-47:20-47:24-47:29-48:4-48:11-48:12-48:18-48:26-49:3-49:7-49:14-50:33-50:37-57:16-57:27-58:22-59:2-59:10-59:14-61:5-63:3-64:11-66:4-74:31-79:8-83:14)",
      "d": "« » means (the heart) the famous organ. Its plural is « ». It is the source and center of spirit and life. Allah the Exalted has chosen the heart for intellect, understanding, thought, and reflection. That is, what modern physiology has declared related to the brain, the Noble Quran has declared related to the heart.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَہُمۡ قُلُوۡبٌ لَّا یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ بِہَا»\nTranslation: They have hearts with which they do not understand."
    },
    {
      "id": 1473,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof/Evidence",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«Bayyinah»: A clear and manifest matter, a proof with which the claimant can invalidate the other party's statement (74 verses: 2:87, 2:92, 2:99, 2:159, 2:185, 2:209, 2:211, 2:213, 2:253, 3:86, 3:97, 3:105, 3:183, 3:184, 4:19, 4:153, 5:32, 5:110, 6:57, 6:157, 7:73, 7:85, 7:101, 7:105, 8:42, 9:70, 10:13, 10:15, 10:74, 11:17, 11:28, 11:53, 11:63, 11:88, 14:9, 16:44, 17:101, 19:73, 20:72, 20:133, 22:16, 22:72, 24:1, 24:34, 24:46, 28:36, 29:35, 29:39, 29:49, 30:9, 30:47, 33:30, 34:43, 35:25, 40:22, 40:28, 40:34, 40:50, 40:66, 40:83, 43:63, 45:17, 45:25, 46:7, 47:14, 57:9, 57:25, 58:5, 61:6, 64:6, 65:1, 65:11, 98:1, 98:4)",
      "d": "«Bayyinah» means a clear and manifest matter, a proof. Some explanation of «Bayyinah» is also derived from this saying of the Prophet (peace be upon him): 'Al-Bayyinatu ‘alā al-mudda‘ī wa-al-yamīnu ‘alā al-mudda‘ā ‘alayhi' (Bukhari). Meaning: Providing proof is the responsibility of the claimant, and if he cannot, then the oath is upon the one against whom the claim is made. Now consider, for example, if Zaid claims a sum of money from Bakr and Bakr denies it. If Zaid has in his possession any writing from Bakr that can prove this claim or assist in proving it, that writing is a «Bayyinah». Similarly, if Zaid can prove it by presenting witnesses, that too is a «Bayyinah». «Bayyinah» is such a proof before which the other party is rendered speechless. The very existence of the Quran is a «Bayyinah». Against which, despite confrontation, the disbelievers cannot present any proof. Similarly, its verses are also «Bayyināt». For example, the Quran states: «Bal huwa āyātun bayyinātun fī ṣudūri alladhīna ūtū al-‘ilma. Wa-mā yajḥadu bi-āyātinā illā al-ẓālimūn» (29:49). Translation: Rather, it [i.e., the Quran] is clear verses [preserved] within the breasts of those given knowledge. And none deny Our verses except the wrongdoers. In this verse, the word «Jahd» is used to indicate that they acknowledge in their hearts that these verses are clear proofs, even though they deny them with their tongues."
    },
    {
      "id": 1474,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«ṣadr» means chest (41 verses: 3:29-3:118-3:119-3:154-4:90-5:7-6:125-7:2-7:43-8:43-9:14-10:57-11:5-11:12-15:47-15:97-16:106-17:51-20:25-22:46-26:13-27:74-28:69-29:10-29:49-31:23-35:38-39:7-39:22-40:19-40:56-40:80-42:24-57:6-59:9-59:13-64:4-67:13-94:1-100:10-114:5)",
      "d": "«ṣadr» means chest; its plural is «ṣudūr». The heart is located within the chest.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَٰكِن تَعْمَى الْقُلُوبُ الَّتِي فِي الصُّدُورِ»\nTranslation: But the hearts which are within the chests become blind.\n«fī ṣ-ṣudūr» «شِفَاءٌ لِمَا فِي الصُّدُورِ» «ṣadr» «ṣadr»\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«وَلَقَدْ نَعْلَمُ أَنَّكَ يَضِيقُ صَدْرُكَ بِمَا يَقُولُونَ»\nTranslation: And We know that your heart is constricted by what they say.\nIn another instance, the Divine declaration is:\n«أَلَمْ نَشْرَحْ لَكَ صَدْرَكَ»\nTranslation: Did We not expand for you your chest?\nAnd «sharḥ ṣadr» or «inširāḥ ṣadr» is an idiom. When a correct path (right opinion) occurs in the heart regarding a difficult and complex matter, it is called «sharḥ ṣadr». Then, since a place of residence is needed to conceal something, the use of «ṣadr» will also occur in mentioning secrets, thoughts, and whispers. For example, the Quran states:\n«يَعْلَمُ خَائِنَةَ الْأَعْيُنِ وَ مَا تُخْفِي الصُّدُورُ»\nTranslation: He knows the betrayal of the eyes and what the hearts conceal.\nSimilarly, in another instance, the Divine declaration is:\n«إِنَّ اللَّهَ عَلِيمٌ بِذَاتِ الصُّدُورِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is Acquainted with the contents of the hearts.\nIn yet another instance, the Divine declaration is:\n«الَّذِي يُوَسْوِسُ فِي صُدُورِ النَّاسِ»\nTranslation: Who [Satan] whispers into the hearts of mankind."
    },
    {
      "id": 1475,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«nafs»: the center of desires. Used for expressing happiness and concealing things (268 verses: 2:9-2:44-2:48-2:54-2:57-2:72-2:84-2:85-2:87-2:90-2:102-2:109-2:110-2:123-2:130-2:155-2:187-2:207-2:223-2:228-2:231-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:240-2:265-2:272-2:281-2:284-2:286-3:25-3:28-3:30-3:61-3:69-3:93-3:117-3:135-3:145-3:154-3:161-3:164-3:165-3:168-3:178-3:185-3:186-4:1-4:4-4:29-4:49-4:63-4:64-4:65-4:66-4:79-4:84-4:95-4:97-4:107-4:110-4:111-4:113-4:128-4:135-5:25-5:30-5:32-5:45-5:52-5:70-5:80-5:105-5:116-6:12-6:20-6:24-6:26-6:54-6:70-6:93-6:98-6:104-6:123-6:130-6:151-6:152-6:158-6:164-7:9-7:23-7:37-7:42-7:53-7:160-7:172-7:177-7:188-7:189-7:192-7:197-7:205-8:53-8:72-9:17-9:20-9:35-9:36-9:41-9:42-9:44-9:55-9:70-9:81-9:85-9:88-9:111-9:118-9:120-9:128-10:15-10:23-10:30-10:44-10:49-10:54-10:100-10:108-11:21-11:31-11:101-11:105-12:18-12:23-12:26-12:30-12:32-12:51-12:53-12:54-12:68-12:77-12:83-13:11-13:16-13:33-13:42-14:22-14:45-14:51-16:7-16:28-16:33-16:72-16:89-16:111-16:118-17:7-17:14-17:15-17:25-17:33-18:6-18:28-18:35-18:51-18:74-20:15-20:40-20:41-20:67-20:96-21:35-21:43-21:47-21:64-21:102-23:62-23:103-24:6-24:12-24:61-25:3-25:21-25:68-26:3-27:14-27:40-27:44-27:92-28:16-28:19-28:33-29:6-29:40-29:57-30:8-30:9-30:21-30:28-30:44-31:12-31:28-31:34-32:13-32:17-32:27-33:6-33:37-33:50-34:19-34:50-35:8-35:18-35:32-36:36-36:54-37:113-39:6-39:15-39:41-39:42-39:53-39:56-39:70-40:10-40:17-41:31-41:46-41:53-42:11-42:45-43:71-45:15-45:22-47:38-48:10-49:11-49:15-50:16-50:21-51:21-53:23-53:32-57:14-57:22-58:8-59:9-59:18-59:19-61:11-63:11-64:16-65:1-65:7-66:6-73:20-74:38-75:2-75:14-79:40-81:7-81:14-82:5-82:19-86:4-89:27-91:7)",
      "d": "«nafs» means soul, life, self, or essence. Its plural is «nufūs». From it comes the meaning of the origin (starting point) of desires and a place of refuge. The heart that desires and rejoices is intended.\nAs far as concealing hidden matters and thoughts is concerned, this attribute is shared between «nufūs» and «ṣudūr».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ تُخْفِی فِی نَفْسِکَ مَا اللّٰہُ مُبْدِیْہِ»\nTranslation: And you were concealing within yourself that which Allah was to reveal.\nThe connection of desires is with the «nafs», whether good or bad.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«إِنْ یَّتَّبِعُوْنَ إِلَّا الظَّنَّ وَ مَا تَهْوَى الْأَنْفُسُ»\nTranslation: They follow not except assumption and what the selves desire.\nRejoicing is also connected to the «nafs».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَإِنْ طِبْنَ لَكُمْ عَنْ شَيْءٍ مِنْهُ نَفْسًا فَكُلُوهُ هَنِیئًا مَرِیئًا»\nTranslation: Then if they are pleased to give you some of it, consume it with [good] enjoyment and gratitude."
    },
    {
      "id": 1476,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«waḥy», «ilhām», and «ilqāʾ» can come from Allah or from Satan, while «waswasah» and «hamz» are exclusively from Satan.\n«waḥy» is related to teaching, beliefs, commands, and matters of the unseen. «ilhām» is related only to the doing or not doing of a specific action, and «ilqāʾ» is related only to teaching.\n«waswasah» refers only to the arrival of evil thoughts in the heart, while «hamz» also includes incitement and urging from Satan along with evil thoughts.\nAny «waḥy», «ilhām», or «ilqāʾ» that conforms to the texts of Sharia is Rahmanī (from the Most Merciful); if not, it is Shayṭānī. (70 verses: 3:44-4:163-5:111-6:19-6:50-6:93-6:106-6:112-6:121-6:145-7:117-7:160-7:203-8:12-10:2-10:15-10:87-10:109-11:12-11:36-11:37-11:49-12:3-12:15-12:102-12:109-13:30-14:13-16:43-16:68-16:123-17:39-17:73-17:86-18:27-18:110-19:11-20:13-20:38-20:48-20:77-20:114-21:7-21:25-21:45-21:73-21:108-23:27-26:52-26:63-28:7-29:45-33:2-34:50-35:31-38:70-39:65-41:6-41:12-42:3-42:7-42:13-42:51-42:52-43:43-46:9-53:4-53:10-72:1-99:5)",
      "d": "«waḥy» lexically means only hidden (concealed) and a swift indication. And «awḥā» means to indicate swiftly regarding a hidden and unknown matter (mufrad). Then, there are several types of «waḥy». One is related to commanding affairs.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ أَوْحَى فِی کُلِّ سَمَاءٍ أَمْرَهَا»\nTranslation: And He decreed within each heaven its command.\nNatural guidance is also referred to as «waḥy», such as a newborn baby instinctively turning to its mother's breast.\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«وَ أَوْحَى رَبُّكَ إِلَی النَّحْلِ»\nTranslation: And your Lord inspired the bees.\nThus, «waḥy» comes from Allah to inanimate objects, animals, and humans alike. And such «waḥy» can also come to non-prophets.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ أَوْحَیْنَا إِلَی أُمِّ مُوسَی أَنْ أَرْضِعِیهِ»\nTranslation: And We inspired the mother of Moses, \"Suckle him.\"\nIn all these examples, the word «waḥy» is used in its lexical meaning. Furthermore, a person can also «waḥy» (inspire) another person in this sense.\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«فَأَوْحَی إِلَیْهِمْ أَنْ سَبِّحُوا بُکْرَةً وَ عَشِیًّا»\nTranslation: So he inspired them that they should exalt [Allah] morning and evening.\nEven Satan inspires others in this manner.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ إِنَّ الشَّیَاطِینَ لَیُوحُوْنَ إِلَی أَوْلِیَائِهِمْ لِیُجَادِلُوكُمْ»\nTranslation: And indeed, the devils will inspire [to] their allies [among mankind] to dispute with you.\nThus, «waḥy» can be Rahmanī or Shayṭānī. Rahmanī «waḥy» is always based on good, and any «waḥy» contrary to Rahmanī «waḥy» is Shayṭānī. In the terminology of Sharia, «waḥy» refers to the teachings, commands, and news of the unseen that Allah sends to His chosen human (prophet) for the guidance of the common people. Three forms of it are mentioned in the Quran:\n(1) Allah directly puts a thought into the heart, (2) He sends an angel to the messenger, and (3) He speaks from behind a veil (as with Moses). However, the most common usage is that Allah, through Jibrīl, places His message upon the hearts of the prophets and messengers, which then issues from the prophet's tongue.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قُلْ مَنْ کَانَ عَدُوًّا لِّجِبْرِیلَ فَإِنَّهُ نَزَّلَهُ عَلَی قَلْبِکَ بِإِذْنِ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: Say, \"Whoever is an enemy to Gabriel – then indeed he brought it [i.e., the Qur’ān] down upon your heart by permission of Allah.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 1477,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«ilhām» in common parlance refers to a matter that is cast into the heart by Allah (1 verse: 91:8)",
      "d": "«ilhām» is that thought which is cast into someone's heart by Allah (mufrad) and means granting understanding and insight. Granting success (munjad). Like «waḥy», «ilhām» can also be Shayṭānī, especially when it cannot be substantiated by any verse or textual evidence. Therefore, apart from the class of Sufis, no scholar considers «ilhām» as legally binding (m. m). The difference between «waḥy» and «ilhām» is that «ilhām» applies only to people of intellect, while «waḥy» is general. Secondly, «ilhām» is related to the doing or not doing of a specific action, while «waḥy» has much broader scope (m. m).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَأَلْهَمَهَا فُجُورَهَا وَ تَقْوَاهَا»\nTranslation: Then He inspired it [i.e., humanity] with its [capacity for] wickedness and righteousness."
    },
    {
      "id": 1478,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«ilqāʾ» lexically means only to throw or cast. (66 verses: 2:37-3:44-4:90-4:91-4:94-4:171-5:64-7:115-7:107-7:116-7:117-7:120-7:150-8:12-10:80-10:81-12:10-12:93-12:96-15:19-16:15-16:28-16:86-16:87-17:39-20:20-20:39-20:65-20:66-20:69-20:70-20:87-22:52-22:53-25:8-25:13-26:32-26:43-26:44-26:45-26:46-26:223-27:6-27:10-27:28-27:29-28:7-28:31-28:86-31:10-37:97-38:34-40:15-41:35-41:40-43:53-50:7-50:24-50:26-50:37-54:25-60:1-67:7-67:8-75:15-84:4)",
      "d": "«ilqāʾ» lexically means only to throw or cast. And «alqā ʿalā» means to teach (m. m).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ءَأُلْقِیَ الذِّکْرُ عَلَیْهِ مِنْ بَیْنِنَا»\nTranslation: Is the message [i.e., the Qur’ān] sent down upon him from among us?\nAnd «talaqqā š-šayʾ minhu» means to learn something. To acquire knowledge (munjad).\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«فَتَلَقَّی آدَمُ مِنْ رَبِّهِ کَلِمَاتٍ»\nTranslation: Then Adam received from his Lord [some] words.\nThus, «ilqāʾ» refers only to a thought that has been cast into the heart and is related to teaching and learning. Like «waḥy» and «ilhām», «ilqāʾ» can also be Shayṭānī.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَیَنْسَخُ اللّٰہُ مَا یُلْقِی الشَّیْطَانُ»\nTranslation: Then Allah will abolish what the devil casts."
    },
    {
      "id": 1479,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«waswās» is Satan putting whispers into a person's heart (5 verses: 7:20-20:120-50:16-114:4-114:5)",
      "d": "«waswās» from a medical perspective is a disease that, due to overwhelming melancholy, disturbs the mind and causes a person to utter futile things that were not previously in his heart and in which there is no goodness (m. m). And «wiswās» means the disease of doubt. An evil or useless thought that enters the heart. And it means Satan's incitement to evil and continuously casting evil thoughts (mufrad). And it means the initial state of madness (f l 135). Thus, «waswās» is every evil thought that arises in the heart or is cast by Satan, and its attribution is exclusively to Satan.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مِنْ شَرِّ الْوَسْوَاسِ الْخَنَّاسِ الَّذِی یُوَسْوِسُ فِی صُدُورِ النَّاسِ»\nTranslation: From the evil of the retreating whisperer – Who whispers [evil] into the breasts of mankind."
    },
    {
      "id": 1480,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Putting a thought into the heart",
      "hw": "دل",
      "s": "«hamazāt» is Satan creating evil and filthy thoughts in the heart (1 verse: 23:97)",
      "d": "«hamaza yadullu ʿalā ḍaghṭin wa-ʿaṣrin» (m. l) meaning to pinch. To prod. To press. And it means to prod a beast's side or muscle with a pointed stick, etc., so that it moves swiftly. Actually, the Punjabi phrase \"chohambaṛ dēna\" (to prod with a stick) is very suitable for this meaning. That is, Satan casting an evil thought into a heart and then inciting it. The attribution of this word is also exclusively to Satan.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ قُلْ رَبِّ أَعُوذُ بِکَ مِنْ هَمَزَاتِ الشَّیَاطِینِ»\nTranslation: And say, \"My Lord, I seek refuge in You from the incitements of the devils.\""
    }
  ],
  "325": [
    {
      "id": 1481,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof",
      "hw": "دلیل",
      "s": "«dalīl» is to obtain guidance from one thing for the recognition of another (1 verse: 25:45)",
      "d": "«dalālat» and «dalīl» mean that guidance by which one's knowledge and recognition are attained. For example, by seeing movement in a living being, one knows that it is alive, or as written words indicate their meanings. In common speech too, words are a means of expressing meaning and are evidence of that meaning (mufrad). And «dalla» means to show. To inform. To guide. To be a means of knowledge and recognition.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«أَلَمْ تَرَ إِلَی رَبِّکَ کَیْفَ مَدَّ الظِّلَّ وَلَوْ شَاءَ لَجَعَلَهُ سَاکِنًا ثُمَّ جَعَلْنَا الشَّمْسَ عَلَیْهِ دَلِیلًا»\nTranslation: Have you not considered your Lord – how He extends the shadow, and if He willed, He could have made it stationary? Then We made the sun for it an indication.\nThus, the increase and decrease of shadows and the setting of the sun are both evidence of each other. The correct determination of the sun's direction can be known from the increase and decrease of shadows. Similarly, it can be for telling time. And by seeing the sun's direction, the direction and length of the shadow can be estimated."
    },
    {
      "id": 1483,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof",
      "hw": "دلیل",
      "s": "«bayyinah» is a clear and manifest statement, a proof with which the claimant can invalidate the opponent's claim (74 verses: 2:87-2:92-2:99-2:159-2:185-2:209-2:211-2:213-2:253-3:86-3:97-3:105-3:183-3:184-4:19-4:153-5:32-5:110-6:57-6:157-7:73-7:85-7:101-7:105-8:42-9:70-10:13-10:15-10:74-11:17-11:28-11:53-11:63-11:88-14:9-16:44-17:101-19:73-20:72-20:133-22:16-22:72-24:1-24:34-24:46-28:36-29:35-29:39-29:49-30:9-30:47-33:30-34:43-35:25-40:22-40:28-40:34-40:50-40:66-40:83-43:63-45:17-45:25-46:7-47:14-57:9-57:25-58:5-61:6-64:6-65:1-65:11-98:1-98:4)",
      "d": "«bayyinah» means a clear and manifest statement. Proof. Some explanation of «bayyinah» is also derived from the saying of the Prophet ﷺ: \"Al-bayyinah ʿalā al-muddaʿī wa-l-yamīn ʿalā al-muddaʿā ʿalayhi\" (Bukhārī) meaning: The burden of proof is upon the claimant, and if he cannot provide it, then the oath is upon the one against whom the claim is made.\nNow consider, for example, Zaid claims a sum of money from Bakr, and Bakr denies it. If Zaid has in his possession a document from Bakr that can prove this matter or assist in proving it, that document is a «bayyinah». Similarly, if Zaid can prove it by presenting witnesses, that too is a «bayyinah». «Bayyinah» is such a proof before which the opponent becomes speechless. The very existence of the Quran is a «bayyinah». Against which, despite confrontation, the disbelievers cannot present any proof. Similarly, its verses are also «bayyināt».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«بَلْ هُوَ آیَاتٌ بَیِّنَاتٌ فِی صُدُورِ الَّذِینَ أُوتُوا الْعِلْمَ ۚ وَ مَا یَجْحَدُ بِآیَاتِنَا إِلَّا الظَّالِمُونَ»\nTranslation: Rather, it [i.e., the Qur’ān] is clear verses in the breasts of those given knowledge. And none reject Our verses except the wrongdoers.\nIn this verse, by using the word «jahd», reference is made to the fact that they acknowledge from the heart that these verses are clear proofs, even though they deny them with their tongues."
    },
    {
      "id": 1484,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof",
      "hw": "دلیل",
      "s": "«Burhan» is a proof that is clear and definitively established, and is also supported by divine revelation. (8 verses: 2:111-4:174-12:24-21:24-23:117-27:64-28:32-28:75)",
      "d": "«Barah» means white and shining. And «Burhan» is a proof that is clear and definitively established, and is also supported by divine revelation (Muf). According to some, «Burhan» is derived from the Persian word «Burran» meaning a sharp-edged sword. And «Burhan» refers to a proof that ends a dispute (Faqih 55).\nFor example, in the Quran: «tilka amaniyyuhum qul hatu burhanakum in kuntum sadiqin» (2/111).\nTranslation: These are merely their idle desires. Say, 'Bring your proof if you are truthful.'\nAt another place, the divine command states: «fa-dhalika burhanani min rabbika ila fir'awna wa malaihi» (28/32).\nTranslation: These two proofs (the staff of Moses and the radiant hand) are from your Lord; go to Pharaoh and his courtiers with them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1485,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Proof",
      "hw": "دلیل",
      "s": "«Sultan» is a proof that is clearly established through divine revelation. (38 verses: 3:151-4:91-4:144-4:153-6:81-7:33-7:71-10:68-11:96-12:40-14:10-14:11-14:22-15:42-16:99-16:100-17:33-17:65-17:80-18:15-22:71-23:45-27:21-28:35-30:35-34:21-37:30-37:156-40:23-40:35-40:56-44:19-51:38-52:38-53:23-55:33-59:6-69:29)",
      "d": "«Sultan» means authority, power, and control (Munjid). Royal decree (Munjid). Authority letter. A proof that is clearly established through divine revelation. Evidence. And the plural of «Sultan» is «Sultanin» meaning kings, which is a metaphorical meaning, not literal. Nor has the Quran used this word in those meanings.\nFor example, in the Quran: «atujadilunani fi asma sammaytumuhum antum wa abaukum ma nazzalallahu biha min sultan» (7/71).\nTranslation: Do you argue with me about names which you have named—you and your fathers—for which Allah has not sent down any authority?"
    }
  ],
  "326": [
    {
      "id": 1486,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day and its times",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "«Nahar» refers to the time from sunrise to sunset. (50 verses: 2:164-2:274-3:27-3:72-3:190-6:13-6:60-7:54-10:6-10:24-10:45-10:50-10:67-11:114-13:3-13:10-14:33-16:12-17:12-20:130-21:20-21:33-21:42-22:61-23:80-24:44-25:47-25:62-27:86-28:72-28:73-30:23-31:29-34:33-35:13-36:37-36:40-39:5-40:61-41:37-41:38-45:5-46:35-57:6-71:5-73:7-73:20-78:11-91:3-92:2)",
      "d": "«Nahar» means day, and its opposite is «Layl» meaning night. «Nahar» refers to the time from sunrise to sunset. The day is divided into 12 hours (or 12 ghadi) which are named respectively: «alshuruq, bukur, ghudwah, duha, hajira, zahira, rawah, asr, qasr, sayl, ashiyy, ghurub» (Fal 292). (The mention of night and day together appears frequently in the Quran.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1487,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day and its times",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "«Yawm» means the combination of day and night, i.e., 24 hours. (262 verses: 2:48-2:85-2:113-2:123-2:174-2:203-2:212-2:254-2:259-2:281-3:9-3:25-3:30-3:55-3:77-3:106-3:155-3:161-3:166-3:180-3:185-3:194-4:87-4:109-4:141-4:159-5:14-5:36-5:64-5:109-5:119-6:12-6:15-6:22-6:73-6:128-6:130-6:141-6:158-7:14-7:32-7:51-7:53-7:59-7:163-7:167-7:172-8:41-9:3-9:25-9:35-9:36-9:77-9:108-10:15-10:28-10:45-10:60-10:93-11:3-11:8-11:26-11:60-11:77-11:84-11:98-11:99-11:103-11:105-14:18-14:31-14:41-14:42-14:44-14:48-15:36-15:38-16:25-16:27-16:80-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:111-16:124-17:13-17:52-17:58-17:62-17:71-17:97-18:19-18:47-18:52-18:105-19:15-19:33-19:37-19:38-19:39-19:85-19:95-20:59-20:100-20:101-20:102-20:104-20:124-21:47-21:103-21:104-22:2-22:9-22:17-22:47-22:55-22:69-23:16-23:100-23:113-24:24-24:37-24:64-25:17-25:22-25:25-25:26-25:27-25:69-26:38-26:87-26:88-26:135-26:155-26:156-26:189-27:83-27:87-28:41-28:42-28:61-28:62-28:65-28:71-28:72-28:74-29:13-29:25-29:55-30:12-30:14-30:43-30:55-31:33-32:5-32:14-32:25-32:29-33:44-33:66-34:30-34:40-35:14-37:144-38:79-38:81-39:13-39:15-39:24-39:31-39:47-39:60-39:67-39:71-40:15-40:16-40:18-40:30-40:32-40:33-40:46-40:49-40:51-40:52-41:9-41:12-41:19-41:40-41:47-42:7-42:45-42:47-43:65-43:83-44:10-44:16-44:41-45:17-45:26-45:27-45:34-46:5-46:20-46:21-46:34-46:35-50:20-50:30-50:34-50:41-50:42-50:44-51:13-51:60-52:9-52:13-52:45-52:46-54:6-54:8-54:19-54:48-55:29-56:50-57:12-57:13-58:6-58:7-58:18-60:3-62:9-64:9-66:8-68:39-68:42-70:4-70:8-70:42-70:43-73:14-73:17-74:9-75:1-75:6-76:7-76:10-76:27-77:12-77:35-78:18-78:38-78:40-79:6-79:35-79:46-80:34-82:19-83:5-83:6-86:9-90:14-101:4)",
      "d": "«Yawm» means day. From sunset to the next day's sunset. The combination of night and day, 24 hours. The plural of «Yawm» is «Ayyam». Time and periods are calculated by «Ayyam».\nFor example, in the Quran: «faman lam yajid fasiyama thalathati ayyamin filhaji wa sab'atin idha raja'tum» (2/196).\nTranslation: And whoever cannot afford a sacrifice should fast for three days during the Hajj and seven when you return.\nAnd «Yawm» in this context is for humans. Its concept can only be formed after the creation of the sun and earth; otherwise, with Allah, «Yawm» is a long period, whether it spans hundreds of thousands of years according to our calculation.\nFor example, the divine command states: «qul a-innakum latakfuru bialladhi khalaqa alarda fi yawmayn» (41/9).\nTranslation: Do you disbelieve in Him who created the earth in two days?\nSimilarly, when «Yawm» is mentioned in the context of the creation of the earth and heavens, it refers to a long period.\nFor example, the divine command states: «wa inna yawman inda rabbika kalalfi sanatin mimma ta'uddun» (22/47).\nTranslation: And indeed, a day with your Lord is like a thousand years of what you count.\nAt another place, the divine command states: «ta'ruju almalakatu wa alrruhu ilayhi fi yawmin kana miqdaruhu khamsina alfa sanatin» (70/4).\nTranslation: The angels and the Spirit ascend to Him in a day the extent of which is fifty thousand years.\nSimilarly, the Day of Judgment will also be a long period, with its duration mentioned in Hadith as fifty thousand years."
    },
    {
      "id": 1488,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day and its times",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "«Al-yawm» means today's day, from sunrise to sunset. (47 verses: 2:249-5:3-5:5-6:93-7:51-8:48-10:92-11:43-12:54-12:92-16:27-16:63-17:14-19:26-19:38-20:64-20:126-23:65-23:111-25:14-34:42-36:54-36:55-36:59-36:64-36:65-37:26-40:16-40:17-40:29-43:39-43:68-45:28-45:34-45:35-46:20-50:22-57:12-57:15-66:7-68:24-69:35-70:44-76:11-78:39-83:34-85:2)",
      "d": "«Al-yawm» means today's day. And the duration of «Al-yawm» is according to «Nahar», not «Yawm», meaning it refers to the time from sunrise to sunset (Munjid). «Zillal-yawm» means the shade of today (Munjid), as in the case of Pharaoh's drowning when Allah the Almighty said: «fal-yawma nunajjika bibidannika litakuna liman khalfaka ayatan» (10/92).\nTranslation: So today We save you in your body that you may be a sign for those after you.\nAnd «Al-yawm» is also used in the Quran for the Day of Judgment.\nFor example, in the Quran: «qala kathalika atatka ayatuna fanasitaha wa kathalika al-yawma tunsa» (20/126).\nTranslation: He will say, 'Thus did Our signs come to you, and you forgot them. And thus today you will be forgotten.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1489,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day and its times",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "«Yawma-idhin» means that day, that very day. (69 verses: 3:167-4:42-6:16-7:8-8:16-11:66-14:49-16:87-18:99-18:100-20:102-20:108-20:109-22:56-23:101-24:25-25:22-25:24-25:26-27:89-28:66-30:4-30:14-30:43-30:57-37:33-40:9-42:47-43:67-45:27-52:11-55:39-69:15-69:16-69:17-69:18-70:11-74:9-75:10-75:12-75:13-75:22-75:24-75:30-77:15-77:19-77:24-77:28-77:34-77:37-77:40-77:45-77:47-77:49-79:8-80:37-80:38-80:40-82:19-83:10-83:15-88:2-88:8-89:23-89:25-99:4-99:6-100:11-102:8)",
      "d": "«Yawma-idhin» is formed by adding «idh» after «yawm». It is used to refer to a specific time. Meaning that day or that very day (Muf).\nFor example, in the Quran: «wujuhun yawma-idhin musfiratun dahikatun mustabshiratun» (80/38,39).\nTranslation: Faces on that day will be bright, laughing, and rejoicing."
    }
  ],
  "327": [
    {
      "id": 1490,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "World and its various names",
      "hw": "دنیا",
      "s": "«Dunya» commonly refers to the planet we live on. (111 verses: 2:85-2:86-2:114-2:130-2:200-2:201-2:204-2:212-2:217-2:220-3:14-3:22-3:45-3:56-3:117-3:145-3:148-3:152-3:185-4:74-4:77-4:94-4:109-4:134-5:33-5:41-6:29-6:32-6:70-6:130-7:32-7:51-7:152-7:156-8:42-8:67-9:38-9:55-9:69-9:74-9:85-10:7-10:23-10:24-10:64-10:70-10:88-10:98-11:15-11:60-12:101-13:26-13:34-14:3-14:27-16:30-16:41-16:107-16:122-18:28-18:45-18:46-18:104-20:72-20:131-22:9-22:11-22:15-23:33-23:37-24:14-24:19-24:23-24:33-28:42-28:60-28:61-28:77-28:79-29:25-29:27-29:64-30:7-31:15-31:33-33:28-33:57-35:5-37:6-39:10-39:26-40:39-40:43-40:51-41:12-41:16-41:31-42:20-42:36-43:32-43:35-45:24-45:35-46:20-47:36-53:29-57:20-59:3-67:5-79:38-87:16)",
      "d": "«Dunya» means near, close. And this word is used in all aspects—place, time, rank, etc.—to mean near. According to Islamic belief, there are two lives: one is the present life, called «shahdat al-ula» (first creation), and the other is life after death, called «shahdat al-akhra» or second. Since the present life is near in terms of time, it is called «Dunya», and its opposite is «Akhirah». And this word is generally used for the present life.\nFor example, in the Quran: «ula'ika alladhina ishtaraw alhayata alddunya bil-akhira» (2/86).\nTranslation: Those are the ones who have purchased the worldly life for the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1491,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "World and its various names",
      "hw": "دنیا",
      "s": "«Adna» is used in meanings of lower rank, inferior, small, and insignificant. (12 verses: 2:61-2:282-4:3-5:108-7:169-30:3-32:21-33:51-33:59-53:9-58:7-73:20)",
      "d": "«Adna» besides temporal nearness, also means lower in rank, inferior. And «Adna» comes in the meaning of «Arzal» and insignificant (Muf). Its opposite is «A'la» and also «Akhra».\nFor example, in the Quran: «fakhalafa min ba'dihim khalaf warithu alkitaba ya'khudhuna 'aradha hada al-adna» (7/169).\nTranslation: Then after them succeeded an evil generation who inherited the Scripture, taking only the mundane gains of this worldly life."
    },
    {
      "id": 1492,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "World and its various names",
      "hw": "دنیا",
      "s": "«Ajilah» means haste and quickness. (3 verses: 17:18-75:20-76:27)",
      "d": "«Ajilah» is opposite to «Akhirah». And «'Ajl» means haste and quickness. And «Ajilah» means that which comes quickly, the present world, and its material possessions (Muf).\nFor example, in the Quran: «kalla bal tuhibbuna al-'ajilata wa tazaruna al-akhira» (75/20,21).\nTranslation: No! But you love the present life and neglect the Hereafter."
    },
    {
      "id": 1493,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "World and its various names",
      "hw": "دنیا",
      "s": "«Ula» is used in meanings of first, previous, earlier, prior, better, superior, etc. (17 verses: 20:21-20:51-20:133-28:43-28:70-33:33-37:59-44:35-44:56-53:25-53:50-53:56-56:62-79:25-87:18-92:13-93:4)",
      "d": "«Ula» means first. And the feminine of «awwal» means first. That is, the first or present life, and its opposite is «akhra» and «akhirah» meaning the last or the Hereafter.\nFor example, in the Quran: «wa inna lana lil-akhirati wa al-ula» (92/13).\nTranslation: And indeed, the Hereafter and the first life are both Ours."
    }
  ],
  "328": [
    {
      "id": 1494,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Distant",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "« » is generally used for time or place (25 verses: 2:176-3:30-4:60-4:116-4:136-4:167-11:83-11:89-14:3-14:18-21:109-22:12-22:53-25:12-27:22-34:8-34:52-34:53-41:44-41:52-42:18-50:3-50:27-50:31-70:6)",
      "d": "The opposite of « » is « », meaning distance. This distance can be in terms of space or time. Its usage is general.\n«وَ اِنۡ  اَدۡرِیۡۤ  اَقَرِیۡبٌ اَمۡ بَعِیۡدٌ مَّا تُوۡعَدُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And I do not know whether what you are promised is near or far.\nBesides sensory perception, it is also used in a spiritual sense.\n«وَ یُرِیۡدُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ اَنۡ یُّضِلَّہُمۡ ضَلٰلًۢا بَعِیۡدًا»\nTranslation: Satan intends to lead them astray to a far deviation."
    },
    {
      "id": 1495,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Distant",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "« » meaning a distant place. This is used only for location. (1 verse: 22:31)",
      "d": "«سَحَقَ» «سَحِیْقَ» «سُحْقًا» «سَحَقَ الرِّیْحُ الْاَرْضَ» «سُحْقًا»\n«فَکَاَنَّمَا خَرَّ  مِنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتَخۡطَفُہُ الطَّیۡرُ  اَوۡ تَہۡوِیۡ بِہِ الرِّیۡحُ فِیۡ مَکَانٍ  سَحِیْقٍ»\nTranslation: (The example of a disbeliever is) as if he fell from the sky, and the birds snatch him, or the wind carries him to a distant place."
    },
    {
      "id": 1496,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Distant",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "« » meaning deep/distant paths, rugged terrain (1 verse: 22:27)",
      "d": "«عَمَقْ» «عَمِیْق» «فَجٍّ عَمِیْق»\n«یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیْقٍ»\nTranslation: They will come from every distant, rugged path."
    },
    {
      "id": 1497,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Distant",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "« » a distance that also implies direction (distance and direction). See also ‘‘to keep far’’ under ‘‘to avoid’’ (5 verses: 8:42-17:1-19:22-28:20-36:20)",
      "d": "«قَصِی ، قَصٰی» «اَقْصَا» «قُصْوٰی» «اَقْصَا»\n«وَ جَآءَ رَجُلٌ مِّنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ یَسۡعٰی»\nTranslation: And a man came running from the farthest edge of the city.\nThus, in « » and « », the concept of direction along with distance is present.\n«فَحَمَلَتۡہُ  فَانۡتَبَذَتۡ بِہٖ مَکَانًا قَصِیًّا»\nTranslation: So she conceived him and withdrew with him to a distant place.\nMeaning, Maryam first went to an eastern place, then went even farther to a distant location."
    },
    {
      "id": 1501,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To remove. To be.",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "« » ( ) means for Allah to forgive sins because of good deeds (17 verses: 2:271-3:193-3:195-4:31-5:12-5:45-5:65-5:89-5:95-8:29-29:7-39:35-47:2-48:5-64:9-65:5-66:8).",
      "d": "« » means to cover. And « » means the darkness of night. And « » is the act whose performance covers over a sin. And when « » is attributed to Allah, it means to remove evils. And « » is related to   (sins), whereas « » is related to   (transgressions).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَنَّ اَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ اتَّقَوۡا لَکَفَّرۡنَا عَنۡہُمۡ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And if the People of the Book had believed and feared Allah, We would have surely removed their evils from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1502,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Distance. To Be.",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "« » means to do something as a completion after finishing a major task (58 verses: 2:117-2:200-2:210-3:47-4:65-4:103-6:2-6:8-6:58-6:60-8:42-8:44-10:11-10:19-10:47-10:54-10:71-10:93-11:44-11:110-12:41-12:68-14:22-15:66-17:4-17:23-19:21-19:35-19:39-19:71-20:72-20:114-22:29-27:78-28:15-28:28-28:29-28:44-33:23-33:36-33:37-34:14-35:36-39:42-39:69-39:75-40:20-40:68-40:78-41:12-41:45-42:14-42:21-43:77-45:17-46:29-62:10-80:23)",
      "d": "«قَضٰی» «فَلَمَّا قَضٰی مُوۡسَی الۡاَجَلَ» «ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡضُوۡا تَفَثَہُمۡ وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ»"
    }
  ],
  "329": [
    {
      "id": 1503,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "« » to run quickly (4 verses: 6:62-10:21-50:44-70:43)",
      "d": "« » means not to delay in doing a work and to do it immediately (muf). And in terms of speed, « » means only fast movement. To run quickly when there is no danger (f l 33). Its opposite is « ».\n«یَوۡمَ یَخۡرُجُوۡنَ  مِنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ سِرَاعًا»\nTranslation: On the Day they will emerge from the graves running swiftly."
    },
    {
      "id": 1504,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "« » a moderate pace between walking and running (14 verses: 2:114-2:205-17:19-20:15-20:20-20:66-28:20-36:20-53:39-57:12-66:8-79:22-79:35-80:8)",
      "d": "« » is a moderate pace between walking and running. « » is that pace like the one between Safa and Marwah (fl 177).\n«وَ جَآءَ مِنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  رَجُلٌ یَّسۡعٰی»\nTranslation: And from the farthest side of the city, a man came running."
    },
    {
      "id": 1506,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "« » to run at full gallop (3 verses: 21:12-21:13-38:42)",
      "d": "«رَکَضَ» «رَکَضَ الرَّجُلُ دَآبَّتَہٗ»\n«فَلَمَّاۤ  اَحَسُّوۡا بَاۡسَنَاۤ  اِذَا ہُمۡ  مِّنۡہَا یَرۡکُضُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: When they sensed Our might, at that they were fleeing from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1507,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "To Run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "« » to break loose and become uncontrollable (1 verse: 9:57)",
      "d": "« » means to snap the ropes. A horse running fast and the rider losing control (Manjad).\n«لَوۡ  یَجِدُوۡنَ مَلۡجَاً  اَوۡ مَغٰرٰتٍ اَوۡ  مُدَّخَلًا لَّوَلَّوۡا  اِلَیۡہِ  وَ ہُمۡ  یَجۡمَحُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: If they find a refuge, or caves, or (underground) hiding places, they would turn towards them while snapping their ropes (i.e., fleeing in panic)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1508,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«harʿa» to run hastily, to run out of control due to emotions (2 verses: 11:78-37:70)",
      "d": "«harʿa» «وَ جَآءَہٗ  قَوۡمُہٗ یُہۡرَعُوۡنَ  اِلَیۡہِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1509,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«nasala» to run from a high place downwards (2 verses: 21:96-36:51)",
      "d": "«nasala» «حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا  فُتِحَتۡ یَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ مَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ ہُمۡ  مِّنۡ  کُلِّ  حَدَبٍ  یَّنۡسِلُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1511,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«haṭaʿa» to come running with fixed gaze and obedience (3 verses: 14:43-54:8-70:36)",
      "d": "«haṭaʿa» «مُّہۡطِعِیۡنَ  اِلَی الدَّاعِ ؕ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ ہٰذَا یَوۡمٌ  عَسِرٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1512,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«ḍabaḥa» (of a horse) to run so fast that it starts panting (1 verse: 100:1)",
      "d": "«ḍabaḥa» «وَ الۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1513,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "to run",
      "hw": "دوڑنا",
      "s": "«sabaqa, istabaqa» to run in an attempt to get ahead in a competition (26 verses: 2:148-5:48-7:80-8:59-8:68-10:19-11:40-11:110-12:17-12:25-15:5-20:99-20:199-21:27-21:101-23:27-23:43-29:4-29:28-36:66-37:171-41:45-42:14-46:11-59:10-79:4)",
      "d": "«sabaqa» «istabaqa» «وَ لَا یَحۡسَبَنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا سَبَقُوۡا ؕ اِنَّہُمۡ  لَا  یُعۡجِزُوۡنَ» «وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ»"
    }
  ],
  "330": [
    {
      "id": 1514,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to run (horse etc.)",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "«awḍaʿa» to run around causing destruction (1 verse: 9:47)",
      "d": "«waḍaʿa» «waḍaʿa» «awḍaʿa al-baʿīr» «awḍaʿa» «لَوۡ خَرَجُوۡا فِیۡکُمۡ مَّا زَادُوۡکُمۡ  اِلَّا خَبَالًا وَّ لَا۠اَوۡضَعُوۡا خِلٰلَکُمۡ یَبۡغُوۡنَکُمُ الۡفِتۡنَۃَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1515,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to run (horse etc.)",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "«awjaf» to run swiftly due to restlessness (1 verse: 59:6)",
      "d": "«wajafa» «qalbun wājifun» «awjafa» «وَ مَاۤ  اَفَآءَ اللّٰہُ  عَلٰی رَسُوۡلِہٖ  مِنۡہُمۡ فَمَاۤ اَوۡجَفۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡ خَیۡلٍ وَّ لَا رِکَابٍ»"
    }
  ],
  "331": [
    {
      "id": 1516,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its different places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«al-nār» meaning fire (102 verses: 2:24-2:39-2:80-2:81-2:126-2:167-2:174-2:175-2:201-2:217-2:221-2:257-2:275-3:10-3:16-3:24-3:103-3:116-3:131-3:151-3:183-3:185-3:191-3:192-4:145-5:29-5:37-5:72-6:27-6:128-7:36-7:38-7:44-7:47-7:50-8:14-9:17-10:8-10:27-11:16-11:17-11:98-11:106-11:113-13:5-13:17-13:35-14:30-14:50-16:62-18:53-20:10-21:39-22:72-23:104-24:57-27:8-27:90-28:29-28:41-29:24-29:25-32:20-33:66-34:42-38:27-38:59-38:61-38:64-39:8-39:16-39:19-40:6-40:41-40:43-40:46-40:47-40:49-40:72-41:19-41:24-41:28-41:40-45:34-46:20-46:34-47:12-47:15-51:13-52:14-54:48-56:71-57:15-58:17-59:3-59:17-59:20-64:10-66:10-74:31-85:5-87:12)",
      "d": "«nār, nūr» «al-» «al-nār» «اِنَّہُمۡ صَالُوا النَّارِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1517,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its different places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«jahannam» is commonly used for Hell (77 verses: 2:206-3:12-3:162-3:197-4:55-4:93-4:97-4:115-4:121-4:140-4:169-7:18-7:41-7:179-8:16-8:36-8:37-9:35-9:49-9:63-9:68-9:73-9:81-9:95-9:109-11:119-13:18-14:16-14:29-15:43-16:29-17:8-17:18-17:39-17:63-17:97-18:100-18:102-18:106-19:68-19:86-20:74-21:29-21:98-23:103-25:34-25:65-29:54-29:68-32:13-35:36-36:63-38:56-38:85-39:32-39:60-39:71-39:72-40:49-40:60-40:76-43:74-45:10-48:6-50:24-50:30-52:13-55:43-58:8-66:9-67:6-72:15-72:23-78:21-85:10-89:23-98:6)",
      "d": "«jahannam» «جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ۚ فَبِئۡسَ الۡمِہَادُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1518,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its different places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "«jahīm» meaning fiercely blazing fire (26 verses: 2:119-5:10-5:86-9:113-22:51-26:91-37:23-37:55-37:64-37:68-37:97-37:163-40:7-44:47-44:56-52:18-56:94-57:19-69:31-73:12-79:36-79:39-81:12-82:14-83:16-102:6)",
      "d": "«jahama» «jahm» «jahīm» «jahīm» «خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1519,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its various places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "« » means intense heat that burns the skin (4 verses: 54:48-74:26-74:27-74:42)",
      "d": "« » means intense heat that burns the skin.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ  مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا سَقَرُ لَا  تُبۡقِیۡ  وَ لَا  تَذَرُ لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ»\nTranslation: And do you know what Sagar is? It neither spares nor leaves any, it will scorch the skin black."
    },
    {
      "id": 1520,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Hell and its various places",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "« » means fire that is constantly blazing (17 verses: 4:10-4:55-17:97-22:4-25:11-31:21-33:64-34:12-35:6-42:7-48:13-67:5-67:10-67:11-76:4-81:12-84:12)",
      "d": "« » means to ignite and intensify fire (transitive). Hence, Hell is called « ». That is, fire that is constantly blazing.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ سَیَصۡلَوۡنَ  سَعِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: Soon they will enter a blazing fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1521,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Names of some layers of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "« » misguidance that occurs due to erroneous belief (4 verses: 2:256-7:146-7:202-19:59-)",
      "d": "« » means to go astray and choose the wrong path. It is a degree beyond « ». And « » refers to misguidance that occurs due to erroneous belief (transitive). « » is also the name of a valley or layer of Hell where such misguided people will be thrown.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ  غَیًّا»\nTranslation: Then after them succeeded an evil generation who neglected prayer and followed their desires. So they will soon meet « »."
    },
    {
      "id": 1522,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Names of some layers of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "« » is the name of a deep pit in Hell (1 verse: 101:9)",
      "d": "«ھَوٰی یَھْوِیْ» «اُھْوِیَّۃ» «اُھْوِیَّۃ» «ھَاوِیَۃ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاُمُّہٗ  ہَاوِیَۃٌ وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا ہِیَہۡ نَارٌ حَامِیَۃٌ»\nTranslation: Its resting place is «Hawiyah». And do you know what it is? It is a fiercely blazing fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1523,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Names of some layers of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "« » is the name of a layer of Hell (2 verses: 104:4-104:5)",
      "d": "« » means to crush, to pulverize. And « » is the name of a layer of Hell.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ  مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا  الۡحُطَمَۃُ نَارُ اللّٰہِ الۡمُوۡقَدَۃُ»\nTranslation: And do you know what «Al-Hutamah» is? It is Allah's kindled fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1524,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Angels of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "« » are the guards and sentinels of Hell (5 verses: 15:22-39:71-39:73-40:49-67:8)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». In « », the concepts of collecting and protecting are found. And « » means one who protects collected wealth: a treasurer, a guardian, a jailer, a warden. The guards and sentinels of the people of Hell.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ  اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ»\nTranslation: The keepers (wardens) of Hell will ask them: Did no warner come to you?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1525,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Angels of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "« » are the harsh and fierce angels of Hell who will drive the people of Hell into it (1 verse: 96:18)",
      "d": "«زَبَانِیَۃ» «زَبْنِیَۃ» «زَبَانِی الْعَقْرَب» «زَبَانِیَۃ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَلۡیَدۡعُ نَادِیَہٗ سَنَدۡعُ  الزَّبَانِیَۃَ»\nTranslation: Then let him call upon his council; we will call upon the guards of Hell (to seize him)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1526,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Angels of Hell",
      "hw": "دوزخ",
      "s": "« » is the name of the chief guardian of Hell (1 verse: 43:77)",
      "d": "« » is the name of the chief of the guardians of Hell.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ نَادَوۡا یٰمٰلِکُ لِیَقۡضِ عَلَیۡنَا رَبُّکَ»\nTranslation: And they will cry out: O Malik! Let your Lord finish us off."
    }
  ],
  "332": [
    {
      "id": 1527,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » means a companion, equal in age and status (6 verses: 4:38-37:51-43:36-43:38-50:23-50:27)",
      "d": "«اَلْقَرَن» «اَلْقِرْنَ» «قِرْاٰنُ السَّعْدَیْن» «قَرِیْن»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا جَآءَنَا قَالَ یٰلَیۡتَ بَیۡنِیۡ وَ بَیۡنَکَ بُعۡدَ الۡمَشۡرِقَیۡنِ فَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرِیۡنُ»\nTranslation: Until when he comes to us, he will say: Would that there were a vast distance between me and you. What an evil companion you are!"
    },
    {
      "id": 1528,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » means a compassionate and kind friend (1 verse: 4:69)",
      "d": "« » means gentle conduct, kind treatment, and that from which help is sought. And « » means a small pillow (Najd). And « » means a compassionate companion, kind, one who agrees and stays close (M. L). And the opposite of « » is « », meaning harshness and severity (M. L).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ ۚ وَ حَسُنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ رَفِیۡقًا»\nTranslation: Those will be with those upon whom Allah has bestowed His favor: the Prophets, the truthful, the martyrs, and the righteous. And excellent are those as companions."
    },
    {
      "id": 1529,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » means helper and protector, supporter and helper (35 verses: 2:107-2:120-2:257-2:286-3:68-3:150-4:33-6:51-6:62-6:70-8:40-9:51-9:74-9:116-10:30-13:37-16:76-17:111-18:26-19:5-22:13-22:78-29:22-32:4-33:5-41:34-42:8-42:31-42:44-44:41-45:19-47:11-57:15-66:2-66:4)",
      "d": "«اَلْوَلَاءِ» «وَلِی» «اَللّٰہُ وَلِیُّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا ۙ یُخۡرِجُہُمۡ مِّنَ الظُّلُمٰتِ اِلَی النُّوۡرِ» «اَلْوَلَاء» «مَوَالِی (singular مولی)» «وَ لِکُلٍّ جَعَلۡنَا مَوَالِیَ  مِمَّا تَرَکَ الۡوَالِدٰنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1530,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » one who maintains friendship, one who agrees from the heart.\nAnd « » truthful, honest, and one who maintains friendship (8 verses: 4:69-5:75-12:46-19:41-19:56-24:61-26:101-57:19)",
      "d": "« » true and loyal friend, a friend who maintains friendship. And « » means agreement of hearts (sincere and selfless love) (Faq l 98/236).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَّ لَا عَلٰۤی  اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ اَنۡ تَاۡکُلُوۡا مِنۡۢ بُیُوۡتِکُمۡ  ۔۔۔۔۔۔۔۔۔ اَوۡ صَدِیۡقِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: Nor is there any blame upon you for eating from your houses.... or from your friend's houses.\nAnd « » is an intensive form, meaning confidant and true friend.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یُوۡسُفُ اَیُّہَا الصِّدِّیۡقُ اَفۡتِنَا فِیۡ سَبۡعِ بَقَرٰتٍ سِمَانٍ یَّاۡکُلُہُنَّ سَبۡعٌ عِجَافٌ»\nTranslation: O Yusuf, the truthful one, inform us about seven fat cows; seven lean ones will devour them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1531,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » a firm and close friend with whom there is heartfelt love (3 verses: 4:125-17:73-25:28)",
      "d": "« » and « » mean friendship entering the heart (maternal), firm and close friendship, and « » means sincere and close friend, and its plural is « ».\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ اتَّخَذَ اللّٰہُ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ خَلِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And Allah the Exalted made Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) His close friend."
    },
    {
      "id": 1532,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » one who shows warm affection (19 verses: 6:70-10:4-22:19-26:101-37:67-38:57-40:18-40:72-41:34-44:46-44:48-47:15-55:44-56:42-56:54-56:93-69:35-70:10-78:25)",
      "d": "«حَمِیْم» «حَمَّ» «حَمَّ الظَّھِیْرَۃ» «حَمِیْم»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ لَا یَسۡئَلُ  حَمِیۡمٌ حَمِیۡمًا یُّبَصَّرُوۡنَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And on that day, no friend will ask about his friend (even though they will be seeing each other face to face) (Jalandhari)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1533,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » such a trusted friend who also intervenes in affairs (1 verse: 9:16)",
      "d": "« » means to enter. And « » is such a friend who intervenes in someone's affairs. Trusted (i.e., one who is trusted). And its second meaning is 'a person who is also attached to another group' (Manjad). Both meanings are almost the same.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ لَمَّا یَعۡلَمِ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ جٰہَدُوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ وَ لَمۡ یَتَّخِذُوۡا مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ وَ لَا رَسُوۡلِہٖ وَ لَا الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ  وَلِیۡجَۃً»\nTranslation: While Allah has not yet seen who among you strive in jihad, and does Allah take anyone other than Himself, His Messenger, and the believers as a special confidant?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1534,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » confidant or one who knows secrets (1 verse: 3:118)",
      "d": "« » means belly and the inner part of everything. And « » means secret, the inner garment (i.e., the inner cloth), a person's family and inner circle (Manjad). And « » refers to such a friend who is a confidant or knows secrets and is familiar with someone's inner affairs (maternal).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا»\nTranslation: O believers, do not take as confidant anyone other than yourselves, for they will not fail to cause you harm."
    },
    {
      "id": 1535,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » one who betrays when the time comes (3 verses: 3:160-17:22-25:29)",
      "d": "« » means not to help someone and to abandon them. And « » refers to such a friend who verbally upholds friendship but abandons when the time comes (Manjad), a betrayer.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ کَانَ الشَّیۡطٰنُ لِلۡاِنۡسَانِ خَذُوۡلًا»\nTranslation: And Satan is a betrayer to man."
    },
    {
      "id": 1536,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » acquaintances, companions, immoral friends (2 verses: 4:25-5:5)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « » and « », meaning companion, immoral person, amorous, companion, acquaintance, immoral, friend, one who has secret friendships, one who fulfills sexual desires. It is used for both masculine and feminine.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«مُحۡصَنٰتٍ غَیۡرَ مُسٰفِحٰتٍ وَّ لَا مُتَّخِذٰتِ اَخۡدَانٍ»\nTranslation: Chaste women, neither promiscuous nor those who take secret companions."
    },
    {
      "id": 1537,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "« » is used in the meaning of making someone a friend (2 verses: 7:196-22:4)",
      "d": "« » is used in the meaning of making someone a friend.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«کُتِبَ عَلَیۡہِ  اَنَّہٗ  مَنۡ تَوَلَّاہُ  فَاَنَّہٗ یُضِلُّہٗ»\nTranslation: It is decreed for him that whoever takes him as a friend, he will mislead him."
    }
  ],
  "333": [
    {
      "id": 1538,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دھتکارا",
      "s": "«دھتکارا ہوا»",
      "d": "« » means to throw stones or pebbles from a distance (maternal), used in both material and spiritual senses. And « » means accursed, rejected.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَاِذَا  قَرَاۡتَ الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  فَاسۡتَعِذۡ بِاللّٰہِ مِنَ  الشَّیۡطٰنِ  الرَّجِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: So when you recite the Quran, seek refuge with Allah from the accursed Satan."
    }
  ],
