    }
  ],
  "381": [
    {
      "id": 1787,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Give Life",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "« » means to give life to any dead person. It is commonly used (53 verses: 2:28-2:73-2:154-2:164-2:243-2:258-2:259-2:260-3:49-3:156-3:169-5:32-6:122-7:158-8:24-9:116-10:56-15:23-16:21-16:65-22:6-22:66-23:37-23:80-25:49-26:81-29:63-30:19-30:24-30:40-30:50-35:9-35:22-36:12-36:33-36:78-36:79-40:11-40:68-41:39-42:9-44:8-45:5-45:26-46:33-50:11-50:43-53:44-57:2-57:17-75:40-77:26-87:13)",
      "d": "«اَحْیَا» «اَمَاتَ» «حَیِیَ» «کَذٰلِکَ یُحۡیِ اللّٰہُ  الۡمَوۡتٰی  ۙ وَ یُرِیۡکُمۡ اٰیٰتِہٖ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1788,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Give Life",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "« » means to give life to and raise the dead lying in graves (27 verses: 2:56-2:259-6:36-6:60-7:14-15:36-16:21-16:38-18:12-18:19-19:15-19:33-22:5-22:7-23:16-23:100-26:87-27:65-30:56-31:28-36:52-37:144-38:79-58:6-58:18-64:7-72:7)",
      "d": "« » basically has two meanings: (1) to raise, to awaken (2) to send alone. And when this word is used in relation to the dead who lie in graves, its meaning will be to revive them in the graves and lead them to the field of resurrection. For example, the Quran says: Translation: And indeed, the Hour is coming - no doubt about it - and indeed, Allah will raise all those who are in the graves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1789,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Give Life",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "« » means to give life, to raise, and to spread (10 verses: 18:16-21:21-42:28-43:11-44:35-74:52-77:3-80:22-81:10-94:1)",
      "d": "«نَشَرَ» «طَوَی» «نَشَرَ الْمَیِّتَ نَشُوْرًا» «اِلَیْہِ النُّشُوْر» «اَنْشَرَ» «ثُمَّ  اَمَاتَہٗ  فَاَقۡبَرَہٗ ثُمَّ  اِذَا شَآءَ  اَنۡشَرَہٗ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1790,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Live, Remain, Keep",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "« » means to live for every living thing (93 verses: 2:85-2:86-2:96-2:179-2:204-2:212-2:255-3:2-3:14-3:27-3:117-3:185-4:74-4:94-4:109-6:29-6:32-6:70-6:95-6:130-6:162-7:25-7:32-7:51-7:152-8:42-9:38-9:55-10:7-10:23-10:24-10:31-10:64-10:88-10:98-11:15-13:26-13:34-14:3-14:27-16:97-16:107-17:75-18:28-18:45-18:46-18:104-19:15-19:31-19:33-19:66-20:72-20:74-20:97-20:111-20:131-21:30-23:33-23:37-24:33-25:3-25:58-28:60-28:61-28:79-29:25-29:64-30:7-30:19-31:33-33:28-35:5-36:70-39:26-40:39-40:51-40:65-41:16-41:31-42:36-43:32-43:35-45:21-45:24-45:35-46:20-47:36-53:29-57:20-67:2-79:38-87:16-89:24)",
      "d": "«حَیِیَ» «حَیٰوۃ» «اِنۡ ہِیَ  اِلَّا حَیَاتُنَا الدُّنۡیَا نَمُوۡتُ وَ نَحۡیَا وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِمَبۡعُوۡثِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1791,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Live, Remain, Keep",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "« » means to live for a living being whose life depends on eating and drinking (3 verses: 7:10-15:20-79:11)",
      "d": "«عَاشَ» «عَیْش» «حَیِیَ» «مَعَائِش» «وَ لَقَدۡ مَکَّنّٰکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ جَعَلۡنَا لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَعَایِشَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1792,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "To Live, Remain, Keep",
      "hw": "زندہ",
      "s": "« » means to let another live (6 verses: 2:49-7:127-7:141-14:6-28:4-40:25)",
      "d": "«اِسْتِحْیَاء» «یُذَبِّحُوۡنَ اَبۡنَآءَکُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیُوۡنَ نِسَآءَکُمۡ» «حَیِیَ» «حیوۃ» «حَیَاء»"
    }
  ],
  "382": [
    {
      "id": 1794,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adornment",
      "hw": "زینت",
      "s": "«Zukhruf» means artificial decoration, i.e., fabricated and superficial adornment (4 verses: 6:112-10:24-17:93-43:35)",
      "d": "«Zukhruf» has two meanings: first, superficial and fabricated decoration, and that adornment obtained from external embellishment. «Zukhruf al-kalam» means adorning speech with falsehood (dictionary). For example, the Quran says: «Yūḥī baʿḍuhum ilā baʿḍin zukhrufa l-qawli ghurūran» (6:112). Translation: (Satan) would cast into each other's hearts adorned words to deceive. And the second meaning is the various colors and forms of plants (dictionary), spring and bloom. For example, the Quran says: «Ḥattā idhā akhadhati l-arḍu zukhrufahā» (10:24). Translation: Until the earth becomes adorned with its greenery."
    },
    {
      "id": 1795,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adornment",
      "hw": "زینت",
      "s": "«Rīsh» means luxurious clothing and adornment obtained from embellishment (1 verse: 7:26)",
      "d": "«Rīsh» means the feathers of birds, especially hawks (dictionary), and «Rayyash» means one who attaches bird feathers to arrows (dictionary). Since bird feathers are like clothing, this word is used metaphorically for luxurious clothing. Embellished garments. For example, the Quran says: «Yā banī ādama qad anzalnā ʿalaykum libāsan yuwārī sawātikum wa rīshan» (7:26). Translation: O children of Adam! We have sent down upon you clothing to cover your private parts and as adornment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1797,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adornment",
      "hw": "زینت",
      "s": "«Jamāl» is used in all senses: apparent beauty, excellence of character, and adornment of the surroundings (1 verse: 16:6)",
      "d": "«Jamāl» this word is used in all aspects: (1) apparent beauty, (2) excellence of character, (3) adornment and beauty of the surroundings (Faqih 217). In the Quran, this word is used in both meanings for «mu'akhkhar al-dhikr». Essentially, it means goodness in actions, morals, and outward deeds. Later, this word also began to be used for apparent beauty. For example, the Quran says: «Wa lakum fīhā jamālun ḥīna turīḥūna wa ḥīna tasraḥūna» (16:6). Translation: And there is beauty for you in it when you bring them (cattle) home in the evening and when you take them out to pasture in the morning."
    }
  ],
  "383": [
    {
      "id": 1798,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Companion",
      "hw": "ساتھی",
      "s": "«Ṣāḥib» means one who remains together for a long time (87 verses: 2:39-2:81-2:82-2:119-2:217-2:257-2:275-3:116-4:36-4:47-5:10-5:29-5:86-6:71-6:101-7:36-7:42-7:44-7:46-7:47-7:48-7:50-7:184-9:40-9:70-9:113-10:26-10:27-11:23-12:39-12:41-13:5-15:78-15:80-18:9-18:34-18:37-18:76-20:135-22:44-22:51-25:24-25:38-26:61-26:176-29:15-31:15-34:46-35:6-36:13-36:55-38:13-39:8-40:6-40:43-46:14-46:16-50:12-51:59-53:2-54:29-56:8-56:9-56:27-56:38-56:41-56:90-56:91-57:19-58:17-59:20-60:13-64:10-67:10-67:11-68:17-68:48-70:12-72:3-74:31-74:39-80:36-81:22-85:4-90:18-90:19-105:1)",
      "d": "«Ṣāḥib» means one who remains together for a long time, whether this companionship is with a human or an animal, and whether it is temporal or spatial (dictionary). According to Ibn al-Faris, two aspects are found in «ṣaḥaba»: (1) «muqārinah» (being a counterpart) and (2) «muqāribah» (being close or together) (dictionary). The plural of «ṣāḥib» is «aṣḥāb» and its feminine is «ṣāḥibah». According to Sahib al-Furuq al-Lughawiyyah, this word is specifically used for humans (Faqih 235). For example, the Quran says: «Iż humā fī l-ghār iż yaqūlu li-ṣāḥibihi lā taḥzan inna Allāha maʿanā» (9:40). Translation: When the two (Prophet ﷺ and Abu Bakr) were in the cave, he said to his companion (Abu Bakr), 'Do not grieve; indeed, Allah is with us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1800,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Companion",
      "hw": "ساتھی",
      "s": "«Qarīn» means peer, equal, of the same age (6 verses: 4:38-37:51-43:36-43:38-50:23-50:27)",
      "d": "«Qarīn» means of the same age. And any person who is equal in bravery, strength, or other qualities, and this word is also used for non-living things. For details, see 'Friend'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1801,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Companion",
      "hw": "ساتھی",
      "s": "«Azwāj» means of the same kind. People similar in habits and customs (47 verses: 2:25-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:12-4:57-6:139-6:143-9:24-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:131-23:6-24:6-25:74-26:166-30:21-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-43:12-43:70-56:7-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-78:8)",
      "d": "«Zawj» means pair, husband and wife. Both are «zawj» for each other and together they are «zawj». Its plural is «azwāj». This word is also used in the Quran in the meaning of «qarīn» (companion or of the same kind), i.e., people similar to each other. (See details under 'Various'). For example, the Quran says: «Uḥshurū l-ladhīnaẓalamū wa azwājahum wa mā kānū yaʿbudūn» (37:22). Translation: Gather those who did wrong and their companions and what they used to worship."
    }
  ],
  "384": [
    {
      "id": 1802,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Year",
      "hw": "سال",
      "s": "«ʿĀm» means a year of prosperity and well-being (6 verses: 2:259-9:28-9:37-9:126-12:49-29:14)",
      "d": "«ʿĀm» its plural is «ʿawām», the year in which there is abundance and plenty (dictionary), a year of prosperity and well-being. For example, the Quran says: «Thumma yātī min baʿdi dhālika ʿāmun fīhi yughāthu n-nāsu wa fīhi yaʿṣirūn» (12:49). Translation: Then after that will come a year in which people will have abundant rain and in which they will press (olives or grapes). And in this sense, the word «ʿām» is also used as a prayer. On the occasion of Eid, Arabs say «antum wa kulla ʿamin bikhayr» instead of congratulating each other, meaning 'May your year pass with goodness and well-being.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1804,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Year",
      "hw": "سال",
      "s": "«Ḥawl» means a full cycle of the year from a specific date or lunar calculation (2 verses: 2:233-2:240)",
      "d": "«Ḥāla» its plural is «ḥālāt», meaning to change from one state to another. «Aḥwāl al-dahr» means the cycles of days, the vicissitudes of time. And «ḥāla l-ḥawl» means the passage of a year's period (dictionary). And «ḥawl» means a full cycle of the year, i.e., the period from a specific date in one year to the same date in the next year. Zakat is also paid according to «ḥawl». And in breastfeeding and divorce, the calculation of «ḥawl» is also observed. For example, the Quran says: «Wa waṣiyyatan li-azwājihim matāʿan ilā l-ḥawli ghayra ikhrāj» (2:240). Translation: And a bequest for his wives of maintenance for a year without expulsion."
    },
    {
      "id": 1805,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Year",
      "hw": "سال",
      "s": "«Ḥijaj» is a rough method of counting years (1 verse: 28:27)",
      "d": "«Ḥijaj» is the plural of «ḥajjah» and «ḥajj» means to come and go repeatedly, to have frequent comings and goings (dictionary). From «ḥajjah», «ḥajj» is a repeated noun (i.e., once a year). And since Hajj occurs once a year, the year is called «ḥajj». In the early centuries (i.e., the time of the companions), there was no regular calendar and calculation of days, months, and years. Therefore, common people used to count years by the number of Hajj pilgrimages. For example, the Quran says: «Innī urīdu an unkiḥaka iḥdā abnatayya hātayni ʿalā an tājuranī thamāniya ḥijaj» (28:27). Translation: I wish to marry you to one of my two daughters, on the condition that you serve me for eight years."
    }
  ],
  "385": [
    {
      "id": 1807,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Goods",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Matāʿ» means any goods from which benefit is derived (34 verses: 2:36-2:236-2:240-2:241-3:14-3:185-3:197-4:77-5:96-7:24-9:38-10:23-10:70-11:3-12:17-12:65-12:79-13:17-13:26-16:80-16:117-21:111-24:29-28:60-28:61-33:53-36:44-40:39-42:36-43:35-56:73-57:20-79:33-80:32)",
      "d": "«Matāʿ» its plural is «amtiʿah» and «mataʿ». It means to derive benefit for a long time (dictionary). And «matāʿ» is any useful thing or any part of a thing that can provide benefit. To take advantage from worldly goods. When the aspect of worldly goods and deriving benefit from them is intended, this word is used. For example, the Quran says: «Wa lakum fī l-arḍi mustaqarrun wa matāʿun ilā ḥīn» (2:36). Translation: And for you in the earth is a place of settlement and provision for a time."
    },
    {
      "id": 1808,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Items",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "« » means miscellaneous household items, necessities (2 verses: 16:80-19:74)",
      "d": "«اَثَاث» «اَثَاثَۃٌ» «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت» «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت» «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت» «وَ کَمۡ اَہۡلَکۡنَا قَبۡلَہُمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡنٍ ہُمۡ اَحۡسَنُ  اَثَاثًا  وَّ رِءۡیًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1809,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Items",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "« » means equipment that accompanies during travel (3 verses: 12:70-12:75-106:2)",
      "d": "«رَحْل» «رَحْل» «رَحَلَ» «لَا تَشَدُّوا الرِّحَالَ اِلاَّ لِثَلٰثَۃِ مَسَاجِدٍ» «جَعَلَ السِّقَایَۃَ  فِیۡ رَحۡلِ اَخِیۡہِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1810,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Items",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "« » means any equipment that is closed or locked (1 verse: 12:76)",
      "d": "«وِعَاء» «اَوْعِیَۃ» «وَعٰی» «اَوْعِیَۃ» «فَبَدَاَ بِاَوۡعِیَتِہِمۡ قَبۡلَ وِعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ ثُمَّ اسۡتَخۡرَجَہَا مِنۡ وِّعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1811,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Jahaaz» is the luggage that a traveler prepares and keeps when embarking on a journey. (2 verses: 12:59-12:70)",
      "d": "«Jahhaza» means to prepare, load, and send luggage (mufrad). And «Jahaaz» is the luggage that a traveler prepares when setting out on a journey. And «Tajhīz» is the luggage prepared for a deceased before burial. And «Jahīz» is the luggage given by parents to a daughter at the time of her marriage departure.\n«فَلَمَّا جَہَّزَہُمۡ بِجَہَازِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: Then when Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) prepared his brothers' luggage."
    },
    {
      "id": 1812,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Zad» is the provisions of food and drink during a journey. (1 verse: 2:197)",
      "d": "«Zada» means increased, surplus, extra supplies (mufrad). And «Zad» generally refers to the road. Zad al-raah (provisions for the journey). During travel, expenses and food/drink supplies. And «Al-muzādata» means a water skin used during travel. And «Mizwadah» means a provision bag. And «Tazawwada» also means to take provisions for the journey (manjad).\n«وَ تَزَوَّدُوۡا فَاِنَّ خَیۡرَ الزَّادِ التَّقۡوٰی»\nTranslation: And take provisions, for indeed the best provision is piety."
    },
    {
      "id": 1813,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Aslihah» are weapons and military equipment. (1 verse: 4:102)",
      "d": "«Aslihah» is plural of «Silaah». This word is related to war or battle. Meaning: war equipment, arms and weapons. And everything with which one fights or resists and defends (mufrad).\n«فَلۡتَقُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّعَکَ وَ لۀِیَاۡخُذُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: Let a group of them stand with you during prayer and let them hold their weapons."
    },
    {
      "id": 1814,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Goods",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "« » meaning all kinds of equipment and preparations for war (1 verse: 9:46)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « » and « ». It means to prepare. « » and « » mean to prepare and keep ready. And « » means equipment related to preparation. In the Quran, since this word was used in the context of war preparations, therefore, its meaning includes all kinds of preparations and equipment.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَرَادُوا الۡخُرُوۡجَ لَاَعَدُّوۡا لَہٗ عُدَّۃً»\nTranslation: And if they had intended to go forth, they would have prepared for it some equipment."
    },
    {
      "id": 1818,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Ma'un» are small household items for general use. (1 verse: 107:7)",
      "d": "«Al-ma'un» means useful item. And «Ma'un» refers to every usable thing that comes into common people's use. Utensils. Small household items. For example, an axe, pots, or other household goods (manjad).\n«الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  یُرَآءُوۡنَ وَ یَمۡنَعُوۡنَ الۡمَاعُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And those who show off and do not lend household utensils."
    },
    {
      "id": 1819,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Supplies",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "«Hidhr» is means of self-protection. (17 verses: 2:19-2:235-2:243-3:28-3:30-4:71-4:102-5:41-5:49-5:92-9:64-9:122-24:63-28:6-39:9-63:4-64:14)",
      "d": "«Hathara» means to be cautious and careful (m. l). And «Hidhr» is every equipment that provides protection and safety. So every means of protection during war is «Hidhr».\n«وَ لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِنۡ کَانَ بِکُمۡ اَذًی مِّنۡ مَّطَرٍ اَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَنۡ تَضَعُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَکُمۡ ۚ وَ خُذُوۡا حِذۡرَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And there is no blame on you if you lay down your arms due to rain or illness, but take your precautions."
    },
    {
      "id": 1820,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Goods",
      "hw": "سامان",
      "s": "« » meaning all goods necessary to sustain or maintain life (3 verses: 7:10-15:20-79:11)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». « » means to live, to exist. And every goods that is necessary to sustain or maintain life. For example, food, grain, water, provisions, etc. These are called « ».\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ مَکَّنّٰکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ جَعَلۡنَا لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَعَایِشَ»\nTranslation: And We have certainly established you in the land and made for you therein means of livelihood."
    }
  ],
  "386": [
    {
      "id": 1821,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Come Forward",
      "hw": "سامنے",
      "s": "«Aqbal» means to turn towards someone and be in front of them or to come forward. (8 verses: 12:71-28:31-37:27-37:50-37:94-51:29-52:25-68:30)",
      "d": "«Qabala al-makaan» means to turn towards a place. And «Qabil» means two things facing each other or opposite. To confront. And «Qabbala» means to kiss. And «Aqbal» means to turn towards someone and be in front or to come. To face. To approach from the front (manjad).\n«قَالُوۡا وَ اَقۡبَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِمۡ  مَّا ذَا  تَفۡقِدُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And they turned towards them saying, 'What is it that you have lost?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1822,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Come Forward",
      "hw": "سامنے",
      "s": "«Baraza» means to come out into an open field. (7 verses: 2:250-3:154-4:81-14:21-14:48-26:91-79:36)",
      "d": "«Barz» means space and open field. And «Baraza» means to come out into an open field (mufrad). And also means to become apparent after obscurity and hiddenness (manjad).\n«وَ بَرَزُوۡا لِلّٰہِ جَمِیۡعًا»\nTranslation: And all people will come forth before Allah."
    }
  ],
  "387": [
    {
      "id": 1823,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Snake",
      "hw": "سانپ",
      "s": "«Hayyah» is used for all kinds of snakes. (1 verse: 20:20)",
      "d": "«Hayyah» is a common noun. Every kind of snake. Used for both masculine and feminine (fal 160). And according to the author of Munjid, «Hayyah» means a coiling snake. And «Hawaya» refers to intestines that are coiled like a snake. And «Tahawwi al-hayyah» means the snake coils. And «Hawi» is the term for one who recites incantations for a snake (manjad). Both meanings seem correct because every snake generally coils. And probably for this reason it is called «Hayyah».\n«قَالَ  اَلۡقِہَا یٰمُوۡسٰی فَاَلۡقٰہَا فَاِذَا ہِیَ حَیَّۃٌ  تَسۡعٰی»\nTranslation: Allah said, 'O Moses, throw it down.' So he threw it down, and suddenly it was a swiftly moving snake."
    },
    {
      "id": 1824,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Snake",
      "hw": "سانپ",
      "s": "«Jaan» is used for slender and long snakes. (7 verses: 15:27-27:10-28:31-55:15-55:39-55:56-55:74)",
      "d": "«Jaan» means jinn, demon, fairy. Strong physique. And every jinn that is in the form of a snake (mufrad). As mentioned in hadith. And Maulana Shabbir Ahmad Uthmani (may Allah have mercy on him) translated it as the swiftness of a snake. A fast and slender snake.\n«فَلَمَّا رَاٰہَا تَہۡتَزُّ  کَاَنَّہَا جَآنٌّ  وَّلّٰی مُدۡبِرًا  وَّ لَمۡ  یُعَقِّبۡ»\nTranslation: When he saw it moving as if it were a swift snake, he turned back and did not look back."
    },
    {
      "id": 1825,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Snake",
      "hw": "سانپ",
      "s": "«Tha'ban» is used for a serpent/dragon. (2 verses: 7:107-26:32)",
      "d": "«Tha'ban» means a serpent. A very large snake (f l 40, 160).\n«فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ  فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ»\nTranslation: He threw his staff, and suddenly it was a clear serpent.\nNow see, Allah used three words for snake in the same incident of the staff turning into a snake: «Hayyah, Jaan, Tha'ban». «Hayyah» for all kinds of snakes. «Jaan» for the initial state of the staff becoming a snake. And «Tha'ban» for its second and final state. And all this happened in an instant."
    }
  ],
  "388": [
    {
      "id": 1826,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "All / Entire",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "« » means both 'every one' and 'all'. (337 verses: 2:20-2:29-2:31-2:60-2:106-2:109-2:116-2:145-2:148-2:164-2:231-2:259-2:260-2:261-2:266-2:276-2:281-2:282-2:284-2:285-3:7-3:25-3:26-3:29-3:30-3:93-3:119-3:154-3:161-3:165-3:185-3:189-4:11-4:12-4:32-4:33-4:41-4:78-4:85-4:86-4:95-4:126-4:129-4:130-4:176-5:17-5:19-5:40-5:48-5:97-5:117-5:120-6:17-6:25-6:44-6:64-6:67-6:70-6:80-6:84-6:85-6:86-6:99-6:101-6:102-6:108-6:111-6:112-6:123-6:132-6:146-6:154-6:164-7:29-7:31-7:34-7:38-7:46-7:57-7:86-7:89-7:112-7:145-7:146-7:156-7:160-8:12-8:39-8:41-8:54-8:56-8:75-9:5-9:33-9:39-9:115-9:122-9:126-10:22-10:30-10:47-10:49-10:54-10:79-10:97-11:3-11:4-11:6-11:12-11:40-11:57-11:59-11:111-11:120-11:123-12:31-12:76-12:111-13:2-13:3-13:7-13:8-13:16-13:23-13:33-13:38-13:42-14:5-14:15-14:17-14:25-14:34-14:51-15:17-15:19-15:44-16:11-16:36-16:69-16:77-16:84-16:89-16:111-16:112-17:12-17:13-17:20-17:29-17:36-17:38-17:71-17:84-17:89-18:45-18:54-18:79-18:84-19:49-19:69-19:93-19:95-20:15-20:50-20:56-20:98-20:135-21:30-21:33-21:35-21:72-21:79-21:81-21:85-21:93-21:96-21:99-22:2-22:3-22:5-22:6-22:17-22:27-22:34-22:38-22:67-23:27-23:53-23:88-23:91-24:2-24:11-24:35-24:41-24:45-24:64-25:2-25:31-25:39-25:51-26:7-26:37-26:63-26:128-26:222-26:225-27:16-27:23-27:83-27:87-27:88-27:91-28:48-28:57-28:75-28:88-29:20-29:40-29:57-29:62-30:26-30:32-30:50-30:58-31:10-31:18-31:29-31:31-31:32-32:7-32:13-33:27-33:40-33:51-33:52-33:54-33:55-34:7-34:9-34:19-34:21-34:47-35:1-35:12-35:13-35:36-36:12-36:32-36:36-36:40-36:79-36:83-37:7-37:8-38:14-38:19-38:37-38:48-38:73-39:5-39:27-39:62-39:70-40:5-40:7-40:17-40:27-40:35-40:48-40:62-41:12-41:21-41:39-41:53-41:54-42:9-42:12-42:33-43:12-43:35-44:4-44:55-45:7-45:22-45:28-46:19-46:25-46:33-47:15-48:21-48:26-48:28-49:16-50:7-50:8-50:14-50:21-50:24-50:32-51:49-52:21-54:3-54:28-54:42-54:49-54:52-54:53-55:26-55:29-55:52-57:2-57:3-57:10-57:23-58:6-58:7-59:6-61:9-63:4-64:1-64:11-65:3-65:12-66:8-67:1-67:19-68:10-70:38-72:28-74:38-74:52-78:29-80:37-83:12-85:9-86:4-97:4-104:1)",
      "d": "«کُلّ» «جُزْء» «قُلۡ کُلٌّ یَّعۡمَلُ عَلٰی شَاکِلَتِہٖ» «وَ عَلَّمَ اٰدَمَ الۡاَسۡمَآءَ کُلَّہَا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1827,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "All. Entire.",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "« » means completely whole and entirely all. It is stronger than « » and « ». (4 verses: 2:208-9:36-9:122-34:28)",
      "d": "« » refers to the entire circumference of something. « » is the active participle and « » is its feminine form (fem). Its usage is of two types.\n(1) When « » refers to many units, it is used for that entire collection, and in this respect it is stronger and more complete than « ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَرۡسَلۡنٰکَ  اِلَّا کَآفَّۃً  لِّلنَّاسِ بَشِیۡرًا وَّ نَذِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: And (O Muhammad ﷺ) We have sent you as a bringer of glad tidings and a warner to all mankind.\n(2) When « » is a single unit, it comes to encompass all its parts. And in this respect it is stronger than « » (fem).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا ادۡخُلُوۡا فِی السِّلۡمِ  کَآفَّۃً»\nTranslation: O you who have believed, enter into Islam completely.\nIn this verse, the word « » gives both its meanings: entirely all and completely whole."
    },
    {
      "id": 1828,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "All / Entire",
      "hw": "سب",
      "s": "« » means all together, collectively, to agree on something. (12 verses: 3:157-3:173-4:23-10:58-10:71-12:15-12:102-15:30-20:64-26:95-38:73-43:32)",
      "d": "«جَمَعَ» «اَجْمَعَ» «اَجْمَعَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» «فَلَمَّا ذَہَبُوۡا بِہٖ  وَ  اَجۡمَعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّجۡعَلُوۡہُ  فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ  الۡجُبِّ» «اَجْمَعُوْن» «فَسَجَدَ  الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ  کُلُّہُمۡ  اَجۡمَعُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "389": [
    {
      "id": 1832,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To hand over. To entrust.",
      "hw": "حوالے",
      "s": "« » means to hand over something to someone to avoid trouble. (2 verses: 2:233-31:22)",
      "d": "«سَلِمَ» «سَلَّمَ» «السلام علیکم» «سَلَّمَہٗ اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» «سَلَّمہُ الشَّیْءَ فَتَسَلَّمَہٗ» «سَلَّمَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ اَرَدۡتُمۡ اَنۡ تَسۡتَرۡضِعُوۡۤا اَوۡلَادَکُمۡ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  اِذَا سَلَّمۡتُمۡ مَّاۤ  اٰتَیۡتُمۡ  بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ»\nTranslation: And if you wish to have your children nursed, there is no blame upon you when you hand over to the nurses what you have given according to the accepted norm.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ  اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا»\nTranslation: And the blood money is to be handed over to the heirs, unless they remit it as charity."
    },
    {
      "id": 1833,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To hand over. To entrust.",
      "hw": "حوالے",
      "s": "« » means to entrust a matter to someone and make them the authority. (1 verse: 40:44)",
      "d": "«فَوَّضَ» «تَفْوِیْضًا اِلَیْہِ الْاَمْر»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اُفَوِّضُ اَمۡرِیۡۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: And I entrust my affair to Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 1834,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "To entrust; to hand over",
      "hw": "حوالے",
      "s": "« » To entrust something as a trust (2 verses: 6:98-11:6)",
      "d": "«وَدَعَ» «اَوْدَعَ الشَّیْ» «وَدَّعَ» «اِسْتَوْدَعَ فُلَانًا شَیْئًا»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡشَاَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ  فَمُسۡتَقَرٌّ وَّ مُسۡتَوۡدَعٌ»\nTranslation: And He it is Who has created you from a single soul, then for you is a place of settlement (in the world) and a place of entrustment (in the grave).\nMeaning: You are kept alive in the world for a period, then you are entrusted (to the earth) after being buried in it. (Jalandhari )"
    }
  ],
  "390": [
    {
      "id": 1835,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "« » Meaning to speak the truth (57 verses: 2:41-2:89-2:91-2:79-2:101-2:177-3:3-3:39-3:50-3:81-3:95-3:152-4:47-4:87-4:122-5:46-5:48-5:113-5:119-6:92-6:115-9:43-10:2-10:93-12:26-17:80-19:50-21:9-26:84-27:27-28:34-29:3-33:8-33:22-33:23-33:24-34:20-35:31-36:52-37:37-37:52-37:105-39:32-39:33-39:74-46:12-46:16-46:30-47:21-48:27-54:55-56:57-61:6-66:12-70:26-75:31-92:6)",
      "d": "« » means to speak the truth. Its opposite is « ». That is, not to say anything contrary to fact. It is a well-known word.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَمَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ  مِمَّنۡ  کَذَبَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ وَ  کَذَّبَ بِالصِّدۡقِ اِذۡ جَآءَہٗ»\nTranslation: So who is more unjust than he who lies against Allah and denies the truth when it comes to him?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1836,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "« » Used for truth and reality (252 verses: 2:26-2:42-2:61-2:71-2:91-2:109-2:119-2:121-2:144-2:146-2:147-2:149-2:176-2:180-2:213-2:236-2:241-2:252-2:282-3:3-3:21-3:60-3:62-3:71-3:86-3:102-3:108-3:112-3:154-3:181-4:105-4:122-4:151-4:155-4:170-4:171-5:27-5:48-5:77-5:83-5:84-5:107-5:116-6:5-6:30-6:57-6:62-6:66-6:73-6:91-6:93-6:114-6:141-6:151-7:8-7:30-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:53-7:89-7:105-7:118-7:146-7:159-7:169-7:181-8:4-8:5-8:6-8:7-8:8-8:32-8:74-9:29-9:33-9:48-9:111-10:4-10:5-10:23-10:30-10:32-10:33-10:35-10:36-10:53-10:55-10:76-10:77-10:82-10:94-10:96-10:103-10:108-11:17-11:45-11:79-11:120-12:51-12:100-13:1-13:14-13:17-13:19-14:19-14:22-15:8-15:55-15:64-15:85-16:3-16:36-16:38-16:102-17:16-17:26-17:33-17:81-17:105-18:13-18:21-18:29-18:44-18:56-18:98-19:34-20:114-21:18-21:24-21:55-21:97-21:112-22:6-22:18-22:40-22:54-22:62-22:74-22:78-23:41-23:62-23:70-23:71-23:90-23:116-24:25-24:49-25:26-25:33-25:68-27:79-28:3-28:13-28:39-28:48-28:53-28:63-28:75-29:44-29:68-30:8-30:38-30:47-30:60-31:9-31:30-31:33-32:3-32:13-33:4-33:53-34:6-34:23-34:26-34:43-34:48-34:49-35:5-35:24-35:31-36:7-36:70-37:31-37:37-38:14-38:22-38:26-38:64-38:84-39:2-39:5-39:19-39:41-39:67-39:69-39:71-39:75-40:5-40:6-40:20-40:25-40:55-40:75-40:77-40:78-41:15-41:25-41:53-42:17-42:18-42:24-42:42-43:29-43:30-43:78-43:86-44:39-45:6-45:22-45:29-45:32-46:3-46:7-46:17-46:18-46:20-46:30-46:34-47:2-47:3-48:27-48:28-50:5-50:14-50:19-50:42-51:19-51:23-53:28-56:95-57:16-57:27-60:1-61:9-64:3-69:51-70:24-78:39-84:2-84:5-103:3)",
      "d": "« » Its opposite is « ». « » is every statement or thing that is proven to be true and correct after experience and observation. Reality. Truth (fem.)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ  لَہُمۡ  اَنَّہُ  الۡحَقُّ»\nTranslation: We will soon show them Our signs in the horizons and in themselves until it becomes clear to them that it (the revelation of the Quran) is the truth."
    }
  ],
  "391": [
