      "h": "Except (other than).",
      "hw": "علاوہ",
      "s": "« » in nouns provides the benefit of exception along with restriction. (609 verses: 2:9-2:26-2:32-2:34-2:45-2:78-2:80-2:83-2:85-2:99-2:102-2:111-2:114-2:130-2:132-2:143-2:150-2:160-2:163-2:171-2:174-2:193-2:210-2:213-2:229-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:246-2:249-2:255-2:267-2:269-2:272-2:275-2:282-2:286-3:2-3:6-3:7-3:18-3:19-3:24-3:28-3:41-3:62-3:64-3:65-3:69-3:73-3:75-3:89-3:93-3:102-3:102-3:111-3:112-3:126-3:135-3:144-3:145-3:147-3:185-4:19-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:29-4:43-4:46-4:62-4:64-4:66-4:83-4:84-4:87-4:90-4:92-4:98-4:113-4:114-4:117-4:120-4:142-4:146-4:148-4:155-4:157-4:159-4:169-4:171-5:1-5:3-5:13-5:25-5:34-5:59-5:73-5:75-5:99-5:110-5:117-6:4-6:7-6:17-6:23-6:25-6:26-6:29-6:32-6:38-6:47-6:48-6:50-6:57-6:59-6:80-6:90-6:102-6:106-6:111-6:116-6:119-6:123-6:128-6:138-6:145-6:146-6:148-6:151-6:152-6:158-6:160-6:164-7:5-7:11-7:20-7:42-7:53-7:58-7:82-7:83-7:89-7:94-7:99-7:105-7:126-7:147-7:155-7:158-7:169-7:184-7:187-7:188-8:10-8:16-8:31-8:34-8:35-8:72-8:73-9:4-9:7-9:8-9:10-9:18-9:31-9:32-9:38-9:39-9:40-9:47-9:51-9:52-9:54-9:74-9:79-9:107-9:110-9:114-9:118-9:120-9:121-9:129-10:3-10:5-10:15-10:19-10:32-10:35-10:36-10:45-10:49-10:52-10:61-10:66-10:72-10:83-10:90-10:98-10:100-10:102-10:107-11:2-11:6-11:7-11:11-11:14-11:16-11:26-11:27-11:29-11:36-11:40-11:43-11:47-11:50-11:51-11:54-11:56-11:81-11:88-11:104-11:105-11:107-11:108-11:109-11:116-11:119-12:25-12:31-12:33-12:37-12:40-12:47-12:48-12:53-12:64-12:66-12:67-12:68-12:76-12:79-12:81-12:87-12:104-12:106-12:109-13:14-13:26-13:30-13:38-14:4-14:9-14:10-14:11-14:22-15:4-15:8-15:11-15:18-15:21-15:31-15:40-15:42-15:56-15:59-15:60-15:85-16:2-16:7-16:33-16:35-16:43-16:64-16:77-16:79-16:106-16:127-17:23-17:33-17:34-17:41-17:44-17:47-17:52-17:58-17:59-17:60-17:61-17:62-17:64-17:67-17:76-17:82-17:85-17:87-17:89-17:93-17:94-17:99-17:102-17:105-18:5-18:16-18:22-18:24-18:39-18:49-18:50-18:55-18:56-18:63-19:60-19:62-19:64-19:71-19:87-19:93-20:3-20:8-20:14-20:98-20:103-20:104-20:108-20:109-20:116-21:2-21:3-21:7-21:22-21:25-21:28-21:36-21:58-21:87-21:107-22:30-20:40-22:52-22:65-23:6-23:24-23:25-23:27-23:33-23:37-23:38-23:62-23:83-23:114-23:116-24:3-24:5-24:6-24:31-24:54-25:4-25:8-25:20-25:33-25:41-25:44-25:50-25:56-25:57-25:68-25:70-26:5-26:77-26:89-26:99-26:109-26:113-26:115-26:127-26:137-26:145-26:154-26:164-26:171-26:180-26:186-26:208-26:227-27:11-27:26-27:56-27:57-27:65-27:68-27:75-27:81-27:87-27:90-28:19-28:36-28:58-28:59-28:70-28:80-28:84-28:86-28:88-29:14-29:18-29:24-29:29-29:32-29:33-29:43-29:46-29:47-29:49-29:64-30:8-30:53-30:58-31:28-31:32-33:6-33:12-33:13-33:14-33:16-33:18-33:20-33:22-33:39-33:52-33:53-33:60-34:3-34:14-34:17-34:20-34:21-34:23-34:28-34:33-34:34-34:37-34:43-34:46-34:47-35:3-35:11-35:23-35:24-35:39-35:40-35:42-35:43-36:15-36:17-36:29-36:30-36:44-36:46-36:47-36:49-36:53-36:54-36:69-37:10-37:15-37:35-37:39-37:40-37:59-37:74-37:128-37:135-37:160-37:163-37:164-38:7-38:14-38:15-38:24-38:65-38:70-38:74-38:83-38:87-39:3-39:6-39:68-40:3-40:4-40:13-40:25-40:29-40:37-40:40-40:50-40:56-40:62-40:65-40:78-41:14-41:35-41:43-41:47-42:14-42:23-42:48-42:51-43:7-43:20-43:23-43:27-43:48-43:58-43:59-43:66-43:67-43:86-44:8-44:35-44:39-44:42-44:56-45:17-45:24-45:25-45:32-46:3-46:9-46:17-46:21-46:25-46:35-47:18-47:19-48:15-50:18-51:42-51:52-51:56-53:4-53:23-53:26-53:28-53:29-53:32-53:39-54:34-54:50-55:33-55:60-56:26-56:79-57:20-57:22-57:27-58:2-58:7-58:10-59:14-59:22-59:23-60:4-64:11-64:13-65:1-65:7-67:9-67:19-67:20-68:52-69:36-69:37-70:22-70:30-71:6-71:21-71:24-71:27-71:28-72:23-72:27-73:2-73:9-74:24-74:25-74:31-74:39-74:56-76:30-78:25-78:30-78:38-79:46-81:27-81:29-83:12-84:25-85:8-87:7-88:6-88:23-92:15-92:20-95:6-98:4-98:5-103:3)",
      "d": "« » means but, except. It is a particle of exception. In this form, it can function as an adjective for an indefinite noun.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَاۤ اِلٰہَ اِلَّا ہُوَ الرَّحۡمٰنُ  الرَّحِیۡمُ»\nTranslation: There is no deity except Him, the Most Merciful, the Especially Merciful.\nBesides, this word also gives the meaning of restriction ( ).\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«وَ مَا یَخۡدَعُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And they do not deceive except themselves.\n«اِلّا» «سَوَی ، غَیْرَ، لَیْسَ ، عَدَا ، خَلَا ، حَاشَا»\nNote 2: (Restriction in Arabic terminology means proving a ruling for one thing and negating it for others; this is also called  .)\nNote 3: An indefinite noun is one that is used for all things of the same type."
    },
    {
      "id": 1897,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Other Than; Except",
      "hw": "علاوہ",
      "s": "« » is found in nouns with the meaning of negation along with exception (101 verses: 1:7, 2:59, 2:173, 2:230, 2:240, 3:83, 3:85, 3:154, 4:12, 4:24, 4:25, 4:46, 4:56, 4:81, 4:82, 4:95, 4:115, 4:140, 5:1, 5:3, 5:5, 5:77, 5:106, 6:14, 6:40, 6:46, 6:68, 6:93, 6:99, 6:114, 6:141, 6:145, 6:164, 7:53, 7:59, 7:65, 7:73, 7:85, 7:140, 7:162, 8:7, 9:2, 9:3, 9:39, 10:15, 11:46, 11:50, 11:57, 11:61, 11:63, 11:65, 11:76, 11:84, 11:101, 11:108, 11:109, 13:4, 14:37, 14:48, 16:21, 16:52, 16:115, 17:73, 20:22, 22:5, 22:31, 23:6, 23:23, 23:32, 24:27, 24:29, 24:31, 24:60, 26:29, 27:12, 27:22, 28:32, 28:38, 28:71, 28:72, 30:55, 33:53, 35:3, 35:37, 39:28, 39:64, 41:8, 43:18, 47:15, 47:38, 50:31, 51:36, 52:35, 52:43, 56:86, 68:3, 70:28, 70:30, 74:10, 84:25, 95:6)",
      "d": "«غَیْر» «وَ ہُوَ فِی الۡخِصَامِ  غَیۡرُ  مُبِیۡنٍ» «ہَلۡ مِنۡ خَالِقٍ غَیۡرُ اللّٰہِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1898,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Besides; Other Than (with inferiority)",
      "hw": "علاوہ",
      "s": "« » in nouns, along with exception, also conveys the meaning of inferiority (141 verses: 2:23, 2:94, 2:107, 2:165, 3:28, 3:64, 3:79, 3:118, 4:48, 4:116, 4:117, 4:119, 4:123, 4:139, 4:144, 4:173, 5:76, 5:116, 6:51, 6:56, 6:70, 6:71, 6:108, 7:3, 7:30, 7:37, 7:81, 7:168, 7:194, 7:197, 7:205, 8:60, 9:16, 9:31, 9:116, 10:18, 10:37, 10:38, 10:66, 10:104, 10:106, 11:13, 11:20, 11:55, 11:101, 11:113, 12:40, 13:11, 13:14, 13:16, 16:20, 16:35, 16:73, 16:86, 17:2, 17:56, 17:97, 18:14, 18:15, 18:26, 18:27, 18:43, 18:50, 18:58, 18:93, 18:102, 19:17, 19:48, 19:49, 19:81, 21:24, 21:29, 21:43, 21:66, 21:67, 21:82, 21:98, 22:12, 22:62, 22:71, 22:73, 23:63, 25:3, 25:17, 25:18, 25:55, 26:93, 27:24, 27:43, 27:55, 28:23, 28:81, 29:17, 29:22, 29:25, 29:41, 29:42, 31:11, 31:30, 32:4, 32:21, 33:17, 33:50, 34:22, 34:41, 35:13, 35:40, 36:23, 36:74, 37:23, 37:86, 39:3, 39:15, 39:36, 39:38, 39:43, 39:45, 40:20, 40:66, 40:74, 42:6, 42:9, 42:31, 42:46, 43:45, 43:86, 45:10, 46:4, 46:5, 46:28, 46:32, 48:27, 52:47, 53:58, 55:62, 60:4, 62:6, 67:20, 71:25, 72:11, 72:22)",
      "d": "«دَان» «دُوْن» «شَیْءٌ دُوْنٌ» «دُوْن» «دُوْن» «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ» «اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَغۡفِرُ اَنۡ یُّشۡرَکَ بِہٖ وَ یَغۡفِرُ  مَا دُوۡنَ ذٰلِکَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» «مَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ مِنۡ وَّلِیٍّ وَّ لَا نَصِیۡرٍ» «دُوْن»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1899,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Beyond; Besides (all-encompassing)",
      "hw": "علاوہ",
      "s": "« » comes for exception in an all-directional (all sides) sense (24 verses: 2:91, 2:101, 3:187, 4:24, 4:102, 6:94, 11:71, 11:92, 14:16, 14:17, 18:79, 19:5, 23:7, 23:100, 33:53, 42:51, 45:10, 49:4, 57:13, 59:14, 70:31, 76:27, 84:10, 85:20)",
      "d": "«وَرَاء» «فَمَنِ ابۡتَغٰی وَرَآءَ ذٰلِکَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الۡعٰدُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "406": [
    {
      "id": 1901,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Sleep",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "« » means (to sleep) sleep; it is the general word for sleeping (9 verses: 2:255, 7:97, 8:43, 25:47, 30:23, 37:102, 39:42, 68:19, 78:9)",
      "d": "«نَامَ» «نَوْم» «مَنَام» «اَفَاَمِنَ اَہۡلُ الۡقُرٰۤی اَنۡ  یَّاۡتِیَہُمۡ  بَاۡسُنَا بَیَاتًا  وَّ ہُمۡ  نَآئِمُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1902,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep.",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "« » to sleep a deep and heedless sleep. (1 verse: 51:17)",
      "d": "«ھَجَعَ» «الھَجَعَۃ» «اَلْھَجَعَۃ» «اَلْھُجَعُ» «صَاحِبِ فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ» «ھَجُوْع»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کَانُوۡا  قَلِیۡلًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ مَا یَہۡجَعُوۡنَ وَ  بِالۡاَسۡحَارِ ہُمۡ  یَسۡتَغۡفِرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: They used to sleep but a little of the night, and in the hours of early dawn they would seek forgiveness."
    },
    {
      "id": 1903,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep.",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "« » to sleep a long and light sleep. (1 verse: 18:18)",
      "d": "« » means to sleep a long sleep (fal 161). « » means pleasant and light sleep ( ). « » and « » mean one who sleeps a lot, and « » means one who always sleeps ( ). From all these, it is known that « » is such a sleep that is long, pleasant, and light. Meaning, a person wakes up at the slightest sound.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ تَحۡسَبُہُمۡ اَیۡقَاظًا وَّ ہُمۡ رُقُوۡدٌ»\nTranslation: And you would think them awake while they are asleep."
    },
    {
      "id": 1904,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep.",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "« » to sleep in the afternoon. (1 verse: 7:4)",
      "d": "«یَقِیْلُ قَیْلًا وَ قَیْلُوْلَۃً»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ کَمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍ اَہۡلَکۡنٰہَا فَجَآءَہَا بَاۡسُنَا  بَیَاتًا  اَوۡ  ہُمۡ  قَآئِلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And how many a city We destroyed while its people were asleep at night or while they were taking a midday rest."
    },
    {
      "id": 1905,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep.",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "« » to lie on one's side to rest, whether sleep comes or not. (3 verses: 3:154-4:34-32:16)",
      "d": "«ضَجَعَ» «مَضَاجِع» «اَضْجَعَہ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«تَتَجَافٰی جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ عَنِ الۡمَضَاجِعِ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ خَوۡفًا وَّ طَمَعًا»\nTranslation: Their sides arise from the beds, calling upon their Lord in fear and hope."
    },
    {
      "id": 1906,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Sleep",
      "hw": "سونا",
      "s": "«tahajjad» waking up at night for tahajjud prayer, etc., praying tahajjud at night (1 verse: 17:79)",
      "d": "«hujūd» means sleeping at night and also waking up, sometimes sleeping sometimes waking up (this is from opposite words in language). And spending the night sleeping and waking. And «hajada» means waking up at night to pray (Mujid).\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَتَہَجَّدۡ بِہٖ نَافِلَۃً  لَّکَ»\nTranslation: And during the night, pray with it as an additional act for yourself."
    }
  ],
  "407": [
    {
      "id": 1907,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Blackness / Black Color",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "«aswad» meaning black color (3 verses: 2:187-3:106-16:58)",
      "d": "«aswad» black color, its opposite is «abyad» meaning white color. «aswad» is used in the well-known meanings and is common, and its plural is «sūd» and its feminine is «sawdā».\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ لَکُمُ الۡخَیۡطُ الۡاَبۡیَضُ مِنَ الۡخَیۡطِ الۡاَسۡوَدِ  مِنَ الۡفَجۡرِ»\nTranslation: And eat and drink until the white thread of dawn becomes distinct to you from the black thread."
    },
    {
      "id": 1908,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Black. Blackness.",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "« » meaning very black. (1 verse: 35:27)",
      "d": "«غُرَاب» «غِرْبَان» «غِرْبِیْب» «غَرَابِیْب» «غُرْبِیْب» «غَرَابِیْب»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ جُدَدٌۢ  بِیۡضٌ وَّ حُمۡرٌ  مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہَا وَ غَرَابِیْبُ سُوۡدٌ»\nTranslation: And among the mountains are streaks white and red, of varying shades, and [some] extremely black."
    },
    {
      "id": 1909,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Blackness / Black Color",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "«aḥwā» meaning greenish-black color (1 verse: 87:5)",
      "d": "«aḥwā» greenish-black color or blackish-red color (Mujid). In the Quran, the words «ghuthā'an aḥwā» are used. «ghuthā» refers to the twigs, leaves, and scum that get stuck in foam, and the river throws that foam and scum to the shore. And when this scum is crushed underfoot repeatedly, its color becomes blackish, and that color is called «aḥwā».\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَخۡرَجَ  الۡمَرۡعٰی فَجَعَلَہٗ  غُثَآءً  اَحۡوٰی»\nTranslation: And who brings forth the pasture, then makes it a dark scum."
    },
    {
      "id": 1910,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Blackness. Black",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "« » meaning a deep greenish-black color (1 verse: 55:64)",
      "d": "«دَھَمَ» «اَلدُّھْمَۃ» «مُدۡہَآ مَّتٰنِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1911,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Blackness / Black Color",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "«qatara» meaning smoke-like color (2 verses: 10:26-80:41)",
      "d": "«qatara al-nar» means the fire produces smoke (Mujid). And «qatara» means dust or dirt that is like smoke, blackish.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ عَلَیۡہَا غَبَرَۃٌ تَرۡہَقُہَا قَتَرَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And on that day, there will be faces covered with dust, and over them will be a blackish smoke."
    },
    {
      "id": 1912,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Ink",
      "hw": "سیاہی",
      "s": "« » means ink, the light with which writing is done (1 verse: 18:109)",
      "d": "«مَدَدْتُ الدَّوَاۃ» «مِدَادَ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ الۡبَحۡرُ مِدَادًا لِّکَلِمٰتِ رَبِّیۡ لَنَفِدَ الۡبَحۡرُ  قَبۡلَ اَنۡ تَنۡفَدَ کَلِمٰتُ رَبِّیۡ»\nTranslation: (O Prophet, tell the people) Say: If the sea were ink for the words of my Lord, the sea would be exhausted before the words of my Lord are exhausted."
    }
  ],
  "408": [
    {
      "id": 1913,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Straight / Upright",
      "hw": "سیدھا",
      "s": "« » balanced, moderate, and straight (41 verses: 1:5-2:142-2:213-3:51-3:101-4:68-4:175-5:16-6:39-6:87-6:126-6:153-6:161-7:16-9:7-10:25-10:89-11:56-15:41-16:76-16:121-17:35-19:36-22:54-22:67-23:73-24:46-26:182-36:4-36:61-37:118-41:6-42:52-43:43-43:61-43:64-46:30-48:2-48:20-67:22-81:28)",
      "d": "«مُسْتَقِیْم» «قَامَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» «اَقَامَ الشَّیْ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ زِنُوۡا بِالۡقِسۡطَاسِ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: And weigh with a straight balance.\nBecause if the beam of the balance, which is already straight, does not remain parallel to the horizontal line, then the weighing will also not be balanced, even though the beam is and remains straight regardless of whether one pan is tilted down. So here, 'straight' means straight in the vertical direction, i.e., it should also remain parallel. And in terms of geometry, the shortest distance between two points or two places is called a straight line. So the 'Sirat-e-Mustaqeem' (Straight Path) is the path that is straight and has no kind of deviation, flexibility, or incline in it, i.e., it is free from excess and deficiency.\nFor example: In the Quran, we have been taught this supplication:\n«اِہۡدِ نَا الصِّرَاطَ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمَ»\nTranslation: O Allah, guide us to the Straight Path."
    },
    {
      "id": 1915,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Straight / Upright",
      "hw": "سیدھا",
      "s": "« » the correct determination of values and the straight path free from excess and deficiency (3 verses: 9:42-16:9-31:19)",
      "d": "« » is the permissible use of something. For example, if a person can take a bath from one bucket of water, and he uses exactly that much, it is 'qasad'. If he uses more, it is 'israf' (extravagance), and if he uses less than the bucket, it is 'bukhl' (stinginess). And to take care of this matter in every transaction and make it a habit is called 'economy' (iqtisad). Now, looking at it spiritually, neither softness nor harshness alone can work in every situation. So, how much harshness or to what extent softness should be applied so that the intended goal is achieved—this is the job of Sharia to tell us.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ  قَصۡدُ السَّبِیۡلِ وَ مِنۡہَا جَآئِرٌ»\nTranslation: And to show the Straight Path is upon Allah (besides that), all other paths are crooked.\nNote: The meaning of « » is not correctly conveyed by merely 'moderating' or 'making moderate'. Therefore, its meaning is taken as 'straight'."
    },
    {
      "id": 1916,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Straight / Upright",
      "hw": "سیدھا",
      "s": "« » such a thing in which there is no obstruction. Firm, clear, and straight (2 verses: 4:9-33:70)",
      "d": "«سَدُّ» «سُدٌّ» «سِدَاد» «قَوْلاً سَدِیْدًا» «قَوْلَ الزُّوْر»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَلۡیَتَّقُوا اللّٰہَ وَ لۡیَقُوۡلُوۡا قَوۡلًا سَدِیۡدًا»\nTranslation: So let them fear Allah and speak straight speech."
    }
  ],
  "409": [
    {
      "id": 1917,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Ladder",
      "hw": "سیڑھی",
      "s": "« » means ladder, staircase (2 verses: 6:35-52:38)",
      "d": "«سُلَّم» «سُلَّم» «سُلَّم» «سَلاَلِمُ» «سَلَالِیْم» «اَدْرَاجُ السُّلَم»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغِیَ نَفَقًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَوۡ  سُلَّمًا فِی السَّمَآءِ»\nTranslation: So if you have the power, then seek a tunnel in the earth or a ladder in the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 1918,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Ladder",
      "hw": "سیڑھی",
      "s": "« » means places of ascent (2 verses: 43:33-70:3)",
      "d": "«مِعْرَاج» «عَرَجَ» «اَعْرَج» «عَرَجَ فِی السُّلم» «مِعْرَاج» «مِعْرَاج» «سُلَّم» «سُلَّم»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّ مَعَارِجَ عَلَیۡہَا یَظۡہَرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And (there are) ladders upon which they ascend."
    }
  ],
  "410": [
    {
      "id": 1920,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "To Learn / To Teach",
      "hw": "سیکھنا",
      "s": "« » to learn something through reception (6 verses: 2:37-7:115-17:39-20:65-27:6-60:1)",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ» «تَلَقّٰی» «تَلَقَّی الشَّیْءُ مِنْہُ» «تَلَقّٰی»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَتَلَقّٰۤی اٰدَمُ مِنۡ رَّبِّہٖ کَلِمٰتٍ فَتَابَ عَلَیۡہِ»\nTranslation: So Adam learned some words from his Lord, then Allah accepted his repentance."
    }
  ],
  "411": [
    {
      "id": 1922,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Branch",
      "hw": "شاخ",
      "s": "« » whatever comes out of something besides its origin is its « » (1 verse: 14:24)",
      "d": "«فَرَعَ» «اصل» «فَرَعَ» «فُرُوْع» «فَرَعُ الشَّجَر»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«مَثَلًا کَلِمَۃً طَیِّبَۃً  کَشَجَرَۃٍ  طَیِّبَۃٍ اَصۡلُہَا ثَابِتٌ وَّ فَرۡعُہَا فِی  السَّمَآءِ»\nTranslation: The example of a good word is like a good tree, whose root is firm and whose branches are in the sky.\nAnd this word is used in both material and spiritual forms. 'Furu'i' (branched) issues are those issues that are based on another thing (the origin) and have been analogized from it. But there is no example of this in the Quran."
    },
    {
      "id": 1924,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Branch",
      "hw": "شاخ",
      "s": "« » means branches and twigs (1 verse: 55:48)",
      "d": "«اَفْنَان» «فَنَن» «فَنَن» «شَجَرَۃٌ فَنَانٌ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«ذَوَاتَاۤ   اَفۡنَانٍ»\nTranslation: Both (trees) are having large branches."
    }
  ],
  "412": [
    {
      "id": 1925,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Evening Times",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "« » means the time from after the sun's zenith (noon) until sunset (1 verse: 34:12)",
      "d": "«رَوَاح» «رَوَاح» «غُدُوّ» «غُدْوَۃ» «اَلْغُدُوُّ وَ الرَّوَاح»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لِسُلَیۡمٰنَ الرِّیۡحَ غُدُوُّہَا شَہۡرٌ وَّ رَوَاحُہَا شَہۡرٌ»\nTranslation: And for Solomon (We subjected) the wind: its morning course was a month's journey and its evening course was a month's journey."
    },
    {
      "id": 1926,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Times of the Evening",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "« » refers to the time after the afternoon (7 verses: 7:205, 13:15, 24:36, 25:5, 33:42, 48:9, 76:25)",
      "d": "The plural of « » is « ». « » means the time after the afternoon (i.e., evening). Its opposite is « », meaning the time of morning (p. 292).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اذۡکُرِ اسۡمَ رَبِّکَ بُکۡرَۃً وَّ اَصِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And remember your Lord in the morning and in the evening."
    },
    {
      "id": 1927,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Times of the Evening",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "« » refers to the time from after the Maghrib prayer until complete darkness, the time of 'Isha' (14 verses: 3:41, 6:52, 12:16, 18:28, 19:11, 19:62, 24:58, 30:18, 38:18, 38:31, 40:46, 40:55, 43:36, 79:46)",
      "d": "The time of « » begins before sunset and its opposite is « ». Its other opposites are « » and « ».\nNow consider the examples:\nExample 1 - Divine command:\n«اَلنَّارُ یُعۡرَضُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا غُدُوًّا وَّ عَشِیًّا»\nTranslation: They will be exposed to the Fire morning and evening.\nExample 2 - Divine command:\n«وَ لَا تَطۡرُدِ الَّذِیۡنَ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ بِالۡغَدٰوۃِ وَ الۡعَشِیِّ یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ وَجۡہَہٗ»\nTranslation: And do not drive away those who call upon their Lord morning and evening, seeking His countenance.\nExample 3 - Divine command:\n«وَ اذۡکُرۡ رَّبَّکَ کَثِیۡرًا وَّ سَبِّحۡ بِالۡعَشِیِّ وَ الۡاِبۡکَارِ»\nTranslation: And remember your Lord much and glorify Him in the evening and the morning.\nThe time for the 'Isha' prayer, which is specified and prescribed, is from when darkness has fully enveloped until the middle of the night.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مِنۡ قَبۡلِ صَلٰوۃِ الۡفَجۡرِ وَ حِیۡنَ تَضَعُوۡنَ ثِیَابَکُمۡ مِّنَ الظَّہِیۡرَۃِ وَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ صَلٰوۃِ الۡعِشَآءِ ثَلٰثُ عَوۡرٰتٍ لَّکُمۡ»\nTranslation: (There is) no blame upon you for entering your houses before the dawn prayer and when you put aside your garments at noon, and after the 'Isha' prayer. These are three times of privacy for you.\nFor 'evening', the word « » (masa) is used."
    },
    {
      "id": 1928,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Times of the Evening",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "« » means to become evening (1 verse: 30:17)",
      "d": "« » means the time of evening. And « » means to do something in the evening, to enter the evening, or to perform an action during the evening time. Its opposite is « », meaning morning, to do something in the morning, to enter the morning, or to perform an action during the morning time.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَسُبۡحٰنَ اللّٰہِ حِیۡنَ تُمۡسُوۡنَ وَ حِیۡنَ تُصۡبِحُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: So glorify Allah when you enter the evening and when you enter the morning."
    }
  ],
  "413": [
    {
      "id": 1929,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Perhaps",
      "hw": "شاید",
      "s": "« » is used for strong hope (28 verses: 2:216, 2:246, 4:19, 4:84, 4:99, 5:52, 7:129, 7:185, 9:18, 9:102, 12:21, 12:83, 17:8, 17:51, 17:79, 18:24, 18:40, 19:48, 27:72, 28:9, 28:22, 28:67, 47:22, 49:11, 60:7, 66:5, 66:8, 68:32)",
      "d": "« » is from the verbs of nearness (af'aal muqarabah) and is a static (jamid) verb. It is used only for the past tense and does not come for the present/future (mudaari'). It is used for strong hope in a desirable matter and for fear in an undesirable matter (Manjad).\nFor strong hope in a desirable matter:\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عَسٰی رَبِّیۡۤ اَنۡ یَّہۡدِیَنِیۡ سَوَآءَ السَّبِیۡلِ»\nTranslation: I hope that my Lord will guide me to the right path.\nAnd for fear in an undesirable matter:\nFor example, Divine command states:\n«فَہَلۡ عَسَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ تَوَلَّیۡتُمۡ اَنۡ تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ تُقَطِّعُوۡۤا اَرۡحَامَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: (O hypocrites!) Is it any wonder to you if you were to turn back on your heels and cause corruption in the land and sever your ties of kinship?\nNote: Verbs of nearness (af'aal muqarabah) are those verbs that bring the news close to the level of a noun."
    },
    {
      "id": 1930,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Perhaps",
      "hw": "شاید",
      "s": "« » is used for a strong possibility (125 verses: 2:21, 2:52, 2:53, 2:56, 2:63, 2:73, 2:150, 2:179, 2:183, 2:185, 2:186, 2:187, 2:189, 2:219, 2:221, 2:242, 2:266, 3:72, 3:103, 3:123, 3:130, 3:132, 3:200, 5:6, 5:35, 5:89, 5:90, 5:100, 6:42, 6:51, 6:65, 6:69, 6:151, 6:152, 6:153, 6:154, 6:155, 7:26, 7:57, 7:63, 7:69, 7:94, 7:130, 7:158, 7:164, 7:168, 7:171, 7:174, 7:176, 7:204, 8:26, 8:45, 8:57, 9:12, 9:122, 11:12, 12:2, 12:46, 12:62, 13:2, 14:25, 14:37, 16:14, 16:15, 16:44, 16:78, 16:81, 16:90, 18:6, 20:44, 20:113, 20:130, 21:13, 21:31, 21:58, 21:61, 21:111, 22:36, 22:77, 23:49, 23:100, 24:1, 24:27, 24:31, 24:56, 24:61, 26:3, 26:40, 26:129, 27:7, 27:46, 28:29, 28:38, 28:43, 28:46, 28:51, 28:73, 30:41, 30:46, 32:3, 32:21, 33:63, 35:12, 36:45, 36:74, 39:27, 39:28, 40:36, 40:67, 41:26, 42:17, 43:3, 43:10, 43:28, 43:48, 44:58, 45:12, 46:27, 49:10, 51:49, 57:17, 59:21, 62:10, 65:1, 80:3)",
      "d": "« » is a particle resembling a verb (harf mushbi bil-fi'l). It is used only for a strong possibility.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا یُدۡرِیۡکَ لَعَلَّ السَّاعَۃَ تَکُوۡنُ قَرِیۡبًا»\nTranslation: And what will make you know? Perhaps the Hour is near.\n«لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ»\nFor example, Divine command states:\n«لَا تَدۡرِیۡ لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ اَمۡرًا»\nTranslation: You do not know; perhaps Allah will bring about after that a (new) matter.\n«إن . أن. كان . لكن ، ليت . لعل»"
    }
  ],
  "414": [
    {
      "id": 1931,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Wine",
      "hw": "شراب",
      "s": "« » is a general term for any drink that intoxicates and deprives one of reason and senses (6 verses: 2:219, 5:90, 5:91, 12:36, 12:41, 47:15)",
      "d": "« » means to cover. The plural of « » is « », meaning a veil or headscarf with which one can cover the face, etc. Wine is also called « » because it covers and destroys reason and senses.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا الۡخَمۡرُ وَ الۡمَیۡسِرُ وَ الۡاَنۡصَابُ وَ الۡاَزۡلَامُ رِجۡسٌ مِّنۡ عَمَلِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ»\nTranslation: Intoxicants, gambling, (sacrificing to) stone altars, and divining arrows are but an abomination of Satan's handiwork."
    },
    {
      "id": 1932,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Wine",
      "hw": "شراب",
      "s": "« » refers to a delicious, delightful, pure, and flawless wine that will be in Paradise (4 verses: 23:50, 37:45, 56:18, 67:30)",
      "d": "«مَعَنَ الْمَاءَ» «مَعَنَ النَّظْر فِی الْاَمْر» «مَعِیْن»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَصۡبَحَ مَآؤُکُمۡ غَوۡرًا فَمَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِمَآءٍ مَّعِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: Do you see, if your water becomes sunken (into the earth), who then can bring you flowing water? (i.e., a spring of sweet water).\nHowever, in the following verse, the word « » (a filled cup) changes the meaning of « » to mean delightful wine. Such wine that is free from the harms of « ». Because the word « » generally refers to a filled cup for wine or for wine itself.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وِلۡدَانٌ مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ - بِاَکۡوَابٍ وَّ اَبَارِیۡقَ ۙ وَ کَاۡسٍ مِّنۡ مَّعِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: Round about them will (serve) endless (youthful) boys, with goblets, (shining) beakers, and cups (full) of a flowing wine."
    }
  ],
  "415": [
    {
      "id": 1934,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To Feel Shame / To be Modest",
      "hw": "شرمانا",
      "s": "« » means to feel shame/modesty due to haya (modesty) (3 verses: 2:26, 28:25, 33:53)",
      "d": "«حَیِیَ یَحْیٰی حَیٰوۃً» «حَیَّ یَحَیُّ حَیًّاء» «اِسْتِحْیَاء»\nExample of material usage: Divine command states:\n«فَجَآءَتۡہُ اِحۡدٰىہُمَا تَمۡشِیۡ عَلَی اسۡتِحۡیَآءٍ»\nTranslation: Then one of the two women came to him, walking shyly (or with modesty).\nExample of spiritual usage: Divine command states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡیٖۤ اَنۡ یَّضۡرِبَ مَثَلًا مَّا بَعُوۡضَۃً فَمَا فَوۡقَہَا»\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is not ashamed to set forth any parable - (be it) that of a mosquito or what is even smaller."
    },
    {
      "id": 1935,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To Feel Shame / To be Modest",
      "hw": "شرمانا",
      "s": "« » is a blameworthy trait, meaning to feel shame/disdain out of arrogance and to consider something a source of shame/disgrace (2 verses: 4:172, 4:173)",
      "d": "« » means to raise one's nose in arrogance. And « » means to consider something, out of arrogance, as a cause of shame and disgrace (Manjad).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَنۡ یَّسۡتَنۡکِفَ الۡمَسِیۡحُ اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ عَبۡدًا لِّلّٰہِ»\nTranslation: The Messiah will never be ashamed to be a servant of Allah."
    }
  ],
  "416": [
    {
      "id": 1936,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To Begin / To Start",
      "hw": "شروع",
      "s": "« » means to begin an action (16 verses: 2:117, 6:101, 7:29, 9:13, 10:4, 10:34, 12:76, 21:104, 27:64, 29:19, 29:20, 30:11, 30:27, 32:7, 34:49, 85:13)",
      "d": "« » comes in two meanings: (1) To begin an action, to initiate, to start. (2) To do something before (someone else). And if its attribution is to Allah, its meanings become 'to create for the first time' (its opposite is « » meaning to repeat the same action).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَبَدَاَ بِاَوۡعِیَتِہِمۡ قَبۡلَ وِعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ»\nTranslation: Then he began the search in their bags before his brother's bag.\nIn this verse, both meanings of « » are found. One meaning is that he started the search with the bags of the other brothers. The second is that he searched the bags of the other brothers before searching his brother's bag.\nAlso, Divine command states:\n«اِنَّہٗ ہُوَ یُبۡدِئُ وَ یُعِیۡدُ»\nTranslation: He it is Who originates the creation and will repeat it."
    },
    {
      "id": 1937,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "To begin",
      "hw": "شروع",
      "s": "« » is an incomplete verb, meaning that the actual action is performed by another [verb]. When combined with it, this verb conveys the meaning of beginning. (3 verses: 7:22-20:121-38:33)",
      "d": "« » is an incomplete verb that requires another verb with it (according to Manjad). It is used in positive sentences. Meaning: to begin.\n«وَ طَفِقَا یَخۡصِفٰنِ عَلَیۡہِمَا مِنۡ وَّرَقِ الۡجَنَّۃِ»\nTranslation: And both (Adam and Eve) began to cover themselves with leaves from Paradise.\n«فَطَفِقَ مَسۡحًۢا بِالسُّوۡقِ وَ الۡاَعۡنَاقِ»\nTranslation: So he (Solomon) began to stroke their shanks and necks.\nNote: Incomplete verb: A verb that does not indicate the completion of an action or does not complete a matter. Until a noun or adjective other than the subject is attached to it."
    }
  ],
  "417": [
    {
      "id": 1938,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Private part",
      "hw": "شرم گاہ",
      "s": "« » is the open space between two things (private part). (7 verses: 21:91-23:5-24:30-24:31-33:35-66:12-70:29)",
      "d": "«فَرْج» «فُرُوْج» «فَرَجَ» «فَرْج» «فَرْجُ الطَّرِیْق» «فَرْج» «فَرْج» «فَرْج»\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِفُرُوۡجِہِمۡ حٰفِظُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And those who guard their private parts."
    },
    {
      "id": 1939,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Private part",
      "hw": "شرم گاہ",
      "s": "« » refers to the private parts if they are exposed, and any thing whose exposure is bad. (6 verses: 5:31-7:20-7:22-7:26-7:27-20:121)",
      "d": "«سَوْء ، سُوْء» «سَوْءَۃَ» «سَوْءَۃَ»\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ  قَدۡ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  لِبَاسًا یُّوَارِیۡ سَوۡاٰتِکُمۡ وَ رِیۡشًا»\nTranslation: O children of Adam! We have sent down upon you clothing that covers your private parts and as adornment.\n«فَلَمَّا ذَاقَا الشَّجَرَۃَ بَدَتۡ لَہِمَا سَوۡاٰتُہُمَا»\nTranslation: When they both tasted the tree, their private parts became exposed to them.\nThen, in the same sense, the word « » has been used for a corpse, because it too, after some time, if not buried, becomes a repulsive sight.\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ»\nTranslation: Then Allah sent a crow that scratched in the earth to show him how to cover the private part of his brother."
    }
  ],
  "418": [
    {
      "id": 1940,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Partner",
      "hw": "شریک",
      "s": "« » means partial partner, i.e., those whose affair is one. (2 verses: 9:102-38:24)",
      "d": "« » means to mix one thing with another; its opposite is « » meaning pure, unadulterated, and clear. « » means one who mixes with people. « » refers to those whose affair is one. And « » means partnership (according to Manjad). In idiomatic meanings, « » means 'partial partner', i.e., partners who have some arrangements jointly and some separately. For example, Zaid and Bakr both have separate herds that are their own property, but for their protection, they have jointly taken a place on rent or pay a common herdsman a shared salary. Such partners are called « » (according to Hadith, Zakat is due on the shared property of such « »).\n«اِنَّ کَثِیۡرًا مِّنَ الۡخُلَطَآءِ لَیَبۡغِیۡ  بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ»\nTranslation: Indeed, many partners wrong each other."
    },
    {
      "id": 1941,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Partner",
      "hw": "شریک",
      "s": "« » means one who has complete participation in a work. (3 verses: 6:163-17:111-25:2)",
      "d": "«شَرِیْک» «وَّ لَمۡ  یَکُنۡ لَّہٗ  شَرِیۡکٌ فِی الۡمُلۡکِ  وَ لَمْ یَکُنۡ لَّہٗ  وَلِیٌّ  مِّنَ الذُّلِّ»\nTranslation: And He has no partner in the kingdom, and He has no protector from humiliation.\nAnd spiritual partnership is like humans and animals sharing in animality. This is an attribute-based partnership. Allah is far above this, as clearly stated in many verses."
    }
  ],
  "419": [
    {
      "id": 1943,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Flame",
      "hw": "شعلہ",
      "s": "« » is a general term for flame, the flame of fire. (2 verses: 77:31-111:3)",
      "d": "« » means the movement and rising of fire, and the tongue of fire rising (according to Muf). It is used in the well-known sense of flame and is a general term for flame.\n«سَیَصۡلٰی نَارًا ذَاتَ  لَہَبٍ»\nTranslation: He will enter a fire having flames."
    },
    {
      "id": 1945,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Flame",
      "hw": "شعلہ",
      "s": "« » is the hottest part above the flame. (1 verse: 55:15)",
      "d": "« » is the hottest part of the flame that is free from smoke, the tip of the flame (according to Muf).\n«وَ  خَلَقَ  الۡجَآنَّ مِنۡ مَّارِجٍ  مِّنۡ نَّارٍ»\nTranslation: And He created the jinn from a flame of fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 1946,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Flame",
      "hw": "شعلہ",
      "s": "« » are small sparks that fly off from a flame. (1 verse: 77:32)",
      "d": "« » are small pieces that break off from a large flame and fly away. Sparks, embers (according to Muf).\n«اِنَّہَا  تَرۡمِیۡ  بِشَرَرٍ  کَالۡقَصۡرِ»\nTranslation: It (Hell) will throw sparks as large as castles."
    }
  ],
  "420": [
    {
      "id": 1947,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "« » is the inability to prefer one of two theories due to lack of knowledge. (15 verses: 4:157-10:94-10:104-11:62-11:110-14:9-14:10-27:66-34:21-34:54-38:8-40:34-41:45-42:14-44:9)",
      "d": "« » means two theories being equal and balanced in the mind when there is no evidence to prefer one over the other. Essentially, the basis of doubt is ignorance or lack of knowledge (according to Muf).\n«اَفِی اللّٰہِ شَکٌّ فَاطِرِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ»\nTranslation: Is there doubt about Allah, the Originator of the heavens and the earth?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1948,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "« » means that two or more things are so similar that one cannot distinguish between them correctly. (9 verses: 2:25-2:70-2:118-3:7-4:157-6:99-6:141-13:16-39:23)",
      "d": "« » means that two or more things are so similar in appearance or attributes that one cannot properly distinguish between them (according to Muf).\n«وَ مَا قَتَلُوۡہُ وَ مَا صَلَبُوۡہُ وَ لٰکِنۡ شُبِّہَ لَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And they did not kill him, nor did they crucify him, but it was made to appear so to them.\n«اِنَّ الۡبَقَرَ تَشٰبَہَ عَلَیۡنَا»\nTranslation: Indeed, the cow has become confusing to us."
    },
    {
      "id": 1949,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and Suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "« » To make an accepted (acknowledged) truth doubtful through speculative (imaginary) and suspicious matters (4 verses: 11:109, 22:55, 32:23, 41:54)",
      "d": "The word « » has two fundamental meanings: (1) For a truth or theory to be accepted (established), and (2) To persistently cast doubt on that truth through suspicious matters. (M, L) Hence, this word also appears in the meanings of arguing and disputing. And the basis of such an argument is these very matters of doubt.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَبِاَیِّ  اٰلَآءِ  رَبِّکَ  تَتَمَارٰی»\nTranslation: So, O human! About which of your Lord's favors will you dispute?\nAnd « » refers to the doubts about a truth created by people.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«فَلَا تَکُنۡ فِیۡ مِرۡیَۃٍ  مِّنۡ لِّقَآئِہٖ»\nTranslation: So, do not be in doubt concerning the meeting (with your Lord)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1950,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and Suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "« » Sometimes one thought comes, sometimes another, and then the first again, and to remain in doubt on this basis (1 verse: 50:5)",
      "d": "«مَرَجَ» «غُصْنٌ مَّرِیۡجٌ» «مَرَجَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَلۡ کَذَّبُوۡا بِالۡحَقِّ لَمَّا جَآءَہُمۡ فَہُمۡ  فِیۡۤ اَمۡرٍ  مَّرِیۡجٍ»\nTranslation: But when the truth came to them, they denied it. So they are (now) in a confused state (of affairs)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1951,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and Suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "« » To mix two theories in such a way that one cannot distinguish between them (7 verses: 2:42, 3:71, 6:9, 6:65, 6:82, 6:137, 50:15)",
      "d": "« » means commingling and intermingling (i.e., one thing mixing with another and being included within it) (M. L). That is, to confuse two things together and to incorporate one into the other. Such as mixing falsehood with truth and blending some truth into falsehood, thereby making the reality so suspicious that the distinction between truth and falsehood cannot be made. And one who is caught in such a state of doubt and suspicion is called « ». This word is also used in the context of rejection and in the form of speech (Faq L 249).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَلۡ ہُمۡ فِیۡ لَبۡسٍ مِّنۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ»\nTranslation: Nay, but they are in doubt about a new creation.\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ لَا تَلۡبِسُوا الۡحَقَّ بِالۡبَاطِلِ»\nTranslation: And do not mix the truth with falsehood."
    },
    {
      "id": 1952,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Doubt and Suspicion",
      "hw": "شک",
      "s": "« » A doubt that also includes agitation, restlessness, and hesitation (18 verses: 2:2, 2:23, 3:9, 3:25, 4:87, 6:12, 9:45, 9:110, 10:37, 17:99, 18:21, 22:5, 22:7, 32:2, 40:59, 42:7, 45:26, 45:32)",
      "d": "«رَیْب» «رَیْبُ الدَّہْر» «رَیْبُ الْمَنُوْن» «رَیْب» «دَعْ مَا یُرِیْبَکَ اِلٰی مَا لَا یُرِیْبَکَ» «رَیْبَۃ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ لَفِیۡ شَکٍّ  مِّنۡہُ  مُرِیۡبٍ»\nTranslation: Indeed, they are in a doubt about it that disturbs them.\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«ذٰلِکَ  الۡکِتٰبُ لَا رَیۡبَ فِیْہِ»\nTranslation: This is the Book about which there is no doubt (or peril)."
    }
  ],
  "421": [
    {
      "id": 1954,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Form and Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "« » Things that resemble each other in form and shape (1 verse: 38:58)",
      "d": "«مُشَاکِلَۃ» «اشکال» «شَکَلَ الْاَمْر» «شَکْل» «اشکال»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ اٰخَرُ  مِنۡ شَکۡلِہٖۤ  اَزۡوَاجٌ»\nTranslation: And other kinds (of punishments) similar to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 1955,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Form and Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "« » The external features of a material thing by which it can be recognized and distinguished from other things (1 verse: 82:8)",
      "d": "« » means the external features of a material thing by which it can be recognized. And it can be distinguished from other things (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فِیۡۤ  اَیِّ صُوۡرَۃٍ  مَّا شَآءَ  رَکَّبَکَ»\nTranslation: Then, in whatever form Allah willed, He composed you."
    },
    {
      "id": 1956,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Form and Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "« » A likeness, image, statue, or representation of an original thing (2 verses: 21:52, 34:13)",
      "d": "« » (plural «  ,  ») means to take on the form and shape of another thing and to stand upright. And « » is a thing made according to a model (sample). And « » means to become in the form of someone, to assume the guise of someone (Muf). And « » means an image, a picture, or a representation of a thing (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ قَالَ لِاَبِیۡہِ وَ قَوۡمِہٖ مَا ہٰذِہِ التَّمَاثِیۡلُ  الَّتِیۡۤ  اَنۡتُمۡ  لَہَا  عٰکِفُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: When he (Prophet Ibrahim) said to his father and his people: What are these statues to which you are devoted?"
    },
    {
      "id": 1957,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Forming a Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "« » To draw a picture, to form a shape (4 verses: 3:6, 7:11, 40:64, 64:3)",
      "d": "« » means to draw a picture, to form a shape (Manjad). This word is generally applied to living things, and forming the shape of living things is a special attribute of Allah, the Most High.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ہُوَ  الَّذِیۡ یُصَوِّرُکُمۡ  فِی الۡاَرۡحَامِ  کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ»\nTranslation: He it is Who shapes you in the wombs however He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 1958,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Forming a Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "« » To make the initial sketch and design (210 verses: 2:21, 2:29, 2:164, 2:228, 3:47, 3:49, 3:59, 3:190, 3:191, 4:1, 4:28, 4:119, 5:17, 5:18, 5:110, 6:1, 6:2, 6:73, 6:94, 6:100, 6:101, 6:102, 7:11, 7:12, 7:54, 7:69, 7:181, 7:185, 7:189, 7:191, 9:36, 10:3, 10:4, 10:5, 10:6, 10:34, 11:7, 11:119, 13:5, 13:16, 14:19, 14:32, 15:26, 15:27, 15:28, 15:33, 15:85, 16:3, 16:4, 16:5, 16:8, 16:17, 16:20, 16:48, 16:70, 16:81, 17:49, 17:51, 17:61, 17:70, 17:98, 17:99, 18:37, 18:48, 18:51, 19:9, 19:67, 20:4, 20:50, 20:55, 21:16, 21:33, 21:37, 21:104, 22:5, 22:73, 23:12, 23:14, 23:17, 23:91, 23:115, 24:45, 25:2, 25:3, 25:49, 25:54, 25:59, 26:78, 26:166, 26:184, 27:60, 27:64, 28:68, 29:17, 29:19, 29:20, 29:44, 29:61, 30:8, 30:11, 30:20, 30:21, 30:22, 30:27, 30:30, 30:40, 30:54, 31:10, 31:11, 31:25, 31:28, 32:4, 32:7, 32:10, 34:7, 35:1, 35:3, 35:11, 35:16, 35:40, 36:36, 36:42, 36:68, 36:71, 36:77, 36:78, 36:79, 36:81, 37:11, 37:96, 37:125, 37:150, 38:27, 38:71, 38:75, 38:76, 39:4, 39:5, 39:6, 39:38, 39:62, 40:57, 40:62, 40:67, 41:9, 41:15, 41:21, 41:37, 42:29, 42:49, 43:9, 43:12, 43:16, 43:19, 43:87, 44:38, 44:39, 45:4, 45:22, 46:3, 46:4, 46:33, 49:13, 50:15, 50:16, 50:38, 51:49, 51:56, 52:35, 52:36, 53:45, 54:49, 55:3, 55:14, 55:15, 56:57, 56:59, 57:4, 59:24, 64:2, 64:3, 65:12, 67:2, 67:3, 67:14, 70:19, 70:39, 71:14, 71:15, 74:11, 75:38, 76:2, 76:28, 77:20, 78:8, 79:27, 80:18, 80:19, 82:7, 86:5, 86:6, 87:2, 88:17, 89:8, 90:4, 92:3, 95:4, 96:1, 96:2, 113:2)",
      "d": "« » To make the initial sketch and design before the completion of a material thing's form.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ مِنۡ مُّضۡغَۃٍ مُّخَلَّقَۃٍ»\nTranslation: Then from a leech-like clot (He creates a formation that is) shaped (in a preliminary form)."
    },
    {
      "id": 1959,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Forming a Shape",
      "hw": "صورت",
      "s": "« » To assume a guise, to take on a form (1 verse: 19:17)",
      "d": "« » means to change one's own form and shape to become like the form and shape of another. To assume a guise.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہَا رُوۡحَنَا فَتَمَثَّلَ لَہَا بَشَرًا سَوِیًّا»\nTranslation: So We sent to her Our spirit, and it assumed for her the form of a perfect man."
    }
  ],
