  "423": [
    {
      "id": 1962,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City. Settlement",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "« » is a settlement where people live under established rules and regulations (14 verses: 7:123-9:101-9:120-12:30-15:67-18:19-18:82-27:48-28:15-28:18-28:20-33:60-36:20-63:8)",
      "d": "«مَدَن» «تَمَدَّن» «مَدِیْنَۃ» «مَدَائِن» «وَ جَآءَ مِنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ رَجُلٌ یَّسۡعٰی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1963,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City. Settlement",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "« » is a city whose boundaries have been defined (14 verses: 2:126-7:57-7:58-14:35-16:7-25:49-27:91-34:15-35:9-43:11-50:11-90:1-90:2-95:3)",
      "d": "«بَلَد» «بِلاَد» «لَاۤ اُقۡسِمُ بِہٰذَا الۡبَلَدِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1964,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City. Settlement",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "« » is a city whose boundaries have been defined and which also has a wall or fortification (5 verses: 2:61-10:87-12:21-12:99-43:51)",
      "d": "«مِصْر» «مُصُوْر» «اِشْتَرٰی فُلَانُ الدَّار بِمُصُوْرِھَا» «مِصْر» «مِصْر» «اِہۡبِطُوۡا مِصۡرًا فَاِنَّ لَکُمۡ مَّا سَاَلۡتُمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1965,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Dwellings. Abodes",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "« » can refer to a home, village, town, city, country, or even the entire world (16 verses: 2:84-2:85-2:243-2:246-3:195-4:66-8:47-11:67-11:94-17:5-22:40-33:27-59:2-59:8-60:8-60:9)",
      "d": "«دِیَار» «دَار» «دُوْر» «دُوْر» «دَار» «دَیْر» «دَار» «دَارُ الْحَرْب» «دَارُ الْقَرَار» «دَارُ الدُّنْیَا» «دَارَان» «دَارَیْن» «فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ اُوۡلٰىہُمَا بَعَثۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ عِبَادًا لَّنَاۤ اُولِیۡ بَاۡسٍ شَدِیۡدٍ فَجَاسُوۡا خِلٰلَ الدِّیَارِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1966,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Settlement. Town",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "« » means a large settlement, city, or village, and also its inhabitants (37 verses: 2:58-2:259-4:75-6:123-7:4-7:82-7:88-7:94-7:161-7:163-10:98-12:82-15:4-16:112-17:16-17:58-18:77-21:6-21:11-21:74-21:95-22:45-22:48-25:40-25:51-26:208-27:34-27:56-28:58-29:31-29:34-34:34-36:13-43:23-43:31-47:13-65:8)",
      "d": "«قَرْیَۃ» «قُرٰی» «وَ کَاَیِّنۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍ عَتَتۡ عَنۡ اَمۡرِ رَبِّہَا وَ رُسُلِہٖ» «تِلۡکَ الۡقُرٰۤی اَہۡلَکۡنٰہُمۡ لَمَّا ظَلَمُوۡا»"
    }
  ],
  "424": [
    {
      "id": 1967,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Glass. Crystal",
      "hw": "شیشہ",
      "s": "« » means glass, crystal, something transparent through which one can see (1 verse: 24:35)",
      "d": "«زُجَاجَۃ» «اَلزُّجَاجِی» «اَلۡمِصۡبَاحُ فِیۡ زُجَاجَۃٍ ؕ اَلزُّجَاجَۃُ کَاَنَّہَا کَوۡکَبٌ دُرِّیٌّ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 1968,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Glass. Crystal",
      "hw": "شیشہ",
      "s": "« » is glass that is made for a specific purpose. Glassware, whether plain or colored (3 verses: 27:44-76:15-76:16)",
      "d": "«قَوَارِیر» «قَارُوْرَہ» «قَارُوْرَہ» «وَ یُطَافُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِاٰنِیَۃٍ مِّنۡ فِضَّۃٍ وَّ اَکۡوَابٍ کَانَتۡ قَؔوَارِیۡرَا۠»"
    }
  ],
  "425": [
    {
      "id": 1969,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "to purify",
      "hw": "صاف",
      "s": "« » means to purify something that has been compounded from several elements, where the mixture has thoroughly permeated it (2 verses: 3:141-3:154)",
      "d": "«مَحَّصَ» «مَحَّصَ الذَّھْب»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لِیُمَحِّصَ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ یَمۡحَقَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: so that Allah may purify the believers and destroy the disbelievers.\nNote: (cupel is the small cup in which gold and silver are melted.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 1972,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "to wipe clean",
      "hw": "صاف",
      "s": "« » means to wipe away dust and dirt by moving the hand, to brush off, to clean. (3 verses: 4:43-5:6-38:33)",
      "d": "« » means to move one's hand over something to remove dust and dirt around it, to brush off, to wipe.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَطَفِقَ مَسۡحًۢا بِالسُّوۡقِ وَ الۡاَعۡنَاقِ»\nTranslation: So Solomon began to wipe clean the necks and legs of the horses.\nIn Shariah terminology, 'masah' means applying clean soil or water to a place first, then wiping it to clean.\nFor example, Allah says:\n«فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا فَامۡسَحُوۡا بِوُجُوۡہِکُمۡ وَ اَیۡدِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہُ»\nTranslation: So intend clean soil, then wipe your faces and hands with it."
    }
  ],
  "427": [
    {
      "id": 1975,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "reconciliation",
      "hw": "صلح",
      "s": "« » refers to a mutual agreement between parties after a dispute (40 verses: 2:11-2:160-2:182-2:220-2:224-2:228-3:89-4:16-4:35-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:146-5:39-6:48-6:54-7:35-7:56-7:85-11:88-17:142-7:170-8:1-10:81-11:117-13:23-16:119-21:90-24:5-26:152-27:48-28:19-33:71-40:8-42:40-46:15-47:2-47:5-49:9-49:10)",
      "d": "« » is its opposite, meaning corruption or disorder. And « » means to correct disorder. And « » refers to a mutual agreement between parties among whom there was previously enmity, dispute, or fighting.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ طَآئِفَتٰنِ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اقۡتَتَلُوۡا فَاَصۡلِحُوۡا بَیۡنَہُمَا»\nTranslation: And if two parties among the believers fight, then make peace between them.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ اِنِ امۡرَاَۃٌ خَافَتۡ مِنۡۢ بَعۡلِہَا نُشُوۡزًا اَوۡ اِعۡرَاضًا فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡہِمَاۤ  اَنۡ یُّصۡلِحَا بَیۡنَہُمَا صُلۡحًا ؕ وَ الصُّلْحُ  خَیۡرٌ»\nTranslation: And if a woman fears from her husband contempt or evasion, there is no blame on them if they arrange a settlement between them. And settlement is good."
    },
    {
      "id": 1976,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "reconciliation",
      "hw": "صلح",
      "s": "« » refers to an agreement or peace that occurs before a fight or dispute arises. (6 verses: 4:90-4:91-8:61-16:28-16:87-47:35)",
      "d": "« » means safety, submission. And « » means to be saved, to be secure. And « » also refers to one who makes peace (manjad). And such an agreement or peace that occurs before a fight or dispute arises. To be obedient.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِنِ اعۡتَزَلُوۡکُمۡ فَلَمۡ یُقَاتِلُوۡکُمۡ  وَ اَلۡقَوۡا اِلَیۡکُمُ السَّلَمَ ۙ فَمَا جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  سَبِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: Then if they withdraw from you and do not fight you and offer you peace, then Allah has not made for you a way against them."
    }
  ],
  "428": [
    {
      "id": 1977,
      "a": "ض",
      "h": "guarantor",
      "hw": "ضامن",
      "s": "« » is a guarantor who is responsible for maintenance and care. (6 verses: 3:37-3:44-16:91-20:40-28:12-38:23)",
      "d": "« » means to be responsible for someone's maintenance and care, to be a guarantor. And « » also carries the meaning of taking guarantee for a criminal.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا کُنۡتَ لَدَیۡہِمۡ  اِذۡ  یُلۡقُوۡنَ اَقۡلَامَہُمۡ اَیُّہُمۡ یَکۡفُلُ مَرۡیَمَ»\nTranslation: And you were not with them when they cast their pens to determine which of them would be the guardian of Mary.\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«وَ قَدۡ جَعَلۡتُمُ اللّٰہَ  عَلَیۡکُمۡ  کَفِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And you have certainly made Allah a guarantor for yourselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 1978,
      "a": "ض",
      "h": "guarantor",
      "hw": "ضامن",
      "s": "« » is a guarantor who is responsible for something on behalf of the government. (2 verses: 12:72-68:40)",
      "d": "« » means leadership, headship. « » is a person who is responsible or guarantor for something on behalf of the government.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا نَفۡقِدُ صُوَاعَ  الۡمَلِکِ  وَ لِمَنۡ  جَآءَ بِہٖ  حِمۡلُ  بَعِیۡرٍ  وَّ اَنَا  بِہٖ  زَعِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: They said, 'We have lost the measuring bowl of the king, and for whoever brings it is the reward of a camel's load, and I am responsible for it.'"
    }
  ],
  "429": [
    {
      "id": 1979,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "« » is a general term meaning the amount of strength required for a task. (2 verses: 2:249-2:286)",
      "d": "« » is a well-known word and is commonly used. It means courage, strength (POWER) required for a task.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«رَبَّنَا وَ لَا  تُحَمِّلۡنَا مَا لَا طَاقَۃَ لَنَا بِہٖ»\nTranslation: Our Lord, do not impose upon us what we have no strength to bear."
    },
    {
      "id": 1980,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "« » refers to the innate ability (capability) and potential that exists within something. (26 verses: 2:63-2:93-2:165-7:145-7:171-8:60-9:69-11:52-11:80-16:92-18:39-18:95-19:12-27:33-28:76-28:78-30:9-30:54-35:44-40:21-40:82-41:15-47:13-51:58-81:20-86:10)",
      "d": "« » means force, innate ability and potential found in something. Its opposite is « » meaning weakness.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ مَفَاتِحَہٗ  لَتَنُوۡٓاُ بِالۡعُصۡبَۃِ  اُولِی الۡقُوَّۃِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, its keys would be carried by strong men."
    },
    {
      "id": 1981,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "« » means intensity. The permanent state of something. Strength. Firmness. (1 verse: 53:6)",
      "d": "« » means intensity, the permanent state of something, strength, firmness. (manjad) Intensity and determination. And « » is a phrase meaning strong and powerful, vigorous. And « » means a twisted rope.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عَلَّمَہٗ  شَدِیۡدُ الۡقُوٰی ذُوۡ مِرَّۃٍ ؕ  فَاسۡتَوٰی»\nTranslation: He was taught by one intense in strength and possessing firmness. So he rose."
    },
    {
      "id": 1982,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "« » is a member of a group, association, or organization, an individual of a faction. (3 verses: 11:80-11:113-17:74)",
      "d": "« » means a member of a group, association, or organization. And it also means pillar, fortress, support, and is used for assistance.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ لَوۡ اَنَّ لِیۡ بِکُمۡ قُوَّۃً  اَوۡ اٰوِیۡۤ اِلٰی رُکۡنٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ»\nTranslation: He said, 'If only I had strength against you or could take refuge in a strong pillar.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1984,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "to have strength",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "« » means to be capable of something, to have strength. (1 verse: 2:184)",
      "d": "« » means to have the courage and strength for a task. It is a well-known word.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ یُطِیۡقُوۡنَہٗ فِدۡیَۃٌ طَعَامُ مِسۡکِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: And upon those who are able to fast is an expiation of feeding a poor person."
    },
    {
      "id": 1985,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Have Power",
      "hw": "طاقت",
      "s": "« » means to have the power to do something. (40 verses: 2:217-2:273-2:282-3:97-4:25-4:98-4:129-5:112-6:35-7:192-7:197-8:60-9:42-10:38-11:13-11:20-11:88-16:73-17:48-17:64-18:41-18:67-18:72-18:75-18:78-18:97-18:101-21:40-21:43-25:9-25:19-26:211-36:50-36:67-36:75-51:45-55:33-58:4-64:16-68:42)",
      "d": "«استطاع الأمر»\n«وَلِلّٰهِ عَلَى النَّاسِ حِجُّ الْبَيْتِ مَنِ اسْتَطَاعَ إِلَيْهِ سَبِيلًا»\nTranslation: And upon the people is the Hajj of the House, for whoever is able to undertake the journey to it.\nTherefore, « » means to have power and capability, or to be able to do something.\n«فَمَا اسْتَطَاعُوا أَنْ يُظْهِرُوهُ وَمَا اسْتَطَاعُوا لَهُ نَقْبًا»\nTranslation: Then they had no power to climb over it, nor could they tunnel through it.\n«إِذْ قَالَ الْحَوَارِيُّونَ يَا عِيسَى ابْنَ مَرْيَمَ هَلْ يَسْتَطِيعُ رَبُّكَ أَنْ يُنَزِّلَ عَلَيْنَا مَائِدَةً مِنَ السَّمَاءِ»\nTranslation: And (remember) when the disciples said, 'O Jesus, son of Mary, can your Lord send down to us a table from the heaven?'"
    }
  ],
  "430": [
    {
      "id": 1986,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "« » refers to those customs and practices which people begin to consider as religious matters. (3 verses: 20:63-20:104-72:16)",
      "d": "« » means habit, state, religion (manjad). Every nation and religion is called « ». Which a person adopts for doing something, whether good or bad (muf).\n«وَ يَذۡہَبَا بِطَرِیۡقَتِکُمُ الۡمُثۡلٰی»\nTranslation: And both (Moses and Aaron) will destroy your noble religion.\n«إِذۡ يَقُوۡلُ أَمۡثَلُہُمۡ طَرِیۡقَۃً إِنۡ لَّبِثۡتُمۡ إِلَّا یَوۡمًا»\nTranslation: Then the best among them in terms of way/method will say, 'You remained only a day.'\nThus, in Islamic terminology, 'way' refers to those customs and habits which people have given the status of religious slogans."
    },
    {
      "id": 1987,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "« » refers to the divine laws that are perpetually in operation in the universe. Or the method which, once its foundation is laid, continues to function. (9 verses: 8:38-15:13-17:77-18:55-33:38-33:62-35:43-40:85-48:23)",
      "d": "«سَنَّ» «مَنْ سَنَّ سُنَّۃً»\n«فَهَلۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ إِلَّا سُنَّتَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ ۚ فَلَنۡ تَجِدَ لِسُنَّتِ اللّٰہِ تَبۡدِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: Do they then await anything but the way of the former peoples? So you will not find any change in Allah's way.\nAnd when only the word 'sunnah' is used, it generally refers to the method established by the Prophet ﷺ, and its plural is « ». The Prophet's example."
    },
    {
      "id": 1988,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "« » refers to a group of people who share the same ideology or belief, and those who think alike. (54 verses: 2:143-2:213-3:104-3:110-3:113-4:41-5:48-5:66-6:38-6:42-6:108-7:34-7:38-7:159-7:160-7:164-7:168-7:181-10:19-10:47-10:49-11:8-11:48-11:118-12:45-13:30-15:5-16:36-16:63-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:93-16:120-21:92-22:34-22:67-23:43-23:44-23:52-27:83-28:23-28:75-29:18-35:24-35:42-40:5-41:25-42:8-43:22-43:23-43:33-45:28-46:18)",
      "d": "« » means a group of people with the same belief or ideology (muf). Then this term is also applied to that ideology or belief upon which people agree, whether that ideology or belief is correct or incorrect.\n«إِنَّا وَجَدۡنَاۤ آبَاءَنَا عَلٰۤی أُمَّۃٍ وَّ إِنَّا عَلٰۤی آثَارِہِمۡ مُّقۡتَدُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Indeed, we found our fathers upon a certain belief, and indeed we are followers of their footsteps."
    },
    {
      "id": 1989,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "« » refers to those divine laws that are changed according to necessity and circumstances. (4 verses: 5:48-42:13-42:21-45:48)",
      "d": "«شَرَع» «شَرَعَ الْبَعِیرُ عُنُقَہٗ» «شَرَعَ لِلْقَوْم» «شَرِیْعَۃ» «شریعت» «شریعت»\n«ثُمَّ جَعَلۡنٰکَ عَلٰی شَرِیۡعَۃٍ مِّنَ الۡاَمۡرِ»\nTranslation: Then We have set you on a clear path of the religion."
    },
    {
      "id": 1990,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "« » is the method of implementing Sharia commands. Clarity and expanse. (1 verse: 5:48)",
      "d": "«نَھَجَ الْاَمْرُ وَ الطَّرِیْق» «مِنْھَاج» «منہاج»\n«لِکُلٍّ جَعَلۡنَا مِنۡکُمۡ شِرۡعَۃً وَّ مِنۡہَاجًا»\nTranslation: For each of you We have appointed a divine law and a clear path."
    },
    {
      "id": 1992,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "« » is one's method of action due to individual inclination. (1 verse: 17:84)",
      "d": "«شَکَلَ» «شَکُلَ الدَّایَۃ» «اَلنَّاسُ أَشْکَالٌ وَّ أُلَّافٌ» «شَاکِلَۃ» «شاکلہ»\n«قُلۡ کُلٌّ یَّعۡمَلُ عَلٰی شَاکِلَتِہٖ»\nTranslation: Say, 'Each acts according to their own manner.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 1993,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "method; custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "« » means goodness, kindness; a custom or practice that is liked in society and upon which there is no religious restriction (36 verses: 2:178-2:180-2:228-2:229-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:240-2:241-2:263-3:104-3:110-3:114-4:5-4:6-4:8-4:19-4:25-4:114-7:157-9:67-9:71-9:112-22:41-24:53-31:15-31:17-33:6-33:32-47:21-60:12-65:2-65:6)",
      "d": "« » means goodness, kindness, and its opposite is « », meaning anything disliked or forbidden by Shariah, evil, bad speech, bad deed. « » means to recognize. And   is any method, custom, or practice that is well-known in society and considered good, even if there is no specific religious guidance regarding it, such as sitting respectfully before elders and addressing them with 'ji' or 'aap'. These are not commanded in Shariah but are good things. This is  .\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لِلۡمُطَلَّقٰتِ مَتَاعٌۢ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ»\nTranslation: And divorced women also have a right to provision according to custom."
    },
    {
      "id": 1994,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "Method / Custom",
      "hw": "طریقہ",
      "s": "« » refers to those habits or ways that have become deeply ingrained in one's nature. (2 verses: 26:137-68:4)",
      "d": "«خَلْق، خِلْقَت» «خُلْق» «خُلْق» «خُلُق» «أخلاق»\n«إِنَّ هَذَاۤ إِلَّا خُلُقُ الْأَوَّلِینَ»\nTranslation: This is nothing but the way of the ancients."
    }
  ],
  "431": [
    {
      "id": 1995,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Taunt",
      "hw": "طعنہ",
      "s": "« » means to point out someone's flaw or weakness in a way that pierces like a thorn. (2 verses: 4:46-9:12)",
      "d": "« » means to wound with a spear, horn, or any sharp, pointed thing (muf). Then this word is used for saying something about a person or in their face that hurts like a spear, i.e., to mention someone's fault in a way that becomes very offensive to them (muf).\n«وَ إِن نَّکَثُوۡۤا أَیۡمَانَہُمۡ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ عَہۡدِہِمۡ وَ طَعَنُوۡا فِیۡ دِیۡنِکُمۡ فَقَاتِلُوۡۤا أَئِمَّۃَ الْکُفۡرِ»\nTranslation: If they break their oaths after their treaty and attack your religion, then fight the leaders of disbelief."
    },
    {
      "id": 1996,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Slander / Find Fault",
      "hw": "طعنہ",
      "s": "The Arabic word « » is used in all these meanings: to defame, to accuse, to slander, to disgrace, to find fault. (4 verses: 9:58, 9:79, 49:11, 104:1)",
      "d": "« » means to find fault or to criticize someone's flaws. To persistently look for someone's faults and, for that purpose, to speak ill of them (backbiting) so that some weak point of theirs is exposed. Then to taunt or mock them about it. It also means to unjustly accuse someone of their actions. (Faqih)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَلۡمِزُوۡنَ الۡمُطَّوِّعِیۡنَ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ فِی الصَّدَقٰتِ»\nTranslation: And those who find fault with the believers who give charity voluntarily."
    },
    {
      "id": 1997,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Slander / Find Fault",
      "hw": "طعنہ",
      "s": "« » means to taunt or mock through hints and allusions. (2 verses: 68:11, 104:1)",
      "d": "«ھَمَزَ» «ھَامَز» «ھَمَّاز» «ھَمَزَاتِ الشَّیٰطِیْن» «ھَامِز» «ھَمَزَ» «ھَمَزَ الْفَرَس»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ہَمَّازٍ مَّشَّآءٍۭ  بِنَمِیۡمٍ»\nTranslation: A taunting, scandal-mongering go-between."
    }
  ],
  "432": [
    {
      "id": 1998,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Put a Collar / Shackle",
      "hw": "طوق",
      "s": "« » can be used for a necklace, an ornament for the neck, a noose, an iron ring placed around the neck—it is applicable for all these. (1 verse: 3:180)",
      "d": "«طَوَّقَ» «اَطْوَاق» «اِطَّوَّقَ الْحَیَّۃ» «طَوَّقَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سَیُطَوَّقُوۡنَ مَا بَخِلُوۡا بِہٖ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ»\nTranslation: They will be shackled with what they hoarded on the Day of Resurrection."
    },
    {
      "id": 1999,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Put a Collar / Shackle",
      "hw": "طوق",
      "s": "« » means handcuffs or a shackle. (9 verses: 5:64, 7:157, 12:23, 13:5, 17:29, 34:33, 36:8, 40:71, 76:4)",
      "d": "The plural of « » is « ». This word is more general than « ». « » refers to anything with which a person's limbs are bound and tied together (Muf). It applies to handcuffs, chains, and collars alike. « » means to put handcuffs or a shackle on. (Majma')\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«خُذُوۡہُ  فَغُلُّوۡہُ ثُمَّ  الۡجَحِیۡمَ  صَلُّوۡہُ»\nTranslation: (The command will be given) 'Seize him and shackle him. Then throw him into the Blazing Fire.'"
    }
  ],
  "433": [
    {
      "id": 2000,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Covet / Have Strong Hope",
      "hw": "طمع",
      "s": "« » means to have a strong hope or desire for something in one's heart. (12 verses: 2:75, 5:84, 7:46, 7:56, 13:12, 26:51, 26:82, 30:24, 32:16, 33:32, 70:38, 74:15)",
      "d": "« » refers to a strong hope or desire arising in the heart for something (M. L). To have a strong hope.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ مَہَّدۡتُّ لَہٗ  تَمۡہِیۡدًا ثُمَّ  یَطۡمَعُ اَنۡ اَزِیۡدَ»\nTranslation: And I have smoothed everything for him. Yet he desires that I should give more."
    },
    {
      "id": 2001,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "To Covet / Have Greed",
      "hw": "طمع",
      "s": "« » is the term used when greed or desire for something becomes intense. (5 verses: 2:96, 4:129, 9:128, 12:103, 16:37)",
      "d": "« » is when greed or desire for something intensifies (M. L). Be it for one's own benefit or for the benefit of another. (Muf) Greed.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ تَحۡرِصۡ عَلٰی ہُدٰىہِمۡ فَاِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا یَہۡدِیۡ مَنۡ یُّضِلُّ»\nTranslation: (O Prophet) if you are greedy for their guidance, then indeed Allah does not guide those whom He lets go astray."
    }
  ],
  "434": [
    {
      "id": 2003,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Traverse (a Path)",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "The word « » is specifically used for crossing a path, especially one involving water. The word « » is general and is used for concluding matters and crossing tracts of land (fields, agricultural land, etc.). (1 verse: 4:43)",
      "d": "«عَبَرَ» «عَبْرُ النَّھْر» «عَبَرَ الْعَیْن» «اَلْعَبَرَات»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا»\nTranslation: And (do not approach prayer while) in a state of major impurity, except those who are travelers on the road (and can perform dry ablution if water is unavailable)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2004,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To Traverse (a Path)",
      "hw": "راستہ",
      "s": "The basic meaning of « » is to cut and separate. (12 verses: 2:27, 3:127, 5:38, 6:45, 7:72, 8:7, 9:121, 13:25, 22:15, 29:29, 59:5, 69:46)",
      "d": "«قَطَعَ» «قَطَعَ النَّھْر» «قَطَعَ السَّبِیْل» «قَطَعَ الْوَادِی» «قَطَعَ الْاَمْر» «عَبَرَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ لَا یَقۡطَعُوۡنَ وَادِیًا اِلَّا کُتِبَ لَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And they do not traverse a valley except it is written down for them.\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n«مَا کُنۡتُ قَاطِعَۃً  اَمۡرًا حَتّٰی تَشۡہَدُوۡنِ»\nTranslation: I will not decide any matter until you are present."
    }
  ],
  "435": [
    {
      "id": 2005,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Appear / Become Visible",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means to become visible in such a way that the eyes can see it. This word is general. (27 verses: 2:85, 6:120, 6:151, 7:33, 9:8, 9:33, 9:48, 13:33, 18:20, 18:22, 18:97, 24:31, 30:7, 30:18, 30:41, 31:20, 34:18, 40:26, 40:29, 43:33, 48:28, 57:3, 57:13, 61:9, 61:14, 66:3, 72:26)",
      "d": "« » means the outer part of anything that can be seen by the eyes. Its opposite is « », meaning the inner part of anything that cannot be seen by the eyes. (Muf) And « » means for something to become apparent, to manifest, to come forward, and to prevail.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ظَہَرَ الۡفَسَادُ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ اَیۡدِی  النَّاسِ»\nTranslation: Corruption has appeared on land and sea because of what the hands of people have earned.\nThen this word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example, the Divine command states:\n«قُلۡ  اِنَّمَا حَرَّمَ رَبِّیَ الۡفَوَاحِشَ مَا ظَہَرَ  مِنۡہَا وَ  مَا بَطَنَ»\nTranslation: Say, 'My Lord has only forbidden immoralities—whether they are open or secret.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2006,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Appear / Proclaim",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means to say something openly or to do something in such a way that others become aware of it. (14 verses: 2:55, 4:148, 4:153, 6:3, 6:47, 7:205, 13:10, 16:75, 17:110, 20:7, 21:110, 49:2, 67:13, 87:7)",
      "d": "« » means to do something in such a way that others know about it. Its opposite is « », meaning to conceal. (Muf)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ قُلۡتُمۡ یٰمُوۡسٰی لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی نَرَی اللّٰہَ جَہۡرَۃً»\nTranslation: And (O Jews) when you said, 'O Moses! We will not believe you until we see Allah openly.'\nHowever, this word is generally used for making the voice audible and for proclamation. (M. L) A loud prayer (Jahri) is one where the Imam recites aloud, i.e., the Fajr, Maghrib, and Isha prayers. A silent prayer (Sirri) is one where the Imam recites in a low voice that others cannot hear. « » means to say something so that others hear it. (M. Q)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَا یُحِبُّ اللّٰہُ  الۡجَہۡرَ  بِالسُّوۡٓءِ مِنَ الۡقَوۡلِ اِلَّا مَنۡ ظُلِمَ»\nTranslation: Allah does not like the public proclamation of evil except by one who has been wronged."
    },
    {
      "id": 2007,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means something becoming apparent without intention, which one tries to hide (9 verses: 3:118-6:28-7:22-12:35-20:121-39:47-39:48-45:33-60:4)",
      "d": "« » means to become manifestly apparent, and in this, there is no involvement of anyone's intention or will. (Faqih, p. 237)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«بَلۡ بَدَا لَہُمۡ مَّا کَانُوۡا یُخۡفُوۡنَ مِنۡ  قَبۡلُ»\nTranslation: Rather, what they used to conceal before has become apparent.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«بَدَتۡ لَہُمَا سَوۡاٰتُہُمَا وَ طَفِقَا یَخۡصِفٰنِ عَلَیۡہِمَا مِنۡ وَّرَقِ الۡجَنَّۃِ»\nTranslation: Their private parts became apparent to them, and they began to cover themselves with leaves from Paradise.\nThen this word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«ثُمَّ بَدَا لَہُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مَا رَاَوُا الۡاٰیٰتِ لَیَسۡجُنُنَّہٗ حَتّٰی حِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: Then after seeing the signs, it became clear to them that they should imprison him for a while."
    },
    {
      "id": 2008,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means the truth becoming apparent in the midst of statements (2 verses: 5:107-18:21)",
      "d": "« » means to slip and fall (intransitive). And « » is used in the sense of becoming apparent when someone tries to hide something by lying, but accidentally a truth slips out, revealing the reality.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ عُثِرَ عَلٰۤی اَنَّہُمَا اسۡتَحَقَّاۤ اِثۡمًا»\nTranslation: Then if it is found that both have earned sin."
    },
    {
      "id": 2009,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means something becoming separate and apparent from another, and clear.\n« » is a statement from which meanings become apparent (20 verses: 2:109-2:187-2:256-2:259-3:187-4:115-6:55-8:6-9:43-9:113-9:114-14:45-16:44-16:64-29:38-34:14-37:117-41:53-47:25-47:32)",
      "d": "« » means something becoming separate and apparent from another, and clear (transitive). Thus, its meaning encompasses three concepts: (1) separation (i.e., distinction), (2) distance, (3) clarity (i.e., bright, apparent, and clear). And « » is also used in these meanings.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ»\nTranslation: Guidance has become distinct from error.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ لِتَسۡتَبِیۡنَ سَبِیۡلُ  الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And so that the path of the criminals becomes apparent."
    },
    {
      "id": 2010,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means something that was hidden due to pressure becomes apparent after the pressure is lifted (1 verse: 12:51)",
      "d": "« » when something remains hidden due to some pressure and becomes apparent after the pressure is lifted (intransitive), then the word « » is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَتِ امۡرَاَتُ الۡعَزِیۡزِ الۡئٰنَ حَصۡحَصَ الۡحَقُّ ۫ اَنَا رَاوَدۡتُّہٗ عَنۡ  نَّفۡسِہٖ»\nTranslation: The wife of the Aziz said, \"Now the truth has become clear. I had indeed tempted him.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 2012,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to become apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means something becoming apparent by stretching out or rising (1 verse: 7:163)",
      "d": "«شَرَعَ» «شَرَعَ الْبَعِیْرُ عُنُقَہٗ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَاۡتِیۡہِمۡ حِیۡتَانُہُمۡ یَوۡمَ سَبۡتِہِمۡ شُرَّعًا»\nTranslation: When their fish came to them openly on the day of their Sabbath."
    },
    {
      "id": 2013,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to make apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means to make apparent (2 verses: 66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "« » means to make apparent, very apparent, extremely clear.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«عٰلِمُ الۡغَیۡبِ فَلَا یُظۡہِرُ عَلٰۤی غَیۡبِہٖۤ اَحَدًا»\nTranslation: The Knower of the unseen, He does not reveal to anyone His unseen."
    },
    {
      "id": 2014,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "to make apparent",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means to make apparent (16 verses: 2:33-2:271-2:284-3:29-3:154-4:149-5:99-5:101-6:91-7:20-12:77-24:29-24:31-28:10-33:37-33:54)",
      "d": "« » means to make apparent.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَعۡلَمُ مَا تُبۡدُوۡنَ وَ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَکۡتُمُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And I know what you reveal and what you conceal."
    },
    {
      "id": 2015,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Manifest",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means to manifest, to inform, to make aware (1 verse: 18:21)",
      "d": "« » means to manifest, to inform, to make aware.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ اَعۡثَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ لِیَعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّ وَعۡدَ اللّٰہِ حَقٌّ»\nTranslation: And thus We made it manifest to them so that they might know that the promise of Allah is true."
    },
    {
      "id": 2016,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Manifest",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means to manifest (14 verses: 2:55-4:148-4:153-6:3-6:47-7:205-13:10-16:75-17:110-20:7-21:110-49:2-67:13-87:7)",
      "d": "« » means to manifest.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَسِرُّوۡا  قَوۡلَکُمۡ  اَوِ اجۡہَرُوۡا بِہٖ ؕ اِنَّہٗ  عَلِیۡمٌۢ  بِذَاتِ الصُّدُوۡرِ»\nTranslation: Whether you conceal your speech or manifest it, indeed, He is Knowing of that within the breasts."
    },
    {
      "id": 2017,
      "a": "ظ",
      "h": "To Manifest",
      "hw": "ظاہر",
      "s": "« » means to manifest (16 verses: 2:77-2:274-11:5-13:22-14:31-14:38-16:19-16:23-27:25-27:74-28:69-35:29-36:76-60:1-64:4-71:9)",
      "d": "« » means to manifest. Its opposite is « ». It is used for the expression of meanings (i.e., making something known), rarely for bodies (see Lisān al-ʿArab), and does not necessarily require a loud voice (see Fatḥ al-Bārī).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ  مَا تُسِرُّوۡنَ وَ مَا  تُعۡلِنُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And Allah knows what you conceal and what you manifest.\nWords for 'manifest' include « », « », and « ». Details have passed earlier."
    }
  ],
  "436": [
    {
      "id": 2019,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "to become incapable",
      "hw": "عاجز",
      "s": "« » to be unable to continue or redo work due to exhaustion (2 verses: 46:33-50:15)",
      "d": "«عَیَّ» «دَاءٌ عِیَاءٌ» «عَیَاءُ» «عَجْز» «اَفَعَیِیۡنَا بِالۡخَلۡقِ الۡاَوَّلِ ؕ بَلۡ ہُمۡ فِیۡ لَبۡسٍ مِّنۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ»"
    }
  ],
  "437": [
    {
      "id": 2023,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "To Show Humility",
      "hw": "عاجزی",
      "s": "« » means to be obedient and submissive to someone (1 verse: 26:4)",
      "d": "«خَضَعَ» «خُضُوْع» «خَاضِع» «رَجُلٌ خَضِیْعٌ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ نَّشَاۡ نُنَزِّلۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  اٰیَۃً فَظَلَّتۡ اَعۡنَاقُہُمۡ  لَہَا خٰضِعِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: If We will, We could send down upon them a sign from the heaven, and their necks would remain humbled to it."
    }
  ],
  "438": [
    {
      "id": 2026,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "scholar",
      "hw": "عالم",
      "s": "« » the literate and people of the pen (4 verses: 5:44-5:63-9:31-9:34)",
      "d": "«اَحْبَار» «حِبْر» «حَبْر» «حِبْر» «حِبْر» «حِبْر» «حَبْر» «اَحْبَار» «اَحْبَار» «اِتَّخَذُوۡۤا اَحۡبَارَہُمۡ وَ رُہۡبَانَہُمۡ اَرۡبَابًا مِّنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2027,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Scholar",
      "hw": "عالم",
      "s": "« » refers to Christian priests and teachers (1 verse: 5:82)",
      "d": "«قَسَّی الشَّیْ» «قَسِیْسَۃٌ» «قِسِّیْسِیْن» «قَسُّ» «قَسُّ» «اُسْقُف» «شَمَّاس»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَتَجِدَنَّ  اَقۡرَبَہُمۡ مَّوَدَّۃً  لِّلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا الَّذِیۡنَ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا نَصٰرٰی ؕ ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّ مِنۡہِمۡ قِسِّیۡسِیۡنَ وَ رُہۡبَانًا»\nTranslation: And you will find the nearest in love to those who believe those who say, 'We are Christians.' That is because among them are priests and monks.\nNote: « » is a senior priest, a Christian religious leader. « » is a servant of the church whose rank is lower than a priest."
    }
  ],
  "439": [
    {
