      "h": "places of worship",
      "hw": "عبادت",
      "s": "« » places of worship for monks (priests) (1 verse: 22:40)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». It means monastery, places of worship for monks."
    },
    {
      "id": 2029,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "places of worship",
      "hw": "عبادت",
      "s": "« » place of worship for Christians (1 verse: 22:40)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». It means the place of worship for Christians."
    },
    {
      "id": 2030,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "places of worship",
      "hw": "عبادت",
      "s": "« » place of worship for Jews (1 verse: 22:40)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». It means places of worship for Jews. The places of worship for Jews are also called « », plural of « » (vol. 275), but the Quran uses « » instead of « » for Jewish places of worship, which is the common term for worship."
    },
    {
      "id": 2031,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "places of worship",
      "hw": "عبادت",
      "s": "« » places of worship for Muslims (6 verses: 2:114-2:187-9:17-9:18-22:40-72:18)",
      "d": "«مَسَاجِد» «مَسْجِد» «وَ لَوۡ لَا دَفۡعُ اللّٰہِ النَّاسَ بَعۡضَہُمۡ بِبَعۡضٍ لَّہُدِّمَتۡ صَوَامِعُ وَ بِیَعٌ وَّ صَلَوٰتٌ وَّ مَسٰجِدُ یُذۡکَرُ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُ اللّٰہِ کَثِیۡرًا»"
    }
  ],
  "440": [
    {
      "id": 2032,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "« » means pain, punishment, recompense for evil deeds. It is general (306 verses: 2:7-2:10-2:49-2:85-2:86-2:90-2:96-2:104-2:114-2:126-2:162-2:165-2:166-2:174-2:175-2:178-2:201-3:4-3:16-3:21-3:56-3:77-3:88-3:91-3:105-3:106-3:176-3:177-3:178-3:181-3:188-3:191-4:14-4:18-4:25-4:37-4:56-4:93-4:102-4:138-4:147-4:151-4:161-4:173-5:33-5:36-5:37-5:41-5:73-5:80-5:94-5:115-6:15-6:30-6:40-6:47-6:49-6:65-6:70-6:93-6:124-6:157-7:38-7:39-7:59-7:73-7:141-7:156-7:164-7:165-7:167-8:14-8:32-8:35-8:50-8:68-9:3-9:34-9:39-9:52-9:61-9:68-9:74-9:79-9:90-9:101-10:4-10:15-10:50-10:52-10:54-10:70-10:88-10:97-10:98-11:3-11:8-11:20-11:26-11:39-11:48-11:58-11:64-11:76-11:84-11:93-11:103-12:25-12:107-13:34-14:2-14:6-14:7-14:17-14:21-14:22-14:44-15:50-16:26-16:45-16:63-16:85-16:88-16:94-16:104-16:106-16:113-16:117-17:10-17:57-17:58-18:55-18:58-18:87-19:45-19:75-19:79-20:48-20:61-20:71-20:127-20:134-21:46-22:2-22:4-22:9-22:18-22:22-22:25-22:47-22:55-22:57-23:64-23:76-23:77-24:2-24:8-24:11-24:14-24:19-24:23-24:63-25:19-25:37-25:42-25:65-25:69-26:135-26:156-26:158-26:189-26:201-26:204-27:5-27:21-28:64-29:10-29:23-29:29-29:53-29:54-29:55-30:16-31:6-31:7-31:21-31:24-32:14-32:20-32:21-33:8-33:30-33:57-33:68-34:5-34:8-34:12-34:14-34:33-34:38-34:42-34:46-35:7-35:10-35:36-36:18-37:9-37:33-37:38-37:176-38:8-38:26-38:41-38:61-39:13-39:19-39:24-39:25-39:26-39:40-39:47-39:54-39:55-39:58-39:71-40:7-40:45-40:46-40:49-41:16-41:17-41:27-41:50-42:16-42:21-42:26-42:42-42:44-42:45-43:39-43:48-43:50-43:65-43:74-44:11-44:12-44:15-44:30-44:48-44:56-45:8-45:9-45:10-45:11-46:20-46:21-46:24-46:31-46:34-48:16-48:17-48:25-50:26-51:37-52:7-52:18-52:27-52:47-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:30-54:37-54:38-54:39-57:13-57:20-58:4-58:5-58:15-58:16-59:3-59:15-61:10-64:5-65:8-65:10-67:5-67:6-67:28-68:33-70:1-70:11-70:27-70:28-71:1-72:17-73:13-76:31-78:30-78:40-84:24-85:10-88:24-89:13-89:25)",
      "d": "«عَذَبَ الرَّجُل» «عَاذِبٌ» «عَذُوْبٌ» «عَذَاب» «تَعْذِیب»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ ۢ  ۬ ۙ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَکۡذِبُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And they will have a painful punishment because they used to deny."
    },
    {
      "id": 2033,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "« » means the consequence of a bad deed and its necessary result (20 verses: 2:196-2:211-3:11-5:2-5:98-6:165-7:167-8:13-8:25-8:48-8:52-13:6-13:32-38:14-40:3-40:5-40:22-41:43-59:4-59:7)",
      "d": "« » means the back part of the foot or the heel. And « » means the end result of everything. And « » means he followed behind him or pursued him (Mufradāt). The terms « », « », and « » are applied to the recompense for evil human deeds and the necessary outcome, i.e., the end result, of that evil deed.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ جٰدَلُوۡا بِالۡبَاطِلِ لِیُدۡحِضُوۡا بِہِ الۡحَقَّ فَاَخَذۡتُہُمۡ ۟ فَکَیۡفَ کَانَ عِقَابِ»\nTranslation: And they argued by falsehood to refute the truth thereby. So I seized them. Then how was My punishment?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2034,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "« » is a punishment that involves both hardship and tightness (26 verses: 2:177-2:214-4:84-6:42-6:43-6:147-6:148-7:4-7:5-7:94-7:97-7:98-12:110-16:81-17:5-18:2-21:12-21:80-27:33-33:18-40:29-40:84-40:85-48:16-57:25-59:14)",
      "d": "« » or « » carries the meaning of tightness and hardship in its connotations (Lisan al-ʿArab). In the Quran, this word has been used in three meanings: war, punishment, and calamity. And in all three, the concept of tightness and hardship is present. If it is used in the meaning of punishment or chastisement, it will come in the meaning of severe punishment.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَوۡلَاۤ  اِذۡ جَآءَہُمۡ بَاۡسُنَا تَضَرَّعُوۡا»\nTranslation: Then why did they not supplicate when Our punishment came to them?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2035,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "« » is an unpleasant, severe, and unexpected punishment (5 verses: 22:44-34:45-35:26-42:47-67:18)",
      "d": "«نُکْر» «مُنْکَر» «نَكُرَ الأَمْرُ» «نَکِیْر»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ کُذِّبَ مُوۡسٰی فَاَمۡلَیۡتُ لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ ثُمَّ  اَخَذۡتُہُمۡ ۚ فَکَیۡفَ کَانَ نَکِیۡرِ»\nTranslation: And Moses was denied. Then I granted respite to the disbelievers, then I seized them. And how was My punishment?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2036,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment; Chastisement",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "« » is an exemplary punishment (3 verses: 2:66-5:38-79:25)",
      "d": "« » means an iron collar, a fetter (Maqayīs al-Kalim), a muzzle (i.e., a rope tied in a collar), and anything by which a person is bound and forced to move. Its plural is « ». And « » means to shackle someone and to inflict an exemplary punishment on someone. And « » means an exemplary punishment by looking at which others take a lesson (Mufradāt).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ السَّارِقُ وَ السَّارِقَۃُ فَاقۡطَعُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیَہُمَا جَزَآءًۢ بِمَا کَسَبَا نَکَالًا مِّنَ  اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: Cut off the hands of the male and female thief as a recompense for what they earned, [as] an exemplary punishment from Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2037,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment. Penalty.",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Wabal» Severe and continuous punishment (4 verses: 5:95-59:15-64:5-65:9)",
      "d": "«Wabl» in its meaning implies heaviness (i.e., burden) and severity is found. «Al-wabalu» and «al-wabilu» refer to such rain which is thick and heavy in droplets (mufradat) and «wablu bil-asaa» means struck with a staff and repeatedly struck. And «wabil» refers to the stick for washing clothes (m. q.) and «wabal» is such a penalty or recompense which is both severe and abundant.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَلَمۡ  یَاۡتِکُمۡ نَبَؤُا  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلُ ۫ فَذَاقُوۡا وَبَالَ  اَمۡرِہِمۡ وَ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ  اَلِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: Have you not received news of those who disbelieved before? They tasted the consequence of their deeds, and there will be a painful punishment for them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2038,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Punishment. Penalty.",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Mathulat» Such a memorable punishment that its image comes to mind upon remembrance (1 verse: 13:6)",
      "d": "«Mathal» in its meaning implies two things: (1) comparing a thing with its counterpart, (2) a model according to which something is made. And «al-muthla» means establishing such an example of a memorable punishment that others may desist from committing crimes (m. l), or it means cutting off the nose, ears, or other limbs after killing (m. q). Its plural is «mathulat». And «mathula» means the image of a thing coming to mind. And «mathul» means such a punishment that upon remembering it, its image comes to mind. Example of a memorable punishment.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ یَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡنَکَ بِالسَّیِّئَۃِ قَبۡلَ الۡحَسَنَۃِ وَ قَدۡ خَلَتۡ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمُ الۡمَثُلٰتُ»\nTranslation: And they hasten you towards evil instead of good, while exemplary punishments have already passed before them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2039,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "To punish",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "« » punishment from Allah for sin (45 verses: 2:284-3:56-3:128-3:129-4:173-5:18-5:40-5:115-5:118-7:164-8:33-8:34-9:14-9:26-9:39-9:55-9:66-9:74-9:85-9:101-9:106-17:15-17:54-17:58-18:86-18:87-20:47-26:138-26:213-27:21-29:21-33:24-33:73-34:35-37:59-48:6-48:14-48:16-48:17-48:25-58:8-59:3-65:8-88:24-89:25)",
      "d": "« » punishment from Allah for sin.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنَّ کَتَبَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡجَلَآءَ لَعَذَّبَہُمۡ فِی الدُّنۡیَا ؕ وَ لَہُمۡ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ عَذَابُ النَّارِ»\nTranslation: And if Allah had not decreed for them exile, He would have punished them in this world. And for them in the Hereafter is the punishment of the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 2040,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "To punish",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "« » punishment from Allah for sin (1 verse: 4:84)",
      "d": "« » punishment from Allah for sin.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ اَشَدُّ بَاۡسًا وَّ اَشَدُّ تَنۡکِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And Allah is Severe in penalty and Severe in retribution."
    },
    {
      "id": 2041,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Different types of punishment",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Husban» Punishment of fire or hail that burns vegetation to ashes (3 verses: 6:96-18:40-55:5)",
      "d": "«Husban» means counting, reckoning. And it means a small arrow (munjad). According to Imam Raghib, it refers to anything that is accounted for and then recompensed accordingly. Some say it means fire and punishment (mufradat). According to Ibn Faris, it also means throwing small arrows and hail (m. l). The following Quranic verse indicates its meaning as a punishment that burns vegetation to ashes, whether it be fire or hail.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  فَتُصۡبِحَ  صَعِیۡدًا  زَلَقًا»\nTranslation: And He will send upon it a hailstorm from the sky, and it will become a bare plain."
    },
    {
      "id": 2042,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Different types of punishment",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Hasib» Violent and fierce wind containing stones (4 verses: 17:68-29:40-54:34-67:17)",
      "d": "«Hasaba al-makaan» means to pave a floor with pebbles. And «ahsaba al-farsu» means the horse ran so much that pebbles flew into the air from its hooves (m. q). «Ardhun hasiyatun» means pebbly ground, and the valley «mu-hassab» is the valley from which pilgrims pick up pebbles. And «hasib» means such a violent and fierce wind that carries pebbles and stones into the air, and also a cloud that showers hail (munjad. m. q).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَمۡ اَمِنۡتُمۡ مَّنۡ فِی السَّمَآءِ  اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا»\nTranslation: Do you feel secure from Him who is in the heaven that He will send upon you a wind laden with stones?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2044,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Different types of punishment",
      "hw": "عذاب",
      "s": "«Rijz» Disturbing punishment (7 verses: 2:59-7:134-7:135-7:162-29:34-34:5-45:11)",
      "d": "«Rijz» fundamentally implies agitation, i.e., restlessness and commotion (m. l). Rijzi poetry refers to poems recited during war to incite agitation (i.e., intensity, severity, force, and dominance). And «rijz» is such a punishment that disturbs and agitates the heart.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا رِجۡزًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡسُقُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: So We sent down upon those who did wrong a punishment from the heaven because they were defiantly disobedient."
    }
  ],
  "442": [
    {
      "id": 2050,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "« » is the intellect that safeguards from harm (3 verses: 6:138-25:22-25:53)",
      "d": "«حِجْر» «حَجَرَ» «عَقْل» «حِجْر» «حِجْر» «ذِیْ حِجْر»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ہَلۡ فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ قَسَمٌ  لِّذِیۡ حِجۡرٍ»\nTranslation: Is not this (the mentioned four things) worthy of being sworn by by those of intellect?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2051,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "« » is the intellect that safeguards from harm and devises the choice of beneficial things (49 verses: 2:44-2:73-2:75-2:76-2:164-2:170-2:171-2:242-3:65-3:118-5:58-5:103-6:32-6:151-7:169-8:22-10:16-10:42-10:100-11:51-12:2-12:109-13:4-16:12-16:67-21:10-21:67-22:46-23:80-24:61-25:44-26:28-28:60-29:35-29:43-29:63-30:24-30:28-36:62-36:68-37:138-39:43-40:67-43:3-45:5-49:4-57:17-59:14-67:10)",
      "d": "« » means to possess understanding and discernment; to be capable of realizing error (Manjad). And « » also means to restrain and prohibit. And « » is the fetter with which a camel's foot is tied (Muf). Thus, the function of intellect is to distinguish between benefit and harm; to adopt measures to avoid harmful things (Faq. L. 65); and to always be prepared for beneficial things and for accepting knowledge. Then, to reflect (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا  لَوۡ  کُنَّا نَسۡمَعُ  اَوۡ نَعۡقِلُ مَا کُنَّا فِیۡۤ   اَصۡحٰبِ السَّعِیۡرِ»\nTranslation: And they will say, 'If we had only listened or used our intellect, we would not have been among the companions of the Blaze.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2052,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "« » is the intellect that maintains control over one's nature and does not allow one to become enraged (16 verses: 2:225-2:235-2:263-3:155-4:12-5:101-9:114-11:75-11:87-17:44-22:59-33:51-35:41-37:101-52:32-64:17)",
      "d": "« » means to forgive; to be forbearing. And « » means one of a forbearing temperament; forbearing. And « » means gravity; forbearance; i.e., to maintain such control over one's nature that one does not flare up even in a situation of anger. Its plural is « » (Muf Manjad). Thus, « » is that intellect which maintains control over one's nature and does not allow it to become enraged, i.e., to flare up.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَمۡ  تَاۡمُرُہُمۡ  اَحۡلَامُہُمۡ  بِہٰذَاۤ   اَمۡ  ہُمۡ قَوۡمٌ  طَاغُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Do their intellects command them to this, or are they a transgressing people?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2053,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«اُولِی الْاَلْبَاب»",
      "d": "«اَلْبَاب» «لُبّ» «لُبّ» «لَبِیْب» «اُولِی الْاَلْبَاب»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنَّ فِیۡ  ذٰلِکَ لَذِکۡرٰی لِاُولِی الۡاَلۡبَابِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, in these examples is a reminder for those of understanding."
    },
    {
      "id": 2054,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«اُولِی الْاَبْصَار»",
      "d": "«بَصُرَ» «اُولِی الْاَبْصَار»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاعۡتَبِرُوۡا یٰۤاُولِی الۡاَبۡصَارِ»\nTranslation: O you who have vision! Take heed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2055,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Intellect. Intelligent person.",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«اُولِی النُّھٰی»",
      "d": "«نُھٰی» «نَھُوَ یَنْھُوْا» «نُھٰی» «نُھْیَہ» «اُولِی النُّھٰی»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِنَّ  فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ لَاٰیٰتٍ  لِّاُولِی  النُّہٰی»\nTranslation: Indeed, in that are signs for those of profound insight."
    }
  ],
  "443": [
    {
      "id": 2058,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman",
      "hw": "عورت",
      "s": "« » refers to every living female. When the mention is of the genus human being, this word will be used for woman (20 verses: 2:178-3:36-3:195-4:11-4:124-4:176-6:143-6:144-13:8-16:58-16:97-35:11-40:40-41:47-49:13-53:21-53:27-53:45-75:39-92:3)",
      "d": "« » means female (as opposed to male or masculine). This word is used for the female of all living beings. And similarly, when the genus human being is mentioned, it refers to woman.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«کُتِبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡقِصۡاصُ فِی الۡقَتۡلٰی ؕ اَلۡحُرُّ بِالۡحُرِّ وَ الۡعَبۡدُ بِالۡعَبۡدِ وَ الۡاُنۡثٰی بِالۡاُنۡثٰی»\nTranslation: Retribution is prescribed for you in the case of murder: the free for the free, the slave for the slave, and the woman for the woman."
    }
  ],
  "444": [
    {
      "id": 2061,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Covenant. Promise. Agreement",
      "hw": "عہد",
      "s": "« » if a promise is related to an evil outcome, it is called a threat; the time or place of the promise is called 'appointed time'. This is generally unilateral (6 verses: 14:14-20:113-50:14-50:20-50:28-50:45)",
      "d": "« » is a promise that is based on evil and is related to a bad outcome. A threat; a warning. (M. L.)\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَذَکِّرۡ بِالۡقُرۡاٰنِ مَنۡ یَّخَافُ وَعِیۡدِ»\nTranslation: So remind by the Quran whoever fears My threat.\n«مَوْعِدَۃ : مَوْعِدًا» «وَعَدَ یَعِدُ» «وَعَدَ یَعِدُ وَعْدًا وَعِدَۃً وَ مَوْعِدًا وَ مَوْعِدَۃً»\n« »: It is an adverbial noun. In a temporal sense, its meaning is the time of the promise; in a locative sense, the place of the promise.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ لَوۡ  تَوَاعَدۡتُمۡ  لَاخۡتَلَفۡتُمۡ  فِی الۡمِیۡعٰدِ»\nTranslation: And if you had appointed a time, you would have differed in the appointed time.\nAt another place, the command of Allah Most High is:\n«رَبَّنَاۤ اِنَّکَ جَامِعُ النَّاسِ لِیَوۡمٍ لَّا رَیۡبَ فِیۡہِ ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا یُخۡلِفُ الۡمِیۡعَادَ»\nTranslation: Our Lord, indeed You will gather the people for a Day about which there is no doubt; indeed, Allah does not fail in His promise."
    },
    {
      "id": 2063,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Covenant. Promise. Agreement",
      "hw": "عہد",
      "s": "« » is essentially a type of covenant; making a covenant of protection (2 verses: 9:8-9:10)",
      "d": "« » is essentially a type of covenant, i.e., a covenant of fulfillment. It also means security; the responsibility of protection; making a covenant to give someone refuge. And 'Ahl al-Dhimmah' are those people who have been given security in return for jizya.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اِنۡ  یَّظۡہَرُوۡا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡا فِیۡکُمۡ  اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً»\nTranslation: And if they overcome you, they will not respect any tie of kinship or any covenant in you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2064,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Covenant. Promise. Agreement",
      "hw": "عہد",
      "s": "« » is a covenant that is burdensome or difficult due to its binding nature. Whether it is a custom/tradition or a religious law (3 verses: 2:286-3:81-7:157)",
      "d": "« » means to tie a knot in something; and to forcibly restrain it (M. L.). « » means a tied knot; a heavy burden; the bonds of custom/tradition; the limits and restrictions of religious law; a great responsibility. Thus, this word contains the concepts of covenant, burden, and confinement.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ یَضَعُ عَنۡہُمۡ اِصۡرَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And he (the Prophet) removes from them their burden (i.e., the burdensome customs).\nAt another place, the command of Allah Most High is:\n«رَبَّنَا وَ لَا  تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡنَاۤ  اِصۡرًا کَمَا حَمَلۡتَہٗ عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِنَا»\nTranslation: Our Lord, do not impose upon us a burden (i.e., the strictures and restrictions of the law) like that which You imposed on those before us."
    },
    {
      "id": 2065,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Covenant. Promise. Agreement.",
      "hw": "عہد",
      "s": "« » refers to a covenant that has been made stronger through writing or repetition (23 verses: 2:27-2:63-2:83-2:84-2:93-3:81-3:187-4:21-4:90-4:92-4:154-4:155-5:7-5:12-5:13-5:14-5:70-7:169-8:72-13:20-13:25-33:7-57:8)",
      "d": "« » refers to the rope or chain with which something is tied and bound. And « » is that covenant or pact or agreement which has been confirmed (i.e., made strong and firm) or has been put in writing, binding the parties to the agreement.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ یَصِلُوۡنَ اِلٰی قَوۡمٍۭ بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ مِّیۡثَاقٌ»\nTranslation: But those who have an alliance with a people between whom and you there is a treaty (of peace)."
    }
  ],
  "445": [
    {
      "id": 2067,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Cave",
      "hw": "غار",
      "s": "« » is a place in mountains where a person can take refuge (2 verses: 9:40-9:57)",
      "d": "«غَوْر» «غَارَ الرَّجُل» «غَارَ الْمَاءُ» «غَوْر» «غَار»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ ہُمَا فِی الۡغَارِ اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ لِصَاحِبِہٖ لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا»\nTranslation: When the two (the Prophet ﷺ and Abu Bakr) were in the cave, when the Prophet ﷺ said to his companion, \"Do not grieve; indeed Allah is with us.\"\n«مَغَار ، غَوْر» «مَغَارَات»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَوۡ یَجِدُوۡنَ مَلۡجَاً اَوۡ مَغٰرٰتٍ اَوۡ مُدَّخَلًا لَّوَلَّوۡا اِلَیۡہِ وَ ہُمۡ یَجۡمَحُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: If the hypocrites find a place of refuge (like a fortress) or caves or any hiding places, they will turn towards them, rushing headlong."
    },
    {
      "id": 2068,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Cave",
      "hw": "غار",
      "s": "«Kahf» Such a cave or hollow which is in a mountain and larger than a cave (6 verses: 18:9-18:10-18:11-18:16-18:17-18:25)",
      "d": "«Khauf» is the plural of «kahf». And «kahf» is more specific than a cave. «Kahf» refers to such a cave or hollow which is in a mountain and large (m. l). If it is small, it is called a cave (ghar) (m. q).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَمۡ حَسِبۡتَ اَنَّ  اَصۡحٰبَ الۡکَہۡفِ وَ الرَّقِیۡمِ ۙ کَانُوۡا  مِنۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا  عَجَبًا»\nTranslation: Do you think that the companions of the cave and the scripture were wonders among Our signs?"
    }
  ],
  "446": [
    {
      "id": 2070,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be heedless. To do.",
      "hw": "غافل",
      "s": "« » means to do another work instead of the original one due to forgetfulness or to add/subtract from it. It is not related to non-intentional acts (2 verses: 51:11-107:5)",
      "d": "« » means to forget. The heart turning to something else. And « » means gentleness. Calmness (manjad). « » essentially refers to the act that occurs due to heedlessness. If there is no intention involved in it, it is excusable. Like a madman swearing. And if it is done with intention, it is punishable and subject to accountability. (muf) Sajdah al-Sahw is a well-known term, i.e., the prostration performed as compensation for deficiencies in prayer acts due to the attention turning elsewhere. And this word does not pertain to the actions of a non-intentional person. (faql 78)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَوَیۡلٌ لِّلۡمُصَلِّیۡنَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ عَنۡ صَلَاتِہِمۡ سَاہُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: So woe to those who pray, [but] who are heedless of their prayer."
    }
  ],
  "447": [
    {
      "id": 2073,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To overcome. To be. To do.",
      "hw": "غالب",
      "s": "« » means to appear with strength, to become manifest, to be an emerging force (27 verses: 2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26)",
      "d": "In the meanings of « », two things are fundamental: (1) to become apparent, to come forward, to be manifest. (2) strength. Then this word is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ظَہَرَ الۡفَسَادُ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ»\nTranslation: Corruption has appeared in the land and sea.\nAt another instance, the divine declaration is:\n«حَتّٰی جَآءَ الۡحَقُّ وَ ظَہَرَ اَمۡرُ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: Until truth came and the command of Allah became dominant.\nThus, « » means the appearance of something with strength and power.\nAnd for \"to make dominant\", « » is used.\nFor example: The divine declaration states:\n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَرۡسَلَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ بِالۡہُدٰی وَ دِیۡنِ الۡحَقِّ لِیُظۡہِرَہٗ عَلَی الدِّیۡنِ کُلِّہٖ»\nTranslation: It is He who has sent His Messenger with guidance and the religion of truth to make it dominant over all religions."
    },
    {
      "id": 2074,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To overcome. To be. To do.",
      "hw": "غالب",
      "s": "« » means to be powerful, dominant, and strong (1 verse: 38:23)",
      "d": "The opposite of « » is « », meaning to be subjugated and defeated. « » means to be in a position of authority, i.e., independent. Just as in today's rural setting, the landowner class is in authority (powerful) and the lowly or laborers are under them and weak. This is the correct meaning of « » (Mighty) and « » (Humble).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَقَالَ اَکۡفِلۡنِیۡہَا وَ عَزَّنِیۡ فِی الۡخِطَابِ»\nTranslation: And he said, \"Give me charge of her\" and he dominated me in conversation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2075,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To overcome. To be. To do.",
      "hw": "غالب",
      "s": "« » means to gain superiority (ghalabah) with force and might (27 verses: 2:249-3:12-3:160-4:74-5:23-5:56-7:113-7:119-8:36-8:48-8:65-8:66-12:21-18:21-21:44-23:106-26:40-26:41-26:44-28:35-30:2-30:3-37:116-37:173-41:26-54:10-58:21)",
      "d": "In « », the meanings of force, coercion, and intensity are found (m. l), i.e., to gain superiority and ascendancy by force. To conquer. And the one who is defeated is one who is forced by force and power. Defeated.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کَمۡ مِّنۡ فِئَۃٍ قَلِیۡلَۃٍ غَلَبَتۡ فِئَۃً کَثِیۡرَۃًۢ بِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: How many a small group has overcome a large group by permission of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2076,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To overcome. To be. To do.",
      "hw": "غالب",
      "s": "« » means to desire to be elevated, to seek superiority and ascendancy (1 verse: 20:64)",
      "d": "«عَلٰی یَعْلو» «اِستعْلٰی» «تَعِلّیْ» «تَعَلّی» «استعلی» «عَلَا یَعْلُوْا» «عَلِیَ یَعْلٰی»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَجۡمِعُوۡا کَیۡدَکُمۡ ثُمَّ ائۡتُوۡا صَفًّا ۚ وَ قَدۡ اَفۡلَحَ الۡیَوۡمَ مَنِ اسۡتَعۡلٰی»\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said) \"So gather your devices and then come in a line. Indeed, he who succeeds today is he who is dominant.\""
    }
  ],
  "448": [
    {
      "id": 2080,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Dust",
      "hw": "غبار",
      "s": "« » refers to those fine particles of dust that are always scattered in the air and are not visible (2 verses: 25:23-56:6)",
      "d": "« » means fine particles of dust (m. l). Such fine particles of soil that are always present in the air and are not even visible.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ قَدِمۡنَاۤ اِلٰی مَا عَمِلُوۡا مِنۡ عَمَلٍ فَجَعَلۡنٰہُ ہَبَآءً مَّنۡثُوۡرًا»\nTranslation: And We will advance toward what they did of deeds, so We will make them as scattered dust."
    }
  ],
  "449": [
    {
      "id": 2081,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "« » means displeasure, dislike; this is the first degree of anger and it always occurs from a superior to an inferior (3 verses: 3:162-5:80-9:58)",
      "d": "«سَخَطَ» «سَخْط» «سَخَطَ الْاَمِیْر عَلَی الْحَاجِب» «سَخَطَ الْحَاجِبِ عَلَی الْاَمِیْر»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَفَمَنِ اتَّبَعَ رِضۡوَانَ اللّٰہِ کَمَنۡۢ بَآءَ بِسَخَطٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: So is he who seeks the pleasure of Allah like him who has earned the anger of Allah?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2082,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "«Ghayz» Such anger that accelerates a person's blood circulation, and this is the second degree of anger; ghayz can also be directed towards oneself (9 verses: 3:119-3:134-9:15-9:120-22:15-25:12-33:25-48:29-67:8)",
      "d": "«Ghayz» is such anger that accelerates a person's blood circulation, and this is the second degree of anger (Fall 169). However, it does not involve retaliatory action nor has it been acted upon. And «ghayz» can be related to one's own self as well (Fiqh 06).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ الۡکٰظِمِیۡنَ الۡغَیۡظَ وَ الۡعَافِیۡنَ عَنِ النَّاسِ»\nTranslation: And those who suppress their anger and pardon the people."
    },
    {
      "id": 2083,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "« » when a person boils with anger and descends to revenge, whether small or big, it is not related to one's own self but to another's self (20 verses: 1:7-2:61-2:90-3:112-4:93-5:60-7:71-7:150-7:152-7:154-8:16-16:106-20:81-20:86-24:9-42:16-42:37-48:6-58:14-60:13)",
      "d": "« » according to the expert in etymology, this word is general and is used for every type of anger (cf. 169). But this definition does not seem correct. The Messenger of Allah ﷺ defined anger as follows:\n«اِتَّقُوْا مِنْ الْغَضَبِ فَاِنَّہٗ جُمْرَۃٌ تُوْقَدُ فِیْ قَلْبِ ابْنِ اٰدَمَ اَلَمْ تَرَوْا اِلَی انْتِفَاخِ اَوْدَاجِہٖ وَجُمْرَۃِ عَیْنَیْہِ»\nTranslation: Be cautious of anger, for it is a spark of fire that burns in the heart of the son of Adam. Do you not see how his veins swell and his eyes turn red?\n«اَشَدّْ السَّخَط» «غَضِبَ» «the intention to harm the one against whom anger is directed» «غَضْب»\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّحۡلِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ غَضَبِیۡ فَقَدۡ ہَوٰی»\nTranslation: And whoever incurs My anger will indeed be destroyed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2084,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "« » the quality of vengeful action due to anger; to pounce quickly or to devise a strategy for attack from a distance (i.e., to plan harm or trouble) (1 verse: 68:25)",
      "d": "« » means to be angry with someone. And « » means to forbid (Munjid). « » means overwhelmed by anger (i.e., in a rage) to swiftly attack someone or to devise a strategy for attack (cf. 169). « » is actually not the name of any quality of anger, but the quality of that strategy or vengeful action which a person carries out while overcome by rage and fury. And according to Abu Halaal, the meaning of « » is, in a state of anger, to distance oneself from the one against whom anger is directed and then bring it to completion (cf. 106).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَّ  غَدَوۡا عَلٰی حَرۡدٍ   قٰدِرِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And they set out in the morning, attacking fiercely, as if they were powerful (over the cultivation)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2086,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To provoke anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "« » meaning to provoke anger (3 verses: 9:120-22:15-48:29)",
      "d": "« » meaning to provoke anger. Details have been discussed above.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ لَا یَطَئُوۡنَ مَوۡطِئًا یَّغِیۡظُ الۡکُفَّارَ»\nTranslation: And they do not tread any ground that would anger the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2087,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To provoke anger",
      "hw": "غصہ",
      "s": "« » is used to denote provoking anger that creates wrath in the powerful and afflicts the weak with grief and sorrow (5 verses: 7:150-12:84-18:6-20:86-43:55)",
      "d": "« »: such anger that is based on regret and grief. If the anger is towards the weak, it takes the form of rage and fury. And if towards the powerful, it merely results in internal grief and sorrow due to inability to act (Mufradat). And « » means to lose something and to regret it (cf. ML). Also, « » means to provoke anger; to make sad (Munjid).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ  اٰسَفُوۡنَا انۡتَقَمۡنَا مِنۡہِمۡ»\nTranslation: Then when they provoked Our anger, We took retribution from them."
    }
  ],
  "450": [
    {
      "id": 2089,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Grief",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "« » such grief whose cause is an incurable calamity (11 verses: 3:176-5:41-6:33-10:65-12:13-12:84-12:86-21:103-31:23-36:76-58:10)",
      "d": "« » means grief, and its opposite is « » meaning happiness. « » is the state of unrest in a matter. And it expresses a person's state of anxiety. When no remedy for anxiety is found, it takes the form of grief. And « » also refers to calamities. Therefore, the grief that befalls due to a calamity is called « ».\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ ابۡیَضَّتۡ عَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡحُزۡنِ»\nTranslation: And his (Jacob's) eyes turned white from grief."
    },
    {
      "id": 2091,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be grieved; To grieve",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "« » to grieve due to an incident or calamity (31 verses: 2:38-2:62-2:112-2:262-2:274-2:277-3:139-3:153-3:170-5:69-6:48-7:35-7:49-9:40-9:92-10:62-15:88-16:127-19:24-20:40-27:70-28:7-28:8-28:13-29:33-33:51-35:34-39:61-41:30-43:68-46:13-)",
      "d": "« » means to grieve; to be sad (details have been discussed above).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا»\nTranslation: Do not grieve; indeed, Allah is with us."
    },
    {
      "id": 2092,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be grieved; To grieve",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "« » to grieve over something that has slipped from the hand (i.e., lost) (2 verses: 7:93-57:23)",
      "d": "« » means to grieve over the loss of something (Mufradat).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَ لَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ  اٰتٰىکُمۡ»\nTranslation: So that you do not grieve over what has escaped you, nor exult over what He has given you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2093,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be grieved; To grieve",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "« » such grief that befalls due to despair in a matter (5 verses: 6:44-23:77-30:12-30:49-43:75)",
      "d": "« » means to become grieved due to intense despair (Mufradat) and also means to be unaware. Grieved and broken-hearted (Munjid), i.e., such grief that befalls due to having despaired in a matter. And Satan is called Iblis because he is despairing and broken-hearted from Allah's mercy.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ اِنۡ کَانُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ یُّنَزَّلَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلِہٖ لَمُبۡلِسِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And before it was sent down upon them, from before it, they were in despair."
    },
    {
      "id": 2094,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "To be grieved; To grieve",
      "hw": "غم",
      "s": "« » for grief to befall due to someone else's unpleasant and unbearable act (2 verses: 11:36-12:69)",
      "d": "In « » are found meanings of severity and unpleasantness (Mufradat). And « » means to find something unpleasant and to grieve over it (Munjid).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«وَ اُوۡحِیَ  اِلٰی نُوۡحٍ اَنَّہٗ  لَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنَ مِنۡ قَوۡمِکَ اِلَّا مَنۡ قَدۡ اٰمَنَ فَلَا تَبۡتَئِسۡ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡعَلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And it was revealed to Noah that none of your people will believe except he who has already believed. So do not grieve over what they have been doing."
    }
  ],
  "451": [
    {
      "id": 2098,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "to ponder",
      "hw": "غور",
      "s": "« » to recall a matter, think and reflect, then derive lessons from it (7 verses: 12:45-54:15-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-54:51)",
      "d": "« » means to remember something. To retain. And « » means to remind someone of something in such a way that they derive lessons from it. And « » means to bring something to mind oneself. To bring into the mind (sing.). To pay attention and ponder over it so that one derives lessons oneself.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ یَسَّرۡنَا الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  لِلذِّکۡرِ  فَہَلۡ مِنۡ مُّدَّکِرٍ»\nTranslation: And We have made the Quran easy to understand. So is there anyone who will ponder and reflect?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2099,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "to ponder",
      "hw": "غور",
      "s": "« » to deeply contemplate a known matter and derive subsidiary issues or results (1 verse: 4:83)",
      "d": "« »: After digging a well, the first water drawn is called « ». And « » means to draw water from the bottom of a well. And « » comes in the meaning of extraction (taking out) (sing.). And « » means to reveal after concealment. To extract by choice. To invent. For a jurist to derive something from their own understanding and reasoning (source). « » is actually a type of ijtihad or tafaqquh where one deeply contemplates within known knowledge, reaches its depths, and derives subsidiary issues or results from it.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَوۡ رَدُّوۡہُ  اِلَی الرَّسُوۡلِ وَ اِلٰۤی اُولِی الۡاَمۡرِ مِنۡہُمۡ لَعَلِمَہُ الَّذِیۡنَ یَسۡتَنۡۢبِطُوۡنَہٗ مِنۡہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And if they referred the matter to their Messenger or to those in authority among them, those who investigate it from them would have known it."
    }
  ],
  "452": [
    {
      "id": 2101,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "benefit; to give benefit",
      "hw": "فائدہ",
      "s": "« » to take benefit from anything that a living being uses to sustain life (33 verses: 2:126-2:196-2:236-4:24-6:128-9:69-10:98-11:3-11:48-11:65-14:30-15:3-15:88-16:55-20:131-21:44-25:18-26:205-26:207-28:61-29:66-30:34-31:24-33:16-33:28-33:49-37:148-39:8-43:29-46:20-47:12-51:43-77:46)",
      "d": "« » means every thing from the provisions of life from which a human or any living being derives benefit to sustain life is « ». Its plurals are « » and « » means to benefit from such provisions.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«اَخۡرَجَ  مِنۡہَا مَآءَہَا وَ  مَرۡعٰہَا وَ الۡجِبَالَ  اَرۡسٰہَا مَتَاعًا  لَّکُمۡ  وَ  لِاَنۡعَامِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: He brought forth from it its water and its pasture and made the mountains its anchors. All this He made for you and your cattle to benefit from.\nAnd « » means to give someone such provisions from which they can benefit. To provide benefit.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَّ مَتِّعُوۡہُنَّ ۚ عَلَی الۡمُوۡسِعِ قَدَرُہٗ  وَ عَلَی الۡمُقۡتِرِ قَدَرُہٗ»\nTranslation: But give them (the divorced women) something according to custom: the wealthy according to his means and the poor according to his means. This is a duty upon the good.\nAnd « » means to derive benefit for oneself. To enjoy.\nFor example: The Divine Command says:\n«تَمَتَّعُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِکُمۡ ثَلٰثَۃَ  اَیَّامٍ»\nTranslation: Enjoy yourselves in your homes for three days."
    },
    {
      "id": 2102,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "benefit; to give benefit",
      "hw": "فائدہ",
      "s": "« » to gain profit from trade (1 verse: 2:16)",
      "d": "« » is the profit gained from buying and selling (sing.). To have profit in trade. Its opposite is « » meaning loss.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَمَا رَبِحَتۡ تِّجَارَتُہُمۡ وَ مَا کَانُوۡا مُہۡتَدِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: So their trade has not profited them, nor were they guided."
    },
    {
      "id": 2103,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "benefit; to give benefit",
      "hw": "فائدہ",
      "s": "« » necessities and means to fulfill them (2 verses: 20:18-24:31)",
      "d": "«اَرْب» «مَارِب ، مَارِبَۃ ، مَارَبَہ» «مَارُبَۃ» «مَارَب»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«قَالَ ہِیَ عَصَایَ ۚ اَتَوَکَّؤُا عَلَیۡہَا وَ اَہُشُّ بِہَا عَلٰی غَنَمِیۡ وَ لِیَ فِیۡہَا مَاٰرِبُ  اُخۡرٰی»\nTranslation: Moses said, 'It is my staff. I lean on it and beat down leaves with it for my sheep, and I have other needs for it.'"
    }
  ],
  "453": [
    {
      "id": 2105,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "to be granted victory; to grant",
      "hw": "فتح",
      "s": "« » a victory where the enemy's chest is pierced with nails, i.e., victory and subsequent dominance (1 verse: 48:24)",
      "d": "«ظَفَر» «ظَفَرَ فُلَانٌ» «اَظْفَرَ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ کَفَّ  اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ  عَنۡکُمۡ وَ اَیۡدِیَکُمۡ عَنۡہُمۡ بِبَطۡنِ مَکَّۃَ  مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ اَنۡ  اَظۡفَرَکُمۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And He is the One Who restrained their hands from you and your hands from them after He granted you victory over them in the valley of Mecca."
    }
  ],
  "454": [
    {
      "id": 2106,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "prosperity; ease",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "« » to pass through easily after hardship (1 verse: 2:280)",
      "d": "« » means ease, and its opposite is « » meaning hardship. And « » means a time of ease. A time when a person can manage their livelihood easily from a financial perspective.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡ عُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ»\nTranslation: And if (the debtor) is in hardship, then grant him respite until a time of ease."
    },
    {
      "id": 2107,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "prosperity; ease",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "« » to be provided with means of livelihood (3 verses: 4:25-9:86-40:3)",
      "d": "« » means length, extension, and (temporal) length. And the word « » comes in the meaning of bounty and favor which is not merely temporary (sing.). And « » means sustenance and expenses for livelihood. Bounty. Grant. Affluence (source).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ مَنۡ لَّمۡ یَسۡتَطِعۡ مِنۡکُمۡ طَوۡلًا اَنۡ یَّنۡکِحَ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتِ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ فَمِنۡ مَّا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ مِّنۡ فَتَیٰتِکُمُ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ »\nTranslation: And whoever among you cannot afford to marry free, believing women, then (marry) from those whom your right hands possess of believing slave girls.\n«اُوْلُوا الطَّوْل»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2108,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "prosperity; ease",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "« » expansion and spaciousness, whether in something (22 verses: 2:245-2:247-5:11-5:28-6:93-7:69-13:14-13:26-17:29-17:30-18:18-28:82-29:62-30:37-30:48-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-42:27-60:2-71:19)",
      "d": "« » means to open and to spread. Its opposite is also « » and « ». And « » means spaciousness (of place), expansion, and abundance (sing.). Whether this expansion is in wealth and property or in any other thing. This word is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ زَادَہٗ بَسۡطَۃً فِی الۡعِلۡمِ وَ الۡجِسۡمِ»\nTranslation: And Allah has preferred them over you and increased them abundantly in knowledge and physique.\nAt another place, the Divine Command says:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِہٖ  وَ یَقۡدِرُ  لَہٗ»\nTranslation: Allah extends provision for whom He wills of His servants and restricts it for whom He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 2111,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "to be spacious; to expand",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "« » to have capacity and spaciousness in place and state (27 verses: 2:115-2:233-2:236-2:247-2:255-2:261-2:268-2:286-3:73-4:97-4:100-4:130-5:54-6:80-6:147-6:152-7:42-7:89-7:156-20:98-23:62-24:32-29:56-39:10-40:7-51:47-53:32)",
      "d": "« » applies to both place and state. It means prosperity, spaciousness, expansion, capacity (CAPACITY).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَسِعَ کُرۡسِیُّہُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ»\nTranslation: His Kursi (Throne) encompasses the heavens and the earth.\nAlso, the Divine Command says:\n«لَا یُکَلِّفُ اللّٰہُ نَفۡسًا اِلَّا وُسۡعَہَا»\nTranslation: Allah does not burden a soul beyond its capacity.\n«اَوْسَعَ» «اَوْسَعَ الْمَوْضَعَ»\nFor example: The Divine Command says:\n«وَ السَّمَآءَ  بَنَیۡنٰہَا بِاَیۡىدٍ وَّ اِنَّا لَمُوۡسِعُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And the heaven We constructed with might, and indeed, We are its expanders."
    },
    {
      "id": 2112,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "to spread out",
      "hw": "فراخی",
      "s": "« » to sit openly in such a way that space becomes available for others (1 verse: 58:11)",
      "d": "«فَسَحَ» «تَفَسَّحَ فِی الْمَجْلِس» «اِذَا  قِیۡلَ  لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی  الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا یَفۡسَحِ اللّٰہُ  لَکُمۡ»"
    }
  ],
  "455": [
    {
      "id": 2113,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "angel",
      "hw": "فرشتہ",
      "s": "« » a messenger angel (86 verses: 2:30-2:31-2:34-2:98-2:102-2:161-2:177-2:210-2:248-2:285-3:18-3:39-3:42-3:45-3:80-3:87-3:124-3:125-4:97-4:136-4:166-4:172-6:8-6:9-6:50-6:93-6:111-6:158-7:11-7:20-8:9-8:12-8:50-11:12-11:31-12:31-13:13-13:23-15:7-15:8-15:28-15:30-16:2-16:28-16:32-16:33-16:49-17:40-17:61-17:92-17:95-18:50-20:116-21:103-22:75-23:24-25:7-25:21-25:22-25:25-32:11-33:43-33:56-34:40-35:1-37:150-38:71-38:73-39:75-41:14-41:30-42:5-43:19-43:53-43:60-47:27-53:26-53:27-66:4-66:6-69:17-70:4-74:31-78:38-89:22-97:4)",
      "d": "«مَلَک» «مَلٰئِکَۃ» «لأک» «اَلْاَکَۃُ اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» «اَلِکْنِیْ» «مَلَأک» «مَلَک» «مَلَک» «مَلَک» «مَلٰئِکَۃ» «مَلٰئِکَۃ» «مَلَک» «اِذۡ قَالَتِ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ یٰمَرۡیَمُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُبَشِّرُکِ بِکَلِمَۃٍ مِّنۡہُ ٭ۖ اسۡمُہُ الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ» «مَلٰئِکَۃ» «مَلَک»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2114,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "angel",
      "hw": "فرشتہ",
      "s": "« » the angel who is appointed by Allah to convey messages to the prophets (20 verses: 2:87-2:253-4:171-5:110-15:29-16:2-16:102-17:85-19:17-21:91-26:193-32:9-38:72-40:15-42:52-58:22-66:12-70:4-78:38-97:4)",
      "d": "«مَلٰئِکَۃ» «مَلَک» «فَاَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہَا رُوۡحَنَا فَتَمَثَّلَ لَہَا بَشَرًا سَوِیًّا»"
    }
  ],
  "456": [
    {
      "id": 2115,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "difference",
      "hw": "فرق",
      "s": "« » is used for the distance of separation and for difference (9 verses: 9:42-11:44-11:60-11:68-11:95-21:101-23:41-23:44-43:38)",
      "d": "«بَعِد» «بَعُد» «بُعْد» «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَنَا قَالَ یٰلَیۡتَ بَیۡنِیۡ وَ بَیۡنَکَ بُعۡدَ الۡمَشۡرِقَیۡنِ فَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرِیۡنُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2116,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "difference",
      "hw": "فرق",
      "s": "« » difference due to two things having different attributes. Incompatibility (1 verse: 67:3)",
      "d": "«تَفَاوُت» «اِسْتَوَاء» «اِسْتَوَاء فَاتَ الْاَمْر» «تَفَاوَتَ الشَّیْئَیْن» «فَات» «تَفَاوُت» «مَا تَرٰی فِیۡ  خَلۡقِ الرَّحۡمٰنِ مِنۡ  تَفٰوُتٍ»"
    }
  ],
  "457": [
    {
      "id": 2118,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "« » that faction for which there is also another faction present or mentioned (29 verses: 2:75-2:85-2:87-2:100-2:101-2:146-2:188-3:23-3:78-3:100-4:77-5:70-6:81-7:30-8:5-9:107-9:117-11:24-16:54-19:73-23:109-24:47-24:48-27:45-30:33-33:13-33:26-34:20-42:7)",
      "d": "«فِرْقَۃ» «فَرِیْق» «فَرِیْق» «فَرِیۡقٌ فِی الۡجَنَّۃِ  وَ فَرِیۡقٌ فِی السَّعِیۡرِ» «اَیُّ الۡفَرِیۡقَیۡنِ خَیۡرٌ  مَّقَامًا وَّ اَحۡسَنُ نَدِیًّا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2119,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "« » a small group of people with the same religion and opinion (19 verses: 3:69-3:72-3:122-3:154-4:81-4:102-4:113-6:156-7:87-8:7-9:66-9:83-9:122-24:2-28:4-33:13-49:9-61:14-73:20)",
      "d": "«طَائِفَۃ» «وَ اِنۡ طَآئِفَتٰنِ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اقۡتَتَلُوۡا فَاَصۡلِحُوۡا بَیۡنَہُمَا» «طَائِفَۃ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2120,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "« » meaning small squads, groups (2 verses: 39:71-39:73)",
      "d": "«زُمَر» «زُمْرَہ» «زُمُر» «وَ سِیۡقَ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّقَوۡا رَبَّہُمۡ  اِلَی الۡجَنَّۃِ زُمَرًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2121,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "« » a party or faction based on difference of belief (10 verses: 6:65-6:159-15:10-19:69-28:4-28:15-30:32-34:54-37:87-54:51)",
      "d": "«شِیْعَۃ» «فَوَجَدَ فِیۡہَا رَجُلَیۡنِ یَقۡتَتِلٰنِ ٭۫ ہٰذَا مِنۡ شِیۡعَتِہٖ وَ ہٰذَا مِنۡ عَدُوِّہٖ» «شِیْعَۃ» «شِیَعًا» «اَشْیَاعَ» «اَشْیَاع» «وَ حِیۡلَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَ مَا یَشۡتَہُوۡنَ کَمَا فُعِلَ بِاَشۡیَاعِہِمۡ مِّنۡ قَبۡلُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2122,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "faction",
      "hw": "فرقہ",
      "s": "« » separate groups belonging to different tribes (5 verses: 2:60-7:82-7:160-17:71-27:56)",
      "d": "«اُنَاس» «نَاس» «اُنَاس» «قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ»"
    }
  ],
  "458": [
    {
      "id": 2123,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Answering a cry",
      "hw": "فریاد",
      "s": "«Istitab» Such a prayer which Allah grants the honor of acceptance (20 verses: 2:186-3:172-3:195-6:36-7:194-8:9-8:24-11:14-12:34-13:14-13:18-17:52-28:50-28:64-35:14-42:16-42:26-42:38-42:47-46:5)",
      "d": "«Jaba» means to carve a stone. And «ajaba» means to respond to speech, i.e., to answer a question (m. l). And «sa'ala» also comes in two meanings: (1) to inquire about something, (2) to ask for or request something. Therefore, «ajaba» also comes in both meanings: (1) in the sense of answering a question.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«یَوۡمَ یَجۡمَعُ اللّٰہُ الرُّسُلَ فَیَقُوۡلُ مَا ذَاۤ اُجِبۡتُمۡ»\nTranslation: On the Day when Allah will gather the messengers, He will say, \"What was your response [from those you were sent to]?\"\n(2) And in the sense of responding to a request, it means to accept.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَمَّنۡ یُّجِیۡبُ الۡمُضۡطَرَّ اِذَا دَعَاہُ»\nTranslation: Who responds to the desperate one when he calls upon Him?\nAnd «istijab» means accepting a prayer, i.e., fulfilling the caller's need or granting his supplication, especially when called upon.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ نُوۡحًا اِذۡ نَادٰی مِنۡ قَبۡلُ فَاسۡتَجَبۡنَا لَہٗ فَنَجَّیۡنٰہُ وَ اَہۡلَہٗ مِنَ الۡکَرۡبِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: And [mention] Noah when he called [to Us] before, and We responded to him and saved him and his family from the great distress."
    },
    {
      "id": 2124,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Answering the Cry",
      "hw": "فریاد",
      "s": "« » means to scream and call for help in times of distress and to reach the help of the one crying out. (3 verses: 14:22-28:18-35:37)",
      "d": "« » means to scream. To shout so that one's cry may be heard. And « » means to reach the cry (36/43) and « » has the same meaning.\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَا تَلُوۡمُوۡنِیۡ وَ لُوۡمُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ ؕ مَاۤ  اَنَا بِمُصۡرِخِکُمۡ وَ مَاۤ  اَنۡتُمۡ بِمُصۡرِخِیَّ»\nTranslation: Satan will say to his followers, 'Do not blame me, but blame yourselves. I am not your helper, nor are you my helpers.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2125,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To cry for help",
      "hw": "فریاد",
      "s": "«Istighath» The word istighath is used when a cry for help is presented before Allah or a temporal ruler (4 verses: 8:9-18:29-28:15-46:17)",
      "d": "«Gatha» means to aid and help someone in times of difficulty (m. l). And «ghayth» refers to rain that comes timely and as needed. And «istighath» means to cry out to Allah for such rain, or to seek aid and help from Allah or another ruler in times of difficulty. Istighathah is a well-known term meaning to complain of injustice or oppression before a ruler or court.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اِذۡ تَسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡنَ رَبَّکُمۡ فَاسۡتَجَابَ لَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: When you cried out to your Lord for help, He responded to you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2126,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Crying Out",
      "hw": "فریاد",
      "s": "« » is used when people are invited through screaming and calling. (2 verses: 14:22-28:18)",
      "d": "« » means to scream and call out to make one's cry heard by the people and seek their help.\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا  الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ  بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ»\nTranslation: Then the man who had sought his help the day before, now began to cry out to him."
    }
  ],
  "459": [
    {
      "id": 2127,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Causing Corruption",
      "hw": "فساد",
      "s": "« » can be used even for a single act of corruption, and when « » becomes a habit, then « » is used. And in « », the fundamental meaning is to interfere, whether in one thing or many. Then, among these, to cause corruption. (47 verses: 2:11-2:12-2:27-2:30-2:60-2:205-2:220-2:251-3:63-5:32-5:33-5:64-7:56-7:74-7:85-7:86-7:103-7:127-7:142-8:73-10:40-10:81-10:91-11:85-11:116-12:73-13:25-16:88-17:4-18:94-21:22-23:71-26:152-26:183-27:14-27:34-27:48-28:4-28:77-28:83-29:30-29:36-30:41-38:28-40:26-47:22-89:12)",
      "d": "« » means for something to become corrupt, to spoil. And « » means to corrupt something and spoil it. The opposite of « » is « ». The word « » is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ بَعۡدَ اِصۡلَاحِہَا»\nTranslation: And do not cause corruption in the land after its reform."
    },
    {
      "id": 2128,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To cause corruption. To throw.",
      "hw": "فساد",
      "s": "«Atha» Meaning to spread corruption (5 verses: 2:60-7:74-11:85-26:183-29:36)",
      "d": "«Atha» or «aath» means to spread corruption, create disorder and corruption.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَا تَعۡثَوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مُفۡسِدِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And do not cause corruption in the land.\n«Tasthawa» «ع ث ی» «athiya yasthu athiyan» «ع ی ث» «aatha ya'ithu athiyan» «la tasthawa»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2129,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To cause corruption; to sow discord.",
      "hw": "فساد",
      "s": "« » means to sow discord between two things (4 verses: 7:200-12:100-17:53-41:36)",
      "d": "« » means to sow discord between two things (according to Majid) and means to create a quarrel. To incite to corruption. To create mischief. To instigate a fight. To sow enmity (according to Quran) and means to spoil a matter and interfere in it (according to Mufradat) or to cause corruption by interference.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ اَنۡ  نَّزَغَ  الشَّیۡطٰنُ  بَیۡنِیۡ وَ بَیۡنَ اِخۡوَتِیۡ»\nTranslation: After that, Satan had sown discord between me and my brothers."
    }
  ],
  "460": [
    {
      "id": 2130,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To engage in idle talk; to chatter.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "« » means to chatter in such a way that others' words are not heard (11 verses: 2:225-5:89-19:62-23:3-25:72-28:55-41:26-52:23-56:25-78:35-88:11)",
      "d": "« » means to speak without thinking or understanding. Idle talk (according to Al-Munjid) and means the chirping of birds. And similarly, to repeatedly mention something (according to Quran). And the meaning of « » is to chatter and make noise in such a way that the listener's words are drowned in the noise so that others also cannot hear.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَا تَسۡمَعُوۡا لِہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنِ وَ الۡغَوۡا فِیۡہِ  لَعَلَّکُمۡ تَغۡلِبُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And the disbelievers said, 'Do not listen to this Quran and make noise while it is being recited, so that you may prevail.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2131,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To engage in idle talk; to chatter.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "« » means to become immersed in idle talk or actions (9 verses: 4:140-6:68-6:91-9:65-9:69-43:83-52:12-70:42-74:45)",
      "d": "«خَاض» «خَاضَ فِی الْمَاءِ» «خَاضَ فِی الْحَدِیْث»\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ اِذَا  رَاَیۡتَ الَّذِیۡنَ  یَخُوۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ  اٰیٰتِنَا فَاَعۡرِضۡ عَنۡہُمۡ حَتّٰی یَخُوۡضُوۡا فِیۡ حَدِیۡثٍ غَیۡرِہٖ»\nTranslation: When you see those who engage in idle talk about Our verses, turn away from them until they engage in a different conversation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2132,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Idle Talk",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "« » is such jesting from which pleasure is derived. Happy banter. (1 verse: 83:31)",
      "d": "«فَکِہَ» «فَکَاہَۃ» «تَفَکَّہَ بِعِرْضِ فَلَانٍ»\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اِذَا  انۡقَلَبُوۡۤا  اِلٰۤی  اَہۡلِہُمُ  انۡقَلَبُوۡا فَکِہِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And when they return to their families, they return jesting."
    },
    {
      "id": 2135,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To spend wastefully; extravagance.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "« » is used for wasteful spending in permissible matters (19 verses: 5:32-6:141-7:31-7:81-10:12-10:83-17:33-20:127-21:9-25:67-26:151-36:19-39:53-40:28-40:34-40:43-43:5-44:31-51:34)",
      "d": "« » and « » mean to exceed the limits of moderation (according to Mufradat) and it is used for spending more than necessary in wealth or food and drink. And the limit of moderation is for that which is permissible (i.e., allowed in Sharia) or lawful. Thus, the meaning of israf is to spend more than necessary in permissible matters.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا وَ لَا  تُسۡرِفُوۡا»\nTranslation: Eat and drink, but do not spend wastefully."
    },
    {
      "id": 2136,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To spend wastefully; extravagance.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "« » means to scatter wealth wastefully and extravagantly. (2 verses: 17:26-17:27)",
      "d": "« » and « » mean seed. And « » means to scatter seed. Just as seed is scattered on the earth, similarly if wealth is scattered, it is called « » (according to Mufradat). Thus, whether the need is lawful or unlawful, spending wealth recklessly is called « » (according to Mufradat) and this is also worse than israf.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَا  تُبَذِّرۡ  تَبۡذِیۡرًا اِنَّ الۡمُبَذِّرِیۡنَ کَانُوۡۤا اِخۡوَانَ الشَّیٰطِیۡنِ»\nTranslation: And do not spend wastefully. Indeed, the wasteful are brothers of the devils."
    },
    {
      "id": 2137,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To grant excellence; to bestow honor.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "« » means for something good to be more or superior. (93 verses: 2:47-2:64-2:90-2:105-2:122-2:198-2:237-2:243-2:251-2:253-2:268-3:73-3:74-3:152-3:170-3:171-3:174-3:180-4:32-4:34-4:37-4:54-4:70-4:73-4:83-4:95-4:113-4:173-4:175-5:2-5:54-6:86-7:39-7:140-8:29-9:28-9:59-9:74-9:75-9:76-10:58-10:60-10:107-11:3-11:27-12:38-13:4-16:14-16:71-17:12-17:21-17:48-17:55-17:66-17:70-17:87-23:24-24:10-24:14-24:20-24:21-24:22-24:32-24:33-24:38-27:15-27:16-27:40-27:73-28:73-30:23-30:45-30:46-33:47-34:10-35:12-35:30-35:32-35:35-40:61-42:22-42:26-44:57-45:12-45:16-48:29-49:8-57:21-57:29-59:8-62:4-62:10-73:20)",
      "d": "« » means for a good thing to exceed the moderate degree. And « » means to give someone, out of kindness, more than their due in something good (according to Mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ  اِسۡرَآءِیۡلَ اذۡکُرُوۡا نِعۡمَتِیَ الَّتِیۡۤ  اَنۡعَمۡتُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ وَ اَنِّیۡ فَضَّلۡتُکُمۡ عَلَی الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: O Children of Israel! Remember My favor which I bestowed upon you and that I preferred you over the worlds."
    },
    {
      "id": 2138,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To grant excellence; to bestow honor.",
      "hw": "فضول",
      "s": "« » means to instill excellence within something. (14 verses: 12:21-17:62-17:70-21:26-22:18-36:27-37:42-49:13-51:24-70:35-80:13-89:15-89:17-96:3)",
      "d": "« » refers to such honor that is inherently present in something or due to its qualities (according to Majid). And « » means to instill the essence of excellence within something (according to Mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ کَرَّمۡنَا بَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ وَ حَمَلۡنٰہُمۡ  فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ»\nTranslation: And We have certainly honored the children of Adam and carried them on the land and sea."
    }
  ],
  "461": [
    {
      "id": 2139,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To judge; to decree.",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "« » is a judgment by which distinction between truth and falsehood is made, complexity is removed, and no party remains in doubt. (7 verses: 7:89-8:19-14:15-26:118-32:28-32:29-34:26)",
      "d": "« » means to remove restriction and complexity from something (according to Mufradat). Its opposite is « » meaning confinement and restriction (according to Majid). And « » means to grant victory and to judge. A judgment by which distinction between truth and falsehood is made, complexity is removed, and no party remains in doubt.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«رَبَّنَا افۡتَحۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَ قَوۡمِنَا بِالۡحَقِّ»\nTranslation: Our Lord, judge between us and our people with truth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2140,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To judge; to decree.",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "« » means to distinguish one thing from another and for it to be distant from it. (6 verses: 37:21-44:40-77:13-77:14-77:38-78:17)",
      "d": "« » means to distinguish one thing from another (to differentiate) and for it to be distant from it (according to Majid). Thus, in contrast to  , « » is specific. In  , there is only distinction, whereas in « », there are two things: distinction and separation. And this distinction and separation can sometimes be in the same thing, such as a chapter of a book. Similarly,   may relate to one thing or to multiple things. (according to Fiqh al-Lughah 113)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«ہٰذَا یَوۡمُ الۡفَصۡلِ ۚ جَمَعۡنٰکُمۡ وَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: This is the Day of Judgment; We will gather you and the former peoples."
    },
    {
      "id": 2141,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To judge; to decree.",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "« » is a judgment by which someone is prevented from oppression and a plan is made to correct them. (43 verses: 2:113-2:213-3:23-3:55-4:58-4:105-4:141-5:1-5:42-5:43-5:44-5:45-5:47-5:48-5:49-5:50-5:95-6:136-7:87-10:35-10:109-12:80-16:59-16:124-21:78-21:112-22:56-22:69-24:48-24:51-29:4-37:154-38:22-38:26-39:3-39:46-40:12-40:48-42:10-45:21-60:10-68:36-68:39)",
      "d": "« » means 'to prevent from injustice' (according to Majid). A judgment in which oppression and excess are prevented. And means 'to prevent from dispute' (according to Fiqh al-Lughah 156), i.e., a ruling to stop fighting and quarreling.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ دَاوٗدَ  وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ  اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ»\nTranslation: And [mention] David and Solomon when they judged concerning a field."
    },
    {
      "id": 2142,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To Decide",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "« » means to give the final and binding decision of the one who has the power to enforce that command. (58 verses: 2:117-2:200-2:210-3:47-4:65-4:103-6:2-6:8-6:58-6:60-8:42-8:44-10:11-10:19-10:47-10:54-10:71-10:93-11:44-11:110-12:41-12:68-14:22-15:66-17:4-17:23-19:21-19:35-19:39-19:71-20:72-20:114-22:29-27:78-28:15-28:28-28:29-28:44-33:23-33:36-33:37-34:14-35:36-39:42-39:69-39:75-40:20-40:68-40:78-41:12-41:45-42:14-42:21-43:77-45:17-46:29-62:10-80:23)",
      "d": "«یَقْضِیْ قَضْیًا وَ قَضَاءً وَ قَضِیَّۃً» «قَضٰی» «فَلَا وَ رَبِّکَ لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ حَتّٰی یُحَکِّمُوۡکَ فِیۡمَا شَجَرَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ ثُمَّ لَا یَجِدُوۡا فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَرَجًا مِّمَّا قَضَیۡتَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2143,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "To Decide",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "« » means a decisive and immutable decree, the decision of Divine will (1 Verse: 19:71)",
      "d": "«حَتَمَ» «حَاتِم» «حَتَمَ الْحَاتِمُ كَذَا» «ھٰذا وَلَدٌ حَتَمٌ» «حَتْم» «حَتْم»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ إِنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ إِلَّا وَارِدُہَا ۚ کَانَ عَلٰی رَبِّکَ حَتۡمًا مَّقۡضِیًّا»\nTranslation: And there is not one of you but will pass over it (Hell). This is for your Lord a decree determined."
    }
  ],
  "462": [
    {
      "id": 2144,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Gain Control",
      "hw": "قابو",
      "s": "«قَدَرَ عَلٰی»",
      "d": "«قَدَر، قَدِر (قَدْرًا، قُدْرَۃً) قَدَر» «قَدَرَ الرِّزْق» «قَدَرَ عَلَی الشَّیْء»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ذَاالنُّوۡنِ إِذۡ ذَّہَبَ مُغَاضِبًا فَظَنَّ أَنَّ لَنۡ نَّقۡدِرَ عَلَیۡہِ»\nTranslation: And [mention] the man of the fish (Prophet Jonah) when he went away in anger and thought that We would not have power over him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2145,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Gain Control",
      "hw": "قابو",
      "s": "« » means to have the power over something associated with it (4 verses: 14:49-25:13-38:38-43:13)",
      "d": "«قَرَنَ» «قَرْن» «اَقْرَنَ» «اَقْرَنَ لِلْاَمْر» «اَقْرَنَ عَلَیْہِ» «اَقْرَنَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡ سَخَّرَ لَنَا ہٰذَا  وَ مَا کُنَّا لَہٗ  مُقۡرِنِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Glorified is He Who has subjected this to us, and we could not have had control over it."
    }
  ],
  "463": [
    {
      "id": 2148,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Caravan",
      "hw": "قافلہ",
      "s": "« » refers to a group traveling together, a caravan or fellow travelers. This word is general. (3 verses: 5:96-12:10-12:19)",
      "d": "« » means to walk, to roam. And « » means anything that walks or roams continuously or has traveled much (it is an intensive form). Celestial bodies are also called « ». And in common usage, « » refers to a group traveling together or fellow travelers. Caravan (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ»\nTranslation: And a caravan came. They sent their water-drawer, who let down his bucket (into the well)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2149,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Caravan",
      "hw": "قافلہ",
      "s": "« » a grain-carrying caravan. (3 verses: 12:70-12:82-12:94)",
      "d": "« » refers to any caravan that carries grain. The camels and people carrying food supplies are all included in it (muf). According to scholars of language, it applies whether the caravan consists of camels, horses, or donkeys (f l 16). Also, the caravan of the Himyar tribe is called « » (m.q.).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ اَذَّنَ مُؤَذِّنٌ اَیَّتُہَا الۡعِیۡرُ اِنَّکُمۡ لَسٰرِقُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then a crier announced, \"O caravan people! Indeed, you are thieves.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 2150,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Caravan",
      "hw": "قافلہ",
      "s": "« » a mounted caravan on camels or horses. (1 verse: 8:42)",
      "d": "« » means to ride. And « » means riding. And « » means rider. However, in common usage, the word « » has become specific to camel riders (muf). The plural of « » is «  ,  » and « » (manjad). And « » means a caravan of horse riders or camel riders.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ اَنۡتُمۡ بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ ہُمۡ  بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الۡقُصۡوٰی وَ الرَّکۡبُ اَسۡفَلَ  مِنۡکُمۡ»\nTranslation: When you were on the near side of the valley, and they were on the far side, and the caravan was below you."
    }
  ],
  "464": [
    {
      "id": 2151,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Grave",
      "hw": "قبر",
      "s": "« » is general for a burial place, whether its markers are present or not. (7 verses: 9:84-22:7-35:22-60:13-80:21-82:4-100:9)",
      "d": "« » means the place where a dead person is buried in the earth. It is a well-known word, and its plural is « ». And a cemetery (maqbara) is also used in the same meaning, and its plural is maqabir. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تُصَلِّ عَلٰۤی اَحَدٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّاتَ اَبَدًا وَّ لَا تَقُمۡ عَلٰی قَبۡرِہٖ»\nTranslation: And do not ever pray [the funeral prayer] over any of them who dies, nor stand by his grave."
    },
    {
      "id": 2152,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Grave",
      "hw": "قبر",
      "s": "« » means a place of sleep, a resting place. (Metaphorically) used for grave, tomb. (1 verse: 36:52)",
      "d": "« » means to sleep a light and long sleep. And « » means a place to rest for a long sleep. A resting place. A place of sleep. This word has been used metaphorically for the grave because the disbelievers will equate the hardship of the Hereafter with the hardship of the grave, calling it a state of rest.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰوَیۡلَنَا مَنۡۢ بَعَثَنَا مِنۡ مَّرۡقَدِنَا»\nTranslation: They [the disbelievers] will say, \"O woe to us! Who has raised us from our resting places?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 2153,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Grave",
      "hw": "قبر",
      "s": "« » specifically a burial place whose traces are no longer present. (3 verses: 36:51-54:7-70:43)",
      "d": "Although some linguists have not made a clear distinction between « » and « ». However, from the study of the Quran, it is known that the word grave (« ») is general, while « » is that grave whose traces have also vanished. Moreover, sometimes it happens that a body is eaten by a wild animal. Sometimes a person drowns in the sea, and sea creatures consume it. Hindus cremate their dead and immerse the ashes in the Ganges. Whatever the case, when the particles of that body are eventually transferred and mix into the earth, that is its « ». And its plural is « ». This word appears twice in the Quran, and both times it is for occasions where the very concept of grave markers is impossible.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یَخۡرُجُوۡنَ  مِنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ سِرَاعًا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اِلٰی نُصُبٍ یُّوۡفِضُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: On that Day they will emerge from the graves in haste, as if they were racing to a goalpost.\nThis verse mentions the Day of Resurrection when all traces of graves will have vanished. Another verse also presents the same scene.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ نُفِخَ فِی الصُّوۡرِ فَاِذَا ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ  اِلٰی  رَبِّہِمۡ  یَنۡسِلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And the Trumpet will be blown; then they will emerge from the graves in haste toward their Lord."
    }
  ],
  "466": [
    {
      "id": 2157,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "« » means lineages, such as the offspring of one man, then the offspring of that offspring, eventually forming a single entity. (1 verse: 49:13)",
      "d": "« » refers to the offspring of one man, then his offspring, and their offspring. Eventually, it forms a single entity. In Arabic, this is called « », and « » also refers to branches. Its plural is « ». The meanings of « » are fundamentally two: (1) separation, i.e., division, and (2) gathering. That is, something that eventually divides into many parts, but its origin and foundation are one, and it is also a gathering (m.l.)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2158,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "« » means brotherhoods, communities. Groups of people of one lineage, nations, many groups. (1 verse: 49:13)",
      "d": "«قَبَائِل» «قَبِیْلَہ» «شَعْب» «قَبَائِلُ الرَّأس»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنٰکُمۡ شُعُوۡبًا وَّ قَبَآئِلَ لِتَعَارَفُوۡا ؕ اِنَّ  اَکۡرَمَکُمۡ  عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ  اَتۡقٰکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And We have made you into nations and tribes that you may know one another. Indeed, the most noble of you in the sight of Allah is the most righteous of you.\nNote: (By 'tribes' is meant a group of people who, while living within a state, follow a distinct way of life. They have their own specific laws and customs. They reside within their specific territories but are not subject to any law of the state. Globally, the number of tribes is around 150 million, which is about 40% of the world's population.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2159,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "« » means family or clan. (1 verse: 70:13)",
      "d": "« » means family. Clan. One's own family of a single individual. Members of one household. The people of the house. A small tribe that includes his wife, sons, daughters, siblings, father, mother, etc. (f l 206)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَوَدُّ  الۡمُجۡرِمُ لَوۡ  یَفۡتَدِیۡ مِنۡ عَذَابِ یَوۡمِئِذٍۭ بِبَنِیۡہِ وَ صَاحِبَتِہٖ وَ اَخِیۡہِ وَ فَصِیۡلَتِہِ الَّتِیۡ تُـئۡوِیۡہِ»\nTranslation: The criminal will wish that he could be ransomed from the punishment of that Day by his children, his wife, his brothers, and even the entire family that had sheltered him."
    },
    {
      "id": 2160,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "« » refers to a small group of young men from a tribe, numbering between 3 and 9 (3 verses: 11:91, 11:92, 27:48).",
      "d": "«رَھْط» «رَھْط» «رَھْط» «خَمْسَۃُ رَھْطٍ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ یٰقَوۡمِ اَرَہۡطِیۡۤ اَعَزُّ  عَلَیۡکُمۡ  مِّنَ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: Shu'aib (AS) said, 'O my people! Is the pressure of my brothers upon you mightier than Allah?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2161,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "« » is a small tribe consisting of male relatives (5 verses: 4:19, 9:24, 22:13, 26:214, 58:22).",
      "d": "« » means to live together (ML), and « » refers to this small tribe comprising only male relatives, such as sons, daughters, father, grandfather, uncles, aunts, etc. (FL 206).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡذِرۡ عَشِیۡرَتَکَ  الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: 'And warn your nearest kinsfolk.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2162,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Tribe and Family",
      "hw": "خاندان",
      "s": "« » means grandsons and granddaughters; if this term is attributed to the Jews, it refers to a tribe (5 verses: 2:136, 2:140, 3:84, 4:163, 7:160).",
      "d": "« » means descendants of descendants, e.g., grandsons and granddaughters (MF). However, this term is more specific to the descendants of daughters. Similarly, « » is specific to grandsons (Al-Munjid). If this term is attributed to the Jews, it refers to a tribe (Al-Munjid). According to the scholar of language, the status of a tribe that Banu Ismail holds is the same as the status of « » in Banu Ishaq (FL 25). In the Quran, the term « » appears for the tribes of Banu Ishaq.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَطَّعۡنٰہُمُ اثۡنَتَیۡ عَشۡرَۃَ  اَسۡبَاطًا اُمَمًا»\nTranslation: 'And We divided them into twelve tribes, communities.'"
    }
  ],
  "467": [
    {
      "id": 2164,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Killing",
      "hw": "قتل",
      "s": "« » means to kill someone unjustly (2 verses: 2:30, 2:84).",
      "d": "« » means to shed blood or water. « » means a liar, and « » means a bloodshedder (MF, MR). This word is generally used to mean killing someone unjustly.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَتَجۡعَلُ فِیۡہَا مَنۡ یُّفۡسِدُ فِیۡہَا وَ یَسۡفِکُ الدِّمَآءَ»\nTranslation: The angels said, 'Will You place upon it one who causes corruption therein and sheds blood?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2166,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Killing",
      "hw": "قتل",
      "s": "« » means to kill without restraint and to continue killing as much as possible (2 verses: 8:67, 47:4).",
      "d": "«ثَخَنَ» «ثَخُنَ» «اَثْخَنَ فِیْ الْاَرْض» «اَثْخَنَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا  لَقِیۡتُمُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا فَضَرۡبَ الرِّقَابِ ؕ حَتّٰۤی  اِذَاۤ  اَثۡخَنۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ فَشُدُّوا الۡوَثَاقَ»\nTranslation: 'When you meet the disbelievers, strike their necks until, when you have inflicted severe casualties upon them, bind them firmly.'"
    }
  ],
  "468": [
    {
      "id": 2168,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Step",
      "hw": "قدم",
      "s": "« » is the distance covered by two steps. And « » means initiatives (STEPS) (4 verses: 2:168, 2:208, 6:142, 24:21).",
      "d": "«خُطُوَۃ» «خُطُوَات» «خُطُوَات لَازِمَہ» «خُطُوَات»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ لَا تَتَّبِعُوۡا خُطُوٰتِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ»\nTranslation: 'And do not follow the footsteps of Satan.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2169,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Step",
      "hw": "قدم",
      "s": "« » means a footprint; a sign of the path (16 verses: 5:46, 18:6, 18:64, 20:84, 20:96, 30:50, 36:12, 37:70, 40:21, 40:82, 43:22, 43:23, 46:4, 48:29, 57:27, 100:4).",
      "d": "«اَثَر» «اٰثَار» «اٰثَار» «آثار قدیمہ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ ذٰلِکَ مَا کُنَّا نَبۡغِ ٭ۖ فَارۡتَدَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمَا قَصَصًا»\nTranslation: [Musa (AS)] said, 'That is what we have been seeking.' So they turned back, retracing their footsteps."
    }
  ],
  "469": [
    {
      "id": 2170,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Settle",
      "hw": "قرار",
      "s": "« » means to settle in a place, to become established, to reside (8 verses: 19:26, 20:40, 25:74, 28:9, 28:13, 32:17, 33:33, 33:51).",
      "d": "« » means to settle in a place. It also means to become cool. There is a connection between these two meanings: coldness or coolness also seeks tranquility, just as heat and motion seek movement (MF).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَرۡنَ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُنَّ وَ لَا تَبَرَّجۡنَ تَبَرُّجَ الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی»\nTranslation: 'And stay in your houses and do not display yourselves as [was] the display of the former times of ignorance.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2171,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Settle",
      "hw": "قرار",
      "s": "«اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی»",
      "d": "«اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» «قَرَّ» «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اسۡتَوَتۡ عَلَی الۡجُوۡدِیِّ»\nTranslation: That is, the ship of Nuh (AS) came to rest on Mount Judi.\nAlso, Allah says:\n«فَاِذَا اسۡتَوَیۡتَ اَنۡتَ وَ مَنۡ مَّعَکَ عَلَی الۡفُلۡکِ»\nTranslation: 'When you and those with you are settled aboard the ship.'\nSimilarly, at another place, Allah says:\n«ثُمَّ اسۡتَوٰی عَلَی الۡعَرۡشِ»\nTranslation: 'Then He settled above the Throne.'"
    }
  ],
  "470": [
    {
      "id": 2172,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Various Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "« » means the Book that is recited repeatedly, frequently, and always (referring to the Noble Quran) (69 verses: 2:185, 4:82, 5:101, 6:19, 7:204, 9:111, 10:15, 10:37, 10:61, 12:2, 12:3, 13:31, 15:1, 15:87, 15:91, 16:98, 17:9, 17:41, 17:45, 17:46, 17:60, 17:78, 17:82, 17:88, 17:89, 17:106, 18:54, 20:2, 20:113, 20:114, 25:30, 25:32, 27:1, 27:6, 27:76, 27:92, 28:85, 30:58, 34:31, 36:2, 36:69, 38:1, 39:27, 39:28, 41:3, 41:26, 41:44, 42:7, 43:3, 43:31, 46:29, 47:24, 50:1, 50:45, 54:17, 54:22, 54:32, 54:40, 55:2, 56:77, 59:21, 72:1, 73:4, 73:20, 75:17, 75:18, 76:23, 84:21, 85:21).",
      "d": "« » means to read. « » is the intensive form (ism mubalaghah), meaning the Book that is recited repeatedly, frequently, and always.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قٓ ۟ ۚ  وَ الۡقُرۡاٰنِ  الۡمَجِیۡدِ »\nTranslation: Qaf. By the Glorious Quran."
    },
    {
      "id": 2173,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Different Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "«Furqan» is a book that distinguishes between truth and falsehood (7 verses: 2:53, 2:185, 3:4, 8:29, 8:41, 21:48, 25:1)",
      "d": "«Faraq» means to separate, to distinguish. It is an intensive form (ism mubalaghah). Meaning a book that discerns and distinguishes every single aspect of truth and falsehood.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Tabarakalladhi nazzalal-furqana 'ala 'abdih» (25:1)\nTranslation: Blessed is He who sent down the Criterion (Furqan) upon His Servant."
    },
    {
      "id": 2174,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Different Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "«Dhikr» means to remember and to be reminded (181 verses: 2:114, 2:221, 2:269, 2:282, 3:7, 3:58, 5:13, 5:14, 5:91, 6:44, 6:68, 6:69, 6:70, 6:80, 6:90, 6:118, 6:119, 6:121, 6:126, 6:138, 6:152, 7:2, 7:3, 7:26, 7:57, 7:63, 7:69, 7:130, 7:165, 7:201, 8:2, 8:57, 9:126, 10:3, 11:24, 11:30, 11:114, 11:120, 12:42, 12:104, 13:19, 13:28, 14:5, 14:25, 14:52, 15:6, 15:9, 16:13, 16:17, 16:43, 16:44, 16:90, 17:41, 17:46, 18:28, 18:57, 18:70, 18:83, 18:101, 19:2, 20:3, 20:14, 20:34, 20:42, 20:44, 20:99, 20:113, 20:124, 21:2, 21:7, 21:10, 21:24, 21:42, 21:48, 21:50, 21:84, 21:105, 22:35, 23:71, 23:85, 23:110, 24:1, 24:27, 24:37, 25:18, 25:29, 25:50, 25:62, 25:73, 26:5, 26:209, 26:227, 27:62, 28:43, 28:46, 28:51, 29:45, 29:51, 32:4, 32:15, 32:22, 33:34, 33:41, 35:37, 36:11, 36:19, 36:69, 37:3, 37:13, 37:155, 37:168, 38:1, 38:8, 38:29, 38:32, 38:43, 38:46, 38:49, 38:87, 39:9, 39:21, 39:22, 39:23, 39:27, 39:45, 40:13, 40:54, 40:58, 41:41, 43:5, 43:36, 43:44, 44:13, 44:58, 45:23, 47:18, 47:20, 50:8, 50:37, 50:45, 51:49, 51:55, 52:29, 53:29, 54:17, 54:22, 54:25, 54:32, 54:40, 56:62, 56:73, 57:16, 58:19, 62:9, 63:9, 65:10, 68:51, 68:52, 69:12, 69:42, 69:48, 72:17, 73:19, 74:31, 74:49, 74:54, 74:55, 74:56, 76:29, 77:5, 79:43, 80:4, 80:11, 80:12, 81:27, 87:9, 87:10, 88:21, 89:23, 94:4, 79:35)",
      "d": "«Dhikr» and «Tadhkirah»: The opposite of «zakara» (to remember) is «nasiya» (to forget). «Zakara» means to remember and to be reminded, which is the opposite of forgetting. The Quran is called «Dhikr» because it reminds humanity of their innate natural inclination towards good and the covenant of «Alast». Therefore, it is also an admonition. And «Tadhkirah» means both admonition and a reminder in this sense. Also, a ticket for a ride, like a train or airplane, is called «tadhkirah». And a certificate and passport are also called that (Quranic usage).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«A unzila 'alihil-dhikru min baynina» (38:8)\nTranslation: Has the Reminder (Admonition) been sent down upon him from among us?\nFurthermore, Allah the Exalted says:\n«Inna hathihi tadhkirah» (73:19)\nTranslation: Indeed, this Quran is an admonition."
    },
    {
      "id": 2175,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Different Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "«Kitabun Mubin» means the clear and luminous book, referring to the Noble Quran (12 verses: 5:15, 6:59, 10:61, 11:6, 12:1, 26:2, 27:1, 27:75, 28:2, 34:3, 43:2, 44:2)",
      "d": "«Bana» means to become distant and separate. «Bayyin» contains three meanings: (1) separation, (2) distance, (3) clarity and lucidity. And «bayyana» means to explain something by clarifying it. And «Kitabun Mubin» means a book in which every matter related to guidance is explained with full clarification and exposition. The clear and luminous book, meaning the Noble Quran.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Qad ja'akum minallahi nurun wa kitabun mubin» (5:15)\nTranslation: There has come to you from Allah a light and a clear Book."
    },
    {
      "id": 2176,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Different Names of the Quran",
      "hw": "قرآن",
      "s": "«Hadith» means the appearance of something new (28 verses: 4:42, 4:78, 4:87, 4:140, 6:68, 7:185, 12:6, 12:21, 12:101, 12:111, 18:6, 20:9, 23:44, 31:6, 33:53, 34:19, 39:23, 45:6, 51:24, 52:34, 53:59, 56:81, 66:3, 68:44, 77:50, 79:15, 85:17, 88:1)",
      "d": "«Hadatha» means the appearance of something new. Its opposite is «'adam», meaning non-existence, disappearance. And «Hadith» refers to every matter that did not exist before and appears anew. Something new.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«La'allaAllaha yuhdithu ba'da thalika amran» (65:1)\nTranslation: Perhaps Allah will bring about after that a new matter.\nThen, the term «Hadith» is also applied to anything that existed before but had faded from people's minds over time. If it is revived anew, then it is also called «Hadith». Something new. The Quran is called «Hadith» in these very meanings.\nFor example: Allah the Exalted says:\n«Allahu nazzala ahsanal-hadith» (39:23)\nTranslation: Allah has sent down the best statement (Hadith)."
    }
  ],
  "471": [
    {
      "id": 2177,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Sacrificial Animal",
      "hw": "قربانی",
      "s": "«Budn» refers to the sacrificial camels that are slaughtered during Hajj (1 verse: 22:36)",
      "d": "«Budn» is the plural of «budnah». And «badan» refers to the body of every living creature, provided its blood has not dried up (Fal 115). And «badana» and «baddana» mean to be fat. And «budn» means sacrificial camels that are taken to Makkah to be slaughtered (Mufradat). And sacrificial camels are also called «budn» due to their large bodies and fatness (Mufradat).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«W-al-budna ja'alnahā lakum min sha'a'irillah» (22:36)\nTranslation: And We have made the sacrificial camels among the symbols of Allah for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2178,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Sacrificial Animal",
      "hw": "قربانی",
      "s": "«Nusuk» refers to every type of animal that is slaughtered in Mina (2 verses: 2:196, 6:162)",
      "d": "The word «nasak» implies worship and seeking closeness to Allah. «Nasik» means an ascetic. And «nasiykah» is the term for a sacrificial animal offered to seek closeness to Allah (M. L.). And «nusuk» is the plural of «nasiykah». Then this word became generally associated with Hajj. «Manasikul-Hajj» means the rites and rulings of Hajj. And also the places where these rulings are performed. Similarly, «nusuk» refers to those sacrificial animals that are slaughtered at the place of Mina during the days of Tashriq.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Faman kāna minkum maridan aw bihi adhan min ra'sihi fa-fidyatun min siyamin aw sadaqatin aw nusukin» (2:196)\nTranslation: Then whoever among you is ill or has an ailment of the head (and must shave his head before the sacrifice), then an expiation by fasting, charity, or sacrifice (nusuk) is due."
    },
    {
      "id": 2179,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Sacrificial Animal",
      "hw": "قربانی",
      "s": "«Hady» is the sacrificial animal that the pilgrim takes with him for slaughter (5 verses: 2:196, 5:2, 5:95, 5:97, 48:25)",
      "d": "«Hady» is the plural of «hadyah». It means the sacrificial animal that is sent towards the Sacred House for slaughter, whether it is a camel, cow, or sheep, and whether it is male or female (Manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Wa la tahliqu ru'usakum hatta yablugha al-hadyu mahillah» (2:196)\nTranslation: And do not shave your heads until the sacrificial animal (had-y) reaches its place of slaughter."
    },
    {
      "id": 2180,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Sacrificial Animal",
      "hw": "قربانی",
      "s": "«Qala'id» refers to those sacrificial animals on which a collar or band has been placed (2 verses: 5:2, 5:97)",
      "d": "«Qala'id» is the plural of «qaladah» and «qallada». It means to put a necklace on someone's neck. And «qaladah» means a necklace (Manjad). Then «qaladah» also refers to a sacrificial animal on which a collar or band has been placed as a sign, whether it is related to Hajj or fulfilling a vow.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Ya ayyuhalladhina amanu la tuhillu sha'a'irillah wa la ash-shahral-harama wa la al-hadya wa la al-qala'id» (5:2)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, do not violate the rites of Allah, nor the sacred month, nor the sacrificial animals, nor the garlands (qala'id) [marking them as sacrificial]."
    }
  ],
  "472": [
    {
      "id": 2182,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Oath. Taking an Oath",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "The word «Yamin» is used for taking an oath, and for removing an accusation, and for strengthening a covenant and pledge (19 verses: 2:224, 2:225, 3:77, 5:53, 5:89, 5:108, 6:109, 9:12, 9:13, 16:38, 16:91, 16:92, 16:94, 24:53, 35:42, 58:16, 63:2, 66:2, 68:39)",
      "d": "«Yamin» comes in the context of clearing oneself from blame.\nA Prophetic Hadith states: «Al-bayyina 'ala al-mudda'i wa al-yamin 'ala al-mudda'i 'alayh» (Sunan Tirmidhi: Hadith 1341)\nTranslation: Abdullah ibn 'Amr (may Allah be pleased with them both) reported that the Messenger of Allah (peace be upon him) said in his sermon: \"The burden of proof is on the claimant, and the oath is on the one who denies (the claim).\"\nMeaning: Presenting evidence is the responsibility of the claimant (the one making the claim). And if they cannot do that, then the oath is upon the one against whom the claim is made.\nAnd «Yamin» also means the right hand. It was the custom of the Arabs that when someone wanted to strengthen a promise or pledge with an oath, the person taking the oath would place their right hand on the other's hand. Hence, the word «Yamin» began to be used for an oath. Its plural is «Ayman» (Mufradat). The word «Yamin» is a borrowed (musta'arah) term for an oath (Faqih 43).\nThen sometimes the Arabs would also place hand over hand merely to add emphasis in speech and take an oath, but it had no relation to reality. Allah the Exalted has declared such oaths as vain and forgivable. And an oath that is in fact based on reality is called «Yamin Mu'niqadah», which is enforceable.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«La yu'akhidhukumullahu bil-lagwi fi aymanikum wa la-yu'akhidhukum bima kasabat qulubukum» (2:225)\nTranslation: Allah will not call you to account for what is unintentional in your oaths, but He will call you to account for what your hearts have earned (i.e., intentional oaths)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2184,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Oath. Taking an Oath",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "«Aliyah» is used for swearing an oath to avoid doing a good deed (1 verse: 24:22)",
      "d": "«Ala (ya'lu aylan)» has essentially two meanings: (1) to be neglectful in a matter and to procrastinate.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«La ya'lunakum khabalan» (3:118)\nTranslation: They will not spare any effort to cause you corruption.\n(2) To take an oath. And «Aliyah» means an oath. An oath that causes trouble and hardship to the one taking it (Mufradat). And according to Ibn al-Faris, it is an oath not to do a good deed (M. L.).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«Wa la ya'tili ulul-fadli minkum was-sa'ati an yu'tu ulil-qurba wal-masakin» (24:22)\nTranslation: And let not those among you who are blessed with means and wealth swear not to give [aid] to their relatives, the poor, and the emigrants for the cause of Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2185,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Oath. Taking an oath.",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "« » Taking an oath to sever relations with one's wife (1 verse: 2:226)",
      "d": "«آلاء یؤلوا إیلاءً»\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«لِلَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡلُوۡنَ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِہِمۡ تَرَبُّصُ اَرۡبَعَۃِ اَشۡہُرٍ»\nTranslation: Those who take an oath to sever relations with their wives must wait for four months."
    },
    {
      "id": 2186,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Breaking an oath.",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "« » is a common and well-known word for breaking an oath (6 verses: 7:135-9:12-9:13-16:92-43:50-48:10)",
      "d": "« » is a common and well-known word for breaking an oath. Breaking the oath of a contract, sale, or covenant, etc. (dictionary)\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اَلَا تُقَاتِلُوۡنَ قَوۡمًا نَّکَثُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: Will you not fight a people who broke their oaths?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2187,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Breaking an oath.",
      "hw": "قسم",
      "s": "« » To render an oath ineffective and ruined through tricks and excuses (9 verses: 2:27-4:155-5:13-8:56-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:92-18:77)",
      "d": "«نَقَضَ» «نَقْضَ الْبَنَاء» «نَقَضَ الْحَبْل» «نَقَّضَ الْعَھْد وَ الْاَمْر» «نَقَّضَ الْاَمْن» «نَقَّضَ» «نَکَثَ»\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَنۡقُضُوا الۡاَیۡمَانَ بَعۡدَ تَوۡکِیۡدِہَا»\nTranslation: And do not break the oaths after their confirmation."
    }
  ],
  "473": [
    {
      "id": 2189,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Fortress",
      "hw": "قلعہ",
      "s": "« » means fortress, a secure place. « » is a fortress that is surrounded and where protection and refuge are arranged (1 Verse: 59:2)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « », meaning a fortress that is surrounded and where protection and refuge are arranged. And it refers to any place where one can find safety (M. L.). Fortresses that also have trenches, so one can take refuge there, protect oneself, and also confront the enemy.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ظَنُّوۡۤا أَنَّہُمۡ مَّانِعَتُہُمۡ حُصُوۡنُہُمۡ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: And they [the Jews] thought that their fortresses would protect them from Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2190,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Fortress",
      "hw": "قلعہ",
      "s": "« » Meaning fortresses, places of refuge. Any thing that can be used for one's defense and protection. (1 verse: 33:26)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « », meaning any such thing through which one can protect oneself. Even a cow's horn is called « » because it protects itself (singular). Meaning: places of protection or fortresses. Any fortress-like thing. The war fortresses of the Jews.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡزَلَ الَّذِیۡنَ ظَاہَرُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ مِنۡ صَیَاصِیۡہِمۡ وَ قَذَفَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمُ الرُّعۡبَ»\nTranslation: And Allah brought down those among the People of the Book who had supported the disbelievers from their fortresses and cast terror into their hearts."
    },
    {
      "id": 2191,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Fortress",
      "hw": "قلعہ",
      "s": "« » Some tall, strong, and dome-shaped building (4 verses: 4:78-15:16-25:61-85:1)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « », meaning to be visible, to be high. And « » means to build a tower. And « » means any tall building with a dome, such as a fortress, domed palace, etc. (dictionary)\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اَیۡنَ مَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا یُدۡرِکۡکُّمُ الۡمَوۡتُ وَ لَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ  فِیۡ  بُرُوْجٍ مُّشَیَّدَۃٍ»\nTranslation: Wherever you are, death will overtake you, even if you are in fortified towers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2192,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Fortress",
      "hw": "قلعہ",
      "s": "« » are places where war-related matters are decided and which are also secure (5 Verses: 3:37-3:39-19:11-34:13-38:21)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». It means the beginning part of a house, the head of a council, the place where people gather. And « » also means a warrior, a fighter, and a brave person (Majid). And any place where war plans or preparations are made, or where fighting can occur. Therefore, it also comes in the meanings of fortress (M. Q).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ لَہٗ مَا یَشَآءُ مِنۡ مَّحَارِیۡبَ وَ تَمَاثِیۡلَ»\nTranslation: They [the jinn] worked for him [Sulaiman] as he desired, [building] fortresses and statues."
    }
  ],
  "474": [
    {
      "id": 2193,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Shirt",
      "hw": "قمیص",
      "s": "« » Meaning clothing, shirt (6 verses: 12:18-12:25-12:26-12:27-12:28-12:93)",
      "d": "« » means clothing, shirt.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ  کَانَ  قَمِیۡصُہٗ  قُدَّ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ فَکَذَبَتۡ»\nTranslation: And if his shirt is torn from the back, then she has lied."
    },
    {
      "id": 2194,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Shirt",
      "hw": "قمیص",
      "s": "« » A shirt or any garment that is worn (2 verses: 14:50-16:81)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». It is used for both shirt and pajama. And according to the author of Munjid, it means a shirt or any garment that is worn (dictionary).\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَّ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ سَرَابِیۡلَ تَقِیۡکُمُ  الۡحَرَّ»\nTranslation: And He has made for you garments that protect you from the heat."
    }
  ],
  "475": [
    {
      "id": 2195,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Giving strength",
      "hw": "قوت",
      "s": "« » To help someone by providing ample strength (9 verses: 2:87-2:253-5:110-8:26-8:62-9:40-38:17-58:22-61:14)",
      "d": "« » means intense strength (singular). And « » means to provide abundant help to someone and to strengthen them, to support.\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَاَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ سَکِیۡنَتَہٗ عَلَیۡہِ وَ اَیَّدَہٗ  بِجُنُوۡدٍ لَّمۡ تَرَوۡہَا»\nTranslation: Then Allah sent down His tranquility upon him and supported him with armies you did not see."
    },
    {
      "id": 2196,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Empower",
      "hw": "قوت",
      "s": "« » inherently means to give strength to something from one's own essence and make it strong (1 verse: 48:29)",
      "d": "«اَلْاِزْر» «اَلْاِزَار» «اٰزَرَ الْبَنَات» «اَزَّرَ» «اٰزَرَ»\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«کَزَرۡعٍ اَخۡرَجَ شَطۡئَہٗ فَاٰزَرَہٗ فَاسۡتَغۡلَظَ فَاسۡتَوٰی عَلٰی سُوۡقِہٖ یُعۡجِبُ الزُّرَّاعَ لِیَغِیۡظَ بِہِمُ الۡکُفَّارَ»\nTranslation: Like a crop that produces its shoot, then strengthens it, then it becomes thick, then stands upright on its stem in a way that delights the farmers, so that Allah may ignite the hearts of the disbelievers through their progress."
    },
    {
      "id": 2197,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To Empower",
      "hw": "قوت",
      "s": "« » means to give such strength to a subordinate (underling) that they are no longer subordinate (1 verse: 36:14)",
      "d": "« » means honor, and its opposite is « » meaning humiliation. And « » also means being independent, i.e., not being under someone's authority. And « » means to grant honor to someone. And « » means to give such strength or assistance to a subordinate that they become respected in society and attain honor. And honor is a state that protects a person from being subordinate or defeated (as per 'Mufradat' and 'Minjad').\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اِذۡ  اَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہِمُ  اثۡنَیۡنِ  فَکَذَّبُوۡہُمَا فَعَزَّزۡنَا بِثَالِثٍ»\nTranslation: When We sent two (messengers) to them, they denied them, so We strengthened them with a third."
    }
  ],
  "476": [
    {
      "id": 2198,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "« » means that which is established in every way (70 verses: 2:85-2:113-2:174-2:212-3:55-3:77-3:161-3:180-3:185-3:194-4:87-4:109-4:141-4:159-5:14-5:36-5:64-6:12-7:32-7:167-7:172-10:60-10:93-11:60-11:98-11:99-16:25-16:27-16:92-16:124-17:13-17:58-17:62-17:97-18:105-19:95-20:100-20:101-20:124-21:47-22:9-22:17-22:69-23:16-25:69-28:41-28:42-28:61-28:71-28:72-29:13-29:25-32:25-35:14-39:15-39:24-39:31-39:47-39:60-39:67-41:40-42:45-45:17-45:26-46:5-58:7-60:3-68:39-75:1-75:6)",
      "d": "« » means that which is established in every way. A day or era that will be established to fulfill the demands of truth and justice. Due to the various states and distinctions of that era, the Quran mentions various names for the Day of Resurrection.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«کُلُّ نَفۡسٍ ذَآئِقَۃُ الۡمَوۡتِ ؕ وَ اِنَّمَا تُوَفَّوۡنَ اُجُوۡرَکُمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ»\nTranslation: Every soul shall taste death, and you will be given your full recompense only on the Day of Resurrection."
    },
    {
      "id": 2199,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "« » means a specific hour, moment, time (36 verses: 6:31-6:40-7:187-12:107-15:85-16:77-18:21-18:36-19:75-20:15-21:49-22:1-22:7-22:55-25:11-30:12-30:14-30:55-31:34-33:63-34:3-40:46-40:59-41:47-41:50-42:17-42:18-43:61-43:66-43:85-45:27-45:32-47:18-54:1-54:46-79:42)",
      "d": "« » means hour. And « » means a specific hour. In the Quran, « » generally refers to the hour when the trumpet will be blown for the first time.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ  بَغۡتَۃً  قَالُوۡا یٰحَسۡرَتَنَا عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡنَا فِیۡہَا»\nTranslation: Until when the Hour comes upon them suddenly, they will say: 'Alas for us for what we neglected therein!'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2200,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«یَوْمُ الدِّیْن»",
      "d": "«یَوْمُ الدِّیْن»\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«مٰلِکِ یَوۡمِ الدِّیۡنِ»\nTranslation: The Master of the Day of Recompense."
    },
    {
      "id": 2201,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«یَوْمُ الْخُرُوْج»",
      "d": "«یَوْمُ الْخُرُوْج»\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«یَّوۡمَ  یَسۡمَعُوۡنَ الصَّیۡحَۃَ  بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ ذٰلِکَ یَوۡمُ  الۡخُرُوۡجِ»\nTranslation: The Day they will hear the cry in truth, that is the Day of coming forth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2202,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«یَوْمُ الْحِسَاب»",
      "d": "«یَوْمُ الْحِسَاب»\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اِنَّ  اِلَیۡنَاۤ  اِیَابَہُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِنَّ  عَلَیۡنَا حِسَابَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: Indeed, to Us is their return, then indeed, upon Us is their account.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا عَجِّلۡ  لَّنَا قِطَّنَا قَبۡلَ یَوۡمِ  الۡحِسَابِ»\nTranslation: And they say: 'Our Lord, hasten for us our share [of the punishment] before the Day of Account.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2203,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«یَوْمُ الْفَصْل»",
      "d": "«یَوْمُ الْفَصْل»\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«ہٰذَا یَوۡمُ الۡفَصۡلِ ۚ جَمَعۡنٰکُمۡ وَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: This is the Day of Separation; We have gathered you and the former [peoples]."
    },
    {
      "id": 2204,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "« » means one thing enveloping or covering another (2 verses: 12:107-88:1)",
      "d": "« » refers to a state where a person's senses are lost. And « » means that thing whose awe will envelop everyone. That which causes loss of senses.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«ہَلۡ  اَتٰىکَ حَدِیۡثُ  الۡغَاشِیَۃِ»\nTranslation: Has there come to you the news of the Overwhelming [event]?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2205,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Resurrection and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "« » means that which is about to occur (2 verses: 56:1-69:15)",
      "d": "« » means that which will definitely happen. That which is inevitable.\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«اِذَا وَقَعَتِ الۡوَاقِعَۃُ لَیۡسَ  لِوَقۡعَتِہَا  کَاذِبَۃٌ»\nTranslation: When the Inevitable [event] befalls, there will be no denial of its having occurred."
    },
    {
      "id": 2206,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "« » that the establishment of which is demanded by truth. (3 verses: 69:1-69:2-69:3)",
      "d": "« » meaning 'necessary' and 'to be established' (source) and « » meaning that the establishment of which is demanded by truth, enduring reality.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡحَآقَّۃُ»\nTranslation: And what do you know what the Inevitable Reality is?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2207,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "« » a sound that deafens the ears. (1 verse: 80:33)",
      "d": "« » a sound that deafens the ears (source) such a harsh and shrill sound that bursts the eardrums. This quality will occur at the time of the first blowing of the trumpet.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَتِ الصَّآخَّۃُ»\nTranslation: So when the Deafening (the Day of Judgment) comes."
    },
    {
      "id": 2208,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "« » meaning near at hand, about to arrive. (2 verses: 40:18-53:57)",
      "d": "In « » the meaning of the shortness of time is found (abbreviation) as we say that the time for the train to depart has become short. And « » meaning near at hand, about to arrive.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اَنۡذِرۡہُمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡاٰزِفَۃِ»\nTranslation: And warn them of the Day that is near at hand."
    },
    {
      "id": 2209,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "« » meaning to strike one thing against another so that a sound is produced. (5 verses: 13:31-69:4-101:1-101:2-101:3)",
      "d": "«قَرَعَ» «قَرَعَ الْبَاب» «قَارِعَۃ» «قَارِعَۃ»\n«وَ مَاۤ اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡقَارِعَۃُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2210,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "The Day of Judgment and its various names",
      "hw": "قیامت",
      "s": "«طَآمَّۃُ الْکُبْرٰی»",
      "d": "«اَلطَّمُّ» «طَمَّ» «طَمَّ الْبِئْرَ» «طَامَّۃ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَتِ الطَّآمَّۃُ الۡکُبۡرٰی»\nTranslation: Then when the Great Overwhelming Calamity comes."
    }
  ],
  "477": [
    {
      "id": 2211,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Prison",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "« » meaning prison, jail. (7 verses: 12:33-12:35-12:36-12:39-12:41-12:42-12:100)",
      "d": "« » meaning prison, jail. It is a well-known word. A place where people sentenced by court are kept in confinement.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَلَبِثَ فِی السِّجۡنِ بِضۡعَ سِنِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then Joseph remained in the prison for several years."
    },
    {
      "id": 2212,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Prison",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "« » meaning to encircle, to besiege. (1 verse: 17:8)",
      "d": "« » meaning to encircle something from all sides. To besiege. And « » meaning a place of confinement for someone.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا جَہَنَّمَ لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ حَصِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: And We have made Hell a prison for the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2213,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To imprison; to make a captive",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "« » to prevent someone from disposing of their property and needs. (2 verses: 5:106-11:8)",
      "d": "«حَبَسَ» «حَبَسَ الشَّیْ» «مَحْبَسَۃ» «حَابَسَ» «حَبَسَ» «مَنَعَ عَنِ التَّصَرُّف» «مَحْبَس»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«تَحۡبِسُوۡنَہُمَا مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الصَّلٰوۃِ فَیُقۡسِمٰنِ بِاللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: You detain both of them after the prayer and they will swear by Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 2214,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To imprison; to make a captive",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "« » to take someone into one's custody by binding them, to place under arrest. (1 verse: 8:30)",
      "d": "« » meaning to bind someone with fetters (source) i.e., to prevent someone from movement by tying them up. And to keep in one's custody.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِذۡ یَمۡکُرُ بِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لِیُثۡبِتُوۡکَ اَوۡ یَقۡتُلُوۡکَ اَوۡ یُخۡرِجُوۡکَ»\nTranslation: And remember, O Muhammad, when the disbelievers were plotting against you to imprison you or kill you or expel you (from your home)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2215,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To imprison; to make a captive",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "« » to make someone a captive by binding them during battle. (4 verses: 2:85-8:67-8:70-33:26-)",
      "d": "The meaning of « » is also to tie someone with a rope (source). The difference between « » and « » is that « » is used only for capturing someone during battle. « » meaning war captive. And its plurals are « » and « ».\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّاۡتُوۡکُمۡ اُسٰرٰی تُفٰدُوۡہُمۡ وَ ہُوَ مُحَرَّمٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِخۡرَاجُہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And if they come to you as captives, you ransom them, although it was forbidden for you to expel them.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«فَرِیۡقًا تَقۡتُلُوۡنَ وَ تَاۡسِرُوۡنَ فَرِیۡقًا»\nTranslation: You killed a party of them and took another party captive."
    },
    {
      "id": 2216,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "To imprison. To make a prisoner.",
      "hw": "قید",
      "s": "« » to imprison someone as a punishment by the court after proof of crime (2 verses: 12:25-12:32).",
      "d": "«سَجَنَ» «قَالَتۡ مَا جَزَآءُ مَنۡ اَرَادَ بِاَہۡلِکَ سُوۡٓءًا اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یُّسۡجَنَ اَوۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ»"
    }
  ],
