  "487": [
    {
      "id": 2260,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "How many?",
      "hw": "کتنے",
      "s": "«Kam» This word is known in Arabic grammar as interrogative kam and informative kam (21 verses: 2:211-2:249-2:259-6:6-7:4-17:17-18:19-19:74-19:98-20:128-21:11-23:112-26:7-28:58-32:26-36:31-38:3-43:6-44:25-50:36-53:26)",
      "d": "«Kam» «قَالَ كَمْ لَبِثْتَ» «Kam» «کَمْ رَجُلاً عِنْدَکَ؟» «کَمْ کُتُب دَرَسْتُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2261,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "How many?",
      "hw": "کتنے",
      "s": "« » or « »: This Arabic term is synonymous with the interrogative « » (how many?). The difference is that « » can appear with or without « », whereas « » generally appears with « ». (7 verses: 3:146, 12:105, 22:45, 22:48, 29:60, 47:13, 65:8)",
      "d": "« » and « » are close in meaning. The only difference is that « » also conveys the sense of abundance or multitude, meaning 'how many indeed', 'so many', i.e., 'many'. It does not function as an interrogative.\n«وَ کَاَیِّنۡ مِّنۡ اٰیَۃٍ  فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ یَمُرُّوۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا»\nTranslation: 'And there are so many (numerous) signs in the heavens and the earth which they pass by.'\nSee also the entries for 'crookedness' and 'to be crooked'."
    }
  ],
  "488": [
    {
      "id": 2262,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to dig",
      "hw": "کریدنا",
      "s": "« »: to dig under the earth. (1 verse: 5:31)",
      "d": "« » means to dig, to excavate, to search for something by digging under the soil.\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ»\nTranslation: 'Then Allah sent a crow who began to dig in the earth to show him how to hide the shame of his brother.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2263,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to dig up; to exhume",
      "hw": "کریدنا",
      "s": "« »: to dig up and extract something. (2 verses: 82:4, 100:9)",
      "d": "«بُعْثِرَ» «بُعِثَ» «اُثِیْرَ» «بَعْثَرَ الْمَتَاع» «بَعثَرَہٗ»\n«اَفَلَا یَعۡلَمُ  اِذَا بُعۡثِرَ مَا فِی الۡقُبُوۡرِ»\nTranslation: 'Does he not know that when that which is in the graves is dug up (and brought forth)...'"
    }
  ],
  "489": [
    {
      "id": 2265,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "bitter",
      "hw": "کڑوا",
      "s": "« »: bitter and salty (brackish) water. (3 verses: 25:53, 35:12, 56:70)",
      "d": "«اُجَاج» «اَجَّ الْمَاءَ»\n«لَوۡ نَشَآءُ  جَعَلۡنٰہُ  اُجَاجًا فَلَوۡ لَا تَشۡکُرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: 'If We willed, We could have made it bitter. Then why are you not grateful?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2266,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "bitter; sour",
      "hw": "کڑوا",
      "s": "« »: bitter and sour (acidic), ill-tasting. (1 verse: 34:16)",
      "d": "« » means sour, acidic, and every thorny and bitter tree. « » refers to something with a bad taste.\n«وَ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ بِجَنَّتَیۡہِمۡ جَنَّتَیۡنِ ذَوَاتَیۡ  اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ»\nTranslation: 'And We replaced their two gardens with two gardens bearing bitter fruit and thorny plants.'"
    }
  ],
  "490": [
    {
      "id": 2267,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "farmer; cultivator",
      "hw": "کسان",
      "s": "« »: one who practices agriculture or tilling the land; a farmer, cultivator. (2 verses: 48:29, 56:64)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « », meaning one who tills the land, a farmer, cultivator. Its usage is general.\n«کَزَرۡعٍ  اَخۡرَجَ  شَطۡئَہٗ  فَاٰزَرَہٗ  فَاسۡتَغۡلَظَ فَاسۡتَوٰی عَلٰی سُوۡقِہٖ یُعۡجِبُ الزُّرَّاعَ»\nTranslation: 'Like a crop that has produced its shoot and thickened and stood firm on its stem, it delights the cultivators.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2268,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "farmer; cultivator (also: disbeliever)",
      "hw": "کسان",
      "s": "« »: In common usage, it refers to those who deny the truth. (1 verse: 57:20)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». « » means to conceal. « » has several meanings: (1) one who denies God, (2) one who is ungrateful for God's blessings, (3) one who conceals the truth, living in seclusion. It can also mean 'remote land', 'soil', 'plants', 'cultivator'. « » means land remote and far from people, i.e., countryside.\n«کَمَثَلِ غَیۡثٍ اَعۡجَبَ الۡکُفَّارَ نَبَاتُہٗ»\nTranslation: 'Like the growth of vegetation after rain, which delights the cultivators (or: the tillers of the land).'"
    }
  ],
  "491": [
    {
      "id": 2269,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "ship; boat",
      "hw": "کشتی",
      "s": "« »: A ship is called « » in consideration of its movement.\n« »: A ship is called « » in consideration of its being smooth and comfortable.\n« »: A ship is called « » in consideration of its being ship-shaped. (5 verses: 42:32, 55:24, 69:11, 81:16, 88:12)",
      "d": "«جَرٰی یَجْرِیْ» «جَارِیَۃ» «جَوَار»\n«وَ لَہُ  الۡجَوَارِ الۡمُنۡشَئٰتُ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ کَالۡاَعۡلَامِ»\nTranslation: 'And his are the ships, lofty on the sea like mountains.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2270,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "ship; boat",
      "hw": "کشتی",
      "s": "« »: means ship, boat. (3 verses: 18:71, 18:79, 29:15)",
      "d": "« » means to peel and make smooth. « » means a tool for scraping and smoothing. « » means an adze for splitting wood. « » means scraping tools. « » means the profession of shipbuilding. « » means ship, boat. Hence, « » refers to a ship that is made smooth and comfortable through planing and smoothing.\n«اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ»\nTranslation: 'As for the ship, it belonged to some poor people who worked on the sea.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2271,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "ship; boat",
      "hw": "کشتی",
      "s": "« »: A ship that carries both passengers and cargo. (23 verses: 2:164, 7:64, 10:22, 10:73, 11:37, 11:38, 14:32, 16:14, 17:66, 22:65, 23:22, 23:27, 23:28, 26:119, 29:65, 30:46, 31:31, 35:12, 36:41, 37:140, 40:80, 43:12, 45:12)",
      "d": "«فُلْک» «فَلْکٌ مِّنَ الْبَحْر» «فَلَک» «اَلْفَلْکَۃ» «فُلْک» «فُلْک» «مَشْحُوْن» «شَخَن» «اَلشَّحْنَۃ» «فُلْک»\n«وَ اِنَّ یوۡنُسَ لَمِنَ الۡمُرۡسَلِیۡنَ . اِذۡ  اَبَقَ  اِلَی الۡفُلۡکِ الۡمَشۡحُوۡنِ»\nTranslation: 'And indeed, Jonah was among the messengers. When he ran away to the laden ship.'"
    }
  ],
