      "hw": "کعبہ",
      "s": "«بَیْتُ الْعَتِیْق»",
      "d": "«بَیْتُ الْعَتِیْق» «عَتِیْق» «وَ لۡیَطَّوَّفُوۡا بِالۡبَیۡتِ الۡعَتِیۡقِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2275,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Different Names of the Kaaba",
      "hw": "کعبہ",
      "s": "« » refers to things from whose use Sharia has strictly prohibited. (2 verses: 28:57-29:67)",
      "d": "«حَرَم» «اَلْمَنْعُ الشَّدِیْد» «حَرَم» «حَرَام» «اَوَ لَمۡ نُمَکِّنۡ لَّہُمۡ حَرَمًا اٰمِنًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2277,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Different Names of the Kaaba",
      "hw": "کعبہ",
      "s": "«مَسْجِدُ الْحَرَام»",
      "d": "«مَسْجِدُ الْحَرَام» «سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا مِّنَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ اِلَی الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡاَقۡصَا»"
    }
  ],
  "493": [
    {
      "id": 2278,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "All",
      "hw": "کل",
      "s": "« » means any day from the past days. (4 verses: 10:24-28:18-28:19-28:82)",
      "d": "«اَمْس» «اَلْاَمْس» «اَمْس» «فَاِذَا الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ» «اَمْس» «فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا حَصِیۡدًا کَاَنۡ لَّمۡ تَغۡنَ بِالۡاَمۡسِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2279,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "All",
      "hw": "کل",
      "s": "« » means the coming next day. (15 verses: 3:121-6:52-7:205-12:12-13:15-18:23-18:28-24:36-31:34-34:12-40:46-54:26-59:18-68:22-68:25)",
      "d": "«غَدْ» «اَمْس» «اَرۡسِلۡہُ مَعَنَا غَدًا یَّرۡتَعۡ وَ یَلۡعَبۡ» «غَدًا» «وَ لۡتَنۡظُرۡ نَفۡسٌ مَّا قَدَّمَتۡ لِغَدٍ» «غَدْ»"
    }
  ],
  "494": [
    {
      "id": 2280,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Diminish. To Reduce. To Shorten.",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "« » is used in a wide sense; it comes for every type of deficiency and excess. (128 verses: 2:54-2:57-2:59-2:150-2:165-2:231-2:272-2:279-2:281-3:25-3:108-3:117-3:135-3:161-4:10-4:30-4:40-4:49-4:64-4:77-4:110-4:124-4:148-4:153-4:160-4:168-5:39-6:21-6:45-6:82-6:93-6:131-6:144-6:157-6:160-7:9-7:23-7:37-7:103-7:160-7:162-7:165-7:177-8:25-8:60-9:36-9:70-10:13-10:17-10:44-10:47-10:52-10:54-11:18-11:37-11:67-11:94-11:101-11:113-11:116-11:117-13:6-14:44-14:45-16:33-16:41-16:61-16:85-16:111-16:118-17:59-17:71-18:15-18:33-18:49-18:57-18:59-18:87-19:60-20:111-20:112-21:3-21:47-22:25-22:39-23:27-23:62-25:4-25:19-26:227-27:11-27:14-27:44-27:52-27:85-28:16-29:40-29:46-29:68-30:9-30:29-30:57-31:13-32:22-34:19-34:42-36:54-37:22-38:24-39:32-39:47-39:51-39:69-40:17-40:31-42:41-42:42-43:39-43:65-43:76-45:22-46:12-46:19-51:59-52:47-53:52-61:7-65:1)",
      "d": "«ظَلَمَ» «عَدْل» «کِلۡتَا الۡجَنَّتَیۡنِ اٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا وَ لَمۡ تَظۡلِمۡ مِّنۡہُ شَیۡئًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2281,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Diminish. To Reduce. To Shorten.",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "« » means to fall short in doing something; not to do a task as it should be done. (1 verse: 3:118)",
      "d": "«اَلَا» «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2282,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Diminish. To Reduce. To Shorten.",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "« » means not to do a task as much as it should be done; to be deficient in it. (3 verses: 4:101-7:202-48:27)",
      "d": "«قَصَرَ» «وَ اِذَا ضَرَبۡتُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ فَلَیۡسَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ جُنَاحٌ اَنۡ تَقۡصُرُوۡا مِنَ الصَّلٰوۃِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2283,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Alata» means to give less than due in wages or to delay payment (1 verse: 52:21)",
      "d": "«Alata» means to diminish from someone's right (manjada) or to diminish from wages. Not giving full recompense for work or giving it with delay. «Al-qasar wa ibta'» (m. q.)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَاۤ  اَلَتۡنٰہُمۡ  مِّنۡ عَمَلِہِمۡ  مِّنۡ شَیۡءٍ»\nTranslation: We did not diminish anything from their deeds."
    },
    {
      "id": 2284,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Hadama» means to squeeze, press, or wring a soft thing and to diminish in it, to suppress the right of the weak (2 verses: 20:112, 26:148)",
      "d": "«Hadama» means to squeeze a soft thing, to press, to wring and to diminish in it (m. l) to suppress the right of the weak. To usurp. And «hadim» means soft and delicate also (26/48) and also that which is quickly digested (m. q.)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّعۡمَلۡ مِنَ الصّٰلِحٰتِ وَ ہُوَ مُؤۡمِنٌ فَلَا یَخٰفُ ظُلۡمًا وَّ لَا ہَضۡمًا»\nTranslation: And whoever does good deeds while being a believer, will have no fear of injustice or diminishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2285,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Fatara» means that weakness causes diminishment to occur (2 verses: 21:20, 43:75)",
      "d": "«Fatara» means that weakness occurs in something (m. l) that while doing work, due to tiredness, a decrease in pace occurs or one becomes stagnant.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ فِیۡ عَذَابِ جَہَنَّمَ خٰلِدُوۡنَ لَا یُفَتَّرُ عَنۡہُمۡ»\nTranslation: The criminals will remain in the punishment of Hell forever; it will not be diminished from them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2286,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Qalla» means to decrease in number or quantity (1 verse: 18:39)",
      "d": "«Qalla» basically has two meanings: (1) to be abundant, (2) to be little. Here the second meaning is under discussion. That is, to be little in number or quantity. And its opposite is «kathura» meaning abundant. For example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ تَرَنِ  اَنَا  اَقَلَّ  مِنۡکَ  مَالًا  وَّ  وَلَدًا»\nTranslation: If you see me as less than you in wealth and children."
    },
    {
      "id": 2287,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Taffafa» means to fill a measuring container slightly less or to keep it small (1 verse: 83:1)",
      "d": "«Taffif» means insignificant and trivial thing. And «Taffafa» means to fill a measuring container a little less or to keep the container slightly small. (muf)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَیۡلٌ   لِّلۡمُطَفِّفِیۡنَ الَّذِیۡنَ  اِذَا  اکۡتَالُوۡا عَلَی النَّاسِ یَسۡتَوۡفُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Woe to the defrauders who, when they take a measure from people, take it in full."
    },
    {
      "id": 2288,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Khasira» means to incur loss in trade (25 verses: 4:119-6:12-6:20-6:31-6:140-7:9-7:53-10:45-11:21-11:22-18:103-21:70-22:11-23:103-26:181-27:5-39:15-40:78-40:85-42:45-45:27-55:9-65:9-83:3-103:2)",
      "d": "«Khasira» means to incur loss in capital (muf) this word is generally specific to trade. To incur loss. To suffer loss. And its opposite is «ramija» meaning to gain. And «khasara al-mizan» means to diminish in weight by suppressing someone's right.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا کَالُوۡہُمۡ  اَوۡ وَّزَنُوۡہُمۡ  یُخۡسِرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And when they measure or weigh for themselves, they diminish."
    },
    {
      "id": 2289,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Naqada» means to decrease, diminish; used in all kinds of contexts for deficiency (9 verses: 2:155-7:130-9:4-11:84-13:41-21:44-35:11-50:4-73:3)",
      "d": "«Naqada» means to decrease, diminish, and its opposite is «zada» meaning increase. And the opposite of «nuqsan» is «ziyada». This word is more general than «khasira». Every loss is a deficiency, but not every deficiency is a loss.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«نِّصۡفَہٗۤ  اَوِ انۡقُصۡ  مِنۡہُ  قَلِیۡلًا . اَوۡ زِدۡ  عَلَیۡہِ  وَ رَتِّلِ الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  تَرۡتِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: Half of it or a little less, or a little more. And recite the Quran with measured recitation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2290,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Bakhasa» means to give less or inferior in exchange for something good (7 verses: 2:282-7:85-11:15-11:85-12:20-26:183-72:13)",
      "d": "«Bakhs» means deficient, inferior, less (manjada). And «bakhasa» means to give deficient or less in exchange or to give little.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ شَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ»\nTranslation: And they sold him for a low price, a few dirhams.\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n«وَ لَا تَبۡخَسُوا النَّاسَ اَشۡیَآءَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And do not give people less than their due in things."
    },
    {
      "id": 2292,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to decrease, to diminish, to reduce",
      "hw": "کم",
      "s": "«Watra» means to decrease in taking or giving recompense or not to give (1 verse: 47:35)",
      "d": "«Watra» means to wrong, to cause harm. To diminish wealth or right. And «al-witr» and «al-witr» mean to take recompense or to wrong in taking recompense (manjada)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ  مَعَکُمۡ  وَ لَنۡ یَّتِرَکُمۡ   اَعۡمَالَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And Allah is with you and will never waste your deeds."
    }
  ],
  "495": [
    {
      "id": 2293,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to earn, to gain",
      "hw": "کمائی",
      "s": "«Amila» means to work generally; it also comes in the meanings of earning (309 verses: 2:25-2:62-2:74-2:82-2:85-2:96-2:110-2:134-2:139-2:140-2:141-2:144-2:149-2:167-2:217-2:233-2:234-2:237-2:265-2:271-2:277-2:283-3:22-3:30-3:57-3:98-3:99-3:120-3:153-3:156-3:163-3:180-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:57-4:94-4:108-4:110-4:122-4:123-4:124-4:128-4:135-4:173-5:5-5:8-5:9-5:53-5:62-5:66-5:69-5:71-5:90-5:93-5:105-6:43-6:54-6:60-6:88-6:108-6:122-6:127-6:132-6:135-7:42-7:43-7:53-7:118-7:129-7:139-7:147-7:153-7:180-8:39-8:47-8:48-8:72-9:9-9:16-9:17-9:37-9:69-9:94-9:102-9:105-9:120-9:121-10:4-10:9-10:12-10:14-10:23-10:41-10:61-10:81-11:7-11:11-11:15-11:16-11:23-11:46-11:78-11:92-11:93-11:111-11:112-11:121-11:123-12:19-12:69-13:29-14:18-14:23-14:42-15:93-16:28-16:32-16:34-16:63-16:93-16:96-16:97-16:111-16:119-17:9-17:84-18:2-18:7-18:30-18:49-18:79-18:88-18:103-18:105-18:107-18:110-19:60-19:96-20:75-20:82-20:112-21:27-21:74-21:82-21:94-22:14-22:23-22:50-22:56-22:68-23:51-23:63-23:100-24:24-24:28-24:38-24:39-24:53-24:55-24:64-25:23-25:70-25:71-26:112-26:168-26:169-26:188-26:216-26:227-27:4-27:19-27:24-27:84-27:90-27:93-28:15-28:55-28:67-28:80-28:84-29:4-29:7-29:8-29:9-29:38-29:55-29:58-30:15-30:41-30:44-30:45-31:8-31:15-31:23-31:29-32:12-32:14-32:17-32:19-33:2-33:9-33:19-33:31-33:71-34:4-34:11-34:12-34:13-34:25-34:33-34:37-35:7-35:8-35:10-35:37-36:35-36:54-36:71-37:39-37:61-37:96-38:24-38:28-39:7-39:35-39:39-39:65-39:70-40:37-40:40-40:58-41:5-41:8-41:20-41:22-41:27-41:33-41:40-41:46-41:50-42:15-42:22-42:23-42:26-43:72-45:15-45:21-45:28-45:29-45:30-45:33-46:14-46:15-46:16-46:19-47:1-47:2-47:4-47:8-47:9-47:12-47:14-47:28-47:30-47:32-47:33-47:35-48:11-48:24-48:29-49:2-49:14-49:18-52:16-52:19-52:21-53:31-56:24-57:4-57:10-58:3-58:6-58:7-58:11-58:13-58:15-59:18-60:3-62:8-63:2-63:11-64:2-64:7-64:8-64:9-65:11-66:7-66:11-67:2-77:43-84:25-85:11-95:6-98:7-99:6-99:7-99:8-103:3)",
      "d": "«Amila» means every action that a person intends to do is his action. And since earning is also an action, therefore it is used in those meanings.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ»\nTranslation: As for the ship, it belonged to some poor people who worked at sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 2294,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Earn; To Gain",
      "hw": "کمائی",
      "s": "« » means to do some work for the purpose of gaining benefit or profit, whether for oneself or for others (57 Verses: 2:79-2:81-2:134-2:141-2:202-2:225-2:264-2:267-2:281-2:286-3:25-3:155-3:161-4:88-4:111-4:112-5:38-6:3-6:70-6:120-6:129-6:158-6:164-7:39-7:96-9:82-9:95-10:8-10:27-10:52-13:33-13:42-14:18-14:51-15:84-18:58-30:41-31:34-35:45-36:65-39:24-39:48-39:50-39:51-40:17-40:82-41:17-42:22-42:30-42:34-45:10-45:14-45:22-52:21-74:38-83:14-111:2)",
      "d": "« » is more specific than 'action' for the purpose of earning or gaining profit or good fortune. Meaning to gain benefit or to do some work for good fortune. Whether this work is for oneself or for others. Whether this earning is good or bad, lawful or unlawful. And « » means a laborer, a wage-earner, a professional.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ السَّارِقُ وَ السَّارِقَۃُ فَاقۡطَعُوۡۤا أَیۡدِیَہُمَا جَزَآءًۢ بِمَا کَسَبَا»\nTranslation: Cut off the hands of the male and female thief as a recompense for what they earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2295,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Earn; To Gain",
      "hw": "کمائی",
      "s": "« » means to do some work for one's own benefit and profit (4 Verses: 2:286-4:32-24:11-33:58)",
      "d": "« » is the work that a human does solely keeping their own interests in mind (Muf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لِلرِّجَالِ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا اکۡتَسَبُوۡا ؕ وَ لِلنِّسَآءِ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا اکۡتَسَبۡنَ»\nTranslation: For men is a share of what they have earned, and for women is a share of what they have earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2296,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Earn; To Gain",
      "hw": "کمائی",
      "s": "« » means to do a bad deed, to earn through illicit means (4 Verses: 6:113-6:120-9:24-42:23)",
      "d": "«قَرَفَ» «اِقْتَرَف» «الاِعْتِرَافُ یَزِیْلُ الْاِقْتِرَاف» «اِقْتَرَاف»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«إِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یَکۡسِبُوۡنَ الۡاِثۡمَ سَیُجۡزَوۡنَ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَقۡتَرِفُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Indeed, those who commit sins will be recompensed for what they used to do [i.e., earn]."
    }
  ],
  "496": [
    {
      "id": 2297,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Room",
      "hw": "کمرہ",
      "s": "« » means room. (1 Verse: 49:4)",
      "d": "« » means room. Its plural is « ». And it also means a dining room (M. R.). So, « » is that small room from which the work of the whole house is done. For example, the Quran states:\n«إِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُنَادُوۡنَکَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ الۡحُجُرٰتِ»\nTranslation: Indeed, those who call you from outside the rooms..."
    },
    {
      "id": 2298,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Chamber",
      "hw": "کمرہ",
      "s": "« » meaning lofty chamber (4 verses: 25:75-29:58-34:37-39:20)",
      "d": "«غُرْفَۃ» «غُرَف» «غُرَفَات» «اُولٰٓئِکَ یُجۡزَوۡنَ الۡغُرۡفَۃَ  بِمَا صَبَرُوۡا»"
    }
  ],
  "497": [
    {
      "id": 2299,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Weak",
      "hw": "کمزور",
      "s": "« » meaning weak, old. Lacking in strength and power. (27 verses: 2:266-2:282-3:146-4:28-4:75-4:76-4:97-4:98-4:127-7:75-7:137-7:150-8:26-8:66-9:91-11:91-14:21-19:75-22:73-28:4-28:5-30:54-34:31-34:32-34:33-40:47-72:24)",
      "d": "«ضَعِیْف» «قَوِی» «ضَعْف» «ضُعْف» «ضُعَفَاء» «ضِعَاف» «فَاِنۡ کَانَ الَّذِیۡ عَلَیۡہِ الۡحَقُّ سَفِیۡہًا اَوۡ ضَعِیۡفًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2300,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Weak",
      "hw": "کمزور",
      "s": "« » weak due to decay (1 verse: 69:16)",
      "d": "«وَھِیَ» «وَھِیَ» «اَلْوَھْی» «وَ انۡشَقَّتِ السَّمَآءُ  فَہِیَ یَوۡمَئِذٍ وَّاہِیَۃٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2302,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Weak",
      "hw": "کمزور",
      "s": "« » defeated, helpless, weak and destitute people (4 verses: 3:123-5:54-27:34-27:37)",
      "d": "«اَذِلَّۃ» «ذَلِیْل» «عَزِیْز» «اِسْتَضْعَفَ» «اَوْھَنَ» «وَ لَقَدۡ نَصَرَکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِبَدۡرٍ وَّ اَنۡتُمۡ اَذِلَّۃٌ» «اَنَّ اللّٰہَ  مُوۡہِنُ کَیۡدِ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "498": [
    {
      "id": 2303,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » the ultimate limit of anything, extremity (5 verses: 3:127-11:114-13:41-20:130-21:44)",
      "d": "«طَرْف» «اَطْرَاف» «وَ اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2304,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Boundary",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » the ultimate limit of anything that separates it from other things (9 verses: 2:187-2:229-2:230-4:13-4:14-9:97-9:112-58:4-65:1)",
      "d": "«حَدَّ السِّکِّیْن» «حَدُّ السَّیْف» «حَدّ» «حَدَّ الْمَکَان» «حُدُوْدُ اللہ» «وَ مَنۡ یَّتَعَدَّ حُدُوۡدَ اللّٰہِ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الظّٰلِمُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2305,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning pointed edge (1 verse: 22:11)",
      "d": "«حَرْفُ الْجَبَل» «فُلَانٌ عَلٰی حَرْفٍ مِنْ اَمْرِہٖ»\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ مِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یَّعۡبُدُ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی حَرۡفٍ ۚ فَاِنۡ  اَصَابَہٗ  خَیۡرُۨ  اطۡمَاَنَّ بِہٖ ۚ وَ اِنۡ اَصَابَتۡہُ فِتۡنَۃُۨ  انۡقَلَبَ عَلٰی وَجۡہِہٖ»\nTranslation: And among people is he who worships Allah on the edge. Then if any good befalls him, he is content with it; but if a trial befalls him, he turns back on his face in despair."
    },
    {
      "id": 2306,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning where two round things meet at their farthest edges (3 verses: 41:53-53:7-81:23)",
      "d": "« » means for two things to meet at their farthest and ultimate limit, or to appear joined (m. l). And that joined edge is called the horizon, as in one side is earth and the other is sky. So at the farthest limit of sight where they appear to meet is the horizon. Its plural is « ». And « » means the vastness of the universe, wherein there is ample expanse and distance (muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ ہُوَ  بِالۡاُفُقِ الۡاَعۡلٰی»\nTranslation: And he (Gabriel) was at the highest horizon.\nAt another place, the Divine decree says:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: Soon We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": 2307,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning the inner edges and sides of a round object (2 verses: 33:14-55:33)",
      "d": "«قَطَرَ» «قَطَرَ الْبَعِیْرُ اِلَی الْبَعِیْر» «اَقْطَارَ الدُّنْیَا» «قَطَرَ»\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ لَوۡ دُخِلَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنۡ اَقۡطَارِہَا ثُمَّ سُئِلُوا الۡفِتۡنَۃَ  لَاٰتَوۡہَا وَ مَا تَلَبَّثُوۡا بِہَاۤ   اِلَّا  یَسِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: And if people from the edges of the city had entered upon them and they had been asked to commit treason, they would have certainly done it, and they would not have hesitated over it except a little.\nAt another place, the Divine decree says:\n«یٰمَعۡشَرَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ  اِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتُمۡ اَنۡ  تَنۡفُذُوۡا مِنۡ  اَقۡطَارِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡفُذُوۡا»\nTranslation: O company of jinn and humans, if you are able to pass through the edges of the heavens and the earth, then pass through."
    },
    {
      "id": 2308,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning the edges of a round object like a well or sky (1 verse: 69:17)",
      "d": "«اَرْجَاء» «رَجَا» «رَجَا الْبِئْر» «رَجَا السَّمَاء»\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَّ الۡمَلَکُ  عَلٰۤی  اَرۡجَآئِہَا ؕ وَ یَحۡمِلُ عَرۡشَ رَبِّکَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ یَوۡمَئِذٍ ثَمٰنِیَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And the angels will be on its edges, and on that Day, eight will bear the Throne of your Lord above them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2309,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning the edge of anything hollow and concave, where standing poses a risk of falling and destruction (2 verses: 3:103-9:109)",
      "d": "« » is a proverb for the brink of destruction. « » refers to the edge of anything that is hollow and concave inside, and standing on its edge entails a risk of falling and being destroyed (muf).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی شَفَا حُفۡرَۃٍ مِّنَ النَّارِ فَاَنۡقَذَکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا»\nTranslation: And you were on the brink of a pit of fire, and He saved you from it.\nAt another place, the Divine decree says:\n«اَمۡ مَّنۡ اَسَّسَ بُنۡیَانَہٗ عَلٰی شَفَا جُرُفٍ ہَارٍ»\nTranslation: Or [consider] he who founded his building on the brink of a collapsing pit?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2310,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning an edge that provides refuge (1 verse: 11:42)",
      "d": "« » means to withdraw, to be on one side, and to escape. In Ibn al-Faris's words, it indicates rescue, delay, and distancing (m. l). That is, « » is the edge to which one goes to be saved from a calamity.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ نَادٰی نُوۡحُۨ  ابۡنَہٗ وَ کَانَ فِیۡ  مَعۡزِلٍ یّٰـبُنَیَّ ارۡکَبۡ مَّعَنَا»\nTranslation: And Noah called his son, and he was at an isolated edge. He said, 'O my son, embark with us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2311,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning one of the two edges of a field or river (1 verse: 28:30)",
      "d": "« » means one of the two edges of something (m. l). The edge of a river or valley. One side or bank.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ  اَتٰىہَا نُوۡدِیَ مِنۡ شَاطِیَٔ الۡوَادِ الۡاَیۡمَنِ»\nTranslation: So when he reached it, he was called from the right bank of the valley."
    },
    {
      "id": 2312,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning the edge of a river or sea (1 verse: 20:39)",
      "d": "« » is specifically used for the edge of a river or sea (source).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«فَلۡیُلۡقِہِ الۡیَمُّ بِالسَّاحِلِ»\nTranslation: Then the sea will cast it onto the shore."
    },
    {
      "id": 2313,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning the opposite side's edge (5 verses: 8:42-17:1-19:22-28:20-36:20)",
      "d": "« » implies being distant and remaining far (m. l). And « » means the farthest side. The outermost edge.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ جَآءَ مِنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  رَجُلٌ یَّسۡعٰى»\nTranslation: And there came from the farthest end of the city a man running."
    },
    {
      "id": 2314,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » meaning a distant edge that is elevated (1 verse: 8:42)",
      "d": "« » means a distant traveler. And it means the edge of a valley. And « » means a high place, the edge of a valley (source). That is, « » is the edge of a valley or field that is both distant and elevated.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«اِذۡ اَنۡتُمۡ بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ ہُمۡ  بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الۡقُصۡوٰی»\nTranslation: When you were at the near edge and they were at the far edge."
    },
    {
      "id": 2315,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Edge",
      "hw": "کنارہ",
      "s": "« » the edge of a mountain (1 Verse: 18:96)",
      "d": "The open field between mountains is called a valley. The edges of the mountains that form the boundaries of this valley are called « ». Therefore, the translation of « » is also taken as the edge of the valley, but 'the edge of the mountain' is its more fitting translation. Hence, Imam Raghib states its meaning is only the edge of the mountain (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا سَاوٰی بَیۡنَ الصَّدَفَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: Until he (Dhul-Qarnayn) made the two mountain edges (the space between them) level."
    }
  ],
  "499": [
    {
      "id": 2316,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Well",
      "hw": "کنواں",
      "s": "« » meaning well (1 Verse: 22:45)",
      "d": "« » means well. It is a general term. Whether it is filled (with water) or not (FL 262). One can also call such wells wells even if they have no water (F. L 31).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ بِئۡرٍ  مُّعَطَّلَۃٍ   وَّ  قَصۡرٍ  مَّشِیۡدٍ»\nTranslation: And (many) abandoned wells and (many) ruined, splendid palaces."
    },
    {
      "id": 2317,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Well",
      "hw": "کنواں",
      "s": "« » a raw well, a well that is only dug and not built with bricks or stones (2 Verses: 12:10-12:15)",
      "d": "« » is a well that is only dug. It is not constructed with bricks or stones (F. L 262). A raw well.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَلَمَّا ذَہَبُوۡا بِہٖ  وَ  اَجۡمَعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّجۡعَلُوۡہُ  فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ  الۡجُبِّ»\nTranslation: Then when they went away with him and agreed to put him into the bottom of the well (i.e., a deep, dark well)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2318,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Well",
      "hw": "کنواں",
      "s": "« » a very large well (2 Verses: 25:38-50:12)",
      "d": "« » is a very large well (F. L 39) in which there is a plentiful amount of water (F. L 262).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«کَذَّبَتۡ قَبۡلَہُمۡ قَوۡمُ نُوۡحٍ وَّ اَصۡحٰبُ الرَّسِّ  وَ  ثَمُوۡدُ»\nTranslation: Before them, the people of Noah and the companions of the well and Thamud denied."
    }
  ],
  "500": [
    {
      "id": 2319,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Whip",
      "hw": "کوڑا",
      "s": "« » a leather whip or scourge (1 Verse: 89:13)",
      "d": "« » means a tanned hide. A whip, a scourge (Muf). And « » means to lash with a whip. And « » means a whip-holding soldier. And « » is the name for a horse that does not move without a whip (Manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَصَبَّ عَلَیۡہِمۡ رَبُّکَ سَوۡطَ عَذَابٍ»\nTranslation: So your Lord will rain upon them a scourge of punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2320,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Scourge",
      "hw": "کوڑا",
      "s": "« » general term for something hard, whether leather or other material, that does not wound when used for striking, whereas a whip or scourge is made of leather (2 verses: 24:2-24:4)",
      "d": "«جِلْد» «جَلَدَ» «جَلْدَۃ» «دُرَہ» «اَرْض جَلْدَۃ» «جَلَّاد» «اَلزَّانِیَۃُ وَ الزَّانِیۡ فَاجۡلِدُوۡا کُلَّ وَاحِدٍ مِّنۡہُمَا مِائَۃَ جَلۡدَۃٍ»"
    }
  ],
  "501": [
    {
      "id": 2321,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Strive",
      "hw": "کوشش",
      "s": "« » to strive for a task (14 Verses: 2:114-2:205-17:19-20:15-20:20-20:66-28:20-36:20-53:39-57:12-66:8-79:22-79:35-80:8)",
      "d": "« » means to walk quickly, to run half-running (metaphorically). To be actively engaged in the completion of a good or bad deed.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اَنۡ  لَّیۡسَ لِلۡاِنۡسَانِ  اِلَّا مَا سَعٰی»\nTranslation: And that man will have nothing but what he strives for."
    },
    {
      "id": 2322,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Strive",
      "hw": "کوشش",
      "s": "« » to employ all means for the completion of a task (27 Verses: 2:218-3:142-5:35-5:54-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:16-9:19-9:20-9:41-9:44-9:73-9:79-9:81-9:86-9:88-16:110-22:78-25:52-29:6-29:8-29:69-31:15-49:15-61:11-66:9)",
      "d": "«جَھَدَ» «اَصْلُہُ الْمُشَقَّۃُ وَمَا یُقَارِبُہٗ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ جَاہَدُوۡا فِیۡنَا لَنَہۡدِیَنَّہُمۡ سُبُلَنَا»\nTranslation: As for those who strive in Our cause, We will surely guide them to Our paths."
    },
    {
      "id": 2323,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Strive",
      "hw": "کوشش",
      "s": "« » to work through hardships (1 Verse: 84:6)",
      "d": "« »: means scraping and « » means to work very hard in a task (Manjad) and means to work through hardships. To proceed with difficulty in doing something (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡاِنۡسَانُ  اِنَّکَ کَادِحٌ  اِلٰی رَبِّکَ کَدۡحًا  فَمُلٰقِیۡہِ»\nTranslation: O man, indeed you are laboring towards your Lord with great labor, and you will meet Him."
    }
  ],
  "502": [
    {
      "id": 2325,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Who",
      "hw": "کون",
      "s": "« » when used in an interrogative form, attached to pronouns, gives the meaning of 'who' (57 Verses: 3:44-4:11-6:19-6:81-7:185-9:124-11:7-17:57-18:7-18:12-19:69-19:73-26:227-27:38-31:34-40:81-45:6-53:55-55:13-55:16-55:18-55:21-55:23-55:25-55:28-55:30-55:32-55:34-55:36-55:38-55:40-55:42-55:45-55:47-55:49-55:51-55:53-55:55-55:57-55:59-55:61-55:63-55:65-55:67-55:69-55:71-55:73-55:75-55:77-67:2-68:6-68:40-77:12-77:50-80:18-81:9-82:8)",
      "d": "« » when used in an interrogative form, attached to pronouns, gives the meaning of 'who', and the annexation (iḍāfa) in it is obligatory (in which conditional meanings are sometimes found), i.e., who among the mentioned things. It also comes for those of sound intellect.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«لِیَبۡلُوَکُمۡ  اَیُّکُمۡ  اَحۡسَنُ عَمَلًا»\nTranslation: So that He may test you [to distinguish] which of you is best in deed.\nAt another place, the command of the Exalted Lord says:\n«لَا تَدۡرُوۡنَ اَیُّہُمۡ اَقۡرَبُ  لَکُمۡ نَفۡعًا»\nTranslation: You do not know which of them is nearer to you in benefit."
    }
  ],
  "503": [
    {
      "id": 2326,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Anyone",
      "hw": "کوئی",
      "s": "« » used for a part of the whole and generally for rational beings (71 verses: 2:96-2:102-2:136-2:180-2:266-2:285-3:73-3:84-3:91-3:153-4:18-4:43-4:152-5:6-5:20-5:27-5:106-5:115-6:61-7:80-9:4-9:6-9:84-9:127-11:81-12:36-12:41-12:78-15:65-16:58-16:76-17:23-18:19-18:22-18:26-18:32-18:38-18:42-18:47-18:49-18:110-19:26-19:98-23:99-24:6-24:21-24:28-29:28-33:32-33:39-33:40-35:41-38:35-43:17-49:12-59:11-63:10-69:47-72:2-72:7-72:18-72:20-72:22-72:26-89:25-89:26-90:5-90:7-92:19-112:1-112:4)",
      "d": "«اَحَد» «قُلۡ ہُوَ اللّٰہُ  اَحَدٌ» «اَحَدَ» «عَشَرَ» «اِحْدٰی» «فَخُذۡ اَحَدَنَا مَکَانَہٗ» «فَمَا مِنۡکُمۡ  مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ عَنۡہُ حٰجِزِیۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "504": [
    {
      "id": 2328,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "That",
      "hw": "گویا",
      "s": "« » when occurring within a sentence, gives the meaning of 'that' or 'as if' (488 verses: 2:26-2:27-2:67-2:75-2:90-2:96-2:105-2:108-2:114-2:125-2:158-2:169-2:177-2:184-2:198-2:210-2:214-2:216-2:224-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:232-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:248-2:254-2:258-2:266-2:267-2:280-2:282-3:28-3:73-3:79-3:80-3:93-3:122-3:124-3:142-3:143-3:145-3:147-3:161-3:188-3:193-4:6-4:19-4:23-4:24-4:25-4:27-4:28-4:29-4:44-4:47-4:48-4:58-4:60-4:66-4:84-4:88-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:99-4:101-4:102-4:113-4:116-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:131-4:135-4:140-4:144-4:150-4:153-4:171-4:172-4:176-5:2-5:3-5:11-5:17-5:19-5:29-5:31-5:33-5:34-5:37-5:41-5:49-5:52-5:59-5:80-5:84-5:91-5:108-5:111-5:112-5:113-5:116-5:117-6:14-6:23-6:25-6:35-6:37-6:51-6:56-6:65-6:70-6:72-6:80-6:111-6:125-6:131-6:145-6:156-6:158-7:5-7:13-7:20-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:50-7:63-7:69-7:82-7:89-7:97-7:98-7:100-7:105-7:110-7:115-7:117-7:123-7:126-7:129-7:160-7:169-7:172-7:185-8:7-8:26-8:62-8:67-9:13-9:16-9:17-9:18-9:32-9:44-9:52-9:54-9:62-9:64-9:74-9:81-9:85-9:86-9:102-9:108-9:110-9:113-9:118-9:120-10:2-10:10-10:15-10:35-10:37-10:72-10:83-10:87-10:100-10:104-10:105-11:3-11:12-11:14-11:26-11:34-11:46-11:47-11:62-11:69-11:87-11:88-11:89-12:13-12:15-12:21-12:24-12:25-12:37-12:38-12:66-12:76-12:79-12:83-12:94-12:96-12:100-12:107-13:21-13:25-13:31-13:36-13:38-14:5-14:10-14:11-14:22-14:31-14:35-15:31-15:54-16:2-16:15-16:33-16:36-16:40-16:45-16:68-16:92-16:123-17:8-17:16-17:46-17:51-17:59-17:68-17:69-17:74-17:79-17:88-17:94-17:99-17:103-18:24-18:35-18:40-18:55-18:57-18:63-18:66-18:77-18:79-18:80-18:81-18:82-18:86-18:94-18:97-18:102-18:109-19:11-19:35-19:45-19:91-19:92-20:39-20:45-20:59-20:63-20:65-20:71-20:77-20:86-20:94-20:97-20:114-20:134-21:17-21:31-21:57-21:87-22:15-22:22-22:26-22:40-22:65-23:24-23:27-23:32-23:95-23:98-24:8-24:16-24:17-24:19-24:22-24:29-24:36-24:50-24:51-24:60-24:61-24:63-25:18-25:42-25:57-25:62-26:10-26:12-26:14-26:17-26:22-26:35-26:49-26:51-26:52-26:63-26:82-26:197-27:8-27:19-27:38-27:39-27:40-27:45-27:56-27:60-27:72-27:91-27:92-28:5-28:7-28:9-28:10-28:19-28:22-28:27-28:30-28:31-28:33-28:34-28:47-28:67-28:82-28:86-29:2-29:4-29:24-29:29-29:33-30:10-30:20-30:21-30:25-30:43-30:46-30:49-31:10-31:12-31:14-31:15-32:20-33:6-33:36-33:37-33:49-33:50-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:59-33:72-34:11-34:14-34:33-34:43-34:46-35:41-36:40-36:60-36:61-36:81-36:82-37:104-38:4-38:6-38:75-39:4-39:11-39:17-39:54-39:55-39:56-40:26-40:28-40:66-40:78-41:22-42:13-42:47-42:51-43:5-43:33-43:66-44:18-44:19-44:20-45:21-45:25-46:15-46:17-46:33-47:18-47:22-47:29-48:12-48:15-48:24-48:25-49:2-49:6-49:11-49:12-49:17-50:2-51:57-53:26-53:39-55:33-56:61-57:16-57:22-58:3-58:4-58:13-59:2-59:3-60:1-60:7-60:8-60:9-60:10-60:12-61:3-63:10-64:7-65:1-65:4-66:5-66:8-67:16-67:17-68:14-68:22-68:24-68:32-68:49-70:38-70:41-71:1-71:3-72:5-72:7-72:12-72:16-72:28-73:20-74:15-74:37-74:52-74:56-75:4-75:25-75:36-75:40-76:30-79:18-80:2-81:28-81:29-84:14-85:8-90:5-90:7-96:7)",
      "d": "«اَنَّ مُخَفَّفَۃ» «اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡیٖۤ اَنۡ یَّضۡرِبَ مَثَلًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2329,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "As If",
      "hw": "گویا",
      "s": "«کَاَنْ ، کَاَنَّ ، کَاَنَّمَا»",
      "d": "«کَاَنْ ، کَاَنَّ ، کَاَنَّمَا» «کَ» «اَنْ» «اَنَّ» «کَاَنۡ  لَّمۡ یَسۡمَعۡہَا کَاَنَّ فِیۡۤ  اُذُنَیۡہِ  وَقۡرًا» «اَنْ» «کَاَنْ» «اَنَّ» «کَاَنَّ» «کَاَنَّمَا یُسَاقُوۡنَ اِلَی الۡمَوۡتِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2330,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "That; as if",
      "hw": "گویا",
      "s": "«اَلَّا» «اَنْ ۔ لَا»",
      "d": "«اَلَّا» «اَنْ ۔ لَا»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«تَتَنَزَّلُ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ  اَلَّا تَخَافُوۡا وَ لَا تَحۡزَنُوۡا»\nTranslation: The angels descend upon them (and say), 'Do not fear and do not grieve.'"
    }
  ],
  "505": [
    {
      "id": 2332,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Where?",
      "hw": "کہاں",
      "s": "« » comes to ask about place along with state or condition. (28  : 2:223-2:247-2:259-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:165-5:75-6:95-6:101-9:30-10:32-10:34-19:8-19:20-23:89-29:61-34:52-35:3-36:66-39:6-40:62-40:69-43:87-44:13-47:18-63:4-89:23)",
      "d": "« » comes to ask about both place and condition (mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«قَالَ یٰمَرۡیَمُ اَنّٰی لَکِ ہٰذَا»\nTranslation: (Zachariah, upon seeing this situation, said, 'O Mary! How does this provision come to you?')\nAnd when it comes only for spatial context, it means 'which direction' or 'where'.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«قٰتَلَہُمُ اللّٰہُ  ۚ ۫  اَنّٰی  یُؤۡفَکُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: May Allah kill them; where (or in which direction) do they wander astray?'"
    }
  ],
  "506": [
    {
      "id": 2333,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Stories; Events",
      "hw": "واقعات",
      "s": "« » baseless events (9  : 6:25-8:31-16:24-23:83-25:5-27:68-46:17-68:15-83:13)",
      "d": "« », « » and « » are all singular forms of « ». And « » is derived from « ». Meaning anything written in lines (i.e., such a text that is in a straight line) or that has been recorded in writing but has no reality. Baseless and unfounded matters (minj) such stories or tales that are not based on reality.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«یَقُوۡلُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡۤا اِنۡ ہٰذَاۤ  اِلَّاۤ  اَسَاطِیۡرُ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: The disbelievers say, 'This is nothing but the tales of the former people.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2334,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Stories; Events",
      "hw": "واقعات",
      "s": "« » forgotten but instructive events (5  : 12:6-12:21-12:101-23:44-34:19)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». Any matter that occurs and did not exist before is a hadith. Then this word is also applied to events that people have forgotten due to the passage of much time. Instructive old events.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«کُلَّمَا جَآءَ اُمَّۃً  رَّسُوۡلُہَا کَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَاَتۡبَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ بَعۡضًا وَّ جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ اَحَادِیۡثَ»\nTranslation: Whenever a messenger came to a nation, they denied him. So We made some of them follow others, and We made them into stories."
    },
    {
      "id": 2335,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Stories; Events",
      "hw": "واقعات",
      "s": "« » are events that are famous among common people and transmitted from chest to chest (10  : 3:62-4:164-7:176-12:3-12:5-12:111-16:118-18:64-28:25-40:78)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». « » means to follow footsteps. And « » means to narrate an event (m. q). And « » refers to events that are famous among common people and transmitted from chest to chest. Spoken events, famous and well-known among all people.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«نَحۡنُ نَقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ اَحۡسَنَ الۡقَصَصِ»\nTranslation: (O Prophet ﷺ!) We relate to you the best of stories."
    }
  ],
  "507": [
    {
      "id": 2336,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Skin",
      "hw": "کھال",
      "s": "« » the skin of any living being's body (7  : 4:56-16:80-22:20-39:23-41:20-41:21-41:22)",
      "d": "« » is the skin of any living being's body and the upper part of the whole body is its skin or hide (mufradat) and this word is general.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«کُلَّمَا نَضِجَتۡ جُلُوۡدُہُمۡ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ جُلُوۡدًا غَیۡرَہَا»\nTranslation: Whenever their skins are roasted/burned, We will replace them with other skins."
    },
    {
      "id": 2337,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Skin",
      "hw": "کھال",
      "s": "« » hands, feet, and the sides of the body (2  : 18:29-70:16)",
      "d": "«شَوٰی» «رَمَاہُ فَاَشْوَاہُ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«کَلَّا ؕ اِنَّہَا  لَظٰی نَزَّاعَۃً   لِّلشَّوٰی»\nTranslation: No! Indeed, it will be a scorching fire, stripping away the skin."
    },
    {
      "id": 2338,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To skin / To peel off",
      "hw": "کھال",
      "s": "« » is used for removing a temporary skin or veil (1 Verse: 36:37)",
      "d": "«سَلَخَ الْحَیَّۃُ» «سَلَخُ الْحَیَّۃ» «مِسْلَاخ» «سَلَخَ الْمِرَاۃ» «سَلَخَ الْخَرُوْف» «سَلَخَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اٰیَۃٌ  لَّہُمُ الَّیۡلُ   ۚ ۖ نَسۡلَخُ مِنۡہُ النَّہَارَ»\nTranslation: And a sign for them is the night; We strip the day from it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2339,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To skin / To peel off",
      "hw": "کھال",
      "s": "« » is used for removing a firm skin or veil (1 Verse: 81:11)",
      "d": "«کَشَطَ الْعَبِیْر » «کِشَاط» «کَشَّاط»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اِذَا  السَّمَآءُ کُشِطَتۡ»\nTranslation: And when the sky is stripped (of its covering)."
    }
  ],
  "508": [
    {
      "id": 2340,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To eat (masdar)",
      "hw": "کھانا",
      "s": "« » is general and is used everywhere for anything that is eaten, whether it is food, bread, sweets, fruit, or any other edible thing (89 Verses: 2:57-2:58-2:60-2:168-2:172-2:174-2:187-2:188-2:275-3:49-3:130-3:183-4:2-4:4-4:6-4:10-4:29-4:161-5:3-5:4-5:62-5:63-5:66-5:75-5:88-5:113-6:118-6:119-6:121-6:141-6:142-7:31-7:73-7:160-7:161-8:69-9:34-10:24-11:64-12:13-12:14-12:17-12:36-12:41-12:43-12:46-12:47-12:48-15:3-16:5-16:14-16:114-20:54-20:81-20:121-21:8-22:28-22:36-23:19-23:21-23:33-23:51-24:61-25:7-25:8-25:20-29:59-32:27-34:14-34:15-35:12-36:33-36:35-36:72-37:66-37:91-40:79-43:73-47:12-49:12-51:27-52:19-56:52-67:15-69:24-69:37-77:43-77:46-89:19)",
      "d": "«اَکَلَ» «اَکَلَتِ النَّارُ الْحَطَبَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَکَلَ السَّبُعُ اِلَّا مَا ذَکَّیۡتُمۡ»\nTranslation: And (forbidden is) that which is devoured by a wild animal, except what you slaughter (before it dies)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2341,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To eat (masdar)",
      "hw": "کھانا",
      "s": "« » means to eat food (for humans) (27 Verses: 2:61-2:184-2:249-2:259-3:93-5:5-5:75-5:93-5:95-5:96-6:145-12:37-18:19-18:77-21:8-25:7-25:20-33:53-44:44-69:34-69:36-73:13-76:8-80:24-88:6-89:18-107:3)",
      "d": "« » is used in a much more limited sense compared to « ». It means to eat food, to eat bread, to dine. And anything that is eaten as food. And this word is generally used for humans. « » means a bread-seller. And « » means a hotel, a restaurant.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَاِذَا طَعِمۡتُمۡ فَانۡتَشِرُوۡا وَ لَا مُسۡتَاۡنِسِیۡنَ لِحَدِیۡثٍ»\nTranslation: Then when you have eaten, disperse and do not remain lingering for conversation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2342,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To eat (masdar)",
      "hw": "کھانا",
      "s": "« » means to eat to one's fill; for animals, to graze, to crop (1 Verse: 12:12)",
      "d": "The basic meaning of « » is for animals to graze, to crop. Then, metaphorically, this word is also used for humans eating and drinking to their fill, like animals. That is, to eat a lot like animals.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَرۡسِلۡہُ  مَعَنَا غَدًا یَّرۡتَعۡ وَ یَلۡعَبۡ»\nTranslation: (O father!) Send him with us tomorrow that he may eat and play to his heart's content."
    }
  ],
  "509": [
    {
      "id": 2343,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To feed (someone)",
      "hw": "کھلانا",
      "s": "« » means to give food to a person (14 Verses: 5:89-6:14-6:138-22:28-22:36-26:79-36:47-51:57-58:4-74:44-76:8-76:9-90:14-106:4)",
      "d": "« » means to give food to a person.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ  یُطۡعِمُنِیۡ وَ  یَسۡقِیۡنِ»\nTranslation: And He it is Who gives me food and gives me drink."
    }
  ],
  "510": [
    {
      "id": 2345,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Date palm",
      "hw": "کھجور",
      "s": "« » means a date palm tree (20 Verses: 2:266-6:99-6:141-13:4-16:11-16:67-17:91-18:32-19:23-19:25-20:71-23:19-26:148-36:34-50:10-54:20-55:11-55:68-69:7-80:29)",
      "d": "« » means a date palm plant or tree.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ ہُزِّیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکِ بِجِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ»\nTranslation: And shake the trunk of the date palm tree towards you.\nAnd « » is the plural of « ». Date palm trees and their fruit. Dates. The fruit of the date palm.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«جَعَلۡنَا لِاَحَدِہِمَا جَنَّتَیۡنِ مِنۡ اَعۡنَابٍ وَّ حَفَفۡنٰہُمَا بِنَخۡلٍ»\nTranslation: We gave one of them two gardens of grapes, and We surrounded them both with date palms.\nAnd « » refers to a garden or plantation in which date palm trees are abundant.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«اَیَوَدُّ اَحَدُکُمۡ اَنۡ تَکُوۡنَ لَہٗ جَنَّۃٌ مِّنۡ نَّخِیۡلٍ وَّ اَعۡنَابٍ»\nTranslation: Would any of you wish to have a garden of date palms and grapes?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2346,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Date palm",
      "hw": "کھجور",
      "s": "« » means 'Ajwa dates (a superior quality of dates) (1 Verse: 59:5)",
      "d": "« » means 'Ajwa (a superior quality of date). Besides this, it also means the tree and fruit of every kind of date.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«مَا  قَطَعۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ  لِّیۡنَۃٍ  اَوۡ  تَرَکۡتُمُوۡہَا قَآئِمَۃً  عَلٰۤی  اُصُوۡلِہَا فَبِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: Whatever date-palms you cut down or left standing on their roots, it was by Allah's leave."
    },
    {
      "id": 2347,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Date palm",
      "hw": "کھجور",
      "s": "« » means fresh, ripe dates (2 Verses: 6:59-19:25)",
      "d": "« » means fresh, ripe dates (the fruit).\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«تُسٰقِطۡ عَلَیۡکِ  رُطَبًا جَنِیًّا»\nTranslation: Fresh ripe dates shall fall upon you."
    }
  ],
  "511": [
    {
      "id": 2348,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To stand / To be standing",
      "hw": "کھڑا ",
      "s": "« » means to stand; its opposites are « » and « » meaning to sit (19 Verses: 2:20-3:191-4:5-4:102-4:103-4:142-5:6-5:97-9:84-9:108-18:14-18:77-25:64-36:8-39:68-51:45-72:19-73:2-74:2)",
      "d": "« » means to stand, and its opposites are « » and « » meaning to sit. It is a well-known word.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ اِذَا قَامُوۡۤا اِلَی الصَّلٰوۃِ قَامُوۡا کُسَالٰی»\nTranslation: And when they stand up for prayer, they stand up lazily.\nAnd « » means to make someone stand, to establish, to set upright, to put a lying thing in an upright position.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«فَوَجَدَا فِیۡہَا جِدَارًا یُّرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یَّنۡقَضَّ فَاَقَامَہٗ»\nTranslation: Then they found a wall that was about to collapse, and he (Khidr) set it upright."
    },
    {
      "id": 2350,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To make stand; to be",
      "hw": "کھڑا ",
      "s": "« » to shake something with such force that it remains rooted but leans to one side (1  : 7:171)",
      "d": "« » means to shake. To raise. To spread. (minj) And to mean to pull something and make it loose (mufradat). And to mean to shake something with such force that it remains rooted but leans to one side (m. l). In Punjabi, for this meaning, the specific word 'Alarna' is used, which expresses its correct meaning.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہٗ وَاقِعٌۢ بِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And when We raised the mountain over them as if it were a canopy, and they thought it was about to fall upon them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2351,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Make Stand / To Be",
      "hw": "کھڑا ",
      "s": "« » means to stand up and to move away. To get up. (2 Verses: 2:259, 58:11)",
      "d": "«نَشَزَ» «نَشَزَ الرَّجُل» «نَشَزَ عَنْ مَکَانِہٖ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا قِیۡلَ انۡشُزُوۡا فَانۡشُزُوۡا»\nTranslation: And when it is said, 'Rise up,' then rise up and move away."
    }
  ],
  "512": [
    {
      "id": 2353,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "« » means for water to boil due to intense heat. (2 Verses: 44:45, 44:46)",
      "d": "«غَلٰی» «غَلٰی الْقَدَر»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَغۡلِیۡ  فِی الۡبُطُوۡنِ کَغَلۡیِ  الۡحَمِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: It will boil in their bellies like the boiling of hot water."
    },
    {
      "id": 2354,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "« » means to open and spread. (22 Verses: 2:245, 2:247, 5:11, 5:28, 6:93, 7:69, 13:14, 13:26, 17:29, 17:30, 18:18, 28:82, 29:62, 30:37, 30:48, 34:36, 34:39, 39:52, 42:12, 42:27, 60:2, 71:19)",
      "d": "« » means to open and spread something, and its opposite is « ». And « » means to spread and make something vast, to make it spacious.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ  وَ یَقۡدِرُ»\nTranslation: Allah extends provision for whom He wills and restricts it for whom He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 2355,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "« » means to open a sealed container or to unravel a complex matter. (14 Verses: 2:76, 6:44, 7:40, 7:96, 12:65, 15:14, 21:96, 23:77, 35:2, 38:50, 39:71, 39:73, 54:11, 78:19)",
      "d": "« » means to remove the complexity of a matter, to open a tied container, and its opposite is « ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا فَتَحُوۡا مَتَاعَہُمۡ وَجَدُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ رُدَّتۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ»\nTranslation: When they opened their baggage, they found their merchandise returned to them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2357,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "« » means to explain the meanings of difficult speech and to clarify. (5 Verses: 6:125, 16:106, 20:25, 39:22, 94:1)",
      "d": "« » means to explain the meanings of difficult speech. According to Ibn al-Faris, two things are fundamental in 'sharh': (1) 'fath' meaning to open, and (2) 'bayān' meaning explanation. 'Sharh al-sadr' means to open the chest, i.e., to understand a difficult and complex matter.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«رَبِّ  اشۡرَحۡ  لِیۡ  صَدۡرِیۡ وَ  یَسِّرۡ لِیۡۤ   اَمۡرِیۡ»\nTranslation: O my Lord, expand for me my breast and ease for me my task."
    },
    {
      "id": 2358,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "« » means to remove one thing to reveal another. (15 Verses: 6:41, 7:134, 7:135, 10:12, 10:98, 16:54, 17:56, 21:84, 23:75, 27:44, 27:62, 43:50, 44:12, 50:22, 68:42)",
      "d": "« » means to open, to remove, to unveil, to remove one thing in place of another, and for the first thing to become apparent and manifest.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَتۡہُ حَسِبَتۡہُ  لُجَّۃً  وَّ کَشَفَتۡ عَنۡ سَاقَیۡہَا»\nTranslation: When she saw it, she thought it was a deep pool, and she uncovered her shins."
    },
    {
      "id": 2359,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "« » to loosen a knot or joint, etc. (1  : 79:2)",
      "d": "«نَشَطَ» «نَشَطَ الْحَبْلَ» «نَشَطَ الْعُقْدَۃ» «اَلْنَشْط» «نَشَطَ» «حَلَّ» «حَلَّ الْعُقٌدَۃ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ النّٰزِعٰتِ غَرۡقًا وَّ النّٰشِطٰتِ نَشۡطًا»\nTranslation: By those who pull forth with force, and by those who untie with ease.\nNote: (The term addad refers to words that have opposite meanings.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2360,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To open",
      "hw": "کھولنا",
      "s": "« » to open and make wide (1  : 77:9)",
      "d": "In « », the concept of spaciousness is found. « » means to open. To make wide. To open up. To expand. (For more detail, see shagaf.)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِذَا السَّمَآءُ  فُرِجَتۡ»\nTranslation: And when the sky is opened up."
    }
  ],
  "513": [
    {
      "id": 2361,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "To Cultivate / To Farm",
      "hw": "کھیتی باڑی",
      "s": "« » means to plow and to sow seeds. (10 Verses: 2:71, 2:205, 2:223, 3:14, 3:117, 6:136, 6:138, 21:78, 42:20, 68:22)",
      "d": "« » means to plow the land and sow seeds in it, preparing it for cultivation. Its plural is « » and its collective plural is « », meaning plowing tools like a plow, etc. Sometimes, cultivation itself is also called « ».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَنِ  اغۡدُوۡا عَلٰی حَرۡثِکُمۡ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰرِمِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: If you are reapers (i.e., intend to harvest), then go early to your cultivation."
    },
    {
      "id": 2362,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to cultivate",
      "hw": "کھیتی باڑی",
      "s": "« » means to irrigate and properly care for (seeds) after planting (10 verses: 6:141-12:47-13:4-14:37-16:11-18:32-32:27-39:21-48:29-56:64)",
      "d": "«زَرَعَ» «أَفَرَأَيْتُمْ مَا تَحْرُثُونَ أَأَنْتُمْ تَزْرَعُونَهُ أَمْ نَحْنُ الزَّارِعُونَ»"
    }
  ],
  "514": [
    {
      "id": 2363,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "« » means to pull and extend, and to lengthen in such a way that the thing remains connected (9 verses: 2:15-7:202-13:3-19:75-25:45-31:27-56:30-74:12-104:9)",
      "d": "«مَدّ» «وَإِخْوَانُهُمْ يَمُدُّونَهُمْ فِي الْغَيِّ ثُمَّ لَا يُقْصِرُونَ» «مَدَّدَ» «فِي عَمَدٍ مُّمَدَّدَةٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2364,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "« » means to pull someone on the ground and drag them (1 verse: 7:150)",
      "d": "«جَرَّ» «جَیْشٌ جَرَارٌ» «وَأَخَذَ بِرَأْسِ أَخِيهِ يَجُرُّهُ إِلَيْهِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2365,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "« » means to forcibly and compellingly pull someone toward a task (8 verses: 2:126-2:173-5:3-6:119-6:145-16:115-27:62-31:24)",
      "d": "«اِضطَرَّ» «وَمَنْ كَفَرَ فَأُمَتِّعُهُ قَلِيلًا ثُمَّ أَضْطَرُّهُ إِلَى عَذَابِ النَّارِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2366,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "« » means to pull off the skin (1 verse: 36:37)",
      "d": "«سَلَخَ» «سَلَخَتِ الشَّهْر» «وَآیَةٌ لَهُمُ اللَّیْلُ نَسْلَخُ مِنْهُ النَّهَارَ فَإِذَا هُمْ مُظْلِمُونَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2367,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "« » means to pull something from its place (10 verses: 3:26-7:27-7:43-7:108-11:9-15:47-19:69-26:33-28:75-54:20)",
      "d": "«نَزَعَ» «وَنَزَعْنَا مَا فِي صُدُورِهِمْ مِنْ غِلٍّ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2368,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to pull",
      "hw": "کھینچنا",
      "s": "«سَفَعَ» «سَفَعَ بِالنَّاصِیَةِ»",
      "d": "«سَفَعَ» «لَئِنْ لَمْ يَنْتَهِ لَنَسْفَعًا بِالنَّاصِیَةِ»"
    }
  ],
  "515": [
    {
      "id": 2370,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "to play",
      "hw": "کھیلنا",
      "s": "« » means any act that distracts from the main purpose (14 verses: 4:135-6:32-6:70-7:51-21:17-29:64-31:6-38:26-47:36-53:3-57:20-62:11-79:40-102:1)",
      "d": "«لَھٰی» «لَعَبَ» «لَھْو» «لَھْو» «اَلْھٰی» «وَمَا الْحَیَاتُ الدُّنْیَا إِلَّا لَعِبٌ وَلَهْوٌ»"
    }
  ],
  "516": [
    {
      "id": 2373,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Is it?",
      "hw": "کیا ",
      "s": "« » is an interrogative particle. A question word, meaning 'Is it?' (88 verses: 2:210-2:246-3:154-5:59-5:60-5:91-5:112-6:47-6:50-6:148-6:158-7:44-7:53-7:147-9:52-9:127-10:34-10:35-10:52-10:102-11:14-11:24-12:64-12:89-13:16-14:21-16:33-16:35-16:75-16:76-17:93-18:66-18:94-18:103-19:65-19:98-20:9-20:40-20:120-21:3-21:80-21:108-22:15-26:39-26:72-26:93-26:203-26:221-27:90-28:12-30:28-30:40-34:7-34:17-34:33-35:3-35:43-37:54-39:9-39:29-39:38-40:11-40:47-42:44-43:66-46:35-47:18-47:22-50:30-50:36-51:24-54:15-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-54:51-55:60-61:10-67:3-69:8-76:1-79:15-79:18-83:36-85:17-88:1-89:5)",
      "d": "«ھَلْ» «هَلْ يَسْتَوِي الْأَعْمَى وَ الْبَصِیرُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2375,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "What?",
      "hw": "کیا ",
      "s": "« » means both 'what' and 'which' (27 verses: 2:26-2:215-2:219-4:39-5:4-5:109-7:110-10:32-10:50-10:101-12:71-16:24-16:30-26:35-27:28-27:33-27:84-28:65-31:11-31:34-34:23-35:40-37:85-37:102-46:4-47:16-74:31)",
      "d": "«مَاذَا» «ذَا» «مَا» «یَسْئَلُونَكَ مَا ذَا يُنْفِقُونَ» «مَاذَا أَجَبْتُمُ الْمُرْسَلِینَ»"
    }
  ],
  "517": [
    {
      "id": 2376,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "How?",
      "hw": "کیسے",
      "s": "« » is used to inquire about the quality and essence of something (83 verses: 2:28-2:259-2:260-3:6-3:25-3:86-3:101-3:137-4:21-4:41-4:50-4:62-5:31-5:43-5:64-5:75-6:11-6:24-6:46-6:65-6:81-7:84-7:86-7:93-7:103-7:129-9:7-9:8-10:14-10:35-10:39-10:73-12:109-13:32-14:24-14:45-16:36-17:21-17:48-18:68-19:29-22:44-25:9-25:45-27:14-27:51-27:69-28:40-29:19-29:20-30:9-30:42-30:48-30:50-34:45-35:26-35:44-37:73-37:154-40:5-40:21-40:82-43:25-47:10-47:27-50:6-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:30-67:17-67:18-68:36-71:15-73:17-74:19-74:20-88:17-88:18-88:19-88:20-89:6-105:1)",
      "d": "« » comes to ask about the quality and essence of something.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«اَفَلَا یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ  اِلَی الۡاِبِلِ کَیۡفَ خُلِقَتۡ»\nTranslation: Do people not look at the camel how (wonderfully) it is created?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2377,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "How?",
      "hw": "کیسے",
      "s": "« » comes to ask for the reason of something (28 verses: 2:223-2:247-2:259-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:165-5:75-6:95-6:101-9:30-10:32-10:34-19:8-19:20-23:89-29:61-34:52-35:3-36:66-39:6-40:62-40:69-43:87-44:13-47:18-63:4-89:23)",
      "d": "« » comes to ask for the reason of something. How come.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«اَنّٰی یَکُوۡنُ لَہُ الۡمُلۡکُ عَلَیۡنَا»\nTranslation: How can the right of kingship be for him over us?"
    }
  ],
  "518": [
    {
      "id": 2378,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Why / Why not",
      "hw": "کیوں",
      "s": "« » meaning why (19 verses: 2:91-3:65-3:66-3:70-3:71-3:98-3:99-3:183-4:77-5:18-7:164-9:43-19:42-20:125-27:46-41:21-61:2-61:5-66:1)",
      "d": "« » meaning why. For what reason.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«رَبِّ  لِمَ حَشَرۡتَنِیۡۤ  اَعۡمٰی»\nTranslation: My Lord, why have you raised me blind?"
    },
    {
      "id": 2379,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Why / Why not",
      "hw": "کیوں",
      "s": "« » meaning why not (41 verses: 2:118-4:77-5:63-6:8-6:37-6:43-7:203-9:122-10:20-10:98-11:12-11:116-13:7-13:27-18:15-18:39-20:133-20:134-24:12-24:13-24:16-25:7-25:21-25:32-27:46-28:47-28:48-29:50-41:44-43:31-43:53-46:28-47:20-56:57-56:62-56:70-56:83-56:86-58:8-63:10-68:28)",
      "d": "«لَوْلَا» «لَوۡ لَا جَآءُوۡ عَلَیۡہِ  بِاَرۡبَعَۃِ شُہَدَآءَ» «لَوۡ لَا تَسۡتَغۡفِرُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2380,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Why / Why not",
      "hw": "کیوں",
      "s": "« » is called a specification particle in Arabic grammar (1 verse: 15:7)",
      "d": "« » is a specification particle. It enters with the present tense and gives the meaning of « ».\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«لَوۡ مَا تَاۡتِیۡنَا بِالۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ»\nTranslation: Why do you not bring angels to us?"
    }
  ],
  "519": [
    {
      "id": 2382,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Embedding",
      "hw": "گاڑنا",
      "s": "« » means to peg like a stake so that more is inside the earth and less outside (11 verses: 13:3-15:19-16:15-21:31-27:61-31:10-34:13-41:10-50:7-77:27-79:32)",
      "d": "«رَسُو» «اَرْسٰی» «رَسَا الْوَتْدَ فِی الْاَرْضِ» «رَاسِیَہ» «رَوَاسِی» «رَاسِیْۃ» «رَوَاسی» «نَصَب» «رسو»\n«وَ الۡجِبَالَ  اَرۡسٰہَا»\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ مَدَّ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ جَعَلَ  فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ وَ اَنۡہٰرًا»"
    }
  ],
  "520": [
    {
      "id": 2385,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Rotation (of time)",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«رَیْب» «رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن»",
      "d": "«رَیْب» «مَنَی» «مَنِیَّۃ» «مَنَایَا» «مَنُوْن» «رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن»\n«اَمۡ  یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ  شَاعِرٌ  نَّتَرَبَّصُ بِہٖ  رَیۡبَ الۡمَنُوۡنِ»\nTranslation: Or do they say [about the Prophet], 'He is a poet; we await for him a misfortune [i.e., his death]'."
    },
    {
      "id": 2386,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Rotation (of time)",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "« » means to circle, to make a cycle, rotation of days and the calamities and afflictions of time (3 verses: 5:52-9:98-48:6)",
      "d": "« » means to circle, to make a cycle. And « » is used in two ways: one is the geometric term for a circle, and the other means rotation of days, the calamities and afflictions of time (from majd). Thus, it is also used in a negative sense, implying awaiting calamities upon someone, and its plural is « ».\n«وَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ مَنۡ یَّتَّخِذُ مَا یُنۡفِقُ مَغۡرَمًا وَّ یَتَرَبَّصُ بِکُمُ الدَّوَآئِرَ ؕ عَلَیۡہِمۡ دَآئِرَۃُ  السَّوۡءِ»\nTranslation: And among the bedouins are those who consider what they spend as a loss and await [misfortunes] to befall you. The calamities will befall them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2387,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Rotation (of time)",
      "hw": "زمانہ",
      "s": "«دُوْلَۃً ، دَوْلَۃً»",
      "d": "«دُوْلَۃً ، دَوْلَۃً» «دَالَ الزَّمَان» «کَیۡ لَا یَکُوۡنَ  دُوۡلَۃًۢ  بَیۡنَ الۡاَغۡنِیَآءِ مِنۡکُمۡ» «وَ تِلۡکَ الۡاَیَّامُ نُدَاوِلُہَا بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ»"
    }
  ],
  "521": [
    {
      "id": 2388,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Neck",
      "hw": "گردن",
      "s": "« » is the general word for neck (9 verses: 8:12-13:5-17:13-17:29-26:4-34:33-36:8-38:33-40:71)",
      "d": "« » means neck or throat. A well-known human organ. Its usage is general. Its plural is « ».\n«وَ کُلَّ  اِنۡسَانٍ اَلۡزَمۡنٰہُ طٰٓئِرَہٗ  فِیۡ عُنُقِہٖ»\nTranslation: And We have bound every human's deeds around his neck."
    },
    {
      "id": 2389,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Neck",
      "hw": "گردن",
      "s": "«jīd» long and beautiful neck (1 verse: 111:5)",
      "d": "«jīd» means thin and long neck (F L 110), a beautiful neck like a deer's.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَّ  امۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ  الۡحَطَبِ فِیۡ  جِیۡدِہَا حَبۡلٌ مِّنۡ مَّسَدٍ»\nTranslation: And his (Abu Lahab's) wife will carry firewood, and around her neck will be a rope of palm fibers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2390,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Neck",
      "hw": "گردن",
      "s": "«raqabah» neck and its back part, the nape. The bond of slavery (4 verses: 4:92-5:89-58:3-90:13)",
      "d": "«raqabah» means neck or the part behind it (nape), and «raqab» means to put a rope or noose around someone's neck. To supervise and guard. Arabs generally use «juz' usharaf» to mean the whole. Similarly, «raqabah» is taken to mean slave because a slave has a bond of slavery around his neck, and its plural is «riqab» (Munjid, Mufradat). And «tahrīr raqabah» means freeing the neck from the noose, i.e., freeing a slave.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡعَقَبَۃُ فَکُّ رَقَبَۃٍ»\nTranslation: And do you know what the 'Iqabah' is? It is freeing a neck (i.e., freeing a slave)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2391,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Neck",
      "hw": "گردن",
      "s": "«watīn» the front part of the neck where the carotid artery is (1 verse: 69:46)",
      "d": "«watīn» means the jugular vein. The carotid artery from the heart to the head (F L 114). The side of the neck where the carotid artery is.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَاَخَذۡنَا مِنۡہُ  بِالۡیَمِیۡنِ ثُمَّ  لَقَطَعۡنَا مِنۡہُ  الۡوَتِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: We would have seized him by the right hand, then cut off his jugular vein (the carotid artery)."
    }
  ],
  "522": [
    {
      "id": 2392,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Seizing",
      "hw": "گرفت",
      "s": "«akhadha» to hold accountable for a disliked act, questioning, or seizing (7 verses: 2:225-2:286-5:89-16:61-18:58-18:73-35:45)",
      "d": "«akhadha» means to take something. To acquire. To encompass. And «akhadha» means to question, to seize, to take (Mufradat), whether it is accountability in speech or action.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«رَبَّنَا لَا تُؤَاخِذۡنَاۤ  اِنۡ نَّسِیۡنَاۤ  اَوۡ اَخۡطَاۡنَا»\nTranslation: Our Lord, do not hold us accountable if we forget or make a mistake."
    },
    {
      "id": 2394,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Seizing",
      "hw": "گرفت",
      "s": "«lamah, lāwama» to say bad things, whether the act is bad or not, without the severity like «tathrīb» (11 verses: 5:54-14:22-17:29-17:39-23:6-37:142-51:40-51:54-68:30-70:30-75:2)",
      "d": "«lamah» means to reproach someone for a bad deed. To blame (Mufradat). And it means to warn someone about the consequence of their action (F Q 39). And «lāwam» means blame and fear (Munjid). So «lam» is used when the doer fears being blamed for an action, whether the action itself is good or bad.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُجَاہِدُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ لَا  یَخَافُوۡنَ لَوۡمَۃَ لَآئِمٍ»\nTranslation: They strive in the way of Allah and do not fear the blame of any blamer."
    }
  ],
  "523": [
    {
      "id": 2395,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«ṣayf» summer season (1 verse: 106:2)",
      "d": "«ṣayf» means summer season. And «ṣayyafa» means the rain of summer and the grass that grows from it. And «ṣāf» and «ṣayyafa bil-makān» means to spend summer in a place (Munjid).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«اٖلٰفِہِمۡ  رِحۡلَۃَ  الشِّتَآءِ  وَ الصَّیۡفِ»\nTranslation: Accustomed to the winter and summer journeys."
    },
    {
      "id": 2396,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«ḥarr» heat, the scorching of the sun (2 verses: 9:81-16:81)",
      "d": "«ḥarr» means heat, warmth, whether from fire or sun, i.e., the intensity of sunlight, or from any other cause like friction. However, this word is generally used for the intensity of sunlight. And «ḥarūr» means scorching heat (see also sunlight).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَا تَنۡفِرُوۡا فِی الۡحَرِّ ؕ قُلۡ نَارُ جَہَنَّمَ اَشَدُّ حَرًّا»\nTranslation: And they said, 'Do not go out in the heat.' Say, 'The fire of Hell is more intense in heat.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2397,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«ḥamma, ḥummi» are synonymous and are used in all contexts of heat and intense warmth (22 verses: 6:70-10:4-22:19-26:101-37:67-38:57-40:18-40:72-41:34-44:46-44:48-47:15-48:26-55:44-56:42-56:54-56:93-69:35-70:10-78:25-88:4-101:11)",
      "d": "«ḥamma» and «ḥummi» are so similar in meaning that distinguishing them is difficult. Hence, lexicographers include both under the same root. There are four sources of heat: fire and sun (material), and emotional heat and bodily warmth (spiritual). Both roots are used for all four. The difference is that «ḥamma» is transitive and «ḥummi» is intransitive, but in passive form they become synonymous. For example, «ḥamma al-mā'» means to heat water, and «ḥumma al-rajul» means the man got a fever. «ḥummi» means fever. Both roots are listed under both roots by lexicographers. And «ḥamma al-tannūr» means to heat the oven, and «ḥummi al-nār» means the fire blazed. And «ḥamīm» means hot water or cold water (antonymic roots, etc.). And a hot-tempered friend or relative (related to emotions). And «ḥamma al-ẓahīrah» means the intense heat at noon. And «ḥammah» means a hot spring. And «ḥummah» means a kettle, or ashes, or everything burning in fire. And «ḥammām» means a place for bathing with hot water (Mufradat, Munjid).\nNow consider their examples:\n«لَہُمۡ شَرَابٌ مِّنۡ حَمِیۡمٍ  وَّ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌۢ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَکۡفُرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: For them is a drink of boiling water and a painful torment because they used to disbelieve.\n«وَ لَا یَسۡئَلُ  حَمِیۡمٌ حَمِیۡمًا»\nTranslation: And no friend will ask about a friend.\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا ہِیَہۡ نَارٌ حَامِیَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And do you know what the 'Hawiyah' is? It is a blazing fire.\n«اِذۡ جَعَلَ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا فِیۡ  قُلُوۡبِہِمُ الۡحَمِیَّۃَ حَمِیَّۃَ  الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ»\nTranslation: When those who disbelieved put in their hearts the pride of Jahiliyyah (ignorance)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2398,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«saqara» to scorch the body with fire or sun's heat (4 verses: 54:48-74:26-74:27-74:42)",
      "d": "«saqara» means to scorch with fire or sun. «saqarat-hu al-shams» means the sun scorched him. Then this word became a proper noun for Hell (Mufradat).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«ذُوۡقُوۡا مَسَّ سَقَرَ»\nTranslation: So taste the touch of Saqar."
    },
    {
      "id": 2399,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Heat, Heating, Being Hot",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "«samūm» scorching wind that penetrates the body (3 verses: 15:27-52:27-56:42)",
      "d": "«sam» means a narrow hole like an eye of a needle, or a nostril, or a nasal passage. Also «sam» means deadly poison. And «samūm» means a scorching wind that penetrates the body like poison.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«فَمَنَّ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡنَا وَ  وَقٰىنَا عَذَابَ السَّمُوۡمِ»\nTranslation: So Allah favored us and saved us from the punishment of the scorching wind."
    },
    {
      "id": 2401,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To obtain heat",
      "hw": "گرمی",
      "s": "« » is used to mean obtaining heat from fire (2 verses: 27:7-28:29)",
      "d": "« » means to enter fire. And « » and « » mean to cause to enter fire. And « » means to obtain heat from fire. To warm by fire. To heat and to warm the body to protect it from cold.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَوۡ اٰتِیۡکُمۡ بِشِہَابٍ قَبَسٍ لَّعَلَّکُمۡ تَصۡطَلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Or I will bring you a glowing ember so that you may warm yourselves."
    }
  ],
  "524": [
    {
      "id": 2402,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » means something falling from above (6 verses: 6:59-7:149-9:49-17:92-26:187-34:9)",
      "d": "«سُقِط» «رَجُلٌ سَاقِط»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا تَسۡقُطُ مِنۡ وَّرَقَۃٍ  اِلَّا یَعۡلَمُہَا»\nTranslation: And not a leaf falls but Allah knows it.\nThen, as this word is used literally, it is also used metaphorically.\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«اَلَا فِی الۡفِتۡنَۃِ سَقَطُوۡا»\nTranslation: Behold, they have fallen into temptation.\n«سُقِطَ فِیْ یَدِہٖ»\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«وَ لَمَّا سُقِطَ فِیۡۤ  اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ رَاَوۡا اَنَّہُمۡ قَدۡ ضَلُّوۡا»\nTranslation: And when they were regretful and saw that they had gone astray.\nAnd for causing to fall, « » is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَسۡقِطۡ عَلَیۡنَا کِسَفًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  اِنۡ  کُنۡتَ مِنَ  الصّٰدِقِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: If you are truthful, then bring down on us a fragment from the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 2403,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » means something falling with agitation (i.e., restlessness) and sound (4 verses: 7:143-22:31-34:14-38:24)",
      "d": "« » means something falling with sound and agitation (i.e., restlessness and unease) (m. l.) meaning that at the time of falling, there is restlessness or trembling, and upon falling, a sound is also produced. And « » means the sound of water falling or dripping (m. l.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا خَرَّ تَبَیَّنَتِ الۡجِنُّ اَنۡ لَّوۡ کَانُوۡا یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ الۡغَیۡبَ مَا لَبِثُوۡا فِی الۡعَذَابِ الۡمُہِیۡنِ»\nTranslation: Then when Solomon fell, the jinn realized that if they had known the unseen, they would not have remained in the humiliating punishment."
    },
    {
      "id": 2404,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » means the falling of a building or wall or structure (1 verse: 22:40)",
      "d": "« » means the falling of a building or structure (m. l.) and « » means to demolish a building. To cause to fall. To tear down. « » is a famous word used in the same meaning as « ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا دَفۡعُ اللّٰہِ النَّاسَ بَعۡضَہُمۡ بِبَعۡضٍ لَّہُدِّمَتۡ صَوَامِعُ وَ بِیَعٌ»\nTranslation: And if Allah did not repel some people by others, then monasteries and churches would have been demolished."
    },
    {
      "id": 2405,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » the collapse of a building, wall, or structure with a loud crash (1 verse: 19:90)",
      "d": "«ھَدَّ» «شُدُّہُ الْہَدَم»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«تَکَادُ السَّمٰوٰتُ یَتَفَطَّرۡنَ مِنۡہُ وَ تَنۡشَقُّ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ تَخِرُّ الۡجِبَالُ ہَدًّا»\nTranslation: It is as if the heavens would almost rupture from it, and the earth would split open, and the mountains would fall in pieces."
    },
    {
      "id": 2406,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » means a wall or building cracking and falling or being about to fall (10 verses: 2:27-4:155-5:13-8:56-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:92-18:77-94:3)",
      "d": "«اِنْقَضَّ» «قَضَّ الْحَائِط» «اِنْقَضَّ الْحَائِط»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَوَجَدَا فِیۡہَا جِدَارًا یُّرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یَّنۡقَضَّ فَاَقَامَہٗ»\nTranslation: Then they found a wall there that was about to collapse, so he (Khidr) set it right."
    },
    {
      "id": 2407,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » means to fall; to descend; to exit. In this word, the aspect of wrath and compulsion (restlessness and unease) is found (8 verses: 2:36-2:38-2:61-2:74-7:13-7:24-11:48-20:123)",
      "d": "«ھَبَطَ» «ھَبَطَ الثَّمَن» «ھَبَطَ الزَّمَان» «ھَبَطَ الْمَرَض»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡہَا لَمَا یَہۡبِطُ مِنۡ خَشۡیَۃِ اللّٰہِ»\nTranslation: And indeed, some of them fall from the fear of Allah.\nThen in « », besides wrath and compulsion, sometimes an element of contempt is also found. In that case, it means 'get out' (GETOUT).\nFor example, the Almighty says:\n«قُلۡنَا اہۡبِطُوۡا مِنۡہَا جَمِیۡعًا»\nTranslation: We said, 'Get out of it, all of you.'\nThis meaning was expressed by a poet in these words:\nTo exit from Paradise was Adam's custom, hearing it came,\nbut we exited from your neighborhood very dishonorably!\nAnd the following verse:\n«قِیۡلَ یٰنُوۡحُ اہۡبِطۡ بِسَلٰمٍ مِّنَّا»\nTranslation: It was said, 'O Noah, disembark with peace from us.'\nI make « » with « » exclude all aspects of wrath, compulsion, or contempt, and make it according to divine decree."
    },
    {
      "id": 2408,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » means in the falling of something, there is also horror and severity (19 verses: 4:100-5:91-7:71-7:118-7:134-7:171-10:51-18:53-27:82-27:85-42:22-51:6-52:7-56:1-56:2-56:75-69:15-70:1-77:7)",
      "d": "« » means to fall; to be established; to occur. This word generally comes to mention horror, severity, and hardship. And by 'event' is meant an incident in which there is severity (muf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہٗ وَاقِعٌۢ بِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And when We raised the mountain over them as if it were a canopy, and they thought it was about to fall on them."
    },
    {
      "id": 2410,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » means to fall from the sky or from a great height (4 verses: 20:81-22:31-53:1-53:53)",
      "d": "« » is a famous word meaning the space between the sky and the earth. And « » means to fall from space or from a great height to the ground (m. l.) It is also used for the falling of a star (f. l. 297).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ النَّجۡمِ   اِذَا ہَوٰی»\nTranslation: By the star when it falls.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«فَکَاَنَّمَا خَرَّ  مِنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتَخۡطَفُہُ الطَّیۡرُ  اَوۡ تَہۡوِیۡ بِہِ الرِّیۡحُ فِیۡ مَکَانٍ  سَحِیۡقٍ»\nTranslation: As if he had fallen from the sky, then the bird snatches him away, or the wind carries him to a distant place."
    },
    {
      "id": 2411,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » means to fall from the void between two things (5 verses: 2:259-18:42-22:45-27:52-69:7)",
      "d": "«خَوٰی» «ھَوٰی» «ھَوَا» «خَوٰی» «ھَوَی النَّجْم» «خَوَی النَّجْم» «تَخْوِیَۃ» «خَوٰی الدَّار»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ وَّ ہِیَ خَاوِیَۃٌ عَلٰی عُرُوۡشِہَا»\nTranslation: Or like the one who passed by a town, and it had fallen upon its roofs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2412,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » to fall with a thud and die, or to fall with a thud while dying (1 verse: 22:36)",
      "d": "«اَلْوَجَبَۃ» «ضَرَبَہٗ فَوَجَبَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاذۡکُرُوا اسۡمَ اللّٰہِ عَلَیۡہَا صَوَآفَّ ۚ فَاِذَا وَجَبَتۡ جُنُوۡبُہَا فَکُلُوۡا مِنۡہَا وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡقَانِعَ وَ الۡمُعۡتَرَّ»\nTranslation: So mention the name of Allah over them when they are lined up in rows. Then, when their sides fall to the ground, eat from them and feed the contented and the one who asks."
    },
    {
      "id": 2413,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«رَدِيَ ، رَدًي»",
      "d": "«رَدِيَ ، رَدًي»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اتَّبَعَ  ہَوٰىہُ  فَتَرۡدٰی»\nTranslation: And he followed his own desire, so he will perish.\n«اَرْدَی الرَّجُل» «رَدَّی الرَّجُل»\nFor example, the Lord says:\n«قَالَ تَاللّٰہِ   اِنۡ  کِدۡتَّ  لَتُرۡدِیۡنِ»\nTranslation: He will say, 'By Allah, you almost ruined me.' (Jalandhri) You were about to throw me into the pit. (Usmani)\nAnd « » means to fall into a well or pit (M. Q.), and « » refers to an animal that falls into a pit or well and dies (5/3).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا یُغۡنِیۡ عَنۡہُ  مَا لُہٗۤ  اِذَا تَرَدّٰی»\nTranslation: And when he falls into the pit of Hell, his wealth will not avail him at all."
    },
    {
      "id": 2414,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » to collapse or faint, as from illness or in a boat (1 verse: 69:7)",
      "d": "« » means to fall to the ground due to agitation, restlessness, and lack of composure (F. L. 130), and also means to fall to the ground due to a head ailment (marghi) (Manjad). « » refers to a patient falling unconscious to the ground with a crash due to illness. « » also means to throw one's opponent to the ground in a boat and pin them down (M. Q.).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اَعۡجَازُ نَخۡلٍ خَاوِیَۃٍ»\nTranslation: So you would see the people lying fallen therein as if they were hollow palm trunks."
    },
    {
      "id": 2415,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » to fall face down, i.e., on one's forehead (1 verse: 37:103)",
      "d": "« » means to make someone fall on their face, i.e., on their forehead (F. L. 189).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَسۡلَمَا وَ تَلَّہٗ  لِلۡجَبِیۡنِ»\nTranslation: Then when both had submitted and he (Ibrahim) laid him (Ismail) on his forehead."
    },
    {
      "id": 2416,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » to stumble and fall face down, unable to rise (1 verse: 47:8)",
      "d": "« » means to stumble and fall, and then be unable to get up; to fall into lowliness and be broken (Maf), and also means to fall face down and perish (M. Q.). « » also means to slip and fall face down. « » means destruction and (Manjad).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا  فَتَعۡسًا لَّہُمۡ»\nTranslation: And those who disbelieve - for them is destruction.\nThey will fall face down. (Usmani)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2417,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » to fall down exhausted and helpless (3 verses: 7:38, 10:90, 27:66)",
      "d": "« » means for one thing to meet another from behind and then join with it (M. L.). « » also refers to the depth of the sea and to the rope that is tied to another to reach the bottom of the water (Maf). Thus, to reach the extremity of something through a means is called « ». The Quran states regarding Pharaoh:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَاۤ  اَدۡرَکَہُ الۡغَرَقُ» «اِدّٰرَک»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«بَلِ ادّٰرَکَ عِلۡمُہُمۡ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ»\nTranslation: Rather, their knowledge has come to an end regarding the Hereafter.\nIt is as if, after gathering all means of knowledge, they will fall down exhausted and helpless.\nAt another place, the Lord says:\n«کُلَّمَا دَخَلَتۡ اُمَّۃٌ  لَّعَنَتۡ اُخۡتَہَا ؕ حَتّٰۤی اِذَا ادَّارَکُوۡا فِیۡہَا جَمِیۡعًا»\nTranslation: Every time a nation enters, it will curse its sister (nation) until, when they have all gathered there one after another.\nIt seems the end and extremity is reaching Hell. And the sequence and connection is one group after another entering and falling in."
    },
    {
      "id": 2418,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » to pour down or flow (of water) (1 verse: 54:11)",
      "d": "«ھَمَرَ الْمَاء» «اِنْھَمَرَ الْمَاء»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَفَتَحۡنَاۤ  اَبۡوَابَ السَّمَآءِ  بِمَآءٍ  مُّنۡہَمِرٍ»\nTranslation: So We opened the gates of the sky with water pouring forth."
    },
    {
      "id": 2420,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to fall; to cause to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » water pouring continuously and flowing (1 verse: 56:31)",
      "d": "«سَکَبَ الْمَاء» «اَسْکَبَ» «اَلْاَسْکُوْب» «مَاءٍ مَّسْکُوۡبٍ» «جَارٍ دَائِمًا» «سَکَبَ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ ظِلٍّ  مَّمۡدُوۡدٍ وَّ مَآءٍ  مَّسۡکُوۡبٍ»\nTranslation: And extended shade and flowing water."
    }
  ],
  "525": [
    {
      "id": 2421,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to keep as collateral",
      "hw": "گروی",
      "s": "« » to keep something as security for a loan (3 verses: 2:283, 52:21, 74:38)",
      "d": "« » means for the borrower to keep something with the lender as security for a loan or debt. To keep as collateral. « » means the thing kept as collateral. It is general, whether inanimate or animate. « » also refers to something kept as a stake in a contest or as security under a loan (Maf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ وَّ لَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا کَاتِبًا فَرِہٰنٌ مَّقۡبُوۡضَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And if you are on a journey and cannot find a scribe, then take a pledge (or collateral) in hand.\nJust as this word is used materially, it is also used spiritually.\nFor example, the Lord says:\n«کُلُّ نَفۡسٍۭ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ رَہِیۡنَۃٌ»\nTranslation: Every person is a hostage to what he has earned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2422,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to surrender to destruction",
      "hw": "گروی",
      "s": "« » means to surrender oneself or a living being as captive or to destruction (slavery). (1 verse: 6:70)",
      "d": "«اَبْسَلَ» «اَبْسَلَ» «رَھَنَ» «اَبْسَلَ نَفْسَہٗ لِلْمَوْت» «وَ ذَکِّرۡ بِہٖۤ  اَنۡ تُبۡسَلَ نَفۡسٌۢ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ»"
    }
  ],
