      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "« » is a sin that occurs unintentionally (13 verses: 2:58-2:81-2:286-4:92-4:112-7:161-17:31-20:73-26:51-26:82-29:12-33:5-71:25)",
      "d": "«خَطَا» «خِطْأ» «خَطْأ» «خَطَاء» «خَطَایَا» «خَطِیْءَ» «خَطِیْئَات» «وَ مَنۡ قَتَلَ مُؤۡمِنًا خَطَئًا فَتَحۡرِیۡرُ رَقَبَۃٍ مُّؤۡمِنَۃٍ وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا» «وَّ ادۡخُلُوا الۡبَابَ سُجَّدًا وَّ قُوۡلُوۡا حِطَّۃٌ نَّغۡفِرۡ لَکُمۡ خَطٰیٰکُمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2443,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "« » a major sin related to family affairs (1 verse: 4:2)",
      "d": "«اَلْحُوْبَۃ» «اِنَّ لِیْ حُوْبَۃٌ اَعْوَلُھَا» «حَوْب» «حُوْب» «حُوْب» «حُوْب»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ لَا تَاۡکُلُوۡۤا اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ  اِلٰۤی اَمۡوَالِکُمۡ ؕ اِنَّہٗ کَانَ حُوۡبًا کَبِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: And do not consume the orphans' wealth by mixing it with your own wealth, for indeed, that is a great sin."
    },
    {
      "id": 2444,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "« » meaning breaking an oath; a major sin related to covenants and pledges (2 verses: 38:44-56:46)",
      "d": "«حِنْث» «حَنَثَ فِی الْیَمِیْن» «حَنِثَ» «حِنْث»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«وَ کَانُوۡا یُصِرُّوۡنَ عَلَی الۡحِنۡثِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ»\nTranslation: And they used to persist in the great sin."
    },
    {
      "id": 2445,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "« » predisposition of the heart towards sin and not refraining from committing it when the opportunity arises (3 verses: 2:283-5:106-76:24)",
      "d": "« » means every action that is delayed or prevented from being a act of goodness or reward (Maf M. L.). Its plural is « ». Its opposite is « » meaning goodness. Also, the lexical meaning of « » is 'negligence' (i.e., fault and error) (Faqih 193).\n«اَلْبِرُّ مَا اطْمَاَنَّتْ اِلَیْہِ النَّفْسُ وَ الْاِثْمُ مَا حَاکَ فِیْ صَدْرِکَ»\nTranslation: That is, goodness is that which the heart finds peace in, and « » (sin) is that which causes doubt in your chest.\nThus, « » is the name of a state where a person's heart turns away from good deeds and inclines towards sinful deeds, and when the opportunity arises, he does not refrain from that sin. That is, « » is more related to the heart than the action. And a person with this quality is called « », whose opposite is « ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡبِرِّ وَ التَّقۡوٰی ۪ وَ لَا تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡعُدۡوَانِ»\nTranslation: Cooperate in righteousness and piety, but do not cooperate in sin and aggression.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَ لَا تَکۡتُمُوا الشَّہَادَۃَ ؕ وَ مَنۡ یَّکۡتُمُہَا فَاِنَّہٗۤ اٰثِمٌ قَلۡبُہُ»\nTranslation: And do not conceal testimony. And whoever conceals it, then indeed, his heart is sinful."
    },
    {
      "id": 2446,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "« » meaning the consequence or penalty of a major sin (1 verse: 11:35)",
      "d": "«جُرْم» «جُرْم ۔ جَرِیْمَۃ» «اَجْرَمَ» «اِجْرَام» «جُرْم» «جُرْم»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«قُلۡ  اِنِ افۡتَرَیۡتُہٗ فَعَلَیَّ  اِجۡرَامِیۡ وَ اَنَا بَرِیۡٓءٌ  مِّمَّا تُجۡرِمُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: (O Prophet) say: If I have invented it, then its penalty is upon me, and I am free from what you commit."
    },
    {
      "id": 2447,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "« » its meaning is actually not sin itself, but inclination or leaning towards sin (24 verses: 2:158-2:198-2:229-2:230-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:240-2:282-4:23-4:24-4:101-4:102-4:128-5:93-24:29-24:58-24:60-24:61-33:5-33:51-33:55-60:10)",
      "d": "«جُنَاح» «جَنَحَ» «لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیْکُمْ ،» «لَیْسَ عَلَیْکُمْ جُنَاحٌ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  اِنۡ طَلَّقۡتُمُ النِّسَآءَ مَا لَمۡ تَمَسُّوۡہُنَّ»\nTranslation: There is no blame upon you if you divorce women whom you have not touched.\nAnd « » (meaning side, wing, flank) is used for inclination towards goodness.\nFor example: The Almighty says:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ»\nTranslation: And lower for them the wing of humility out of mercy.\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ جَنَاحَکَ لِمَنِ اتَّبَعَکَ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: And lower your wing humbly for the believers who follow you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2448,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sin",
      "hw": "گناہ",
      "s": "« » minor sins that lead one towards a major sin (1 verse: 53:32)",
      "d": "« » means small sins that lead towards a major sin and those that assist in that act. And « » means to commit minor sins (Manjad). For example, approaching a non-mahram woman before adultery, or free conversation with her, or consulting about theft before committing it—all these are included in the definition of « ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَجۡتَنِبُوۡنَ کَبٰٓئِرَ الۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡفَوَاحِشَ  اِلَّا اللَّمَمَ ؕ اِنَّ  رَبَّکَ وَاسِعُ  الۡمَغۡفِرَۃِ»\nTranslation: Those who avoid major sins and immoralities, except for minor slips—indeed, your Lord is vast in forgiveness."
    }
  ],
  "532": [
    {
      "id": 2450,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sinner",
      "hw": "گنہگار",
      "s": "« » a disobedient or sinner who considers sin to be sin (37 verses: 2:26-2:99-3:82-3:110-5:25-5:26-5:47-5:49-5:59-5:81-5:108-7:102-7:145-9:8-9:24-9:53-9:67-9:80-9:84-9:96-21:74-24:4-24:55-27:12-28:32-32:18-43:54-46:35-49:6-51:46-57:16-57:26-57:27-59:5-59:19-61:5-63:6)",
      "d": "« » means to deviate from the path of truth and reform; to become wicked; to step out of obedience (M. L.). Not to consider religious commands (Maf). « » is a term used for a habitual disobedient person; wicked. However, such a person must consider sinful acts as sin and disobedience.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا»\nTranslation: O you who have believed! If a wicked person brings you news, verify it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2451,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Sinner",
      "hw": "گنہگار",
      "s": "« » a sinner and wicked person who has become hardened and does not even consider sin as sin (4 verses: 38:28-71:27-82:14-83:7)",
      "d": "« » its plural is « » and its opposite is « ». « » means to widely tear something. And « » means one who violates religion and commits disobedience; wicked. A sinner who continues to sin and does not repent (Maf). And « » means to commit evil acts; to become hardened. And a « » is a sinner who does not even consider sin as sin; a depraved person.\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«کَلَّاۤ  اِنَّ  کِتٰبَ الۡفُجَّارِ لَفِیۡ  سِجِّیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: No! Indeed, the record of the wicked is in Sijjin."
    }
  ],
  "533": [
    {
      "id": 2452,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Impurity / Filth",
      "hw": "گندگی",
      "s": "« » bodily dirt and filth (1 verse: 22:29)",
      "d": "«تَفِثَ» «قَضٰی تَفِثَ» «قَضٰی تَفِثَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡضُوۡا تَفَثَہُمۡ وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ وَ لۡیَطَّوَّفُوۡا بِالۡبَیۡتِ الۡعَتِیۡقِ»\nTranslation: Then let them complete their cleanliness, fulfill their vows, and circumambulate the Ancient House."
    },
    {
      "id": 2453,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Impurity / Filth",
      "hw": "گندگی",
      "s": "« » satanic whispers that cause disturbance (2 verses: 8:11-74:5)",
      "d": "«رَجَزَ» «رَجَزَ فُلَانٌ» «عَذَابٌ مِّنْ رِجْزٍ اَلِیْم» «رِجْز»\nFor example: The Noble Quran says:\n«اِذۡ یُغَشِّیۡکُمُ النُّعَاسَ اَمَنَۃً مِّنۡہُ وَ یُنَزِّلُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً  لِّیُطَہِّرَکُمۡ بِہٖ وَ یُذۡہِبَ عَنۡکُمۡ رِجۡزَ الشَّیۡطٰنِ»\nTranslation: When He overwhelmed you with drowsiness [giving] security from Him and sent down upon you from the sky rain by which to purify you and remove from you the impurity of Satan.\n«رِجۡزَ الشَّیۡطٰنِ»\n«  :  » are essentially the same word (Manjad). And it has the same relationship as « » and « » or « » and « » (see details under 'Burden'). And this word is used for all such satanic whispers present in the heart, whether related to worship of other than Allah or evil thoughts.\nFor example: The Almighty says:\n«وَ  ثِیَابَکَ فَطَہِّرۡ وَ الرُّجۡزَ  فَاہۡجُرۡ»\nTranslation: And your clothing, purify it, and from impurity, keep away."
    },
    {
      "id": 2454,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Impurity. Filth",
      "hw": "گندگی",
      "s": "« » The impurity of things that are haram and filthy (9 verses: 5:90-6:125-6:145-7:71-9:95-9:125-10:100-22:30-33:33)",
      "d": "« » refers to the impurity of things that the Shariah has declared impure (napaak) or haram (manjid). It is used in both material and spiritual senses.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ مَیۡتَۃً اَوۡ دَمًا مَّسۡفُوۡحًا اَوۡ لَحۡمَ  خِنۡزِیۡرٍ فَاِنَّہٗ رِجۡسٌ»\nTranslation: Except that it be a dead animal, or flowing blood, or the flesh of swine, for indeed, it is impure.\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High states:\n«وَ اَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ مَّرَضٌ فَزَادَتۡہُمۡ رِجۡسًا اِلٰی رِجۡسِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And as for those in whose hearts is disease, it has added filth upon their filth.\nHere, « » refers to the impurity of disbelief and polytheism. And this is the spiritual usage of « ». (Also see 'Napaak')"
    }
  ],
  "534": [
    {
      "id": 2456,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To Count",
      "hw": "گننا",
      "s": "« » To count and maintain order and discipline in it so that there is no error (2 verses: 6:96-55:5)",
      "d": "«یَحْسَبُ ، حَسَابًا ، وَ حُسْبَانًا»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جَعَلَ الَّیۡلَ سَکَنًا وَّ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ حُسۡبَانًا»\nTranslation: He has made the night a place of rest and the sun and moon a means of reckoning."
    },
    {
      "id": 2457,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To Count",
      "hw": "گننا",
      "s": "« » meaning to count and to have power over it. To record. To remember (11 verses: 14:34-16:18-18:12-18:49-19:94-36:12-58:6-65:1-72:28-73:20-78:29)",
      "d": "«حَصٰی» «حَصٰی یَحْصِی» «حَصٰی» «عَدَّ»\nFor example: The command of Allah the Most High states:\n«اِنۡ تَعُدُّوۡا نِعۡمَتَ اللّٰہِ لَا تُحۡصُوۡہَا»\nTranslation: If you should count the favors of Allah, you would not be able to enumerate them.\nAnd sometimes this word also comes for having power over the account.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«عَلِمَ  اَنۡ  لَّنۡ تُحۡصُوۡہُ فَتَابَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ»\nTranslation: He knew that you would not be able to do it, so He turned to you in mercy."
    }
  ],
  "535": [
    {
      "id": 2458,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Lap",
      "hw": "گود",
      "s": "« » The mother's lap for a breastfeeding child (7 verses: 3:46-5:110-19:29-20:53-30:44-43:10-74:14)",
      "d": "« » means cradle. A child's swing. And it means the mother's lap for a breastfeeding child. As long as he is breastfeeding. For the mother's lap is also a cradle for him. And the concept of upbringing or means of upbringing is also found in this word. (See 'Bachhona')\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یُکَلِّمُ النَّاسَ فِی الۡمَہۡدِ وَ کَہۡلًا»\nTranslation: He will speak to people in the cradle and in maturity, and he will be a righteous one."
    },
    {
      "id": 2459,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Lap",
      "hw": "گود",
      "s": "« » Lap for older children. It refers to a guardian who can impose restrictions on the property and authority of a child under his care (1 verse: 4:23)",
      "d": "«حُجُور» «حِجْر» «حِجْر» «فُلَانٌ فِیْ حِجْرِ فُلَانٍ» «فُلَانٌ فِیْ حِجْرِ فُلَانٍ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ رَبَآئِبُکُمُ الّٰتِیۡ فِیۡ  حُجُوۡرِکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And your step-daughters who are under your care (i.e., raised by you)."
    }
  ],
  "536": [
    {
      "id": 2461,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Deep. Depth",
      "hw": "گہرائی",
      "s": "« » Subterranean depth. Depth from the earth's surface. Low-lying land (2 verses: 18:41-67:30)",
      "d": "« » means to go down towards low-lying land. Ghār (cave) is a famous word meaning cave. And « » means low-lying land. And it means subterranean depth (Muf). So to speak, the concept of a dwelling with depth is also found in it.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ  اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ  اَصۡبَحَ مَآؤُکُمۡ غَوۡرًا فَمَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِمَآءٍ مَّعِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: Say, [O Muhammad], 'Have you considered: if your water were to become sunken [into the earth], then who could bring you [any] flowing water?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2462,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Deep. Depth",
      "hw": "گہرائی",
      "s": "« » meaning deep. In a general sense (1 verse: 22:27)",
      "d": "« » means the depth of anything and its opposite is « » meaning height. If the distance is in the horizontal (i.e., towards the edge) direction, then it is length or distance. And if it is straight and upwards from the ground, then it is height or « ». And if it is downwards from the ground or if one is standing above, then that same height is « » or depth. And « » means deep.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ»\nTranslation: They will come to you from every distant pass.\nSo here, the meaning of 'deep' is due to its relation to the distant « ». « » is the path between two mountains which passes through valleys and hills."
    }
  ],
  "537": [
    {
      "id": 2463,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Watering Place",
      "hw": "گھاٹ",
      "s": "« » A place for drinking and filling water. Watering place (2 verses: 2:60-7:160)",
      "d": "« » A place for drinking and filling water. Watering place. This word is general.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: All the people had come to know their (respective) watering places."
    },
    {
      "id": 2464,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Watering Place",
      "hw": "گھاٹ",
      "s": "« » meaning a place to drink water. (4 verses: 11:98-19:86-21:99-28:23)",
      "d": "« » means to reach the place of water for drinking. And its opposite is « », meaning to return from there after drinking water. And « » is that water which is prepared for travelers (Muf). Just as we prepare water tanks etc. for giving water to livestock, and « » also refers to a thirsty person (19/86).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَقۡدُمُ  قَوۡمَہٗ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ فَاَوۡرَدَہُمُ النَّارَ ؕ وَ بِئۡسَ الۡوِرۡدُ  الۡمَوۡرُوۡدُ»\nTranslation: He will precede his people on the Day of Resurrection and will lead them into the Fire. And evil is the watering place to which they will be led."
    }
  ],
  "538": [
    {
      "id": 2465,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Valley",
      "hw": "گھاٹی",
      "s": "« » A general word for valley (1 verse: 90:10)",
      "d": "« » means valley. Elevated land. Land empty of trees. Elevated path. (Manjid) And « » means to be clear and elevated (Manjid) and also means elevated and hard land (Muf). « » originally means both a valley and the path that ascends or descends from it (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  النَّجۡدَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: And We have shown him the two highways (Jalandhari).\nWe showed him two valleys (Osmani)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2466,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Pass",
      "hw": "گھاٹی",
      "s": "« » refers only to a pass that is difficult to traverse (2 verses: 90:11-90:12)",
      "d": "«عَقَبَۃ» «عَقَبَۃ» «فَلَا  اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡعَقَبَۃُ فَکُّ رَقَبَۃٍ» «عَقَبَۃ»"
    }
  ],
  "539": [
    {
      "id": 2467,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "house",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "« » means a place where a person resides with his family and spends the night, i.e., overnight stay. (48 verses: 2:125-2:127-2:158-2:189-3:49-3:96-3:97-3:154-4:15-4:81-4:100-5:2-5:97-7:74-8:5-8:35-10:87-11:73-12:23-14:37-15:82-16:68-16:80-17:93-22:26-22:29-22:33-24:27-24:29-24:36-24:61-26:149-27:52-28:12-29:41-33:13-33:33-33:34-33:53-43:33-43:34-51:36-52:4-59:2-65:1-66:11-71:28-106:3)",
      "d": "«بَاتَ» «بَیْت» «بَیْت» «بُیُوْت» «وَ قَرۡنَ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُنَّ وَ لَا تَبَرَّجۡنَ تَبَرُّجَ الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی» «بَیْت» «اَلْبَیْت» «اَلْخَلْقُ عَیَالُ اللہ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2468,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "house",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "« » means only residence, whether it is a place for overnight stay or not, so it is more specific than « ». (12 verses: 9:24-9:72-14:45-20:128-21:13-27:18-28:58-29:38-32:26-34:15-46:25-61:12)",
      "d": "«سَکَنَ» «مَسْکَنْ» «سَاکِنٌ» «مَسْکَن» «فَتِلۡکَ مَسٰکِنُہُمۡ لَمۡ تُسۡکَنۡ مِّنۡۢ  بَعۡدِہِمۡ  اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2469,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "house",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "« » is very commonly used for house. When it means house, it refers to the external aspect of the house, as there can be several « » within one « » (haveli). (30 verses: 2:94-6:32-6:127-6:135-7:78-7:91-7:145-7:169-10:25-11:65-12:109-13:22-13:24-13:25-13:31-13:42-14:28-16:30-28:37-28:77-28:83-29:37-29:64-33:29-35:35-38:46-40:39-40:52-41:28-59:9)",
      "d": "«دَار» «دَوْر» «دِیَار» «دَار» «دَار» «دَار» «دَار» «فَقَالَ تَمَتَّعُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِکُمۡ ثَلٰثَۃَ  اَیَّامٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2470,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "house",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "« » includes both the house and the household, family, all are included in this meaning. (69 verses: 2:196-2:126-2:217-3:121-4:25-4:35-4:58-4:75-4:92-5:89-6:131-7:83-7:94-7:100-7:123-10:24-11:40-11:45-11:46-11:81-11:117-12:26-12:62-12:65-12:88-12:93-15:65-18:71-18:77-19:16-19:55-20:10-20:29-20:132-21:76-21:84-23:27-24:27-26:169-26:170-27:7-27:34-27:49-27:57-28:4-28:15-28:29-28:59-29:31-29:32-29:33-29:34-35:43-36:50-37:76-37:134-38:43-39:15-42:45-48:11-48:12-48:26-51:26-52:26-66:6-75:33-83:31-84:9-84:13)",
      "d": "«اَھْل» «اَھْل» «اٰل» «اَہْلُ الرَّجُل» «قَرْیَۃ» «اَھْل» «وَ اِذۡ غَدَوۡتَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِکَ تُبَوِّئُ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مَقَاعِدَ لِلۡقِتَالِ»"
    }
  ],
  "540": [
    {
      "id": 2471,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "hour",
      "hw": "گھڑی",
      "s": "« » means any one of the hours of day and night. Time. The Hour (Resurrection). (8 verses: 7:34-9:117-10:45-10:49-16:61-30:55-34:30-46:35)",
      "d": "«سَاعَۃ» «سَاعَات» «سَاعَۃ» «لَمۡ  یَلۡبَثُوۡۤا اِلَّا سَاعَۃً  مِّنۡ نَّہَارٍ» «سَاعَۃ» «سَاعَاتِی» «سَاعَۃ» «لَقَدۡ تَّابَ اللّٰہُ عَلَی النَّبِیِّ وَ الۡمُہٰجِرِیۡنَ وَ الۡاَنۡصَارِ الَّذِیۡنِ اتَّبَعُوۡہُ فِیۡ سَاعَۃِ الۡعُسۡرَۃِ» «اَلسَّاعَۃ» «حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ  بَغۡتَۃً»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2472,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "hour",
      "hw": "گھڑی",
      "s": "« » means the hours of the night. (4 verses: 3:113-20:130-39:9-57:16)",
      "d": "«اٰن» «اٰنَاء» «اَنٰی یَانِیْ» «اَنٰی» «اٰنَاء» «لَیْل» «اٰنَاء» «یَّتۡلُوۡنَ اٰیٰتِ اللّٰہِ اٰنَآءَ الَّیۡلِ  وَ ہُمۡ  یَسۡجُدُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "541": [
    {
      "id": 2474,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to enter",
      "hw": "گھسنا",
      "s": "« » is used for entering a tight place (8 verses: 3:27, 7:40, 22:61, 31:29, 34:2, 35:13, 57:4, 57:6)",
      "d": "«وَلَجَ» «وَ لَا یَدۡخُلُوۡنَ الۡجَنَّۃَ حَتّٰی یَلِجَ الۡجَمَلُ فِیۡ سَمِّ الۡخِیَاطِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2475,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to enter",
      "hw": "گھسنا",
      "s": "« » means to enter (a house or shop etc.) for loot and mischief (1 verse: 17:5)",
      "d": "«جَاسَ» «جَاسَ فِی الْبَیْت» «جَوَّاس» «بَعَثۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  عِبَادًا  لَّنَاۤ   اُولِیۡ  بَاۡسٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ فَجَاسُوۡا خِلٰلَ الدِّیَارِ»"
    }
  ],
  "542": [
    {
      "id": 2476,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To Drag",
      "hw": "گھسیٹنا",
      "s": "« » means to pull something upright so that it starts to drag, and if there is harshness and ruthlessness in this « », then it is « », and if something lying down is pulled, then it is « » (1 verse: 7:150)",
      "d": "«جَرّ» «جَرّ» «وَ اَخَذَ بِرَاۡسِ اَخِیۡہِ یَجُرُّہٗۤ اِلَیۡہِ» «جَیْشٌ جَرَّارٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2477,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to drag",
      "hw": "گھسیٹنا",
      "s": "« » to drag on the ground, to snatch, to control, to take back (2 verses: 40:71, 54:48)",
      "d": "In « », the aspect of dragging (being pulled along) is prominent, while the aspect of being drawn or pulled is less so. According to Imam Raghib, its meaning is to drag someone face down (muf). When a thing is in a lying position instead of standing, or moves horizontally (sideways) instead of straight, and it is dragged, this is « ». And « » means cloud. A cloud is called « » because the wind drags it along, and it moves forward as if being dragged (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یُسۡحَبُوۡنَ فِی النَّارِ عَلٰی وُجُوۡہِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: The Day they will be dragged on their faces into the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 2478,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to drag",
      "hw": "گھسیٹنا",
      "s": "« » means to pull forward with extreme force by placing something on the neck (1 verse: 44:47)",
      "d": "«عَتَلَ» «جَرّ» «خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ»"
    }
  ],
  "543": [
    {
      "id": 2479,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "horse",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "« » a common noun. Its usage is general for horses, for horse riders, and for a group (of horses) (4 verses: 3:14, 8:60, 16:8, 59:6)",
      "d": "« » is a common noun (ism jins). That is, it applies to all kinds of horses, whether male or female (muf). Then its usage also applies to a group or herd of horses, like « » meaning a flock of sheep. Additionally, it is also used for a horse rider (manj).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ الۡخَیۡلَ وَ الۡبِغَالَ وَ الۡحَمِیۡرَ لِتَرۡکَبُوۡہَا وَ زِیۡنَۃً»\nTranslation: And (He created) horses, mules, and donkeys for you to ride and as adornment.\nIn this verse, « » is used as a common noun. In the following verse, « » is used to mean horse riders or a group of horse riders and horses.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَجۡلِبۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِخَیۡلِکَ وَ رَجِلِکَ»\nTranslation: And charge against them with your horsemen and your foot soldiers.\nThe fundamental meaning of « » is the movement of various concepts in the mind (m, l). From this, the word « » (imagination) is derived. And « » refers to the pride and arrogance a horse rider feels when mounted compared to a pedestrian. From this, the word « » (conceit) is derived, meaning to know something with foresight (manj), high-flying."
    },
    {
      "id": 2480,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "horse",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "« » horses that stand on three legs, well-bred and sleek (1 verse: 38:31)",
      "d": "«صٰفِنٰت» «صافن» «صَفَنَ الْفَرَس»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ عُرِضَ عَلَیۡہِ بِالۡعَشِیِّ الصّٰفِنٰتُ الۡجِیَادُ»\nTranslation: When presented to him in the evening were the sleek, excellent (horses)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2481,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "horse",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "« » means swift and excellent horses (1 verse: 38:31)",
      "d": "«جِیَاد» «جَیَِّد» «جُوْد» «جَوَّاد» «جَادَ الْفَرْس» «جَیَِّد» «جِیَاد» «اِذۡ عُرِضَ عَلَیۡہِ بِالۡعَشِیِّ الصّٰفِنٰتُ الۡجِیَادُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2482,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "horse",
      "hw": "گھوڑا",
      "s": "« » horses that participate in races and are prepared for battle (1 verse: 100:1)",
      "d": "«عَادِیَات» «عَادِیَۃ» «عَادِیَۃٌ» «عَادِی» «عَادِی» «عَدَ الْفَرْس» «تَعَادَی الْقَوْم» «عَادِیَات»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا»\nTranslation: By the chargers at dawn, panting (hard)."
    }
  ],
  "544": [
    {
      "id": 2483,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to encircle",
      "hw": "گھیرنا",
      "s": "« » to mean only to encircle or to surround (2 verses: 18:32, 39:75)",
      "d": "«حَفَّ» «حَفَّہٗ بکذا» «مَحِفَّۃ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ حَفَفۡنٰہُمَا بِنَخۡلٍ وَّ جَعَلۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمَا زَرۡعًا»\nTranslation: And We surrounded them both with date-palms and placed between them a field of crops.\nAt another place, the Lord Almighty says:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ حَآفِّیۡنَ مِنۡ حَوۡلِ الۡعَرۡشِ»\nTranslation: And you will see the angels surrounding the Throne from all sides."
    },
    {
      "id": 2484,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to encircle",
      "hw": "گھیرنا",
      "s": "« » to encircle with the purpose of protection (7 verses: 2:81, 12:66, 17:60, 18:29, 48:21, 65:12, 72:28)",
      "d": "« » means to encircle, to build a wall around, to surround something in such a way that its protection is ensured (muf). In such a way that the thing itself cannot get out, nor can anyone else take it out. Just as the enclosure of a house is made with four walls.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ جَآءَہُمُ الۡمَوۡجُ مِنۡ کُلِّ مَکَانٍ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ اُحِیۡطَ بِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And the waves came upon them from every side, and they thought they were surrounded (by the sea).\nThis word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Lord Almighty says:\n«بَلٰی مَنۡ کَسَبَ سَیِّئَۃً وَّ اَحَاطَتۡ بِہٖ خَطِیۡٓئَتُہٗ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ اَصۡحٰبُ النَّارِ»\nTranslation: Yes indeed! Whoever earns evil and his sins have encompassed him, those are the companions of the Fire."
    },
    {
      "id": 2485,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to encircle",
      "hw": "گھیرنا",
      "s": "« » encirclement and confinement, i.e., to imprison something (4 verses: 2:196, 2:273, 4:90, 9:5)",
      "d": "« » means to besiege, to lay siege, to surround something in such a way that it remains confined and cannot get out (m, l, muf). To imprison, and to prevent any supplies (food, drink), aid (military support), or any kind of help from reaching them from outside.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ احۡصُرُوۡہُمۡ وَ اقۡعُدُوۡا لَہُمۡ کُلَّ مَرۡصَدٍ»\nTranslation: And besiege them and lie in wait for them at every ambush site."
    },
    {
      "id": 2486,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "to encompass",
      "hw": "گھیرنا",
      "s": "« » means to encompass someone with a calamity (10 verses: 6:10, 11:8, 16:34, 21:41, 35:43, 39:48, 40:45, 40:83, 45:33, 46:26)",
      "d": "«حَاقَ» «حَیْق» «وَ حَاقَ بِہِمۡ  مَّا کَانُوۡا بِہٖ یَسۡتَہۡزِءُوۡنَ» «وَ لَا یَحِیۡقُ الۡمَکۡرُ السَّیِّیئُ  اِلَّیۡ بِاَہۡلِہٖ»"
    }
  ],
  "545": [
    {
      "id": 2487,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Staff",
      "hw": "لاٹھی",
      "s": "« » means shepherd's staff. (12 verses: 2:60-7:107-7:117-7:160-20:18-20:66-26:32-26:44-26:45-26:63-27:10-28:31)",
      "d": "« » means shepherd's staff. A stout staff. Its plural is « ».\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ  فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ»\nTranslation: So when Moses (peace be upon him) threw his staff, it became a clear serpent."
    },
    {
      "id": 2488,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Staff",
      "hw": "لاٹھی",
      "s": "« » means the staff of a sick or weak person. (1 verse: 34:14)",
      "d": "« » means the staff of a sick or weak person (see p. 231).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضَیۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ الۡمَوۡتَ مَا دَلَّہُمۡ عَلٰی مَوۡتِہٖۤ اِلَّا دَآبَّۃُ الۡاَرۡضِ تَاۡکُلُ مِنۡسَاَتَہٗ»\nTranslation: Then when We decreed death for Solomon, nothing informed them of his death except the creature of the earth which was eating his staff.\nAnd a staff whose head is bent is called « » (see p. 231). « » and « » both do not have bent heads. « » is a thick and strong staff. And « » is a relatively thinner and well-shaped kind of staff."
    }
  ],
  "546": [
    {
      "id": 2489,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "« » means to bring, and its usage is general. (49 verses: 2:87-2:92-3:183-3:184-4:170-5:32-5:70-6:91-6:160-7:43-7:53-7:101-7:116-10:13-10:74-11:69-12:18-12:72-12:100-14:9-19:23-23:70-24:11-24:13-25:4-27:89-27:90-28:37-28:84-28:85-29:39-30:9-30:47-35:25-37:37-37:84-39:33-40:25-40:28-40:34-40:83-43:47-43:63-49:6-50:19-50:21-50:33-51:26-61:6)",
      "d": "« » means to bring, and its usage is general.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَقَدۡ کُذِّبَ رُسُلٌ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِکَ جَآءُوۡ بِالۡبَیِّنٰتِ»\nTranslation: So before you, messengers were denied who brought clear proofs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2490,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "«اَتٰی بِہٖ»",
      "d": "«اَتٰی بِہٖ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاۡتُوۡا بِسُوۡرَۃٍ مِّنۡ مِّثۡلِہٖ»\nTranslation: Then bring a surah like it."
    },
    {
      "id": 2491,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "« » when used to call and bring. (2 verses: 6:150-33:18)",
      "d": "« » is a verbal noun. Meaning call. That is, to call and bring someone repeatedly. This word is used both as intransitive and transitive. When intransitive, it gives the meaning of coming.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n« لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ ہَلُمَّ اِلَیۡنَا»\nTranslation: They say to their brothers, 'Come to us.'\nAnd when used transitively, it gives the meaning of bringing.\nFor example: The command of Allah is:\n«قُلۡ ہَلُمَّ  شُہَدَآءَکُمُ»\nTranslation: Say, 'Bring your witnesses.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2492,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "« » meaning bring here, bring hither. (4 verses: 2:111-21:24-27:64-28:75)",
      "d": "According to linguists, this word is originally « », which is the imperative plural masculine present form from « ». And this word is used as an imperative noun. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is also to call out. But according to some, its meanings are to bring here or bring quickly.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ ہَاتُوۡا بُرۡہَانَکُمۡ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Say, 'Bring your proof if you are truthful.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2493,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "« » to bring something forcibly, i.e., by compulsion and helplessness, or to be the cause of bringing. (1 verse: 19:23)",
      "d": "« » to bring something forcibly, i.e., by compulsion and helplessness, or to be the cause of bringing.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَجَآءَہَا الۡمَخَاضُ  اِلٰی جِذۡعِ  النَّخۡلَۃِ»\nTranslation: Then the pangs of childbirth brought her to the trunk of the palm tree."
    },
    {
      "id": 2494,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To bring",
      "hw": "لانا",
      "s": "« » to bring someone forcibly from behind by driving or urging. (1 verse: 17:64)",
      "d": "«جَلَبَ» «اَجْلَبَ عَلَیْہِ»\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَجۡلِبۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِخَیۡلِکَ وَ رَجِلِکَ»\nTranslation: And bring against them your cavalry and infantry."
    }
  ],
  "547": [
    {
      "id": 2495,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to be fitting",
      "hw": "لائق",
      "s": "« » means to be fitting. This word comes for an action for which it is appropriate (i.e., subject to it) (6 verses: 19:92, 25:18, 26:211, 36:40, 36:69, 38:35)",
      "d": "«اِنْبَغٰی» «ینبغی» «اَلنَّارُ یَنْبَغِیْ اَنْ یُّحْرِقَ الثَّوْبَ» «لَا الشَّمۡسُ یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہَاۤ اَنۡ تُدۡرِکَ الۡقَمَرَ» «وَ مَا عَلَّمۡنٰہُ الشِّعۡرَ وَ مَا یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہٗ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2496,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To be worthy",
      "hw": "لائق",
      "s": "« » is an intensive form and it comes for optional matters. (1 verse: 9:97)",
      "d": "«جَدَرَ» «اَجْدَر» «جَدِیْرُ الذِّکْر» «جَدِیْرُ الثَّنَاء»\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَلۡاَعۡرَابُ اَشَدُّ کُفۡرًا وَّ نِفَاقًا وَّ اَجۡدَرُ اَلَّا یَعۡلَمُوۡا حُدُوۡدَ  مَاۤ  اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ»\nTranslation: The bedouins are more severe in disbelief and hypocrisy, and it is more fitting that they should not know the limits of what Allah has revealed."
    },
    {
      "id": 2497,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to be worthy",
      "hw": "لائق",
      "s": "'Awla' is used in wider meanings than 'ajdar' and comes only for affirmation in optional matters. (5 verses: 3:68-4:135-8:75-19:70-33:6)",
      "d": "'Wali' means guardian, friend, and one meaning of 'mawali' is heir of the estate. And 'wala' means the estate of a freed slave and the right of guardianship. And 'awla' means more worthy, more suitable, more deserving. It comes for optional matters and only for affirmation. And it is stronger than 'yanbaghi' (m.f.) and only this form is used for it too. And its response will come with 'ba'. And its meaning will be: He is the one who is worthy of it, He is more suitable or deserving.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«ثُمَّ لَنَحۡنُ اَعۡلَمُ بِالَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ اَوۡلٰی بِہَا صِلِیًّا»\nTranslation: Then We are also well aware of those who are more worthy of entering Hell.\nAt another place, the divine declaration says:\n«اَلنَّبِیُّ  اَوۡلٰی بِالۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: The Prophet is more worthy of the believers than their own selves.\nAnd if the response of 'awla' comes with 'lam', then this word becomes a reproach, condemnation, and warning. Meaning: destruction, perdition, etc.\nFor example, the divine declaration says:\n«اَوۡلٰی لَکَ  فَاَوۡلٰی»\nTranslation: May destruction be for you, then may destruction be for you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2498,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to be worthy",
      "hw": "لائق",
      "s": "'Huqqa' means that doing such a thing is obligatory and deserving for it. (13 verses: 2:228-2:247-5:107-6:81-9:13-9:62-9:108-10:35-10:53-33:37-48:26-84:2-84:5)",
      "d": "'Haqqa' means to be established, to be obligatory. And 'huqqa an yaf'ala kaza' means that doing such a thing is obligatory and deserving for it (m.n.j.) meaning it was its right that it does so. Its usage is only in the affirmative.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِذَا السَّمَآءُ  انۡشَقَّتۡ وَ اَذِنَتۡ لِرَبِّہَا وَ حُقَّتۡ»\nTranslation: When the sky splits and listens to its Lord's command, and it is also obligatory for it."
    }
  ],
  "548": [
    {
      "id": 2500,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to wrap, to coil",
      "hw": "لپیٹنا",
      "s": "'Laff' means to place one thing on another and mix them, i.e., to combine. (2 verses: 17:104-75:29)",
      "d": "'Laff' means to mix one thing with another and combine them (m.f.) to layer one thing, then mix by layering another on top, then after that layer the third layer on top (m.l.)\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  جِئۡنَا بِکُمۡ  لَفِیۡفًا»\nTranslation: Then when the promise of the Hereafter comes, We will bring you all together in a wrapped state.\nAnd for 'to coil', 'iltaffa' will be used. Meaning: to cling and stick to one thing on another.\nFor example, the divine declaration says:\n«وَ الۡتَفَّتِ السَّاقُ بِالسَّاقِ . اِلٰی رَبِّکَ یَوۡمَئِذِ ۣ الۡمَسَاقُ»\nTranslation: And the shank will be wrapped with the shank. To your Lord will be the gathering on that day."
    },
    {
      "id": 2501,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to wrap, to coil",
      "hw": "لپیٹنا",
      "s": "'Kawwara' means to wrap in a round shape and to gather. (2 verses: 39:5-81:1)",
      "d": "'Kawwara' means to wrap something like a turban or scarf and turn it up and down. And 'iktaru al-farsi' means the horse turning its tail (m.f.). And for wrapping a scarf, 'laff' is also used. They say 'laffa'tu amamati 'ala ra'si' meaning I wrapped the scarf on my head. It is in the sense that one layer gathers on another. And for wrapping a scarf, the word 'kawwara' is stronger. Because in 'kawwara', both the concepts of gathering and roundness are present, which are found in a scarf.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«یُکَوِّرُ الَّیۡلَ عَلَی النَّہَارِ وَ یُکَوِّرُ النَّہَارَ عَلَی»\nTranslation: He wraps the night over the day and wraps the day over the night.\nAt another place, the divine declaration says:\n«اِذَا  الشَّمۡسُ کُوِّرَتۡ»\nTranslation: When the sun is wrapped up."
    }
  ],
  "549": [
    {
      "id": 2502,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to hang, to suspend",
      "hw": "لٹکانا",
      "s": "'Adla' means to hang something slowly and gently. (10 verses: 2:188-7:22-12:19-20:40-20:120-28:12-34:7-34:14-53:8-61:10)",
      "d": "'Dala' means to approach something with ease and gentleness (m.l.). 'Dalahu' means to behave with softness and consideration towards someone. And 'dalw' means to pull an empty bucket to lower and raise it in a well. And 'adla dalwahu' means he hung the empty bucket in the well to fill it with water.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ»\nTranslation: And a caravan came, and they sent their water-drawer, and he let down his bucket.\n'Tadalla' means to hang down by itself with ease and gentleness. They say 'tadallatha al-thamaru mina al-shajari' meaning the fruit hangs down from the tree.\nFor example, the divine declaration says:\n«ثُمَّ  دَنَا فَتَدَلّٰی»\nTranslation: Then he drew near and hung down."
    },
    {
      "id": 2503,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to hang, to suspend",
      "hw": "لٹکانا",
      "s": "'Alaqa' means to hang and entangle something. (1 verse: 4:129)",
      "d": "'Alaqa' means to get entangled in something. They say 'alqata al-saydu fi al-ju'alati' meaning the prey got entangled in the net. And 'alaqa' means to hang, to entangle. And 'alaqun' means a hanging thing.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَلَا تَمِیۡلُوۡا کُلَّ الۡمَیۡلِ فَتَذَرُوۡہَا کَالۡمُعَلَّقَۃِ»\nTranslation: So do not incline entirely to one side and leave her like the suspended one."
    }
  ],
  "550": [
    {
      "id": 2506,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to take heed, to be cautious",
      "hw": "لحاظ",
      "s": "'Raqiba' is used only for paying attention to something with a stern look or aversion. (3 verses: 9:8-9:10-20:94)",
      "d": "'Raqiba' means to keep an eye on someone's neck. To watch over sternly (m.f.). And also means to supervise, to guard, to wait (m.n.j.), to protect.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً»\nTranslation: They do not regard any kinship or treaty with a believer."
    },
    {
      "id": 2507,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "to take heed, to be cautious",
      "hw": "لحاظ",
      "s": "'Ra'a' means to protect something well and pay attention to it. (2 verses: 20:54-28:23)",
      "d": "'Ra'a' means to protect something well and pay attention to it (m.f.) to fulfill a covenant or responsibility and think about it. And 'ra'i' means a shepherd who is in charge of protecting his flock, and also means to protect something and to take measures to ward off external dangers. Its opposite is 'ihmal', meaning grazing the flock without a shepherd (f.q.l. 15).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِاَمٰنٰتِہِمۡ وَ عَہۡدِہِمْ رٰعُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And those who are to their trusts and their promises are protectors."
    }
  ],
  "551": [
    {
      "id": 2508,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army, host",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "'Jund' means a contingent of recruited armed armies. (7 verses: 19:75-36:28-36:75-37:173-38:11-44:24-67:20)",
      "d": "'Jund' is used for a military army and is a well-known word commonly used. 'Jundi' means military, and 'jannada' means to recruit in the army (m.n.j.). Its plural is 'junud'. Besides 'jund', another common word for army is 'jaysh', whose plural is 'juyush'. It is not used in the Quran, and another word is 'askar', whose plural is 'asakar'. This is also not in the Quran. 'Asakar' and 'juyush' are generally used for those armies that start gathering from different aspects upon the announcement of jihad, whether they have war equipment or not. And 'jund' refers only to an armed army.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَلَمَّا فَصَلَ طَالُوۡتُ بِالۡجُنُوۡدِ»\nTranslation: When Talut set out with the armies."
    },
    {
      "id": 2509,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army, host",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "'Fawj' means a group that passes quickly. (5 verses: 27:83-38:59-67:8-78:18-110:2)",
      "d": "'Fawj' means a group that passes quickly. A war contingent (m.f.). Its plural is 'afwaj'. And a larger group than 'ta'ifa' is called (f.l. 205), but in the Quran, this word generally comes in the meaning of 'a group'. It does not come in the meaning of a war contingent. Thus, the concept that arises from the word 'fauj' (army) today does not emerge from the Quran.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ یَوۡمَ نَحۡشُرُ مِنۡ کُلِّ اُمَّۃٍ  فَوۡجًا مِّمَّنۡ یُّکَذِّبُ بِاٰیٰتِنَا»\nTranslation: And on the Day We will gather from every nation a group of those who denied Our signs."
    },
    {
      "id": 2510,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "« » means party; political faction (17 verses: 5:56, 11:17, 13:36, 18:12, 19:37, 23:53, 30:32, 33:20, 33:22, 35:6, 38:11, 38:13, 40:5, 40:30, 43:65, 58:19, 58:22)",
      "d": "«حِزْب» «اَحْزَاب» «حَازَبَ» «حَزَّب» «حِزْب» «حِزْب» «یَحۡسَبُوۡنَ الۡاَحۡزَابَ لَمۡ  یَذۡہَبُوۡا ۚ وَ اِنۡ یَّاۡتِ الۡاَحۡزَابُ یَوَدُّوۡا لَوۡ اَنَّہُمۡ بَادُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَعۡرَابِ یَسۡاَلُوۡنَ عَنۡ اَنۡۢبَآئِکُمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2511,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "« » means a fighting group that has mutual cooperation among its members (9 verses: 2:249, 3:13, 4:88, 8:16, 8:19, 8:45, 8:48, 18:43, 28:81)",
      "d": "«فَاَیَ الرَّاْسَ فُلَانٌ» «فِئَۃ» «کَمۡ مِّنۡ فِئَۃٍ قَلِیۡلَۃٍ غَلَبَتۡ فِئَۃً  کَثِیۡرَۃًۢ بِاِذۡنِ  اللّٰہِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2512,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "« » means people setting out on an expedition or battle (11 verses: 4:71, 9:38, 9:39, 9:41, 9:81, 9:122, 17:6, 46:29, 18:34, 46:29, 72:1)",
      "d": "« » means to set out for battle or an expedition. « » has two meanings: (1) people marching to battle (2) a group of less than ten people (noun)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2513,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "army",
      "hw": "لشکر",
      "s": "« » means a small unit of brave cavalry (1 verse: 4:71)",
      "d": "«ثُبَاتٍ» «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا خُذُوۡا حِذۡرَکُمۡ فَانۡفِرُوۡا ثُبَاتٍ اَوِ انۡفِرُوۡا جَمِیۡعًا»"
    }
  ],
  "552": [
    {
      "id": 2514,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Wood",
      "hw": "لکڑی",
      "s": "« » is wood that is only fit for burning. (2 verses: 72:15-111:4)",
      "d": "«حَطَبَ» «وَّ  امۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ  الۡحَطَبِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2515,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Wood",
      "hw": "لکڑی",
      "s": "« » is wood that is useful. (1 verse: 63:4)",
      "d": "«خَشَبَ» «خُشُب» «کَاَنَّہُمۡ خُشُبٌ مُّسَنَّدَۃٌ»"
    }
  ],
  "553": [
    {
      "id": 2516,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Write",
      "hw": "لکھنا",
      "s": "« » means to draw lines, to mark, and to make them long in length. (1 verse: 29:48)",
      "d": "«خَطَّ» «مُخَلَّط» «خَطَّاط» «خَطَّ» «وَ مَا کُنۡتَ تَتۡلُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِہٖ مِنۡ کِتٰبٍ وَّ لَا تَخُطُّہٗ  بِیَمِیۡنِکَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2517,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Write",
      "hw": "لکھنا",
      "s": "« » means to write by forming lines, to write in one line. (4 verses: 17:58-33:6-52:2-68:1)",
      "d": "«سَطَرٌ» «سَطَرَ» «وَ الۡقَلَمِ وَ مَا یَسۡطُرُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2518,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Write",
      "hw": "لکھنا",
      "s": "« » is writing such that the script is clear and thick. (2 verses: 83:9-83:20)",
      "d": "«رَقَم» «مِرْقَمُ» «مَرْقُوم» «رَقَمَ» «کِتٰبٌ مَّرۡقُوۡمٌ یَّشۡہَدُہُ  الۡمُقَرَّبُوۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2519,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Write",
      "hw": "لکھنا",
      "s": "« » is writing that fully conveys its intended meaning. (40 verses: 2:79-2:178-2:180-2:183-2:187-2:216-2:246-2:282-3:53-3:154-3:181-4:66-4:77-4:81-4:127-5:21-5:32-5:45-5:83-6:12-6:54-7:145-7:156-9:51-9:120-9:121-10:21-19:79-21:105-22:4-36:12-43:19-43:80-52:41-57:27-58:21-58:22-59:3-68:47-98:3)",
      "d": "«کَتَبَ» «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا تَدَایَنۡتُمۡ بِدَیۡنٍ اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی فَاکۡتُبُوۡہُ»"
    }
  ],
  "554": [
    {
      "id": 2520,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To have written / To cause to be written",
      "hw": "لکھوانا",
      "s": "« » means to give something to be copied. To have written (1 Verse: 45:29)",
      "d": "«نَسْخُ الْکِتَاب» «نَسْخَة» «اِسْتَنْسَخَ»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ہٰذَا کِتٰبُنَا یَنۡطِقُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ اِنَّا کُنَّا نَسۡتَنۡسِخُ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: This Our Book will speak the truth about you. Indeed, We used to have recorded (or cause to be recorded) all that you used to do."
    },
    {
      "id": 2522,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To have written / To cause to be written",
      "hw": "لکھوانا",
      "s": "The usage of « » is generally for false and forged transcription (1 Verse: 25:5)",
      "d": "« » means to write, to have something written, to cause to be written, to request writing (Majid). The word « » is generally used in the context of false and fabricated writings (Mufradat).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡۤا اَسَاطِیۡرُ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ اکۡتَتَبَہَا فَہِیَ تُمۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِ بُکۡرَۃً وَّ اَصِیۡلًا»\nTranslation: And they (the disbelievers) say, 'These are the fables of the ancients; he has got them written down, and they are dictated to him morning and evening.'"
    }
  ],
  "555": [
    {
      "id": 2523,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The writer / The scribe",
      "hw": "لکھنے",
      "s": "« » is general; every person who writes anything is called a scribe (5 Verses: 2:282-2:283-21:94-24:33-82:11)",
      "d": "« » is any person who writes something. This word is well-known and its usage is general.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ وَّ لَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا کَاتِبًا فَرِہٰنٌ مَّقۡبُوۡضَۃٌ»\nTranslation: And if you are on a journey and cannot find a scribe, then take a pledge in hand (or with security)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2524,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The writer / The scribe",
      "hw": "لکھنے",
      "s": "« » means those who write blessed and pure writings (1 Verse: 80:15)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « ». « » means a book that unveils realities (M. L.), and « » means the Torah's expositions and interpretations. « » is a person who writes or composes such a writing. The angels who write the record of deeds. Those who write divinely inspired writings.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فِیۡ صُحُفٍ مُّکَرَّمَۃٍ مَّرۡفُوۡعَۃٍ مُّطَہَّرَۃٍۭ بِاَیۡدِیۡ سَفَرَۃٍ کِرَامٍۭ بَرَرَۃٍ»\nTranslation: (This revelation is) in honored, exalted, and purified pages, (written) by the hands of noble, pure, and most honorable scribes."
    }
  ],
  "556": [
    {
      "id": 2525,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "« » means successive, continuous; one after the other without a break in between (1 Verse: 23:44)",
      "d": "« » means one after the other in such a way that there is no interval between them (Majid). « » and « » are famous terms meaning that many can be simultaneous, but it is impossible that at any time none exist.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ اَرۡسَلۡنَا رُسُلَنَا تَتۡرًا»\nTranslation: Then We sent Our messengers in succession."
    },
    {
      "id": 2526,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "«عَلٰی فَتْرَۃٍ»",
      "d": "« » means the pace of an action becomes slow while doing it, and weakness (i.e., feebleness) occurs in it (M. L. Muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ قَدۡ جَآءَکُمۡ رَسُوۡلُنَا یُبَیِّنُ لَکُمۡ عَلٰی فَتۡرَۃٍ مِّنَ الرُّسُلِ»\nTranslation: O People of the Book! Our Messenger has come to you, clarifying for you after a break (or interval) in the messengers, lest you say, 'No bearer of good news or warner has come to us.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2527,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "« » means relentless and successive calamity and ill-omen that erases name and trace (1 Verse: 69:7)",
      "d": "«حَسَمَ» «حَسْمُ الدَّاءِ» «نَاَلَہٗ حُسُوْمًا» «حَسَمَ» «حَسَمَ الْعِرْق» «حُسُوْم» «حُسُوْم»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَمَّا عَادٌ فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍ عَاتِیَۃٍ . سَخَّرَہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَبۡعَ لَیَالٍ وَّ ثَمٰنِیَۃَ اَیَّامٍ ۙ حُسُوۡمًا ۙ فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی»\nTranslation: And as for 'Ad, they were destroyed by a furious, violent wind, which He imposed on them for seven nights and eight days, so you would see the people therein prostrate as if they were trunks of hollow palm trees."
    },
    {
      "id": 2528,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "« » means one after the other when they are also helpers to each other (2 Verses: 8:9-27:72)",
      "d": "«رَدِفَ» «اَرْدَفَ» «تَرَادَفَ» «اِرْدَافُ الْمُلُوْک»\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡنَ رَبَّکُمۡ فَاسۡتَجَابَ لَکُمۡ اَنِّیۡ مُمِدُّکُمۡ بِاَلۡفٍ مِّنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ مُرۡدِفِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: When you asked help of your Lord, He answered you, 'Indeed, I will reinforce you with a thousand angels, coming in succession.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 2529,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "« » means to go on continuously with effort and toil (2 Verses: 12:47-14:33)",
      "d": "« » means to continue doing a thing with effort and toil (Majid). To proceed continuously and without interruption (Muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ دَآئِبَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: And He has subjected for you the sun and the moon, both constantly pursuing their courses."
    },
    {
      "id": 2530,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous / Successive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "« » means two things of the same kind coming one after the other such that no third thing intervenes between them (2 Verses: 4:92-58:4)",
      "d": "« » means two things coming one after another or being in such a succession that no third thing intervenes between them (Muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَنۡ لَّمۡ یَجِدۡ فَصِیَامُ شَہۡرَیۡنِ مُتَتَابِعَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: But whoever cannot find (the means for freeing a slave) – then a fast for two consecutive months (is prescribed) as a penalty."
    },
    {
      "id": 2531,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Continuous; Consecutive",
      "hw": "لگاتار",
      "s": "« » means to join one thing with another in such a way that the possibility of a pause is completely eliminated (18 verses: 2:27-4:10-4:90-6:136-11:81-13:21-13:25-14:29-17:18-28:35-28:51-38:56-58:8-82:15-84:12-87:12-92:15-111:3)",
      "d": "«وَصَلَ» «وَصَّلَ» «وَاصِلُ الشَّیء» «وَاصِلُ بِالشَّیء» «وَ لَقَدۡ وَصَّلۡنَا لَہُمُ الۡقَوۡلَ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَذَکَّرُوۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "557": [
    {
      "id": 2532,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "« » means for something to return to its beginning or origin (98 verses: 2:18-2:28-2:196-2:210-2:245-2:281-3:55-3:72-3:83-3:109-5:48-5:105-6:36-6:60-6:108-6:164-7:150-7:168-7:174-8:44-9:83-9:94-9:122-10:4-10:23-10:46-10:56-10:70-11:4-11:34-11:123-12:46-12:50-12:62-12:63-12:81-19:40-20:40-20:86-20:89-20:91-21:13-21:35-21:58-21:64-21:95-22:76-23:99-23:115-24:28-24:64-27:28-27:35-27:37-28:39-28:70-28:88-29:8-29:17-29:57-30:11-30:41-31:15-31:23-32:11-32:12-32:21-33:13-34:31-35:4-36:22-36:31-36:50-36:67-36:83-37:68-39:7-39:44-40:77-41:21-41:50-43:28-43:48-43:85-45:15-46:27-50:3-56:87-57:5-57:13-60:10-63:8-67:3-67:4-86:8-86:11-89:28-96:8)",
      "d": "«رَجَعَ» «کُلُّ شَیْءٍ یَرْجِعْ اِلٰی اَصْلِہٖ» «الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ  اَصَابَتۡہُمۡ مُّصِیۡبَۃٌ   ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا لِلّٰہِ وَ  اِنَّاۤ اِلَیۡہِ رٰجِعُوۡنَ» «اَرْجَعَ» «وَ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ تُرۡجَعُ  الۡاُمُوۡرُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2533,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "« » means for a living being to return, with or without intention. « » means for a living being to return frequently with intention (7 verses: 17:25-38:17-38:19-38:30-38:44-50:32-88:25)",
      "d": "«اٰبَ» «رَجَعَ» «مَاٰب» «اَیَاب» «ذِھَاب و اِیَاب» «اٰبَ» «اِنَّ  اِلَیۡنَاۤ  اِیَابَہُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِنَّ  عَلَیۡنَا حِسَابَہُمۡ» «اٰوَبَ» «اَوَّبَ» «اَوَّاب» «فَاِنَّہٗ  کَانَ  لِلۡاَوَّابِیۡنَ غَفُوۡرًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2534,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "« » means to revert from sinful deeds (62 verses: 2:37-2:54-2:128-2:160-2:187-2:222-3:89-3:90-3:128-4:16-4:17-4:18-4:26-4:27-4:64-4:92-4:146-5:34-5:39-5:71-5:74-6:54-7:153-9:5-9:11-9:15-9:27-9:74-9:102-9:104-9:106-9:117-9:118-9:126-11:3-11:52-11:61-11:90-11:112-13:30-16:119-19:60-20:82-20:122-24:5-24:10-24:31-25:70-25:71-28:67-33:24-33:73-40:3-40:7-42:25-49:12-58:13-66:4-66:8-73:20-85:10-110:3)",
      "d": "«تَابَ» «اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ تَابُوۡا وَ اَصۡلَحُوۡا وَ بَیَّنُوۡا فَاُولٰٓئِکَ اَتُوۡبُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ۚ وَ اَنَا التَّوَّابُ الرَّحِیۡمُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2535,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "« » means to keep returning repeatedly (6 verses: 13:27-31:15-38:24-38:34-39:17-60:4)",
      "d": "«نَابَ اِلَیْہِ» «نَوْبَۃ» «اَنَاب» «اَنَابَ اِلَی اللہ» «رَبَّنَا عَلَیۡکَ تَوَکَّلۡنَا وَ اِلَیۡکَ اَنَبۡنَا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2536,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "« » means to return to a bad state (5 verses: 2:61-2:90-3:112-3:162-8:16)",
      "d": "«بَوْء» «وَ بَآءُوۡ بِغَضَبٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ  ؕ ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمۡ کَانُوۡا یَکۡفُرُوۡنَ بِاٰیٰتِ اللّٰہِ وَ یَقۡتُلُوۡنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ بِغَیۡرِ الۡحَقِّ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2538,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "« » means to return after quenching thirst at a well or trough (2 verses: 28:23-99:6)",
      "d": "«صَدَرَ» «اَصْدَر» «صَدَرَتِ الْاِبِلُ مِنَ الْمَاءِ» «قَالَتَا لَا نَسۡقِیۡ حَتّٰی یُصۡدِرَ الرِّعَآءُ» «صَدَرَ» «وَرَدَ» «وِرْدُ» «وَارِد» «وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2539,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "« » means to ultimately return, to end up (29 verses: 2:126-2:285-3:28-3:162-4:97-4:115-5:18-8:16-9:73-14:30-22:48-22:72-24:42-24:57-25:15-31:14-35:18-40:3-42:15-42:53-48:6-50:43-57:15-58:8-60:4-64:3-64:10-66:9-67:6)",
      "d": "«صَیْر» «اَلَاۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ  تَصِیۡرُ الۡاُمُوۡرُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2541,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "« » means to change one's direction or state completely to the opposite of what it was (32 verses: 2:143-2:144-3:127-3:144-3:149-3:174-3:196-5:21-6:110-7:119-7:125-9:48-9:95-12:62-16:46-18:18-18:36-22:11-24:37-24:44-26:50-26:219-26:227-29:21-33:66-40:4-43:14-47:19-48:12-67:4-83:31-84:9)",
      "d": "«قَلَبَ» «اِنْقَلَبَ» «سَیَحۡلِفُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ لَکُمۡ اِذَا انۡقَلَبۡتُمۡ اِلَیۡہِمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2542,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "To return; To bring back; To revert",
      "hw": " رجوع",
      "s": "« » means to return in a continuous flow or throng (6 verses: 2:199-5:83-7:50-9:92-10:61-46:8)",
      "d": "«فَاضَ الْمَاءَ» «اَفَاضَ الْاِنَاءَ» «ثُمَّ  اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ»"
    }
  ],
  "558": [
    {
      "id": 2544,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The Preserved Tablet and Its Various Types",
      "hw": "لوح محفوظ",
      "s": "«اللوح المحفوظ»",
      "d": "«اللوح المحفوظ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَلۡ ہُوَ  قُرۡاٰنٌ  مَّجِیۡدٌ فِیۡ  لَوۡحٍ مَّحۡفُوۡظٍ»\nTranslation: Rather, it is a Glorious Quran, (inscribed) in a Preserved Tablet.\nFrom this, it is known that the Noble Quran has been taken from the Preserved Tablet."
    },
    {
      "id": 2545,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The Preserved Tablet and Its Various Types",
      "hw": "لوح محفوظ",
      "s": "«أُمُّ الْكِتَاب»",
      "d": "«أُمُّ الْكِتَاب»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا جَعَلۡنٰہُ  قُرۡءٰنًا عَرَبِیًّا  لَّعَلَّکُمۡ تَعۡقِلُوۡنَ وَ اِنَّہٗ  فِیۡۤ  اُمِّ الۡکِتٰبِ لَدَیۡنَا لَعَلِیٌّ حَکِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: Indeed, We have made it an Arabic Quran that you might understand. And indeed, it is, in the Mother of the Book with Us, exalted in position and full of wisdom.\nBy stating in the Quran that it is in the 'Umm al-Kitab', an important reality is clarified: that the various Books revealed to different Prophets in different times and for different nations and peoples all invited to the same creed. The standard of good and evil is the same, and the principles of morality and civilization are uniform. That is, the religion has been one. As for the Shariah, the divine command regarding change in legal rulings according to circumstances and conditions is:\n«یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ   ۚ ۖ وَ عِنۡدَہٗۤ   اُمُّ   الۡکِتٰبِ»\nTranslation: Allah eliminates what He wills and confirms what He wills. And with Him is the Mother of the Book.\nThis verse shows that the record of changes and alterations in legal rulings across different times is also present in this Book."
    },
    {
      "id": 2546,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The Preserved Tablet and Its Various Types",
      "hw": "لوح محفوظ",
      "s": "«إِمَامٌ مُبِین»",
      "d": "«إِمَامٌ مُبِین»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ كُلَّ شَیۡءٍ اَحۡصَیۡنٰہُ  فِیۡۤ   إِمَامٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ»\nTranslation: And We have encompassed all things in a clear Book (Imam Mubin)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2547,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "The Preserved Tablet and Its Various Types",
      "hw": "لوح محفوظ",
      "s": "«كِتَابٌ مَّكْنُوْن»",
      "d": "«كِتَابٌ مَّكْنُوْن»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّہٗ   لَقُرۡاٰنٌ   کَرِیۡمٌ فِیۡ  كِتٰبٍ مَّکۡنُوۡنٍ»\nTranslation: Indeed, it is a noble Quran, in a well-protected Book.\nFrom this verse, it is known that the details of what is written in it are known to no one besides Allah, not even to Gabriel (peace be upon him), who is the means of conveying revelation to the Prophets."
    }
  ],
  "559": [
    {
      "id": 2548,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Female Slave / Male Slave",
      "hw": "غلام",
      "s": "« » (Abd) meaning slave. (123 Verses: 2:23-2:90-2:178-2:186-2:207-2:221-3:15-3:20-3:30-3:79-4:118-4:172-5:118-6:18-6:61-6:88-7:32-7:128-7:194-8:41-9:104-10:107-12:24-14:11-14:31-15:40-15:42-15:49-16:2-16:75-17:1-17:3-17:5-17:17-17:30-17:53-17:65-17:96-18:1-18:65-18:102-18:110-19:2-19:30-19:61-19:63-19:93-20:77-21:26-21:105-23:109-24:32-25:1-25:17-25:58-25:63-26:22-26:52-27:15-27:19-27:59-28:82-29:56-29:62-30:48-34:9-34:13-34:39-35:28-35:31-35:32-35:45-36:30-37:40-37:74-37:81-37:111-37:122-37:128-37:132-37:160-37:169-37:171-38:17-38:30-38:41-38:44-38:45-38:83-39:7-39:10-39:16-39:17-39:36-39:46-39:53-40:15-40:31-40:44-40:48-40:85-42:19-42:23-42:25-42:27-42:52-43:15-43:19-43:59-43:68-44:18-44:23-50:8-50:11-53:10-54:9-57:9-66:10-71:27-72:19-76:6-89:29-96:10)",
      "d": "«عَبْد» «عَبَادَۃ» «عَبُوْدِیَت» «عَبْد» «عَبْد» «عَبْد» «عِبَاد» «عَبِیْد» «عَبْد» «عَبدُ الدِّرْہم» «عَبدُ الدِّیْنَار» «عَبدُ الطَّاغُوت» «عَبْد» «حُرّ» «عَبَّدَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلۡحُرُّ بِالۡحُرِّ وَ الۡعَبۡدُ بِالۡعَبۡدِ وَ الۡاُنۡثٰی بِالۡاُنۡثٰی»\nTranslation: The free for the free, the slave for the slave, and the female for the female."
    },
    {
      "id": 2549,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Female Slave / Male Slave",
      "hw": "غلام",
      "s": "« » (Ama) meaning female slave. (2 Verses: 2:221-24:32)",
      "d": "« » is the feminine form of « ». It means female slave. This word is also used in all the same senses in which « » is used. The plural of « » is « ».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ أَنكِحُوا الأَيَامَى مِنكُمۡ وَ الصَّالِحِینَ مِنۡ عِبَادِكُمۡ وَ إِمَاءِكُمۡ»\nTranslation: And marry the unmarried among you and the righteous among your male slaves and female slaves.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ لَا أَمَةٌ مُؤْمِنَةٌ خَيْرٌ مِن مُشْرِكَةٍ وَلَوْ أَعْجَبَتْكُم»\nTranslation: And a believing female slave is better than a polytheist woman, even if she pleases you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2550,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Female Slave / Male Slave",
      "hw": "غلام",
      "s": "« » (Raqabah) meaning slave or female slave, regardless of how they come into one's possession. (4 Verses: 4:92-5:89-58:3-90:13)",
      "d": "«رَقَبَۃ» «رَقَبَ» «جُزْءُ أَشَرْف» «رَقَبَۃ» «رِقَاب» «رَقَبَۃ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ آتَی الْمَالَ عَلَى حُبِّهِ ذَوِي الْقُرْبَى وَ الْیَتَامَى وَ الْمَسَاکِینَ وَ ابْنَ السَّبِیلِ وَ السَّائِلِینَ وَ فِی الرِّقَابِ»\nTranslation: And those who give wealth, in spite of love for it, to relatives, orphans, the needy, the traveler, those who ask, and for freeing necks (i.e., slaves). (Jalandhari)"
    }
  ],
  "560": [
    {
      "id": 2552,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Take",
      "hw": "لینا",
      "s": "« » (Akhadha) meaning to acquire something, to take into possession, to seize. (121 Verses: 2:48-2:55-2:63-2:83-2:84-2:93-2:206-2:229-2:255-2:260-2:267-3:11-3:81-3:160-3:187-4:20-4:21-4:71-4:89-4:91-4:102-4:118-4:153-4:154-4:161-5:12-5:14-5:41-5:70-6:42-6:44-6:46-6:70-7:31-7:73-7:78-7:91-7:94-7:95-7:96-7:130-7:144-7:145-7:150-7:154-7:155-7:165-7:169-7:171-7:172-7:199-8:52-8:68-8:70-9:5-9:50-9:103-9:104-10:24-11:56-11:64-11:67-11:94-11:102-12:76-12:78-12:79-12:80-13:32-15:73-15:83-16:46-16:47-16:113-18:77-18:79-19:12-19:78-19:87-20:21-20:39-20:94-22:44-22:48-23:41-23:64-23:76-24:2-26:189-28:40-29:14-29:37-29:40-33:7-33:61-34:51-35:26-36:49-38:44-40:5-40:21-40:22-41:17-43:48-44:47-48:15-48:19-48:20-51:16-51:40-51:44-54:42-55:41-57:8-57:15-59:7-69:10-69:30-69:45-73:16-79:25)",
      "d": "« » means to acquire something, to take into possession, to seize. (See Mufradat). Its usage is both literal (i.e., for something perceptible by one of the five senses) and metaphorical.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ إِذْ أَخَذَ اللَّهُ مِيثَاقَ النَّبِيِّینَ»\nTranslation: And when Allah took the covenant from the Prophets.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَلَمَّا سَكَتَ عَن مُوسَى الْغَضَبُ أَخَذَ الْأَلْوَاحَ»\nTranslation: And when the anger subsided from Moses, he took up the tablets."
    },
    {
      "id": 2553,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Take",
      "hw": "لینا",
      "s": "« » (Talaqqa) meaning to reach something and take it. (4 Verses: 3:143-21:103-24:15-50:17)",
      "d": "«لَقِیَ» «تَلَقَّی الشَّیْء» «تَلَقَّی»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا يَحْزُنُهُمُ الْفَزَعُ الْأَكْبَرُ وَ تَتَلَقَّاهُمُ الْمَلَائِكَةُ»\nTranslation: The greatest terror will not grieve them, and the angels will meet them (to receive them)."
    }
  ],
  "561": [
    {
      "id": 2555,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "To Lend/Borrow",
      "hw": "لین دین",
      "s": "« » (Tadayan) is used for lending and borrowing by hand (i.e., physically handing over). And « » (Adara) is used for lending and borrowing on credit. (1 Verse: 2:282)",
      "d": "« » (Dayn) means loan, credit (see details under 'Adhar'). And « » (Tadayana) means to borrow from each other on credit, to lend and borrow on credit (See Manjad).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَا أَیُّهَا الَّذِینَ آمَنُوا إِذَا تَدَایَنْتُم بِدَیْنٍ إِلَى أَجَلٍ مُسَمًّی فَاكْتُبُوهُ»\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you contract a debt for a specified term, write it down."
    },
    {
      "id": 2556,
      "a": "ل",
      "h": "Lending and borrowing",
      "hw": "لین دین",
      "s": "«adara» means to circulate, to rotate. (1 verse: 2:282)",
      "d": "«dawar, dara» means to revolve, to circulate. And «adarah» means to circulate, to rotate. And «adara al-shay'» means to take and give something.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ تَکُوۡنَ تِجَارَۃً حَاضِرَۃً  تُدِیۡرُوۡنَہَا بَیۡنَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: Yes, if the trade is hand-to-hand (immediate), then you take and give among yourselves (there is no need to write it down)."
    }
  ],
  "562": [
    {
      "id": 2557,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«daraba» means to hit someone with a hand or something else. (13 verses: 2:60-2:61-2:73-3:112-4:34-7:160-8:12-8:50-26:63-37:93-38:44-47:4-47:27)",
      "d": "«daraba» generally, its pattern has « », meaning to hit someone with a hand or something else. And after the pattern « », the thing is mentioned with which one is hit. That is, the instrument of hitting. This word is commonly used for hitting (f l 188).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ»\nTranslation: So we said to Moses: Strike the rock with your staff."
    },
    {
      "id": 2558,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«wakaza» means to strike with the heel. (1 verse: 28:15)",
      "d": "«wakaza» means to strike with the heel. And according to the scholar of language, to strike with the palm or heel on the chest or side (f l 188).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَوَکَزَہٗ  مُوۡسٰی فَقَضٰی عَلَیۡہِ»\nTranslation: So Moses struck him with his heel, and he died."
    },
    {
      "id": 2559,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«sakka» means to slap with the hand on the face. (1 verse: 51:29)",
      "d": "«sakka» means for two things to strike each other with force and intensity so that a sound is produced. «sakka al-baba» means the door's latch striking each other (m l). And it means to slap on the face, to give a slap, to slap the face (f l 188).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَصَکَّتۡ وَجۡہَہَا وَ قَالَتۡ عَجُوۡزٌ  عَقِیۡمٌ»\nTranslation: So she (the woman) slapped her face and said, 'Am I an old barren woman?' (that a boy is born?)"
    },
    {
      "id": 2560,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«dalla» means to push. (2 verses: 52:13-107:2)",
      "d": "«dalla» means to push. To repel with force (f l 188).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَذٰلِکَ الَّذِیۡ یَدُعُّ  الۡیَتِیۡمَ»\nTranslation: So such a man pushes the orphan."
    },
    {
      "id": 2561,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«damagha» means to strike on the head or brain. (1 verse: 21:18)",
      "d": "«damagha» means to strike someone on the brain or head (muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«بَلۡ نَقۡذِفُ بِالۡحَقِّ عَلَی الۡبَاطِلِ فَیَدۡمَغُہٗ»\nTranslation: Rather, we cast truth upon falsehood, so it smashes its brain."
    },
    {
      "id": 2562,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«rajama» means to stone from a distance. To stone to death. (6 verses: 11:91-18:20-18:22-19:46-36:18-44:20)",
      "d": "«rajama» «رَجْمًا بِالْغَیْب»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا رَہۡطُکَ لَرَجَمۡنٰکَ»\nTranslation: If it were not for your clan, we would have stoned you."
    },
    {
      "id": 2563,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«waqadha» means to deliver a severe blow with a stick or stone. (1 verse: 5:3)",
      "d": "«waqadha» means to deliver a severe blow with a stick or stone so that it dies. And «waqadh» means severe blow (muf). And «waqadha» means lethal, i.e., delivering a blow that causes destruction (minjad)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2564,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To hit",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«nataha» means for an animal to strike with its horns. (1 verse: 5:3)",
      "d": "«nataha» «تَنَاطَعَ الْکَبْشَان» «نَطِیْح»\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ الۡمُنۡخَنِقَۃُ وَ الۡمَوۡقُوۡذَۃُ وَ الۡمُتَرَدِّیَۃُ وَ النَّطِیۡحَۃُ»\nTranslation: The animal that dies by strangulation, by a violent blow, by a fall, or by horn strike (all these are forbidden to you)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2566,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To kill; to die",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "«mata» means the soul separating from the body. It is general. (30 verses: 2:28-2:161-2:258-2:259-3:91-3:144-3:156-6:122-6:162-7:158-9:84-9:116-9:125-10:56-15:23-17:75-22:58-22:66-23:80-26:81-30:40-40:68-44:8-45:21-45:26-47:34-50:43-53:44-57:2-80:21)",
      "d": "«mata» means death, and its opposite is «hayat» meaning life. «mata» means for a living being to lose its soul or power (m l). The separation of soul from the body. To die. In any form.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا وَ مَاتُوۡا وَ ہُمۡ کُفَّارٌ»\nTranslation: Indeed, those who disbelieved and died while they were disbelievers.\nAnd «amata» means to cause death to someone else. To end their life.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«ثُمَّ یُمِیۡتُکُمۡ ثُمَّ یُحۡیِیۡکُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِلَیۡہِ تُرۡجَعُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Then He will cause you to die, then He will give you life, then to Him you will be returned."
    },
    {
      "id": 2567,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "« » means to kill someone unjustly. And « » means to kill in a brutal manner. (77 verses: 2:54-2:61-2:72-2:85-2:87-2:91-2:154-2:178-2:191-2:217-2:251-3:21-3:112-3:144-3:154-3:156-3:157-3:158-3:168-3:169-3:181-3:183-3:195-4:29-4:66-4:74-4:89-4:91-4:92-4:93-4:155-4:157-5:27-5:28-5:30-5:32-5:33-5:70-5:95-6:137-6:140-6:151-7:127-7:141-7:150-8:17-8:30-9:5-9:111-12:9-12:10-17:31-17:33-18:74-20:40-22:58-25:68-26:14-28:9-28:19-28:20-28:33-29:24-33:16-33:26-33:61-40:25-40:26-40:28-47:4-51:10-60:12-74:19-74:20-80:17-81:9-85:4)",
      "d": "«قَتَلَ» «قَالَ اَقَتَلۡتَ نَفۡسًا زَکِیَّۃًۢ بِغَیۡرِ نَفۡسٍ» «قَتَّلَ» «قَالَ سَنُقَتِّلُ اَبۡنَآءَہُمۡ وَ نَسۡتَحۡیٖ نِسَآءَہُمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2568,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "« » means to perish, to die helplessly, and it is used for non-living things as well. (63 verses: 2:195-2:205-3:117-4:176-5:17-6:6-6:26-6:47-6:131-7:4-7:129-7:155-7:164-7:173-8:42-8:54-9:42-10:13-11:117-12:85-14:13-15:4-17:16-17:17-17:58-18:59-19:74-19:98-20:128-20:134-21:6-21:9-21:95-22:45-23:48-26:139-26:208-27:49-28:43-28:58-28:59-28:78-28:88-29:31-32:26-36:31-38:3-40:34-43:8-44:37-45:24-46:27-46:35-47:13-50:36-53:50-54:51-67:28-69:5-69:6-69:29-77:16-90:6)",
      "d": "«ھَلَکَ» «اِنِ امۡرُؤٌا ہَلَکَ لَیۡسَ لَہٗ وَلَدٌ» «کُلُّ شَیۡءٍ ہَالِکٌ اِلَّا وَجۡہَہٗ» «اَہۡلَکَ» «قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَہۡلَکَنِیَ اللّٰہُ وَ مَنۡ مَّعِیَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2569,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "« » means to crucify. « » means to crucify with torture. (6 verses: 4:157-5:33-7:124-12:41-20:71-26:49)",
      "d": "«صَلَبَ» «صَلَّبَ» «وَ مَا قَتَلُوۡہُ وَ مَا صَلَبُوۡہُ وَ لٰکِنۡ شُبِّہَ لَہُمۡ» «صَلَّبَ» «فَلَاُقَطِّعَنَّ اَیۡدِیَکُمۡ وَ اَرۡجُلَکُمۡ مِّنۡ خِلَافٍ وَّ لَاُصَلِّبَنَّکُمۡ فِیۡ جُذُوۡعِ النَّخۡلِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2570,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "« » means to kill by inflicting pain intermittently. (9 verses: 2:49-2:67-2:71-5:3-14:6-27:21-28:4-37:102-37:107)",
      "d": "«ذَبَحَ» «ذَبَّحَ» «ذَبَّحَ» «قَتَّلَ» «یُذَبِّحُ اَبۡنَآءَہُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیٖ نِسَآءَہُمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2571,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "« » means to stone to death. To kill by throwing stones. (6 verses: 11:91-18:20-18:22-19:46-36:18-44:20)",
      "d": "«رَجَمَ» «رَجَم» «لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ تَنۡتَہِ لَاَرۡجُمَنَّکَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2572,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "« » means for a living being to die by strangulation. (1 verse: 5:3)",
      "d": "«خَنَقَ» «خِنَاق» «خُنَّاق» «خَنَقَ» «مُنْخَنِقٌ» «وَ الۡمُنۡخَنِقَۃُ وَ الۡمَوۡقُوۡذَۃُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2573,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Killing / Dying",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "« » means to complete the lifespan, to take the soul. This is solely the act of Allah the Almighty or His appointed angels. (30 verses: 2:234-2:240-2:281-3:55-3:161-3:185-3:193-4:15-4:97-5:117-6:60-6:61-7:37-7:126-8:50-10:46-10:104-12:101-13:40-16:28-16:32-16:70-16:111-22:5-32:11-39:42-40:67-40:77-47:27-83:2)",
      "d": "«وَفٰی» «تَوَفّٰی» «تَوَفَّنِیۡ مُسۡلِمًا وَّ اَلۡحِقۡنِیۡ بِالصّٰلِحِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2574,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To Kill; To Die",
      "hw": "مارنا",
      "s": "« » is to give up one's life in the way of Allah. (60 verses: 2:23-2:84-2:133-2:143-2:185-2:204-2:282-3:18-3:52-3:64-3:70-3:81-3:86-3:99-3:140-4:6-4:15-4:69-4:135-4:166-5:8-5:44-5:111-6:19-6:130-6:144-6:150-7:37-7:172-9:107-11:54-12:26-12:81-18:51-19:37-21:61-22:28-22:78-24:2-24:4-24:6-24:8-24:13-24:24-25:72-27:32-27:49-36:65-39:69-41:20-41:21-41:22-43:19-43:86-46:10-57:19-59:11-63:1-65:2-83:21)",
      "d": "«شَھِدَ» «شَاھِدْ» «شَھِیْد» «شَھِیْد» «فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ»"
    }
  ],
  "563": [
    {
      "id": 2577,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth, Giving",
      "hw": "مال",
      "s": "« » means all that which is physical or spiritual sustenance or a means to it. (105 verses: 2:3-2:22-2:25-2:57-2:60-2:126-2:172-2:212-2:233-2:254-3:27-3:37-3:169-4:5-4:8-4:39-5:88-5:114-6:140-6:142-6:151-7:32-7:50-7:160-8:3-8:4-8:26-8:74-10:31-10:59-10:93-11:6-11:88-12:37-13:22-13:26-14:31-14:32-14:37-16:56-16:67-16:71-16:72-16:73-16:75-16:112-16:114-17:30-17:31-17:70-18:19-19:62-20:81-20:131-20:132-22:28-22:34-22:35-22:50-22:58-24:26-24:38-27:64-28:54-28:57-28:82-29:17-29:60-29:62-30:28-30:37-30:40-32:16-33:31-34:4-34:15-34:24-34:36-34:39-35:3-35:29-36:47-37:41-38:54-39:52-40:13-40:40-40:64-42:12-42:19-42:27-42:38-45:5-45:16-50:11-51:22-51:57-56:82-63:10-65:3-65:7-65:11-67:15-67:21-89:16)",
      "d": "«رِزْق» «رِزْق» «مَرْزُوْق» «رُزِقْتُ عِلْمًا» «رِزْق» «رِزْق» «وَ فِی السَّمَآءِ رِزۡقُکُمۡ» «رَزَقَ» «رَزَّاق» «وَ اِذَا حَضَرَ الۡقِسۡمَۃَ اُولُوا الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنُ فَارۡزُقُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡہُ وَ قُوۡلُوۡا لَہُمۡ قَوۡلًا مَّعۡرُوۡفًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2578,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth, Giving",
      "hw": "مال",
      "s": "« » means the good aspect of wealth, i.e., wealth acquired and spent according to Shariah. (170 verses: 2:54-2:61-2:103-2:105-2:106-2:110-2:148-2:158-2:180-2:184-2:197-2:215-2:216-2:220-2:221-2:263-2:269-2:271-2:272-2:273-2:280-3:15-3:26-3:30-3:54-3:104-3:110-3:114-3:115-3:150-3:157-3:178-3:180-3:198-4:19-4:25-4:46-4:59-4:66-4:77-4:114-4:127-4:128-4:149-4:170-4:171-5:48-5:114-6:17-6:32-6:57-6:158-7:12-7:26-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:155-7:169-7:188-8:19-8:23-8:30-8:70-9:3-9:41-9:61-9:74-9:88-9:109-10:11-10:58-10:107-10:109-11:31-11:84-11:86-12:39-12:57-12:59-12:64-12:80-12:109-16:30-16:76-16:95-16:126-17:11-17:35-18:36-18:40-18:44-18:46-18:81-18:95-19:73-19:76-20:73-20:131-21:35-21:73-21:89-21:90-22:11-22:30-22:36-22:58-22:77-23:29-23:56-23:61-23:72-23:109-23:118-24:11-24:12-24:27-24:33-24:60-25:10-25:15-25:24-27:36-27:59-27:89-28:24-28:26-28:60-28:80-28:84-29:16-30:38-33:19-33:25-34:39-35:32-37:62-38:32-38:76-41:40-41:49-42:36-43:32-43:52-43:58-44:37-46:11-47:21-49:5-49:11-50:25-54:43-55:70-58:12-61:11-62:9-62:11-64:16-66:5-68:12-68:32-70:21-70:41-73:20-87:17-93:4-97:3-98:7-99:7-100:8)",
      "d": "«خَیْر» «قُلۡ مَاۤ اَنۡفَقۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ خَیۡرٍ فَلِلۡوَالِدَیۡنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنِ وَ ابۡنِ‌السَّبِیۡلِ» «وَ اِنَّہٗ لِحُبِّ الۡخَیۡرِ لَشَدِیۡدٌ» «اَنَّمَاۤ اَمۡوَالُکُمۡ وَ اَوۡلَادُکُمۡ فِتۡنَۃٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2580,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth and property, to grant",
      "hw": "مال",
      "s": "« » refers to wealth obtained after victory over an enemy (9 verses: 4:94-6:146-8:41-8:69-20:18-21:78-48:15-48:19-48:20)",
      "d": "«غَنَم» «اَلْغَنَمُ» «مَغْنَم» «مَغَانِم» «مَغْنَم» «فَکُلُوۡا مِمَّا غَنِمۡتُمۡ حَلٰلًا طَیِّبًا» «تَبۡتَغُوۡنَ عَرَضَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا ۫ فَعِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ مَغَانِمُ کَثِیۡرَۃٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2581,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Wealth and property, to grant",
      "hw": "مال",
      "s": "« » refers to wealth and belongings obtained in battle with disbelievers, which is also called spoils (1 verse: 8:1)",
      "d": "«نَفَل» «اَنْفَال» «نَفْل» «اَنْفَال» «یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡاَنۡفَالِ ؕ قُلِ الۡاَنۡفَالُ لِلّٰہِ وَ الرَّسُوۡلِ»"
    }
  ],
