      "a": "م",
      "h": "To ask/request",
      "hw": "مانگنا",
      "s": "« » meaning to come forward to ask for forgiveness (1 verse: 22:36)",
      "d": "«عَرّ» «اِعْتَرّ» «وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡقَانِعَ وَ الۡمُعۡتَرَّ»"
    }
  ],
  "567": [
    {
      "id": 2592,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "مٹانا",
      "s": "« » To erase by rubbing in such a way that some effects remain (5 verses: 4:47, 10:88, 36:66, 54:37, 77:8)",
      "d": "« » means to erase by rubbing so that some traces or effects remain. The word « » is generally used for the eyes, stars, and the face. The « » of eyes and stars is that they become devoid of light, and the « » of the face is that it becomes disfigured, i.e., it becomes ugly.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اٰمِنُوۡا بِمَا نَزَّلۡنَا مُصَدِّقًا لِّمَا مَعَکُمۡ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ نَّطۡمِسَ وُجُوۡہًا»\nTranslation: Believe in what We have revealed, confirming that which is with you, before We obliterate (i.e., erase, efface) faces (meaning, erase their eyes, noses, etc.).\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«فَاِذَا النُّجُوۡمُ  طُمِسَتۡ»\nTranslation: When the stars are obliterated (lose their light)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2593,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "مٹانا",
      "s": "« » To terminate the power of something and render it lifeless (2 verses: 2:276, 3:141)",
      "d": "« » means to make something weak and feeble, to invalidate it, to make it fruitless and lifeless (m. l.), and also means to be inferior and decrease (m.f.). Its opposite is « » or « », meaning to nurture, to rear, and to cause to grow.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَمۡحَقُ اللّٰہُ الرِّبٰوا وَ یُرۡبِی الصَّدَقٰتِ»\nTranslation: Allah effaces (destroys) usury and causes charity to grow."
    },
    {
      "id": 2594,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "مٹانا",
      "s": "« » To terminate in such a way that no trace remains (2 verses: 13:39, 17:12)",
      "d": "«مَحُو» «مَحَتِ الرِّیْحُ السَّحَابَ» «اَثْبَتَ»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ»\nTranslation: Allah effaces what He wills and establishes what He wills."
    },
    {
      "id": 2595,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "To erase",
      "hw": "مٹانا",
      "s": "« » To erase something and replace it with another (2 verses: 2:106, 22:52)",
      "d": "« » means to cause to perish, to invalidate, to transform, to erase (manj). It also means to remove one thing and bring another in its place (m.f.). The first thing that is removed or erased is called « » (abrogated), and the second thing that replaces it is called « » (abrogating). Sometimes this word is used merely in the sense of causing to perish or erasing.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَیَنۡسَخُ اللّٰہُ مَا یُلۡقِی الشَّیۡطٰنُ ثُمَّ  یُحۡکِمُ  اللّٰہُ  اٰیٰتِہٖ»\nTranslation: So Allah will efface what Satan casts and then Allah will confirm His verses.\nAnd sometimes it is used in the sense of terminating the first thing and bringing another.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«مَا نَنۡسَخۡ مِنۡ اٰیَۃٍ اَوۡ نُنۡسِہَا نَاۡتِ بِخَیۡرٍ مِّنۡہَاۤ  اَوۡ مِثۡلِہَا»\nTranslation: We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring forth [one] better than it or similar to it."
    }
  ],
  "568": [
    {
      "id": 2596,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "« » Dry dust; a general term for all kinds of earth (17 verses: 2:264, 3:59, 13:5, 16:59, 18:37, 22:5, 23:35, 23:82, 27:67, 30:20, 35:11, 37:16, 37:53, 40:67, 50:3, 56:47, 78:40)",
      "d": "« » means dust, dry earth that has no moisture (f.l. 31), which the wind blows around. It is a general term for earth.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُ یٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ  کُنۡتُ تُرٰبًا»\nTranslation: And the disbeliever will say, \"Oh, I wish I had been dust.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 2597,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "« » Wet clay, but without straw in it (12 verses: 3:49, 5:110, 6:2, 7:12, 17:61, 23:12, 28:38, 32:7, 37:11, 38:71, 38:76, 51:33)",
      "d": "« » means wet clay, but without straw in it (f.l. 31). Even if its moisture, i.e., wetness, dries up, that dry mud is still called « ». For example: The Noble Quran states:\nTranslation: And Allah originated the creation of man from clay."
    },
    {
      "id": 2598,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "« » Clay that sticks to the hand; sticky, adhesive clay (1 verse: 37:11)",
      "d": "« » means clay that sticks to the hand (manj), sticky and adhesive clay (f.l. 268).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُمۡ مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ لَّازِبٍ»\nTranslation: Indeed, We created them from sticky clay."
    },
    {
      "id": 2600,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "« » Dry, crackling, resonant clay (4 verses: 15:26, 15:28, 15:33, 55:14)",
      "d": "« » is when black, foul-smelling mud becomes completely dry and begins to make a sound or ring when struck slightly (f.l. 168).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ مِّنۡ حَمَاٍ مَّسۡنُوۡنٍ»\nTranslation: And We have certainly created man from an extract of clay.\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«خَلَقَ الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ کَالۡفَخَّارِ»\nTranslation: He created man from clay like pottery."
    },
    {
      "id": 2601,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "« » Baked, resonant clay; pottery (1 verse: 55:14)",
      "d": "« » means pottery. Baked clay (manj), i.e., baked clay or earthenware that rings or sounds when struck. And « » means a potter who makes and sells earthenware (manj). The creation of man ultimately came from such clay.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«خَلَقَ الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ کَالۡفَخَّارِ»\nTranslation: He created man from clay like pottery."
    },
    {
      "id": 2602,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Dust and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "« » The upper part of the earth's surface; the dust that rises upon it (4 verses: 4:43, 5:6, 18:8, 18:40)",
      "d": "«صَعَدَ» «صَعِیْد» «صَعِیْد» «وَجْہُ الْاَرْض»\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n« فَلَمۡ  تَجِدُوۡا مَآءً فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا»\nTranslation: Then if you do not find water, then seek clean earth (for purification)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2603,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«Sulālah» means essence, extract, useful part, something extracted from a thing (2 verses: 23:12-32:8)",
      "d": "«Sulālah» «وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنْسَانَ مِنْ سُلَٰلَةٍ مِّنْ طِينٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2604,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil and its various states",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "«Tharā» the wet and soft soil of the deepest part of the earth (1 verse: 20:6)",
      "d": "«Tharā» «لَهُ مَا فِي السَّمَاوَاتِ وَمَا فِي الْأَرْضِ وَمَا بَيْنَهُمَا وَمَا تَحْتَ الثَّرَى»"
    }
  ],
