      "d": "«زَالَ» «زوال» «لَا» «مَا» «لَا» «مَا» «وَ لَا تَزَالُ تَطَّلِعُ عَلٰی خَآئِنَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا مِّنۡہُمۡ» «فَمَا زَالَتۡ تِّلۡکَ دَعۡوٰىہُمۡ  حَتّٰی  جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ  حَصِیۡدًا  خٰمِدِیۡنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2990,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To Be Always / To Remain",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "« » used only in the imperfect with negation « » or « » and conditional « », as a place adverb (3 verses: 12:80-18:60-20:91)",
      "d": "«بَرَحَ» «بَرَزَ» «بَرَزَ» «بَرَحَ» «لَا» «لَنْ» «حَتّٰی» «وَ اِذۡ قَالَ مُوۡسٰی لِفَتٰىہُ لَاۤ  اَبۡرَحُ حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ» «قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نَّبۡرَحَ عَلَیۡہِ عٰکِفِیۡنَ حَتّٰی یَرۡجِعَ   اِلَیۡنَا مُوۡسٰی»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2991,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To always be. To remain.",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "« » means to prevent someone from doing something. When the negation particles « » and « » are added to it, it means to continue doing something perpetually. (1 verse: 12:85)",
      "d": "«فَتَا» «لَا» «مَا» «مَا فَتَاَ یَفْعَلُ ذٰلک» «حَتّٰی» «لَا»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: The brothers of Yusuf said to their father, 'By Allah! You will continue to remember Yusuf (AS) until you become ill or die.'"
    }
  ],
  "653": [
    {
      "id": 2992,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to laugh",
      "hw": "ہنسنا",
      "s": "« » means to laugh with sound, opening the mouth such that teeth become visible. (8 verses: 9:82-11:71-23:110-43:47-53:43-53:60-83:29-83:34)",
      "d": "« » means to laugh with sound, opening the mouth such that teeth become visible (from Majid).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ امۡرَاَتُہٗ  قَآئِمَۃٌ  فَضَحِکَتۡ فَبَشَّرۡنٰہَا بِاِسۡحٰقَ»\nTranslation: And his wife, who was standing, laughed, so We gave her glad tidings of Ishaq (AS)."
    },
    {
      "id": 2993,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to laugh",
      "hw": "ہنسنا",
      "s": "« » means to smile. (1 verse: 27:19)",
      "d": "« » and « » mean to smile (from Majid). To laugh a little without sound, such that signs of happiness appear.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَتَبَسَّمَ ضَاحِکًا مِّنۡ قَوۡلِہَا»\nTranslation: So he (Sulaiman AS) smiled, laughing at her words."
    }
  ],
  "654": [
    {
      "id": 2994,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » means wind. (18 verses: 3:117-8:46-10:22-12:94-14:18-17:69-21:81-22:31-30:51-33:9-34:12-38:36-41:16-42:33-46:24-51:41-54:19-69:6)",
      "d": "« » and « » are well-known words for wind. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is wind and movement (M.L.). Although it has been used in the Quran in wider meanings. For example:\n(1) « » meaning wind in the well-known sense, which moves (F.L. 172).\nFor example, the divine declaration is:\n«اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ»\nTranslation: If Allah wills, He can make the wind stationary.\n(2) « » meaning scent or fragrance.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اِنِّیۡ لَاَجِدُ رِیۡحَ یُوۡسُفَ»\nTranslation: Indeed, I find the scent of Yusuf (AS).\n(3) « » meaning terror and awe.\nFor example, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ لَا  تَنَازَعُوۡا فَتَفۡشَلُوۡا  وَ تَذۡہَبَ رِیۡحُکُمۡ»\nTranslation: And do not dispute, lest you lose courage and your wind (spirit) depart.\n«رِیْح» «رِیَاح» «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیَاح» «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیْح»"
    },
    {
      "id": 2995,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » means mercy. The continuous flowing waves of Allah's favors and bounties. (2 verses: 12:87-56:89)",
      "d": "«رَوْح» «یَوْمٌ رَوْحٌ» «رُوْح» «رَوْح» «رُوْح» «اَرَاحَ الْاِنْسَان» «رُوْح»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«لَا تَایۡئَسُوۡا مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ ؕ اِنَّہٗ  لَا یَایۡئَسُ مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡقَوۡمُ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: Do not despair of Allah's mercy. Indeed, none despairs of Allah's mercy except the disbelieving people."
    },
    {
      "id": 2996,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » fragrant flowers/plants, herbs. (2 verses: 55:12-56:89)",
      "d": "« » means every fragrant plant. Sustenance. Livelihood (from Majid). And « » means a fragrant scent, and « » means a bouquet of flowers (from Majid). Contemplating these meanings shows that if « » refers to rizq (sustenance) or items of food and drink obtained from agriculture, then they are things whose fragrance and scent are pleasant.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«فَرَوۡحٌ وَّ رَیۡحَانٌ  ۬ ۙ وَّ جَنَّتُ نَعِیۡمٍ»\nTranslation: Then for him are comfort, fragrant flowers, and gardens of bliss.\nAt another place, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ الۡحَبُّ ذُو الۡعَصۡفِ وَ الرَّیۡحَانُ»\nTranslation: And the grain with its husk and fragrant flowers."
    },
    {
      "id": 2997,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » winds that bring glad tidings of rain. (1 verse: 30:46)",
      "d": "« » means winds that bring glad tidings of the descent of mercy or rain. The breeze that is moist and pleasant before the rain (F.L. 254).\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ مِنۡ اٰیٰتِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ الرِّیَاحَ مُبَشِّرٰتٍ وَّ  لِیُذِیۡقَکُمۡ  مِّنۡ  رَّحۡمَتِہٖ»\nTranslation: And among His signs is that He sends the winds as glad tidings so that you may taste His mercy."
    },
    {
      "id": 2998,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (pleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » rain-bearing winds. Those winds that carry the burden of water before raining. (1 verse: 15:22)",
      "d": "« » is the plural of « » and « », meaning rain-bearing wind. And this burden can be of two types: (1) the burden of water that winds carry before raining, (2) the burden of male plant's pollen (i.e., seed, pod, grain, or sperm) that it carries and deposits on the female plant (M.L.). In the Quran, this word is used only in the first meaning.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ اَرۡسَلۡنَا الرِّیٰحَ لَوَاقِحَ فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً»\nTranslation: And We sent the rain-bearing winds, then We caused water to descend from the sky."
    },
    {
      "id": 2999,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » stormy wind carrying dust and chaff. (4 verses: 10:22-14:18-21:81-77:2)",
      "d": "« » means chaff. Husk. Dry plants that become crumbled (Mufradat). And « » is the name for that strong wind or storm that carries chaff or similar things.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا کُنۡتُمۡ فِی الۡفُلۡکِ ۚ وَ  جَرَیۡنَ بِہِمۡ بِرِیۡحٍ طَیِّبَۃٍ وَّ فَرِحُوۡا بِہَا جَآءَتۡہَا رِیۡحٌ عَاصِفٌ وَّ جَآءَہُمُ الۡمَوۡجُ مِنۡ کُلِّ مَکَانٍ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ اُحِیۡطَ بِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: Until when you are in the ships, and they sail with them with a good wind and they rejoice therein, there comes upon them a stormy wind, and the waves come upon them from every side, and they think that they are surrounded."
    },
    {
      "id": 3000,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind and its types (unpleasant winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » stormy wind carrying stones. (4 verses: 17:68-29:40-54:34-67:17)",
      "d": "«حَصَب» «حاصِبَۃ» «اَحْصَبَ الْفَرْس»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«اَفَاَمِنۡتُمۡ اَنۡ یَّخۡسِفَ بِکُمۡ جَانِبَ الۡبَرِّ اَوۡ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا»\nTranslation: Then do you feel secure that He will not cause the side of the land to engulf you or send upon you a storm of stones?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3001,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "wind and its types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » refers to a windstorm that uproots trees (1 verse: 17:69)",
      "d": "«قَصَفَ» «قَاصِف»\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«فَیُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ قَاصِفًا مِّنَ الرِّیۡحِ فَیُغۡرِقَکُمۡ بِمَا کَفَرۡتُمۡ»\nTranslation: Then He will send upon you a violent wind from the sky, which will drown you because of your disbelief."
    },
    {
      "id": 3002,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » A scorching, intensely hot wind (3 verses: 15/27, 52/27, 56/42)",
      "d": "« » means an intensely hot wind. A sirocco. A wind that scorches bodies (Fayruz al-Lughah, p. 254).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَمَنَّ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡنَا وَ  وَقٰىنَا عَذَابَ السَّمُوۡمِ»\nTranslation: So Allah bestowed favor upon us and saved us from the punishment of the scorching wind."
    },
    {
      "id": 3003,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » A whirlwind. A violent wind filled with dust and debris that ascends straight towards the sky (1 verse: 2/266)",
      "d": "« » is a violent wind that whirls in the air (Mufradat). It means a violent wind filled with dust and debris that ascends straight towards the sky (Fayruz al-Lughah, p. 253). A wind-cyclone.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَصَابَہَاۤ اِعۡصَارٌ فِیۡہِ نَارٌ فَاحۡتَرَقَتۡ»\nTranslation: Then a whirlwind befell it, in which there was fire, and it was burnt to ashes."
    },
    {
      "id": 3004,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » A wind-borne calamity or affliction sufficient for settling the account (3 verses: 6/96, 18/40, 55/5)",
      "d": "« » means to calculate, count, or enumerate. And « » means a calamity or affliction that is sufficient for settling the account. Different lexicographers have given various meanings for « ». However, it is related to the punishment of wind.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  فَتُصۡبِحَ  صَعِیۡدًا  زَلَقًا»\nTranslation: And Allah sends upon it a calamity from the sky, and it becomes a smooth, empty plain."
    },
    {
      "id": 3005,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » Meaning a cold blast, a single gust of intensely cold wind (1 verse: 21/46)",
      "d": "« » means a cold blast. Like a single puff of wind from a bellows. A blast. A puff. A surge of intensely cold wind. Its opposite is « », meaning a surge of hot wind (Fayruz al-Lughah, p. 29).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَئِنۡ مَّسَّتۡہُمۡ نَفۡحَۃٌ مِّنۡ عَذَابِ رَبِّکَ»\nTranslation: And if a single puff of your Lord's punishment touches them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3007,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Winds and their types (disastrous winds)",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم»",
      "d": "«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم» «لَا قِحَہ»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ فِیۡ عَادٍ  اِذۡ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمُ  الرِّیۡحَ الۡعَقِیۡمَ»\nTranslation: And in 'Ad (was a sign) when We sent upon them the barren, destructive wind."
    }
  ],
  "655": [
    {
      "id": 3008,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to be",
      "hw": "ہونا",
      "s": "« » conveys the meaning of past and present, such as: is, became, and was (657 verses: 2:10-2:16-2:34-2:36-2:57-2:59-2:61-2:75-2:89-2:94-2:97-2:98-2:102-2:103-2:111-2:113-2:114-2:134-2:135-2:140-2:141-2:142-2:143-2:170-2:184-2:185-2:196-2:213-2:232-2:280-2:282-3:13-3:24-3:67-3:79-3:93-3:95-3:97-3:110-3:112-3:137-3:145-3:147-3:154-3:156-3:161-3:164-3:179-4:1-4:2-4:6-4:11-4:12-4:16-4:17-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:29-4:30-4:32-4:33-4:34-4:35-4:36-4:39-4:43-4:46-4:47-4:56-4:58-4:66-4:76-4:82-4:85-4:86-4:92-4:94-4:96-4:99-4:100-4:101-4:102-4:103-4:104-4:106-4:107-4:108-4:111-4:113-4:126-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:130-4:131-4:133-4:134-4:135-4:141-4:147-4:148-4:149-4:152-4:158-4:165-4:169-4:170-4:176-5:14-5:44-5:61-5:62-5:63-5:75-5:78-5:79-5:81-5:104-5:106-6:4-6:5-6:10-6:11-6:24-6:28-6:35-6:43-6:49-6:70-6:88-6:108-6:111-6:120-6:122-6:124-6:127-6:129-6:130-6:136-6:138-6:140-6:152-6:157-6:159-6:161-7:5-7:9-7:37-7:39-7:51-7:53-7:64-7:70-7:72-7:82-7:83-7:84-7:86-7:87-7:92-7:96-7:101-7:103-7:118-7:133-7:136-7:137-7:139-7:146-7:147-7:148-7:157-7:160-7:162-7:163-7:165-7:175-7:177-7:180-8:32-8:33-8:34-8:35-8:42-8:44-8:54-8:67-9:9-9:17-9:24-9:42-9:62-9:66-9:69-9:70-9:77-9:81-9:82-9:95-9:113-9:114-9:115-9:120-9:121-9:122-10:2-10:4-10:8-10:12-10:13-10:19-10:30-10:37-10:39-10:42-10:43-10:45-10:63-10:70-10:71-10:73-10:74-10:75-10:93-10:98-10:100-11:7-11:8-11:15-11:16-11:17-11:20-11:21-11:34-11:36-11:42-11:43-11:78-11:116-11:117-12:7-12:20-12:26-12:27-12:38-12:57-12:68-12:69-12:76-12:109-12:111-13:32-13:38-14:10-14:11-14:22-14:46-15:2-15:8-15:11-15:63-15:78-15:81-15:82-15:84-15:93-16:33-16:34-16:36-16:39-16:41-16:87-16:88-16:96-16:97-16:112-16:118-16:120-16:123-16:124-17:3-17:5-17:11-17:18-17:19-17:20-17:25-17:27-17:30-17:31-17:32-17:33-17:34-17:36-17:38-17:42-17:44-17:53-17:57-17:58-17:66-17:67-17:72-17:78-17:81-17:83-17:87-17:88-17:95-17:96-17:100-17:108-18:9-18:28-18:34-18:43-18:45-18:50-18:54-18:79-18:80-18:82-18:98-18:101-18:107-18:109-18:110-19:5-19:8-19:13-19:21-19:28-19:29-19:35-19:41-19:44-19:47-19:51-19:54-19:55-19:56-19:61-19:63-19:64-19:71-19:75-20:129-21:8-21:11-21:22-21:30-21:41-21:47-21:63-21:73-21:74-21:77-21:90-21:99-22:15-22:44-23:46-23:48-23:66-23:91-23:109-24:7-24:9-24:24-24:51-24:62-25:6-25:15-25:16-25:18-25:20-25:26-25:29-25:40-25:54-25:55-25:65-25:67-25:70-26:5-26:6-26:8-26:40-26:63-26:67-26:86-26:103-26:112-26:121-26:139-26:158-26:174-26:189-26:190-26:199-26:206-26:207-27:12-27:14-27:20-27:43-27:48-27:51-27:53-27:56-27:60-27:69-27:82-28:4-28:6-28:8-28:32-28:40-28:59-28:63-28:64-28:68-28:75-28:76-28:81-28:84-29:5-29:7-29:13-29:24-29:29-29:31-29:32-29:33-29:34-29:38-29:39-29:40-29:41-29:64-30:9-30:10-30:13-30:32-30:35-30:42-30:47-30:49-30:55-31:21-32:5-32:17-32:18-32:19-32:24-32:25-33:1-33:2-33:5-33:6-33:9-33:15-33:19-33:20-33:21-33:24-33:35-33:27-33:30-33:34-33:36-33:37-33:38-33:40-33:43-33:50-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:54-33:55-33:59-33:69-33:72-33:73-34:14-34:15-34:21-34:33-34:40-34:41-34:43-34:45-34:54-35:10-35:18-35:26-35:41-35:44-35:45-36:29-36:30-36:46-36:53-36:65-36:70-37:22-37:30-37:35-37:51-37:73-37:116-37:141-37:143-37:167-38:69-38:74-39:8-39:26-39:35-39:43-39:46-39:48-39:50-40:5-40:21-40:22-40:63-40:78-40:82-40:83-41:15-41:17-41:18-41:20-41:25-41:27-41:28-41:48-41:52-42:20-42:46-42:51-43:7-43:25-43:40-43:54-43:69-43:76-43:81-44:27-44:29-44:31-44:37-45:14-45:17-45:25-45:33-46:6-46:10-46:11-46:14-46:16-46:18-46:26-46:28-47:10-47:14-47:21-48:4-48:5-48:7-48:11-48:14-48:15-48:19-48:21-48:24-48:26-49:5-50:27-50:37-51:16-51:17-51:35-51:45-51:46-52:34-53:9-53:52-54:14-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:30-54:31-55:37-56:6-56:24-56:45-56:46-56:47-56:88-56:90-56:92-58:7-58:15-58:22-59:9-59:17-60:4-60:6-62:2-63:2-64:6-65:2-65:9-66:10-66:12-67:18-68:14-68:33-68:41-68:43-69:27-69:33-70:4-70:44-71:10-72:4-72:6-72:15-73:14-73:18-74:16-75:38-76:5-76:7-76:15-76:17-76:22-76:30-77:39-78:17-78:19-78:20-78:21-78:27-83:14-83:29-83:36-84:13-84:15-90:17-96:11-110:3)",
      "d": "« » conveys the meaning of past and present, such as: is, became, and was. And its imperfect form is « », which conveys the meaning of present and future. According to Ibn al-Faris, the meaning of « » is 'to inform about the coming into existence of something'.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«اِلَّاۤ اِبۡلِیۡسَ ؕ اَبٰی وَ اسۡتَکۡبَرَ ٭۫ وَ کَانَ مِنَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: Except Iblis; he refused and was arrogant. And he became of the disbelievers.\nIn another place, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ یَخَافُوۡنَ یَوۡمًا کَانَ شَرُّہٗ  مُسۡتَطِیۡرًا»\nTranslation: And they fear a Day whose evil will be widespread.\n«کَانَ» «کَانَ ذَھَبَ»\n«فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا رِجۡزًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡسُقُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: So We sent upon those who wronged a punishment from the heaven because they used to disobey.\nNote: (Continuous past: that verb which indicates the repeated occurrence or continuation of an action, e.g., he used to come.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3010,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "To be / Existence",
      "hw": "ہونا",
      "s": "« » For an affair to occur; for a decree to be issued, to be promulgated (2 verses: 28/23, 99/6)",
      "d": "« » means for an affair to occur; for a decree to be issued, to be promulgated. Its opposite is « », meaning to arrive or come in. And « » is said after a task is completed successfully and then upon departure (Mufradat).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَئِذٍ یَّصۡدُرُ  النَّاسُ اَشۡتَاتًا  ۬ ۙ لِّیُرَوۡا اَعۡمَالَہُمۡ»\nTranslation: On that Day, people will depart in groups to be shown their deeds.\nAt another place, the Divine declaration states:\n«قَالَتَا لَا نَسۡقِیۡ حَتّٰی یُصۡدِرَ الرِّعَآءُ»\nTranslation: They said, 'We will not water until the shepherds have departed.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3011,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "to happen / to befall",
      "hw": "ہونا",
      "s": "« » means the occurrence of a calamitous event (19 verses: 4:100-5:91-7:71-7:118-7:134-7:171-10:51-18:53-27:82-27:85-42:22-51:6-52:7-56:1-56:2-56:75-69:15-70:1-77:7)",
      "d": "« » basically has two meanings: (1) for something to be established, (2) to fall. And an event generally refers to an incident that involves severity and hardship.\nIn the Quran, this word has been used for punishment, detestable things, and calamities ( ).\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«سَاَلَ  سَآئِلٌۢ  بِعَذَابٍ  وَّاقِعٍ»\nTranslation: A seeker of truth asked about the impending punishment.\nIn another place, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ وَقَعَ الۡقَوۡلُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِمَا ظَلَمُوۡا»\nTranslation: And the decree will be fulfilled against them because of what they used to do."
    }
  ],
  "656": [
    {
      "id": 3012,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Or",
      "hw": "یا",
      "s": "« » It comes to indicate one thing out of two or more options (211 verses)",
      "d": "« » comes to indicate one thing out of two or more options.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ»\nTranslation: Or like the one who passed by a town."
    },
    {
      "id": 3013,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "or",
      "hw": "یا",
      "s": "« » is called a conjunction in Arabic grammar. It comes after an interrogative hamzah meaning equality.",
      "d": "« » is called a conjunction in Arabic grammar. It comes after an interrogative hamzah meaning equality.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَشَدُّ خَلۡقًا اَمِ السَّمَآءُ»\nTranslation: Which is harder to create, you or the sky?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3014,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "or",
      "hw": "یا",
      "s": "« » comes to mention each of two things and is used with repetition.",
      "d": "« » comes to mention each of two things and is used with repetition.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«اِنَّا ہَدَیۡنٰہُ السَّبِیۡلَ اِمَّا شَاکِرًا وَّ اِمَّا کَفُوۡرًا»\nTranslation: We have shown man the way; then he is either grateful or ungrateful."
    }
  ],
  "657": [
    {
      "id": 3015,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to remember. to come. to keep.",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "« » means to remember, to keep, to come, to remember in the heart or on the tongue; it is used everywhere and its usage is common.",
      "d": "« » means something coming to mind or tongue. Whether a matter remains remembered or comes to mind after forgetting, it is used generally.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«اَوَلَا یَذۡکُرُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ اَنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ وَلَمۡ یَکُ شَیۡئًا»\nTranslation: Does man not remember that We created him before, while he was nothing?\nAnd « » means to remember a forgotten past matter.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡ نَجَا مِنۡہُمَا وَ ادَّکَرَ بَعۡدَ اُمَّۃٍ»\nTranslation: And the one who escaped from the two said, and the matter came to his mind after a long time."
    },
    {
      "id": 3016,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to remember. to come. to keep.",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "« » means to memorize something verbally, to preserve in the heart, then keep its remembrance and not forget.",
      "d": "« » means to remember something and then keep its remembrance (to not let it be lost or forgotten). To protect something from being wasted or ruined.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«حٰفِظُوۡا عَلَی الصَّلَوٰتِ وَ الصَّلٰوۃِ الۡوُسۡطٰی»\nTranslation: Guard the prayers, and the middle prayer."
    },
    {
      "id": 3017,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to remember. to come. to keep.",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "« » means to remember and not allow any decrease or increase in it.",
      "d": "« » means to store something in a container and close its mouth. To protect it and not let anything come out of it. And « » means a closed container.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«لِنَجۡعَلَہَا لَکُمۡ تَذۡکِرَۃً وَّ تَعِیَہَاۤ اُذُنٌ وَّاعِیَۃٌ»\nTranslation: So that We may make it a reminder for you, and an ear that remembers."
    }
  ],
  "658": [
    {
      "id": 3018,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to be certain",
      "hw": "یقین",
      "s": "« » means to understand something completely and reach its foundation of proof.",
      "d": "« » means no doubt or suspicion remains. According to Imam Raghib, « » means 'to understand something completely and reach its foundation of proof.' Its degree is above knowledge and wisdom. According to Abu Al-Halal Asakri, the degree of certainty is higher than knowledge. He writes: 'Certainty is the soul's tranquility and the heart's coolness with what is known.'\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَ بِالۡاٰخِرَۃِ ہُمۡ یُوۡقِنُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: (One of the traits of believers is that) they are certain about the Hereafter.\nAnd « » means certainty gradually coming after experience.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«فَلَمَّا جَآءَتۡہُمۡ اٰیٰتُنَا مُبۡصِرَۃً قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا سِحۡرٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ . وَ جَحَدُوۡا بِہَا وَ اسۡتَیۡقَنَتۡہَاۤ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ»\nTranslation: So when Our signs came to them as clear evidence, they said, 'This is clear magic.' And they denied them, while their souls were convinced thereof."
    },
    {
      "id": 3019,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "to be certain",
      "hw": "یقین",
      "s": "« » means to infer certainty through signs and indications.",
      "d": "« » essentially comes in the meanings of inferring and guessing through evidence and indications. The weaker the signs and evidence, the weaker the « ». The stronger they are, the stronger the « ». In this case, « » means strong certainty. Its sign is that after « », the word « » or « » generally comes.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَظُنُّوۡنَ اَنَّہُمۡ مُّلٰقُوۡا رَبِّہِمۡ»\nTranslation: And give glad tidings to the believers who think they will meet their Lord."
    }
  ],
  "660": [
    {
      "id": 3022,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "« » is a general term for travel.",
      "d": "« » means to depart from one's place of residence and to cover distance. This word is general. Whether the travel is for any purpose.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَ إِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی أَوۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ»\nTranslation: Whether you are ill or on a journey."
    },
    {
      "id": 3023,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "« » is used for intending purification with soil as an alternative to wudu.",
      "d": "« » linguistically means to intend, to resolve, or to turn towards something. In Islamic jurisprudence, and specifically in the context of wudu, « » refers to the intention and act of seeking purification with clean soil when water is unavailable or its use is excused (e.g., due to illness). It is the Shariah alternative to wudu (and ghusl), called tayammum. Its specific nuance is that it is the intention and act of purification with soil instead of water. Allah has granted this concession to Muslims for ease so they can attain purity in all circumstances.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا قُمْتُمْ إِلَى الصَّلَاةِ فَاغْسِلُوا وُجُوهَكُمْ وَأَيْدِيَكُمْ إِلَى الْمَرَافِقِ وَامْسَحُوا بِرُءُوسِكُمْ وَأَرْجُلَكُمْ إِلَى الْكَعْبَيْنِ ۚ وَإِن كُنتُمْ جُنُبًا فَاطَّهَّرُوا ۚ وَإِن كُنتُم مَّرْضَىٰ أَوْ عَلَىٰ سَفَرٍ أَوْ جَاءَ أَحَدٌ مِّنكُم مِّنَ الْغَائِطِ أَوْ لَامَسْتُمُ النِّسَاءَ فَلَمْ تَجِدُوا مَاءً فَتَيَمَّمُوا صَعِيدًا طَيِّبًا فَامْسَحُوا بِوُجُوهِكُمْ وَأَيْدِيكُم مِّنْهُ ۚ مَا يُرِيدُ اللَّهُ لِيَجْعَلَ عَلَيْكُم مِّنْ حَرَجٍ وَلَٰكِن يُرِيدُ لِيُطَهِّرَكُمْ وَلِيُتِمَّ نِعْمَتَهُ عَلَيْكُمْ لَعَلَّكُمْ تَشْكُرُونَ»\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you rise to pray, wash your faces and your hands up to the elbows, wipe over your heads, and wash your feet up to the ankles. And if you are in a state of janabah, then purify yourselves. But if you are ill or on a journey or one of you comes from the place of relieving himself or you have contacted women and do not find water, then perform tayammum with clean earth. So wipe your faces and hands with it. Allah does not intend to make difficulty for you, but He intends to purify you and complete His favor upon you that you may be grateful."
    },
    {
      "id": 3024,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "« » in the context of wudu refers to that body part (hands) which must be washed up to the elbows for purification.",
      "d": "« » means 'hands'. In the context of wudu, this word indicates the body part (hands) that must be washed up to the elbows as part of the purification ritual. Its meaning relates to the physical organ itself, which is part of fulfilling a religious ruling.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا قُمْتُمْ إِلَى الصَّلَاةِ فَاغْسِلُوا وُجُوهَكُمْ وَأَيْدِيَكُمْ إِلَى الْمَرَافِقِ وَامْسَحُوا بِرُءُوسِكُمْ وَأَرْجُلَكُمْ إِلَى الْكَعْبَيْنِ ۚ»\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you rise to pray, wash your faces and your hands up to the elbows, wipe over your heads, and wash your feet up to the ankles."
    },
    {
      "id": 3025,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "‘Nasu’ refers to the state of forgetting or neglecting, where a part or condition of wudu is unintentionally omitted, resulting in incomplete wudu.",
      "d": "‘Nasu’ means to forget, overlook, abandon, or leave behind. In the context of wudu, this term describes the condition when a person unintentionally forgets or neglects to perform one of the obligations or sunnahs of wudu, potentially affecting its validity. It highlights human weakness and negligence, indicating that errors can occur even in acts of worship; thus, in such cases, repeating wudu or completing the omitted part becomes necessary.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا بَلَغَا مَجْمَعَ بَيْنِهِمَا نَسِيَا حُوتَهُمَا فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِيلَهُ فِي الْبَحْرِ سَرَبًا»\nTranslation: Then when they both reached the place where the two rivers met, they forgot their fish, and it took its way into the sea as a sudden disappearance."
    },
    {
      "id": 3026,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Wudu",
      "hw": "وضو",
      "s": "‘Marid’ has no direct linguistic or Shariah connection to the concept of wudu, as wudu is derived from ‘wadhā’ while ‘marid’ means illness.",
      "d": "‘Marid’ means illness, ailment, or defect. This word is completely unrelated to the Shariah or linguistic meaning of wudu (a specific act of purification), as wudu is derived from the Arabic root ‘w-ḍ-ā’ which fundamentally means cleanliness, purity, and radiance. In contrast, ‘marid’ pertains to physical or spiritual sickness and disease. Therefore, using this term in the context of wudu is neither linguistically correct in Arabic nor does it have any basis in Islamic Shariah.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فِي قُلُوبِهِم مَّرَضٌ فَزَادَهُمُ اللَّهُ مَرَضًا ۖ وَلَهُمْ عَذَابٌ أَلِيمٌ بِمَا كَانُوا يَكْذِبُونَ»\nTranslation: In their hearts is a disease, so Allah has increased their disease, and for them is a painful punishment because they used to lie."
    }
  ],
  "661": [
    {
      "id": 3027,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Naskh",
      "hw": "منسوخ",
      "s": "When ‘khair’ is used in conjunction with the concept of ‘naskh’ (abrogation), it means that the ruling or verse that is abrogated is replaced by something better or similar from Allah.",
      "d": "‘Khair’ means ‘better’ or ‘good’. When this word is used in the context of ‘naskh’, it signifies that when Allah abrogates a ruling or verse, He replaces it with a new ruling or verse that is ‘better’ or equivalent, to fulfill the requirements of wisdom and the interests of the servants. This demonstrates Allah’s wisdom, knowledge, and benevolence towards His creation, that none of His decisions are without purpose; rather, every change carries more goodness and benefit for humanity.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَا نَنسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِّنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا ۗ أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ»\nTranslation: We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring forth [one] better than it or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things competent?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3028,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Naskh",
      "hw": "منسوخ",
      "s": "‘Nasi’ is used to denote the concept of ‘naskh’ by means of abandoning, erasing, or eliminating the effect of a ruling, thereby indicating its abrogation.",
      "d": "‘Nasi’ means ‘to abandon’, ‘to forget’, or ‘to erase from the mind’. When used in the context of ‘naskh’, it refers to terminating a ruling or verse in such a way that it no longer retains its previous status, whether by removing it from people’s minds or by revoking its practical ruling and declaring it void, thus rendering it abrogated. This essentially describes the act of Allah revoking a Shariah ruling or ceasing its application.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَا نَنْسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنْسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ»\nTranslation: \"Whatever verse We abrogate or cause to be forgotten, We bring a better one or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things capable?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3029,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Naskh",
      "hw": "منسوخ",
      "s": "‘Ati’ refers to the advent or arrival of a new verse or ruling from Allah, which causes the abrogation of the previous ruling or takes its place.",
      "d": "‘Ati’ means ‘to bring’, ‘to convey’, or ‘to come’. In the context of naskh, this word describes the descent or appearance of a divine ruling, law, or verse that replaces or terminates the previous ruling. It does not directly mean abrogation but indicates how a new ruling or decree ‘comes’ that abrogates the old one. This is part of the process where Allah, in His wisdom, ‘brings’ a better or similar ruling, resulting in the abrogation of the previous one.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَا نَنْسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنْسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ»\nTranslation: \"Whatever verse We abrogate or cause to be forgotten, We bring a better one or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things capable?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3030,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "abrogated - abrogation",
      "hw": "منسوخ",
      "s": "When used in the concept of 'abrogated', « » refers to the new ruling or verse that comes in place of the abrogated ruling or verse, and is similar or equivalent to it.",
      "d": "« » means similar, equal, or like. When mentioned in the context of 'abrogated', it refers to the new ruling or verse that Allah reveals in place of a previous abrogated ruling or verse, and this new ruling is similar in its wisdom, effect, or ruling to the previously abrogated one. This indicates that when Allah abrogates a ruling, He replaces it with either something better or something similar, which is more suitable for the servants.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«مَا نَنسَخْ مِنْ آيَةٍ أَوْ نُنسِهَا نَأْتِ بِخَيْرٍ مِّنْهَا أَوْ مِثْلِهَا ۗ أَلَمْ تَعْلَمْ أَنَّ اللَّهَ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ»\nTranslation: 'We do not abrogate a verse or cause it to be forgotten except that We bring forth [one] better than it or similar to it. Do you not know that Allah is over all things competent?'"
    }
  ],
  "662": [
    {
      "id": 3033,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Murtabi'",
      "hw": "متبنیٰ",
      "s": "The word ‘haqq’ in the context of ‘murtabi’ (adopted child) refers to establishing the true lineage and affirming the truth, which negates false claims of parentage.",
      "d": "‘Haqq’ means to establish something as true, to make it a reality, to confirm it, and to uphold the truth. In the concept of ‘murtabi’’, where a child is declared the son of someone other than his biological father, Islam has prohibited this. In this context, ‘haqq’ denotes the truth that Allah establishes through His commands and negates all false claims, including the determination of a child’s true lineage.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَيُحِقُّ اللَّهُ الْحَقَّ بِكَلِمَاتِهِ وَلَوْ كَرِهَ الْمُجْرِمُونَ»\nTranslation: \"And Allah will establish the truth by His words, even if the criminals dislike it.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3035,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "adopted - adoption",
      "hw": "متبنیٰ",
      "s": "« » means the existence of something or the establishment of a state. In the concept of adoption, it indicates the existence or non-existence of the legal or social status that is established regarding the adopted.",
      "d": "«كون»\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«لِكَيْ لَا يَكُونَ عَلَى الْمُؤْمِنِينَ حَرَجٌ فِي أَزْوَاجِ أَدْعِيَائِهِمْ إِذَا قَضَوْا مِنْهُنَّ وَطَرًا»\nTranslation: 'So that there may be no discomfort for the believers concerning the wives of their adopted sons when they have consummated the marriage with them.'"
    }
  ],
  "663": [
    {
      "id": 3037,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Zina",
      "hw": "زنا",
      "s": "The use of ‘kun’ in the context of zina refers to the reality of its existence, meaning its eternal and inherent nature as an immoral and evil act.",
      "d": "‘Kun’ means ‘to be’, ‘to exist’, or ‘to become’. In relation to zina, this word is generally used to describe the eternal and inherent characteristic of the act, i.e., it has always been an immoral and evil act since eternity. This clarifies its unchanging and inherently bad nature, that its wickedness is not temporary or subject to change but is intrinsic to it.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَقْرَبُوا الزِّنَا إِنَّهُ كَانَ فَاحِشَةً وَسَاءَ سَبِيلًا»\nTranslation: \"And do not approach unlawful sexual intercourse. Indeed, it is ever an abomination and is evil as a way.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3038,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Zina",
      "hw": "زنا",
      "s": "The use of ‘ati’ in relation to zina means to commit or practically carry out that immoral act.",
      "d": "‘Ati’ means ‘to come’, ‘to do’, or ‘to perform’. When this word is used in the context of ‘zina’, it signifies committing that heinous act (zina), carrying it out practically, or being involved in it. This indicates not merely approaching or intending the act but actually its occurrence and giving it practical form. The word explicitly states the regular commission of a sin or immorality.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالَّلَاتِي يَأْتِينَ الْفَاحِشَةَ مِن نِّسَائِكُمْ فَاسْتَشْهِدُوا عَلَيْهِنَّ أَرْبَعَةً مِّنكُمْ»\nTranslation: \"And those of your women who commit illegal sexual intercourse - take the evidence of four witnesses from among you.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3040,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Adultery - Adultery",
      "hw": "زنا",
      "s": "« » expresses a desire for complete oblivion, as if one never existed, due to the shameful accusation of adultery or the fear of its social disgrace.",
      "d": "« » lexically means to forget, overlook, or cause to be forgotten. Within the concept of adultery, this word directly describes the moral, social, and psychological effects of the act rather than the act itself. It reflects that intense mental and emotional state where a person, to avoid the infamous charge of adultery or its possible consequences, or due to the extreme shame and humiliation it brings, wishes they had been completely forgotten or never come into existence at all. It points to the desire for total social erasure and self-annihilation that arises in such a situation.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَأَجَاءَهَا الْمَخَاضُ إِلَىٰ جِذْعِ النَّخْلَةِ قَالَتْ يَا لَيْتَنِي مِتُّ قَبْلَ هَٰذَا وَكُنتُ نَسْيًا مَّنسِيًّا»\nTranslation: Then the pangs of childbirth drove her to the trunk of a palm tree. She said, \"Oh, I wish I had died before this, and had been a thing utterly forgotten!\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3041,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "adultery - adultery",
      "hw": "زنا",
      "s": "When « » is used outside of lawful marriage or in a prohibited relationship, it refers to an illicit sexual act that falls under the category of adultery.",
      "d": "« » means to have sexual relations or to marry. Although this word is generally used in the sense of lawful and religiously sanctioned marriage, when it is used for an illicit or prohibited relationship, it refers to adultery or similar severe immorality ( ). In this case, the act of 'nikāḥ' becomes illicit and reprehensible, i.e., it becomes forbidden because it is outside the bounds of religious law.\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَلَا تَنكِحُوا مَا نَكَحَ آبَاؤُكُم مِّنَ النِّسَاءِ إِلَّا مَا قَدْ سَلَفَ ۚ إِنَّهُ كَانَ فَاحِشَةً وَمَقْتًا وَسَاءَ سَبِيلًا»\nTranslation: 'And do not marry those [women] whom your fathers had married, except what has already occurred. Indeed, it is an immorality, an abomination, and an evil way.'"
    }
  ],
  "664": [
    {
      "id": 3042,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperous - Prosperous",
      "hw": "خوشحال",
      "s": "« » denotes that prosperity or wealth which is based on abundance, luxury, and comfort, and which often leads to negligence, arrogance, or ingratitude.",
      "d": "« » means to live in luxury, to have a very comfortable and pleasurable life, and to be engrossed in worldly comforts. This word does not merely refer to general prosperity but points to an excessive prosperity and wealth that spoils a person, making them overly indulged in ease. The inevitable result of such prosperity is that such people often fall into negligence, pride, ingratitude, and rebellion, turning away from the truth. In the Quran, this word is often used for people who, engrossed in their worldly luxuries, become heedless of the Hereafter and Allah's commands.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَإِذَا أَرَدْنَا أَن نُّهْلِكَ قَرْيَةً أَمَرْنَا مُتْرَفِيهَا فَفَسَقُوا فِيهَا فَحَقَّ عَلَيْهَا الْقَوْلُ فَدَمَّرْنَاهَا تَدْمِيرًا»\nTranslation: \"And when We intend to destroy a people, We send an order to their affluent ones, but they defiantly disobey therein; so the word [of punishment] comes into effect upon them, and We destroy them utterly.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3043,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperous - Prosperous",
      "hw": "خوشحال",
      "s": "« » highlights that aspect of prosperity in which abundance of sustenance and comfort bestow the capacity for hospitality and generosity.",
      "d": "« » means hosting a guest, feeding and nurturing them. This word expresses that prosperity and abundance which makes a person or community capable of hospitality and generosity. Although the word « » (as hospitality) does not appear explicitly in the Quran, its cognate term « » (town or city) is often used for towns that were prosperous in their economy or living conditions. Thus, « » presents that deep meaning of prosperity which includes not only material comfort but also that generosity and munificence which enables one to consider others and practice the humility of entertaining guests. That is, truly prosperous is one who, in their abundance, keeps an open heart for others.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَكَمْ أَهْلَكْنَا مِن قَرْيَةٍ بَطِرَتْ مَعِيشَتَهَا ۖ فَتِلْكَ مَسَاكِنُهُمْ لَمْ تُسْكَن مِّن بَعْدِهِمْ إِلَّا قَلِيلًا ۖ وَكُنَّا نَحْنُ الْوَارِثِينَ»\nTranslation: \"And how many a town have We destroyed that was arrogant in its manner of living? Those are their dwellings which have not been inhabited after them except a little; and We are the inheritors.\"\nIn this verse, « » is mentioned whose \" \" (sustenance/livelihood) they were arrogant about, which reflects their prosperity and comfort. This arrogance included the misuse of that sustenance, which involves not being grateful for Allah's blessings and not fulfilling the rights of others, especially the needy and guests. Thus, the true essence of « » (hospitality and generosity) emerges in contrast to that prosperity whose rights were not fulfilled."
    },
    {
      "id": 3044,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperous - Prosperous",
      "hw": "خوشحال",
      "s": "« » does not directly relate to prosperity; rather, this word comes in the meaning of making a vow or warning; however, its connection with prosperity can be established indirectly through a vow made as an expression of gratitude or for seeking blessings.",
      "d": "« » essentially means \"making a vow\" or \"dedicating something to Allah\", and another important meaning is \"to warn\" or \"to threaten\". This word is not directly synonymous with \"prosperous\". However, in the Islamic context, a person makes a vow ( ) out of gratitude for their attained prosperity and Allah's blessings, or in hope of acquiring future prosperity and blessings. Thus, the act of making a vow can be indirectly linked to a state of prosperity or the desire for it, where a believer intends to sacrifice something to attain Allah's pleasure and additional favor.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمَا أَنفَقْتُم مِّن نَّفَقَةٍ أَوْ نَذَرْتُم مِّن نَّذْرٍ فَإِنَّ اللَّهَ يَعْلَمُهُ ۗ وَمَا لِلظَّالِمِينَ مِنْ أَنصَارٍ»\nTranslation: \"And whatever you spend or whatever vow you make, indeed Allah knows it, and the wrongdoers will have no helpers.\"\nExplanation: In this verse, « » refers to a \"vow\" or \"pledge\" made for Allah. Although the verse does not mention « » in the meaning of \"prosperous\", the act of making a vow often arises from a person's own prosperity or better conditions (which are part of prosperity), or in gratitude for them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3046,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Prosperous - Prosperous",
      "hw": "خوشحال",
      "s": "« » when used in the meaning of prosperity, refers to the attainment or fulfillment of a truth, promise, or hope that brings about contentment and ease.",
      "d": "« » means to prove something true, to give it the form of reality, or to fulfill a promise or expectation. When this word is associated with the concept of 'prosperity,' it means the attainment or completion of a truth, right, or purpose that manifests as inner peace, satisfaction, and success, forming the very foundation of an individual's or community's prosperity. It does not directly mean prosperity but describes the process or result that causes it.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَقَدْ صَدَقَ اللَّهُ رَسُولَهُ الرُّؤْيَا بِالْحَقِّ لَتَدْخُلُنَّ الْمَسْجِدَ الْحَرَامَ إِن شَاءَ اللَّهُ آمِنِينَ مُحَلِّقِينَ رُءُوسَكُمْ وَمُقَصِّرِينَ لَا تَخَافُونَ فَعَلِمَ مَا لَمْ تَعْلَمُوا فَجَعَلَ مِن دُونِ ذَلِكَ فَتْحًا قَرِيبًا»\nTranslation: Allah has confirmed His Messenger's vision with truth: \"You will surely enter al-Masjid al-Haram, if Allah wills, in safety, with your heads shaved and [hair] shortened, not fearing [anyone].\" He knew what you did not know and has arranged before that a conquest near [at hand]."
    }
  ],
  "665": [
    {
      "id": 3047,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Covenant - Covenant",
      "hw": "معاہدہ",
      "s": "« » in the context of a covenant denotes the inevitable fulfillment and practical manifestation of a promise, decree, or its consequences.",
      "d": "« » means \"to come,\" \"to bring,\" or \"to give.\" When used in the concept of a 'covenant' (i.e., a promise or decree), it refers to the certainty of that promise or decree coming to pass and its results becoming manifest in reality. It emphasizes that what has been decided or promised will inevitably occur. It describes the final enforcement of the covenant's terms or the appearance of its outcome, not the covenant itself.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«أَتَىٰ أَمْرُ اللَّهِ فَلَا تَسْتَعْجِلُوهُ ۚ سُبْحَانَهُ وَتَعَالَىٰ عَمَّا يُشْرِكُونَ»\nTranslation: The command of Allah has come, so do not seek to hasten it. Exalted is He and high above what they associate with Him."
    },
    {
      "id": 3051,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Covenant - Covenant",
      "hw": "معاہدہ",
      "s": "« » refers to a covenant that is based on the mutual consent, pleasure, and complete agreement of the parties involved.",
      "d": "« » means to be pleased, to be content, to approve, or to accept something. When used in the context of a covenant, it clarifies the nature of that covenant as being established through the complete mutual consent, pleasure, and sincere approval of the parties, not under coercion or compulsion. It highlights the free will and genuine willingness of the individuals involved in the covenant, without which no covenant is considered complete and valid in the sight of Shariah. It means the parties have willingly accepted any condition or responsibility.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَإِنْ أَرَادَا فِصَالًا عَن تَرَاضٍ مِّنْهُمَا وَتَشَاوُرٍ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَيْهِمَا ۗ»\nTranslation: But if they both desire weaning by mutual consent and consultation, there is no blame upon them."
    }
  ],
  "666": [
    {
      "id": 3052,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahmad - Ahmad",
      "hw": "احمد",
      "s": "« » refers to the coming, arrival, and manifestation of Ahmad's prophethood.",
      "d": "« » means \"to come,\" \"to bring (honor),\" or \"to be present.\" This word, when used in the context of Ahmad, specifically points to that blessed advent and manifestation of Prophethood of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) which was foretold in previous heavenly scriptures. Its profound meaning relates to the fulfillment of prophecies and the clarification of the truth. It highlights the reality that the coming of Ahmad (peace be upon him) was not an ordinary event but the fulfillment of a great prophecy that came as a source of guidance for humanity.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ عِيسَى ابْنُ مَرْيَمَ يَا بَنِي إِسْرَائِيلَ إِنِّي رَسُولُ اللَّهِ إِلَيْكُمْ مُصَدِّقًا لِّمَا بَيْنَ يَدَيَّ مِنَ التَّوْرَاةِ وَمُبَشِّرًا بِرَسُولٍ يَأْتِي مِن بَعْدِي اسْمُهُ أَحْمَدُ ۖ فَلَمَّا جَاءَهُم بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ قَالُوا هَٰذَا سِحْرٌ مُّبِينٌ»\nTranslation: And [mention] when Jesus, the son of Mary, said, \"O children of Israel, indeed I am the messenger of Allah to you confirming what came before me of the Torah and bringing good tidings of a messenger to come after me, whose name is Ahmad.\" But when he came to them with clear evidences, they said, \"This is obvious magic.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3055,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahmad - Ahmad",
      "hw": "احمد",
      "s": "In the context of 'Ahmad', the specific meaning of « » emerges as a sign of power, authority, and divine support.",
      "d": "« » means hand or the manifestation of power and authority. This word is derived from the Arabic root ' - - ' which denotes one's strength, ownership, or control. Unlike other synonyms such as ' ' (palm) or ' ' (forearm), in ' ' the aspect of vastness, encompassment, and complete authority is predominant. For example: The Quran states:\n«إِنَّ ٱلَّذِينَ يُبَايِعُونَكَ إِنَّمَا يُبَايِعُونَ ٱللَّهَ يَدُ ٱللَّهِ فَوْقَ أَيْدِيهِمْ»\nTranslation: \"Indeed, those who pledge allegiance to you, they are actually pledging allegiance to Allah. The hand of Allah is over their hands.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3056,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahmad - Ahmad",
      "hw": "احمد",
      "s": "In the context of 'Ahmad', the specific meaning of 'ati' pertains to the prophecy of the advent of prophethood, rather than simply coming or bringing.",
      "d": "«وَمُبَشِّرًا بِرَسُولٍ يَأْتِي مِن بَعْدِي اسْمُهُ أَحْمَدُ»"
    }
  ],
  "667": [
    {
      "id": 3058,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ahzab - Al-Ahzab",
      "hw": "احزاب",
      "s": "In the context of Al-Ahzab, this word 'kun' describes the specific aspect of the emergence or formation of enemy groups.",
      "d": "«وَإِذْ يَقُولُ الْمُنَافِقُونَ وَالَّذِينَ فِي قُلُوبِهِم مَّرَضٌ مَّا وَعَدَنَا اللَّهُ وَرَسُولُهُ إِلَّا غُرُورًا * وَإِذْ قَالَت طَّائِفَةٌ مِّنْهُمْ يَا أَهْلَ يَثْرِبَ لَا مُقَامَ لَكُمْ فَارْجِعُوا وَيَسْتَأْذِنُ فَرِيقٌ مِّنْهُمُ النَّبِيَّ يَقُولُونَ إِنَّ بُيُوتَنَا عَوْرَةٌ وَمَا هِيَ بِعَوْرَةٍ ۖ إِن يُرِيدُونَ إِلَّا فِرَارًا * وَلَوْ دُخِلَتْ عَلَيْهِم مِّنْ أَقْطَارِهَا ثُمَّ سُئِلُوا الْفِتْنَةَ لَآتَوْهَا وَمَا تَلَبَّثُوا بِهَا إِلَّا يَسِيرًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3059,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ahzab - Al-Ahzab",
      "hw": "احزاب",
      "s": "'Haqq' means to establish the truth of Allah and clarify His reality, such as the command in Al-Ahzab to prioritize the fear of Allah.",
      "d": "«وَاللَّهُ أَحَقُّ أَن تَخْشَوْهُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3060,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Al-Ahzab - Al-Ahzab",
      "hw": "احزاب",
      "s": "'Wa'ada' means to make a promise when hope is given to someone.",
      "d": "«وَ قَالَ  الشَّیۡطٰنُ لَمَّا قُضِیَ الۡاَمۡرُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ وَعَدَکُمۡ وَعۡدَ الۡحَقِّ وَ وَعَدۡتُّکُمۡ فَاَخۡلَفۡتُکُمۡ»"
    }
  ],
  "668": [
