      "s": "«Laqī» in the specific sense of an army refers to encountering a group or army in an unexpected or significant battle or meeting.",
      "d": "«Laqī» «يَا أَيُّهَا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا إِذَا لَقِيتُمُ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا زَحْفًا فَلَا تُوَلُّوهُمُ الْأَدْبَارَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3119,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Army - Army",
      "hw": "فوج",
      "s": "«Jamaʿa» is a general word for gathering. It is used to bring together different parts of one thing or different things together.",
      "d": "«Jamaʿa» is a word that comes for gathering different parts of one thing, or different things together. These things can be animate or inanimate.\nFor example: For animate things: The Divine command states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ قَالَ لَہُمُ النَّاسُ اِنَّ النَّاسَ قَدۡ جَمَعُوۡا لَکُمۡ»\nTranslation: When people came to them and said, 'The disbelievers have gathered a great army against you.'\nAnd for inanimate things: The Divine command states:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَمَعَ مَالًا وَّ عَدَّدَہٗ»\nTranslation: Who has gathered wealth and counted it.\nThen the word 'jamaʿa' is used for gathering apparent things. It is also used metaphorically.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَتَوَلّٰی فِرۡعَوۡنُ فَجَمَعَ کَیۡدَہٗ ثُمَّ اَتٰی»\nTranslation: Then Pharaoh turned away and gathered his plan, then came [to the confrontation]. (Uthmani )"
    }
  ],
