  "694": [
    {
      "id": 3192,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "حیاتیات",
      "s": "«Mawh» in the context of biology refers to the basic element or substance that is essential for the formation and sustenance of life.",
      "d": "«Mawh» «وَهُوَ الَّذِي خَلَقَ مِنَ الْمَاءِ بَشَرًا فَجَعَلَهُ نَسَبًا وَصِهْرًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3193,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Biology - Biology",
      "hw": "حیاتیات",
      "s": "In the context of biology, 'kūn' describes the coming into existence of a thing, its formation, and the evolutionary process.",
      "d": "«إِنَّمَا أَمْرُهُ إِذَا أَرَادَ شَيْئًا أَنْ يَقُولَ لَهُ كُنْ فَيَكُونُ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3194,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Biology - Biology",
      "hw": "حیاتیات",
      "s": "« » in the context of biology refers to the concept of something being all-encompassing or completely covering, such as a comprehensive analysis of biological systems.",
      "d": "«كلل» «شمل» «ضم» «وَدَانِيَةً عَلَيْهِمْ ظِلَالُهَا وَذُلِّلَتْ قُطُوفُهَا تَذْلِيلًا * وَيُطَافُ عَلَيْهِم بِآنِيَةٍ مِّن فِضَّةٍ وَأَكْوَابٍ كَانَتْ قَوَارِيرَا * قَوَارِيرَ مِن فِضَّةٍ قَدَّرُوهَا تَقْدِيرًا» «كلل»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3195,
      "a": "ح",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "حیاتیات",
      "s": "«Shi'a» in the context of biology refers to bringing something into existence or its creation, particularly under Allah's will and wisdom.",
      "d": "«Shi'a» means to intend something, to will it, or to give it existence. This word differs from other terms like 'khalq' (to create) in that it particularly emphasizes will and intention, whereas 'khalq' generally describes the act of creation. For example, in the Quran, Allah's will and creation are mentioned in these words:\n«إِنَّمَا أَمْرُهُ إِذَا أَرَادَ شَيْئًا أَن يَقُولَ لَهُ كُن فَيَكُونُ»\nTranslation: When He intends a thing, His command is only to say to it, 'Be,' and it is."
    }
  ],
  "695": [
    {
      "id": 3197,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "«Tair» refers to the general form of birds, but in the Quran, it sometimes also alludes to divine signs or fate.",
      "d": "«Tair» means the collective concept of flying creatures, which includes all birds. This word originates from the Arabic root 'ṭ-y-r' (flight) which conveys the meaning of movement and circulation in the air. Unlike other terms like 'ṭa'ir' (a single bird) or 'ʿasfūr' (sparrow), 'ṭair' is general and sometimes carries symbolic meanings, especially in the Quran as signs of divine power.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَأَرْسَلَ عَلَيْهِمْ طَيْرًا أَبَابِيلَ»\nTranslation: And Allah sent upon them birds in flocks."
    },
    {
      "id": 3198,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "«Kull» in the context of birds describes the characteristic of including each one individually and completely.",
      "d": "«Kull» has the lexical root 'k-l-l' which means to encompass, surround, or include completely. This word differs from other synonyms like 'jamiʿ' (all) in that it collectively encompasses while giving individual attention to each part or member. For example, in the Quran, during the mention of birds, this word is used to highlight their distinct identities and the comprehensiveness of their actions.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«أَلَمْ تَرَ أَنَّ اللَّهَ يُسَبِّحُ لَهُ مَن فِي السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ وَالطَّيْرُ صَافَّاتٍ ۖ كُلٌّ قَدْ عَلِمَ صَلَاتَهُ وَتَسْبِيحَهُ»\nTranslation: Do you not see that whoever is in the heavens and earth exalts Allah, and the birds with wings spread? Each one has known its [own way of] prayer and exaltation."
    },
    {
      "id": 3199,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Birds - Birds",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "« » in the Quran is used to describe the specific quality of birds' flight and movement.",
      "d": "«راي» «طير» «راي» «أَوَلَمْ يَرَوْا إِلَى الطَّيْرِ فَوْقَهُمْ صَافَّاتٍ وَيَقْبِضْنَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3200,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Bedouin - Bedouin",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "«Kun» describes the specific act of the creation of birds and their coming into existence, which is a sign of Allah's perfect power.",
      "d": "«Kun» means to come into existence or to appear in a specific state. This word differs from other terms like 'khalq' (to create) or 'jaʿal' (to make) in that it emphasizes the continuity of a thing's existence and its natural qualities. In the context of birds, it highlights the delicacy of their creation, their ability to fly, and Allah's wisdom in their system of life.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«أَلَمْ يَرَوْا إِلَى الطَّيْرِ مُسَخَّرَاتٍ فِي جَوِّ السَّمَاءِ مَا يُمْسِكُهُنَّ إِلَّا اللَّهُ»\nTranslation: Do they not see the birds subjected in the atmosphere of the sky? None holds them except Allah."
    },
    {
      "id": 3201,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Birds - Birds",
      "hw": "پرندے",
      "s": "The specific meaning of « » (ati) points to the swift arrival or being brought of birds.",
      "d": "« » (ati) means to come or be brought, especially with immediacy and speed. This word differs from others like ' ' (ja'a - to come) in that it expresses movement with purpose and subjugation. For example, in the Quran, this word was used in the context of birds to describe their gathering instantly by Allah's command.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَخُذْ أَرْبَعَةً مِّنَ الطَّيْرِ فَصُرْهُنَّ إِلَيْكَ ثُمَّ اجْعَلْ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنْهُنَّ جُزْءًا ثُمَّ ادْعُهُنَّ يَأْتِينَكَ سَعْيًا»\nTranslation: Then take four birds, incline them to yourself (slaughter them), then place on every hill a portion of them, then call them; they will come to you swiftly."
    }
  ],
  "696": [
    {
      "id": 3202,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Blame - Blame",
      "hw": "ملامت",
      "s": "« » (lawaam) means to admonish someone gently for their fault or shortcoming, which carries an aspect of reform.",
      "d": "«لوم» «وَلَا أُقْسِمُ بِالنَّفْسِ اللَّوَّامَةِ»\nTranslation: And I swear by the self-reproaching soul. (Here, ' ' refers to the soul that reproaches itself for bad deeds, embodying the meaning of admonition and reform.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3204,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Blame - Blame",
      "hw": "ملامت",
      "s": "In the context of 'blame', the word « » (kana) expresses the continuity and persistence of an action or state that becomes a cause for blame.",
      "d": "« » (kana) means existence, proof, or the continuity of a state. This word differs from other verbs (like ' ' or ' ') in that it emphasizes the quality of something being or remaining in a certain state, not merely its occurrence. In the Quran, this word is often used to refer to the persistent nature of human deeds or attributes that lead to blame.\n«وَضُرِبَتْ عَلَيْهِمُ الذِّلَّةُ وَالْمَسْكَنَةُ وَبَاءُوا بِغَضَبٍ مِنَ اللَّهِ ۗ ذَٰلِكَ بِأَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا يَكْفُرُونَ بِآيَاتِ اللَّهِ وَيَقْتُلُونَ النَّبِيِّينَ بِغَيْرِ الْحَقِّ ۗ ذَٰلِكَ بِمَا عَصَوْا وَكَانُوا يَعْتَدُونَ»\nTranslation: And humiliation and poverty were imposed upon them, and they became subject to the wrath of Allah. That is because they disbelieved in the signs of Allah and killed the prophets without right. That is because they disobeyed and were transgressing."
    }
  ],
  "697": [
    {
      "id": 3208,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Blood Money (Diyah) - Diyah",
      "hw": "دیت",
      "s": "« » in the context of blood money refers to the value determined and associated with the status of a free individual.",
      "d": "«حرر» «یٰۤاَیُّهَا الَّذِیْنَ اٰمَنُوْا كُتِبَ عَلَیْكُمُ الْقِصَاصُ فِی الْقَتْلٰى اَلْحُرُّ بِالْحُرِّ وَالْعَبْدُ بِالْعَبْدِ»"
    }
  ],
  "698": [
    {
      "id": 3213,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Bones - Bones",
      "hw": "ہڈی",
      "s": "« » (kana) expresses the specific aspect of the state of existence of bones or their transformation.",
      "d": "« » (kana) means to come into existence or to change into a particular state. This word differs from others like ' ' (to create) or ' ' (to make) in that it fundamentally describes the process of something coming into being or changing state, not just its outward structure. For example, in the context of bones, ' ' refers to the stage of their composite existence or formation.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوٓا۟ أَئِذَا كُنَّا عِظَـٰمًا وَ رُفَـٰتًا أَءِنَّا لَمَبْعُوثُونَ خَلْقًا جَدِيدًا»\nTranslation: And they say, 'When we have become bones and crumbled dust, will we indeed be resurrected as a new creation?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3215,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Bones - Bones",
      "hw": "ہڈی",
      "s": "In the context of bones, « » (mawt) describes the specific quality of the dissolution of the human body after death and its being revived by Allah's power.",
      "d": "« » (mawt) means the end of life and the separation of body and soul. This word is derived from the Arabic root ' - - ', which expresses the general state of transition for any living being. However, in relation to bones, it pertains to the lifeless human structure and the miracle of its revival. Other words like ' ' (wafat) or ' ' (rahmat) focus only on the aspect of transition, whereas ' ' includes a profound concept of physical transformation.\n«وَضَرَبَ لَنَا مَثَلًا وَنَسِيَ خَلْقَهُ قَالَ مَنْ يُحْيِي الْعِظَامَ وَهِيَ رَمِيمٌ»\nTranslation: And he presents an example for us and forgets his own creation. He says, 'Who will give life to the bones while they are decayed?'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3216,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Bone - Bone",
      "hw": "ہڈی",
      "s": "« » refers to the original material of bones, i.e., soil and dust, which indicates the initial state of human creation.",
      "d": "«ترب» «عظم» «ترب» «عظم» «وَضَرَبَ لَنَا مَثَلًا وَنَسِيَ خَلْقَهُ ۖ قَالَ مَن يُحْيِي الْعِظَامَ وَهِيَ رَمِيمٌ»"
    }
  ],
  "699": [
    {
      "id": 3217,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Books - Books",
      "hw": "کتابیں",
      "s": "The word « » has been used in the Quran for divinely revealed books and sacred scriptures that are written by Allah and their preservation is their characteristic.",
      "d": "«كتب» «قرأ» «خط» «كتب» «فِيهَا كُتُبٌ قَيِّمَةٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3218,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Books - Books",
      "hw": "کتابیں",
      "s": "In reference to books, « » (ati) signifies the descent of divine revelation or heavenly scriptures.",
      "d": "« » (ati) in its literal Arabic sense means 'to come' or 'to bring'. However, in Quranic terminology, it is specifically used for the sending down of revelation, commandments, or heavenly books. This word is distinct from synonyms like ' ' (nazala - to descend) in that 'ati' includes the meanings of wisdom, completion, and honor in its arrival.\n«وَلَمَّا جَآءَهُمْ كِتَـٰبٌۭ مِّنْ عِندِ ٱللَّهِ مُصَدِّقٌۭ لِّمَا مَعَهُمْ»\nTranslation: And when a Book came to them from Allah confirming that which was with them..."
    }
  ],
  "700": [
    {
      "id": 3223,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "نباتیات",
      "s": "The meaning of « » (mawh) in the context of botany describes the life and growth granted to plants by Allah.",
      "d": "« » (mawh) means to grant something as a gift or with a specific quality. This word is distinguished from others like ' ' (to give) or ' ' (to create) in that it emphasizes a natural and divine bestowal. In botany, it refers to the earth being given water and life.\n«وَأَنزَلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ مَاءً بِقَدَرٍ فَأَسْكَنَّاهُ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَإِنَّا عَلَىٰ ذَهَابٍ بِهِ لَقَادِرُونَ»\nTranslation: And We sent down from the sky water in a measured amount and settled it in the earth. And indeed, We are able to take it away."
    },
    {
      "id": 3224,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "نباتیات",
      "s": "In the context of botany, « » (layl) describes the specific role of nighttime in the growth and biological processes of plants.",
      "d": "« » (layl) means the time of night, derived from the Arabic root ' - - '. This word conveys not only the cycle of darkness but also a specific division of time and the circadian rhythm. It differs from other synonyms like ' ' (darkness) in that ' ' includes the meaning of a defined period and a natural cycle. In botany, it is deeply connected to the catabolic processes of plants at night (such as respiration) and activities like flower opening.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَآيَةٌ لَّهُمُ اللَّيْلُ نَسْلَخُ مِنْهُ النَّهَارَ فَإِذَا هُم مُّظْلِمُونَ»\nTranslation: And a sign for them is the night; We remove from it the daylight, and suddenly they are in darkness."
    },
    {
      "id": 3225,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "نباتیات",
      "s": "« » (ghashaw) in the context of botany describes the quality of grass or greenery that covers the earth.",
      "d": "« » (ghashaw) means to cover something else or to spread over it. This word is derived from the Arabic root ' - - ', which conveys the meaning of any kind of veil, covering, or enveloping. In botany, it refers to the density of grass or greenery spread on the earth, such as the growth of crops or wild plants. It differs from other words like ' ' (to grow) or ' ' (to sow) in that ' ' emphasizes spreading and covering.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَأَنبَتْنَا فِيهَا مِن كُلِّ زَوْجٍ بَهِيجٍ»\nTranslation: And We have produced therein every kind of beautiful pair."
    },
    {
      "id": 3226,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Botany - Botany",
      "hw": "نباتیات",
      "s": "« » in the context of botany indicates the basic role of water sources and the flourishing of plant life.",
      "d": "«نهر» «بحر» «وادي» «وَبَشِّرِ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ أَنَّ لَهُمْ جَنَّاتٍ تَجْرِي مِن تَحْتِهَا الْأَنْهَارُ»"
    }
  ],
  "701": [
    {
      "id": 3227,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Bow - Bow",
      "hw": "کمان",
      "s": "The specific Quranic meaning of « » (rak'a) describes the state of bowing in prayer.",
      "d": "« » (rak'a) means to bow in prayer where one places the knees on the ground and straightens the back. It differs from general bending (like ' ' or ' ') which only indicates physical movement, whereas 'rak'a' includes the intention of worship and the prescribed method.\n«وَأَقِيمُوا الصَّلَاةَ وَآتُوا الزَّكَاةَ وَارْكَعُوا مَعَ الرَّاكِعِينَ»\nTranslation: And establish prayer and give zakah and bow with those who bow [in worship]."
    },
