      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "«Regret» expresses grief or remorse over an irreparable loss or missed opportunity, indicating intense sorrow.",
      "d": "«Regret» «حَسْرَة» «Regret» «نَدم» «يَا حَسْرَةً عَلَى الْعِبَادِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3322,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret - Yearning",
      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "«Yearning» conveys the intensity of regret, lingering remorse, and the feeling that arises after a missed opportunity has passed.",
      "d": "«Yearning» «ح-س-ر» «يَقُولُ يَا لَيْتَنِي قَدَّمْتُ لِحَيَاتِي»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3323,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Regret - Sorrow",
      "hw": "افسوس",
      "s": "«Sorrow» describes a deep and enduring form of regret associated with feelings of remorse over failure or past actions.",
      "d": "«Sorrow» «رُّبَمَا يَوَدُّ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا لَوْ كَانُوا مُسْلِمِينَ»"
    }
  ],
  "724": [
    {
      "id": 3324,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happiness - Happiness",
      "hw": "خوشی",
      "s": "«Happiness» in the Quran refers to inner joy, contentment, and gratitude for God's blessings, transcending temporary worldly pleasures.",
      "d": "«Happiness» «قُلْ بِفَضْلِ اللَّهِ وَبِرَحْمَتِهِ فَبِذَٰلِكَ فَلْيَفْرَحُوا هُوَ خَيْرٌ مِّمَّا يَجْمَعُونَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3325,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happiness - Bliss",
      "hw": "خوشی",
      "s": "«Bliss» means deep inner happiness and heartfelt joy that is lasting and pure.",
      "d": "«Bliss» «فَوَقَاهُمُ اللَّهُ شَرَّ ذَٰلِكَ الْيَوْمِ وَلَقَّاهُمْ نَضْرَةً وَسُرُورًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3326,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Happiness - Cheerfulness",
      "hw": "خوشی",
      "s": "«Cheerfulness» is the essence of happiness that expresses the prosperity and comfort of the human heart.",
      "d": "«Cheerfulness» «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلًّا لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا رَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَّحِيمٌ»"
    }
  ],
  "725": [
    {
      "id": 3327,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sorrow - Sorrow",
      "hw": "دکھ",
      "s": "«Sorrow» means to show, display, and present prominently, particularly used to express emotions.",
      "d": "«Sorrow» «د-ك-ه» «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَإِنَّا لَهُمْ مُّحْتَجَّةٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3328,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sorrow - Grief",
      "hw": "دکھ",
      "s": "'Grief' is used in all meanings such as distress, sorrow, pain, and regret.",
      "d": "«ثُمَّ اَنۡزَلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الۡغَمِّ اَمَنَۃً نُّعَاسًا یَّغۡشٰی طَآئِفَۃً مِّنۡکُمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3329,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Sorrow - Anguish",
      "hw": "دکھ",
      "s": "«Anguish» is the essence of sorrow that exerts a strong impact on the human heart and mind.",
      "d": "«Anguish» «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ حَبٌّ حَتَّى تَأْتِيَهُمُ الْبَيِّنَةُ مِن رَّبِّكَ فَقَدْ كَانَ فِي أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ مِن قَبْلِهَا حَبٌّ وَإِنَّهُمْ لَمْ يَكُونُوا مُحَرَّكِينَ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ حَبٌّ حَتَّى تَأْتِيَهُمُ الْبَيِّنَةُ مِن رَّبِّكَ»"
    }
  ],
  "726": [
    {
      "id": 3330,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Restlessness - Restlessness",
      "hw": "بےچینی",
      "s": "«Restlessness» indicates doing something without interest or enthusiasm, which deviates from the true meaning.",
      "d": "«Restlessness» «وَلَوْلَا دَعَوْتُهُمْ لَقَدْ كُنتُمْ مِّنَ الْمُحْسِنِينَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3331,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Restlessness - Anxiety",
      "hw": "بےچینی",
      "s": "«Anxiety» means that something stands still and does not move easily, like a sundial's gnomon standing in the sun and expanding.",
      "d": "«Anxiety» «وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا غَفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلًّا لِلْمُؤْمِنِينَ وَرَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَحِيمٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3332,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Restlessness - Anxiety",
      "hw": "بےچینی",
      "s": "'Anxiety' means to live in an unknown and unprotected place, which expresses the meaning of 'restlessness'.",
      "d": "'Anxiety' originates from the Arabic 'be-qarari', which means unknown, unprotected, and residing in an unknown place. This word essentially indicates all kinds of hopelessness and lack of stability, clarifying the human condition in the context of restlessness. In contrast, 'restlessness' means to place something in an unknown and unprotected place, which is an explanatory meaning of anxiety. Its synonyms are 'instability' or 'unsettledness', but 'anxiety' specifically means placing something in an unknown place which is a characteristic of restlessness.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا أَنْزِلْ لَنَا مِنْ فَوْقِنَا ظَهْرًا مِّنْ سَاقِطٍ وَرَحْمَةً مِّنْ عِندِكَ وَلِيَكُونَ لَنَا آمِنًا مِّنْ لَّدُنْهُ وَلَوْ أَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا يَعْلَمُونَ»\nTranslation: 'And those who came after them say, \"Our Lord, send down to us from above us a rain of what falls and a mercy from Yourself, and make for us from Yourself a secure place. If they had known, what would they have done?\"'"
    }
  ],
  "727": [
    {
      "id": 3333,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Assurance - Assurance",
      "hw": "اطمینان",
      "s": "'Assurance' means firm and stable trust gained from God that gives peace to the heart and is not abandoned again.",
      "d": "'Assurance' derives from the Arabic 'itminan', which is related to the meanings of 'faith' and 'trust', and thus embodies the attribute of natural and faithful trust. It means that the human heart improves itself, and with it comes a sense of faith and love. Its synonym is 'faith', but 'assurance' includes additional trust and a sense of heart's peace along with faith.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِهِ وَيَتَوَakkَّفُونَ فِي أَمْرِهِمْ وَلَا يَرْتَابُونَ»\nTranslation: 'And those who come after them will believe in it and will not be perturbed in their matters, nor will there be doubt in them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3334,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Assurance - Tranquility",
      "hw": "اطمینان",
      "s": "'Tranquility' is the original meaning of assurance that expresses the peace and comfort of the human heart when it is before God and presents its duties.",
      "d": "'Tranquility' means the connection and peace of the heart, which also makes a person feel that they have reached their God. It is a new state in terms of words that provides the heart's tranquility. It is an expression of a person's heart's tranquility when they present their actions and duties.\nIn contrast, the meanings of 'amin' and 'itminan' are similar, but in 'sukun', the expression of the human heart's peace is more evident.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ»\nTranslation: 'And those who came after them say, \"Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3335,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Assurance - Consolation",
      "hw": "اطمینان",
      "s": "'Consolation' is the original meaning of assurance that expresses faith in the human heart and the peace gained from the Lord.",
      "d": "'Consolation' originates from the Arabic root 'tasallā', which expresses a state that imparts a sense of peace and comfort to the human heart. This word expresses faith, certainty, and trust gained from the Lord in the human heart. It is a specific kind of assurance that not only expresses a feeling like the heartbeat but also demonstrates the strengthening of faith and the state of being with God.\nIn contrast, 'aman' means general assurance, 'itminan' means only trust, and 'taminan' means a sense of peace along with trust.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَحْنُ هُمُ الْمُهْتَدُوْنَ»\nTranslation: 'And those who strive in Us, We will guide them.'"
    }
  ],
  "728": [
    {
      "id": 3336,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khushamad - Khushamad",
      "hw": "خوشامد",
      "s": "«Khushamad» means that which increases beyond joy and comfort, and because of it, a person feels happiness.",
      "d": "The original root of «Khushamad» is related to joy, comfort, and support, which naturally gives a person happiness and ease. Its lexical meaning is \"joy\" or \"comfort\" that is the best and most giving of happiness. In contrast, \"joy\" (khush) only indicates general happiness, whereas \"khushamad\" indicates a joy that is specifically superior, that which surpasses many joys.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَإِذَا مَسَّكُمُ الْقَلَقُ أَشَدَّ مِنَ الْقَلَقِ»\nTranslation: \"And when distress touches you, it is a greater distress than the previous one.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3337,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khushamad - Chaplusi",
      "hw": "خوشامد",
      "s": "«Chaplusi» (flattery/ingratiation) is a specific aspect of khushamad that expresses a person's excellent conduct and courage.",
      "d": "«Chaplusi» means that a person's heart and soul are happy, and their behavior and courage are also better when they show khushamad to someone. This term, in contrast to others, signifies a specific point of khushamad that manifests a person's excellent conduct and courage. This word is also used in the Quran when a person shows khushamad to someone with all their heart's happiness. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَإِذَا جَاءُوا عَلَيْهِمْ قَالُوا سَلَامًا»\nTranslation: \"When they came to them, they said, 'Peace.'\""
    }
  ],
  "729": [
    {
      "id": 3339,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Ilm - Danish",
      "hw": "علم",
      "s": "«Danish» means reading, understanding, and a specific quality of knowledge that gives a person the ability to comprehend and utilize information.",
      "d": "«Danish» means reading, understanding, and a specific quality of knowledge that gives a person the ability to comprehend and utilize information. Its original root is « - - », which means to read and understand repeatedly. In contrast to «Ilm» (knowledge), which generally looks at information or cognition, «Danish» is that information which gives a person the ability to understand and use. «Ilm» is a general term, while «Danish» is a specific term that denotes a person's education, understanding, and performance. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاللَّهُ يَعْلَمُ مَا تَحْمِلُ كُلُّ أُنْثَىٰ وَمَا تَغِيضُ الْأَرْحَامُ وَمَا تَزْدَادُ فِي الْكَلَامِ إِلَّا مِنْهُ وَيَعْلَمُ مَا فِي الْقُلُوبِ»\nTranslation: \"And Allah knows what every female carries and what the wombs lose [prematurely] or exceed. And with Him, no matter is hidden from the knowledge of the heavens and the earth, and not even the weight of an atom, nor less than that nor greater, except it is in a clear register. And He knows what is in the hearts.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3340,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Ilm - Aagahi",
      "hw": "علم",
      "s": "«Aagahi» means the ability to know and the collection of learning that particularly expresses divine wisdom and the teachings of the Prophet.",
      "d": "The root of «Aagahi» is « », which originally means wisdom, knowledge, and learning. This word is used in several different meanings, but «Aagahi» is specifically used to mean knowing, understanding, and acquiring related knowledge. It implies knowledge divinely ordained and the acquisition of that knowledge. In contrast to other terms, «Aagahi» specifically means the acquisition of wisdom and its educational use, which is divinely given. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«أَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا أَن تَكُونَ لِقَوْمٍ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَيَعْمَلُونَ الصَّالِحَاتِ مَرْحَبًا؟»\nTranslation: \"Has it not been for the believers that they should be for a people who believe in Allah and work righteousness, a welcome?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3341,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Ilm - Marifat",
      "hw": "علم",
      "s": "«Marifat» means a specific nature of knowledge that describes detailed information about things already known.",
      "d": "«Marifat» means a specific nature of knowledge that describes detailed information about things already known. Its Arabic root is « », which originally means \"to know\" and \"to recognize.\" It means that a person has such knowledge that they can retain it in their mind and also convey it to others. It differs from the knowledge of knowing and the knowledge of information, because «Marifat» implies knowing something and also being able to express it clearly. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاللَّهُ أَعْلَمُ بِمَا يُوعَدُونَ»\nTranslation: \"And Allah is most knowing of what they are promised.\""
    }
  ],
  "730": [
    {
      "id": 3342,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Aql - Aql",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«Aql» is the intellect that saves from harm and devises means to choose beneficial things.",
      "d": "« » means to be sensible, to be capable of realizing error (manjad), and « » means to restrain and forbid. And « » is the fetter with which a camel's foot is tied (muf). Thus, the function of intellect is to distinguish between benefit and harm, to adopt measures to avoid harmful things (fiqh. l 65), and to always be prepared for beneficial things and the acceptance of knowledge. Then, to ponder (muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَقَالُوا لَوْ كُنَّا نَسْمَعُ أَوْ نَعْقِلُ مَا كُنَّا فِي أَصْحَابِ السَّعِيرِ»\nTranslation: \"And they will say, 'If we had only listened or used our intellect, we would not be among the companions of the Blaze.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3343,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Aql - Khird",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«Khird» refers to a person's mental ability and capacity for understanding, which Allah has given humans so that they may comprehend truth and reform.",
      "d": "«Khird» «خرد» «عقل» «فکر» «تفکر» «ہوش» «عقل» «خرد» «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ رُسُلًا أَخْبَرْنَا بِهِمُ الْقُرْآنَ وَلَقَدْ جَاءَتْهُمْ رُسُلُهُم بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ فَكَانُوا لَهُمْ لَمْ يَكُونُوا يُؤْمِنُونَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3344,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Aql - Fahm",
      "hw": "عقل",
      "s": "«Fahm» means intellectual sagacity and the knowledge of wisdom that gives a person a sense of guidance from Allah.",
      "d": "The original root of «Fahm» is « », which in Urdu means \"to understand\" and \"to comprehend.\" These words are very important and more specific, whereas the meaning of intellect generally refers to mental power. Terms related to intellect mean, for example, the power of understanding, the capacity to comprehend, and forming a theory. The meaning of intellect is a person's mental power that gives them the ability to understand and comprehend, while the meaning of fahm is the capacity to understand, which is specifically a part of a person's mental power. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ لَهُمْ أَجْرٌ غَيْرُ مَمْنُونٍ»\nTranslation: \"For those who believe and do righteous deeds, there will be a reward uninterrupted.\""
    }
  ],
  "731": [
    {
      "id": 3345,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Soch - Soch",
      "hw": "سوچ",
      "s": "«Soch» means mental thought, contemplation, and analysis that is divinely given.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «Soch» is « - - », which expresses thought, contemplation, analysis, and mental activity. Its verbal synonyms are contemplation, thought, reflection, analysis, and mention, but «Soch» particularly expresses the vision and thought given by the Lord. Its explanation is like one or more words that occur in the matter of God and while turning oneself towards God. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«أَفَلَا يَتَفَكَّرُونَ فِي خَلْقِ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالأَرْضِ»\nTranslation: \"Then do they not reflect upon the creation of the heavens and the earth?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3346,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Soch - Fikr",
      "hw": "سوچ",
      "s": "«Fikr» is the original meaning of soch, which is the act of contemplation and realization through the mind.",
      "d": "The Arabic root word of «Fikr» is « - - », which expresses contemplation, thought, and mental activity. This word differs from other synonyms of soch like « » (deliberation) or « » (the other) because the element of mental contemplation and analysis is more evident in fikr. This word describes the operation of a person's mind, which is the act of thinking, understanding, and comprehending. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّيَ حَوْفٌ أَنْ يَّكُونَ مَعَهُمْ وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّيْ حَوْفٌ أَنْ أَطْرُدَهُمْ فَأَنْتَ أَعْلَمُ بِمَا يَفْعَلُونَ»\nTranslation: \"And I had no fear of them, nor was I with them when they plotted. And I only fear Allah, and I am not heedless of what they do.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3347,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Thought - Idea",
      "hw": "سوچ",
      "s": "'Idea' is a specific way of thinking that is based on the mind's concepts and thoughts.",
      "d": "'Idea' means the mind's concepts, thoughts, and the act of thinking that arises in the human mind. It does not involve words but expresses the internal process of the mind. Unlike synonymous words such as 'thought' and 'experience', 'idea' particularly expresses human mental concepts.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَوْ أَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا أَمَامًا وَلَا خَلْفًا وَلَا نَحْوًا مِّنَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ لَكَانَ خَيْرًا لَّهُمْ وَلَهُمْ فَرَجٌ مِّنْهُمْ وَلَهُمْ مَّوْعِدٌ مُّقَرَّبٌ»\nTranslation: 'If they had been in front, behind, or to the sides of the believers, it would have been better for them, and they would have had relief from them, and they would have had a nearby appointment.'"
    }
  ],
  "732": [
    {
      "id": 3348,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Remembrance - Remembrance",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "'Remembrance' means to keep in mind from the heart and its relation is then with performance and mention.",
      "d": "'Remembrance' originates from the Arabic 'yad' (remembrance), which is related like a calculation, and it means to keep in mind from the heart, to mention, and its difference with other words is that 'remembrance' is a human mental ability that keeps a thing as a mention and related performance, while other words like 'dhikr' or 'tazkira' generally refer to mentioning something.\nIt is established: 'If you remember, it will happen' (Al-Baqarah 2:286)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3349,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Remembrance - Memory",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "'Memory' means to remember, to store as a reserve, and to preserve it.",
      "d": "'Memory' means to remember, to protect, and such a reserve that is preserved. Its original linguistic root is 'hifz' which means to remember, to protect, and to save. The specificity of 'remembrance' in this meaning is that it is not only remembering but also preserving it diligently. In comparison to other words, 'remembrance' generally means remembering, while 'memory' includes the protection and reserve of remembrance.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«أَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا أَن تَكُونَ تَحْتَهُمْ أَرْضٌ تَجْرِي مِن تَحْتِهَا الْأَنْهَارُ وَلَوْ كَانَتْ لَهُمْ أَعْمَالٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ لَقَدْ نَزَّلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ مَاءً فَأَخْرَجْنَاهُ مِن تَحْتِ الْأَرْضِ فَأَرْبَى مِنْهُمْ مُّؤْمِنُونَ وَلَكِنْ لَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ حَافِظٍ مَّا أَنْشَأْنَا فِي الْأَرْضِ مِنْ شَجَرَةٍ وَلَوْ كَانَتْ لَهُمْ أَعْمَالٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ لَقَدْ نَزَّلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ مَاءً فَأَخْرَجْنَاهُ مِن تَحْتِ الْأَرْضِ فَأَرْبَى مِنْهُمْ مُّؤْمِنُونَ وَلَكِنْ لَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ حَافِظٍ مَّا أَنْشَأْنَا فِي الْأَرْضِ مِنْ شَجَرَةٍ وَلَوْ كَانَتْ لَهُمْ أَعْمَالٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ لَقَدْ نَزَّلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ مَاءً فَأَخْرَجْنَاهُ مِن تَحْتِ الْأَرْضِ فَأَرْبَى مِنْهُمْ مُّؤْمِنُونَ وَلَكِنْ لَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنْ حَافِظٍ مَّا أَنْشَأْنَا فِي الْأَرْضِ مِنْ شَجَرَةٍ»\nTranslation: 'Do those people not remember that when there was a little land, rivers would flow beneath it, and if they worked in the land, We would send down water from the sky and bring it out from beneath the earth, then more believers would be among them, but they had no protector for what We created in the land of trees, even if they had worked in the land, We would send down water from the sky and bring it out from beneath the earth, then more believers would be among them, but they had no protector for what We created in the land of trees.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3350,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Remembrance - Reminder",
      "hw": "یاد",
      "s": "'Reminder' means to remember, especially things that come from God, and to mention them that help humans.",
      "d": "'Reminder' is an Arabic root 'tazkir', which essentially means to remember, to mention, and to understand and present things that come from God. This word of remembering is particularly used for remembering God's commands and His words.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ أَنْجَيْنَا مُوسَىٰ وَأَهْلَهُ مِنَ الْعَذَابِ الْأَلِيمِ»\nTranslation: 'And when We saved Moses and his family from the painful punishment.'"
    }
  ],
  "733": [
    {
      "id": 3352,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech - Conversation",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "'Conversation' means talk, instructive talk, dialogue that is with understanding.",
      "d": "'Conversation' originates from the Arabic 'goftegu', which shows the act of speaking and listening. This word is related to talk, dialogue, instructive talk, and understanding.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ رَبُّكَ لِلْمَلَائِكَةِ إِنِّي جَاعِلٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ حَكَمًا»\nTranslation: 'And when your Lord said to the angels, \"I am going to place a vicegerent on earth.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3353,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Speech - Utterance",
      "hw": "بات",
      "s": "'Utterance' means speech that is transmitted through text and words.",
      "d": "'Utterance' originates from the word 'kalam', which is related to speech, talk, and text. This word is the name for both 'kalam' and 'bat', while other synonyms like 'qawl' or 'bayan' only refer to the formulation of speech. 'Kalam' essentially means speech that is the state of talk.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ اللَّهُ يَا عِيسَى ابْنَ مَرْيَمَ أَأَنتَ قَالَتْ لِي بَابَاكَ أَنْتَ تَحْمِلُهُ مِنْهُمْ وَأَنْتَ تَقُولُ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ مَا لَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ بِهِ عِلْمٌ وَلَكِنْ كَانَ لَهُمْ بِهِ مَعْرِفَةٌ»\nTranslation: 'At that time Allah said to Jesus son of Mary, \"What did you say to your father?\" He said, \"You said to them that you should not take your child from them, and you said about the believers something that they did not have knowledge of, but they had recognition of it.\"'"
    }
  ],
  "734": [
    {
      "id": 3355,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Debate - Disputation",
      "hw": "بحث",
      "s": "'Mubāhasah' means to debate, to engage in dispute on a topic with opposition, which is done to defend a theory or argument.",
      "d": "«وَمَا آتَىٰكُمُ الرَّسُولُ فَخُذُوهُ وَمَا نَهَاكُمْ عَنْهُ فَانْتَهُوا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3356,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Debate - Discussion",
      "hw": "بحث",
      "s": "'Munāzarah' means debate that assists in discussing alternative opinions on a topic.",
      "d": "«وَالَّذِينَ جَادَلُوا فِي آيَاتِ اللَّهِ بِغَيْرِ سُلْطَانٍ أَنْزَلْنَاهُ أُولَٰئِكَ يَخْرُجُونَ مِنَ الْمَنَازِرِ»"
    }
  ],
  "735": [
    {
      "id": 3357,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Judgment - Judgment",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "'Faisalah' means decision, judgment, and ruling that emerges under human mental deduction in a specific situation.",
      "d": "«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ إِلَّا أَن يَّكُونَ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ وَلَوْ كَانَ مُحَارِبًا مُّعَدٍّ لَّقَدْ مَكَّنَّاهُمْ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ وَأَغْنَىٰهُمْ عَنْ أَن يَّكُونُوا بِالْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ وَإِنْ كَانَ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ وَلَوْ كَانَ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ فِي فِصَالِهِمْ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3358,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Judgment - Ruling",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "'Ḥakam' is a ruling that stops someone from injustice and provides a means for correction.",
      "d": "«وَ دَاوٗدَ  وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ  اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3359,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Judgment - Case",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "'Qaḍiyyah' means a legal or religious ruling given to solve issues.",
      "d": "«وَقَضَىٰ رَبُّكَ أَنَّهُۥ لَيْسَ لَهُۥٓ إِلَٰهٌ إِلَّا هُوَ وَأَنَّهُۥٓ لَيْسَ لَهُۥٓ شَرِيكٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3360,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Judgment - Ruling",
      "hw": "فیصلہ",
      "s": "'Fatah' is such a judgment that truth and falsehood are distinguished, complexity is removed, and no party remains in doubt.",
      "d": "'Fatah' means to remove restriction and complexity from something (opening). Its opposite is 'Ighlaq' meaning confinement and restriction. And 'Fatah' means to grant victory and to judge. Such a judgment that truth and falsehood are distinguished, complexity is removed, and no party remains in doubt.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«رَبَّنَا افۡتَحۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَ قَوۡمِنَا بِالۡحَقِّ»\nTranslation: 'O our Lord! Judge between us and our people with truth.'"
    }
  ],
  "736": [
    {
      "id": 3361,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Consultation - Consultation",
      "hw": "مشورہ",
      "s": "'Mushāwarah' means consultation with politics and wisdom, based on human wisdom and educational necessity.",
      "d": "«وَلَا تُكَلِّمُوا الَّذِينَ يَدْعُونَ رَبَّهُم بِالْغَدَاةِ وَعَشِيًا يُرِیدُونَ وَجْهَ رَبِّهِمْ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3362,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Consultation - Opinion",
      "hw": "مشورہ",
      "s": "'Rā'ah' means understanding the original and real meaning of a related issue, referring to a person's thoughts and views.",
      "d": "«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّن بَعْدِ ذٰلِكَ مَوْلَىٰ وَلَا مَنْصُورٌ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3363,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Consultation - Reform",
      "hw": "مشورہ",
      "s": "'Ṣalāḥ' means consulting with truth, justice, and fairness, necessary for resolving related issues.",
      "d": "«وَلِلَّذِينَ اتَّخَذُوا دِينَهُمْ مَّلْهَىٰ وَلِلَّذِينَ اتَّخَذُوا دِينَهُمْ مَّلْهَىٰ وَالْمُسْتَقِيمِينَ الْمَلْهَىٰ فِي الدِّينِ وَالْمَلْهَىٰ فِي الدِّينِ»"
    }
  ],
  "737": [
    {
      "id": 3364,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Question - Question",
      "hw": "سوال",
      "s": "'Su'āl' means what is genuinely and truly asked, pointing to information or wisdom.",
      "d": "«أَلَا إِلَٰهُ إِلَّا هُوَ لَهُ الْأَسْمَاء الْحُسْنَىٰ وَلَهُ الْمُلْكُ وَلَهُ الْحَمْدُ فِي الْآخِرَةِ وَالْأُولَىٰ وَلَهُ الْمُلْكُ وَلَهُ الْحَمْدُ فِي الْآخِرَةِ وَالْأُولَىٰ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3365,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Question - Inquiry",
      "hw": "سوال",
      "s": "'Pursh' is a specific type of question that is best viewed when encouragement is given to find the answer.",
      "d": "«أَفَغَیۡرَ اللَّهِ أَرۡبَابٌ سَمِعۡتُمۡ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3366,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Question - Clarification",
      "hw": "سوال",
      "s": "'Istifsar' is a specific form of question asked to clarify the original issue.",
      "d": "'Istifsar' in Urdu is a specific form of question used to clarify the original issue, obtain information, and seek clarification about a problem. Its Arabic root 'Istifsar' means inquiry in Urdu. Its depth is that this question is asked to clarify an issue, and its purpose is to know whether we have understood correctly.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«أَفَأَنْتُمْ أَعْجَبُ مِنْ أَنْ يَكُونَ لَكُمْ سُؤَالٌ فِي الْقُرْآنِ وَلَوْ كُنْتُمْ لَمْ تَكُونُوا مُؤْمِنِينَ»\nTranslation: 'Do you wonder that there is a question in the Quran for you, even if you were not believers?'"
    }
  ],
  "738": [
    {
      "id": 3367,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Response - Response",
      "hw": "جواب",
      "s": "Response means answering a question and then saying something relevant to it.",
      "d": "«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِينٍ فَأَخَذْتُمُوهُ بِالْعَيْنِ وَكَذَّبْتُمُوهُ بِغَيْرِ عِلْمٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3368,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Answer - Rejection",
      "hw": "جواب",
      "s": "'Radd' means to return something due to being unacceptable.",
      "d": "'Radd' means to return something due to being unacceptable. To return. To reject.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَمَّا فَتَحُوۡا مَتَاعَہُمۡ وَجَدُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ رُدَّتۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ»\nTranslation: 'And when they opened their baggage, they found their property returned to them.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3369,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Answer - Answer",
      "hw": "جواب",
      "s": "« » means to answer a question.",
      "d": "« » is opposite to « », and « » means to ask a question, and also to request something and to inquire. Similarly, « » also means to answer a question. And if something is requested, it also means to accept or give it. Here, the answer to a question is under discussion.\n«یَوۡمَ یَجۡمَعُ اللّٰہُ الرُّسُلَ فَیَقُوۡلُ مَا ذَاۤ اُجِبۡتُمۡ»\nTranslation: On that day, Allah will gather the messengers and then ask, 'What response were you given?'"
    }
  ],
  "739": [
    {
      "id": 3370,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Clarification - Clarification",
      "hw": "وضاحت",
      "s": "Clarification means detailing and clear statement that elucidates God's actions and attributes.",
      "d": "«الَّذِي أَنزَلَ الْكِتَابَ بِالْحَقِّ وَقَدْ أَنزَلَهُ فَرَقًا مِّنْهُ وَقَدْ جَعَلَ لَهُ مِنْهُ قَدَرًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3371,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Clarification - Explanation",
      "hw": "وضاحت",
      "s": "Explanation means clarification that elucidates the original subject and provides its details.",
      "d": "«وَإِذَا تُتْلَىٰ عَلَيْهِمُ الْآيَاتُ نَقُولُ لِلَّذِينَ أُوتُوا الْكِتَابَ مِن قَبْلِهِمْ مَّا هَٰذَا إِلَّا أَسَرَّ الْقُرْآنِ وَإِنَّهُ لَمِنْ تَشْرِيحٍ وَجْدِيٍ وَمَعْرِفَةٍ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3372,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Clarification - Interpretation",
      "hw": "وضاحت",
      "s": "Interpretation means stating something clearly that reveals the original meaning, implication, and details.",
      "d": "«أَلَمْ يَرَوْا كَمْ أَخْرَجْنَا مِنْهُمْ مِّنْ أَزْوَاجِهِمْ وَذُرِّيَّتِهِمْ وَمَا أَخْرَجْنَا لَهُمْ مِّنْ أَزْوَاجٍ وَذُرِّيَّةٍ مُّحَرَّبَةٍ»"
    }
  ],
  "740": [
    {
      "id": 3373,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth - Truth",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "Truth specifically means reality, actuality, and the opposite of falsehood—something definitively correct.",
      "d": "«أَلَا لَكُمْ مِّنَ اللَّهِ نَبَأٌ مُّصَدِّقٌ لِّلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا بِاللَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3374,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth - Veracity",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "Veracity means the ability to present reality and truth, which is a fundamental aspect of human moral and religious constitution.",
      "d": "«وَاللَّذِينَ إِذَا أَنْفَقُوا لَمْ يُسْرِفُوا وَلَمْ يَكُونُوا الْمُسْتَغْنَوْنَ وَالَّذِينَ هُمْ لِلْأَمْوَالِ حَافِظُونَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3375,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Truth - Reality",
      "hw": "سچ",
      "s": "Reality expresses the actual truth and correctness that influences a person's heart and speech.",
      "d": "«وَالْحَقُّ مِن رَّبِّكَ فَلَا تَكُونَنَّ مِنَ الْمُمْتَرِينَ»"
    }
  ],
  "741": [
    {
      "id": 3376,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Falsehood - Falsehood",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "Falsehood means something that is not true and does not align with reality, and it expresses disobedience to truth.",
      "d": "«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُشْرِكِينَ قَدْرٌ فَأَنْزَلَ اللَّهُ الْقُرْآنَ وَهُوَ خَيْرٌ وَأَحْسَنُ تَأْوِيلًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3377,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Falsehood - Lying",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "« » is a false statement against reality.",
      "d": "« » means to deliberately give false information (manjada), lack of harmony between heart and tongue (mutabq), or saying something contrary to reality. And its opposite is « ».\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ وَ ہُمۡ  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And they speak falsehood against Allah while they know."
    },
    {
      "id": 3378,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Falsehood - Falsity",
      "hw": "جھوٹ",
      "s": "Falsity is the original meaning of falsehood, related to a series of irregular and false statements.",
      "d": "«وَلَا تَقُولُوا لِمَنْ يَّسْتَمِعُ مِنكُمْ أَنْ يَّكُونَ فِي الْعِلْمِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ فِي الْمَلَكِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ فِي الْعِلْمِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ فِي الْمَلَكِ»"
    }
  ],
  "743": [
    {
      "id": 3382,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Certitude - Certitude",
      "hw": "یقین",
      "s": "Certitude means the assurance arising from the heart's conviction, firm against doubt and uncertainty.",
      "d": "«أَلَا إِلَهُ إِلَّا هُوَ الْحَيُّ الْقَيُّومُ لا إِلَهَ إِلَّا هُوَ الْمَلِكُ الْقُدُّوسُ السَّلَامُ الْمُؤْمِنُ الْمَهْدِي لِلْمُؤْمِنِينَ الْمُعِينُ لِلْمُؤْمِنِينَ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3383,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Yaqeen - Trust (I'timad)",
      "hw": "یقین",
      "s": "\"I'timad\" is the true meaning of Yaqeen, which is a firm and strong feeling in a person's heart that cannot be changed by others.",
      "d": "\"I'timad\" means a hidden and strong feeling in a person's heart that manifests with certainty and faith. These words are distinct from others, such as \"Iman\" or \"Sidq,\" which express faith, but \"I'timad\" is the essence of Yaqeen that resides within the heart and represents its state of faith. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاهَدُوا فِينَا لَنَحْنَهُمْ وَلَنَحْنَهُمْ وَالَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَالَّذِينَ اسْتَجَابُوا لِلَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ وَالَّذِينَ اعْتَدَوْا لَهُمْ عَذَابًا شَدِيدًا فِي الْحَيَاةِ الدُّنْيَا وَفِي الْآخِرَةِ»\nTranslation: \"And those who strive for Us - We will surely guide them to Our ways. And indeed, Allah is with the doers of good. And those who believed and those who responded to Allah and His Messenger - and those who opposed them - will have a severe punishment in the life of this world and in the Hereafter.\""
    }
  ],
  "744": [
    {
      "id": 3385,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khabar - News",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "\"Khabar\" is news that pertains to the listener's own self and can have an impact on them.",
      "d": "The plural of \"Khabar\" is \"Akhbar.\" It is a common term. It refers to an event of which a person has no prior knowledge, and they are informed about it through someone else. It is knowledge of the surrounding circumstances.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ لِأَهْلِهِ امْكُثُوا إِنِّي آنَسْتُ نَارًا لَعَلِّي آتِيكُم مِّنْهَا بِخَبَرٍ»\nTranslation: Moses said to his family, \"Stay here; indeed, I have perceived a fire. Perhaps I will bring you from there information or a burning firebrand.\"\nAt another place, the Divine declaration states:\n«قُل لَّا تَعْتَذِرُوا قَدْ نَبَّأَنَا اللَّهُ مِنْ أَخْبَارِكُمْ»\nTranslation: \"Say, 'Do not make excuses; we will not believe you. Allah has already informed us of your news.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3386,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "Khabar - Information (I'tila)",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "\"I'tila\" is the original meaning of news, which is the act of conveying information to a person.",
      "d": "\"I'tila\" means to give someone knowledge of something, to inform. Its Arabic root is \"I'tila,\" which signifies the act of learning, informing, and giving news. Synonymous terms like Khabar, Akhbar, and Khabardari exist, but \"I'tila\" specifically denotes the act of conveying information to a person. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن بَعْدِهِ مُوسَىٰ إِلَى فِرْعَوْنَ بِسُلْطَانٍ فَقَالَ إِنِّي أَعُوذُ بِرَبِّ الْعَالَمِينَ»\nTranslation: \"And when We sent Moses after him to Pharaoh with clear signs, he said, 'Indeed, I seek refuge in the Lord of the worlds.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3387,
      "a": "خ",
      "h": "News - Announcement",
      "hw": "خبر",
      "s": "« » means announcing news or giving information that makes a person aware so they change their behavior.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of « » is   (kh-b-r), which conveys meanings of information, news, announcement, and conveying. The full term   means the act of conveying news. In contrast, « » simply means information or news, while « » refers to the act of its dissemination or publication. « » means announcing news or giving information that makes a person aware so they change their behavior. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِنْ بَعْدِهِمْ رَسُولًا إِلَىٰ أَهْلِهِمْ فَأَخْبَرَهُمْ بِآيَاتِنَا وَكَانَ هُوَ الْعَلِيُّ الْعَظِيمُ»\nTranslation: \"And when We sent a messenger to their people after him, he informed them of Our signs, and he was the Exalted in might, the Great.\""
    }
  ],
  "745": [
    {
      "id": 3388,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Information - Information",
      "hw": "معلومات",
      "s": "« » specifically means consciously understanding and conveying available information based on the relevant topic.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of « » is   (ma'lumat), which refers to the attribute of knowing and making known information. This term is distinct from other terms such as « » which generally means knowledge, « » which are simple news, and « » which is mental agreement or understanding. The specific meaning of   is to consciously understand available information based on the relevant topic, to correctly comprehend incoming information, and to use it correctly. For example:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ إِلَّا أَنْ يَكُونَ اللَّهُ وَلِيَّهُمْ وَلَا يَكُونَ اللَّهُ وَلِيَّ الْمُشْرِكِينَ»\nTranslation: \"It is told in the Quran to the disbelieving people that Allah is the protector of His friends and not of the polytheists.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3389,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Ma'lumat - Data",
      "hw": "معلومات",
      "s": "\"Data\" is the original meaning of information that becomes known to a person through knowledge and understanding.",
      "d": "\"Data\" means information that enters a person's mind, related to knowledge, information, and wisdom. These terms are used differently, but \"Data\" specifically refers to what becomes known to a person through comprehension. It pertains to information rather than speech. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ أَنزَلْنَا الْكِتَابَ مِن لَّدُنْهُ وَالْمَوْعِظَةَ وَالْمُحَكَّمَةَ فِي الْقُرْآنِ وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا مِنْهُ حَجَّةٌ وَلَكِنَّ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَلَمْ يَكُونُوا مُشْرِكِينَ فَإِنَّهُمْ هُمُ الْمُسْتَمِعُونَ»\nTranslation: \"And when We sent down the Scripture to you, [O Muhammad], those who disbelieved from the People of the Book and the polytheists did not expect any good from it. But those who believed and did not associate anything with Allah - they are the listeners.\""
    }
  ],
  "746": [
    {
      "id": 3391,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Education - Education",
      "hw": "تعلیم",
      "s": "« » means learning through support and education that gives a person the opportunity to learn with their own understanding.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of « » is  - - , which originally means \"education\" and \"teaching,\" giving a person the opportunity to learn with their own understanding. It means that a person should be given the opportunity to learn, which allows them to learn with their innate understanding. This concept is a specific type of education that gives a person the opportunity to learn their principles and moral values. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَمَا كُنتَ تَدْرِي لَعَلَّهُ يَكُونُ خَيْرًا لَّكَ»\nTranslation: \"And you did not know that it might be better for you.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3392,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Education - Instruction",
      "hw": "تعلیم",
      "s": "« » means the act of teaching, which is the act of imparting knowledge with the art of learning.",
      "d": "The original Arabic term for « » is  , which in Arabic means \"the act of teaching someone\" or \"imparting knowledge.\" These words describe the general concept of education, but « » specifically refers to the act of imparting knowledge, the accompanying art of learning, and the supervision of its principled and skillful organization. In contrast, « » generally means a formal or facilitative learning opportunity, while « » means the act of teaching. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ رُسُلًا مِّنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ فَأَخَذْنَاهُمْ بِالْعَذَابِ وَالضَّرَّاءِ لَعَلَّهُمْ يَتَضَرَّعُونَ»\nTranslation: \"We had indeed sent messengers from the People of the Book before you, and We subjected them to trials and hardships so that they might attain success.\""
    }
  ],
  "747": [
    {
      "id": 3394,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Seekhna - To Learn",
      "hw": "سیکھنا",
      "s": "\"Seekhna\" means to understand and examine something with scrutiny and interest.",
      "d": "The original Urdu term \"Seekhna\" means to understand, to examine, and the act of understanding. These words differ from others, such as \"Janta hoon\" (I know) or \"Jaana\" (to know), which generally refer to possessing information. However, \"Seekhna\" includes the notions of scrutiny, detailed examination, and interest. These terms are specifically distinct from each other concerning the related activity. For example: The Quran states:\n«أَفَلَمْ يَتُوبُوا إِلَى اللَّهِ وَيَسْتَغْفِرُوهُ ۖ إِنَّ اللَّهَ كَانَ غَفُورًا رَّحِيمًا»\nTranslation: \"And why do they not repent to Allah and seek His forgiveness? For Allah is Forgiving and Merciful.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3395,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Learning - Acquiring Education",
      "hw": "سیکھنا",
      "s": "«تعلیم حاصل کرنا»",
      "d": "«تعلیم حاصل کرنا» «تعلیم» «سیکھنا» «تعلیم حاصل کرنا»\n«الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْآخِرِ وَيَعْمَلُونَ صَالِحًا فَأُولَٰئِكَ يَرْبُونَ فِي أَمَامِ اللَّهِ»\nTranslation: \"Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day and do righteous deeds, it is they who will achieve a high status before Allah.\""
    }
  ],
  "748": [
    {
      "id": 3396,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Understanding - Understanding",
      "hw": "سمجھ",
      "s": "« » means to form an understanding of the meaning, and to use wisdom and intellect through it.",
      "d": "The root of « » is  - - - , which means the act of forming and understanding a meaning. It is not just with words but with intellect, wisdom, and comprehension to form an understanding of the meaning. This word is similar to other synonyms like « » or « », but « » specifically relates to intellectual understanding, comprehension, and wisdom. For example, the Quran states:\n«أَلَا يَسْتَوِي الْأَعْمَى وَالْبَصِيرُ»\nTranslation: \"Do they not know that the blind and the seeing are not equal?\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3397,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Understanding - Comprehension",
      "hw": "سمجھ",
      "s": "« » is a specific degree of understanding that indicates deep perception and comprehension.",
      "d": "In Urdu, « » is a specific degree of understanding that indicates deep perception and comprehension. Its Arabic root is  , which means to see and understand things, and to have a deep understanding of them. This term refers to a specific nature of meaning that is beyond simple understanding. In comparison to synonymous words like « » or « », « » means to understand things clearly and to see their reality. For example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِيْ أَنْزَلَ الْكِتَابَ مِنَ الْقَبْلِ لَكَانَ لَهُ أَمَامٌ وَّ مَعْرُوْفٌ»\nTranslation: \"For the one who sent down the Book before, it would have been for him a precedent and a known matter.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3398,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Understanding - Insight",
      "hw": "سمجھ",
      "s": "« » means to understand with scrutiny, to understand with wisdom, and to understand the meaning in a better way.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of « » is  , which originally means \"to understand,\" \"to scrutinize,\" and \"to recognize.\" These words are different: « » (hearing), « » (understanding), and « » (knowing). The specific meaning of « » is to understand something with its true meaning, wisdom, and comprehension, not just hearing but scrutinizing and understanding. It is a detailed and better way of understanding. For example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِاللَّهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْآخِرِ وَيَأْمُرُونَ بِالمَعْرُوفِ وَيَنْهَوْنَ عَنِ الْمُنكَرِ وَيُقِيمُونَ الصَّلَاةَ وَيُؤْتُونَ الزَّكَاةَ وَهُمْ يَرْجُونَ رَحْمَةَ رَبِّهِمْ ۚ أُولَٰئِكَ هُمُ الْمُهْتَدُونَ»\nTranslation: \"Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day, and enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong, and establish prayer and give zakah, and they await the mercy of their Lord, it is those who are the guided.\""
    }
  ],
  "749": [
    {
      "id": 3399,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking - Walking",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "« » means to move, to advance with intention, and to present oneself towards one's goal.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of « » is  - - - , which originally means movement, advancing, and doing something with intention. These words are used in different ways, for example, there is a difference between « » and « », where « » indicates human and logical movement, while « » generally means to move at extreme speed or to appear at a specific occasion. « » is a famous term for human and safe movement.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَإِذَا مَا اَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ بِآيَاتِنَا فَقَالَ أَنَا مُحَرِّكٌ مُّلُوكًا»\nTranslation: \"When We sent Moses to Pharaoh with Our signs, he said, 'I am one who changes kingdoms.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3400,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Walking - Moving",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«حرکت کرنا»",
      "d": "«حرکت کرنا» «چلنا» «حرکت کرنا»\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا تَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلَىٰ لِلْمُؤْمِنِينَ رَبَّنَا وَأَنْتَ رَبُّ الْعَالَمِينَ»\nTranslation: \"And those who came after them say, 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith, and do not place in our hearts resentment toward the believers. Our Lord, indeed You are the Lord of the worlds.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3401,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "to walk - to flow",
      "hw": "چلنا",
      "s": "«to flow» means that something moves with constant pace, like walking feet.",
      "d": "«to flow» «to walk» «to flow» «وَالرَّاحِلَةِ إِلَى رَاحِلَةٍ»"
    }
  ],
