      "s": "'To create' [means to make something appear, to see intentionally, or for its existence to emerge.]",
      "d": "«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ بِسُلْطَانٍ فَلَمَّا رَآهُ مُحَرَّكًا لَّمْ يَعِدْ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3431,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To produce - to create",
      "hw": "پیدا کرنا",
      "s": "«تخلیق کرنا» «پیدا کرنا»",
      "d": "«TPLQ» «پیدا کرنا» «TPLQ» «پیدا کرنا»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَجَعَلْنَاهُ سَمِيعًا بَصِيرًا»\nTranslation: \"We have created man from a drop of mixed fluid, then We made him hearing and seeing.\""
    }
  ],
  "762": [
    {
      "id": 3432,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be built - to be built",
      "hw": "بننا",
      "s": "« » means the act of building which is fundamentally done by Allah, and its meaning is to create, to produce, and to make creatures according to His will.",
      "d": "« » in Urdu refers to a singular action that is done by Allah. Its root meaning is to create, to produce, and to make creatures according to His will. Its English equivalents are \"to create\" or \"to make\". Another synonym is \" \", but « » carries the sense of bringing creatures into existence through Allah. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَأَنْبَتْنَا لَهُ حَسَنَةً وَإِنَّا إِلَيْهِ لَمُحْتَشِرُونَ»\nTranslation: \"We have created man from a sperm-drop, and We have produced goodness for him, and We will gather him to Us.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3433,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To be built - to be formed",
      "hw": "بننا",
      "s": "«تشکیل پانا»",
      "d": "«تشکیل پانا» «بناونا» «تشکیل پانا»\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ بِآيَاتِنَا وَسُلْطَانٍ مُّبِينٍ»\nTranslation: \"And We sent Moses with Our signs and a clear authority.\""
    }
  ],
  "763": [
    {
      "id": 3434,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To decrease - to decrease",
      "hw": "گھٹنا",
      "s": "« » means to reduce something or to become less, when the quantity or importance of something diminishes.",
      "d": "«گھٹنا» «گھٹنا»\n«وَلَوْلَا كَلِمَةٌ مِّن رَّبِّكَ لَقَدْ أَخَذْنَا مَن فِي الْأَرْضِ مَوْسَىٰ وَلَوْلَا كَلِمَةٌ مِّن رَّبِّكَ لَمْ يُؤَخِّرْنَهُمْ إِلَىٰ أَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّى»\nTranslation: \"And if it were not for a word from your Lord, We would have seized those on earth by Moses, and if it were not for a word from your Lord, We would not have delayed them until an appointed term.\"\nHere, «decrease» means that if something diminishes or its quantity lessens, it reflects the effect of Your wisdom."
    },
    {
      "id": 3435,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Decrease - To Become Less",
      "hw": "گھٹنا",
      "s": "«To become less» means to decrease or become less in quantity.",
      "d": "«To become less» «to become less» «وَإِذَا مَرَّتْ عَلَيْهِمُ الْقَوْمُ الْمُؤْمِنُونَ فَقَالُوا لَهُمْ إِنَّكُمْ لَمَّا بَلَغْتُمْ مَّوْعِدَنَا وَأَنْتُمْ تَكْتُمُونَ»"
    }
  ],
  "764": [
    {
      "id": 3436,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "To increase - to increase",
      "hw": "بڑھنا",
      "s": "« » means that the original quantity or production of something increases, such as wealth, offspring, or the spread of religious teaching.",
      "d": "« » derives from the root B-R-D, meaning to increase the quantity or production of something. It conveys the sense of 'more' as opposed to 'less'. Like other words, it is specifically used to denote increase, addition, productivity, and a flourishing flower. In the Quran, the concept of increase is presented in the context of religious teaching, faith, and reform. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ ظَلَمُوا مِنْ أَهْلِهِمْ شَفَاعَةٌ وَلَمْ يُؤْخَذَ مِنْهُمْ مَّوْعِظَةٌ فَأَصَابَهُمْ مَّا كَانُوا يَحْسَبُونَ وَمَنْ تَعَالَى فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَضِلُّونَ وَيَرْبُو بِهَا فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَّهُمْ مِّنْ أَهْلِهِمْ شَفَاعَةٌ وَلَمْ يُؤْخَذَ مِنْهُمْ مَّوْعِظَةٌ فَأَصَابَهُمْ مَّا كَانُوا يَحْسَبُونَ وَمَنْ تَعَالَى فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَضِلُّونَ وَيَرْبُو بِهَا فِي الْمَوْعِظَةِ»\nTranslation: \"Such people's families will have no intercession, and no advice will be taken from them; thus they will receive what they thought. Those who increase after advice will go astray.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3437,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Increase - To Be Added",
      "hw": "بڑھنا",
      "s": "«To be added» means that something becomes more than its original, such as progress or advancement.",
      "d": "«To be added» «وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ رُسُلًا مِّنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَأَحَدًا مِّنْ أَصْحَابِ الْكِتَابِ وَإِنَّهُمْ لَيَكُونُونَ مُسْتَقِرَّةً مَّعَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي الْمَدِينَةِ وَلَمْ يَكُونُوا مُحَارِبِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي الْمَدِينَةِ وَكَانُوا يَزْدَادُونَ فِي الْإِيمَانِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْكِتَابِ وَالْمُؤْمِنِينَ مِنْ أَصْحَابِ الْكِتَابِ وَكَانُوا يَكُونُونَ مُسْتَقِرَّةً مَّعَ الْمُؤْمِنِينَ فِي الْمَدِينَةِ»"
    }
  ],
  "765": [
    {
      "id": 3438,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To rise - to rise",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "« » means to lift the body upward or to increase the load, whereas it differs from other words in that this letter is also used in the sense of work.",
      "d": "« » means to lift the body upward or to increase the load, whereas it differs from other words in that this letter is also used in the sense of work. Its roots are   ( ),   ( ), and   (n), which denote the act of lifting something upward. These words are also used in the sense of work, such as when a person begins work or lifts a task. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مِّنَ الْمُسْتَقْرِمِينَ مِنْهُمْ فَأَخَذَتْهُمُ الْحَزَنَةُ وَالْمَسَعَةُ وَكَانُوا فِي ذَلِكَ لَيَسْتَفْتِحُونَ»\nTranslation: \"At that time, none of them had taken the sacrificial animal upward, so grief and distress overwhelmed them, and they again took the sacrificial animal upward for themselves and others.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3439,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "To Rise - To Become Elevated",
      "hw": "اٹھنا",
      "s": "«To become elevated» means to bring something up or elevate it, which is different from merely mentioning extreme height.",
      "d": "«To become elevated» «وَإِذَا سَقَطَتْ سَاقِطَةٌ مِّنْهُمْ فَأَوْرَدَتْ فِي الْعَرْضِ فَأَخْرَجَتْهُ مِنَ الْعَرْضِ»"
    }
  ],
  "766": [
    {
      "id": 3440,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To flow - to flow",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "« » means to spread, increase, and to show oneself together with something visible, in the sense of spreading, adding, and showing progress or an increasing state.",
      "d": "« » has the linguistic root 'resh' which in Urdu means ' ' or ' '. Its Arabic root 'gradation' means to spread, add, increase, and to show oneself together with something visible. Its meaning applies when something is increased or progresses. Another meaning is to show something together with something visible. This word is used when something is spread, added, or progresses.\nIndeed, its meaning applies when something is increased or progresses, and showing together with something visible occurs when something is shown together with something visible.\nExample: In the Quran:\n«وَإِذَا رَأَيْتَ الْعُدُوَّ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ كَرَأْيَةِ الْعُدُوِّ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ»\nTranslation: \"When you see that the disbelievers appear among the believers as if they were disbelievers among the believers, then it means that you have seen them appearing as disbelievers among the believers.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3441,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "To flow - to fall",
      "hw": "گرنا",
      "s": "«سقوط ہونا»",
      "d": "«سقوط ہونا» «سقوط ہونا»\n«وَإِذَا مَا أَنْزَلْنَا مِنْ آَيَةٍ فَإِنَّمَا يُسْرِفُ فِي الْمُؤْمِنِينَ بِهَا وَيَقُولُونَ أَيُّهُمْ أَكْبَرُ مَوْلَىٰ لَهُ الْمَلَكُ فَأَنْزَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ مَّوْلَىٰ لِلْمَلَكِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَقُولُونَ أَنَّهُمْ سَقَطُوا فِي الْمَلَكِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ عَلَى الْمَلَكِ مَوْلَىٰ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ فِي الْمَلَكِ حَقٌّ فَأَنْزَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ مَّوْلَىٰ لِلْمَلَكِ فَإِنَّهُمْ يَقُولُونَ أَنَّهُمْ سَقَطُوا فِي الْمَلَكِ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ عَلَى الْمَلَكِ مَوْلَىٰ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ فِي الْمَلَكِ حَقٌّ»\nTranslation: \"When We sent down a verse, the believers indulge in claiming that one of them is the greater lord of sovereignty, but We sent down upon them a lord of sovereignty, so they say they have fallen in sovereignty and they have no lord over sovereignty nor any right in it.\""
    }
  ],
  "767": [
    {
      "id": 3442,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To leave - to leave",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "« » means to let something be on its own and to keep an eye on it.",
      "d": "«چھوڑنا» «چھوڑنا»\n«وَلَوْلَا دَعْوَتُكُمْ لَقَدْ كُنتُمْ مُّهْلِكِينَ»\nTranslation: \"If your invocation had not been effective, you would have been among the dead.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3443,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "To leave - to abandon",
      "hw": "چھوڑنا",
      "s": "«ترک کرنا»",
      "d": "«ترک کرنا» «ترک کرنا» «چھوڑنا» «ترک کرنا» «بے نظیر کرنا» «روکنا» «بند کرنا» «انداز کرنا» «ترک کرنا»\n«وَلَوْ أَنَّهُمْ كَانُوا أَعِدَّةً مِّنْ عَادٍ أَوْ مُتَّقِينَ لَكَانَ خَيْرًا لَّهُمْ وَأَحْسَنَ تَرْكًا»\nTranslation: \"If they had considered themselves as the people of 'Ad or the righteous, it would have been better for them and a better abandonment.\""
    }
  ],
  "768": [
    {
      "id": 3444,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "grasp - grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«To grasp» means to physically hold or envelop something, or to exert control over it, like holding it close to the chest.",
      "d": "«To grasp» has the Arabic root pakr (q) meaning to physically hold or envelop, to hold close to the chest, and its meaning is to keep something bound or retained, like physically holding something or exerting control over it. Its synonyms include «gherna» (to surround), «band karna» (to bind), «rakhna» (to keep), but the specific meaning of «pakarna» is to hold something firmly in one's grasp. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا أَن يَكُونُوا مُحَرَّكِينَ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَأَن يَكُونُوا مُحَرَّكِينَ فِي الْأَرْضِ»\nTranslation: This means that for them, the only thing was that they would move about on the earth and move about on the earth."
    },
    {
      "id": 3445,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "To Catch - To Grasp",
      "hw": "پکڑنا",
      "s": "«Grasping» means to catch something by closing (the hand) or to enforce upon it, as mentioned in the Quran.",
      "d": "«Grasping» etymologically roots from 'graft' (qaf-ra-fa) which originally means to close something, to enforce upon it, and to keep it secure. These words come with other meanings such as 'to catch' or 'to make available'. In grasping, there is essentially an awareness of keeping something secure by enforcing it. In the Quran, it is used with this meaning:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي ذَٰلِكَ إِلَّا أَن يَكُونُوا مُحَارِبِينَ فِي الْأَرْضِ وَيَكُونُوا فَاسِقِينَ»\n(Al-An'am/148)\nTranslation: \"And it was not for them in that except that they should be warriors in the land and be sinners.\""
    }
  ],
  "769": [
    {
      "id": 3446,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "«Human» means to understand the attribute of human with awareness, and to see its capability of education and thought.",
      "d": "«Human» is an Arabic root 'insan' which looks at the attribute of human. Its original meaning is \"a living being who understands with awareness.\" When defining the word 'human', we should note its various attributes, such as its mental power, education, thought, and human characteristics. Another word related to human is \"rajul\" (man) which only looks at the male, and \"abd\" (servant) which looks at the human's spiritual attribute. In the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَنَجْعَلُهُ سَمِيعًا بَصِيرًا»\n(Al-Isra/67)\nTranslation: \"And We have certainly created man from a sperm-drop mixture that We may try him; and We made him hearing and seeing.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3447,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human - Bashar",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "«Bashar» generally refers to human, but it is also used for the outer surface of human skin.",
      "d": "«Bashar» «ins» «al-bashara» «لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ» «بَشَرٌ» «اَبْشَارٌ» «بَشَرَیْن» «اَنُؤۡمِنُ لِبَشَرَیۡنِ مِثۡلِنَا» «مَلَک» «وَ مَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ اَنۀ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡۤا اِذۡ جَآءَہُمُ الۡہُدٰۤی اِلَّاۤ  اَنۀ قَالُوۡۤا اَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ بَشَرًارَّسُوۡلًا .قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَلٰٓئِکَۃٌ یَّمۡشُوۡنَ مُطۡمَئِنِّیۡنَ لَنَزَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ  السَّمَآءِ  مَلَکًا  رَّسُوۡلًا»\nTranslation: \"And nothing prevented people from believing when guidance came to them except that they said, 'Has God sent a human as a messenger?' Say, 'If there were angels in the land walking securely, We would have sent down an angel as a messenger.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3448,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Human - Adam (earthly)",
      "hw": "انسان",
      "s": "«Adam (human)» indicates the essential nature of human as an animal and its existence on earth.",
      "d": "«Adam (human)» «إنسان» «بَشَر» «Adam (human)» «وَإِذْ قَالَ رَبُّكَ لِلْمَلَائِكَةِ إِنِّي جَاعِلٌ فِي الْأَرْضِ خَلِيفَةً»\nTranslation: \"And when your Lord said to the angels, 'I am going to place a vicegerent on earth.'\""
    }
  ],
  "770": [
    {
      "id": 3449,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«Friend» means a special relationship of the heart that invites a person towards friendship.",
      "d": "«Friend» «م.friend» «رِبْع» «وَالَّذِینَ جَاهَدُوا فِيْنَا لَنَكُوْنَنَّ مِنْهُمْ وَلَنَكُوْنَنَّ مِنْهُمْ»\nTranslation: \"And those who strive for Us, We will surely be among them and they will be among Us.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3450,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend - Companion (compassionate)",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«Rafiq» is a compassionate and soft-hearted friend.",
      "d": "«Al-rifq» «mirfaqa» «rafiq» «rafaqa» «anafa» «فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ ۚ وَ حَسُنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ رَفِیۡقًا»\nTranslation: \"Those will be with those upon whom God has bestowed His grace: the prophets, the truthful, the martyrs, and the righteous. And excellent is that companionship.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3451,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Friend - Companion (one who accompanies)",
      "hw": "دوست",
      "s": "«Sathi» means a friend who walks alongside, and becomes a cause of companionship.",
      "d": "«Sathi» «وَاللَّذِي جَاءَ بِالْحَقِّ مِنْ عِندِهِ فَقَدْ جَاءَ الْمُحْتَجَىٰ»\nTranslation: \"He who has come with the truth\" means one who walks alongside, and \"companion\" means one who is with someone."
    }
  ],
  "771": [
    {
      "id": 3452,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "«Enemy» means one who is distant from friends and causes danger and opposition to others.",
      "d": "«Enemy» «عدوی» «مُعَارِض» «ضَدّ» «وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ دَاعٍ إِلَّا أَن يَقُولُوا سُبْحَانَ رَبِّنَا إِنَّا كُنَّا ظَالِمِينَ»\nTranslation: \"And they had no call except that they should say, 'Glory be to our Lord! Indeed, we were wrongdoers.'\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3453,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy - Opponent",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "«Mukhalif» refers to a person who, in the sense of enemy, opposes God's command and acts according to his own desires.",
      "d": "«Mukhalif» «mukhalif» «وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلْمُؤْمِنِينَ أَن يَخْرُجُوا كُلَّهُمْ وَلَكِن يَخْرُجُ مِن كُلِّ قَوْمٍ مِّنْهُمْ مُّسَارِيَةٌ لِّيَتَبَعُوا الْحَدِيثَ وَلَيْسَ بِهِمْ بَأْسٌ»\nTranslation: \"It is not for the believers to go forth all together, but from each group, some should go forth to understand the command and constitution and to maintain consistency with them.\""
    },
    {
      "id": 3454,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Enemy - Adversary",
      "hw": "دشمن",
      "s": "«Adu» means enemy.",
      "d": "«Adu» «a'daa» «siddiq» «اِنَّ الشَّیۡطٰنَ لَکُمَا عَدُوٌّ مُّبِیۡنٌ»\nTranslation: \"Indeed, Satan is a clear enemy to you both (Adam and Eve).\" And «adaawa» means enmity and ill-will, and it is the first degree of enmity (f.l 169). And it means to withdraw from someone's help, its opposite is wilayat (f.l 106)."
    }
  ],
  "772": [
    {
      "id": 3455,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "king - king",
      "hw": "بادشاہ",
      "s": "«King» means ruler, the supreme owner of sovereignty, who governs sovereignty through his ownership and power.",
      "d": "«King» has Arabic root (b-d-sh-') which originally means 'kingship', indicating a sovereign ruler. It means that the person who preserves his ownership and rules sovereignty through his power. Compared to 'mulk' (kingdom) and 'sultan' (sultan), which have similar meanings, 'king' specifically denotes the supreme ruler who governs sovereignty through his power and ownership. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ فِرْعَوْنُ لِمَنْ أَنْزَلَ الْكِتَابَ مِنْ بَعْدِهِ قَدْ جَاءَكُمْ رَسُولٌ مِّنْ لَدُنِّي بِالْحَقِّ فَأَكْفُوا بِهِ فَأَنْتُمْ لَمْ تَكُونُوا مُؤْمِنِينَ»\nTranslation: Pharaoh said to him, 'After you, the one who sent down the Book has come to you with a messenger from me bearing the truth, so believe in him; but you did not believe.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3457,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "king - shah",
      "hw": "بادشاہ",
      "s": "«Shah» is the representative of the king's rule and heavenly sovereignty, who stands by God's permission.",
      "d": "«Shah» means the owner of sovereignty, the representative of heavenly power and rule, who governs by God's permission. Its root is shah (sh-h) indicating rule and sovereignty. These terms differ from others like 'mulk' or 'sultan' because 'shah' specifically denotes a ruler who governs by God's permission. For example, in the Quran:\n«أَلَمْ يَرَوْا كَمْ أَخْرَجْنَا مِنَ الْأَرْضِ جُزْءًا مِّنْهَا وَأَنْبَتْنَاهُ فَأَخْرَجْنَاهُ كَمْ لَمْ يَكُونُوا مُنْبَتِيْهِ»\nTranslation: Do they not see how We brought forth from the earth a part of it and caused it to grow, then We brought it forth again, though they were not the ones who caused it to grow?"
    }
  ],
  "773": [
    {
      "id": 3459,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "minister - advisor",
      "hw": "وزیر",
      "s": "«Advisor» means, in addition to minister, a person who brings news to the sultan or ruler and also assists in governmental affairs.",
      "d": "«Advisor» has the Arabic root m-sh-r, which originally means something that causes understanding or makes something clear. Moreover, 'minister' also means a person who works for the sultan or ruler. These terms are different: 'minister' is used for an important official in the royal government, whereas 'advisor' refers to a person who brings news or explains something. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مُوسَىٰ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ بِسُلْطَانٍ فَلَمَّا جَاءَهُۥ سُلْطَانُهُۥ قَالَ لَهُۥ مُوسَىٰٓ إِنِّي عَبْدُ اللَّهِ الَّذِي آتَىٰ بِالْحَقِّ وَأَنَا مِنَ الْمُرْسَلِينَ»\nTranslation: We sent Moses to Pharaoh with authority, and when he came to him with his authority, Moses said, 'I am the servant of Allah who has brought the truth, and I am among the messengers.'"
    }
  ],
  "774": [
    {
      "id": 3460,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Teacher - Teacher",
      "hw": "استاد",
      "s": "«Ustad» means one who teaches knowledge and religion, and its original meaning is a scholar and instructor.",
      "d": "«Ustad» has its Arabic root associated with riz (meaning the possessor of relevant knowledge), and its meaning is a teacher or instructor of knowledge and religion. This term is specifically used for religious instruction, whereas other words like «mu'allim» (teacher) or «parhawa» (teaching) are generally used for educational assistance. Its particular emphasis is on religious sciences, prophethood, and moral education. For example:\n«Ustad» means one who teaches knowledge and religion, and its original meaning is a scholar and instructor.\nFor instance, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَبِيَّينَا وَأَرْسَلْنَاهُم بِالْبَيِّنَاتِ وَأَنْزَلْنَا مَعَهُمُ الْكِتَابَ وَزَنَّا فِيهِ الْمِيزَانَ»\nTranslation: «We had sent messengers before you to previous nations, and we sent them with clear signs and revealed the Scripture with them, and We set up the balance within it.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3461,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "teacher - instructor",
      "hw": "استاد",
      "s": "«Instructor» means one who disseminates knowledge and teaches his students.",
      "d": "«Instructor» derives from the Arabic root m-l-m (from the noun 'ma'lam' via 'ma'lamah'), expressing the voice of knowledge. Its literal meaning is 'one who is the embodiment of knowledge' or 'one who spreads knowledge'. Generally it refers to a person who embodies knowledge and teaches others. Compared to 'ustad' or 'mudarris', which have similar meanings, 'mu'allim' specifically denotes one who embodies knowledge. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَ مُوسَىٰ لِقَوْمِهِ يَا قَوْمِ إِنَّكُمْ أَظْلَمُ مِنَ الْأَرْضِ فَاسْتَغْفِرُوا رَبَّكُمْ ثُمَّ تُوبُوا إِلَيْهِ فَإِنَّ رَبَّكُمْ رَحِيمٌ رَّحِيمٌ»\nTranslation: 'And when Moses said to his people, \"O my people! You have wronged yourselves, so seek forgiveness from your Lord, then turn to Him in repentance; indeed your Lord is Forgiving and Merciful.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3462,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "teacher - instructor",
      "hw": "استاد",
      "s": "«Instructor' means one who teaches, nurtures wisdom, and explains knowledge, a teacher's name who, in the Quran, guides Muslims through his wisdom and knowledge.",
      "d": "«Instructor' means one who teaches, nurtures wisdom, and explains knowledge, a teacher's name. In Urdu its meaning is ustad, mu'allim, and one who nurtures wisdom. Its Arabic root is madrasa (d-r-s) meaning to read, to understand, and to impart wisdom. Its meaning is to impart knowledge and to teach. These terms are different expressions, but 'madras' generally means to impart knowledge. For example:\n«وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِنْهُمْ رَسُولًا مِّنْهُمْ يَتْلُو عَلَيْهِمْ آيَاتِنَا وَيُزَكِّيهِمْ وَيُعَلِّمُهُمُ الْكِتَابَ وَالحِكْمَةَ»\nTranslation: 'And when We sent among them a messenger from themselves who recites to them Our verses, purifies them, and teaches them the Scripture and wisdom.'"
    }
  ],
  "775": [
    {
      "id": 3463,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "seeker of knowledge - seeker of knowledge",
      "hw": "طالب علم",
      "s": "«Seeker of knowledge' means one who seeks knowledge, especially a person concerned with religious sciences.",
      "d": "«Seeker of knowledge' comes from the Arabic root t-l-b meaning 'to seek' or 'to turn toward success'. Its synonyms are 'talmidh' or 'durrah', but the difference is that 'talib al-ilm' generally refers to a person concerned with religious sciences who preserves and acquires education under religious tradition. Regarding this, the Quran says:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّلَّذِينَ اتَّخَذُوا مِن دُونِ اللَّهِ وَلِيًّا أَهْلَ الْقُرْآنِ مُحَدَّثِينَ»\nTranslation: 'And it was not for those who took besides Allah allies that they would be people of the Quran speaking.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3464,
      "a": "ط",
      "h": "nation - nation",
      "hw": "طالب علم",
      "s": "«Nation' means a group, tribe, or community that shares a common religion, language, and tradition.",
      "d": "«Nation' has the Arabic root q-w-m, which originally means 'a group of people of the same kind' or 'a group of people adhering to the same tradition'. These words are used to denote a specific group or community that shares a common religion, language, tradition, tribe, or land. In contrast, 'nation' can mean a 'group' or 'assembly', whereas 'tribe' or 'community' refers to a specific tribe or community. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَحْنُ أَرْسَلْنَا إِلَيْهِمْ رُسُلًا مِّنْهُمْ وَنَحْنُ أَعْرَضْنَا عَنْهُمْ وَأَخَذْنَا مِنْهُمُ الْمَوْتَى وَأَرْسَلْنَا عَلَيْهِمُ الْبَرَدَ وَالْمَلَائِكَةَ وَالْبَيِّنَاتِ فَكَانُوا لَهُمْ نَادِمِينَ»\nTranslation: 'We have sent before you messengers to nations before you, and We sent to them messengers from among themselves, and We turned away from them, and We took from them the dead, and We sent upon them hail, angels, and clear signs, so they became remorseful.'"
    }
  ],
  "776": [
    {
      "id": 3465,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Qawm (Nation)",
      "hw": "قوم",
      "s": "«qawm» means a group, tribe, or nation that shares a common religion, language, and customs.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «qawm» is q-w-m, which originally means 'a group of people of the same kind' or 'a group associated with one custom'. These words are used to denote a specific group or nation that shares a common religion, language, customs, tribe, or country. In contrast, 'qawm' means 'group' or 'gathering', while 'qabīlah' or 'millah' specifically denotes a tribe or nation.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَحْنُ أَرْسَلْنَا إِلَیْهِمْ رُسُلًا مِّنْهُمْ وَنَحْنُ أَعْرَضْنَا عَنْهُمْ وَأَخَذْنَا مِنْهُمُ الْمَوْتَیٰ وَأَرْسَلْنَا عَلَیْهِمُ الْبَرَدَ وَالْمَلَائِکَةَ وَالْبَیِّنَاتِ فَکَانُوا لَهُمْ نَادِمِینَ»\n(Al-Anbiyā 21:70)\nTranslation: \"And We certainly sent [messengers] before you, [O Muhammad], among the nations of those before you. And We sent them with clear proofs and with the Scriptures and the enlightening Book. And We have sent down to you the Book with the truth, confirming what is before it of the Book and as a criterion over it. So judge between them by what Allah has revealed and do not follow their inclinations away from what has come to you of the truth. For each [of you], We have appointed a divine law and a way of life. And if Allah had willed, He could have made you [all] one nation [united in faith], but [He intended] to test you in what He has given you; so race to [all that is] good. To Allah is your return all together, and He will inform you concerning that over which you used to differ.\""
    }
  ],
  "777": [
    {
      "id": 3468,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "kingdom - homeland",
      "hw": "ملک",
      "s": "«Homeland' in the concept of kingdom denotes a specific region or people that is a safe and nurturing place for humans.",
      "d": "«Homeland' linguistically refers to homeland, region, and people. These words are used in different ways: watan (place), i'laqah (region), and qawm (people). Originally the word consisted of two parts: 'watan' meaning 'your specific place' which is a safe and relevant location for humans. In the concept of kingdom, 'watan' denotes a specific region or people that is a safe and nurturing place for humans. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَالْمَلَكُ يَوْمَئِذٍ بِأَيْدِي النَّاسِ»\nTranslation: 'And on that day, sovereignty will be in the hands of people.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3469,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Country - State",
      "hw": "ملک",
      "s": "«State» originally means the manifestation of political governance and national wisdom of a country.",
      "d": "«State» means political governance, national wisdom, and administrative order that is given by Allah. These terms are different: mulk (kingdom), dawlat (sultanate), wilaya (guardianship), and sultan (sultan) may appear similar in meaning, but «state» specifically refers to political governance and administrative system. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ وَلَا نَجْعَلْ فِي قُلُوبِنَا غِلَّ اَلَّذِينَ آمَنُوا رَبَّنَا إِنَّكَ رَءُوفٌ رَحِيمٌ»\nTranslation: «And those who came after them say: «Our Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith, and do not put in our hearts any resentment toward those who have believed. Our Lord! Indeed, You are Kind and Merciful.»"
    }
  ],
  "778": [
    {
      "id": 3470,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City - City",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "«City» means a place established for hospitality and tourism that is suitable for people to live in.",
      "d": "«City» has the Arabic root shahr, which originally is the term for naming a place where people have a dwelling. Its literal meaning is \"to name a place\", and with its increasing usage, the term has changed to now mean a place suitable for hospitality. Its synonym «mahallah» or «qaryah» differs, which is for a short time, whereas «city» means a permanent place of residence. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَالْقُرْآنِ الْحَكِيمِ»\nTranslation: «And with the wise Quran, which I have made my city in such a way that it is easy for its people to understand.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3471,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "City - Town",
      "hw": "شہر",
      "s": "«Nagar» means a city or place that is large, orderly, and well-structured.",
      "d": "«Nagar» means a city or place that is large, orderly, and well-structured. These words derive from the root nagar (n-g-r) which signifies a city, place, or an orderly and structured area. These words are also used in other meanings, but the best meaning of this term is city or place. Compared to «madinah» (m-d-y-n-t) which also means city, but it refers to a specific small type of city or place. «Shahr» also means city, but its meaning is the same as that of «nagar». For example, in the Quran:\n«وَالْقَرْيَةَ الْعَادِيَةَ»\nTranslation: «And the people of ʿĀd’s village.»"
    }
  ],
  "779": [
    {
      "id": 3473,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Village - Village",
      "hw": "گاؤں",
      "s": "«Village» means a large and short learning vehicle that is specifically used to learn other parts of the land.",
      "d": "«Village» means a large and short learning vehicle that is specifically used to learn other parts of the land. Its Arabic root is gaon (q) meaning a part of one's house to learn. This is one of the words that originally is the name of a specific learning vehicle used to learn other parts of the land. Compared to «gaon» meaning learning a part of one's house. In the Quran:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي شَرْكَائِهِمْ حُجَّةٌ وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ فِي شَرْكَائِهِمْ حُجَّةٌ»\nTranslation: «When their partners had no argument, and their partners had no argument.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3474,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "Village - Rural areas",
      "hw": "گاؤں",
      "s": "«Dehāt» means the original meaning of village, which is a specific reference for learners and agriculture.",
      "d": "«Dehāt» means a specific part of land that is designated for agricultural work and homes, which is a specific reference for learners and agriculture. Its Urdu meaning is village. Explaining its root: village means a specific part of land that is for learners and agriculture. Explaining its root again: village means a specific part of land that is for learners and agriculture.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَقَدْ أَرْسَلْنَا مِن قَبْلِكَ فِي أُمَمٍ مِّن قَبْلِكَ نَبِيِّينَ وَجَعَلْنَا لَهُمْ زَوْجَةً وَذُرِّيَّةً وَمَا كَانَ لِنَبِيٍّ أَن يَأْخُذَ مِن قَبْلِهِ مِنْ عَطَاءٍ وَمَا كَانَ لَهُمْ مِّنْ عَطَاءٍ وَلَكِنَّ اللَّهَ أَعْطَىٰ بِعِلْمِهِ مَن يَشَاءُ وَاللَّهُ وَاسِعٌ عَلِيمٌ»\nTranslation: «Before you, We had sent prophets to previous nations, and We gave them spouses and offspring, and it was not permissible for a prophet to take anything before him from charity, nor did they have any charity, but Allah gives by His knowledge to whom He wills, and Allah is All-Encompassing and Knowing.»"
    }
  ],
  "780": [
    {
      "id": 3475,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House - House",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "«House» means a place where a human soul finds peace and security, which is connected with Islamic morals and religious principles.",
      "d": "«House» derives from the Arabic word «bayt» ( ) which originally means \"place\" or \"location\", but in Islamic language its meaning specifically includes human and religious values. This term differs from other words like «makan» (place) or «hotel» because a house is not merely a physical foundation but also includes human relationships, religious ethics, and an environment of faith. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا غَفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ»\nTranslation: «And those who came after them say: «Our Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3477,
      "a": "گ",
      "h": "House - Residence",
      "hw": "گھر",
      "s": "«Manzil» means a house, which is a place of human rest and residence, and its specific indication lies in its context.",
      "d": "«Manzil» has the Arabic root «manazil» which originally means guidance and residence. This word indicates a person's dwelling during travel, or a place of upbringing, or even a religious and social setting. It differs from words like «bayt» (house) or «dar» (home) because the specificity of «manzil» lies in its human and social importance. «Bayt» generally refers to a place, whereas «dar» pertains to connections with specific individuals. The uniqueness of «manzil» lies in its capacity for human and social organization. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلِلَّذِينَ هَاجَوْا إِلَى الْبَيْتِ الْحَرَامِ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْقُرَىٰ كَمَنْ هَاجَ فِي الْبَيْتِ الْحَرَامِ مِنْ أَهْلِ الْقُرَىٰ»\nTranslation: «And those who emigrated to the Sacred House from the people of the towns are like those who emigrated to the Sacred House from the people of the towns.»"
    }
  ],
  "781": [
    {
      "id": 3478,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "People - People",
      "hw": "اہل",
      "s": "«Ahl» means specifically those people who are related to a place, religion, or field and act accordingly.",
      "d": "«Ahl» has the Arabic root «ahl» ( ) which originally means \"such people\" or \"pair\", relating to a specific thing or place. Its difference from other terms is that «ahl» generally refers to people who are associated with a specific place or field, whereas terms like «ulu al-amr» (those in authority) or «al-mu'minun» (the believers) denote specific positions or the quality of faith. For example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَا تَكُونُوا كَالَّذِينَ تَفَرَّقُوا وَكَانُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ أَحَادِيثَ الْأَهْلِ فِي الْمُلْكِ لَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُمْ مَّعْرِفَةٌ»\nTranslation: «Do not be like those who split up and had, after them, tales of the people in the kingdom, having no knowledge.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3479,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Ahl - Family/Clan",
      "hw": "اہل",
      "s": "«Family/Clan» (Ahl) means a specific tribe or family, indicating a group of individuals who share a common relationship with their companions.",
      "d": "The Arabic origin of «Family/Clan» is 'khadaan', which originally denotes each tribe or family, signifying a group that shares a common bond with its members. This implies that 'Ahl al-khanaan' refers to a specific tribe or family that maintains a shared relationship with its members. This concept is used specifically in the context of a tribe or family, unlike other synonyms which may indicate general relationships or social groups. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَالَّذِینَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ»\nTranslation: «And those who came after them say: 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith.'»"
    }
  ],
  "782": [
    {
      "id": 3480,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Child - Child",
      "hw": "بچہ",
      "s": "«Child» (Bachah) originally signifies the characteristics of a child, namely weakness, tenderness, and sensitivity.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «Child» is 'bachah', which originally denotes weakness, tenderness, sensitivity, and a series of pleasantness like a flower. These words relate to the meaning of child, but «Bachah» specifically expresses weakness and tenderness. This term is particularly used for individuals who are weak, highly sensitive, or not prepared for very significant tasks. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَاللَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ»\nTranslation: «And those who came after them say: 'Our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who believed before us.'»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3481,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Child - Infant/Minor",
      "hw": "بچہ",
      "s": "«Infant/Minor» (Tifl) refers to a child who has not yet reached puberty.",
      "d": "The meaning of «Tifl» is to be soft and tender, and «Tiflah» refers to a woman with a delicate body. Thus, as long as a child remains soft and tender, they are considered a «Tifl» (masc.). However, this term specifically refers to children who have not yet become adults. Its plural is 'atfal'. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا بَلَغَ الۡاَطۡفَالُ مِنۡکُمُ الۡحُلُمَ فَلۡیَسۡتَاۡذِنُوۡا کَمَا اسۡتَاۡذَنَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ»\nTranslation: «And when your children reach puberty, let them seek permission as those before them used to seek permission.»\nThis verse clarifies that after puberty, a child exits the stage of infancy and enters the stage of adulthood."
    },
    {
      "id": 3482,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Child - Boy/Son",
      "hw": "بچہ",
      "s": "«Boy/Son» (Ladka) denotes the original meaning and fundamental form of a child, understood according to the lineage of birth.",
      "d": "«Ladka» means the sign of the original lineage of birth, which in the Quran fundamentally represents a child. Its residual meanings are those that originate as human. Additionally, its synonyms include «Bachah» (child), «Walad» (offspring), and «Dhakar» (male), but «Ladka» specifically carries the meaning aligned with the original lineage of birth. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ قَالَتْ إِمْرَأَةُ عَامِرٍ لِّمَاكَ الْعَمِيَةُ لَوْلَا تَعَرَّفَتْ وَلَوْلَا تَرَكَتْ مَعَهُ فِي الْمَسْجِدِ فَأَخَذَتْ مِنْهُ حَمَلَةً فَكَانَتْ مِنَ الْمُحْسِنِينَ»\nTranslation: «When the wife of 'Imran said: 'My Lord, I have vowed to You what is in my womb, so accept this from me. Indeed, You are the Hearing, the Knowing.'» (Note: The provided Urdu description and verse reference seem mismatched; the translation above is a general example from the verse context.)"
    }
  ],
  "783": [
    {
      "id": 3483,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman - Woman",
      "hw": "عورت",
      "s": "«Woman» (Aurat) is a specific term denoting femininity, which manifests human ethics in accordance with mercy, tradition, and religious principles.",
      "d": "The Arabic root word for «Woman» is 'A-W-R', which fundamentally denotes characteristics related to femininity. This word refers to the human body, which signifies the state of childbirth and upbringing. In contrast, «Ummah» or «Zunūjah» generally denote human gender, while «Aurat» specifically manifests human ethics, mercy, and religious principles. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَمْ يَكُن لِّذَٰلِكَ عَلَيْهِمْ حَرَجٌ أَن يُؤْمِنُوا بِاللَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ وَيَتُوبُوا إِلَيْهِ فَإِنَّ اللَّهَ غَفُورٌ رَّحِيمٌ»\nTranslation: «And there is no blame upon them for that in which they have been tried, [but] if they believe in Allah and His Messenger and do righteous deeds, then indeed, Allah is Forgiving and Merciful.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3484,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman - Lady/Matron",
      "hw": "عورت",
      "s": "«Lady/Matron» (Khatoon) is used to denote an excellent and more specific attribute of a woman, which also emerges from wisdom, courtesy, and ethics.",
      "d": "The original linguistic root of «Lady/Matron» is 'Khatoon', which specifically defines a woman in terms of her nobility, implying 'as a lady should be'—wise, courteous, ethical, and distinguished in her view. This word is related to a woman's life, ethics, wisdom, and courtesy. Compared to other synonyms, it is used specifically to denote an excellent and more specific attribute. For instance, «Aurat» generally defines a woman, but «Khatoon» speaks of her under a more refined and elevated description. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَاللَّذِي جَاءَ بِالْحَقِّ مِنْ عَدُوِّهِ فَهُوَ الْمُحْسِنُ وَالْمُحْسِنَةُ مِنْهُمَا»\nTranslation: «And whoever does good, whether male or female, and is a believer—We will surely cause him to live a good life, and We will surely reward them according to the best of what they used to do.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3485,
      "a": "ع",
      "h": "Woman - Feminine",
      "hw": "عورت",
      "s": "«Feminine» (Niswan) denotes the original meaning of a woman's sexual characteristics, which fundamentally expresses the attribute of being most compassionate and loving in humans.",
      "d": "«Niswan» means the attribute that displays human sexual characteristics, which fundamentally expresses the attribute of being greater, more loving, and compassionate in humans. Its original terminology is used to define human nature and sexual characteristics, whereas other words like 'zawj' (spouse) or 'mar'ah' (woman) specifically denote the attribute of human compassion and love. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَإِذْ أَرْسَلْنَا هُوَ وَإِخْوَتَهُ إِلَىٰ فِرْعَوْنَ وَمَلَئِهِۦ فَقَالُوا أَنَّا رَسُولُ رَبِّ الْعَالَمِينَ»\nTranslation: «And when We sent him and his brother with Our signs to Pharaoh and his establishment, they said, 'Indeed, we are messengers of the Lord of the worlds.'»"
    }
  ],
  "784": [
    {
      "id": 3487,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Man - Human/Person",
      "hw": "مرد",
      "s": "«Human/Person» (Admi) means the original essence of men who are servants of God, and their characteristic is manifested when they live their lives according to God's command.",
      "d": "«Human/Person» (Admi) means the original essence of men who are servants of God, and their characteristic is manifested when they live their lives according to God's command. Its root is originally from 'Adam', who was created by God's name, and in contrast, «Mard» (man) generally includes human ethical and religious attributes in addition to physical masculinity. «Admi» means the original essence of human qualities created by God. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَقَدْ خَلَقْنَا الْإِنسَانَ مِن نُّطْفَةٍ أَمْشَاجٍ نَّبْتَلِيَهِ فَجَعَلْنَاهُ سَمِيعًا بَصِيرًا»\n(Surah Al-Hujurat / 27)\nTranslation: «And We have certainly created man from a sperm-drop mixture that We may try him; and We made him hearing and seeing.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3488,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Man - Man",
      "hw": "مرد",
      "s": "« » is used when the expression of bravery and masculine strength is intended.",
      "d": "« » (meaning man) is used when the expression of strength, bravery, and masculinity is intended. « » is the verbal noun meaning masculine strength. The plural of masculine strength (mujarrad) is « ». Its feminine is « » and « ».\n«اَلرِّجَالُ قَوّٰمُوۡنَ عَلَی النِّسَآءِ بِمَا فَضَّلَ اللّٰہُ بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ»\nTranslation: Men are the protectors of women, because Allah has given one of them preference over the other."
    }
  ],
  "785": [
    {
      "id": 3489,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Poor - Poor/Needy",
      "hw": "غریب",
      "s": "«Poor/Needy» (Ghareeb) means one who is innocent, carefree, and defenseless, unable to emerge from circumstances beyond their control.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of «Poor/Needy» is Gh-R-B, which originally means 'carefree' or 'defenseless'. Its literal meaning is one who cannot emerge from any problem greater than themselves, defenseless, unaware, and helpless. In contrast, «Miskīn» and «Faqeer» have similar meanings, but «Ghareeb» expresses a particular kind of helplessness and failure. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْغَرِيبِ فَیْهِ لَمْ یَکُنْ لَهُ نَقِیّ»\nTranslation: «And for the stranger [in need] there is no blame upon you if you do not provide for him, but if you are able, then provide for him.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3490,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Poor - Needy/Destitute",
      "hw": "غریب",
      "s": "«Needy/Destitute» (Muhtaj) provides another significant meaning in the context of 'poor', expressing the need for assistance.",
      "d": "«Muhtaj» means a person who wants something and has a need for it, related to seeking help or facilitation. Its root emphasizes a person's importance. It denotes someone who has a need to obtain something. This differs from «Ghareeb», which not only means poverty but also implies a need for help. For example, the Quran states:\n«وَالَّذِينَ إِن مَّآ أَنفَقُوآ لَمْ یَکُونُوا مُهَادِینَ وَلَمْ یَکُونُوا مُحْتَاجِینَ إِلَى الْعَمَلِ فَإِنَّ اللَّهَ لَا یُضِلُّ مَنْ ہُوَ مُهَادٍ وَلَا مُحْتَاجٍ إِلَى الْعَمَلِ»\nTranslation: «And those who spend [in the cause of Allah] are not [to be] extravagant or stingy, but they are [always] between that [excess and deficiency], and those who, when they spend, are neither wasteful nor stingy, but are ever mindful of their Lord's pleasure.»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3491,
      "a": "غ",
      "h": "Poor - Destitute",
      "hw": "غریب",
      "s": "‘ ’ means poor and destitute, deprived of wealth and justice, and suffering from lack of resources.",
      "d": "«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ مَّالٌ وَلَا بَنُونَ»"
    }
