  "787": [
    {
      "id": 3495,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Laborer - Laborer",
      "hw": "مزدور",
      "s": "‘Mazdoor’ means worker, a specific term used for official employees in the sense of one who works.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of ‘Mazdoor’ is mazdoor, meaning those who work. These terms are used for workers and official employees. In contrast, other terms like ‘ ’ (karkun) or ‘ ’ (amal) have similar meanings, but ‘ ’ specifically refers to one who works officially or organizationally. ‘Mazdoor’ is used for official employees or household workers.\nEvidence:\n«وَالَّذِينَ جَاءُوا مِن بَعْدِهِمْ يَقُولُونَ رَبَّنَا اغْفِرْ لَنَا وَلِإِخْوَانِنَا الَّذِينَ سَبَقُوا بِالْإِيمَانِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3496,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Laborer - Worker",
      "hw": "مزدور",
      "s": "‘Karkun’ (worker) refers to a person who works as an assistant to a laborer, taking wages for his work.",
      "d": "«وَلَمْ يَكُن لَّهُمْ كَأَحَدٍ فِي الْعَرَضِ مِنْ أَصْحَابِ الْجَنَّةِ وَلَا مِنْ أَصْحَابِ النَّارِ»"
    }
  ],
  "788": [
