      "id": 3497,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Trader - Trader",
      "hw": "تاجر",
      "s": "‘Tajir’ means one who buys and sells anything, especially a person who works through financial and commercial transactions.",
      "d": "«وَالَّذِينَ يَتَّخِذُونَ مَوْلَىٰهُم مِّن دُونِ اللَّهِ أَرْبَابَ الْأَمْوَالِ وَالْأَبْنَاءِ وَالْأَمْوَالِ وَالْأَبْنَاءِ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3498,
      "a": "ت",
      "h": "Trader - Usurer",
      "hw": "تاجر",
      "s": "‘Soudagar’ refers to a person who trades for the purpose of gaining profit (benefit or gain), while ‘Tajir’ refers to a general trader or merchant.",
      "d": "The linguistic root of ‘Soudagar’ comes from the Arabic triad s-w-d, which means to trade, to take benefit, or to earn profit. This word is derived from ‘ ’ (sod - profit/interest). In contrast, the root of ‘Tajir’ is t-j-r, which means to travel and trade. The difference between the two terms is that ‘ ’ is more specific and refers to profit-oriented trade, while ‘ ’ is a more general term. In the Quran, the word ‘ ’ does not appear as an adjective or independent noun, but the word ‘ ’ does appear."
    }
