  "789": [
    {
      "id": 3499,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time - Time",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "«waqt, miqat» means a fixed time or place.",
      "d": "The word «waqt» is well-known (TIME). «al-waqt» means «a known time» (M.L). «waqt» its plural is «awqat». And according to Imam Raghib's words, for any work, the appointed time's final limit (maf). For example, in the Quran:\n«قُلۡ اِنَّمَا عِلۡمُہَا عِنۡدَ رَبِّیۡ ۚ لَا یُجَلِّیۡہَا لِوَقۡتِہَاۤ اِلَّا ہُوَ»\nTranslation: 'Say, \"Its knowledge is only with my Lord; none will reveal it at its time except Him.\"'\nAnd «miqat» is a noun of place derived from «waqt». It is used in both temporal and spatial senses. Its plural is «mawaqit». In the following verse, miqat is used as a temporal noun.\nFor example, a guidance from Allah:\n«وَ وٰعَدۡنَا  مُوۡسٰی ثَلٰثِیۡنَ  لَیۡلَۃً وَّ اَتۡمَمۡنٰہَا بِعَشۡرٍ فَتَمَّ  مِیۡقَاتُ رَبِّہٗ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ  لَیۡلَۃً»\nTranslation: 'And We promised Moses thirty nights, then completed them with ten more, so the appointment of his Lord was completed as forty nights.'\nAnd in the following verse, the word miqat is used both temporally and spatially, meaning the time is fixed and also the place.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ لَمَّا جَآءَ مُوۡسٰی لِمِیۡقَاتِنَا وَ کَلَّمَہٗ رَبُّہٗ»\nTranslation: 'Then when Moses came at our appointed time and his Lord spoke with him.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3500,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time - Era",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "«Era» is used for a specific period or age, expressing a particular duration or period in the context of time.",
      "d": "The linguistic root of «zamanah» is «z-m-n-h» which indicates a specific era or age in the sequence of time. This word differs from «zaman» (general time) and «waqt» (a particular moment) in that «zamanah» usually refers to a long era or age, whereas «waqt» refers to a specific point in time, and «zaman» is used for the concept of time. An example from the Quran:\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَقَالُوا لَوْ كُنَّا سَمِعْنَا أَوْ عَقَلْنَا مَا كُنَّا فِي أَصْحَابِ السَّعِيرِ»\nTranslation: 'And they say, \"If we had only listened or used reason, we would not have been among the companions of the Blaze.\"'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3501,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "Time - Era",
      "hw": "وقت",
      "s": "‘Daur’ refers to a specific temporal period or era.",
      "d": "The word ‘Daur’ originates from the Arabic root  - - , which signifies circulation, cycle, and the passage of time. It is related to ‘ ’ (time) in that ‘ ’ means a specific temporal period or duration. Its synonyms include ‘ ’ (zamanah - time), ‘ ’ (ahd - era), and ‘ ’ (muddat - duration), but the particularity of ‘ ’ is that it describes the cyclical aspect of time, i.e., a complete cycle or period of time. For example:\n«وَقَالَ الَّذِينَ أُوتُوا الْعِلْمَ وَالْإِيمَانَ لَقَدْ لَبِثْتُمْ فِي كِتَابِ اللَّهِ إِلَى يَوْمِ الْبَعْثِ فَهَذَا يَوْمُ الْبَعْثِ وَلَكِنَّكُمْ كُنْتُمْ لَا تَعْلَمُونَ»"
    }
  ],
  "790": [
    {
      "id": 3502,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day - Day",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "‘Din’ refers to the bright time spent during the presence of the sun, which is expressed in Arabic as ‘ ’ (yawm).",
      "d": "«وَاللَّيْلِ إِذَا يَغْشَىٰ وَالنَّهَارِ إِذَا تَجَلَّىٰ»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3503,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Day - Yawm",
      "hw": "دن",
      "s": "Yawm: The combination of day and night, i.e., 24 hours.",
      "d": "Yawm means day. The time from sunset to the next day's sunset. The combination of night and day, 24 hours. The plural of Yawm is Ayyam. Time and periods are calculated by Ayyam.\n«فَمَنۡ لَّمۡ یَجِدۡ فَصِیَامُ ثَلٰثَۃِ اَیَّامٍ فِی الۡحَجِّ وَ سَبۡعَۃٍ اِذَا رَجَعۡتُمۡ»\nTranslation: And whoever cannot find (a sacrifice) should fast for three days during the Hajj and seven when you return.\nAnd this duration of Yawm is for humans. Its concept can only be formed after the creation of the sun and earth; otherwise, with Allah, Yawm's duration is a long period, whether it extends to hundreds of thousands of years according to our calculation.\n«قُلۡ اَئِنَّکُمۡ لَتَکۡفُرُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الۡاَرۡضَ فِیۡ یَوۡمَیۡنِ»\nTranslation: Do you then disbelieve in Him Who created the earth in two days?\nSimilarly, when Yawm is mentioned in the context of the creation of the earth and heavens, it refers to a long period.\n«وَ اِنَّ یَوۡمًا عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ کَاَلۡفِ سَنَۃٍ مِّمَّا تَعُدُّوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And indeed, a day with your Lord is like a thousand years of what you count.\n«تَعۡرُجُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ وَ الرُّوۡحُ اِلَیۡہِ فِیۡ یَوۡمٍ کَانَ مِقۡدَارُہٗ خَمۡسِیۡنَ اَلۡفَ سَنَۃٍ»\nTranslation: To Him ascend the angels and the Spirit in a day the measure whereof is fifty thousand years.\nSimilarly, Yawm al-Din (the Day of Judgment) will also be a long period, whose duration is mentioned in Hadith as fifty thousand years."
    }
  ],
  "791": [
    {
      "id": 3504,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night - Raat",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "Raat refers to the time from sunset until Fajr, and it is more commonly used in everyday language than Layl.",
      "d": "Raat: Linguistic analysis – This is a basic Arabic noun meaning night. Its root is  - -  (r-w-t), meaning to settle or remain. Night's opposition to day and its continuity are its basic characteristics. Its synonyms include Layl and Zalim. Layl is more classical and literary, frequently appearing in the Quran and Hadith, while Raat is more common in everyday speech and carries a sense of rest and tranquility. Zalim is used specifically for a dark night.\n«وَقُرْآنًا فَجْرًا إِنَّ قُرْآنَ الْفَجْرِ كَانَ مَشْهُودًا»\nTranslation: And (recite) the Quran at dawn. Indeed, the recitation of the Quran at dawn is ever witnessed.\n(Another clear example):\n«وَجَعَلْنَا اللَّيْلَ وَالنَّهَارَ آيَتَیْنِ فَمَحَوْنَا آيَةَ اللَّيْلِ وَجَعَلْنَا آيَةَ النَّهَارِ مُبْصِرَةً»\nTranslation: And We have made the night and the day two signs, and We have obscured the sign of the night and made the sign of the day visible."
    },
    {
      "id": 3505,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Night - Shab",
      "hw": "رات",
      "s": "Shab refers to the time after sunset when darkness envelops.",
      "d": "Shab ( - ) is a basic Arabic noun meaning night or darkness. It means the entire period of night or the time of darkness. The plural of Shab is Layal or Shayub. Other words like Layl also mean night, but Shab more specifically denotes the time when darkness is at its peak and it is the time for sleep. This word appears in the Quran in many places.\n«وَاللَّيْلِ إِذَا يَغْشَاهُ»\nTranslation: And by the night when it envelops."
    }
  ],
  "792": [
    {
      "id": 3506,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Morning - Subh",
      "hw": "صبح",
      "s": "Subh refers to the time after Fajr when daylight fully appears.",
      "d": "Subh originates from the Arabic trilateral root  - -  (s-b-h). It means the time of morning (Subh) and refers to the period after Fajr when the light of the sun begins to spread in the sky. It carries the idea of the manifestation and radiance of light. Its form   means 'morning has come'.\nThe difference between Subh and its synonyms: Fajr refers to the time of Fajr prayer or the beginning of morning, while Subh refers to the broader period of morning. Namā' also means morning but is more used in Arabic poetry. The word Subh appears in the Quran in several places.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالصُّبْحِ إِذَا أَشْرَقَ»\nTranslation: And by the morning when it shines."
    },
    {
      "id": 3507,
      "a": "ص",
      "h": "Morning - Sahar",
      "hw": "صبح",
      "s": "Sahar refers to the time just before Fajr, the transition from darkness to light, which is the origin of the word Subh.",
      "d": "Sahar's basic meaning is magic or sorcery, but in the context of morning, it refers to the time immediately after Fajr, i.e., the early morning. It is derived from the root  - -  (s-h-r), which has multiple meanings including   (magic) and   (morning time). The distinction from other terms: Fajr refers to the time of Fajr prayer or the start of morning, Subh refers to the entire morning period in a broad sense, and Sahar specifically denotes the delicate moment of transition from darkness to light.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَاللَّيْلِ وَمَا وَسَقَ وَالشَّمْسِ وَمَا غَسَقَ وَالْقَمَرِ إِذَا تَلَاهَا وَالنَّهَارِ إِذَا جَلَّاهَا وَالظِّلِّ وَمَا زَحَاهُ»\nTranslation: By the night when it covers, and by the day when it appears, and by that which He created, male and female."
    }
  ],
  "793": [
    {
      "id": 3508,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Evening - Sham",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "Sham refers to the time of sunset or the entire evening period.",
      "d": "For example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّلَيْلِ إِذَا يَغْشَاهُ وَالنَّهَارِ إِذَا جَلَّاهُ»\nTranslation: By the night when it envelops and by the day when it appears."
    },
    {
      "id": 3509,
      "a": "ش",
      "h": "Evening - Maghrib",
      "hw": "شام",
      "s": "Maghrib refers to the west or the direction of sunset, and Sham is related because the Arabian Peninsula is located west of it.",
      "d": "Maghrib's Arabic root is  - -  (gh-r-b), meaning to set or go west. In the Quran, Maghrib refers to the place of sunset or the western direction. Meanwhile, Sham (Syria/Levant) is a geographical name located northwest of the Arabian Peninsula. In Arabic, Sham is named because it is west (Maghrib) relative to the Arabian land. The difference is that Maghrib is an adjective and direction, while Sham is a specific region's name.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَالَّذِينَ يُؤْمِنُونَ بِمَا أُنْزِلَ إِلَيْكَ وَمَا أُنْزِلَ مِنْ قَبْلِكَ وَبِالْآخِرَةِ هُمْ يُوقِنُونَ»\n(Al-Baqara / 4)\nTranslation: And who believe in what has been revealed to you, [O Muhammad], and what was revealed before you, and of the Hereafter they are certain."
    }
  ],
  "794": [
    {
      "id": 3510,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Today - Aaj",
      "hw": "آج",
      "s": "Aaj in Urdu refers to the present day.",
      "d": "Aaj is actually an Urdu/Hindi word derived from the Sanskrit 'adya' (अद्य), meaning 'this day' or 'present time'. It entered Urdu via Persian. In Arabic, there is no word 'Aaj'; the Arabic equivalent is al-yawm ( ), which means today. In Urdu, 'Aaj' is very common in temporal contexts and refers to the current or same day. Its synonyms include 'Aaj ke din' and 'is waqt'."
    },
    {
      "id": 3511,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Today - Amrooz",
      "hw": "آج",
      "s": "Amrooz is an Arabic word meaning today, and in Persian-Urdu it appears as 'Aaj'.",
      "d": "Amrooz's linguistic root is from Arabic 'amru' meaning 'day' (yawm). In Urdu, 'Aaj' is derived from Arabic via Persian. Its meaning is 'this day' or 'the present day'. The Quran does not use 'Amrooz' as 'today'; instead, it frequently uses words like Yawm (day)."
    }
  ],
  "795": [
    {
      "id": 3513,
      "a": "ک",
      "h": "Tomorrow - Farda",
      "hw": "کل",
      "s": "Farda means tomorrow or the time after today, expressing the reality of being separate and distinct from today.",
      "d": "Its synonyms include 'ghadan' ( ), which is more common in the Quran. The difference is that 'farda' is more formal and classical Arabic, while 'ghadan' is more general in the Quran and Hadith.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«سَأُرْهِقُهُمْ صَعُودًا»\nTranslation: \"I will make them (tomorrow) climb a difficult ascent.\"\n(Here 'sa'urhiqhum' means I will burden them, and 'sa'udan' refers to a steep ascent or difficult path, describing the hardship of the Day of Judgment.)"
    }
  ],
  "796": [
    {
      "id": 3514,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Always - Always",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "The word 'Hamesha' is actually derived from Persian, which means 'always', but in Arabic, its meaning is eternity and perpetuity.",
      "d": "When analyzing 'Hamesha' scientifically, it is necessary to clarify that this word is originally from Persian, and its origin is from Persian 'hamesha'. In Persian, 'ham' means 'always' and 'shah' means 'like', i.e., 'like always'. In Arabic, the meanings are expressed with ' ' (abadan) and ' ' (da'iman).\nIn Urdu, 'Hamesha' means 'at all times', 'for always', 'eternally'. Its synonyms include 'hamesha', 'hamesha se', 'hamesha ke liye'.\nSince 'Hamesha' is not an Arabic word, therefore, there is no Arabic text of it in the Quran. However, in the Quran, the word ' ' is used for eternity and perpetuity.\n«خَالِدِينَ فِيهَا أَبَدًا»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3515,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Always - دائماً",
      "hw": "ہمیشہ",
      "s": "'Da'iman' is an Arabic word that means constantly, without interruption, and for always, which is used in Urdu as a synonym for 'Hamesha'.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of 'Da'iman' is d-w-m (dal, waw, mim) which means to remain constant, to continue, and to be continuous. This word is derived from 'da'im' which is an adjective meaning constant, always remaining. In Urdu, 'Hamesha' is its complete translation. Other words like 'abadan' (never or for always) and 'sarmadan' (always) differ from this because 'da'iman' is more eloquent and used in Quranic language.\n«إِنَّ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ كَانَتْ لَهُمْ جَنَّاتُ الْفِرْدَوْسِ نُزُلًا (۱۰۷) خَالِدِينَ فِيهَا أَبَدًا لَا يَبْغُونَ عَنْهَا حِوَلًا (۱۰۸)»"
    }
  ],
  "797": [
    {
      "id": 3516,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Immediately - Immediately",
      "hw": "فوراً",
      "s": "« » is a recent Arabic noun that is used in the meaning of immediate and without delay.",
      "d": "The linguistic basis of « » is on the Arabic root « - - ». This root indicates immediacy, speed, and beginning. Its source is « » which expresses immediacy or that very moment.\nAmong its synonyms, « », « », « », and « » are included, however, in « » the meaning of particularly more immediate and without delay is found, which is not present in other words in this way.\nIn the Quran, its literal usage is not present at all, however, words that express the concept of immediacy such as « » and « » etc. are present."
    },
    {
      "id": 3517,
      "a": "ف",
      "h": "Immediately - In an immediate manner",
      "hw": "فوراً",
      "s": "«فوری طور پر»",
      "d": "«فوری طور پر» «ف-و-ر» «فور» «عجلتاً» «بے درنگ» «ہنگامی طور پر»\nIts difference from other words is that in « » both immediacy and speed are specially considered, while other words such as « » only indicate speed.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَاسْتَعِينُوا بِالصَّبْرِ وَالصَّلَاةِ ۚ وَإِنَّهَا لَكَبِيرَةٌ إِلَّا عَلَى الْخَاشِعِينَ»\nTranslation: And seek help through patience and prayer; indeed, it is difficult except for the humble.\n«فوراً» «إِلَّا عَلَى الْخَاشِعِينَ»"
    }
  ],
  "798": [
    {
      "id": 3518,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Near - Near",
      "hw": "قریب",
      "s": "« » means to be near to something or time, whether in terms of distance or time.",
      "d": "«قریب» «ق ر ب» «محبت» «مہربانی»\nAnd among the synonyms of « », « » (adna) and « » (muqarib) are also included, but the characteristic of « » is that it particularly expresses nearness and closeness, while « » has more inclination towards inferiority.\nIn the Quran, a clear example of « » is found in the statement of Allah:\n«إِنَّ رَبَّكَ لَقَرِيبٌ مُجِيبٌ»\nTranslation: Indeed, your Lord is near and responsive.\nIn this verse, Allah is giving glad tidings to His servants that He is near to them and hears and accepts their prayers. Here the word « » not only expresses temporal or spatial proximity but also points to the spiritual relationship between Allah and the servant."
    },
    {
      "id": 3519,
      "a": "ق",
      "h": "Near - Nazdīk",
      "hw": "قریب",
      "s": "The word « » is derived from the Arabic root « - - » and its basic meaning is 'near or close,' which indicates the reduction of distance.",
      "d": "« » is an Arabic word derived from the root « - - » (qurb). The basic meaning of this root is 'to be near' or 'to be close to something.' Linguistically, this word expresses the reduction of distance, but in the Quran, its metaphorical usage is also frequently found. Its meaning has three basic aspects: first, being near in terms of place; second, being near in terms of time; and third, being near in terms of relationship or connection.\nFurthermore, among the synonyms of « », « » and « » etc. are included, but the characteristic of « » is that it not only expresses mere distance but also indicates the servant's connection with Allah, as mentioned in the Hadith Qudsi that the servant becomes near to Me when he calls upon Me.\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«إِنَّ رَبَّكَ لَقَرِيبٌ مُّجِيبٌ»\nTranslation: Indeed, your Lord is near (close) and He is the One who responds to prayers."
    }
  ],
  "799": [
    {
      "id": 3520,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Era - Era",
      "hw": "دور",
      "s": "« » refers to the duration of a specific time or era.",
      "d": "The origin of « » is from the Arabic root « - - » whose basic meaning is rotation, cycle, and succession of time. This word comes in the meaning of « » (time, era), and its closest words include « » (covenant, era) and « » (time). However, the characteristic of « » is that it expresses the continuity of time, i.e., the rotation from one era to another, while « » indicates the beginning or end of a specific era. In the Quran, the word « » is used in the meaning of time and era."
    }
  ],
  "800": [
    {
      "id": 3522,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Above - Above",
      "hw": "اوپر",
      "s": "'Upar' is a Persian-origin word used in Urdu meaning 'above / on height', in Arabic its meaning is 'fawq' or 'a'la'.",
      "d": "Linguistically, 'Upar' is originally a Persian word used in Urdu as 'upar / on height / sar-e bala'. Its original source is Persian; in Arabic, its synonymous terms are 'fawq' (fawq) and 'a'la' (a'la). In Urdu, 'upar' is commonly used to describe a location, while in Arabic, 'fawq' is more excellent and used in literature. The Quran uses the Arabic word 'fawq', which is translated as 'upar' (above) in Urdu translation.\n«وَهُوَ الَّذِي خَلَقَ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ فِي سِتَّةِ أَيَّامٍ وَكَانَ عَرْشُهُ عَلَى الْمَاء»"
    },
    {
      "id": 3523,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Above - بالا",
      "hw": "اوپر",
      "s": "'Bala' denotes the attribute of height, elevated position, and being above.",
      "d": "«سَبِّحِ اسْمَ رَبِّكَ الْأَعْلَى»"
    }
  ],
  "801": [
    {
      "id": 3524,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Below - Below",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "'Niche' is actually a Persian word spoken in Urdu, in the Quran, its meaning is expressed with Arabic words like 'asfal', 'taht' and the concept of 'below'.",
      "d": "According to lexical analysis, 'Niche' is originally a Persian word used in Urdu as 'niche', but in Arabic, its synonymous terms are 'asfal' (asfal), 'taht' (taht), and 'safali' (safali). The Arabic word 'asfal' originates from 'safal' which is the opposite of 'above' and its root is s-f-l. 'Taht' originates from h-w-t which means below and beneath. Urdu's 'niche' is the translation of these words, and this concept is found in various verses of the Quran.\nDifference from synonyms: 'Asfal' is more used for being below in terms of position or rank, while 'taht' is generally used for being under something.\n«وَقِيلَ يَا أَرْضُ ابْلَعِي مَاءَكِ وَيَا سَمَاءُ أَقْلِعِي وَغِيضَ الْمَاءُ»\nHere, the description is about the water being below and the earth swallowing it."
    },
    {
      "id": 3525,
      "a": "ن",
      "h": "Below - زير",
      "hw": "نیچے",
      "s": "'Zair' means to be under or below something, i.e., to be under something.",
      "d": "'Zair' is an Arabic word whose root is zayr. This word is originally a noun that expresses being under or below something. In Arabic, it is used when something is located under another thing or is under it. In contrast, 'fawq' expresses above and 'amam' expresses front. 'Zair' often comes in the Quran in the form of addition (idafa).\n«وَاللَّهُ أَعْلَمُ بِمَا يُوعُونَ»\nHere, the concept of 'zair' is implied in the context of concealment."
    }
  ],
  "802": [
    {
      "id": 3526,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Inside - Inside",
      "hw": "اندر",
      "s": "'Andar' is a Persian word used in Urdu with meanings of 'inside, internal, interior' and is not an Arabic word.",
      "d": "'Andar' is actually derived from the Persian verb 'andardan' which means 'to enter, to be inside'. This word is not of Arabic origin but entered Urdu from Persian. In Arabic, synonyms for 'inside' include « » (d-kh-l), « », and « ». However, in Urdu, this word is very common and is often used in meanings like 'ke andar', 'andaron', and 'batin'. Since the Quran was revealed in Arabic, this word does not appear in any verse due to Persian influence."
    },
    {
      "id": 3527,
      "a": "ا",
      "h": "Inside - داخل",
      "hw": "اندر",
      "s": "'Dakhil' is an Arabic word meaning 'to enter inside or internally', which is synonymous with Persian/Urdu 'andar'.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of 'Dakhil' is d-kh-l (dal, kha, lam) which means 'entry' i.e., to enter. This word comes in Arabic in contrast between internal and external, where 'dakhil' refers to the internal thing as opposed to the external. Urdu's 'andar' is derived from Persian and means 'andaron' or 'batin'.\nIts other synonyms include 'fi', 'bayn', and 'damn', but 'dakhil' is particularly used when expressing the state of entering or being inside something.\n«وَمَن يَخْرُجْ مِن بَيْتِهِ مُهَاجِرًا إِلَى اللَّهِ وَرَسُولِهِ ثُمَّ يُدْرِكْهُ الْمَوْتُ فَقَدْ وَقَعَ أَجْرُهُ عَلَى اللَّهِ»\nHere, the root of 'muhajiran' implies 'dakhil' which expresses entering from one place to another through migration."
    }
  ],
  "803": [
    {
      "id": 3528,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Outside - باہر",
      "hw": "باہر",
      "s": "'Bahar' means apparent, clear, and evident, which describes the external or obvious aspect of something.",
      "d": "'Bahar' originates from the Arabic root b-h-r (ba, ha, ra) which refers to something being apparent, evident, and clear. This word is different from 'kharaj' (outside) and 'zahir' (apparent) because 'bahar' specifically describes the external aspect or state of being evident of something, while 'kharaj' merely means outside and 'zahir' means apparent. The Quran contains words derived from this root.\n«وَ لَقَدۡ أَرۡسَلۡنَا مُوسىٰ بِـَٔايٰتِنَآ أَنۡ أَخۡرِجۡ قَوۡمَكَ مِّنَ الظُّلُمٰتِ إِلَى النُّورِ وَ ذَكِّرۡهُمۡ بِأَيَّامِ اللَّهِ ۚ إِنَّ فِي ذَٰلِكَ لَأٓيَاتٍ لِّكُلِّ صَبّارٍ شَكُورٍ»\nIn this verse, the word ' ' (nur) is from the b-h-r root, which means bright, clear, and evident."
    },
    {
      "id": 3529,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Outside - خارج",
      "hw": "باہر",
      "s": "'Kharij' lexically means 'to exit outside' or 'to be outside', and it is the Arabic basis for 'bahar', which is the opposite of 'inside'.",
      "d": "'Kharij' is an Arabic masdar (verbal noun) whose meanings are 'to exit outside', 'to be outside', or 'to go towards outside'. This verb comes from 'kharaja' and its derivatives include 'kharaj' (active participle), 'makhraj', 'makharij', and 'khuruj'. In Urdu, 'bahar' is derived from this Arabic root.\nIts synonyms include 'barun' and 'aziz', etc., but 'kharij' particularly carries the concept of 'exiting from something' or 'being beyond a limit', which distinguishes it from other words.\n«وَإِذَا سَأَلْتُمُوهُنَّ مَتَاعًا فَاسْأَلُوهُنَّ مِن وَرَاءِ حِجَابٍ ذَٰلِكُمْ أَطْهَرُ لِقُلُوبِكُمْ وَقُلُوبِهِنَّ»\nIn this verse, the concept of 'kharaj' is implied in 'wara'i hijab' (behind the partition) meaning to speak from outside."
    }
  ],
  "804": [
    {
      "id": 3530,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Here - Here",
      "hw": "یہاں",
      "s": "'Yahan' is a demonstrative adverb that indicates a place close to the speaker.",
      "d": "Linguistically, the root of 'Yahan' is from Arabic 'huna' (huna) which is related to the system of demonstrative pronouns. In Urdu, 'yahan' is derived from Arabic and is a combination of 'yeh' (this) with the suffix 'an' which indicates spatial proximity. Its synonyms include 'vahan' (there - that place) and 'kahan' (where - interrogative or unknown place). 'Yahan' indicates the immediate vicinity of the speaker, while 'vahan' indicates a distant place, and 'kahan' indicates an interrogative or unknown location. The Quran contains the Arabic equivalent 'huna' (huna).\n«وَكَذَٰلِكَ أَوۡحَيۡنَا إِلَيۡكَ رُوحًا مِّنۡ أَمۡرِنَاۚ مَاكُنتَ تَدۡرِي مَا الۡكِتَابُ وَلَا الۡإِيمَانُ وَلَٰكِن جَعَلۡنَاهُ نُورًا نَّهۡدِي بِهِۦ مَنۡ نَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِنَاۚ وَإِنَّكَ لَتَهۡدِي إِلَىٰ صِرَاطٍ مُّسۡتَقِيمٍ»\nNote: In the Quran, the Arabic word 'huna' (huna) appears, which means 'yahan' in Urdu."
    },
    {
      "id": 3531,
      "a": "ی",
      "h": "Here - Adhar",
      "hw": "یہاں",
      "s": "«Adhar» refers to pointing towards the place that is near the speaker.",
      "d": "«Adhar» linguistic origin is from the Arabic root « - - - » which is used for proximity and direction. It differs from « » and « » because « » carries a subtle undertone of movement or direction, whereas « » is purely static location. In Urdu, « » is actually derived from Arabic « » and its literal meaning is «this side», i.e., where the speaker is present.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«إِنَّ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا بِآيَاتِنَا سَوْفَ نُدْخِلُهُمْ فِي نَارٍ مَاْ أُخْرِجُوا عَنْهَا وَسَاءَ مَثْوًى»\nTranslation: Indeed, those who deny Our signs, We will admit them into a Fire from which they will not be brought out, and wretched is the dwelling."
    }
  ],
  "805": [
    {
      "id": 3532,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "There - There",
      "hw": "وہاں",
      "s": "'Vahan' is an adverb that indicates a distant place.",
      "d": "'Vahan' is actually a word derived from Persian that entered Urdu. Its basis is the Persian word 'vah' (vah: that) which means 'that' or 'those', and the suffix '-an' indicates a place. In Urdu, 'vahan' means 'there' i.e., a place that is far from both the speaker and the listener. In contrast, 'yahan' refers to a place near the speaker, and 'kahan' is used for interrogative or unknown locations. Since 'vahan' is a Persian word and the Quran was revealed in Arabic, this word does not appear in the Quran. However, in Urdu translations, when a verse mentions a distant place, the word 'vahan' is often used."
    },
    {
      "id": 3533,
      "a": "و",
      "h": "There - Adhar",
      "hw": "وہاں",
      "s": "«Adhar» is an Arabic word that indicates direction and place, whereas «whaan» is an Urdu word derived from «woh» to indicate a distant place.",
      "d": "«Adhar» linguistic root is from Arabic root letters and it means direction, side, or this way. In Urdu its meaning is «here», «there», or «this way». Its difference from other synonyms is that «Adhar» carries a sense of direction of movement, whereas «whaan» merely points to a distant place.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَإِذۡ قُلۡنَا لِلۡمَلَائِکَةِ ٱسۡجُدُوا۟ لِأٰدَمَ فَسَجَدُوۡا۟ إِلَّاۤ إِبۡلِیسَ كَانَ مِنَ ٱلۡجِنِّ فَفَسَقَ عَنۡ أَمۡرِ رَبِّهِۦۗ أَفَتَتَّخِذُونَهُۥ وَذُرِّیَّتَهُۥ خُلَفَآءَ مِن دُونِی وَهُمۡ لَكُمۡ أَعۡدَآءُۚ بِئۡسَ لِلظَّالِمِینَ بَدَلࣰا»\nTranslation: And when We said to the angels, 'Prostrate to Adam,' they prostrated except Iblis. He was among the jinn and defied the command of his Lord. Will you then take him and his offspring as allies instead of Me, while they are your enemies? What a wretched substitute for the wrongdoers.\nIn this verse the word « » appears, which is related to «Adhar» and means successor or one who takes someone's place."
    }
  ],
  "806": [
    {
      "id": 3534,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Everywhere - Everywhere",
      "hw": "ہر جگہ",
      "s": "«ہر جگہ» «ہر» «جگہ»",
      "d": "«ہر جگہ» «ہر» «کُلّ» «جگہ» «مَکَان» «امکنہ» «ہر طرف» «ہر جانب» «ہر جگہ»\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَسِیقُوا۟ إِلَى ٱلَّذِیۡۤ أَحۡدَثَ فِی ٱلۡأَرۡضِ هَلۡ مِّن مَّحِیۡثٍ»\nTranslation: And they will be driven to the one who has created something new in the earth in every place; is there any savior?"
    },
    {
      "id": 3535,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Every place - Every position",
      "hw": "ہر جگہ",
      "s": "«Every maqam» literal meaning is every position or every place of a position, referring to a specific position or situation.",
      "d": "«Maqam» linguistic root is w-q-f (standing, the place of standing) from which Arabic derives a specific place, position, or situation. Its difference from «jagah» is that «jagah» is a general Urdu-Persian word denoting any place, whereas «maqam» in Arabic refers to a specific place, position, or spiritual station that holds significance.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلِلَّهِ الْمَشۡرِقُ وَالۡمَغۡرِبُۚ فَأَیۡنَمَا تُوَلُّوا۟ فَثَمَّ وَجۡهُ اللَّهِۚ إِنَّ اللَّهَ وَاسِعٌ عَلِیمٌ»\nTranslation: To Allah belong the east and the west; so wherever you turn, there is the Face of Allah. Indeed, Allah is All-Encompassing and Knowing."
    }
  ],
  "807": [
    {
      "id": 3536,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Quickly - Quickly",
      "hw": "جلدی",
      "s": "«Jaldi» means speed, haste, or quickness, derived from the Arabic root (j-l-d) whose basic meaning is skin (leather), from which the sense of haste and quickness developed.",
      "d": "«Jaldi» comes from the Arabic root j-l-d. From this root are derived words such as «jad» (skin), «jalid» (hard), and «jalidi» (haste, speed). Linguistically, «jalidi» means to accomplish a task without delay, swiftly. Its synonyms include «ajalat» (haste), «tez» (speed), «surrat» (speed), and «shataab» (acceleration). However, «jalidi» carries an implicit sense of rash haste or impatience, whereas «tez» simply denotes speed. An example of this word in the Quran:\n«وَلَا تَسۡتَعۡجِلُوا۟ بِالۡقُرۡآنِ مِنۡ قَبۡلِ أَنۡ یُقۡضَیٰۤ إِلَیۡکَ وَحۡیُهُۥ»\nTranslation: And do not rush in reciting the Quran before its revelation is completed to you."
    },
    {
      "id": 3537,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Quickly - Haste",
      "hw": "جلدی",
      "s": "«Ajlat» means doing something quickly, but it carries a negative connotation of rashness and acting without thought.",
      "d": "«Ajlat» in Arabic is written « - - ». It is derived from the verb « » meaning to do something quickly and without delay. However, it carries an implicit nuance that distinguishes it from synonyms like «sur'ah» (speed). «Sur'ah» merely denotes speed or velocity, whereas «ajlat» implies hasty action, rashness, and sometimes foolish behavior. In Urdu, «jalidi» is borrowed from Arabic and reflects the sense of ajlat. The Quran contains many usages of this word.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَقَالُوا لَن نُّؤْمِنَ لَكَ حَتَّى تَفجُرَ لَنَا مِنَ الأَرضِ يَنبُوعًا أَو تَكُونَ لَكَ جَنَّةٌ مِّن نَّخِيلٍ وَعِنبٍ فَتُفَجِّرَ الأَهوارَ فِيهَا وَتَجۡعَلَ لَهُمۡ كُلَّ شَيۡءٍ مُّفَتَّرًا أَو تَقَعَ السَّمَاءُ كَمَا قلتَ عَلَينَا كُتُّابًا أۡو تَأۡتِيَ بِاللَّهِ وَالۡمَلَائِكَةِ قَبِيلًا أَو يَكُونَ لَكَ بَيۡتٌ مِّن زُخۡرُفٍ أَو تَرۡقَىٰ فِي السَّمَاءِ وَلَن نُّؤۡمِنَ لِرُقِيِّكَ حَتَّى تُنَزِّلَ عَلَينا كِتَابًا نَّقرَؤُهُ قُلۡ سُبۡحَانَ رَبِّي هَلۡ كُنتُ إِلَّا بَشَرًا رَّسُولًا وَمَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ أَن يُؤۡمِنُوا إِذۡ جَاءَهُمُ الۡهُدَىٰ إِلَّا أَن قَالُوا أَبۡعَثَ اللَّهُ بَشَرًا رَّسُولًا قُلۡ لَوۡ كَانَ فِي الۡأَرۡضِ مَلَائِكَةٌ يَمۡشُونَ مُقۡتَدِينَ لَنَزَّلۡنَا عَلَيهِم مِّنَ السَّمَاءِ مَلَكًا رَّسُولًا»\nTranslation: And they said, 'We will not believe in you until you cause a spring to gush forth from the earth for us, or you have a garden of date palms and vines and make rivers flow therein, or you cause the heaven to fall upon us in pieces as you claimed, or you bring Allah and the angels before us face to face, or you have a house of gold, or you ascend into the heaven—and we will not believe in your ascension until you bring down a book for us to read.' Say: 'Glory be to my Lord! Am I anything but a human messenger?' And what prevented people from believing when guidance came to them, except that they said, 'Has Allah sent a human as a messenger?' Say: 'If there were angels walking on the earth as messengers, We would have sent down an angel from heaven as a messenger.'"
    }
  ],
  "808": [
    {
      "id": 3538,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Monastery - Monastery",
      "hw": "دیر",
      "s": "«Deer» refers to the dwelling of Christian monks, i.e., the house or monastery of Christian monks.",
      "d": "«Deer» linguistic form «dayr» is derived from the Arabic root d-y-r (d-y-r). It originally comes from «dar» meaning house or dwelling. This word specifically denotes the residence of Christian monks (presbyters). Its synonyms include «dayr» (the same word) used for a particular religious establishment of a certain community. It differs from «bi'ah» (church) because «bi'ah» is the place of worship for Christians, whereas «dayr» is the monks' residence.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَكَأَيِّن مِّن قَرْيَةٍ عَتَتْ عَنْ أَمْرِ رَبِّهَا وَرُسُلِهِ فَحَاسَبْنَاهَا حِسَابًا شَدِيدًا وَعَذَّبْنَاهَا عَذَابًا نُّكْرًا ﴿٥٨﴾ كُلُوا مِمَّا رَزَقَكُمُ اللَّهُ وَلَا تَطْغَوْا فِيهِ وَاحْذَرُوا النَّارَ الَّتِي أُعِدَّتْ لِلْكَافِرِينَ»\nTranslation: And how many cities have rebelled against the command of their Lord and His messengers, so We called them to a strict account and punished them with a severe punishment. Eat of what Allah has provided for you, and do not exceed therein, and beware of the Fire which has been prepared for the disbelievers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3539,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Monastery - Delay",
      "hw": "دیر",
      "s": "«Ta'kheer» means delaying an action or event beyond its scheduled time, or being late in timing.",
      "d": "«Ta'kheer» «أ خ ر» «ta'kheer» «mua'khir»\nIts synonyms include «ta'akhkhar» (delay) and «ta'weez» (compensation), but «ta'kheer' is generally used for temporal delay, whereas «ta'akhkhar» also includes the notion of falling behind.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَلَوْ يُعَجِّلُ اللَّهُ لِلنَّاسِ الشَّرَّ اسْتِعْجَالَهُمْ بِالْخَيْرِ لَقُضِيَ إِلَيْهِمْ أَجَلُهُمْ»\nTranslation: And if Allah were to hasten punishment for people as they hasten for good, their terms would have been decreed immediately."
    }
  ],
  "809": [
    {
      "id": 3540,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water - Water",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«Pani» is a word of Persian origin that entered Urdu, whereas in the Quran the Arabic word «ma'» (water) is used instead.",
      "d": "«Pani» actually comes from Persian into Urdu; it is not Arabic. In Arabic, water is expressed by «ma'» (mim with fatha on alif) and also «miyah». The Quran uses only the Arabic word «ma'» for water. In Urdu, «pani» means a liquid, transparent substance that flows on the earth and sustains all living beings. This word is derived from Sanskrit «paniya*».\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَجَعَلۡنَا مِنۡہُ الۡحَیۡوٰانَ مَآءً حَیًّا»\nTranslation: And We made from it every living creature."
    },
    {
      "id": 3541,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Water - Aab",
      "hw": "پانی",
      "s": "«Aab» means water in Arabic, and in Quranic vocabulary it is a sign of life and purity.",
      "d": "«Aab» linguistic root consists of the Arabic letters alif and ba, and its basic meaning is water. In Urdu, «pani» is derived from Sanskrit, whereas in Arabic «aab» is used in compounds like Zamzam water, rainwater, and the water of life. In the Quran, the word «aab» appears in contexts of water’s purity, life, and Allah’s blessings.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«أَوَلَمْ يَرَ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا أَنَّ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ كَانَتَا رَتْقًا فَفَتَقْنَاهُمَا وَجَعَلْنَا مِنَ الْمَاءِ كُلَّ شَيْءٍ حَيٍّ أَفَلَا يُؤْمِنُونَ»\nTranslation: Have the disbelievers not seen that the heavens and the earth were a joined entity, then We split them apart and made from water every living thing? Then will they not believe?"
    }
  ],
  "810": [
    {
      "id": 3542,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Fire - Fire",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "« » refers to that which is intensely hot flame, which is a sign of the punishment of Hell.",
      "d": "The word « » is derived from Persian, which is also used in Arabic. In Arabic, words for fire include « », « », and « ». « » is the original Arabic word, while « » entered from Persian. In the Quran, fire is described as a sign of the punishment of Hell and a mark of the torment for disbelievers and polytheists.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«إِنَّ الْمُتَّقینَ فِی جَنَّاتٍ وَعُیُونٍ آخِذِینَ مَا آتَاهُم رَبُّهُم»\nTranslation: Indeed, the righteous will be in gardens and springs, taking what their Lord has given them."
    },
    {
      "id": 3543,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Fire - Aatash",
      "hw": "Fire",
      "s": "«Aatash» is an Arabic word used for fire, meaning a flame that denotes both worldly fire and divine punishment.",
      "d": "«Aatash» linguistic root is A-T-SH ( - - ). It is an old Arabic word denoting a flame and blazing fire. In Urdu 'aag' and Persian 'aatash' derive from this root. Its meaning includes intensity and heat.\nCompared to other words like 'nar' (fire) and 'hariq' (conflagration), the difference is that 'nar' is a general term for fire of any kind, whereas 'aatash' emphasizes the flame and heat, and 'hariq' specifically refers to a burning fire.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«إِلَّا مَنْ أَتَى اللَّهَ بِقَلْبٍ سَلِيمٍ»\nTranslation: Except the one who comes to Allah with a sound heart.\nHere the word 'salim' comes from the root 'salm' meaning safety and health, and it refers to the heart being saved from the trial of fire (aatash)."
    }
  ],
  "811": [
    {
      "id": 3544,
      "a": "ز",
      "h": "Earth - Earth",
      "hw": "زمین",
      "s": "« » refers to the stable and spread-out earth that Allah has created and on which He has provided residence for living beings.",
      "d": "«زمین» «زمین» «زمین» «زمین»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْأَرْضَ بَعْدَ ذَٰلِكَ دَحَاهَا»\nTranslation: And after that, He spread out the earth."
    }
  ],
  "812": [
    {
      "id": 3546,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sky - Sky",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "« » in Arabic relates to height and elevation, and it refers to all the celestial layers above the earth.",
      "d": "The linguistic root of « » comes from the Arabic letters  - -  (s-m-w), which convey the meaning of height and elevation. This word is the plural of « » (sama') in Arabic, meaning sky, firmament, or that part above the earth which we see above our heads. Its difference from other words is that « » directly refers to the tangible part of the sky, whereas « » (Jannah) is related to Allah's special reward, and « » (saqf) means merely roof or hood. In the Quran, Allah has described « » as a sign of His signs and power.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِي جَعَلَ لَكُمُ الْأَرْضَ فِرَاشًا وَالسَّمَاءَ بِنَاءً»\nTranslation: He (Allah) has made the earth a bed for you and the sky a structure (roof)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3547,
      "a": "آ",
      "h": "Sky - Falak",
      "hw": "Sky",
      "s": "« » refers to the orbits (paths) of planets in space.",
      "d": "«فلک»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ وَ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ ؕ کُلٌّ فِیۡ  فَلَکٍ یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And He it is Who created the night and the day, and the sun and the moon; each floating in an orbit."
    }
  ],
  "813": [
    {
      "id": 3548,
      "a": "ہ",
      "h": "Wind - Wind",
      "hw": "ہوا",
      "s": "« » refers to the movement or blowing of wind, which is among the signs of Allah's power.",
      "d": "«ہوا» «ہَوَاء» «ہوا» «رِيح» «عَاصِف» «ہوا» «رِيح»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَهُوَ الَّذِي يُرْسِلُ الرِّيَاحَ بُشْرًا بَيْنَ يَدَيْ رَحْمَتِهِ»\nTranslation: And He it is Who sends the winds as glad tidings before His mercy."
    }
  ],
  "814": [
    {
      "id": 3550,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain - Mountain",
      "hw": "پہاڑ",
      "s": "« » refers to a high and verdant or barren elevated land that is geologically a high and stable landform.",
      "d": "The word « » is actually not originally from Arabic but is borrowed from Persian and used in Urdu. In Arabic, the words « » (jabal) and « » are used for mountain. In Arabic, « » means a large elevated land that is high from the earth's surface and has extensive length and width. « » has come into Urdu and Persian with the same meaning and is the semantic equivalent of Arabic « », but etymologically different.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالطُّورِ»\nTranslation: And by the mountain (Tur) upon which the speech of Allah was revealed to Moses (peace be upon him)."
    },
    {
      "id": 3551,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Mountain - Koh",
      "hw": "پہاڑ",
      "s": "« » refers to a strong and firm mountain, which is a sign of the earth's structural strength.",
      "d": "What does « » mean: In Arabic, the root « » (k-w-h) comes from the meanings of hardness, firmness, and remaining steadfast. This word is used for mountain and its original meaning is a large and hard earthly element that remains firm. Other words such as « » (jabal) are also used for mountain, but « » emphasizes hardness and firmness. « » refers to those mountains that protect the earth from sinking and are signs of Allah's power."
    }
  ],
  "815": [
    {
      "id": 3552,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "River - River",
      "hw": "دریا",
      "s": "« » refers to that wide waterway that flows between lands, used for both sea and river.",
      "d": "The origin of « » is Persian, which entered Arabic. In Arabic, the word « » (bahr) is more commonly used for sea, but « » is also found in Arabic and means large water, sea, or river. The difference is that « » is derived from Arabic zakrah (masdar) meaning to be wide or expansive, whereas « » is borrowed from Persian. In the Quran, the word « » appears in very few verses; mostly « » is used.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَهْوَ الَّذِي مَرَجَ الْبَحْرَيْنِ هَذَا عَذْبٌ فُورٌ وَهَذَا مِلْحٌ أُجَاجٌ»\nTranslation: And He it is Who has merged the two seas, this one sweet and palatable, and that one salty and bitter.\nNote: In the Quran, « » is used less, and « » is more common, but the meaning of « » is also sea or wide water."
    },
    {
      "id": 3553,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "River - Rod",
      "hw": "دریا",
      "s": "« » refers to that flowing water which flows continuously from one place to another.",
      "d": "«رود» «رود» «نَہَر» «عَیۡر» «وَادی» «رود»\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْجِبَالَ أَرْسَاهَا»\nTranslation: And He has firmly set the mountains.\n«رود» «دریا»"
    }
  ],
  "816": [
    {
      "id": 3554,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Rain - Rain",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » refers to the water that descends from the sky or a downpour that falls on the earth in the form of many droplets.",
      "d": "According to linguistic analysis, « » is derived from the Arabic root  - - . The original meaning of this root is 'to scatter' or 'to spread', and « » is its mashdar (verbal noun) that describes the action of scattering rain and falling on the earth. Compared to other words, where « » (matr) and « » (ghaith) are also used for rain, « » specifically emphasizes the falling of rain in many scattered droplets, which distinguishes it from other synonyms."
    },
    {
      "id": 3555,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Rain - Barsat",
      "hw": "بارش",
      "s": "« » refers to the rain of mercy sent down from Allah from the sky that revives the earth.",
      "d": "The root in Arabic for « » is « - - », which is associated with the concept of rain. This word is formed from « » (meaning to flow or fall) and the suffix « », indicating continuity and abundance. Other words like « » (matr) and « » (ghayth) differ in that « » mostly describes the rain that comes in barren (desert) areas, which is a sign of Allah's mercy. In the Quran, Allah has described rain in the context of His blessings and mercy.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَهُوَ الَّذِي يُنَزِّلُ الْغَيْثَ مِن بَعْدِ مَا قَنَطُوا»\nTranslation: And He it is Who sends down rain after they have despaired."
    }
  ],
  "817": [
    {
      "id": 3556,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Substitute",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "The term ' ' (badal) is derived from the Arabic root  - -  and means 'one who substitutes', i.e., an alternative or replacement.",
      "d": "The root of ' ' is  - -  (badala) which means 'to substitute' or 'to change one thing with another'. These words are derived from ' ' (badal), which is formed from the masdar ' '. Linguistically, ' ' is in the active participle form, meaning 'one who substitutes'. Its synonyms include ' ' (mubaddal), ' ' (badil), and ' ' (mustabdal), but ' ' specifically refers to the person or thing that takes the place of another or is engaged in the act of substitution. In the Quran, this root often appears in the context of Allah replacing one nation with another or changing commandments.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَإِذۡ قَالَتۡ أُمَّتُہُمۡ رَبَّنَاۤ أَرۡسِلۡ فِیۡهِمۡ رَسُولࣰا مِّنۡہُمۡ یَتۡلُواۡ عَلَیۡهِمۡۤ آیَاتِكَ وَیُعَلِّمُهُمُ ٱلۡكِتَٰبَ وَٱلۡحِكۡمَةَ وَیُزَكِّیۡهِمۡۚ إِنَّكَ أَنتَ ٱلۡعَزِیزُ ٱلۡحَكِیمُ»\nTranslation: 'And when their people said, \"O our Lord! Send among them a messenger from themselves who will recite Your verses upon them and teach them the Book and wisdom and purify them. Indeed, You are the Exalted in Might, the Wise.\"' Here, the root of ' ' is  - -  which means 'to purify'. However, examples of the root  - -  are found in several Quranic verses where Allah has replaced nations with others."
    },
    {
      "id": 3557,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Badal - Sahab",
      "hw": "بادل",
      "s": "« » is commonly used for clouds in general.",
      "d": "« » means 'to pull' or 'to draw', and it is commonly used for clouds (see F. L. 454). All types of clouds are called « », however, this term is specifically applied to clouds that are raised by winds and spread in the sky. Thus, it is the initial form of all clouds.\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَاللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡۤ اَرۡسَلَ الرِّیٰحَ فَتُثِیۡرُ سَحَابًا»\nTranslation: 'And Allah is the One who sends the winds, and they raise the clouds.'"
    }
  ],
  "818": [
    {
      "id": 3558,
      "a": "د",
      "h": "Tree",
      "hw": "درخت",
      "s": "The term ' ' refers to a woody plant that has branches and a trunk, and it is synonymous with ' ' in Arabic.",
      "d": "The word ' ' is actually derived from Persian and is used in Urdu, while in Arabic the original word is ' ' (shajarah). Its synonyms include ' ' (nabat) and ' ' (ghirs), but ' ' specifically refers to a tree that has branches and fruit, while ' ' is also used for general plants, and ' ' relates to planting. In the Urdu translation of the Quran, the word ' ' appears in verses that in the original Arabic text mean ' ' or ' '.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِينَ يَذْكُرُونَ اللَّهَ قِيَامًا وَقُعُودًا وَعَلَى جُنُوبِهِمْ وَيَتَفَكَّرُونَ فِي خَلْقِ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ رَبَّنَا مَا خَلَقْتَ هَذَا بَاطِلًا سُبْحَانَكَ فَقِنَا عَذَابَ النَّارِ»\nTranslation: 'Who remember Allah while standing or sitting or [lying] on their sides and give thought to the creation of the heavens and the earth, [saying], \"Our Lord, You did not create this aimlessly; exalted are You [above such a thing]; then protect us from the punishment of the Fire.\"' (In the context of this verse, the mention of Allah's power is evident in the creation of trees and plants.)"
    }
  ],
  "819": [
    {
      "id": 3560,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Flower",
      "hw": "پھول",
      "s": "The word ' ' is a Persian-Urdu term that does not exist as an original word in Arabic; its equivalent in Arabic is ' ' (zahrah).",
      "d": "According to lexical analysis, the word ' ' entered Urdu from Persian and is not an original Arabic word. In Arabic, for the meaning of 'flower', ' ' (zahrah) and ' ' (waraq) are used. The root of ' ' is  - - , which means 'to shine' or 'to bloom'. The Quran refers to this word where Allah has given examples of flowers."
    },
    {
      "id": 3561,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Flower - Gul",
      "hw": "پھول",
      "s": "The word ' ' is a Persian term used to mean 'flower', although in Arabic, this root has different meanings.",
      "d": "Lexically, the Arabic root ' - ' (jalla) means 'to appear', 'to be majestic', and 'honor and respect'. In Persian, the word ' ' means 'flower', which is used in Urdu as ' '. In Arabic, for flower, the words ' ' and ' ' (which entered Arabic from Persian) are used. The characteristic of this word is that it was transferred from Persian to Urdu and does not have a direct connection with the Arabic root.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْوَرْدِ وَالْحُورِ»\nTranslation: 'By the flowers and the houris.' (Here, ' ' refers to the flowers of Paradise.)"
    }
  ],
  "820": [
    {
      "id": 3562,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Leaf",
      "hw": "پتہ",
      "s": "The term ' ' refers to the part of a tree that grows on its branches, and its basic Arabic equivalent is ' '.",
      "d": "The word ' ' is originally derived from Persian and is widely used in Urdu. In Arabic, the original word is ' ' (waraq), from which ' ' (waraqah) is formed. This root ( ) is  - - , which means 'skin' or 'peel', and this same root is also the basis for ' ' (qirtas - paper). Its synonyms include ' ', ' ', and ' ' (green leaf). The difference between ' ' and ' ' is that ' ' is the original Arabic word, while ' ' is a Persian-Urdu word that is more commonly used in everyday speech.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالَّتِي أَحَاطَتْ بِهِمْ أَوْ عَضَّهُمْ فِي الْغَابَاتِ»\nTranslation: 'And that which encompassed them or devoured them in the thickets.'\nNote: The word ' ' is not explicitly mentioned in the Quran, but sources of ' ' and the word ' ' (green leaf) are present."
    },
    {
      "id": 3563,
      "a": "پ",
      "h": "Leaf - Waraq",
      "hw": "پتہ",
      "s": "The term ' ' refers to the leaves that grow on trees or the parts of paper on which writing is done.",
      "d": "In Arabic, the initial meaning of ' ' is the leaf of a tree and the thin, spread-out layers of paper. This root  - -  indicates thin layers and spread. In Urdu, ' ' is actually derived from the Persian-Arabic ' ' (warqah). Its synonyms include ' ' (warqah - leaf), ' ' (safiyah - leaf like a boat), and ' ' (sahifah - written paper). The difference is that ' ' is more general and wide-ranging, including both natural and artificial leaves, while ' ' specifically refers to written paper."
    }
  ],
  "821": [
    {
      "id": 3564,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Egg",
      "hw": "بیج",
      "s": "The word ' ' is derived from the Arabic root  - -  and means 'egg'.",
      "d": "The word ' ' is an Arabic noun derived from the root  - - . Its basic meaning is 'egg', particularly a bird's egg. This word is synonymous with ' ' (bayd), and both are related to the root  - -  which means 'white'. The word ' ' was more commonly used in ancient Arabic, and in the Quran, the form ' ' appears more frequently. For egg, Arabic also has ' ' (baydatun).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالطَّیْرِ صَافَّاتٍ مَّا لَهُنَّ مِنْ فَرْعٍ وَمِمَّا یَكِیْلُونَ»\nTranslation: 'And by the birds that smooth their feathers, they have no shelter.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3565,
      "a": "ب",
      "h": "Egg - Seed",
      "hw": "بیج",
      "s": "The word ' ' in Arabic comes in the meanings of egg, seed, and offspring, and it is used in the context of both plants and humans.",
      "d": "The word ' ' is derived from the Arabic root  - -  and its basic meaning is egg or seed. This word is used for the seeds of plants as well as for the offspring and lineage of humans. Its Urdu synonym is ' ', which is derived from Persian. The special thing about ' ' is that it is used in Arabic for both aspects of agriculture and lineage, while ' ' is more commonly used for the seeds of plants.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«أَمۡ حَسِبۡتَ أَنَّ أَصۡحَـٰبَ الۡکَہۡفِ وَالرَّقِیۡمِ کَانُواۡ مِنۡ ءَالَیۡتِنَا عَجَبًا أَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ أَصۡحَابَ بَقَرَۃٍ مَّا کَانَتۡ لَهُمۡ فِیۡهَا مِنۡ نَّسۡلٍ ذُکۡرًا فَإِمۡسَاکٌۭ بِمَعۡرُوفٍ أَوۡ تَشۡرِیۡدٌۭ بِظُلمٍۚ»\nTranslation: 'Do you think that the companions of the cave and the inscription were among Our signs a wonder? Or are you among those who believe that the people of the cow had no male offspring in it? So they should hold to what is good or drive away with injustice?'"
    }
  ],
  "822": [
    {
      "id": 3566,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "The term ' ' refers to that soft, dust-like substance of the earth from which human creation occurred.",
      "d": "The word ' ' is an Urdu word that actually originates from the Arabic word ' ' (tin). It means clay or wet soil found on the earth's surface. In Urdu, it is generally called ' ', while in Arabic there are several words such as ' ' (clay), ' ' (dust), and ' ' (earth). The difference is that ' ' specifically refers to the soft, sticky soil that is the basic material of human creation, while ' ' refers to general dust. In the Quran, Allah created humans from this soil.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«إِنَّ اللَّهَ يُحِبُّ الْمُحْسِنِينَ»\nTranslation: 'Indeed, Allah loves the doers of good.'"
    },
    {
      "id": 3567,
      "a": "م",
      "h": "Soil - Khak",
      "hw": "مٹی",
      "s": "The word ' ' is an Arabic term that in Urdu means ' ', i.e., soil, dust, dry earth.",
      "d": "The root of ' ' is the Arabic triad  - - . Its basic meaning is earth, soil, dust, and dry soil. In Urdu, ' ' is originally from Sanskrit/Prakrit, but in Quranic translations, ' ' is used and understood to mean ' '. The difference is that Arabic ' ' refers to the dust scattered on the earth's surface and dry soil, while Urdu ' ' generally includes both wet and hard soil. In the Quran, the word ' ' also appears in the context of earth and human creation.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَإِنَّ عَلَیۡکُمۡ لَحَافِظِینَ ۙ﴿۱۰﴾ کِرامًا کَاتِبِینَ ۙ﴿۱۱﴾ یَعۡلَمُونَ مَا تَفۡعَلُونَ»\nTranslation: 'And indeed, upon you are keepers, noble and recording, who know whatever you do.'\nAnother clear example:\n«وَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ یَّقُولُ رَبَّنَاۤ اٰتۡنَا فِی الدُّنۡیَا حَسَنَۃً وَّفِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ حَسَنَۃً وَّقِنَا عَذَابَ النَّارِ»\nTranslation: 'And among them are those who say, \"Our Lord, grant us in this world [that which is] good and in the Hereafter [that which is] good and protect us from the punishment of the Fire.\"'"
    }
  ],
  "823": [
    {
      "id": 3568,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Jungle - Jungle",
      "hw": "جنگل",
      "s": "Jungle refers to a dense forested area filled with wild plants, borrowed from Persian into Urdu.",
      "d": "The word 'jungle' originates from the Persian language and is used similarly in Urdu. In Arabic, its root is different from 'j n l'; Arabic words related to 'jun' pertain to heavenly hosts or jinn. In Urdu and Persian, 'jungle' means a vast area where trees are abundant and wildlife thrives. Its synonyms include 'jungle, junglestan, beshan, jhari', but 'jungle' is the most appropriate and common term.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَكَمْ مِّن شَجَرَةٍ مُّمْبِدَةٍ»\nTranslation: And how many a tree is there that sheds its leaves.\n(Note: The word 'jungle' does not appear explicitly in the Quran, but Allah has described many types of 'shajar' (trees) that indicate wild forest areas.)"
    },
    {
      "id": 3569,
      "a": "ج",
      "h": "Jungle - Ban",
      "hw": "جنگل",
      "s": "Ban refers to the act of building and creation, which in the context of jungle signifies natural settlements and trees.",
      "d": "Ban is an Arabic root meaning to build, construct, and procreate. It appears in Arabic as 'bani' ( ), which denotes building structures or settlements. The Urdu word 'jungle' actually derives from Sanskrit (Sanskrit: जंगल / jhangal) and is not related to the Arabic root 'ban'. However, conceptually, 'ban' can be linked to jungle as a naturally built settlement by Allah, where trees and plants are like constructed edifices. This differs from other Arabic terms like 'ghabah' ( ), which is used for jungle and has the root 'gh b w'."
    }
  ],
  "824": [
    {
      "id": 3570,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rigistan - Rigistan",
      "hw": "ریگستان",
      "s": "Rigistan refers to land abundant in sand (bajra), i.e., a sandy and desert area.",
      "d": "Rigistan is a Persian-Urdu compound word formed from 'rig' (sand, bajra) and 'stan' (place, land). It means sandy land or desert. Arabic has no exact equivalent, though close terms include 'sahra' (barren, desert land), 'raml' (sand dune), and 'fala' (desolate, remote land). In Urdu, 'rigistan' is borrowed from Persian and applies to areas with abundant sand. The Quran primarily uses terms like 'sahra' and 'ard' to describe such concepts."
    },
    {
      "id": 3571,
      "a": "ر",
      "h": "Rigistan - Sahara",
      "hw": "ریگستان",
      "s": "Sahra literally means barren, sandy, and desert land, used in Urdu as 'rigistan'.",
      "d": "Sahra is an Arabic word meaning barren, sandy, and desert land. It derives from the Arabic root  - -  (sad-hah-ra), implying dryness, barrenness, and emptiness. In Urdu, it is adapted as 'rigistan', combining 'rig' (sand) and 'stan' (place). The distinction from other terms is that 'sahra' specifically refers to arid, sandy desert regions, while 'fala' ( ) generally means open, desolate land, and 'bar' ( ) can mean land or country.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَضَرَبَ لَهُم مَّثَلًا وَذَكَرَ أَجَلًا»\nTranslation: And Allah gave them a parable and reminded them of a fixed time.\nAnd another example:\n«كَأَنَّهُمۡ حُمُرٞ مُّسۡتَنۡفِرَةٞ فَرَّتۡ مِّنۡ قَسۡوَرَةِۭ»\nTranslation: As if they were runaway wild donkeys."
    }
  ],
  "825": [
    {
      "id": 3572,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Samandar - Samandar",
      "hw": "سمندر",
      "s": "Samandar refers to a vast body of water covering most of the Earth's surface.",
      "d": "The root of 'samandar' in Arabic is  - - -  (s-m-n-d). Lexicons define it as a vast body of water. Its literal meaning is 'chest' or 'spread-out water', encompassing both expanse and depth. Unlike terms like 'bahr', 'samandar' conveys a sense of vastness and boundlessness. The word 'samandar' is derived from Arabic and used similarly in Urdu.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالہٗ أَنۢبَتَكُمۡ مِّنَ الۡأَرۡضِ نَبَاتًا ۙ-ثُمَّ يُعِیدُكُمۡ فِیۡهَا وَيُخۡرِجُكُمۡ إِخۡرَاجًا»\nTranslation: And Allah has caused you to grow from the earth like a growth; then He will return you into it and bring you forth again.\nAnd another example:\n«وَسَخَّرَ لَكُمُ الۡفُلۡكَ لِتَجۡرِیَ فِیۡہِ بِأَمۡرِہٖ وَالۡسُّفُنَ فِیۡ الۡبَحۡرِ بِأَمۡرِہٖ»\nTranslation: And He has subjected for you the ships that they may sail upon the sea by His command, and the ships that run upon the sea by His command.\nHere, 'samandar' denotes the entire vastness of the sea."
    },
    {
      "id": 3573,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Samandar - Bahr",
      "hw": "سمندر",
      "s": "Bahr refers to a sea or ocean.",
      "d": "The plural of 'bahr' is 'abhar'. Lexicographers define 'bahr' as a sea or ocean. In modern usage, 'bahr' refers to a large body of water collected in a low-lying area, constantly receiving water from all sides. If the water is small, it's a 'johar' (pool); larger, a 'jheel' (lake); even larger, a 'buheerah' (small sea); and very large, a 'bahr'. The Quran uses 'bahr' for both 'buheerah' and 'bahr'.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ وَ اَغۡرَقۡنَاۤ اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ»\nTranslation: And [remember] when We parted the sea for you and saved you and drowned the people of Pharaoh.\nHistorical research suggests this 'bahr' was the Red Sea.\nWater in a sea or ocean can sometimes be stagnant. Often, winds create waves and keep it moving, though not necessarily toward a low area. Within a collected body of water, rivers flow downstream, and sometimes two rivers flow together—one warm, one cold; or one fresh, one salty—without mixing, contrary to natural properties, all under Allah's perfect power. Referring to this, the Quran states:\n«مَرَجَ  الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ بَیۡنَہُمَا بَرۡزَخٌ  لَّا  یَبۡغِیٰنِ»\nTranslation: He released the two seas, meeting [side by side]; between them is a barrier so neither of them transgresses.\nIn this verse, 'bahr' is used for rivers that flow into the sea. Hence, such rivers are within the sea."
    }
  ],
  "826": [
    {
      "id": 3574,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Suraj - Suraj",
      "hw": "سورج",
      "s": "Suraj means the sun in Arabic 'shams', the source of light and life in the universe.",
      "d": "Suraj is actually a Persian/Urdu word derived from the Arabic 'shams' ( ). Its original Arabic root is  - -  (sh-m-s), meaning 'to shine' or 'to be bright'. In the Quran, the phrase 'ash-shams' ( + ) is used for the sun.\nOther Arabic synonyms include 'aftab' and 'zia', but 'shams' specifically refers to the sun as a celestial body, while 'zia' denotes general brightness.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالشَّمْسُ تَجْرِي لِمُسْتَقَرٍّ لَّهَا ۚ ذَٰلِكَ تَقْدِيرُ الْعَزِيزِ الْعَلِيمِ»\nTranslation: And the sun runs [on course] toward its stopping point. That is the determination of the Exalted in Might, the Knowing."
    },
    {
      "id": 3575,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Suraj - Aftab",
      "hw": "سورج",
      "s": "Aftab refers to the light or radiance of the sun, used in Arabic for light and brightness.",
      "d": "The linguistic root of 'aftab' is  - -  (ayn-tay-ba), meaning to emerge, appear, or spread light. This word describes the sun's light and radiance rather than the celestial body itself. In Arabic, 'shams' ( - - ) is the most common term for the sun, while 'aftab' emphasizes its illuminating aspect.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَآيَةٌ لَّهُمُ اللَّيْلُ نَسْلَخُ مِنْهُ النَّهَارَ فَإِذَا هُم مُّظْلِمُونَ»\nTranslation: And a sign for them is the night; We remove from it the [light of] day, and they are in darkness.\nHere, 'aftab' is not explicitly mentioned, but the concept refers to the sun's light that is removed, causing darkness."
    }
  ],
  "827": [
    {
      "id": 3576,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Chand - Chand",
      "hw": "چاند",
      "s": "Chand refers to the celestial body that provides light at night and has various phases.",
      "d": "Chand is actually a Persian word used in Urdu, derived from the Arabic 'qamar' ( ). The Arabic root is  - -  (q-m-r), meaning 'to be white' or 'to shine'. In Urdu, 'chand' comes directly from Persian, while Arabic uses 'qamar'. The difference is that 'qamar' is the Arabic term found in the Quran, whereas 'chand' is the Persian-Urdu equivalent.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالْقَمَرَ قَدَّرْنَاهُ مَنَازِلَ»\nTranslation: And the moon - We have determined it [in phases] until it returns [to its starting point]."
    },
    {
      "id": 3577,
      "a": "چ",
      "h": "Chand - Mah",
      "hw": "چاند",
      "s": "Mah is used in Arabic for both moon and month, associated with the lunar calendar.",
      "d": "The Arabic root of 'mah' is  - -  or  - -  (m-w-h/m-y-h). This word carries two meanings: moon and month, as ancient Arabic months were determined by lunar cycles. In contrast, Arabic typically uses 'qamar' for moon and 'shahr' for month. In Urdu, 'chand' derives from Sanskrit 'chandra', but 'mah' is also used in Urdu to mean month.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«إِنَّ عِدَّةَ الشُّهُورِ عِندَ اللَّهِ اثْنَا عَشَرَ شَهْرًا فِي كِتَابِ اللَّهِ يَوْمَ خَلَقَ السَّمَاوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضَ مِنْهَا أَرْبَعَةٌ حُرُمٌ»\nTranslation: Indeed, the number of months in the sight of Allah is twelve months in the register of Allah from the day He created the heavens and the earth; of these, four are sacred."
    }
  ],
  "828": [
    {
      "id": 3578,
      "a": "س",
      "h": "Star",
      "hw": "ستارہ",
      "s": "The term 'Star' refers to those bright celestial bodies that shine in the sky, and it originates from the Arabic root  - - .",
